<HEADER>
A1879 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-HNS &LR;      05-22 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
MIAMI _ There was a time when Pat Riley dreamed of coaching the New
York Knicks to victory in a series-deciding Game 7 against a heated
rival.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sunday, he realized that dream. But Riley now coaches the Miami
Heat.
</P>
<P>
   With Riley pulling all the wrong strings and unable to come up
with an effective play on Miami's final possession, the Heat _
again _ went down in flames. The Knicks hammered out an 83-82
victory before a crowd of 20,063 at AmericanAirlines Arena, ending
the Eastern Conference semifinals after seven grueling games.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks advance to play the Indiana Pacers in the conference
finals, which begin Tuesday at Conseco Fieldhouse in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   The game was full of the usual twists and turns, but nobody was
shocked to see this game between two of the league's fiercest
rivals come down to the wire. Certainly not the Miami fans, who
have seen this deja coup de grace at the hands of the Knicks far
too many times in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it was the third straight year the Knicks pulled off a
series-clinching victory at Miami, winning a pair of first-round
Game 5s in 1998 and '99 before Sunday's Game 7 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that you're ever surprised about how a game
goes,'' said New York coach Jeff Van Gundy. ``Certainly that it
came down to the last possession was (not a surprise). This was two
teams playing very well and very hard, and I feel very proud of our
accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially because it easily could have been the Heat jetting
off to Indy for the next round. But Riley and the Heat couldn't
pull off the same kind of magic Van Gundy managed last year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, with the Knicks down by one point and seconds left, Van
Gundy got Allan Houston the ball for one last shot. Houston broke
down the Heat for a leaning shot in the lane that dropped in for a
one-point win.
</P>
<P>
   This time the Heat had the ball, 12.4 seconds away from
exorcising the ghosts of heartbreaks and chokes of past playoffs
with the Knicks. But Riley couldn't get the ball to one of his
primary scorers, with the ball going from Alonzo Mourning to Jamal
Mashburn, who couldn't get rid of it fast enough after a 3-for-15
day.
</P>
<P>
   The ball finally wound up in the hands of Clarence Weatherspoon,
whose 13-foot baseline jumper clanged off the rim into the hands of
Latrell Sprewell (24 points), who managed to tiptoe along the
baseline before calling a timeout that saved the possession for the
Knicks with 2.1 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Weatherspoon? Not Mourning, who had dominated the game with 29
points, 13 rebounds and five blocks?
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the ball in my hands, and they (the Knicks) ran two guys
at me, so I had to kick it to Mash,'' Mourning said. ``Mash was
wide-open but swung it to 'Spoon, and they ran at him. I would have
taken the last shot if I had a good look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of this series, not to mention the four-year
playoff history between these teams, you get used to seeing the
players struggle _ bricking easy shots, making questionable
decisions in key situations and making unforced blunders at the
most inopportune times. But when Riley, regarded as one of the best
in the business, does it
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps his most critical mistake came in the second quarter,
which began with Miami leading the reeling Knicks 25-16.
</P>
<P>
   Riley benched all of his offensive mainstays _ Mourning (14
first-quarter points), Tim Hardaway (who had started the game by
making three of his first four shots), Dan Majerle and Mashburn.
</P>
<P>
   Minus any offensive talent, the Heat scored just four points
over the first 5:01 of the quarter, and the Knicks rallied to tie
it before Riley could hustle Mourning back in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a bad run there,'' Riley said. ``Leads have never
really been safe in this particular series. Teams have been ahead,
and then there have been comebacks. Go down and come back. They
came back, but we came back in the second half, but they came back
again at us.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither team scored over the last 1:21, after a baseline dunk by
Ewing (20 points, 10 rebounds) put the Knicks up by one point.
</P>
<P>
   That's when things got ugly. Not that Riley did it all by
himself. No, he had plenty of help from his players. Mashburn, a
native New Yorker, did all he could to help the Knicks' cause. P.J.
Brown fouled out with 2:21 left. And after sitting for so long
following his fast start, Hardaway never recovered, needing 20
field-goal attempts (making six) to score 15 points.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, Hardaway could not contain Chris Childs, who scored 13
straight New York points in one stretch, including 10 in a row over
the first eight minutes of the fourth quarter when no other Knick
could manage a point.
</P>
<P>
   Toss in the fact the Heat missed 10 of its 21 free throws,
including five straight in the fourth quarter, and three
fourth-quarter 24-second violations, and you have reasons the Heat
deserved to lose.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than look at the obvious, Riley took to griping about
the officiating, pointing to the Knicks' 28-of-31 foul shooting as
proof his team got jobbed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been around 30 years, coaching for 18, and I've been
involved in a whole lot of playoff games, but I've never been
involved in a playoff game where it was determined with fouls,''
Riley said. ``And fouls out on the floor, not even shooting fouls.
Just touch fouls. It was very, very tough to take that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, there's always next year.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
