u s BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     05-22 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
LOS ANGELES _ Hey, you looking at me?
</P>
<P>
   One game down and the battle of NBA superpowers already might
have turned on the whim of a Travis Bickle wannabe with a whistle
around his neck.
</P>
<P>
   Referee Ronnie Garretson calls a pair of technical fouls on
Rasheed Wallace _ the second one for simply staring _ and
Portland's best player is ejected from the game with 6:43 left in
the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ain't never heard of nobody gettin' thrown out for lookin'
before,'' said Trail Blazers teammate Brian Grant, who had better
beware of the grammar police.
</P>
<P>
   But Wallace isn't just anybody. With 38 technical fouls, six
ejections and a disposition just this side of Bob Knight in the
regular season, Wallace is the guy most referees think should be
driving a taxi with Robert DeNiro.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody would be surprised if he showed up for Game 2 wearing a
Mohawk haircut and a vest loaded with explosives.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace is to self-control what Madonna is to abstinence. Yet he
wants us to feel his pain. And to some extent, we do.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Garretson qualifies as a registered voter of
``Egoville'' for tossing a player in a game of such significance
for a look.
</P>
<P>
   Was it a scowl or a sneer? A glare or a stare? And, oh, did
little Ronnie stay up that night trembling under the covers from
such a grievous act of intimidation?
</P>
<P>
   Suffice to say the 5-8 Garretson has Napoleonic tendencies and
is familiar with confrontation. He was knocked over the media table
a few years back during a run-in with then-Laker Nick Van Exel. And
he did learn a few things about the arbiting arts from his father,
former NBA chief of officials and foremost prig, Darell Garretson.
Self-importance does run in the family. And yet there is no getting
around the one salient fact: Wallace was dead wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not for anything he said or for how he looked, but for
putting himself in a position to have let his teammates down with
his absence. Perhaps not for the specific act but for his perpetual
air of confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace just doesn't seem to get it. He lives in a put-upon
dream world where every referee has gotten every call wrong against
him. In his mind, he is always the persecuted party.
</P>
<P>
   It is the victim role, so prevalent in society today, that keeps
lawyers clogging up the court system and multimillionaire athletes
unaccountable and unrepentant for any of their actions.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace is the linear descendant of Dennis Rodman,
bad-as-I-wanna-be but not tough enough to accept the consequences.
</P>
<P>
   The unrepentant part of the equation is nobody's business but
his own if Wallace chooses to go through life as the angry young
man. But there is no getting around the accountability, if to
nobody but his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   For it was not Garretson or the Lakers fans at Staples Center or
anyone in the media who suffered when Wallace had to spend the last
1{ periods of the game in the locker room, especially when the
Blazers cut LA's lead to single digits in the final five minutes.
He is Portland's best player, but he can't score if he isn't in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot have an All-Star sitting in the locker room,'' said
Blazers coach Mike Dunleavy again Sunday. ``At some point he has
got to understand that, even if he's right and it's a bad call.
That doesn't do us any good, because he's in the locker room and
we're on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had another talk. Mostly it was me talking, and I think
he understands. There seemed to be recognition in his eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   To what end? After his technical-foul-ridden season, Wallace
promised to clean up his act for the playoffs. Now he has picked up
seven technicals in the postseason, and in Game 1 against the
Lakers scored just 11 points in 16 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace's responsibility to his teammates is to do whatever it
takes to stay in the game. There are no points for pride and no
honor in leaving the fight.
</P>
<P>
   At Sunday's practice, he shot jumpers and worked on post-up
moves and refused to utter a sound, shaking his head at a request.
Wallace has left his teammates in the uncomfortable _ and
unconvincing _ position of having to alibi.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just like a stare-down in a heavyweight fight,'' Damon
Stoudamire said with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   Except it wasn't a fight and Garretson wasn't the opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He talks with a different kind of aggression than most
people,'' said a sheepish Scottie Pippen. ``You have to try to know
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, maybe at a tea party in the summer. For now, it's all so
tiresome.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
