u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-EXPOS-HNS &LR;      05-22 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-EXPOS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
MONTREAL _ The Astros will wake up this morning in last place in
the National League Central, their second visit to the cellar this
year after winning three straight division titles.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A miserable road trip got worse Sunday afternoon as the Montreal
Expos sent the Astros to an 8-3 loss, their fifth straight defeat,
before a crowd of 20,111 at Olympic Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The five-game skid is the Astros' longest since they dropped six
in a row in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a bad start (to the season), but we started a long time
ago,'' outfielder Moises Alou said. ``We're having a bad season.
It's time for us to regroup and play the way we should be playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We win two games in a row and then get satisfied. We have a
lot of ground to catch up. If we continue thinking, `It's early,
it's early,' it's going to be August and we're going to be 30 games
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's loss dropped the Astros into last place in NL Central,
percentage points behind the Chicago Cubs. The Astros also fell
into last place April 27 after a 12-3 loss to the Cubs. At 15-26,
they are nine games behind division leader St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos completed their first three-game sweep of the Astros
since 1995, tagging righthander Jose Lima (1-7) for seven runs and
10 hits in 5 innings. Montreal built a 6-2 lead after five innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos finished their 12-game homestand with an 8-4 mark to
go seven games over .500 for the first time since July 21, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   While Lima struggled, Expos righthander Javier Vazquez (5-1)
continued to puzzle the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Vazquez allowed three runs and seven hits and left to a standing
ovation after surrendering a leadoff homer to Richard Hidalgo in
the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Vazquez retired the first eight batters he faced before Lima
singled in the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the pitcher they had on the mound, it was hard to come
back,'' manager Larry Dierker said of Vazquez, who is 1-0 with a
1.69 ERA in two career starts against the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Lima never got on track, allowing a triple to the second batter
he faced, Jose Vidro. Rondell White hit a sacrifice fly for the
Expos' first run, and Andy Tracy's homer in the second made it 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Vidro had three hits to raise his average to .393.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you make mistakes up there, you're going to give it up,''
Lima said. ``I'm going through a tough time right now. The whole
team is going through a tough time. When things aren't going your
way, there's nothing you can do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Daryle Ward, who started at first base as Jeff Bagwell was given
the day off, hit his career-high ninth homer _ a two-run shot deep
into the right-field stands _ in the fourth inning to tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal seized the lead for good in the fifth, sending seven
batters to the plate during a four-run inning.
</P>
<P>
   After Vazquez flied out, Lima allowed three consecutive singles.
On one play, White pushed a soft roller to the first-base side of
the mound. Ward moved in to make the play _ the ball rolled past
him _ and Lima failed to cover first as a run scored.
</P>
<P>
   Two batters later, Lee Stevens hit a three-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every game has its moment,'' Dierker said. ``When you look at
things he (Lima) is supposed to do as a starting pitcher, like get
a bunt down and cover first base, the starting pitcher didn't do
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a four-run swing. We still lost by more than four runs,
but you never know.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima said, ``I looked bad there because the pitcher is supposed
to come over to first base to make the play.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima also failed to get down a bunt in the fifth with a runner
at first and no outs.
</P>
<P>
   A 21-game winner last year, Lima has dropped a career-worst
seven consecutive decisions. He has allowed a major-league-high 19
home runs and 51 earned runs in 53 innings _ an 8.77 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every pitch I threw, they hit,'' Lima said. ``I made a pitch
in the dirt, and they still hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Expos' Geoff Blum homered off closer Billy Wagner in the
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros need to win at least once in today's doubleheader in
Milwaukee to avoid their first winless road trip in four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to start playing the way we're capable of playing,''
Alou said. ``Earlier, you could say our pitching wasn't good. Right
now we either hit and don't pitch well or pitch and don't hit
well.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
