<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LEBRETON-MICKELSON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICKELSON WILL FIT JUST FINE ON THE WALL OF CHAMPIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ By any standard, Phil Mickelson's name will
look regal on the Wall of Champions lining Colonial Country Club's
first tee.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves town as the PGA Tour's second-leading money winner. He
departs as only the 10th player in golf history to surpass the $11
million mark in career earnings.
</P>
<P>
   And he joins young Whatsisname as the only two players with
three wins on the tour this season.
</P>
<P>
   By virtue of his final-round 63, Mickelson overtook Stewart Cink
and won the 54th annual MasterCard Colonial yesterday. Considering
the stakes, considering the valley that Mickelson faced as late as
the 63rd hole, it may have been as dazzling a round of golf as has
ever been played at the grand old tournament.
</P>
<P>
   And for that, Mickelson deserves all the applause, plus his name
etched on the great wall, plus the right to be Forever Plaid.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be a great champion,'' tournament chairman Phil Thomas,
dressed in traditional plaid blazer, proudly predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've watched him for years. I was tickled to death that Phil
was the winner.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas isn't kidding. The honorable chairman didn't discuss it,
but golf is unique in how it embraces its champions. Underdogs and
unknowns, for the most part, need not apply.
</P>
<P>
   Golf fans want their leader board to be anointed with familiar
names. If Robert Allenby wants to win, let him go to Hattiesburg.
</P>
<P>
   But a name like Mickelson's is seen as somehow validating the
weekend. The best golfers don't just win a tournament _ they mark
their territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have won this tournament is an amazing feeling,'' Mickelson
said, respectfully.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be a part of the history of this event, which has a
tremendous history, one of the best that we have on the tour, to
see Ben Hogan having won here in '46 and '47, Craig Wood winning
the Open here in '41, and to be associated with those past
champions means a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Not as good as it feels out at Colonial this morning, I'm going
to guess.
</P>
<P>
   With the party-hearty Byron Nelson Classic tossing out dollars
as if they were cheap pick-up lines, and with the concurrent German
Deutsche Bank-SAP tournament giving away checks as door prizes, it
was being increasingly whispered that Colonial's grip on the tour's
heartstrings was slipping.
</P>
<P>
   Young Whatsisname _ Tiger Woods, they call him in Germany _
hasn't played Colonial in three years. Hal Sutton hasn't been here
in six.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not real certain how people are gauging that when they say
the tournament is slipping,'' chairman Thomas said. `` I guess
people are judging it by Tiger Woods and the fact that some guys
have gone over to the SAP.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I thought we had a great field, and I think we'll have an
even better field next year. And I certainly don't think the
stature of our tournament is slipping.''
</P>
<P>
   Enter Mr. Mickelson. Tall, handsome, blessed with a photogenic
wife and a gushingly cute 11-month-old daughter. Mickelson has won
16 times on the PGA Tour. He missed winning the U.S. Open last year
by a single stroke. Even before he shot 63 yesterday, he would have
been on most everyone's list as one of the world's great players.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson's, indeed, is just the kind of sexy name that
Colonial's Wall of Fossils needed.
</P>
<P>
   Look it up. At 29, Mickelson is the youngest Colonial champion
in 11 years. The previous 10 winners of the tournament were an
average of 37.6 years old. What goes on at the annual Colonial
champions dinner, anyway _ bingo?
</P>
<P>
   Chairman Thomas said, ``We need some younger guys to start
getting in that top tier. We're proud to have Phil on our wall.
He'll be around for quite a few years.''
</P>
<P>
   If the 54th Colonial proved anything these past seven days, it
is that the hallowed course has never been better. Player after
player sang its praises. On television, CBS made the grand old club
resemble an emerald Shangri-La.
</P>
<P>
   But the Nelson tournament, with its trucked-in trees and
freeway-side address, managed to attract seven of the tour's top 10
money-winners. Colonial had four.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're still right in there,'' Thomas said. ``That
might be one of the reasons that the commissioner has us in the
position \Ron the PGA schedule\S we're in. Because he knows that we
have a strong tournament that won't slip.''
</P>
<P>
   Golf fans, ever star-struck, will have to be the judge of that.
</P>
<P>
   Everything old is new again. Maybe the pros will grow weary of
the weinerschnitzel. Maybe Colonial will become a retro sensation.
Maybe next year, Tiger Woods will again grace us with his presence.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, there was Phil Mickelson yesterday, in all his
world-class, 7-under-par glory.
</P>
<P>
   His name will probably be etched on the wall by noon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
