<HEADLINE>
STRONG FINISH KEEPS ESTES ON TRACK FOR BRITISH OPEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Troy Phillips 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH _ Bob Estes didn't win during his two-week visit to
North Texas, but he might have punched a ticket to Scotland in
July.
</P>
<P>
   Estes' two-round charge up the MasterCard Colonial leader board
should solidify his standing in the World Golf Rankings Top 50 and
earn his exempt status to the British Open, scheduled for July
17-23 at St. Andrews Old Course in Fife, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Estes closed yesterday with a 66 to finish Colonial at 7-under
273, tied for sixth with Greg Kraft. His three sub-par rounds,
including two 66s, had their share of moments in which Estes
escaped trouble with his short game.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Estes closed by chipping out of the No. 10 tee
entrance over a wide cart path/walking area outside the No. 9 green
to cap his first 66.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, Estes overshot the par-3 No. 16 hole, chipped on and
drained a perfectly read long putt that broke two feet right and
dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Estes' 10 birdies over the final two rounds (five each day)
served as a dramatic turnaround from his three-bogey 72 during the
rain-delayed second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I have time or take the time to really work on my short
game, I play rounds like that,'' said Estes, a University of Texas
graduate in his 13th season on the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might hit 12 greens and get the other six up and down. The
stats will bear out that I have a really good short game.''
</P>
<P>
   His sixth-place finish at last week's GTE Byron Nelson Classic
moved Estes from 52nd to 49th in the world rankings, not as high up
as he expected to go. Estes said he knew that anything less than
sixth again might cost him what little ground he gained last week.
</P>
<P>
   The top 50 in the world rankings May 30 will receive exempt
status into the British Open. Estes can also strengthen his
position with a high finish in this week's Memorial Tournament in
Dublin, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday also marked the 10th top-10 finish for Estes in two
seasons, signs that he is regaining some form that helped him make
27 of 28 cuts and finish 26th in PGA Tour earnings ($1,357,618) in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was extra pressure on me this week and/or next week to
have a really good tournament,'' said Estes, who has missed four of
nine cuts in 2000. You don't think about \Rworld rankings\S while
you're playing. You just know you'd better play good.''
</P>
<P>
   Estes carded his only bogey yesterday at No. 18 after a
wide-right tee shot and scrambling approach into one of the hole's
two greenside bunkers. After his miracle save at 16 and other
highlights, such as a 30-foot birdie putt at 13, Estes had little
regret over his finish. When it comes to saving pars, I saved a lot
when I had to this week,'' he said. I just couldn't get that last
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really understanding what I have to do to get in a
position where everything's more natural and will hold up under
pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest world rankings should reflect just that. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
