<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-COLONIAL-LEDE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWN 7 WITH 9 HOLES LEFT, MICKELSON ROLLS TO COLONIAL VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Phil Mickelson peeked at the scoreboard and
reassessed his goals. A chance for outright victory, he reasoned,
seemed unattainable as he headed to the back nine Sunday at
Colonial Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson, seven strokes down with nine holes to play, figured
his best-case scenario would be a blistering back nine and ``an
outside chance'' for a playoff at the MasterCard Colonial. He
figured wrong.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of regulation, Mickelson was hoisting the Leonard
Trophy after posting the lowest final-round score (63) of any
Colonial champion. Mickelson, 29, closed with five birdies on the
back nine _ eight overall _ and reeled in a fading Stewart Cink to
win his third PGA Tour event of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson finished at 12-under par, two strokes ahead of Cink
and Davis Love III, to become the youngest winner at Colonial since
a 28-year-old Ian Baker-Finch prevailed in 1989. By erasing a
six-stroke deficit in the final round, Mickelson collected a
$594,000 paycheck and authored the second-largest comeback in
Colonial history.
</P>
<P>
   Only Nick Price, who came from seven strokes off the pace to win
the 1994 event, slipped into a plaid jacket after beginning the
final round further behind than Mickelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an amazing feeling,'' said Mickelson, who punctuated a
35-foot birdie putt on the final hole of regulation with a vigorous
pump of his left fist. ``To have won this tournament after being
seven (strokes) back with nine (holes) to play is amazing. I really
can't remember a finish like this. I didn't think at the turn that
it was going to be possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson made it possible with a back-nine 30 and three
ill-timed bogeys over the final four holes by Cink, who held a
three-stroke lead after 54 holes. Cink reached 14-under par with a
birdie at the fourth hole during Sunday's round, which coincided
with Mickelson's bogey from the bunker at No. 9 to drop to 7 under.
</P>
<P>
   Although playing well, Mickelson said he never envisioned ending
his round wrapped in a plaid jacket. But he began making strides in
that direction with a three-foot birdie putt at No. 10. When he
rescued birdie at No. 11 after clanging his second shot off a tree
at the par-5 hole, Mickelson began gaining confidence. The momentum
carried on to No. 12, where he buried a 12-foot birdie putt.
</P>
<P>
   At that juncture, Mickelson scanned another scoreboard and
realized he had shaved five strokes off Cink's advantage. Down by
only two strokes with six holes remaining, Mickelson began thinking
about a possible playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where I thought, `Hey, I've got a shot of winning this
thing,''' said Mickelson, whose birdie binge coincided with Cink
bogeys at Nos. 5 and 6.
</P>
<P>
   Because Cink had more holes remaining, Mickelson said he
projected himself with ``an outside chance'' at forcing a playoff
if he closed with a flurry of birdies. He added his next at No. 15,
dropping a 12-foot putt to regain a stroke he lost when Cink
collected his final birdie, at No. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson turned up the heat at No. 18, knocking a pitching
wedge approach 35 feet above the hole and dropping the downhill
putt for his final birdie. The putt moved Mickelson to 12 under,
one stroke behind Cink, who arrived at the 15th tee box clinging to
a one-stroke lead.
</P>
<P>
   The lead would not last long. Cink drove into the right rough at
No. 15, then chipped across the fairway into the left rough. He
wound up missing a four-foot par putt, knotting matters atop the
leader board while Mickelson watched from a television in the
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Cink backtracked again at No. 17, where he three-putted from 40
feet. Cink blew his birdie attempt five feet past the hole and
missed the comeback putt for par. As Cink's par putt slid past the
right lip, Mickelson said, ``Oh, wow!'' as he took his first lead
of tournament week.
</P>
<P>
   From the right rough at No. 18, Cink's bid for a closing birdie
to force a playoff resulted in a wedge shot from 158 yards that
stopped short of the green. Cink three-putted for bogey from the
fringe _ his third bogey in the final four holes _ to seal a
two-stroke victory for Mickelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of things I wish I could do over,'' said Cink,
who split just six of 14 fairways and needed 33 putts during a
closing round of 71. ``I just lost it. You can't open the door for
guys like this. Phil ... came back and took the trophy away from
me, and he is deserving.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson, whose closing 63 surpassed Price's 64 in 1994 as the
lowest final-round effort by a Colonial champion, said he began the
final day with a good feeling when he looked at the Wall of
Champions before his initial tee shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw that Craig Wood won the 1941 U.S. Open here, and that
Ben Hogan won the first two Colonials, in 1946 and 1947,''
Mickelson said. ``I thought, `Those are some pretty good names at
the front end of that plaque. I'd like to put my name on the other
end.'''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day, Mickelson had done so. In the process, he
jumped to No. 2 on the season money list, with $2,355,264. And he
did so in a manner that even Mickelson termed ``amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't ever remember a finish like this,'' said Mickelson,
who lost a playoff to Jesper Parnevik at last week's GTE Byron
Nelson Classic. ``I know that Stewart looks at this and knows it
should have been his tournament. I look at last week and feel the
same way. So I understand how that can feel. Now, I understand this
side of it, too. And it feels great.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
