<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICKEY'S QUICK START WITH M'S HELPS FILL HOLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Among the lesser known virtues of Rickey Henderson is
his knowledge of what's going on around baseball. Which only makes
sense _ after 21 years in the majors, he's been a teammate with
just about everybody still in the game. He should know everybody's
business.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, he's always known the Mariners business. As a major
part of the persistent, weird dominance by the Oakland A's of the
Mariners, Henderson watched bemused over the years as the Seattles,
despite an impressive offense led by Ken Griffey Jr., always lacked
one key attack element _ Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Henderson said, he and Griffey bantered about the
prospect of coming to Seattle to fix three problems at once _ left
field, leadoff hitting and speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They always had a lot of offense, but somewhere in the late
innings, the bullpen would lose it for them,'' he said, smiling.
``I'd joke with him and tell him I always got two runs in me, and
you guys always lose by one run.
</P>
<P>
   ``So get me up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Dang.
</P>
<P>
   Missed by a year.
</P>
<P>
   Not because of lack of effort on Griffey's part. In his
long-term role as general-manager-without-portfolio, he steadily
lobbied for Henderson's acquisition. Then again, Griffey steadily
lobbied for the acquisition of Orlando and a golf-course home, as
well as the preservation of the Kingdome. Rebuffed on all fronts,
he chose other options.
</P>
<P>
   The Henderson idea, however, was not preposterous. The Mariners
pursued the free agent after the 1998 season, but the New York
Mets' offer of a two-year guaranteed contract was better than a
one-year deal from the Mariners, whose owners were busy choking on
the cost of the new ballpark and wanted no payroll risks.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Mariners that off-season signed John Mabry, Tom
Lampkin, Matt Mieske and traded for Butch Huskey, none of whom
fixed the aforementioned problems. The Mariners were on their way
to a second straight losing season.
</P>
<P>
   After watching Henderson over the weekend get on base five times
in his first 10 at-bats and score four runs while hitting two
leadoff homers, the majesty of the mistake in not getting him here
sooner is apparent.
</P>
<P>
   Now, of course, he's 41 and he could creak to a stop at any
moment. And his history of volatility towards club management could
turn the Mariners into a Jerry Springer show, also at any moment.
</P>
<P>
   For now, he's a vital patch on a tire that is suddenly covering
some highway.
</P>
<P>
   A 5-1 homestand, concluding Sunday with an 8-4 win over Tampa
Bay, was notable for what didn't happen. After an unpleasant 2-5
road trip, the pitching didn't blow up.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly a month after No. 2 starting pitcher Freddy Garcia
followed No. 1 starter Jamie Moyer onto the disabled list, the
Mariners lead the AL West with a 23-18 mark, as far over .500 as
they've been this season. In this homestand, the revamped rotation
in 37 innings over the six games gave up just 10 earned runs,
including four Sunday by Aaron Sele. The Mariners' team ERA of 4.76
entering the day was fifth best in the AL.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Minnesota and Tampa Bay produce flop sweats in no one.
But they still must be beaten, and the fact that the Mariners did
so with a big hole in the top of the rotation speaks well for a
prosperous summer.
</P>
<P>
   While Moyer's expected return is June 2, Garcia's cracked leg
bone won't allow him to pitch until after the All-Star break, if
then. He has to go through virtually a second spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Even when both return to form, the use for now of temporaries
Paul Abbott and Brett Tomko in the rotation puts a strain on an
unsettled bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get a few more innings from our starters,'' manager
Lou Piniella said. ``Our bullpen will wear down.''
</P>
<P>
   Which gets back to Henderson. No, he's not going to pitch. But
he does add an offensive weapon when the Mariners have no choice
but to cover the inevitable pitching stumbles with many crooked
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   During the homestand in the alleged pitchers' park, the Mariners
hit .337 and outscored the opposition 45-19. While Henderson was
around for only part of that fusillade, he represents the asset
unseen since Vince Coleman in 1995 _ a player who can get a run
when good pitching shuts down everything else.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners' primary leadoff hitters this season, Mike Cameron
and Mark McLemore, combined for the American League's worst batting
average (.190) and second-lowest on-base percentage (.305) out of
the opening slot.
</P>
<P>
   As long as Henderson contributes in the fashion of his first
weekend in Seattle, that problem is over. He'll cost them a little
in the outfield, but the price figures to be small for something so
long needed.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine if Griffey had gotten his way on one of the few
general-manager matters he was right about. Then again, as
Mariners, both would have wanted jersey No. 24, Henderson would
have out-talked and maybe out-homered him, the clubhouse would have
to be expanded to accommodate the egos ...
</P>
<P>
   Ah, never mind.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
