<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S GET BEST OF DEVIL RAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Although they were part of Saturday's storyline, Jose
Canseco and Arthur Rhodes took no significant part in the game
itself.
</P>
<P>
   The whims of baseball are such, however, that Canseco and
Rhodes, combatants in a baseball brawl on Saturday, were the
crucial matchup Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes won, striking out Canseco with two outs and the bases
loaded in the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   And that meant Seattle won. Rhodes, who also struck out Greg
Vaughn with the bases loaded before facing Canseco, preserved an
8-4 win as the Mariners ended a 5-1 homestand with a flourish by
beating Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes and Canseco tangled on Saturday in the wake of the Devil
Rays' Esteban Yan having thrown at Seattle's Mark McLemore.
</P>
<P>
   Canseco won that battle, remaining in the game while Rhodes was
ejected. A repeat victory by the Rays' DH could have been fatal for
the Mariners, but Rhodes made sure it didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes threw two fastballs, a slider, another fastball and then
came back with a slider on which Canseco basically had no chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the most pivotal parts of the game,'' shortstop
Alex Rodriguez said. ``He started it by striking out Vaughn, and
then came back and got Jose. And you could tell Jose wanted it. He
took swings that he hadn't taken earlier in the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``That 2-2 slider Arthur threw was just plain nasty.''
</P>
<P>
   It was more than Canseco could handle, coming as it did at 83
mph. The fastballs had been clocked at 96 and 97 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave me two fastballs to hit earlier in the count, and I
missed them both,'' Canseco said. ``I got not one but two fastballs
to hit and I fouled them both back.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a guy is throwing that hard and has that kind of slider,
if you miss two pitches you can hit, you're basically done.''
</P>
<P>
   The first quarter of the Mariners' season is basically done, and
41 games into 2000, Seattle has put together a team that's in first
place in the AL West. The M's are where they are because most days
someone, or several someones, has stepped up to take command.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday it was Rhodes. But it was also Edgar Martinez, who had
two hits, including his 13th homer. It was John Olerud, who had
four hits. It was Dan Wilson and Mike Cameron, who broke a 2-all
tie with back-to-back homers in the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like our position,'' Martinez said. ``And I like the way
we've been playing. What I like most is that we're playing very
consistent baseball. I can only remember one or two games where we
were out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost some games we should have won, sure. Everybody
does. But the thing is we're in there every day with an opportunity
to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle has matched its season high by getting to five games
over .500. Next up is a day-long flight Monday to Baltimore and the
start of a six-game road trip in Camden Yards. The Mariners also
play the Devil Rays in Tropicana Field next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Starting pitcher Aaron Sele, who won to improve to 4-2, was not
keen on analyzing the season to date.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to assess a season midway through it,'' Sele said.
``Instead, what you have to do is grind it out.''
</P>
<P>
   That grind-it-out philosophy came in handy for the Mariners
Sunday, with Sele having trouble getting comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Another leadoff homer by Rickey Henderson, the 77th of his
career, helped get Seattle to a 2-0 lead, but Sele gave those back
in the second inning. It wasn't until the fourth, when Wilson and
Cameron both went deep, that Seattle moved ahead for good.
</P>
<P>
   And the game wasn't Seattle's to own before a four-run sixth
inning was capped by Martinez's two-run homer. He's hit in 18 of
his last 19 games and is hitting .444 in May with eight homers and
26 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen Edgar hot, hitting for average or hot, hitting for
power,'' Rodriguez said. ``I've never seen him this hot, hitting
for power and for average.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez equated his current numbers _ 13 homers, 50 RBIs and a
.363 average _ to a similar quick bolt from the gate in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only year that the numbers have been anything like
this,'' Martinez said. ``Every time I make contact, it feels good.
Every contact is solid contact.''
</P>
<P>
   Solid contact put the Mariners in position to win the game.
Avoiding solid contact on Canseco's part was how they were going to
have to win it. And while Rhodes said there was no carryover from
Saturday's on-the-field brush with Canseco, the radar gun told a
different story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Except for maybe his first game with us in April, I haven't
seen Arthur throw the ball that hard,'' pitching coach Bryan Price
said. ``The most impressive thing to me is that he really does rise
to the situation. When the game is on the line, he's ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted Jose. He was upset about what happened Saturday. And
what he did was turn that negative energy into a positive result
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson went to the mound a couple of time with Canseco
representing the potential tying run in the seventh. With so much
riding on the game, the catcher didn't want to make any mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that situation, I want him to be 100 percent comfortable
with the pitch I call,'' Wilson said. ``We changed up our signs,
because that situation was the key to the whole entire game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only was his fastball hard, but the couple of sliders he
threw were very hard. You could tell he was reaching back. The best
thing about that was that when he reached back, he stayed right
there, driving the ball through the strike zone.''
</P>
<P>
   And driving the Mariners home winners.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
