<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICE TEAM YIELDS DULL HEADACHE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ They are so wholesome and effective, so full of
character and camaraderie, they are impossible to rip _ even when
they blow a close one, and even when they lose two straight to the
Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   These first-place Red Sox are killing me.
</P>
<P>
   They were down, 7-0, in the sixth inning Sunday. Did they quit?
Of course not. They put the tying run on second base in the eighth
inning of a 7-5 loss.
</P>
<P>
   It's not like the old days when selfish Sox players pointed
fingers, ripped teammates, made the police blotter, and threatened
reporters. Remember Roger Clemens tearing into Wade Boggs after
Boggsie got an official scorer to erase a Boggs error and inflate
Clemens's ERA? Remember flipped SUVs, Mo Vaughn blasting Dan
Duquette, a chorus line of drunks in the manager's office, and the
days of 25 players, 25 cabs?
</P>
<P>
   Those days are gone. These Red Sox of the new millennium are 25
John Boy Waltons, golly-gee characters from a young-reader novel by
John R. Tunis. They hustle, they scrap, they give the dedicated Sox
fans a bang for the buck. Every day.
</P>
<P>
   It's big news if they lose, no news when they win.
</P>
<P>
   The Sons of Jimy Williams are the 25 Musketeers, one for all and
all for one. Nomar Garciaparra refuses to talk about his stats.
Darren Lewis won't gripe about losing his starting job to Carl
Everett. Jeff Frye helps Jose Offerman. John Valentin helps Wilton
Veras. Scott Hatteberg helps Jason Varitek. Pedro Martinez helps
little old ladies carry grocery bags that are too heavy. These guys
have all the edge of a Neil Diamond song.
</P>
<P>
   Ownership takes some well-deserved pounding over its quest for
taxpayer help to build a new park, but discouraging words are never
uttered in the Sox clubhouse. On Saturday the Townies lost, 2-1,
because of twin-kill baserunning blunders by Brian Daubach and Trot
Nixon. None of the players assigned blame to teammates. Sunday
Ramon Martinez was routed early, but no one is worried. Sox fans
now operate with the confidence that there'll be a Bret Saberhagen
or a Pete Schourek to fill the gap if someone breaks down. The team
just went 6-1 on a trip that ended with Garciaparra, Everett, and
Varitek on the shelf.
</P>
<P>
   These guys are deadly for nitwit radio. The most controversial
Red Sox topic for the talk jocks recently was . . . Andy Sheets or
Manny Alexander? Nothing like good 25th-man-on-the-roster talk,
right guys?
</P>
<P>
   After Sunday's loss, the cameras invaded manager Williams's
office, and one of the talking heads asked about the rarity of the
Red Sox losing a series.
</P>
<P>
   Returning fire with a chuckle and a shrug, a smiling Williams
said, ``Losing series? Ah, Boston. You guys are beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   These days it's just about impossible to suck the Sox into
controversy. They have become the model organization in all of
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   It starts at the top. Much as I hate to give credit to general
manager Duquette, let's look at what His Arrogance has done. He
lost Clemens and Vaughn and made the Sox better. He got Pedro and
Nomar for (relatively) short dough and locked them up for the prime
of their careers. He went to the salvage yard and found good
starting pitchers. He got the Pirates to pay 90 percent of
Schourek's salary. He stole Everett from Houston. He assembled a
roster of few stars and multiple role players. He's allegedly
putting together a good farm system. He's made the Red Sox the
blueprint for overachievement and clubhouse calm.
</P>
<P>
   Boston has the lowest earned run average in the majors. Pitching
coach Joe Kerrigan, a.k.a. the Nutty Professor, has become a mound
MENSA without peer. Williams is a sandlot savant _ Sunday Frye
pinch hits for Nixon, who is batting .331, and cracks a single and
double _ who says little but makes the guys want to play for him.
Boston's bench is stocked with hungry hearts ready and able to help
when needed.
</P>
<P>
   Here in the Hub, the Sox are the feel-good movie of the summer.
Ridicule is heaped on the Celtics and Bruins, and the Patriots claw
to regain respectability, but the Sox have become the Team of the
People. They consistently play the game the way it is supposed to
be played, even when they lose. They don't get too high or too low.
Physically and mentally, they are built for the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to stay that way the best we can,'' said Williams.
``Saturday we were in the game from the first pitch. Today we were
back in the game and that's all you can ask when you're down,
7-0.''
</P>
<P>
   Players and managers from other teams rave about the Red Sox.
The national media fawns all over Boston's nine. The Red Sox could
reach the playoffs for the third time in three years. They are one
game ahead of the Yankees and they have not been blown out in a
while. They're in New York this weekend and the Apple will be agog
_ trying to figure out how Boston is able to keep up with New York
with what appears to be an inferior roster.
</P>
<P>
   I can't figure it out myself. I tell ya, these guys are killing
me.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
