<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1889 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-TIGERS-BOS     05-22 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-TIGERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX FINALLY TAMED BY TIGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Don't panic, Red Sox fans. Pedro's pitching Tuesday
night against the Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   Not that anyone in the Red Sox clubhouse was worried after a
second straight loss to the lowly Tigers, who came into Fenway for
a weekend series with the worst record in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's 7-5 teaser of a loss ended a string of six series the
Red Sox had won, dating back to a set in Cleveland April 28-30.
</P>
<P>
   In a frustrating afternoon for the sellout Fenway faithful of
31,893, the Red Sox fell behind, 7-0, early as starter Ramon
Martinez showed more rust than resiliency after his mini-vacation
resting a pulled hamstring. And their comeback attempt fell short
as they left 11 runners stranded.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox were a miserable 4 of 24 with runners in scoring
position in the series, 2 of 12 Sunday, which was the main reason
they lost two of three to the Tigers, including a 2-1 decision
Saturday in which shaky baserunning also proved costly.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jimy Williams, not surprisingly, downplayed leaving all
those runners on when his team was chipping away at the big lead
the Tigers and starter Hideo Nomo had built after the first three
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were in scoring position,'' said Williams. ``The right
guys got on. We can't do it every time.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was chased after 2 1/3 innings in which he gave up six
hits and allowed seven earned runs on a series of bloop hits.
``They had good aim,'' joked Williams. But the Sox slowly came
back.
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Mike Stanley started it by hitting his eighth home
run of the year (five off Tigers pitching) with one out in the
sixth. A single to right by Carl Everett caused Detroit manager
Phil Garner to go to his bullpen quickly.
</P>
<P>
   It started a series of moves and counter-moves that brought in
seven Tigers pitchers, who threw 195 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   It was Stanley who also ended the Red Sox' comeback in the
bottom of the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   By then, the Detroit lead was down to 7-5, with Donnie Sadler on
third and Jeff Frye on second with two out and Stanley at the plate
representing the go-ahead run.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley said he was looking only to make contact. ``All I wanted
to do was tie the game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Tigers pitcher Doug Brocail was worried about more than that
as he threw pitch after pitch that Stanley fought off. Brocail also
was conscious of Stanley's ability to determine what type of pitch
was coming before it was delivered.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's given me some of the toughest at-bats,'' said Brocail,
who was so paranoid about facing Stanley that he used different
grips and disguised his delivery as best he could.
</P>
<P>
   This time it worked as Brocail slipped a curveball on the inside
corner past Stanley that was good for an inning-ending strikeout.
``He just froze me,'' said Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I threw him a fastball that he hits out of the stadium, we
lose,'' said Brocail.
</P>
<P>
   This time the Red Sox lost. Stanley said it was just part of the
game. ``We're still just as good as anybody in the league,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of the game. Sometimes things go that way. We'll
take the day off (Monday) and come back and start again, ready to
play.''
</P>
<P>
   With Pedro Martinez pitching, the Red Sox will be more than
ready. Over the last two seasons, Martinez has a 13-2 record in
starts following Boston losses.
</P>
<P>
   Williams just smiled when asked if a Pedro start on the horizon
gave him a sense of comfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth, I didn't even think of that,'' he said.
``I just know we have an off day. Certainly Pedro is a fine young
pitcher. But we have a lot of them.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, was pure Williams. What happened over the
weekend was not the way the Red Sox want the rest of the season to
play out, especially with their first encounter of the season with
the Yankees in New York this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But losing a series every once in a while is acceptable as long
as the confidence level remains high, which Williams says is the
case. ``The fire is still right in the clubhouse,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Yesterday &LR;  just temporarily doused the flames.
</P>
</TEXT>
