<SLUG> BC-GLASS-CEILING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTINE VENDEL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Labor official talks about paycheck inequity  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Full-time working women had to work all of
1999 and until May 11 of this year to make the same median wage men
did in 1999, according to the U.S. Department of Labor.
</P>
<P>
   Rose Kemp, regional administrator of the department's Women's
Bureau, talked about Equal Pay Day (May 11) and issues facing
working women at a public forum Sunday at All Souls Unitarian
Universalist Church in Kansas City. About 30 persons attended the
event, titled ``Lifting the Glass Ceiling.''
</P>
<P>
   Kemp said the public should be aware of the pay gap that exists
between men's and women's wages. She said women in 1999 earned only
76.5 percent of men's median weekly earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pay gap is very real,'' she said. ``With so many women as
heads of households now, it's even more important to address this
discrepancy.''
</P>
<P>
   Kemp said pay inequities translate into a pension inequities for
older women.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no wonder the poverty rate among older women is so
great,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kemp said one obstacle to equal pay is lack of information about
salaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employees are told that people aren't supposed to discuss
salaries,'' she said. ``But there is nothing illegal about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kemp also invited employers to evaluate their pay structures to
check for discrepancies that can't be explained by legitimate,
nondiscriminatory factors.
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy A. Witherspoon, a process development specialist at the
bureau, also spoke at the forum about child labor abuse nationwide
and worldwide. She detailed federal child labor laws and encouraged
people to know the laws.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 0034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000522.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 00:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1891 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-BOS &LR;      05-22 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS BEAT HEAT IN MIAMI, AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Memo to the Miami Heat: The Knicks are better. Deal with
it.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, Miami. You can slice, dice, dissect, analyze, and
otherwise ponder just exactly how these big games turn out the way
they do, but when all the scrutinizing is done the fact is that in
each of the last three years the New York Knicks have gone into
your house and walked off with the victory that advances them, and
not you, into the next round of the Eastern Conference playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The 65th lead change in this seven-game series was the ultimate
difference in the latest installment of basketball's fiercest
rivalry. Trailing, 82-81, with 1:32 remaining following a
straightaway Tim Hardaway 3-pointer, New York regained the lead 12
seconds later when an Alonzo Mourning gamble failed and Patrick
Ewing converted a Larry Johnson entry pass for a dunk. Neither team
would score again, and thus New York's 83-82 victory sends it into
the Eastern Conference finals that begin Tuesday night at Indiana's
Conseco Field House.
</P>
<P>
   It will be a very, very painful offseason for the Heat, who
couldn't hold an 18-point lead in Game 6, who led this one by 6
(79-73) with 4:44 remaining, and who scored just two Hardaway field
goals in the final 7:01. ``There's not much more we can learn from
it,'' sighed Heat coach Pat Riley, who had a lot to say about the
officiating of Dick Bavetta, Danny Crawford, and Bennett Salvatore.
``We've been here before.''
</P>
<P>
   The Riley view is that there were too many ticky-tack fouls
called, especially in the last five minutes of the game. New York,
the road team, was 28 for 31 from the line. ``I've been around 30
years, and I've been coaching for 18, and I've never seen a playoff
game determined by so many fouls out on the floor, not shooting
fouls,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. But Riley and his staff would be poring over Pacers
tapes right now if his team had submitted a professional
performance when it did get to the line. Yes, the Knicks were great
from the stripe. But the Heat were a dismal 11 for 21. In such an
instance, it's probably better not to whine about the officiating.
</P>
<P>
   It was a game, to borrow one of Riley's old LA expressions, of
``skirmishes.'' Miami led by 11 (25-14) early, as Mourning (29
points, 13 rebounds, 5 blocks) got off to a spirited start. A great
performance by both Latrell Sprewell (20 of his 24 in the first
half) and the New York bench sparked a 29-14 second quarter and a
6-point (45-39) halftime lead. Trailing, 49-42, the Heat responded
with a 14-4 run, at which point New York made its own little charge
and thus the teams entered the final 12 minutes of a four-year,
24-game war tied at 65.
</P>
<P>
   Before crying about the officials, Miami should review the
fourth-quarter tape and ask itself where it would have been had
there not been three (3) 24-second violations. And with his team
up, 79-73, with the ball, Mourning might re-consider his decision
to take a corner fallaway while guarded by Johnson instead of
taking it to the hoop. That miss turned out to be doubly disastrous
when P.J. Brown fouled Chris Childs on the rebound and Childs made
both free throws.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Childs. Talk about seizing the moment. Guess who scored
the first 10 New York points of the fourth period? Childs. Guess
whose steal and conventional fast-break 3-point play at a juncture
(71-65, Heat) when Miami had momentum was, according to Knicks
coach Jeff Van Gundy, ``critical, because we were teetering?''
Childs. ``It was the best pressure game of his career,'' said
assistant coach Brendan Malone.
</P>
<P>
   It all came down to this: New York by 1 and Miami in possession
with 12.4 seconds left. New York came out in its usual ABM (Anybody
But Mourning) swarming defense. The ball went from Zo to Jamal
Mashburn and then to sub forward Clarence Weatherspoon, whose shot
would determine Miami's fate. His 12-footer in the lane bounced off
the rim. Sprewell beat Dan Majerle to the bouncing ball and called
time with 2.1 seconds left. One timeout later, it was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're never surprised how a game goes,'' said Van Gundy.
``That it came down to the last possession was fitting.''
</P>
<P>
   Agreed. And when the same team wins the big one three years in a
row on the other guy's court, it's got the bragging rights. Next
time, Miami, make the free throws.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
