<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDIANAPOLIS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. JAMES, BOAT MAKE INDY FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
 500-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Against incredible odds, Lyn St. James and Billy
Boat combined to provide a bit of history and dash of bravado on
Bump Day, the second and final day of time trials that set the
33-car field for the 84th running of the Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   Both overcame seemingly insurmountable obstacles after crashing
their primary cars and jumping into backup cars belonging to other
drivers to make last-gasp qualifications in the final and frenzied
half-hour of Bump Day.
</P>
<P>
   Driving Stephan Gregoire's backup fielded by Dick Simon Racing
that had the engine cowling emblazoned with the words ``Yes She
Can!,'' the 53-year-old St. James became the oldest competitor and
second woman to earn a starting spot with a four-lap average of
218.826 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   Boat, meanwhile, qualified a new backup belonging to front-row
starter Eliseo Salazar. Fielded by Boat's former boss, A.J. Foyt,
the car had yet to turn a lap at the Speedway. And yet, with 46
seconds remaining before the final gun went off, Boat jumped into
the car and put it into next Sunday's show with a daring four-lap
run of 218.872 m.p.h.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was quite a day for me and my family,'' said a beaming
Boat. ``There's no place like Indy for the roller coaster of
emotions, and we experienced it all today.''
</P>
<P>
   St. James, who landed in the middle of Row 11 after failing to
qualify the last two years, joined 19-year-old Sarah Fisher, who
qualified on the outside of Row 7 Saturday, as the first two women
to compete in the same race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope women around the country know that you can do this and
that there's more coming,'' said St. James, who created a
foundation in her name to help promote women in racing. ``This is
not a male-dominated sport.''
</P>
<P>
   After tearing up her primary car Saturday ``on a big hit that
certainly put a dent in our program,'' St. James was asked if she
felt any additional pressure to make the field, especially after
Fisher had qualified.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not at all,'' she said. ``I just wanted to be in the race.
I was proud of Sarah and I cheered her when she went down pit road
on her attempt, but, no, I was feeling the pressure I had put on
myself to get into the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just elated to be in the field,'' she added, ``because I
know what it feels like to be bumped and I'm just glad to be back
in it.''
</P>
<P>
   So was Boat.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Boat was sitting pretty on the pole as Foyt's
driver, but Sunday the 34-year-old native of Phoenix was left
scrambling for a ride. He waved off his initial qualifying attempt
Saturday, crashed his primary car fielded by Team Pelfrey on his
second attempt early Sunday, and was left knocking on the garage
door of his former car owner in Gasoline Alley when another ride
fell through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think a lot of Billy,'' said Foyt, who had an
amicable parting of the ways last season after campaigning Boat for
three years on the Indy Racing League circuit. ``I've got a lot of
respect for him and I came here ready to run just two cars, but
when I saw a friend of mine who was in trouble, I just wanted to
help. It was just one way I try to pay back all those people who
have helped me.''
</P>
<P>
   With fewer than 3 1/2 hours left before the end of Bump Day,
Foyt put Boat in a car that Roberto Guerrero had failed to qualify
in two attempts. Boat put together two solid laps before his third
was hampered by a short on the electronic dash that caused the car
to slow from 219 to 150 m.p.h.
</P>
<P>
   Boat became the 31st qualifier when he brought the car home with
a last lap of 198.724 m.p.h., good for a spot with a four-lap
average of 192.105.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
