<SLUG> BC-PAC-10-TRACK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON'S HOOKER SPRINTS TO PAC-10 DOUBLE VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUGENE, Ore. _ Ja'Warren Hooker is in a zone. Or a groove. Or a
rhythm. Or whatever you call it when an athlete seems to transcend
his competition and is running basically against himself and the
clock.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Washington junior sprinter came into the
Pacific-10 Conference track and field championships expected to do
big things, and came up even bigger in the two-day meet by winning
the 100- and 200-meter dashes and leading the Huskies to a
surprising third-place finish in the 4x100 relay.
</P>
<P>
   Hooker's time in the 100 Sunday night was 10.19 seconds. Half an
hour later, he won the 200 in 20.39.
</P>
<P>
   He has run faster, but rarely with such ease and powerful grace.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you run easy, you usually run better,'' Hooker said after
finishing his impressive weekend by running a devastating second
leg on the Huskies' 4x400 relay. ``When you try to run hard, you
usually don't run as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Hooker, an eight-time state high school champion while at
Ellensburg High School, has been making everything look easy.
</P>
<P>
   In the past three weeks, he has lowered his own school record in
the 200 meters, broken the UW record in the 400 and doubled at the
conference meet _ winning the same sprint titles he did as a
freshman two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   What's next?
</P>
<P>
   Hooker will run the 100 and 200 at the NCAA championships in two
weeks in Durham, N.C. The plan is to then switch the focus to the
200 and 400 for the U.S. Olympic Trials in July in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   But looking too far ahead is taking too much away from what
Hooker accomplished at Hayward Field the past two days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not peaking yet,'' Hooker said. ``I think my training is
just kind of picking up and everything is going in the right
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Hooker's sprint double and a victory in the shot put by Ben
Lindsey gave the Huskies 30 of their 83 points as they finished
tied for fourth with UCLA in the team competition.
</P>
<P>
   USC defended its men's title with 154 points and UCLA won its
fourth consecutive women's championship with 167{ points. The
Washington State women were fourth and the Washington women
finished seventh.
</P>
<P>
   But no individual performer in this meet was more impressive
than Hooker, who simply did what he was expected to do and
expecting to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the thing,'' he said, ``you want to make it look easy.
It's not supposed to look hard.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 100, Hooker again had only a so-so start, coming out of
the blocks a blink behind the Arizona State duo of Dwight Phillips,
the Pac-10 leader this spring who was on Hooker's right; and Marcus
Brunson, who had the conference's third fastest time and was on
Hooker's left.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, however, it was Hooker's second, third and fourth
steps that provided the impetus he needed to surge away from the
pack 20 meters in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, who had run 10.11, was second in 10.30 and Brunson
finished third in 10.32.
</P>
<P>
   ``My start is generally not that great,'' said Hooker, who was
even slower out of the blocks in the prelims Saturday but still
managed to run the day's best time (10.20). ``My two, three, four
step is usually the key to my race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy to have it done.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hooker wasn't done. There was still the 200 to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in lane 4, Hooker had made up the stagger on USC's
Andre Ammons in lane 5 by the time they emerged from the turn. That
was basically the race, as Hooker seemed to glide to the finish
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going for a special time, I was just trying to go out
and run a special race,'' Hooker said.
</P>
<P>
   In the 4x100 relay, Hooker was moved into the lead-off leg and
put the Huskies in front with an opening 100 meters that was as
graceful as it was powerful. The Huskies hung on to finish third,
after entering the meet with the conference's seventh-best time.
</P>
<P>
   In the 4x400 relay, Hooker was fourth and 20 meters behind
UCLA's Tom Jonsson when he got the baton for his second leg. He
passed two other runners down the back stretch and pulled ahead of
Jonsson just before making his pass to Greg Forni. Despite Hooker's
45.9-second leg, the Huskies faded to fifth.
</P>
<P>
   It was a bit of sweet revenge for Hooker. After becoming the
first UW athlete to win two events at the Pac-10 meet two years
ago, Hooker struggled because of a stress fracture in his left shin
last year _ when he finished fourth in the 100 and third in the 200
at the conference meet and didn't even compete at the NCAA meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels good after being out last year,'' Hooker said. ``A
lot of people forgot about me. To come back and run well at Oregon
and at the conference meet, it's a good feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Clare Farnsworth can be reached at 206-448-8016
</P>
<P>
   or clarefarnsworth &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 0044EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
