<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION HAVE EXCELLENT FOOTHOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Revolution have a right to celebrate
Monday. This is the one-month anniversary of their elevation into
first place in the Eastern Division, a position they retained with
a 1-0 victory at Chicago Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   On April 22, the Revolution salvaged a 1-1 tie with the Fire on
a frigid night at Foxboro Stadium to creep into the division lead.
They since have lost only once, and have 16 points in 11 games,
tied with Miami for the lead in the division and fourth place among
the 12 Major League Soccer teams. Both Miami and the Revolution
have capitalized on the demise of D.C. United, which fell to 2-9-1
with a 2-1 loss at Los Angeles Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   One-third of the way into the season, the Revolution are on pace
to break their record of 37 points, earned in 1997. They have been
on similar paces in the past, including last season, but collapsed
after a facing adversity.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Revolution were on course for the playoffs when
they were hammered by Los Angeles, 5-2, July 11, then experienced a
disastrous second half. But this Revolution squad might not be as
fragile.
</P>
<P>
   It recovered from a 4-3 loss to Colorado last Wednesday with a
concise and pragmatic performance against Chicago. Many of the
costly mistakes _ the lack of concentration, the failure to find
skill players in the final minutes _ were eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   The Fire became frustrated and, lacking their two best players,
Lubos Kubik (knee) and Hristo Stoitchkov (groin), lost direction.
Meanwhile, the Revolution remained faithful to their game plan,
which was based more on stamping out the Fire's attack than
creating their own. This was a valid strategy, since the Revolution
were under no obligation to attack as the visiting team, and
because their forwards were providing only a minimal threat.
</P>
<P>
   The goal resulted from a dead-ball situation as Wolde Harris
headed in a Mauricio Ramos corner kick. The winning strike in three
of the Revolution's four victories has been off a restart, as have
10 of their 17 goals.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos has been effective off set pieces with accurate and
powerful left-footed drives. This is a weapon the Revolution's
creative players should be able to continue to thrive on. William
Sunsing is adept at drawing fouls in dangerous positions, and
Johnny Torres is improving in this respect.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution don't have to rely only on Ramos to take free
kicks. Imad Baba and Harris have scored on direct kicks this
season, and John Harkes and Ivan McKinley are also effective.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, the Revolution seem to be finding a balance.
They performed without three of their most proven players _ Leonel
Alvarez (left ankle sprain), Dan Calichman (groin), and Harkes
(calf) _ but appeared poised and purposeful against Chicago. At the
end, there were six Revolution players on the field age 24 or less.
And coach Fernando Clavijo appears willing to continue to give the
youngsters a chance as the Revolution prepare to host Los Angeles
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good mix of veteran and young players on the field,
and you need that,'' said Mike Burns, who moved from defense into
midfield. ``In the past, we might have given up a late goal and
lost a game like this.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Benfica, which finished in third place in Portugal this year,
will meet Colombia's national team in the second game of
Wednesday's doubleheader at Foxboro Stadium. Benfica tied AS Roma,
1-1, in an exhibition before more than 29,000 at Giants Stadium
Saturday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
