<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-R.MARTINEZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ HAUNTED BY BLOOPER SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The pitching line came straight from a slaughterhouse
butcher block: 2 1/3 innings, 6 hits, 7 runs, all earned.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was as revealing as a Jimy Williams press
conference: brimming with evasion, devoid of useful information.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Martinez, author of those numbers, was beaten by the
Detroit Tigers, who outlasted the Red Sox, 7-5, Sunday at Fenway
Park. But he wasn't exactly battered by the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   Making his first start in 11 days because of a balky left
hamstring, Martinez was undone by wretched location. Where he
placed his pitches wasn't his problem; where the Tigers sent them
was.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had some breaks,'' said Martinez's catcher, Jason
Varitek. ``Some balls fell in.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Jefferies, the first batter Martinez faced on this raw
autumn afternoon that somehow wandered into May, set the elusive
tone when he gift-wrapped a 2-1 pitch around the Pesky Pole in
right field for a 300-foot home run.
</P>
<P>
   And the unlikely hits just kept on coming.
</P>
<P>
   In the second, Dean Palmer opened with a double that skipped
over the first-base bag and caromed off the right-field grandstand;
cue shots have been struck with greater vigor in the billiards
parlor down the block on Brookline Avenue. Palmer went to third on
a grounder to second and made it 2-0 on Jose Macias's single to
left, perhaps Detroit's only bona fide hit off Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was similarly blessed in the third, his farewell
inning. Brad Ausmus launched his demise with a grounder into the
hole between shortstop and third; after racing to his right to
snare the ball, shortstop Donnie Sadler tried to get the Detroit
catcher with a jump shot to first that wound up in the Boston
dugout as Ausmus settled in at second. Rich Becker advanced him to
third with a bloop single to left, and Juan Gonzalez made it 3-0
with a check-swing double into the gap in right-center. These were
shaving nicks, not gouges. But two walks and a fielder's choice
later, the bases were loaded, the Tigers were up, 4-0, and Martinez
was getting a conciliatory sendoff from Williams. The manager waved
in John Wasdin, who finished the five-run inning by allowing the
baserunners to score, though all the damage was charged to
Martinez's account.
</P>
<P>
   The righthander's stint on the mound was a marathon compared to
his postgame stay in the clubhouse. He had vanished within minutes
of the final out in order to meet his family. But he relayed an
apology to the curious media and offered a brief analysis of his
performance via Red Sox spokesman Kevin Shea: ``My location was out
of focus a little bit. The hammy didn't bother me. The cold didn't
bother me. The extra days (between starts) got me off my rhythm. I
was just out of the zone with my pitches. That was it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, rust seemed to hurt Martinez more than the Tiger bats.
He readily acknowledges that he is a slave to routine, and his
regimen was disrupted beyond repair after May 10, when the
hamstring betrayed him in a five-inning, three-hit shutout effort
that propelled the Red Sox to a 5-3 Fenway victory over the Chicago
White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   As a precaution, Williams kept him in ice packs for his
scheduled start last week, and the layoff was reflected in Sunday's
25-32 ball-strike ratio.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a repetition guy,'' said pitching coach Joe Kerrigan.
``He needs his side (work) and his start every fifth or sixth
day.''
</P>
<P>
   But both Williams (``Ramon threw the ball good'') and Varitek
(``He looked pretty strong'') offered critical endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   And Varitek anticipates brighter prospects for Martinez during
the weekend's Armageddon against the Yankees in New York: ``I don't
expect him to give up seven the next time he throws.''
</P>
<P>
   Assuming he can remove misfortune from his repertoire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 0047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
