u v PM-BUDGET-NYT     05-22 2148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For MONDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Monday, May 22.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-STUDENTS (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ A student movement
demanding sweeping political change is surging in popularity and is
now a significant target for attack by the government of Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic. The movement, called Otpor, or
Resistance, has given fresh energy, insouciance and an arrogant
innocence to Milosevic's political opposition, which has had
difficulty preserving its unity and its credibility over the last
few years. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CHINA (Washington) _ For seven years now, very little
has gone as planned in Bill Clinton's effort to shape a new
relationship with China. The problem has not been lack of vision;
it has been one of execution. The Chinese have hardly cooperated,
jailing more dissidents even as Clinton argued that economic
freedom would eventually produce political freedom. Nor has there
been much help from the president's fellow Democrats, most of whom
have fought his trade and China policies at every turn. And Clinton
himself tells close colleagues he has let political calculations
lead him into major mistakes in dealing with China. By David E.
Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-PUTIN (Moscow) _ It turns out that the most momentous act
of Vladimir Putin's first days as Russia's elected president has
not been his choice of a cabinet, or the internal debate over a
sweeping economic restructuring plan, or even the approval of two
nuclear-arms treaties. Rather, it is Putin's launch last week of a
swift and stunning crusade to gut the power and political influence
of Russia's 89 governors _ and not coincidentally, perhaps, to
enhance his own. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   NUCLEAR-ARMS (Undated) _ It took decades of international
pressure and weeks of intense negotiations, but when a month-long
conference of more than 185 nations ended at the United Nations
this weekend, the five original atomic powers had agreed for the
first time to the ``unequivocal'' elimination of nuclear arms. By
Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   ETHIOPIA-ERITREA-U.S. (Washington) _ President Clinton and a
trio of his aides took a special interest in trying to head off one
of the continent's biggest and costliest wars. But the
behind-the-scenes courting of the Ethiopian prime minister, Meles
Zenawi, and the Eritrean president, Isaias Afewerki, ended in
tatters 10 days ago when Ethiopia rolled into Eritrea with tanks
and artillery and launched trench warfare reminiscent of World War
I. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PRIESTS-RECRUIT (Undated) _ At a time when other dioceses
throughout the nation are struggling through a shortage of priests,
Edward M. Egan, the bishop of Bridgeport, soon to become New York's
next archbishop, has vigorously recruited men for the priesthood,
ordaining a higher proportion of priests than any other diocese in
the Northeast. The bishop's success weighed heavily in his
nomination to head the New York archdiocese, said one church
official involved in the highly secretive process. By Diana Jean
Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-CARTLAND (Undated) _ Barbara Cartland, whose outpouring of
more than 700 romance novels during seven decades made her the
undisputed queen of a genre for hundreds of millions of readers the
world over, died Sunday at her home near Hatfield in Hertfordshire,
England. She was 98. By Richard Severo.
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE-CLOSING (Haverhill, Mass.) _ Bradford College, a small
liberal arts school that had been struggling to find a niche since
it became a four-year, coeducational institution a generation ago,
died Sunday after a bittersweet commencement ceremony that drew
hundreds of alumni from around the country. It was 197 years old.
By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   ASTHMA-TRACKING (Undated) _ As the number of asthma cases in the
United States rises sharply and researchers scramble to find the
cause, newly released data from the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention shows that a majority of states have no system to track
the number of people with asthma or monitor what happens to them,
and only a few states have any recent reports on the illness in
their jurisdictions. By Philip J. Hilts.
</P>
<P>
   CANCER-TREATMENT (New Orleans) _ The early promise of thalimode
as a treatment for cancer is holding up. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GORE-BIO (Undated) _ Part 1: A Boyhood Divided. Even the rawest
and most intimate moments in Al Gore's life are now widely seen as
mere theatrics, all part of a presidential campaign strategy
designed by his ambitious, up-from-nothing parents, Albert and
Pauline LaFon Gore, before he was born, and even unto death. A
special report. (Articles in this series will examine the lives of
the presidential candidates as the campaign progresses.) By Melinda
Henneberger.
