<P>
   GORE-DAD (Undated) _ Born poor in the remote settlement of
Possum Hollow, Tenn., Albert Arnold Gore lived through the worst of
the Depression and spent seven years working his way through
college. He always said he ran for office because as a kid he had
seen the picture of a cousin who was running for the state
Legislature on a utility pole and liked the idea of seeing his own
face up there. But he was also moved by ideas, and was a committed
free trader and New Dealer who believed that, as he said, ``nothing
cures poverty like money.'' By Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
