   BRASSAI-EXHIBIT (Paris) _ With the publication of his first
book, ``Paris de Nuit,'' in 1932, Brassai did more than win
immediate acclaim as a photographer. In what was already a much
photographed city, he created iconic images of nighttime Paris that
redefined how it was seen, almost as if darkness were its natural
condition. In the process he established an artistic trademark
that, if exploited, would have assured him a lifetime of fortune as
well as fame. Brassai, however, was something of a reluctant
photographer. A retrospective look at his work. By Alan Riding.
