<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-FRYE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THROWN INTO FIRE, FRYE PANS OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It's tough enough being a reserve and trying to stay
sharp, but even tougher when you're the object of some booing from
the home fans when you get a shot to produce.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened to Red Sox infielder/outfielder Jeff Frye
at Fenway Park Sunday when manager Jimy Williams sent the
righthanded hitter up for Trot Nixon against Tigers lefthanded
reliever Allen McDill.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon, one of Boston's hottest hitters, swings from the left
side and when Frye walked to the plate in the seventh inning, the
displeasure of some fans was audible.
</P>
<P>
   But Frye made Williams's move pay off, singling with two runners
on to load the bases in a three-run inning that closed the deficit
to 7-4. Then, after going to right field to replace Nixon, Frye
battled back from an 0-2 count against righthander Doug Brocail in
his next at-bat and doubled to the left-field corner, scoring John
Valentin with Boston's final run in the 7-5 loss.
</P>
<P>
   Frye, who entered batting .417 against lefties but only .129
against righties, hadn't had a pinch hit since the 1997 season when
he homered against Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Once Boston's starting second baseman, Frye now gets his playing
time behind Jose Offerman and wherever else Williams needs him,
mainly in the infield.
</P>
<P>
   There has been talk of the Red Sox shopping Frye to break the
roster logjam, but until a trade comes _ and it may not _ all he
can do is try to contribute when called upon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult,'' said Frye, who is 5 for his last 8.
``There's something wrong with you if you don't want to be an
everyday player. I try to stay sharp when I'm not getting the
at-bats and all I can do is come out, work hard, and try to be
prepared when I get the chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Replacing Nixon, who was batting .351 in his previous 10 games
and had made a great leaping catch to end the top of the seventh,
was, according to the manager, not based on Frye's average against
lefthanders.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was playing the percentages, Williams seemed a bit
miffed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Percentages, what percentages?'' said the manager. ``I don't
know about them percentages. Just play them all. These kids can
play. I believe in all of them. That's the most important thing,
whether they're successful or not. And if they come through, that
doesn't surprise me.''
</P>
<P>
   So Frye strode to the plate the innocent target of the fans'
displeasure with Williams's strategy, but soon he was standing on
first base with the cheers of the converts ringing in his ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew (Williams) had used me in that spot before,'' said
Frye, who is hitting .244. ``Jimy just pointed my way and said I
was going in for Trot.''
</P>
<P>
   But more impressive was the way he battled back against Brocail,
a pitcher who always has given him problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 0 and 2, I just didn't want to strike out,'' said Frye. ``I
didn't want to get beat chasing a slider. I had my mind set that
he'd have to get me out with his fastball. He gave me a good slider
that I fouled off and then I got a pitch to hit and hit it well.''
</P>
<P>
   Going to right field ``felt strange,'' he said. ``It's a
position I don't play a lot. It's definitely different. I've got a
lot more going on in the infield.''
</P>
<P>
   Come Tuesday against Toronto, Frye can only glance at the lineup
card to see if his recent success will translate into more playing
time. But he won't count on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an easy job,'' he said. ``Sometimes that's the way
the cards are dealt. All you can do is make the most of your
chances and be prepared. I know what the situation is here. I don't
expect to be the starting second baseman.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I can help, sometimes I don't,'' added Frye. ``But
you can't drive yourself crazy worrying about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
