<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROW-EASTERN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN, COLUMBIA TRIUPH 
</HEADLINE>
 SPRINTS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MONAHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ Lake Quinsigamond had a brown tint to it
Sunday &UR;  &LR; night. As in Brown University.
</P>
<P>
   The undefeated Bears lived up to their pre-regatta billing as
they captured the varsity heavyweight title in the 55th edition of
the Eastern Sprints under gloomy skies. It was Brown's fourth
Sprints win, the last coming in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears covered the 2,000-meter course in 5 minutes 43.18
seconds and displayed exceptional power over the last 300 meters.
Brown really poured it on, much to the delight of its hundreds of
fans. Princeton was second (5:44.99), Wisconsin third (5:46.21),
Harvard fourth (5:46.59), Dartmouth fifth (5:53.21), and
Northeastern sixth (5:53.44).
</P>
<P>
   The win also put Brown in a position to row at England's Henley
Regatta in July. ``Winning this makes Henley a strong
possibility,'' said coach Scott Roop.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's victory certainly wasn't a surprise because it entered
the event with a 6-0 record and was top-seeded among the heavies.
But Brown also made a statement that it will have a huge overall
say in future Sprints.
</P>
<P>
   Brown also was top-seeded in the second varsity and freshman
events and did well (first and third, respectively). Only two will
graduate from the varsity boat, so the future looks good.
</P>
<P>
   Brown doesn't have a varsity lightweight program, which was good
for the rest of the field, as fourth-seeded Columbia prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we were capable of winning here,'' said Roop. ``We
came here confident but certainly not cocky. We had to row a
perfect race and we did. You have to be perfect. One little mistake
could be very costly and opponents like Harvard, Princeton, and
Wisconsin could take advantage of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We rowed well. I'm very proud of my guys and hopefully we can
do as well at the IRAs in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our game plan was simple. Get out fast and stay there. The
guys did that. You can't approach the Sprints like a dual race.
There are always four or five other solid crews to worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown smashed its rivals during the regular season. The victims
were Syracuse by 5 lengths; Boston University by 10; Harvard by a
half-length after Brown relaxed during the final 200 meters;
Dartmouth by 4 lengths; Northeastern by 2; and Princeton by 2.
</P>
<P>
   The Harvard heavies won the Adams Cup under odd circumstances.
The Adams, contested annually among Harvard, Navy, and the
University of Pennsylvania, was canceled because of inclement
weather at Annapolis April 29. It was agreed that the boat that
finished highest in the Sprints would win the Cup. Penn and Navy
failed to qualify for the finals.
</P>
<P>
   Northeastern qualified for finals in varsity, JV, and freshmen
for the first time since 1981.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UFdots &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Columbia lightweight crew won its first varsity Eastern Sprints
crown by nipping top-seeded Yale and second-seeded Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia, seeded fourth, was a hair behind Yale after 1,500
meters, and the boats slugged it out inch by inch. The Lions posted
a photo-finish 5 minutes 52.48 seconds to the Eli's 5:52.59.
Harvard finished in 5:55.63.
</P>
<P>
   A Columbia gold medal is a rare commodity. The only other time
the Lions struck gold was in 1964 when they won a freshman
lightweight race.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia coach Tom Terhaar, in his fourth season, said, ``We
just took it 500 meters at a time. The guys really hung tough and
it was just a terrific race and effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Columbia dropped its first two races of the year to Rutgers and
Georgetown, narrowly lost to Yale, then beat Cornell, MIT, and
Dartmouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we were capable of winning,'' said Terhaar. ``It took
a super effort and we got it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
