<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BULLET' MAY CREATE EXPLOSIVE RIVALRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Could a heated rivalry develop between Red Bullet,
who won Saturday's Preakness at Pimlico, and Fusaichi Pegasus, who
won the Kentucky Derby and finished second in the Preakness?
</P>
<P>
   Neither side seemed very enthused Sunday about trying to reenact
Affirmed vs. Alydar or Sunday Silence vs. Easy Goer. Right now they
stand even, as Fusaichi Pegasus defeated Red Bullet in the Wood
Memorial at Aqueduct last month (Red Bullet did not run in the
Derby). There is a lot of politics involved in racing, and both
camps are trying to maneuver into position to gain the 3-year-old
championship, and, possibly, Horse of the Year. Whether they meet
again, and how often, is an open question.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Orseno, who trains Red Bullet, said it was only ``50-50''
that the Preakness winner would run in the Belmont Stakes June 10.
Neil Drysdale, who trains Fusaichi Pegasus, is pointing his charge
straight for the Belmont. However, Drysdale, who won't comment on
horses he doesn't train, refuses to even discuss the possibility of
a rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came back great, no nicks or anything,'' said Orseno, who
was basking in the glow of Red Bullet's victory of nearly 4 lengths
at odds of 6-1 ($14.40 to win), accomplished under Jerry Bailey.
``Right now, I'd say we're 50-50 to go in the Belmont. We'll
probably take a week to make a decision. We'll see how he comes out
of the race, weigh him to see if he lost any weight, and see how he
acts when he goes back to the track. A lot of factors will be
considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``After we make that decision, we'll take a longer look at what
races to consider as the season goes on. The Travers (at Saratoga
Aug. 26) would likely be one.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss by Fusaichi Pegasus, who was the prohibitive 3-10
favorite, cost him a chance to be the first Triple Crown winner
since Affirmed in 1978, and his connections a shot at a $5 million
bonus. The Derby winner no sooner crossed under the Pimlico finish
line when his rider and trainer blamed the wet track (officially
labeled as ``good,'' after going from ``sloppy'' to ``muddy''
earlier).
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we all had to run over it,'' said Orseno. ``The track
was similar when they ran in the Wood. I don't know if the horses
will be facing each other again this year. We'll see. Hopefully, we
can map this out, and do it the right way, so we can have a
3-year-old champion.''
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus will be shipped from Pimlico to Aqueduct
Monday. Drysdale intends to train him at the Big A for two weeks,
then van to Belmont Park for a final week of preparation for the
Belmont Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The horse is happy, and well,'' said Drysdale. When asked
about a rematch with Red Bullet, he said, ``I'm just looking
forward to running in the Belmont. I said prior to the Preakness
that Fusaichi Pegasus's style is very suitable to a mile and
one-half (the Belmont distance). When I said that, I didn't know
the Preakness would come up with a nasty track.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are 11 possible starters for the Belmont. Red Bullet,
Fusaichi Pegasus, and Impeachment, who finished third in the
Preakness and Derby, may all go in the Belmont. The others are
Aptitude, second in the Derby; Wheelaway, fifth in the Derby;
Tahkodah Hills, winner of the Lone Star Derby; Unshaded, winner of
the Lexington at Keeneland; Chief Seattle, a top 2-year-old last
year who has not run officially this year and is owned by Godolphin
Stable; Curule, seventh in the Derby and also owned by Godolphin;
Globalize, second in the Lexington, and Commendable, who has won
only a maiden race but would represent trainer D. Wayne Lukas.
</P>
</TEXT>
