<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVS-DRAFT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARK CUBAN WANTS NO MORE OF NBA DRAFT LOTTERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SECAUCUS, N.J. _ There were no fireworks for Mavericks owner
Mark Cuban in his first appearance at the NBA Draft Lottery
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks were slotted to pick No. 12 _ and with a
6-in-1,000 chance of winning the top pick _ they wound up with the
12th pick.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Cuban, wearing a pullover black shirt, gray slacks,
black shoes and a silver chain, was talking about steering clear of
the lottery from now on. He views the lottery as a place where
losers converge in search of being sprinkled with some magical dust
that may or may not turn their franchise into instant winners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me realize quite clearly that I don't want to be back
here ever again,'' said Cuban, the only person among the 11 men on
the dais without a suit and tie. ``It means we didn't make the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't ever want to have to worry about, `Am I going to get
the No. 1, or am I getting No. 12, or am I getting No. 13?' I just
want to say, `I experienced it, I was here, and hopefully I'll
never have to see this place again.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Was the lottery fun for Cuban?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said. ``You're here because it means you \Rdidn't
play well\S last year, to a certain extent. That's never fun.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the second time in team history that the Mavericks came
away with the 12th pick. In 1995, they used the 12th pick to draft
Duke forward Cherokee Parks.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban said since there's a dearth of talent in this year's draft
pool, he isn't against trading the pick. However, told that the Los
Angeles Lakers chose Kobe Bryant with the 13th pick of the 1996
draft, Cuban said he was well aware of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``That goes to show you that you just never know,'' Cuban said.
``But the short time that I've been in this league, I've realized
very quickly that there's no one thing to commit to.''
</P>
<P>
   The home-state New Jersey Nets won the lottery, overcoming a 4.4
percent chance of obtaining the top pick. Vancouver finished second
and the Los Angeles Clippers were third.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago and Orlando were the only teams with multiple lottery
picks. The Bulls got the fourth and seventh choices, and the Magic
will select fifth, 10th and 13th.
</P>
<P>
   After the lottery, Cuban and Nets owner Lewis Katz were hugging
and laughing. Cuban told Katz beforehand that the Nets were going
to win the lottery. Cuban said Katz was one of the owners who was
supportive while he was going through the ownership process a few
months ago, and he had a feeling that Katz's generosity was going
to pay off.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was there for me every step of the way,'' Cuban said. ``So
if it wasn't going to be us \Rwinning the lottery\S, I wanted it to
be him.''
</P>
<P>
   Katz was appreciative of Cuban, whom he refers to as ``a great
owner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What he's doing is bringing the fans back,'' Katz said. ``And
he's not afraid to be innovative, and not afraid to speak his mind.
And he's young enough that he's going to be the future of the
NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nets arena is about three miles from where the lottery was
held, and Katz was reminding everyone how the home court prevailed.
He also still has to hire a director of basketball operations and a
head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly the people that are going to come in and take over
this program are going to have a wonderful start and a wonderful
opportunity,'' Katz said. ``There's a lot of good stuff and a lot
of good talent out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The homecourt advantage clearly helped. Here we are in New
Jersey, and it finally worked for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban flew to New York on Friday from London, where he was
vacationing for nearly two weeks. He also used part of the overseas
journey to speak at the Cannes Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   But yesterday Cuban was speaking basketball, saying he was tired
of the Mavericks' 10-year absence from the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I'm trying to absorb all of this, because it's the
last time the Mavericks are going to be here,'' Cuban said. ``So I
just wanted to experience this, and good things will happen from
here.''
Charting No. 12 The Mavericks will have the No. 12 pick in the June
28 NBA Draft. Here are the past five No. 12 picks in the NBA Draft.
Year Player Team 1999 Alek Radojevic Toronto Raptors 1998 Michael
Doleac Orlando Magic 1997 Austin Croshere Indiana Pacers 1996
Vitaly Potapenko Cleveland Cavaliers 1995 Cherokee Parks Dallas
Mavericks
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
