<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1903 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-GLF-COCHRAN-COLUMN-TE     05-22 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-COCHRAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLONIAL HAS EARNED ITS SPOT AMONG THE ELITE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE COCHRAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ They joke endlessly about the splendidly
garish plaid jackets, the legendary lounge lizards, the killer
margaritas and a band called the Sons of the Beaches.
</P>
<P>
   They chuckle still about a millionaire murder suspect's dirty
movie.
</P>
<P>
   They recount with gusto the erratic golf shots and mercurial
golfers, the floods and fires and the time ABC's TV cameras
captured a couple cavorting in the woods on the back nine.
</P>
<P>
   Just three days ago, during Friday's rain delay, a leggy blonde
and her equally tipsy boyfriend got themselves locked in a torrid,
escalating and quite public embrace outside the press room. As it
started to get really exciting, a female cop arrived and broke it
up.
</P>
<P>
   All this is to say that Colonial has earned its longstanding
reputation for erotic merriment and its distinction as the dynamite
girl-watching stop on the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   But there were constant reminders all week about what really
makes this such a very special golfing event. In a nutshell, I
think it's history, Hogan, hospitality and, perhaps foremost, the
course itself.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Mickelson touched on this after Sunday's dramatic victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's really cool for me as a player is the feeling that I'm
now a part of the history of this tournament, part of the history
of the game and I'm now associated somewhat with these great
players from the past,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And to have that sense of being on the Champions' Wall on the
first tee is very rewarding as a player.''
</P>
<P>
   Although neither has won here, Tom Kite calls Colonial one of
his favorite places on earth and Curtis Strange insists it is one
of the great golf courses of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great championships, the great finishes and the great
champions make the tournament,'' Tom Watson, the winner here in
1998, once said. ``And Colonial is no different from the Masters in
that respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Maintained the late Payne Stewart: ``This is the standard by
which all golf courses should be built.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, you might reasonably wonder: Where's Tiger Woods,
Ernie Els, Hal Sutton, et al?
</P>
<P>
   But then there's Rocco Mediate, who, after firing rounds of 68
and 67, professed his longstanding affection for Colonial and its
Trinity River treachery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just love this golf course,'' he gushed. ``I could be
playing lousy and find some reason to play good around here. ...
I've always loved this golf
course.''
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because it allows you to play many, many different ways. It
doesn't say, `If you don't do this, you're (done).' ''
</P>
<P>
   Mediate revealed that Nos. 3, 4 and 5, the so-called ``Horrible
Horseshoe,'' are his favorite stretch of holes on the entire PGA
Tour. That would, by the way, include the famous Masters trio known
as Amen Corner.
</P>
<P>
   Olin Browne, the 1999 champion, said Colonial demonstrated a
typical touch of class with the subtle changes in the course since
his victory a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greens are so smooth that we would be hard pressed to find
better ones during the course of this year,'' he said. ``But
basically it's the same golf course that it was last year and the
year before and however long before that.''
</P>
<P>
   He expressed a common concern that most rebuilt courses suffer
in the transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm very pleased to see that these guys maintained the
integrity of the course,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mediate agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did a job on this redo that is second to none,'' he
volunteered. ``If the (PGA) Tour would send all the guys who want
to fix golf courses here, we might have a chance, because every
time they've tried to fix it, they've ruined it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think they could make this better, but ... they just
did a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Kraft, who wound up tied for sixth at 7-under 273, was
almost as effusive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really like playing here and that helps me to have a good
attitude,'' he said. ``This course is not all tricked up. It is a
straightforward golf course.''
</P>
<P>
   The trees and the doglegs dictate your shots, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is refreshing to come out here, to see some trees, some
doglegs, some sand,'' he added. ``That helps.''
</P>
<P>
   After Tuesday's Shootout, three or four of us sat down to chat
with Browne about his year as the defending champion. Hardly the
most illustrious name on Colonial's famous Wall of Champions, he is
in fact one of its most articulate, assertive and amiable winners.
</P>
<P>
   He said he and caddie Mike Harmon, whom everyone calls Stump,
made a memorable trip to the champion's wall on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played in the pro-am, and he asked me if my name was up on
the wall, and I said, `Yeah.' He wanted to go up and take a look,
so we went up there and there it was right next to Tom Watson,
truly one of the great players ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``So my name will live in infamy for however long.''
</P>
<P>
   Browne, who got hooked on golf as a student at Occidental
College in Los Angeles, has won only twice during 16 years on the
Tour. So don't blame him for being a bit gushy over Colonial and
don't harangue me for quoting him. I believe he captured the
essence of what makes Colonial so special for many of the players.
</P>
<P>
   What Browne said was not so much new as different.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are spooks running around here _ Ben Hogan's ghost _ and
there are so many great players who have played here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there are so many players who value this championship.
This tournament has such a rich history to it that I couldn't have
picked a better tournament I'd rather win.''
</P>
<P>
   I suspect if Browne wins a major, he might change his tune. But
it's a good point.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the most stylish tournaments,'' he continued.
``It's got that thread _ that connection to what really made this
game great. As time marches on, we're losing our connection to the
great history of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Browne said his friend Gardner Dickinson, a Colonial champion in
the Sixties, talked often of his experiences here and his
relationship with Hogan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played a lot of golf around the world and around this
country and he won a bunch of times, but Colonial was the
tournament that he spent his time talking about,'' Browne said.
``There's a special feeling _ it's an invitational, there's a small
field, it's an old-style golf course, it's where Hogan used to hang
his hat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Hogan's Alley. There's really nothing more to be said
about it.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
