<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1904 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BOX-TEXAS-BOXERS-TEX     05-22 1390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TEXAS-BOXERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETURN TO BOXING GLORY IS GORMAN'S PLAN FOR FORT WORTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH _ David Gorman is a nicotine addict born seemingly
with a fresh pack of smokes in his shirt pocket. He has read the
warnings, he has seen the danger. And he can barely wait to light
up.
</P>
<P>
   He has the same addiction to boxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can you say? It's just in his blood,'' said Gorman's
wife, Loretta. ``He's supposedly quit countless times, but
eventually he always finds his way back.''
</P>
<P>
   After six years of fist-free living, the patriarch of Fort Worth
boxing has climbed back into the ring. Gorman, who built countless
gyms and managed four world champions in the 1980s, is preparing to
re-establish Fort Worth as one of America's foremost Fight Towns.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to transform another wayward kid into the next Donald
Curry, Gene Hatcher, Stevie Cruz or Troy Dorsey, Gorman opened his
latest gym _ Gorman's Boxing Club _ at 3606 N. Main by Meacham
Field earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pumped to be back into it,'' Gorman said. ``I've made the
commitment to bring another world champion to Fort Worth. This time
I just can't afford to wait five or six years. I might not be
around that long to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of nurturing street-tough kids from their teens, Gorman
is now attempting to put the finishing shine on already polished
boxers. With the financial support of Dallas friends who have
helped him establish Gorman Sports Management, he has signed two
fighters (Robert Tubbs and Dan Batchelder), a female kick-boxer
from Holland, and is looking at new fighters each week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tubbs has a real chance to be another Donald Curry,'' Gorman
said of the Cincinnati fighter who is 12-0 with six amateur titles.
``He's a special talent.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the first steps, he said, will be relocating the fighters
to Fort Worth, the city he helped turn into Fight Town in the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried to stay as busy as a tick on a dog,'' said Gorman,
who pays his bills owning a masonry construction company. ``But I
keep getting the itch. I guess it will never go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorman said he turned down numerous similar offers in recent
years. But shortly before his son, Mike, passed away in November,
Gorman became convinced he needed to get back in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike told me to stop denying myself what I love to do,''
Gorman said. ``He told me to do what I do best: get a couple of
promising fighters and mold them into champs. In doing so I could
make some money and do some traveling. It all makes sense to me. He
was right.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorman has never been afraid to pick a fight.
</P>
<P>
   From the time he began training sons Mike and David Jr. on the
family's Joshua farm in 1970, Gorman has been seduced by the sport.
In '76, he started the Gorman Masonry Team in a gym on South
Hemphill Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work with boxers the same way I lay bricks,'' the
bespectacled Gorman said in his slow, gruff voice. ``You start with
work and desire, then you learn and listen. I try to make it a
family atmosphere, something you never found anywhere else in the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Loretta, ``These weren't boxers and fighters to David; they
were like his children.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gormans merged with trainer Paul Reyes in the late 1970s and
began holding wildly popular club fights, where amateurs would
bludgeon each other for $50 purses. At the same time, he and Reyes
discovered local talents like Curry, Hatcher, Cruz and Vincent
Releford Jr. on the toughest streets of Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really have a vision, just a desire to make it all
work,'' Gorman said. ``One day we looked up and realized we had
something pretty special on our hands. These kids just needed some
direction, and boxing gave it to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay was Titletown, Detroit was Hockeytown, and Fort Worth
suddenly was Fight Town.
</P>
<P>
   Often paying for fighter's meals out of his own pocket or giving
them rides to and from the gym, Gorman evolved into the Man Who
Would Never Be (Don) King. He opened a more spacious gym _ Gorman's
Super Pro's on South Main _ heavy on guts, void of glitz.
</P>
<P>
   In the gym on a given day in the early '80s were Curry, Hatcher
and Cruz, each world champions at one time under Gorman's guidance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the top gym in the country, even better than Kronk's in
Detroit,'' said longtime matchmaker Wayne Harrison, who set up the
bulk of Gorman's fights along with trainer ``Papa'' Joe Barrientes.
``When you saw David barking at some young fighter, you knew he was
a champion then or would be soon. It was the place to be and be
seen if you were into boxing. It put Fort Worth on the map.''
</P>
<P>
   Operating on a shoestring budget, Gorman molded tough men first,
then tough fighters. Living on combined income of $25,000, David
and Loretta taught their fighters a bob-and-weave survival on the
streets, and then how to box in everything from worn-out gyms to
the back of abandoned trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't always pretty,'' Gorman said. ``But it's the only
way I knew how to get my message across.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the world eventually heard Gorman's gospel loud and
clear.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting with Gorman's trademark grit, Hatcher won the World
Boxing Association junior welterweight title in 1984, Cruz the WBA
featherweight belt in June 1986 and Troy Dorsey the International
Boxing Federation featherweight title in June 1991. Curry, however,
was the thoroughbred of Gorman's stable.
</P>
<P>
   After years under Gorman's wing, Curry won what once was Sugar
Ray Leonard's belt as undisputed welterweight champ in December
1985. At the time, he was considered one of the five best fighters
in the world.
</P>
<P>
   But then, just as the Gormans were on the verge of multimillion
dollar paydays and Curry on the cusp of celebrity, the dynasty was
cold-cocked by a surprise upper cut.
</P>
<P>
   On March 10, 1986, Curry made a shocking announcement. He was
hiring Akbar Muhammad of Top Rank as his new manager and reducing
Gorman's role to training-camp coordinator. On the surface, it
meant a slice in payday percentage from 28 percent to 6 percent.
Deep down, however, it meant a proud man who had built his
reputation on loyalty was having one of his own turn his back on
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was devastating,'' Loretta Gorman said. ``We went to
pieces. The money was bad enough, but losing Donald was like losing
one of our children.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Gorman, ``For six months I could barely function as a human
being.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone but Curry seems to agree that the move to Muhammad was
disastrous.
</P>
<P>
   Arum said Curry could have been one of the top five fighters
all-time for Top Rank had he stayed with Gorman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He concocted these paranoid ideas that Gorman was kow-towing
to me,'' Arum said, ``that Gorman wasn't tough enough \Rin
negotiations\S. He had dreams of instant gratification and ended up
with nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That decision was a terrible mistake, one that cost us and
\RCurry\S literally millions of dollars,'' Gorman said. ``I still
hate to think about \RMuhammad\S, because he had Donald in all
these bad investments. Donald asked my advice, and I told him he
should keep the money he's making for the rest of his life. I got
outvoted, Donald wound up broke, and we ended up closing the gym.''
</P>
<P>
   Curry still defends Muhammad. ``I learned so much from him, I
really did,'' Curry said recently. ``Akbar was good for me, he
really was.''
</P>
<P>
   Living on a combined salary of $250,000 and salivating over
million-dollar paydays to come, the Gormans were suddenly knocked
to the canvas and forced to live on 1/10th as much. The South Main
Gym, the one with the ``Home of Donald Curry'' sign over the door,
closed under mounting debt a year after Curry's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the beginning of the end of the Fort Worth dynasty,''
Harrison said. ``You could feel the wind go out of the sails of the
boxing community.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorman has kicked the boxing habit numerous times, but it has
always rope-a-doped him back in. He is genuinely excited about his
next round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a dreamer. I'm not really a dreamer any more,'' Gorman
said. ``But I do know full well that I'm capable of doing as much
for a fighter as anyone in this area. And I know I'll be doing what
I love again.''
</P>
<P>
   Ring the bell, David Gorman has survived another eight-count.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 0104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
