r s BC-BOX-BOXING-CAMP-TEX     05-22 0397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING-CAMP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH TEXAS BOXERS 
CHAMP CAMP WAS BOOT CAMP FOR FORT WORTH BOXERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jimmy Johnson's asthma field.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hitchcock's doghouse.
</P>
<P>
   David Gorman's tough-love shack.
</P>
<P>
   On the Fort Worth-Dallas roll call of toughest places to live
and work, the mid-1980s brick farmhouse outside Granbury is at the
top. Welcome to Champ Camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those places that you hated at the time, but now
you realize you kinda loved it,'' former boxing champ Gene Hatcher
said. ``It was the perfect place to grow ornery.''
</P>
<P>
   The camp was the brainchild of manager David Gorman, who sought
a secluded, spartan refuge to train his world-class fighters in
1985. He borrowed the house from his daughter, Cindy, took eight
would-be boxers there, and returned with eight men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the best memories I have,'' Gorman said. ``I guess you
could say it was out of tough love. But I still believe in it as a
way to train and focus. Nowadays you have guys working out in
glitzy hotels with photographers all around. We had none of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Gorman provided his fighters with few options but to
hone their considerable skills. Up at 5:30 a.m. for breakfast, a
seven-mile jog on Tolar's dirt roads, followed by five hours of
training under 100-degree temperatures, under Gorman's watchful eye
and menacing bark. A similar routine followed in the afternoon, a
process Gorman was convinced would give his fighters a
``street-tough, survivalist mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   If the boxers weren't exhausted by sundown, they could play
cards, watch a 37-inch TV or dare to indulge some of Paul Reyes'
homemade hot sauce on paper plates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have a maid,'' chuckled Donald Curry. ``But if we
would've, she'd a been big and fat with no teeth. That was no place
for the beautiful people.''
</P>
<P>
   Some boxers slept outside at night, one even sun-bathed in the
nude, and none say they've ever experienced such intense male
bonding since.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, it wasn't that bad,'' Gorman joked. ``One time I cooked
them barbecue just to convince them it wasn't prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorman, now back in the boxing business, revealed he might even
reopen Champ Camp once he builds his next stable of fighters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have the key,'' he said. ``And a fighter can never be
too tough.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 0104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000522.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
