<SLUG> BC-GLF-COLONIAL-LOVE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND-PLACE FINISHES CAUSE LOVE FRUSTRATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHARLES CLINES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ For the second consecutive week, Davis Love
III played just good enough not to win. For someone who has said he
is ``obsessed'' with breaking a victory drought, Sunday's runner-up
finish at the MasterCard Colonial was another stab to the ego.
</P>
<P>
   Although not as gut-wrenching as last week's GTE Byron Nelson
Classic when he lost in a playoff to Jesper Parnevik after leading
each round, Love conceded his tie with Stewart Cink for second at
Colonial adds to his mounting frustration of not winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting tired of playing good golf, but not playing great
for four days. It's frustrating,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said, ``I played better this week (than last), but I
didn't get the ball in the hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Love is trying to end a victory drought that has stretched back
to the MCI Classic in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another frustration, but I did a better job the past two
weeks'' of being in contention, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he said key putts again didn't fall, key iron shots didn't
get close to the pins and too many drives strayed off line. Yet, he
has hopes that everything can straighten out by the time the U.S.
Open rolls around in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mainly, it's consistency,'' he said. ``I just need to play
consistent for four days.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, when he began the day in second place, three shots
behind leader Stewart Cink, Love said, ``I let it get away from me
in the middle of the round,'' and finished with a 2-under 68 and
270 total, two behind winner Phil Mickelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I missed a little (birdie) putt on No. 6, then I bogeyed No. 9
and didn't birdie (the par-5) 11th,'' he said of his squandered
chances. Then, on No. 10, Love couldn't match Cink's birdie and
fell four shots off Cink's pace while Mickelson was charging to a
closing 63.
</P>
<P>
   Love birdied the 14th, but couldn't get the ball close enough
the rest of the way to take advantage of Cink's collapse down the
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Early Sunday, Love tried to make a move with birdies on the
second and fourth holes. But Cink, his playing partner, birdied the
first, third and fourth and seemed to have an answer for anything
Love could throw at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I would have to play great and shoot a good score just
like Phil did'' Love said. Love expected someone to take advantage
of the sunny day that had little wind.
</P>
<P>
   He was close. But close isn't good enough for him. With 18
runner-up finishes, he been there too many times before.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
