<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-DEBATE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLFERS AT ODDS OVER MASTERS REQUIREMENTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHARLES CLINES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The PGA Tour Policy Board is scheduled to
meet Monday and Tuesday in Jacksonville, Fla., and the
controversial new rules the Masters implemented this year might get
some air time, board member John Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Masters will be an issue, I'm sure,'' Cook said of the
Masters' decision to not grant automatic berths into the tournament
for winners of PGA Tour events.
</P>
<P>
   If the issue is broached at the meetings, not everyone will be
in harmony with Cook, who wants the Masters to reconsider its new
rule. Davis Love III, Sunday's runner-up at the MasterCard Colonial
and also a board member, believes the issue shouldn't be on the
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the point,'' he said Sunday. ``We have no control of
the Masters. It's their tournament. It's not ours.''
</P>
<P>
   The controversy began when Masters Tournament officials changed
their qualifications and took away the automatic exemption for tour
winners.
</P>
<P>
   Now, part of the new qualifications include being in the top 50
of the World Rankings. Olin Browne, last year's MasterCard
Colonial's champ, was one of seven winners who didn't make it to
Augusta because he wasn't ranked high enough.
</P>
<P>
   Some players, including Cook, said Masters officials made a bad
decision and expects the policy to be discussed at the board
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (the rule change) is a tragedy,'' he said Sunday after
his round at Colonial.
</P>
<P>
   But Love isn't supporting Cook's side, and calls the critics of
the new rule ``malcontents.''
</P>
<P>
   Love said the PGA Tour has no business trying to change rules at
the Masters, the U.S. Open or the British Open, which aren't under
the wing of the tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``These aren't our tournaments. We don't make the rules there,''
Love said.
</P>
<P>
   He said it would be wrong for the PGA Tour to try to threaten or
cajole the Masters into submitting to its desires _ whatever they
might be.
</P>
<P>
   Cook, however, said, ``It's all about winning out here. Always
has been. And it doesn't matter what tournament or where; it's a
big deal to win out here. I certainly think a PGA Tour winner
deserves to be in the Masters more than the semifinalist of the
U.S. Amateur, and I'm not trying to do a disservice to the Amateur
semifinalist. But they (Masters officials) need to realize it's not
going to diminish their fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the big deals about winning out here was ``I can't wait
to get to Augusta,''' Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Cook said hinging qualifications on the World Rankings is
not a good system, ``because the World Rankings are screwy. You can
actually choose not to play in a tournament so that you can hold
your position (in the rankings).''
</P>
<P>
   Love defended the system, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I think it's easier now to get in the Masters than
it has ever been,'' he said. ``I'm fourth in the World Rankings,
but I haven't won a tournament in two years. So, obviously it's not
that hard to get in the Masters.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
