<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-AVALANCHE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELFOUR, HULL SAVE DAY AS STARS EVEN SERIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Don't ask the Stars to explain why they need to dig
themselves into a hole as inspiration to play well. They can't.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I don't know,'' Stars winger Brett Hull said. ``I think
that's just human nature, knowing your backs are against the wall,
you are in a must-win situation and it's almost like you have
nothing to lose. You are either going to be down 3-1 or you are
back in it at 2-2.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars were faced with exactly that situation in Game 4 after
digging themselves a pretty-massive hole in Game 3. They responded
with a 4-1 victory against the Colorado Avalanche at the Pepsi
Center on Sunday to knot the Western Conference Finals at 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   Don't look now, but the series just became a
best-two-out-of-three, and the Stars have home ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hats off to Belfour,'' Avs defenseman Aaron Miller said. ``He
played a great game.''
</P>
<P>
   You can't blame the Avs for fingering Stars goalie Ed Belfour as
the sole reason they lost. Of course, there were others. They
wasted 64 seconds of a five-on-three power play, getting only a
single shot. They allowed the Stars to score four goals on 15
shots, including two goals by Hull. The Avs were neither aggressive
nor physical enough.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they had 39 shots, including a 21-4 advantage in the
second period. They should've won right? Belfour wouldn't let them,
stopping all but one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's playing with a lot of confidence and gets stronger every
game,'' Stars backup goalie Manny Fernandez said. ``If a team is
going to beat him, they're going to have to hurry up and do it.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of play was given to Belfour's assertion that he felt
himself to be as good, if not better than Avalanche goalie Patrick.
</P>
<P>
   As good? Try better. At least in the past two games.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Avs forward Peter Forsberg, who had six shots,
including a couple of no-brainers, only to watch Belfour deny them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this is anything different for Eddie Belfour. He
has a huge bite in the series,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
``We got the win in this building that we badly needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock had been fuming after Game 3, annoyed that his team
had ``wasted'' an unbelievable performance by Belfour by playing
stupid, penalty-filled hockey.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't waste it Sunday. They knew they couldn't afford to.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we got down 3-1 to this team, it would be very difficult to
come back,'' Belfour said.
</P>
<P>
   Or as Stars winger Mike Keane so aptly said: ``It's just not
wise to put yourself in a situation where you have to win three in
a row against these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Stars did anything and everything Sunday to prevent it.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock changed up their lines. All of them, including taking
Brenden Morrow right from the training room with what everybody
thought was a season-ending fractured right ankle in Game 1 to the
first line with Hull and Mike Modano.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was big surprise,'' Hull said of Morrow's return, ``but as
long as Big 9 is there, I don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   The line was on the ice for the Stars' final three goals,
including what turned out to be the game-winner by Hull at 17:30 of
the first period for a 2-0 Stars lead.
</P>
<P>
   He added another goal at 7:52 of the second period to give the
Stars breathing room after Avs forward Dave Reid's goal had sliced
Dallas' lead to 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Hull and Modano then assisted on defenseman Richard Matvichuk's
game-sealing goal at 4:39 of the third period.
</P>
<P>
   And, just like that, Game 3 became a distant memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been very consistent in the past at answering back,''
Modano said. ``We rally around it and learn from it, but don't
dwell on it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars certainly learned from the first three games of the
series. They finally scored first.
</P>
<P>
   Stars center Joe Nieuwendyk scored a power-play goal at 7:12 of
the first period, finishing a beautiful feed from Jamie
Langenbrunner and Scott Thornton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been tough sledding,'' Nieuwendyk said. ``Goals haven't
been easy. You have to scratch and claw for everything you have.
When you get shut out twice in a series, you just try to get shots
to the net.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, so the Stars didn't do everything right.
</P>
<P>
   But they scored on their chances, which wasn't the case in Game
3.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way it goes,'' Reid said. ``They scored on their
opportunities, and, if we scored on our opportunities, we could
have had four goals easily. I don't think we let them off the hook.
That's not the case at all.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, if they say so.
</P>
<P>
   The Avs lost for the first time at the Pepsi Center in the
playoffs. The series now returns to Reunion Arena for Game 5 and
again for Game 7 if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position was to get one of these two and have two of the
remaining three games,'' Modano said. ``It would be a shame to let
this pass by and let it slip out of our hands.''
</P>
<P>
   But history would suggest the Stars need a poor performance in
Game 5 to provide the necessary adversity.
</P>
<P>
   Stars center Guy Carbonneau thinks he has a solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we should practice (Monday) and have a bad practice,''
Carbonneau said. ``Maybe that will work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
