r s BC-HKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     05-22 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HULL LOVES TO DO WHAT HE DOES BEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The grin crept over Brett Hull's face as soon as the
question was asked. He couldn't help it. His favorite subject in
all the world had just been broached in the aftermath of the Stars'
had-to-have-it 4-1 victory against the Avalanche to even the
conference finals series at two games apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Hull, who had just become the sixth-best playoff sniper in NHL
history with two goals to pass the great Maurice ``Rocket'' Richard
on the all-time list, was asked to explain how he does it.
</P>
<P>
   Did I mention that he loves this question?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said before, I'm scared to death I'm going to wake up one
day and never be able to score another goal,'' Hull admitted, his
eyes growing wide with amazement and that little-boy grin stealing
across his face as he considered this innate ability with which
he's been blessed. ``I don't know if it's that inner drive that
makes me continue to do it or what, but it's really the only thing
I enjoy out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what I truly, heartfelt, love to do. Thankfully I have a
knack for getting goals and hopefully that'll continue. But I have
no idea why I'm able to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Why, of course, doesn't really matter. You won't hear Stars
coach Ken Hitchcock or Hull's teammates ask that question. They're
only happy that, on days like this, with their playoff fate hanging
in the balance, the guy with the biggest shot in hockey is on their
side.
</P>
<P>
   The schizophrenic Stars, who whimpered like Sybil in a 2-0 loss
in Game 3 and roared like Simba on Sunday, return to Dallas with
the split they came here for and the home-ice advantage once again
in their pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really dwell on our poor performances,'' said Mike
Modano, who drew so much attention from the Avs that he was able to
pick up three assists dishing the puck out to Hull and others.
``Especially in the playoffs, you don't really have time to figure
out what went wrong or point fingers or talk about the shoulda,
coulda, woulda things.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew the type of game we had to play today to win and we
all came and put in a great effort. Our position was to get one of
these two and have two of the remaining three games in Dallas. It
would be a shame to let this pass by and let it slip out of our
hands.''
</P>
<P>
   The guys who needed to step up for the Stars _ Joe Nieuwendyk,
Modano and Hull _ did exactly that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our star players played very well,'' Mike Keane pointed out.
``Joe played great. Mo played great and Hull scored big goals for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Big isn't the word for Hull's performance, but then, as the
Stars saw in Game 6 of the Stanley Cup Finals against Buffalo last
June, he's never been averse to scoring big-time goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a big game for us,'' Hull said. ``The quality of team
they have, you don't want to go home down 3-1. We knew we had to
have this game, especially after kind of a lackluster effort in
Game 3. We came out and played more of our style and capitalized on
the chances we had.''
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk took a beautiful, soft feed from Jamie Langenbrunner
from behind the Avs' net just over seven minutes into the game and
flipped it over Patrick Roy's right shoulder to put the Stars in
front.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get that first goal on the road, it settles everybody in
and lets everybody take a deep breath,'' Modano said.
</P>
<P>
   The goal galvanized the Stars and when Modano fed Hull in the
slot after intercepting a Dave Andreychuk pass 10 minutes later,
Hull sizzled it over Roy's right shoulder and into the net,
breaking a tie with Richard for sixth all-time in postseason goals
(he now has 84).
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike made a great pass,'' Hull said. ``I was going across the
grain and I just tried to hit the far side and got some good wood
on it and it found an opening.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the mantras of the Denver press has been that if the Avs
get a 2-0 lead, the Stars don't have the firepower to come back.
Let it be known that the flip side is also true. Give the Stars a
2-0 lead and they clamp down like a vise defensively.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe vise is a bit strong. The Avs would finish with 39
shots to the Stars' 15, but it was the Stars who made their
opportunities count.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a big shot-total team,'' Hull said, ``but I looked
up late in the second period and then asked Joe, `Are they
(shorting) us on the clock or do we really only have seven shots?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no grasp either way. It was one of those weird games.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest goal of the game was Hull's second midway in the
second period, giving the Stars some breathing room after a
turnover had allowed former teammate Dave Reid to wrist home an
unlikely 30-footer from the left circle and cut Dallas' lead to
2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Hull and Brenden Morrow, the rookie forward who wasn't supposed
to be able to skate because of what was thought to be a fractured
ankle, broke loose on a 2-on-1 rush, Hull speeding down the right
side with the puck. Hull wound up, cut loose and spanked it between
Roy's legs. The Avs goalie got a piece of the puck, but not enough
to keep it from squirting into the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were on our heels a little bit and Hully scoring that goal,
that was huge,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   He has made a career out of scoring goals like that. Go ahead,
ask him why. He loves it. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
