<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PRICE-BELMONT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DERBY BYPASS SETS UP BELMONT SHOWDOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ No regrets. No looking back.
</P>
<P>
   The handlers of Red Bullet have no regrets about skipping the
Kentucky Derby, even though it means they never had a chance to win
the Triple Crown. But they're not asking what could have been after
Red Bullet won the Preakness Stakes on Saturday by almost four
lengths over Derby winner Fusaichi Pegasus.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would have run great in the Derby,'' Red Bullet trainer Joe
Orseno said. ``But he wouldn't have been doing as good as he is
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now the horse is fine. He looks good. I don't see any
reason not to \Rgo to the Belmont Stakes\S. It should be quite a
showdown.''
</P>
<P>
   The showdown is between Red Bullet and Fusaichi Pegasus, with a
few familiar faces thrown in.
</P>
<P>
   Aptitude, who finished third in the Wood Memorial Stakes behind
Fusaichi Pegasus and Red Bullet and second in the Derby, skipped
the Preakness in favor of the Belmont. Unshaded, an impressive
winner of the Lexington Stakes at Keeneland, may finally get into a
Triple Crown race after his owner passed on the late entry fee of
$100,000-plus for the first two legs. And Tahkodha Hills has a shot
at a $1 million bonus for winning a Triple Crown event along with
his Lone Star Derby victory last month.
</P>
<P>
   The field could exceed 10, two more than the Preakness when many
horse owners decided to dodge Fusaichi Pegasus after he beat 18
with ease in the Derby. So it looks though the bloom has fallen off
the Kentucky Derby roses. At odds of 3 to 10, Fusaichi Pegasus was
the biggest favorite to lose the Preakness since Riva Ridge in
1971.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys don't lack for imagination,'' said trainer D. Wayne
Lukas, who often accuses the media of hyping ``super horses'' to
ridiculously low odds. ``I never could anoint this horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Orseno loaded Red Bullet on a van for the trip to Belmont
yesterday and said the colt is 50-50 for the race. But Neil
Drysdale, trainer of Fusaichi Pegasus, appears unusually eager for
a rematch. Slow to commit to the Preakness after the Derby, this
time he has scheduled to ship Fusaichi Pegasus from Pimlico to New
York today.
</P>
<P>
   ``That race \Rthe Preakness\S, he didn't extend himself,''
Drysdale said by telephone from his barn at Hollywood Park.
``That's good and bad. Good that he didn't extend himself coming
into this next race, but bad because he didn't handle the track and
didn't win.
</P>
<P>
   ``The horse pulled up well. He was quite bright and alert after
the race. In fact, he was playing when he got to the barn.''
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale continues to claim that Fusaichi Pegasus couldn't
handle the wet surface at Pimlico Race Course. But the wet surface
at Aqueduct didn't hinder Fusaichi Pegasus in the Wood, where he
beat Red Bullet by four lengths.
</P>
<P>
   Here's their theory on the turnaround: Kent Desormeaux, the
jockey on Fusaichi Pegasus, rode at Pimlico for several years
before moving to Southern California. He said Pimlico has a
limestone base that is covered by dirt and other materials. When it
gets wet, he said, it becomes more slippery or ``greasy.''
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale said the surfaces at New York tracks have a clay base
covered by a sandier surface that provide for better traction. Even
Lukas said the surface Saturday at Pimlico had a ``peanut butter''
feel too it that tired some of the horses.
</P>
<P>
   And Jerry Bailey, who rode Red Bullet, said his colt was fit for
the off going. He said a friend of his from California called him
before the race and told him he remembered that Red Bullet's dam (a
Caro mare named Cargo) was a ``freak'' on a wet track.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a wet fast track in New York,'' Drysdale said. ``It's
completely different. \RPimlico\S was far from being wet fast. It
was heavier, and \RFusaichi Pegasus\S is a long-striding colt who
didn't handle it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I thought he did good to even keep going. He
continued on very courageously to get second. A lot of times when a
horse can't handle the track they finish in the back. They ease
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale said he thought about equipping Fusaichi Pegasus with
``stickers,'' horseshoes with small protrusions that help a horse
grab into the mud. But he decided against it.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Eastern tracks, they either handle \Rwet tracks\S or they
don't,'' Drysdale said. ``Putting hardware on the bottom of the
foot can injure horses.''
</P>
<P>
   But the only thing injured after the Preakness appears to be
Drysdale's pride in his colt. It looks as though he's going for the
cure in the Belmont.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
