<HEADLINE>
STARS MAKE FOOTE, AVS PAY ON SEVERAL DEFENSIVE LAPSES
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Defenseman Adam Foote's return from an eye injury
hardly went as planned. He took the ice with Ray Bourque on the
third shift of the game to a rousing ovation from the capacity
crowd at the Pepsi Center.
</P>
<P>
   Foote, who said his eye gave him no problems, finished a minus-2
and was on the ice for three of the Stars' four goals. Foote and
the Avs' defense limited the Stars to 15 shots, but mistakes were
costly.
</P>
<P>
   The killer was a Stars two-on-one breakaway led by Brett Hull.
Adam Deadmarsh and Foote retreated but were too late. Hull put a
shot between Patrick Roy's legs for a 3-1 lead 7 minutes, 32
seconds into the second period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once Deady got back, I started to move over, and \RHull\S
slipped it through Patty, and it was one of those things,'' Foote
said. ``We played it how we always play a two-on-one. \RHull\S
doesn't need much room.''
</P>
<P>
   When Foote, who plans to finish the playoffs wearing a visor,
was out of action, the big question circulating was, `Can the Avs
win without him?' A dominating performance in Game 3 positively
answered those doubts. His return was supposed to bring an even
grittier, hard-hitting edge to the Avs.
</P>
<P>
   Foote's only hit of the game was a heavy one on Hull in the
first period, but Hull had the last laugh. POWERLESS The Stars
short-circuited the Avalanche power play, and a blown five-on-three
opportunity in the second period was a back-breaker.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche scored a power-play goal in each of the first
three games but squandered three chances through the first two
periods yesterday, including a two-man advantage for one minute,
four seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The Avs rolled out four forwards _ Joe Sakic, Peter Forsberg,
Milan Hejduk and Dave Andreychuk _ along with Ray Bourque on the
two-man advantage, but got off only one shot and only two for the
entire power play.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the game, the Avs had a 20 percent success rate on
power plays goals at a 20-percent rate. However, they are 1-for-14
in the past two games. A SAVE TO REMEMBER
</P>
<P>
   Avs forward Peter Forsberg will have a hard time forgetting the
save Stars goalie Ed Belfour made on him during Colorado's first
power play of the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Sandis Ozolinsh launched a shot from the point. The rebound came
to Forsberg at the right crease, but Belfour made an outstretched
save with his blocker to prevent a goal and a 2-2 tie.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two minutes later, Hull beat Roy for a 3-1 lead.
Forsberg had several good scoring chances, including three shots on
goal in the first period and six overall.
</P>
<P>
   His third shot of the first period also came off a Belfour
rebound. Belfour stopped Forsberg, then left another rebound for
Joe Sakic, who had the left side of the net wide open. Sakic pushed
the puck into the post and was denied. Sakic has not scored a goal
in this series and has only two in the playoffs. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   -- Ray Bourque inadvertently delayed the game eight minutes 3:30
into the third period when his dump-in shattered a panel of glass
near the right circle. Pieces of glass sprayed into the first two
rows. One woman needed assistance picking glass out of her hair.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Stars' first-period power-play goal was the second the
Avs have allowed on 30 chances at the Pepsi Center during the
playoffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
