<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-MORROW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS' BRENDEN MORROW MAKES MOST OF SURPRISE RETURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Sometime Saturday, Stars rookie winger Brenden Morrow
determined he might be able to play.
</P>
<P>
   There was one problem. And, no, it wasn't his fractured right
ankle.
</P>
<P>
   His equipment wasn't in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one expected me to play so it was back in Dallas,'' said
Morrow, who had to borrow Mike Modano's skates on Saturday. ``After
morning skate yesterday I knew I would be in warmup at least, so
they flew the equipment in.''
</P>
<P>
   It arrived in plenty of time for Morrow to be a vital player in
the Stars' 4-1 Game 4 victory yesterday at the Pepsi Center in
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   He played 13 minutes and 26 seconds with four hits and one
penalty to finish a plus-2 and was on the ice for three of the
Stars' goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea he was ready to play,'' Stars winger Brett Hull
said. ``I thought he was out for this series and might be back for
the next one.''
</P>
<P>
   No, Morrow was back for this one and just in time. The fact that
he was playing, never mind contributing, is a surprise. Remember,
after fracturing his right ankle late in Game 1, he wasn't supposed
to play the rest of the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had me in the funny boot and I was sort of cheating a
little bit and I would take it off and it felt pretty good to me,''
Morrow said. ``There wasn't much pain. I'm not really surprised as
some others.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, it's a bone chip, Stars team trainer J.J.
McQueen said, who also said the injury can't get any worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played the whole regular season and got to the fun part and
I thought it was all over,'' Morrow said. ``I was really
disappointed after my first game; I thought it was one of my worst
games. ... It was a big relief when the doctor said I had at least
a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   It took no time for Morrow to be thrown back on his normal spot
on the top line with Mike Modano and Brett Hull. Not that his name
appears on the scorers sheet, but he did have impacts on both of
Hull's goals.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the first period, Morrow had circled around the net to
the low-right circle where Colorado defenseman Ray Borque had no
choice but to cover Morrow. That left Hull open for his wrister and
a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   On the Stars' third goal, Hull had an open two-on-one when Avs
forward Adam Deadmarsh cheated toward Morrow, preventing the pass.
Hull took the shot and scored for a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   If Morrow's ankle was hurting, he wasn't showing it. Not when
Colorado defenseman Adam Foote drove him into the boards midway
through the third period and the two got into a scuffle drawing
penalties. Nor was he showing it when he came out of the penalty
box and Colorado forward Peter Forsberg gave him a shove.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was nervous and a little bit uptight on how things
would turn out,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``As he got
going, he got better and better and better as the game went on. So
he should be hopefully a significant player as we move along.''
</P>
<P>
   With Morrow back, it gives the Stars something they have only
flirted with all season: A healthy lineup. It gives Hitchcock room
to maneuver his second line with either Scott Thornton or Jere
Lehtinen. And it gives the Stars another banger in a series that is
growing reminiscent of ``Fight Club./
</P>
<P>
   ``You need those types of players against \RAdam\S Foote,
\RJon\S Klemm, \RAaron\S Miller and \RRay\S Borque to take the
body,'' Stars center Mike Modano said. ``The more players we have
like that the more we can wear them down and find some cracks and
seams and some create some chances.''
</P>
<P>
   More importantly for Morrow, this creates the chance to finish
the season on the ice. With his equiptment.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
