<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-AVALANCE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUMBERS ARE MIND-NUMBING IN GOAL
</HEADLINE>
 GOALIES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Avalanche goalie Patrick Roy and Stars goalie Ed
Belfour head to Dallas all even after four games. The shots they've
faced after two meetings in Colorado have been anything but even.
</P>
<P>
   Strictly by the numbers, it's mindboggling that Game 5 at
Reunion Arena tomorrow won't be the Avs' first of three chances to
close out the defending champion Stars:
</P>
<P>
   In Games 3 and 4, Belfour stopped 76 of 79 shots. Roy stopped 32
of 36, a mammoth 43 fewer shots.
</P>
<P>
   In the second period of Game 4, the Avs pelted Belfour with 21
shots, while the Stars, for the second consecutive period, managed
four shots on Roy.
</P>
<P>
   Shots on goal after the second period: Avalanche 31, Stars 8.
Score after the second period: Stars 3, Avalanche 1. The Avs
finished with 39 shots compared with the Stars' 15. The Stars won,
4-1, to tie the series at 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie stoned us. You have to give him credit,'' said Avs
winger Dave Reid, who scored their lone goal 1 minute, 43 seconds
into the second period to cut the Stars' lead to 2-1. ``I don't
think the Stars would be where they are without him. I think he's
played great all series. I don't think he did anything different
tonight than he did all series.''
</P>
<P>
   The Avs played in the Stars' zone for nearly half of the second
period. Once Reid got them on the scoreboard, their forwards
started to fly and Belfour was forced to save this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal was to get one win, and we did that,'' Belfour said.
``If we go down 3-1 to this team, it would be very difficult to
come back.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first seven minutes of the second period, he stopped a
chance from Milan Hejduk, made a sliding save on Chris Drury and
then made a remarkable pad save on Peter Forsberg right on the
doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   For all the Avs' ammunition, it took one two-on-one breakaway
led by Brett Hull to nullify it. Hull beat everyone into the Avs'
zone, and one future Hall of Famer beat another, as Hull went
five-hole off the inside Roy's blocker to give the Stars a 3-1 lead
that robbed a rocking crowd of its exuberance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hull scored on the two-on-one. That should have been a save by
me,'' Roy said. ``It would have been a key save. I was a little mad
at myself on that one.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy received little help defending the chances the Stars had.
Sloppy play and defensive mistakes led to the Stars' best chances,
and the Stars capitalized.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 15 shots \Rthe Stars had\S were great opportunities. It
wasn't like it was a shot from the point that he \RRoy\S saw and
just missed,'' Reid said. ``Don't worry about Patrick. Patrick is
going to bounce back.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Belfour and Roy have been around the block too many times
to worry. They have four Stanley Cups between them. Roy has two
shutouts in the series. Belfour hasn't allowed more than two goals
in all four games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have felt better and better every day,'' Belfour said. ``I
am looking forward to getting back in front of our home fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Bet that Roy is eager, too. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
