<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-CHANGES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS' LINE CHANGES OPEN UP NIEUWENDYK, OFFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ After seeing his team come up empty in two of the first
three games of the Western Conference Finals, Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock made something happen in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   It was a change for the better for the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock's line changes put the goal _ and the Joe _ back in
the Stars' offense.
</P>
<P>
   Center Joe Nieuwendyk, who had no goals, no assists, three
shots, a minus-1 rating and four penalties in the first three games
of the series, scored the first goal in the Stars' 4-1 victory
against the Colorado Avalanche yesterday. The Stars' four goals,
which was one more than they had scored in the first three games of
the series, came on only 15 shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``My approach hasn't changed at all,'' Nieuwendyk said. ``You
just try and keep working and fighting for your opportunities,
because they don't come easy in this series. I just felt I had a
few good looks at the net, which hasn't been there in the last few
games, and I was able to bury one.''
</P>
<P>
   What has changed is Nieuwendyk's second line.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' shots were hitting nothing but Roy in the first three
games of the series. Colorado goalie Patrick Roy, who had shutouts
in Games 1 and 3, had allowed only three goals on 79 Stars' shots
before yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   That, and the unexpected return of Stars winger Brenden Morrow,
prompted Hitchcock to shake up his lines.
</P>
<P>
   Morrow, who injured his right ankle in Game 1, joined Mike
Modano and Brett Hull on the Stars' top line. Nieuwendyk played
with Jere Lehtinen and Jamie Langenbrunner on the second line. On
the bottom two lines, Guy Carbonneau had Grant Marshall and Scott
Thornton as his linemates, and Roman Lyashenko, Kirk Muller and
Mike Keane played together.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Hitch looking like a genius again,'' Keane said. ``Once
in a while, you need a change. I don't think it's that much of a
change, but we got output. We got chances from everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars found that four was better than one.
</P>
<P>
   Before yesterday, the first line had carried the scoring load
with all three of the team's goals. While Hull got two of the
team's four goals yesterday, he and Modano finally got a little
help from their friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always said I think that our strength is our depth,''
Carbonneau said. ``Look at our team the last two or three years. We
seem to tire teams out. I think \Ryesterday\S was a little bit of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk's goal, which came at 7:12 of the first period, might
have been the biggest of the series. It gave the Stars a 1-0 lead
for the first time in the series, and it gave Nieuwendyk his first
goal of the series.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Nieuwendyk had the game-winning goals in Games 2 and
3 of the Western Conference Finals against Colorado, and he went on
to earn the Conn Smythe Trophy as most valuable player of the
playoffs, with 11 postseason goals, including six game-winners, and
21 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``For whatever reason, this is about the time Joe comes into the
series,'' Hitchcock said. ``... He did it again \Ryesterday\S.''
\Ntagtop:Charean Williams (817) 390-7760
\Ntagbottom:cjwilliams\Nstar-telegram.com
</P>
</TEXT>
