<HEADLINE>
CUBAN, NELSON SET FOR CONTRACT TALKS
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SECAUCUS, N.J. _ Mavericks owner Mark Cubanrepeated yesterday
that Don Nelson will coach the Mavericks next season.
</P>
<P>
   He just doesn't know if Nelson will also coach the Mavericks
when the team moves into the American Airlines Center for the
2001-02 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it's one year or 20 years, I wanted Nellie to be part
of the organization one way or another for a long, long time,''
Cuban said. ``Even if it's 30 years from now and I'm calling him up
in his rocking chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how much respect I have for Don Nelson.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban said he plans to remain in New York this week to work with
the NBA on some Internet issues. He said he'll meet with Nelson and
work on a new contract for his coach when he returns to Dallas
possibly at the end of this week, or early next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already talked on the phone and I don't anticipate any
problems,'' Cuban said. ``Nellie and I get along great.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson supposedly had retired after this past season, but then
had a change of heart before any of his possible successors could
be interviewed. Asked if he plans to interview anyone other than
Nelson, Cuban said: ``I don't think so at this point. At this
point, I don't see any reason to.'' WIZARDS LOSE PICK
</P>
<P>
   The big loser at the lottery was the Washington Wizards.
</P>
<P>
   The Wizards had a 64-in-1,000 chance of receiving the top pick
in the draft, but wound up without a first-round pick. Since the
Wizards did not finish among the top three lottery picks _ they
finished seventh _ the pick automatically went to the Chicago Bulls
via a previous three-team trade involving Chris Webber.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're realistic,'' said Darrell Walker, the Wizards' director
of player personnel. ``We're prepared to move on without having a
first-round pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll just concentrate on the second round and see if we can
get a nice player in the second round.'' IRONY FOR ROCKETS
</P>
<P>
   The irony of the lottery was not lost on Carroll Dawson, the
vice president of basketball operations for the Houston Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets were in the lottery this year for the first time in
the lottery's 16-year history.
</P>
<P>
   The worst team in the Eastern Conference and the worst team in
the Western Conference used to flip a coin to determine which one
would receive the top pick. But former Mavericks coach Dick Motta
complained to the league that the Rockets intentionally lost games
in order to enhance their draft position.
</P>
<P>
   That effort, Motta said, netted the Rockets top picks Ralph
Sampson and Hakeem Olajuwon in 1983 and '84.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember that,'' Dawson said of Motta's assertion. ``That
was a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Dawson admitted he was nervous before the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was kind of like the seventh game of the NBA championship
for me,'' he said. ``I didn't sleep \RSaturday\S night.''
</P>
<P>
   Utah and Portland are the only teams that haven't been in the
lottery. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
