r s BC-GLF-COLONIAL-CINK-TEX     05-22 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-COLONIAL-CINK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOGEYS ON FINAL TWO HOLES DOOM CINK'S COLONIAL CHANCES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Stewart Cink armed himself with an 8-iron in
what would be his last line of defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `We're starting from scratch here, and I'm tied. I
need to make a birdie on one of the last three holes, and I win the
tournament,' '' he recalled late yesterday afternoon. ``I hit one
of the best iron shots of my life right there on No. 16.''
</P>
<P>
   Cink's high, arching shot stopped within eight feet of the cup
on the 188-yard hole and rewarded him with an uphill putt with no
break.
</P>
<P>
   The missed putt would be his breaking point.
</P>
<P>
   Cink closed with bogeys at No. 17 and 18 and finished two
strokes behind Phil Mickelson, the eventual 2000 MasterCard
Colonial champion.
</P>
<P>
   Can anyone think of a better way to celebrate a 27th birthday
with mom, dad and wife in attendance?
</P>
<P>
   ``My putts were all missing, and I didn't have any confidence on
the greens,'' said Cink, who required 33 putts during his final
round after averaging 27 the previous three days. ``That's really
strange because I had just enormous confidence the second and third
rounds. I just didn't have it today.''
</P>
<P>
   Cink's game deserted him after draining a 15-foot putt for
birdie at No. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Misfiring from 21/2 feet for par at No. 5 will do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going along pretty good until then,'' Cink said.
</P>
<P>
   Cink, the only person to post birdies this week at Nos. 3, 4 and
5 _ known as ``The Horrible Horseshoe'' _ appeared destined to be
fitted for his first royal tartan sports coat after his move to
14-under par through 58 holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just thinking, `You've been in this situation before,
and you've been way ahead in tournaments. The one thing you can't
do is start playing against the field because that's a sure way to
start backing up,' '' Cink recalled. ``I've trained myself to keep
focusing on each shot at hand and try to make birdies. I had a
little hiccup on No 5. I missed a short putt about two-feet long,
and that kind of threw me off a little bit. I felt a little shaky
after that.''
</P>
<P>
   No, not nervous, Cink said, but he was shaking, literally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that somebody was going to come out and tear it up,''
he said. ``I knew that I had to keep on going. The deeper into the
round we got _ I don't know if it was the heat or that I was
sweating a lot, which I always do _ I felt a little bit shaky on
everything, and I mean shaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard enough to play against these guys out here when you
feel good, and I just didn't feel very good. It showed. I don't
think it was the heat. I've played enough in the heat. It was just
... I don't know. I just didn't feel very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson drained a 35-foot putt for birdie at No. 18 moved the
left-hander within a stroke of Cink, whose wheels soon fell off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was right in the middle of the fairway with a wedge to the
green, and I didn't hit a very good second shot,'' Cink said of his
approach at No. 17. ``It was in between \Rclubs\S, so it was a
really small wedge. I caught it a little chunky and left it about
30 or 40 feet from the hole. I made a good run at my first putt,
but it went about five feet past and missed it coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   Cink needed a birdie on No. 18 to force a playoff, but his shot
from the tee caught the rough and left him a 158-yard, downwind
approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit what I thought was a really good shot _ right on my
target and drawing in there toward the flag a little bit,'' he
said. ``I thought it was going to land just on the front edge and
just release right up there. It hit short of the green, where it
was kind of soft, and just stuck there.''
</P>
<P>
   Cink's three-putt from the fringe cost him second place alone
and $66,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only one player in the field was able to beat me,'' Cink said,
``two if you count myself.''' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
