<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY-BOAT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILLY BOAT EKES INTO INDY FIELD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ His was the first car out on the track for
practice yesterday morning, and the last to make a qualifying
attempt at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In between, Billy Boat endured a madcap day en route to a
starting position for the 84th Indianapolis 500. Hot-lapping in a
second backup car provided by former boss A.J. Foyt, the legendary
Texan who had fired him at the end of last season, Boat barely beat
the 6 p.m. deadline and barged into the field on the final
qualifying attempt of Bump Day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boat's four-lap//10-mile average of 218.877 mph around the
2.5-mile Speedway bumped Jack Miller from a field that for the
first time in race history includes two women drivers. Lyn St.
James, whose car momentarily got airborne after crashing in Turn 2
on Saturday, scrambled into the field at 218.826 mph in a backup
yesterday. St. James, who qualified 32nd for her seventh Indy 500,
will join 19-year-old rookie Sarah Fisher on the grid for the
traditional flying start Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Boat, who began the day crashing the car owned by
Team Pelfrey and ended it in an exchange of bear hugs with Foyt,
who provided the day's drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing in the world like trying to qualify for the
Indy 500 between 5 and 6 o'clock on Bubble Day,'' said Boat, a
34-year-old resident of Phoenix. ``I know the emotion of this
place, because I've been bumped between 5 and 6 o'clock. I know
what that feels like. And I feel very fortunate that I was with a
team that was able to get the job done under those circumstances. I
mean, I was in two \RFoyt\S race cars within an hour. It was enough
to get qualified for the Indy 500.''
</P>
<P>
   Forty-six seconds remained in yesterday's six-hour qualifying
session when Boat rolled out Foyt's No. 11 Rio G Force/Aurora. The
car is the backup for Eliseo Salazar, the Chilean who comfortably
qualified on the outside of the three-car front row Saturday at
223.231 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``That car had never turned a wheel, had never seen the
racetrack,'' Boat said. ``But A.J. said it was set up just like the
other one.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I could see the urgency in everybody's faces.''
</P>
<P>
   Boat, who won the pole for the 1998 Indy 500 with a four-lap
average of 223.503 mph while driving for Foyt, started his run at
219.947 mph and got progressively slower on each lap yesterday. But
his 218-plus average easily eclipsed Miller's 216.154 mph effort,
securing the 31st position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of Billy,'' said Foyt, who shared in the Victory
Lane celebration with Boat when he scored his first Indy Racing
League victory at Texas Motor Speedway in Fort Worth in June 1998.
``Billy and I go way back. I see a good friend struggling, so I
have to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Boat was one lap into his second qualifying attempt in Dale
Pelfrey's No. 81 Dallara/Aurora when he spun in Turn 1 and hit the
wall shortly after noon. The unsponsored car sustained heavy damage
to the left side and rear. Boat was checked at the track's medical
center and cleared to drive.
</P>
<P>
   But drive what? The car he wrecked could not be repaired in
time, and Pelfrey's only backup was a 1999 model deemed to be
obsolete. That's when Foyt came to the rescue. Foyt had opted to
release former Indy 500 pole sitter Roberto Guerrero from the seat
of the No. 41 car co-owned by himself and Kenny Brack, the 1999
Indy 500 champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just couldn't get him \RGuerrero\S going,'' Foyt said. ``I
really felt bad about pulling him out. Sometimes it don't click.''
Boat approached Foyt about the car's availability and was told to
bring his seat over.
</P>
<P>
   At 5:18 p.m., Boat qualified the No. 41 G Force/Aurora 31st at
192.105 mph _ a four-lap average that went awry when the car's
electronic dash malfunctioned and cut the engine on the third lap.
The hiccup dropped Boat's speed from 219.085 mph to 150.928. Boat's
fourth lap in that run also was a bust at 198.724 mph. Boat held
the 31st spot for 16 minutes, until St. James qualified a backup G
Force/Aurora owned by Dick Simon at 218.826 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning at 5:39 p.m., the bumping process saw Robby Unser,
Davy Jones, and Scott Harrington tossed from the lineup. By that
time, Foyt had decided to loan his untried backup to Boat, who
finished third in the 1999 Indy 500 for A.J. but was fired after a
disappointing season. Salazar and Jeff Ward, who qualified sixth
here Saturday at 222.639 mph, are flying Foyt's colors this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes careers go in different directions,'' Boat said of
his dismissal. ``I feel very fortunate that A.J. and I maintained
the relationship that we did, and that I still felt that I could
walk into his garage and say, `I'm in trouble. Can I get in one of
your cars?'''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
