<SLUG> BC-GLF-COLONIAL-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MICKELSON, PRACTICE MAKES PERFECT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH AND CHARLES CLINES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH _ MasterCard Colonial champ Phil Mickelson needed
only 26 putts during yesterday's final round, the fewest among the
top five finishers on the leader board.
</P>
<P>
   The key, Mickelson said, was a putting drill he initiated after
Saturday's third round. Mickelson placed 10 balls in a circle
around one hole, all inside three feet. He did not leave the
putting green until he drained 100 consecutive putts from that
distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm putting good, it takes me 20 minutes. But
\RSaturday\S night, it took 45,'' said Mickelson, who was the last
player remaining on the Colonial practice green when he dropped his
100th consecutive three-footer at 8 p.m. Saturday. ``I didn't have
my stroke where it needed to be, but I got it back. I was making
them in the middle of the cup by the time I finished.''
</P>
<P>
   During yesterday's final round, Mickelson drained eight birdie
putts, including the tournament-winner from 35 feet on the 18th
hole. ON SECOND THOUGHT ... Phil Mickelson committed one of his few
gaffes yesterday during his acceptance speech on the 18th green.
After closing with a 63, the lowest final round of any Colonial
champ, Mickelson attempted to compliment local citizens for their
Texas hospitality.
</P>
<P>
   Problem was, the Phoenix resident underestimated the provincial
pride of the pro-Fort Worth crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife and I have had two great weeks in Dallas,'' said
Mickelson, who finished in a tie for second at last week's GTE
Byron Nelson Classic. ``We really enjoy the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson was immediately shouted down by fans, who reminded him
he was standing in Fort Worth, not Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just bit my tongue,'' Mickelson told the crowd. ``We've had
two wonderful weeks HERE.'' TIGER WATCH BEGINS
</P>
<P>
   Before the tournament, Colonial tournament chairman Phil Thomas
said he ``would come close to betting'' that Tiger Woods would
return to Fort Worth in 2001 unless he successfully defended his
title at this week's Deutsche Bank Open in Alveslohe, Germany.
Woods, however, surrendered a one-stroke lead with eight holes
remaining in yesterday's final round and lost by four strokes to
Lee Westwood at the European Tour event.
</P>
<P>
   That means Woods will not have a title to defend next season if
the European Tour event falls on the same week as Colonial for a
third consecutive year. Thomas reiterated his optimistic stance
yesterday about a probable return to Colonial in 2001 by the PGA
Tour's top gate attraction. ESTIMATED ATTENDANCE
</P>
<P>
   Colonial officials estimated attendance for tournament week at
170,000, with a high of 45,000 during yesterday's final round.
Estimated attendance for the Thursday-Sunday rounds included:
Sunday, 45,000; Saturday, 40,000; Friday, 30,000; and Thursday,
25,000. The remaining 30,000 came from practice rounds and pro-am
days. STARTING POINT
</P>
<P>
   John Cook shot a 2-under 68 yesterday to finish at 6-under 274
for the tournament and cashed only his fourth check in 14
tournaments this season. But he said it's too early to ``say I'm
back. This is just a starting point.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook has tried several putters and went to a cross-handed grip
for two weeks before switching to a new putter and a regular grip
Monday in an effort to climb out of his slump.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a relief,'' he said of his efforts at Colonial. ``It has
been a long time since I've played this good. Houston is the first
time I've felt like had any control.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook didn't make the cut at Houston but did the next week in New
Orleans. Then he missed the cut again at last week's GTE Byron
Nelson Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not back, but I hit some good shots when I had to this
week and putted reasonably well, something I haven't done in a long
time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a start.'' STARS TRACKING
</P>
<P>
   Fans were watching golf around the 18th green, but several had
on headphones to keep track of the Stars' playoff game against the
Avalanche. A cheer went up once among several spectators when
someone reported the Stars had just gone up 3-1. They won, 4-1.
MEDIATE'S WILD RIDE
</P>
<P>
   Rocco Mediate said ``something crazy'' would have to happen
yesterday in order for him to win. It almost did.
</P>
<P>
   Mediate, who finished tied for fourth with David Toms at 8
under, dropped in an eagle on the par-4 No. 15 to pull within
serious striking distance at 9 under. Mediate holed out from 167
yards with a 7-iron.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit a better shot at 16 and made bogey, so go figure,''
Mediate said. Mediate dropped his tee shot on the 188-yard par-3
No. 16 within 4 feet of the hole. His birdie put slid by the hole
and down to the green's bottom shelf, where Mediate had to two-putt
from for bogey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was getting kind of frustrated,'' he said. ``I missed a
short one for par at 14, and then I get the eagle.'' FAR EAST SHOWS
WELL
</P>
<P>
   For only the second time in tournament history, the MasterCard
Colonial saw three Japanese players play all four days.
</P>
<P>
   Shigeki Maruyama (5 under) tied for 13th, Kaname Yokoo (4 over)
tied for 55th and Kazuhiko Hosokawa (8 over) tied for 62nd. In
1997, Maruyama, Hosokawa and Joe Ozaki all made the cut.
</P>
<P>
   Maruyama won $56,571 to add to an impressive earnings total
($730,640), which ranked him 19th overall on the PGA Tour. He has
five top-10 finishes.
</P>
<P>
   Japan Tour regular Hosokawa earned his first PGA check in two
starts this season, and Yokoo has made three of four cuts in the
United States in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can get into the top 10 in Japan, I'll have a good chance
of coming to play here full time,'' said Yokoo, 27, through his
translator and manager, Aaron Buckmister. ``That's the goal, of
course. If I can't, I'll stay in Japan and try harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Yokoo finished ninth in Japan Tour earnings in 1998 and '99 and
sits in the top 20 this season. CHANGES BRING CHANGES
</P>
<P>
   The more than $3.5 million in course renovations at Colonial the
past year met with approval by the PGA Tour competitors, and the
changes affected the way the pros played some of the holes.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest change was No. 9, which had the tee moved back some
30 yards. It jumped to third-hardest hole, replacing the third hole
of the ``Horrible Horseshoe.''
</P>
<P>
   The 470-yard fifth hole that skirts the Trinity River remained
the hardest for the competitors as the scoring average was 4.363.
The second-hardest over the years had been the 476-yard third hole,
but this week, the 246-yard fourth hole proved more difficult. It
played to a 3.146 average, while the third hole played to a 4.118
average and dropped to fifth hardest.
</P>
<P>
   In past years, the hardest holes at Colonial have been, in
order, Nos. 5, 3, 4 (the ``Horrible Horseshoe''), and Nos. 12, 10,
15, 14, 8, 18, 16, 7, 9, 13, 17, 6, 2, 11 and 1.
</P>
<P>
   This year, they were holes 5, 4, 9, 18, 3, 7, 14, 15, 13, 2, 10,
12, 8, 16, 6, 17, 11 and 1.
</P>
<P>
   The par-5 first hole, the par-4 sixth and 17th holes were the
only ones that the field averaged under par. They averaged 4.713
strokes on the 565-yard first hole, 3.944 on the 393-yard sixth and
3.938 on the 383-yard 17th. OUT OF NOWHERE
</P>
<P>
   Carl ``A Cinderella Story'' Paulson _ forgive the Bill Murray
impersonation _ came from nowhere to card a 29 on the back nine
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Paulson, who witnessed no gophers on the course, posted a
six-birdie, bogey-free nine to match the second-best back nine at
Colonial. Keith Clearwater carded a 28 during the 1993 tournament.
Paulson and six others earned $26,117 for their 24th-place finish.
Staff writers Johnny Paul and Troy Phillips contributed to this
report. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
