<HEADLINE>
NEBRASKA ATTACK SUBDUES BAYLOR IN BIG 12 FINAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ Plotting his team's strategy before the Big 12
Tournament championship game, Nebraska coach Dave Van Horn issued a
public vow: ``We will do anything necessary to win, except put
Shane Komine on the mound.''
</P>
<P>
   Who?
</P>
<P>
   Komine, the Cornhuskers pitching ace who was knocked out by
Missouri in the tournament opener, was probably the only guy
wearing red who declined to step up and take a swing at Baylor
(45-15) yesterday, as Nebraska (47-15) rode a 15-hit barrage to an
11-3 victory in a battle of top seeds.
</P>
<P>
   The attack was led by left- fielder Adam Stern, designated
hitter Justin Cowan and right fielder Adam Shabala _ voted the
tournament's Outstanding Player _ who combined to drive in eight
runs. But the hero of the hour was Chad Wiles (4-2), who carried a
no-hitter into the sixth and gave the Bears little hope of a
counterattack.
</P>
<P>
   Wiles, who has struggled through a so-so year, found himself in
familiar circumstances: he got the save in this game last year when
Nebraska topped the Bears, 4-3, and also threw a one-hitter against
Oklahoma State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it is about this tournament,'' he said.
``Maybe I just get focused a little better. I've been struggling
all year, but I don't know why ... just baseball, I guess. But I
had an extra motivation because they swept us down there early in
the year, and we didn't want them to beat us a fourth time.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn recalled that after the final game of the Baylor
series, ``I told them that if we didn't have a really good April,
we were going to be sitting home at this point, and we're too good
a team for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next day, they had a players-only meeting, and I think
some of the older guys had a few things to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska is 29-4 since that point, and Shabala _ who had
problems seeing the ball until he tried contact lenses _ is hitting
.449. After losing the tournament opener, the Cornhuskers won five
consecutive games to claim the title for the second consecutive
year.
</P>
<P>
   They finished the charge with glittering pitching performances
from Scott Fries and R.D. Spiehs _ who each held hard-hitting
Oklahoma to one run in a doubleheader victory Saturday _ and Wiles,
three pitchers who are not the mainline figures in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the things is, they were last year,'' Van Horn said. ``I
think what you've seen the last two days is three guys with their
backs to the wall who came out battling. Guys who were good last
year and have been relatively forgotten this year.''
</P>
<P>
   With both teams assured a berth in the NCAA regionals _ Baylor
will be a host next weekend _ Nebraska was able to save Komine and
Baylor coach Steve Smith saved the aces that had compiled a 1.67
earned-run average coming into this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their bats just killed us today,'' Smith said. ``But they were
also deeper on the mound than we were. We were throwing freshmen,
but they still had Wiles. He made our bats look awfully slow.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
