<HEADLINE>
NOT CAPITALIZING ON THIS PENALTY KILLED AVS' SPIRIT
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER -- Lost in the Stars' victory yesterday was their
five-on-three penalty kill in the second period that seemed to
break the Colorado Avalanche's spirit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a turning point for us,'' Stars forward Mike Keane
said. ``We still had a two-goal lead, but they could have jumped
back in. They were slowly getting momentum. Then, we got the
kill.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Stars _ who won, 4-1 _ held a 3-1 lead when defenseman
Derian Hatcher was given a two-minute penalty for high sticking.
Only 56 seconds into the Avs' power play, Keane joined him in the
penalty box for high sticking. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It gave the Avs a five-on-three, and a chance to get back into
the game. But Ed Belfour stopped three Colorado shots during the
power play, including one during the five-on-three. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's trying to keep the puck out of your net,'' Stars center
Guy Carbonneau said. ``Obviously, they've got a great power play.
You have to be a little bit lucky, and you need your goaltender to
make the save. We just try and keep the puck away from the net as
much as possible, and give them the worst shot possible.'' &QL; 
FIGHTING BACK &QL; 
The Stars talked Saturday of needing to turn this series into a
street fight. It appears the Avalanche had the same idea. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the final half of the third period, both teams seemed content
to muck it up. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The period included[ There were] 11 penalties, two fights and
too much pushing and shoving to count. Problems began when Stars
captain Derian Hatcher and Avs forward Adam Deadmarsh exchanged
blows with 7 minutes, 43 seconds remaining. Jamie Langenbrunner and
Adam Foote followed not long after, with more tussles between
Darryl Sydor and Shjon Podein, Brenden Morrow and Aaron Miller and
Sylvain Cote and almost everybody.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``In the playoffs, that's the way it goes,'' said. ``When[ gusy]
guys have been banging heads for four games, usually when the score
is like that, you are going to have guys giving each other extra
little[ shtos,] shots, extra little whacks. I don't think it's a
surprise to anybody.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As for the Hatcher-Deadmarsh fight, it wasn't really a fight.
There was one punch, a right hook by Hatcher that drew blood,
before both players fell down. &QL; 
LYASHENKO PLAYS &QL; 
Stars rookie center Roman Lyashenko made his Western Conference
Finals debut; he[ yesterday. The rookie had been] was a healthy
scratch in the first three games. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And while the stat sheet [ only]showed him with only one shot,
25 percent in the faceoff circle and two hits, he had a very busy
afternoon. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lyashenko drew a[ the] roughing call on Serge Aubin at 5:39 of
the first period. Joe Nieuwendyk scored on the ensuing power play
for a 1-0 lead. Lyashenko replaced[ came in for] Aaron Gavey, who
was a healthy scratch[ along with winger Blake Sloan] for the first
time[ in] this series.  &QL; 
Manson fits his niche &QL; 
Stars defenseman Dave Manson was brought in from Chicago to be
physical. Yesterday, Manson played 24 physical minutes and at one
point demonstrated that the Stars will take care of those who touch
Stars goalie Ed Belfour. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Colorado forward Peter Forsberg took a little swipe at
Belfour, Manson did all he could to get at Forsberg. Before he
could, however, he was separated. The play was indicative of
Manson's day; he finished with two shots and four hits. &QL; 
A ONE AND A ... 222? &QL; 
Stars center Guy Carbonneau passed Bryan Trottier, now a Colorado
assistant, for fourth place on the NHL's all-time playoff list for
games played. Yesterday was Carbonneau's 222nd postseason game.
Only Mark Messier (236), Larry Robinson (227) and Glenn Anderson
(225) have appeared in more playoff games. Did I?'' Carbonneau said
when asked about passing Trottier. I stopped counting after one.''
FIGHTING MAD
</P>
<P>
   Stars center Scott Thornton received a 10-minute misconduct
penalty with 1:54 left in the game. It was the Stars' fifth penalty
of the period and ninth of the game. They had warned us that any
extracurricular at that time, they'd throw the player out,'' Stars
coach Ken Hitchcock said. Second-period blues The Stars have been
outshot, 56-29, in the second period of the four games of the
conference finals. And that includes outshooting the Avs 17-5 in
the second period of Game 2. The one thing that is concerning us is
our second period in this building,'' said Hitchcock, whose team
has been outshot, 41-8, in the second period of the past two games.
It has been poor. We stopped playing a strong territorial game
\Ryesterday\S, and it put us behind the eight ball again. We tried
to make extra plays with the puck that were unnecessary.'' FACEOFF
FOLLIES
</P>
<P>
   They aren't the sexiest stats in the world, but in terms of zone
time and setting up goals, faceoffs are usually vital. Yesterday,
the Stars won the game but were beaten on faceoffs 38-29. This
coming after a first period in which they won 13-9. Center Guy
Carbonneau, who was 13-8, was the only Stars player to win more
faceoffs than he lost. Sometimes you play, and it doesn't really
matter,'' Carbonneau said. But I always take pride in winning the
one that we need to. Those are the ones that count. Sometimes you
go through a game where you feel like you are unbeatable, and
sometimes you just can't win one.'' nn
</P>
