<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ORIOLES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS RALLY, CAP SWEEPS WEEK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Scott Erickson was dealing, Darren Oliver was
finished, and the national ESPN television audience had to be doing
some serious channel surfing.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere around the fifth inning Sunday night, all signs were
pointing to a real snoozer taking place at The Ballpark in
Arlington, one that would bring the Rangers' immensely successful
homestand to a disappointing end.
</P>
<P>
   But some simple truths could not be erased. The Rangers are on a
serious roll, the Baltimore Orioles are spiraling out of control,
and Frank Catalanotto still bids to be the first .600 hitter in
major-league history.
</P>
<P>
   Catalanotto got his sagging batting average back to the .600
level Sunday night with a two-out pinch-hit single in the eighth
inning, driving in Ruben Mateo with the winning run and giving the
Rangers a 6-5 victory against the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers trailed 5-0 going into the sixth inning before
mounting a comeback that gave them their sixth consecutive victory
and 15th in 20 games. The Rangers finished with a 6-0 homestand for
only the fourth time in club history, and they are 14-5 in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're up there pretty high right now,'' said Catalanotto,
speaking of the Rangers' confidence. ``We feel even if we're down
early in the game, we're going to come back and score some runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Said manager Johnny Oates: ``It's been a good month of May.
Offensively we've scored a lot of runs, the bullpen is coming
around, and we've been able to win a lot of one-run ballgames. The
bullpen has a lot to do with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers starter Darren Oliver put the Rangers down early by
giving up three runs in the first inning and left trailing 5-0 with
two on and two out in the fifth. But the bullpen combination of
Mark Clark, Francisco Cordero, Mike Venafro and John Wetteland
threw 41/3 scoreless innings to give the Rangers a chance to rally.
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen, after being the whipping boys for six weeks, helped
make it a successful homestand by holding opponents to two earned
runs in 20 innings. Wetteland, who struck out Will Clark with the
tying run at second to end the game, saved five of the six
victories and has been successful on seven consecutive save
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bullpen has been a big key for us,'' first baseman Rafael
Palmeiro said. ``They keep us close, and, when we get the lead,
they come in and close the door. They're giving us a chance to win
these games late.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Rangers were toasting their success, the Orioles were
left to ponder the pain of having lost 15 of 17 games, effectively
removing them _ at least for the foreseeable future _ from the
American League East race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were our own worst enemy,'' Orioles manager Mike Hargrove
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles seemed fine through five innings yesterday. Erickson
had a two-hitter, a five-run lead and his sinking fastball working
well. Then all of a sudden, it started to unravel. Rafael Palmeiro
hit a solo home run in the sixth, Mike Lamb followed with a two-run
shot, and the Rangers were down 5-3.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson, in his fifth start since coming off the disabled list,
went back out for the seventh, but got in trouble when he walked
Jason McDonald, gave up a single to Luis Alicea and walked Chad
Curtis to load the bases. Ivan Rodriguez's sacrifice fly off Al
Reyes brought home one run, and Palmeiro's slow grounder off Buddy
Groom drove in the tying run.
</P>
<P>
   Mateo got the winning rally started by drawing a leadoff walk.
Lamb bunted him to second and Catalanotto's two-out single off Mike
Trombley brought Mateo home. Catalanotto, who is bothered by a
strained groin muscle, has 21 hits in 35 at-bats this season and is
9-for-11 since coming off the disabled list at the start of the
homestand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I can say is the ball is finding holes,''
Catalanotto said. ``I'm seeing the ball good, but it's not like I'm
crushing it. It's just getting through the infield.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
