<HEADLINE>
LONG BEACH STATE WANTS TO KEEP PLAYING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ There will be no begging.
</P>
<P>
   No one at Long Beach State spent Sunday evening trying to lobby
members of the NCAA Baseball selection committee about the
postseason-worthiness of the Dirtbags.
</P>
<P>
   Dirtbag coach Dave Snow did not wake up this morning and feel
the need to reach out to anyone within earshot of the committee. It
isn't his style, and everyone who knows him knows better than to
even ask the question.
</P>
<P>
   If the Dirtbags get one of the 64 invitations to the postseason,
to be handed out at noon today (ESPN), it will be on the program's
merit and the 31 wins it claimed during an odd 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   No win was bigger than Sunday's, of course, a 9-5 victory at
Blair Field over cross-county rival Fullerton. It gave the 49ers
two wins in their final three-game series against the Titans, a tie
for third-place in the Big West standings (18-12), and four wins in
six games on the season against a team that will host one of the 16
first-round tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Those are some of the positives in the 49ers' case. But clearly,
the oddest season in Snow's dozen on Atherton has everyone
associated with the program guessing on the 49ers' future,
including Snow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no feel for it,'' he said. ``No thoughts, no feel. No
body knows what they'll do. It's all speculation. I'd like to think
we've got some good wins this season, maybe enough to get us in. We
also had some ugly losses.''
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers' 31-25 regular season mark is the worst in Snow's 12
years, although it isn't so far off some other regular season marks
-- the 49ers had regular season marks of 32-22 in 1996 and 34-22 in
1997 -- to make one recoil in horror. The season only pales because
the expectations are so high.
</P>
<P>
   If someone were to try and influence a committee member, these
are the stats that would be emphasized:
</P>
<P>
   (bullet) The 49ers went 11-13 against seven opponents currently
ranked in Collegiate Baseball's Top 30. In a year in which there
was no dominant west coast team, that's not a bad number. Fullerton
finishes the season 35-19 overall and 14-12 against ranked teams.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between the two schools isn't so great that one
team is host for a playoff round while the other has to watch.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet) In one unofficial ranking that the committe doesn't
necessarily use but is similar to college basketball's RPI, the
49ers rank 40th in the nation. A separate strength of schedule
index by another college basketball number-crusher says the 49ers
played the 10th toughest schedule in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet) The 49ers swept a Texas Tech team that will earn an
at-large berth, split a two-game series with a 40-win Wichita State
team, and swept a three-game series at Arkansas, a team that just
won two of three games against No. 1-ranked South Carolina and
played the second-toughest schedule in the country. There was also
a win in three games at Miami.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet) And finally, there's the nine-straight tournament
appearances. This is one of the few moments when Long Beach State
can actually site tradition an asset. Snow's Dirtbags have been to
the tourney nine straight years (and 10 of 11) and the College
World Series four times.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to say we deserve a spot,'' Snow said. ``There were
a lot of disappointing things about the season. There have been
times when we've played horribly. We had some deficiencies that it
took us 20 games to show.'' The 49ers opened the season 16-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the guys before the series that we needed to hang in
there. Coming in, we had to have a
whatever-it-takes-to-get-the-job-done attitude. Even in our loss
Saturday (4-2), we went about the game the way we're supposed to. I
told them not to let the lack of a result bring on any negativity,
because we've struggled with (bad vibes) the last few weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers certainly could have given in against Fullerton
Sunday. The Titans opened up a 4-0 first-inning lead, and the 49ers
trailed 5-2 after a sixth-inning, bases-loaded, no out situation
produced just one run. Instead, they bundled together a classic
rally for six runs in the seventh -- two walks, four singles, a
double and a game-tying non-sacrifice bunt. The key hit was a
pinch-hit, chalk-drawing line drive by pinch-hitter Casey Grzecka.
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth, the Titans loaded the bases with two outs and sent
outfielder Chris Beck, who hit a three-run first-inning homer, to
the plate as the game-tying run. But reliever Josh Alliston blew a
2-2 fastball by Beck for the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I absolutely believe we belong,'' said catcher Bryan Kennedy.
``The way we played this weekend shows what this team can do. We've
played and beaten good teams this season.''
</P>
<P>
   No kidding. Losses to mediocre teams -- three to UCSB, two to
Sacramento, Northridge and Pepperdine -- were the team's biggest
problem. The 49ers lost their last seven mid-week non-conference
games. Win three of those seven games and the Snowmen are wondering
where they're headed, not if.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach told us that if we don't get in, we'll spend the season
wondering `what if.' But if we do get in, we're all going to start
0-0. I don't care where they send us. I just want to keep
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just looking for a shot,'' said reserve Bobby Womack.
``We like being the underdog, and nobody likes playing the
Dirtbags.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one notion the committee hopefully won't consider.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 0112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
