<HEADLINE>
A TEX-BOOK CASE OF HOW TO PERSEVERE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The book: ``Trial By Basketball: The Life and Times of Tex
Winter''
</P>
<P>
   Author: Mark Bender, forward by Phil Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Publishing info: Addax Publishing, $22.95, 303 pgs.
</P>
<P>
   To know him is to love him: NBA fans may only be aware of the
78-year-old Winter as the triangle guru, first with the Chicago
Bulls (for 14 years), and now the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   So Cal basketball people may know he played at USC (with Alex
Hannum and Bill Sharman), coached at Washington against UCLA's John
Wooden and ended up directing Long Beach State's struggling program
in the late '70s, where after his ``retirement'' at age 60 looked
to be out of the game for good.
</P>
<P>
   There had to be a beginning. And an in between. That's where
this book fills the gaps.
</P>
<P>
   The last chapter about his coming to the Lakers entitled
``Escape to L.A.'' could also be one of the book's first chapters.
As a 14-year-old, born in Wellington, Texas, who came to L.A. with
his mom during the Great Depression, he learned to play basketball
in Huntington Park. The kids called him ``Tex'' - not as a
compliment.
</P>
<P>
   In 16 chapters, plus plenty of photos from the family album,
this pieces together Winter's ride through basketball and life to
where he's finally received the respect and admiration of his peers
and players.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 0126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
