<HEADLINE>
ST. JAMES, FISHER MAKE HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Lyn St. James has been racing cars longer than
Sarah Fisher has been alive. But on Sunday, the oldest and youngest
drivers in the field will make history as the first two women to
start an Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, a 19-year-old rookie, will start 19th after compiling a
four-lap//10-mile qualifying average of 220.237 mph[ on] Saturday.
St. James, 53, secured the 32nd spot in the field of 33 with a
qualifying effort of 218.826 mph yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   St. James' Bump Day run ended a streak of two frustrating years
of missing the race and put her in the company of postergirl
Fisher. But St. James said her motivation for the race's 84th
edition was not about making statements on gender.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to be in the race,'' said St. James, who
followed Janet Guthrie (1977-79) as the second woman to compete in
the Indy 500. ``What Sarah is doing has no pressure on my deal, to
be my best and drive my best. I've been racing for 26 years, as one
who loves the sport. I am proud of Sarah Fisher. She came up the
right way. She realized she had to go fast. But not all fast
drivers come to Indy.''
</P>
<P>
   St. James put together her run approximately 24 hours after
crashing her primary No. 90 Yellow Freight Systems G Force/Aurora
in Turn 2 of the 2.5-mile Indianapolis Motor Speedway. The car she
qualified was a hybrid 2000 chassis based on the backup of Dick
Simon Racing teammate Stephan Gregoire, who will start 20th in the
No. 7 Mexmil G Force/Aurora.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two years of not making it \Rthe Indy 500\S tore me
up inside,'' St. James said. ``It was the strongest test I've had
in knowing who Lyn St. James is. I'm happy and pleased to be where
I am.'' Texas team starts two Rockwall-based TeamExtreme saw both
its drivers qualify when veteran Davey Hamilton joined rookie
Airton Dare on the final grid yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, the only driver to start all 38 Indy Racing League
events, landed in the 28th spot after qualifying at 219.878 mph.
Dare, of Brazil, earned the 21st spot Saturday at 219.970 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton never had qualified lower than 11th in four previous
Indy 500s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard horror stories about starting in the back,'' said
Hamilton, driver of the No. 16 Lycos G Force/Aurora. ``I'll let you
know what it's like back there after the race.'' Mears lends
expertise Indianapolis native Andy Hillenburg realized a lifelong
dream when he qualified for the race, with a little help from a
famous friend. Hillenburg will start 33rd and last after qualifying
at 218.285 mph in the No. 48 The Sumar Special Dallara/Aurora.
Hillenburg's coaching staff was headed by Rick Mears, the third man
to win four Indy 500s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nothing,'' said Mears, the race winner in 1979, 1984,
1988 and 1991 with Team Penske. ``I was visiting with Bill Simpson
\Rteam co-owner\S, and he said they were struggling a bit. I didn't
really do much. I was just another set of eyes and ears. Andy went
out there and stood on it, and got it done.'' Matsuda hospitalized
Popular Japanese driver Hideshi Matsuda, 45, was admitted to
Methodist Hospital downtown with a fractured right wrist and left
knee after crashing his backup No. 20 Hubbard-Imke Dallara/Aurora
in Turn 3 on a practice run late in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Matsuda, who has started four previous Indy 500s, was scheduled
to undergo surgery last night. It was Matsuda's third crash in as
many days.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
