<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-NCAA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGIA WINS TITLE ON TIEBREAKER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. - Don't think tennis is a team sport? Try
explaining that to the women of Georgia and Stanford, who battled
into the early evening and had their NCAA Championship match
decided in doubles play.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but the final doubles match went to a tiebreaker
before Georgia's Marissa Catlin and Lori Grey pulled out a 9-8
(7-3) victory over Teryn Ashley and Marissa Irvin to give the
Bulldogs a 5-4 victory and their second national championship
Sunday at Pepperdine.
</P>
<P>
   Catlin and Grey led 6-1, but Ashley and Irvin won the next six
games, and later forced the tiebreaker with a service break.
Stanford won the first two points of the tiebreaker but just one
point after that.
</P>
<P>
   A double fault set up match point for Georgia, and Irvin hit
into the net on match point. Stanford lost its only match of the
season and finished 30-1, and Georgia (27-2) added another title to
the one it won in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went away from each other for a while, but we got it under
control,'' Grey said. ``We had to do it for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   The teams split the six singles matches, sending the match to
doubles play. Stanford got some momentum in the final singles
match, when Gabriela Lastra held off Grey for a 6-2, 6-7 (7-9), 6-1
victory, and based on rankings, the Cardinal had the advantage of
two of the three doubles matchups.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not how it worked out. Georgia's Esther Knox and
Aarthi Venkatesan beat Laura Granville and Keiko Tokuda 8-3, and
Stanford's Lauren Kalvaria and Gabriela Lastra beat Anne Nguyen and
Zoe Mellis 8-2, meaning the match would be decided on Court 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw our girls standing around cheering, I knew we had
to win,'' Grey said.
</P>
<P>
   The match seemed destined for doubles play almost from the
beginning. The Cardinal got off to a quick start in singles when
Granville continued her torrid play with a 6-0, 6-3 victory over
Knox at No. 2, and Stanford's prospects looked even better when
fifth singles Jennifer Heiser pounded Kelly Baskin 6-4, 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, the Cardinal seemed a lock for at least one or two
more victories, but Stanford's fortunes headed south quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Almost simultaneously, Georgia's No. 3 and No. 6 players, Catlin
and Nguyen, held off challenges to earn two crucial points. Catlin,
ranked No. 55, upset No. 9 Kalvaria, 7-5, 7-6 (7-2) and Nguyen,
after a dreadful second set, came back to beat Tokuda 6-3, 1-6,
6-3.
</P>
<P>
   The match of the day, however, was the contest between
top-ranked Irvin (a graduate of Harvard-Westlake High) and No. 5
Venkatesan, who earned the 6-3, 5-7, 6-3 victory in a match that
featured 17 service breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Down 5-4 in the second set, Irvin held off two break points and
broke Venkatesan. Irvin went up a break early int the third set,
but Vekatesan broke Irvin's serve the next three times to pull out
the surprising victory.
</P>
<P>
   The singles tournament begins at 9 a.m. today with 32
first-round matches. Second- and third-round matches will be held
Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 0142EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
