<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 02:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1931 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-SIDEWAYS-LADN     05-22 0409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-SIDEWAYS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYING WITH BASEBALL-STYLE MONOPOLY MONEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Game: Dodgers Collector's Edition Monopoly
</P>
<P>
   Price: $50
</P>
<P>
   How to get it: Dodger Stadium gift shop, the team Web site
(www.dodgers.com) or by phone at 323-224-1HIT.
</P>
<P>
   How it's played: Like regular Parker Brothers' classic - roll
the dice, buy property, put up houses (in this case, luxury boxes)
and hotels (or ballparks) and try to clean out your opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Who's on Boardwalk? Jackie Robinson ($400).
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the gameboard: Fernando Valenzuela might be a rather
curious choice to occupy Robinson's neighborhood at the Park Place
property (with a $350 price). Vin Scully ($260) is part of the
yellow lot purchase with Dodger Stadium and Ebbets Field.
</P>
<P>
   The green group is Tom Lasorda ($320), Don Drysdale and Steve
Garvey, while the red trio consists of Duke Snider ($240), Pee Wee
Reese and Roy Campanella. The orange group is Eric Karros ($200),
Kirk Gibson and Orel Hershiser. The three property families from
the ``Go'' position are represented by the team's Dominican and
spring training facilities, the minor-league affiliates and the
World Championships of '55, '63 and '88.
</P>
<P>
   The two utilities are replaced by the TV and radio rights, while
the railroad foursome consists instead of the Stadium Club, Dugout
Club, Diamondvision and Stadium Suites.
</P>
<P>
   What's obviously missing: Sandy Koufax. The Dodgers asked if the
Hall of Famer would be part of the game, but, as is his way, he
respectfully declined.
</P>
<P>
   Game pieces: A Dodgers cap, a Dodger dog, a Dodgers pennant, a
catcher's mask, a baseball glove and a statue of a pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chance'' card we wish was included: ``You mooned John Rocker.
Go directly to jail. Do not pass Lasorda.''
</P>
<P>
   The unique packaging: ``Trying to fit a square game into a round
box was an engineering nightmare,'' admits Mike Nygren, the
Dodgers' director of merchandising. ``But we're the only ones who
are going to have a Monopoly game in that kind of (15''-diameter)
baseball-shaped box.'' (Other games for the New York Yankees and
Boston Red Sox are currently being co-produced by those teams).
</P>
<P>
   In conclusion: It's only been out about three weeks, but ``the
reception has been nothing short of incredible,'' Nygren said. ``We
think it's a good representation of the franchise's rich history.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 0201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
