<P>
   &UR; THE DEFECTION OF AMERICA'S COUNTRY-CLUB REPUBLICANS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COUNTRYCLUB-GOP-ECONOMIST-775&AMP;add-NYTSF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Country clubs have traditionally been places where
affluent, white (mostly Protestant) Americans could get together to
play golf, drink, eat mediocre food and casually discuss business.
Talking politics was never polite but, come election time, the
members would line up behind Republican candidates, including that
consummate club member, George Bush, Sr. But George W. Bush would
be wise not to take his father's group for granted. He may have
solid country-club credentials and even a decent golf swing, but
America's country-club Republicans are not the dependable political
force they once were. ``It's not your father's country club any
more, and it's not your father's Republican Party either,'' says
Marshall Wittmann of the Heritage Foundation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 50-word optional trim; story uncut is 1,075) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNCLE SAM AND U.S. FARMERS: PLANTING THE SEEDS OF RUIN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FARMING-AMERICA-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ The Freedom to Farm Act of 1996 was supposed to wean
American farmers off federal handouts. That act ended price
supports for common crops such as corn and wheat, encouraging
farmers to switch instead to more unusual plantings in response to
market demand. But last year proved they were still relying on
government money in the form of emergency payments and loans, and
this year will probably prove it again. This is, after all, an
election year, and most of the money will conveniently arrive in
the autumn. But farmers might find Congress less kind when the
pressure to win friends is over. ``I am much less convinced we can
count on that kind of largesse next year and down the road,'' says
an Iowa State University economist. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: MIDWEST, Farming-State Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (800 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IT'S OFFICIAL: U.S. `GOLDILOCKS' ECONOMY IS TOO, TOO HOT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ECON-OH-MY!-ECONOMIST-675&AMP;add-NYTSF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ America's economy has been roaring along, with low
inflation, for so long now that any mention of speed limits and
overheating was becoming decidedly unfashionable. No longer. In
recent weeks, the signs that the economy is being stretched beyond
its limits have become unmistakable. All eyes are now on the
Federal Reserve's next policy-making meeting on May 16. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Two optional trims, totaling 450. Total uncut is 1,375) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONGRESS, SAY `AYE' FOR CHINA'S FREEDOM &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; VOTE-`YES'-CHINA-PNTR-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Next week, the American Congress will vote on
whether to grant China permanent normal trading relations (PNTR) as
part of that country's entry into the World Trade Organization. It
promises to be a razor-close vote. Congress should vote in favor of
the bill, not mainly for reasons of American economic
self-interest, but because PNTR will speed the very changes in
China that critics of the measure say they want to see. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1,025 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHY IS CAPITOL HILL SO DIVIDED OVER CHINESE TRADE STATUS? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHINA-HILL-CLIFFHANGER-ECONOMIST-300&AMP;add-NYTSF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ It is, by common consent, the most important trade
vote in Congress since the approval of the North American
Free-Trade Agreement (NAFTA) in 1993. When the House of
Representatives decided next week whether to give China
most-favored-nation trading status on a permanent basis (PNTR),
very little will actually change. But the crucial vote will have
far-reaching repercussions for both countries _ and for both
political parties. Place your bets, gentlemen _ it's going to be a
cliffhanger. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Three optional trims, totaling 325; total uncut is
1,300) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INDONESIAN INDECISION: `RIVER' WAHID MEANDERS DANGEROUSLY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WAVERING-WAHID-ECONOMIST-525&AMP;add-NYTSF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ When he was no more than a leading Islamic figure
and part-time opposition politician, Abdurrahman Wahid was known
for his sometimes bewildering changes of course. These rarely
disconcerted his admirers, one of whom compared him to a river.
Viewed from on high, he seemed to be meandering all over the place.
Go with the flow, however, and you would find he was always moving
in the same general direction. Unfortunately, Wahid's
seven-month-old government presides over an Indonesia that is far
from stable. If he is not to follow in the steps of his ousted
predecessor, President Suharto, Wahid needs to chart a straight and
steady course _ and stick to it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Story can stand in 525 words; 800 uncut) &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SIERRA LEONE: SAVED BY THE CAVALRY _ BUT NOW WHAT? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DESPAIRA-LEONE-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ The cavalry, in the form of seven British warships
and 1,000 British paratroopers and marines, thundered in and
secured Freetown, the capital of Sierra Leone. Foday Sankoh, the
rebel leader, has been captured. Extra U.N. troops are being flown
in to provide security in the rest of the country. Are Sierra
Leone's troubles now on the way to being solved? Alas, far from
it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (800 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RAMALLAH RIOTS: PALESTINE'S PRECURSOR OF THINGS TO COME &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WESTBANK-WARNING-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RAMALLAH _ In the worst bout of violence for several years,
thousands of Palestinians battled with the Israeli army on May 15.
They were marking al-Nakba Day: the term Palestinians use for the
``catastrophe'' of Israel's establishment and their dispossession
from most of Palestine. The al-Nakba anniversary always casts a
sombre pall over Palestinians, wherever they are. But this time, in
the West Bank and Gaza, the violence was fuelled by other, more
incendiary causes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (725 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEWLY REARMED, ETHIOPIA AND ERITREA FIGHT TO THE DEATH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENDGAME-ETHIOPIA-ERITREA-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ The Ethiopians came in waves, like ghosts from the
battle of the Somme transported to the parched Mereb Valley that
forms the border between Ethiopia and Eritrea. And, as at the Somme
in 1916, they were cut down in their thousands. But Ethiopia's
human-wave advance was more successful than earlier invasions of
the same kind. After two years of an intermittently ferocious war,
this could be the start of the Ethiopian-Eritrean endgame. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (900 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHOLLY TOLEDO?: WHO'LL WIN PERU'S PRESIDENTIAL RUNOFF? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PERU-MAY28-PUZZLE-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LIMA _ The first vote produced an expectedly close result: in
the runoff, the candidate of the governing coalition won by less
than three percentage points. But the result was declared within
hours, the defeated candidate embraced the victor and, under an
unquestionably legitimate government, the economy is now steaming
ahead. That was Chile's presidential vote in January. Unfortunately
for Peru, the outcome of the runoff in its presidential election,
due on May 28, may be much less happy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (TIMELY for Peru's May 28 runoff election) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (975 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HAITI'S DUBIOUS CHANCES FOR MAY 21 ELECTION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HAITI-BALLOTBUSTERS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE _ Political opposition in Haiti is getting more
dangerous by the day. One parliamentary candidate narrowly escaped
a firebombing. Another candidate was kidnapped for 12 days and
beaten. And on May 9, a rural leader of the coalition party and his
son were murdered. The perpetrators have claimed to be from the
Lavalas Family, the political party of Jean-Bertrand Aristide, the
predecessor and mentor of Haiti's current president, Rene Preval.
Will such intimidation and violence prevent local and parliamentary
elections from proceeding on May 21 as scheduled? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (TIMELY for May 21) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (550 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BRAZILIAN-FRENCHMAN STEERS NISSAN DOWN ROAD TO RECOVERY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NISSAN-`MR.FIXIT'-ECONOMIST-700&AMP;add-NYTSF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ He's something of a hybrid Superman: a
Brazilian-Frenchman who now runs Japan's beleaguered,
second-largest car company, Nissan. Carlos Ghosn used to be the
chief operating officer at Renault, France's biggest car company,
where he made his considerable reputation as ``le cost cutter.''
Indeed, Ghosn paved the way for Renault's dramatic turnaround after
he arrived there from the Michelin tire company. Now he must
perform the same, badly needed magic at Nissan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Business Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Two optional trims, totaling 450; 1,500 uncut) &QL;
</P>
