<P>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE _ Political opposition in Haiti is getting more
dangerous by the day. One parliamentary candidate narrowly escaped
a firebombing. Another candidate was kidnapped for 12 days and
beaten. And on May 9, a rural leader of the coalition party and his
son were murdered. The perpetrators have claimed to be from the
Lavalas Family, the political party of Jean-Bertrand Aristide, the
predecessor and mentor of Haiti's current president, Rene Preval.
Will such intimidation and violence prevent local and parliamentary
elections from proceeding on May 21 as scheduled? &QL;
