<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEKKIE-YACHTS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMOOTH-SAILING ECONOMY BOOSTS LUXURY BOAT SALES  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 475-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   ANNAPOLIS, MD. _ Is the high-tech party over, as Nasdaq bucks
and slides? Not if messing about in boats is anything to go by.
</P>
<P>
   Buying something that needs a rudder has always been an
indicator of economic confidence (few people need a boat to take
the children to school).
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two years, yachting and power-boating have taken
off in a big way, especially among the techies of the Pacific
Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   James Denn, executive editor of Boating Industry International
magazine, reports that total sales in the American recreational
boating market were up more than 19 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the plushest yachts actually come from Germany. But
Sailing/Cruising World magazine still reckons that sailing-boat
production in North America increased by 16 percent from 1998 to
1999, with strong growth in the large (over 36-foot) boat sector.
</P>
<P>
   Boating-accessory sales are booming, too. Don Durant, the owner
of Club Nautique/Cruising Specialists, a San Francisco firm, has
seen fresh demand for his products at close hand. Since March 1999
``it's been almost straight uphill.''
</P>
<P>
   Are his customers mostly the IT crowd? ``And how! We're close to
Silicon Valley so we're seeing a huge increase in buyers with cash
as opposed to credit. Lots of people with bonuses, options,
founder's stock, etc.''
</P>
<P>
   Three thousand miles away in Annapolis, Md., Rob Emmet, the
owner of Performance Yacht Systems, a boating-accessory e-business
set up in 1997, noticed demand from areas such as Silicon Valley
and the Northwest almost immediately. Orders came from the Seattle
area ``even before we advertised.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology folk are not known for their love of natural light,
let alone the great outdoors. Boats seem to be an exception.
</P>
<P>
   The influence of technology gurus such as Bill Gates
(Microsoft), Larry Ellison (Oracle) and Jim Clark (Netscape), all
owners of extremely sleek sail or power yachts, cannot be
discounted.
</P>
<P>
   Durant says he saw a flow diagram published recently showing the
steps to going public. One of the steps was ``Order new yacht.''
</P>
<P>
   A good deal of this watery enthusiasm has been sated on borrowed
money.
</P>
<P>
   The National Marine Bankers Association recorded a 25 percent
growth in marine loans booked for 1998, with similar figures
expected for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom in the industry holds that interest-rate
fluctuations have a great impact on the purchase of boats. Now
people are beginning to talk about there being so much credit
available that the old rules no longer apply.
</P>
<P>
   The link between boating and confidence in laptop land appears
to be a strong one. Despite the travails of Nasdaq, larger
purchases are still holding up.
</P>
<P>
   When the high-tech admirals start leaving their vessels at the
pier, it may be time to bail out. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 0250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
