<SLUG> BC-SINGER-NEIL-YOUNG-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREVER YOUNG: NEIL YOUNG REVISITS HIS PAST WITH AN EYE ON THE
FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of singer Neil Young.) 
 By GARY GRAFF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Neil Young is on the outside, looking in. Literally.
 &HT;    Sporting a long, dark coat, a T-shirt and jeans, the singer has
stepped into a hallway at the stately Driskill Hotel in Austin,
Texas, to greet an interviewer, only to let the door to his room
shut behind him.
 &HT;    ``I left my key in there,'' he says, more bemused than sheepish.
 &HT;    Fortunately, there are a couple of couches in the hall, so Young
shrugs.
 &HT;    ``Let's just do it out here,'' he says, and sits down for an
interview.
 &HT;    It's a day off between tour dates for Crosby, Stills, Nash &AMP;
Young in Charlotte, N.C., and in Pittsburgh, so Young has dropped
into Austin to premiere ``Silver &AMP; Gold,'' a concert DVD _ sharing
the name of his latest album _ that was filmed at Austin's Bass
Concert Hall during his 1999 solo tour.
 &HT;    Like many entries in Young's canon, ``Silver &AMP; Gold'' has a
history far more convoluted than the simple recording of an album.
It's another one of the periodic forays into gentler, acoustic
music that dot Young's catalog, alongside the roaring electric rock
of Crazy Horse and his ambitious, underrated detours into country,
blues and rockabilly.
 &HT;    It's an area that has also brought Young his greatest commercial
successes: ``After the Goldrush'' (1970) and ``Harvest'' (1972)
were multimillion-sellers, and the latter is Young's only album to
hit No. 1. ``Comes a Time'' (1978) also made its way into the Top
10, while ``Harvest Moon'' (1992) was another million-seller.
 &HT;    So wood and steel clearly suit the Toronto-born Young _ though
he says that has nothing to do with his decision to make this
particular album.
 &HT;    ``There's no real logic to it,'' says the 55-year-old Rock and
Roll Hall of Fame honoree _ twice, actually, once on his own and
once with his 1960s band Buffalo Springfield. ``I may make two
rock-'n'-roll albums in a row at some point, or I may do two soft
ones in a row. I may do some different kind of album that everybody
wonders what the hell I did that for. It just depends.
 &HT;    ``There's no plan,'' he says. ``I'm just going with the songs _
the songs dictate the direction. There's no way to tell where the
songs are going to come from and when, so there's no need for a
plan. I just wait.''
 &HT;    ``Silver &AMP; Gold'' began life in 1997, when Young returned to his
ranch near Woodside, Calif., after a tour with Crazy Horse. He had
a variety of projects to work on, including his long-planned
boxed-set retrospective and an extensive Buffalo Springfield
anthology, but he found himself drawn back into the studio.
 &HT;    ``I came back and recorded a couple of tunes that I had written
on the road,'' he recalls. ``I recorded them just solo acoustic,
and then I went on and recorded a bunch of tunes with the band over
time.
 &HT;    ``Every three months or so we'd get together and play a little
more,'' Young continues. ``I'd write a few more tunes and we'd do
them, and I'd do some old songs at the same time, just for feel and
so we had enough songs to do to make it worth it for everybody to
come.
 &HT;    ``Sometimes I'd just throw those in to have something to do to
get warmed up with,'' he adds, ``and in this case we caught a
couple of them and we got masters on them, which was a big surprise
that they actually came to the party.''
 &HT;    Among those, Young says, was the first single, ``Razor Love,''
which was originally written for ``Trans'' (1982) but not used, and
the title track, which had long baffled him.
 &HT;    ```Silver &AMP; Gold' I recorded 11 times,'' he says, ``and didn't
like any of the recordings because, as soon as the band learned the
song, it sounded contrived. The song's so simple that once you
actually started playing parts _ `Wow, that's terrible.'
 &HT;    ``It's better if it's just simple,'' Young says. ``They're the
kind of songs that have to be performed in a way that is real _ you
have to deliver the song.''
 &HT;    There's a settled, calming nature to ``Silver &AMP; Gold.'' Its
songs are sweet, warm and even sentimental, celebrating romance,
family and friendships with an open, genial spirit.
 &HT;    It isn't the album Young set out to make, however, or even the
one he actually had finished when he hit the road to tour in 1999.
 &HT;    While he was working on the album, Young was also compiling the
Buffalo Springfield box set, and eventually he invited former
bandmate Stephen Stills out to the ranch to listen to the songs
with him. Stills played a song that he was working on for an new
album with David Crosby and Graham Nash, and ended up inviting
Young to join them in recording the number.
 &HT;    One thing led to another, and soon a full-fledged CSNY reunion
was up and running. For his contribution, Young offered up the
songs he'd recorded for ``Silver &AMP; Gold.''
 &HT;    ``I said, `Just take the ones you want, they're yours. Go ahead
and take the best ones that you think we can do the best job on,'''
he recalls.
 &HT;    By the time CSNY's ``Looking Forward'' was done, Young was short
four of his own album's original 14 tracks, but he says the end
result actually benefited ``Silver &AMP; Gold.''
 &HT;    ``I'd listened to `Silver &AMP; Gold' a bunch of times, and I could
never get the sequence right,'' he explains. ``It always seemed too
heavy to me. It was a revelation to me, after trying for a year to
sequence this thing in a way that would work right for me and never
feeling right about it, that I really received the perfect
combination by letting them take the cream of the crop, whatever
they wanted.
 &HT;    ``So it worked out great _ I'm ecstatic about it.''
 &HT;    Young did cut two additional tracks, ``The Great Divide'' and
``Buffalo Springfield Again.'' The latter is, perhaps, the most
attention-getting track on ``Silver &AMP; Gold.'' A pleasant, jaunty
tune _ ``kind of Sunday afternoon,'' Young calls it _ it's filled
with sentiments such as ``Like to see those guys again/and give it
a shot.''
 &HT;    So is he officially proposing a reunion? Young says no.
 &HT;    ``I don't know if the Springfield will ever play again,'' he
says. ``I played with Dewey Martin and Bruce Palmer a couple of
years ago, at my ranch for a couple of days. I wasn't playing much,
because that was right after I cut my finger _ I had a big
(bandage) on my finger, so I really couldn't play that much. But we
had fun, so anything's possible.''
 &HT;    As for CSNY, there too Young is reluctant to commit to anything
beyond the current tour.
 &HT;    ``We'll stop for a while,'' he says opaquely, ``and see what
we're going to do after that.''
 &HT;    Next on his agenda is bringing out the Buffalo Springfield boxed
set and possibly the first installment of an eight-CD set that will
track his solo career from 1969 to 1972.
 &HT;    As far as original music is concerned, however, he remains
vague.
 &HT;    ``Again, I don't really have an idea of what the next song I'm
going to write is about,'' he says. ``I don't ever know. I don't
try to know ...
 &HT;    ``I have a notebook in my room,'' he says. ``I have a guitar in
my room, I have a piano in my room. Everywhere I go, I like to have
musical instruments ... so I'm ready when something comes.''
 c.2000 Gary Graff  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Gary Graff is a Beverly Hills, Mich.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site
at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
