<SLUG> BC-KENNETH-BRANAGH-IN-LOVES-LABOURS-LOST-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROADWAY BARD?: KENNETH BRANAGH FILMS A SHAKESPEARE MUSICAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Kenneth Branagh with Matthew Lillard,
Alessandro Nivola and Adrian Lester in a scene from ``Love's
Labour's Lost.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Believe it or not, his new musical version of Shakespeare's
``Love's Labour's Lost'' isn't an entirely new departure for the
acclaimed actor/director Kenneth Branagh.
 &HT;    ``I know I have this reputation as Mr. Serious,'' Branagh says.
``But few know I do have a musical background, which seems to have
fallen off my resume.''
 &HT;    In fact, one of his first professional jobs after graduating
from the Royal Academy of Dramatic Art was in a London production
of the Gershwins' ``Lady Be Good.''
 &HT;    ``I was a waiter in the background chorus,'' Branagh recalls,
relaxing at Los Angeles' Four Seasons hotel. ``To tell you the
truth, it was the most fun I've ever had doing live theater. The
pressure was off _ all I had to do was pop up from behind a little
window with this huge tray of drinks.
 &HT;    ``Of course, the only hard part was praying I didn't drop
anything.''
 &HT;    ``Love's Labour's Lost'' is more demanding, calling on Branagh
and most of his cast _ including Nathan Lane, Matthew Lillard and
Alicia Silverstone _ to sing, dance and generally kick up their
heels in a complicated story of three aristocrats who vow to give
up women and devote their lives to scholarly study.
 &HT;    ``I admit that I was in a daffy mood when the concept came into
my mind,'' says Branagh, who also wrote the screenplay and
directed. ``I thought to myself, `OK, I've done ``Henry V'' (1989)
and ``Othello'' (1995) and ``Hamlet'' (1996) the straight way. Now
here is this obscure work by Shakespeare _ you know, the one play
in the entire Shakespearean canon that was not performed for maybe
200 years after his death.
 &HT;    ``It's a very funny vaudevillian comedy about a war of the
sexes,'' Branagh hastens to add, ``but it does have a rather
melancholy ending which left the audience unsatisfied. I said, `I
want to take all of the above and do it in a really different
manner.' I said, `I know! I'll do it as a '30s musical, full of
songs by Cole Porter and George Gershwin!''
 &HT;    ``At which point,'' he admits, ``I started having these
recurring nightmares where people screamed, `What the hell was he
thinking?' Or, quite simply, `Branagh has snapped. News at 11.'''
 &HT;    Part of his desire to do a musical stemmed from his role as a
crippled mad scientist in last summer's flop ``Wild Wild West.''
 &HT;    ``I was stuck in a wheelchair for that entire movie, playing
this deranged villain,'' Branagh says. ``Honestly, I felt this mass
amount of impotent rage at being so confined. It really did make me
angry at others for their mobility.
 &HT;    ``I thought, `What can I do that is the direct opposite of this
situation?''' he says. ``The only thing I could think of was that I
could sing and dance.'''
 &HT;    He had feared that the Porter and Gershwin estates would be wary
of lending their songs for so bizarre a project, but was pleasantly
surprised to find them helpful.
 &HT;    ``They were very cooperative. The songs cost money, but I got
them,'' Branagh says. ``I think both estates are just very
concerned in the way the songs are used. But they both told me,
based on the relationship I had with Shakespeare, they knew I would
use the songs with respect.''
 &HT;    The hardest part of the whole thing, the British actor says, was
writing a screenplay that would be accessible to modern audiences.
 &HT;    ``It was very painstaking, intricate work to find the right
balance,'' Branagh says. ``The hard part was deciding how quickly
or slowly you should come out of the song. Should I cut immediately
to dialogue? Or give people a moment to say, `Hey, they're not
singing anymore'?
 &HT;    ``Also, I didn't want to offer this thing up like a theater
piece,'' he adds. ``I didn't want each song to be a show-stopper,
with a pause as if I was waiting for an audience to applaud the
number.''
 &HT;    Casting was easier _ even the controversial choice of Alicia
Silverstone as the princess whose arrival destroys the men's serene
retreat.
 &HT;    Yes, Batgirl does the Bard. And a swimming-pool dance number, to
boot.
 &HT;    ``She will shock people,'' Branagh says. ``She turns in a great
performance. Alicia speaks as if she was a Shakespearean natural.
It's like she was born to do this work _ which you might find
unbelievable, but it's true.''
 &HT;    And she sings well enough that Branagh claims to be more worried
about his own contribution to the soundtrack, including a rendition
of the Gershwin classic ``They Can't Take That Away From Me.''
 &HT;    ``I just hope the audience doesn't stand to leave when I get up
to sing,'' he says.
 &HT;    In recent years, Branagh has made fewer of his own movies,
instead lending his acting services to films as diverse as Robert
Altman's ``The Gingerbread Man'' (1998), Woody Allen's
``Celebrity'' (1998) and ``Wild Wild West.'' Still, he says, his
heart is in filmmaking.
 &HT;    ``Most times I would rather direct, but only if the subject
matter is compelling for me,'' he says. ``I often feel like I must
direct this project or I can't do it at all. The whole thing
bubbles away at me for two or three years, until I'm just dying to
get behind that camera. I've made note after note. In my sleep,
when I'm awake _ I'm often just consumed with a movie.''
 &HT;    In his early career, every project Branagh touched seemed to be
charmed. Shortly after graduating from the Academy, he was accepted
into the Royal Shakespeare Company, for which he starred in ``Henry
V'' and ``Hamlet.'' He went on to form his own troupe, the
Renaissance Theater Company _ through which he met former wife Emma
Thompson _ and then to a triumphant film debut as director and star
of ``Henry V,'' a success that led to two more hits, ``Dead Again''
(1991) and ``Much Ado About Nothing'' (1993).
 &HT;    In 1994, however, he came a cropper with ``Mary Shelley's
Frankenstein.''
 &HT;    ``It taught me that I wasn't the golden boy,'' he says. ``I
could fumble.''
 &HT;    Thereafter Branagh lived through a series of ups and downs, with
successes such as ``Hamlet'' balanced by flops such as ``The
Gingerbread Man'' and ``The Theory of Flight'' (1998).
 &HT;    Offscreen he endured similar tumult, divorcing Thompson to take
up with Helena Bonham Carter, from whom he recently split. The
resulting tabloid frenzy was disconcerting to the privacy-loving
actor.
 &HT;    ``Being in the spotlight has made me feel very uncomfortable at
times,'' he admits. ``I've just wanted to do the work _ to act, to
direct, to be a creative person.
 &HT;    ``But understand that it's a learning process,'' he adds. ``I
was just a slip of a boy when I made `Henry V.' I was 27 when we
made the film, and no one sat me down and said, `Now, Kenneth, your
entire world is about to change.'
 &HT;    ``But what I'm most grateful for is that the fame buys me a
ticket into a room where I can pitch a movie like a Shakespearean
musical,'' he adds, more cheerfully. ``It's humbling when someone
hands me a check and says, `I believe in you.' It's humbling when a
movie opens, and someone writes me a letter saying it affected
their life.
 &HT;    ``At such moments I'm reminded of how these projects touch
people, and it's all worth it.''
 c.2000 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Love's Labour's Lost,''
consult the official Web site at www.loveslabourslost.com. And
