<SLUG> BC-JASON-ROBARDS-LOOKS-BACK-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE 2: TURNER CLASSIC CAPTURES HOLLYWOOD HISTORY ON FILM 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of actor Jason Robards.) 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Sam Peckinpah, Fred Zinneman, Katharine Hepburn, Hank Fonda,
Lana Turner, Dalton Trumbo, Sergio Leone, Jason Robards Sr.,
Jonathan Demme. ``A Thousand Clowns,'' ``All the President's Men''
and ``Magnolia.''
 &HT;    The stars, movies and stories spill from Jason Robards' lips,
and there's no hiding his enthusiasm. For nearly an hour, the
77-year-old actor has sat and recounted his memories for an
ambitious archival project undertaken by Turner Classic Movies, the
cable channel that specializes in old-time Hollywood films.
 &HT;    Afterward, Robards warmly shakes hands with his interviewer,
producer Alexa Foreman, and steps into another room at the
Swissotel in Manhattan. Despite recent health scares, Robards
remains tall and strong, and the sparkle in his eyes is
undiminished.
 &HT;    ``I enjoyed that,'' he says. ``I hope I didn't talk too much
about myself. I still have no idea who I am, but maybe I'm the sum
of all the projects I've been in, the history of the movies and the
stage that I've been a part of. I'm probably a witness to history,
more than a part of it.
 &HT;    ``It's so funny to think I've devoted all of my life to the
stage and not done big movies I was offered because I wanted to do
a play instead,'' he adds. ``I like to think, `I'm a stage actor,'
but sitting here I realized I've done 60-odd films.
 &HT;    ``How the hell did I fit that in? I'm not that old that I could
have done 60 films.''
 &HT;    He managed, and even won back-to-back Oscars for supporting
performances in ``All the President's Men'' (1976) and ``Julia''
(1976).
 &HT;    ``Whether the films or plays turned out good or bad is really
not the point,'' Robards says. ``The point for me was to be a part
of what the author put down on paper, to help give life to it.
That's the true art of movies and stage, taking words and bringing
them to life.
 &HT;    ``It all begins with the words,'' he says. ``I've been
interested in words all of my life _ the words propel our business,
and I don't know if enough actors know that. The more they know it,
the better they are.''
 &HT;    Robards' interview is only the latest installment in the TCM
archives project, which since 1994 has included more than 200
people, among them such actors, directors and behind-the-scenes
people as Marge Champion, Cyd Charisse, Betty Comden, Stanley
Donen, Farley Granger, Garson Kanin, Lena Horne, Andre Previn, Rod
Steiger and Gloria Stuart.
 &HT;    ``Our goal is to preserve as much history of the motion-picture
industry as we can,'' Foreman says. ``By doing it on film the
people look good and sound good and, to me, it's better than an
oral history. You're able to see these people, their mannerisms,
gestures and expressions.
 &HT;    ``People love movies,'' she adds. ``and it's important to
remember how it all began. A number of the people who were there at
the time are dying, unfortunately, and that makes what we're doing
urgent.
 &HT;    ``Thank God for Kevin Brownlow and David Gill, who'd already
done their television documentaries and got most of the people from
the silent-film era,'' Foreman says. ``If we'd started our project
today, we'd have lost 15 percent of the people.''
 &HT;    Responsibility for lining up _ and, sometimes, locating _ the
interviewees falls to Darcy Hettrich, director of talent for TCM
and Turner Network Television.
 &HT;    ``Some of the names we all know, and they're still active and
still working,'' she says. ``But the obscure ones are tough.
Sometimes we get someone who comes in and has a great time _ we had
Ricardo Montalban and George Wells, who were both using walkers,
racing down the hall together _ and that someone puts us in touch
with two or three people we'd love to get. Or we'll follow a small
lead from an article. We'll call the writer and say, `Where did you
find so-and-so?'''
 &HT;    Foreman and Hettrich can't grab everybody, however. Among those
they'd most like to talk to _ but who have, for reasons obvious and
not so obvious, remained elusive _ are Kirk Douglas, Sue Mengers,
Nancy Reagan, Ray Stark, Billy Wilder and Elia Kazan.
 &HT;    While waiting patiently for those folks, Foreman and Hettrich
continue to corral a dozen or more people for two several-day
sessions held twice a year, once each in New York and in Los
Angeles. During one March weekend in New York, TCM trained its
camera on Robards, Budd Schulberg, Gwen Verdon, Jane Powell, Skitch
Henderson and others.
 &HT;    Verdon may be best known as a hoofer, a multiple Tony Award
winner who is also the former wife of the legendary choreographer
Bob Fosse, but she also appeared in the film version of ``Damn
Yankees'' (1958), in which she reprised her Broadway role as the
seductive demon Lola. She returned to the big screen 25 years later
for non-musical roles in ``The Cotton Club'' (1984), ``Cocoon''
(1985), ``Marvin's Room'' (1996) and the upcoming ``Walking Across
Egypt.''
 &HT;    ``I'd forgotten about some of the earlier things I'd done,''
Verdon says by telephone from her Long Island home, her voice still
bourbon over gravel. ``Actually, I remember the films, but I hadn't
thought about them or talked about them in years.
 &HT;    ``People still think of me as Lola,'' she says, ``and that's
part of the reason I was supposedly away so long. I took three
years off after my daughter was born, and then it took me a long
time to convince people that I could play older women, such as in
`Marvin's Room.'
 &HT;    ``As I say, they still think of me as Lola. I should probably
take that as a compliment, but it was also frustrating.''
 &HT;    Henderson, currently music director of the New York Pops, has
spent his life on television and the concert stage. Still, he has
some unique Hollywood memories to impart: As a young pianist in the
1930s, he worked with Charlie Chaplin, and served as a rehearsal
accompanist for Judy Garland and Mickey Rooney and for Fred Astaire
and Ginger Rogers.
 &HT;    ``I was just a beginner,'' Henderson, now 82, says by telephone
from his Manhattan apartment. ``I didn't get any star billing, I
wasn't to be photographed or talked about. But that period was my
education _ Hollywood was my high school and college.
 &HT;    ``I remember walking onto a sound stage for the first time and
hearing Max Steiner conducting an orchestra at Warner Bros.,'' the
conductor says. ``I remember first playing in an orchestra on a
sound stage at MGM. I was a rehearsal pianist and generally didn't
play with the orchestra _ I worked individually with people.
 &HT;    ``If it hadn't been for World War II,'' he adds, ``I probably
would have made it for a while, then disappeared like everybody
else. But I wouldn't change a thing _ I learned a lot in Hollywood
and now, being at Carnegie Hall, I've got my Valhalla.''
 &HT;    Like almost everyone who has stepped before the camera for TCM's
archival project, Henderson considers it an effort of great
importance.
 &HT;    ``Somebody has to take care of the history,'' he says,
``because, if nobody does, it will all disappear downstream. I'm
astounded that so many people have no concept of what this world
was like. Rock 'n' roll killed the music, and television killed the
film business. Between the rock 'n' roll and television, it was a
hell of a blow to all of us.
 &HT;    ``So I'm thrilled that someone is taking the time to look back
and get on the record what happened so many years ago.''
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
