<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Not the retiring type
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ A fellow I went to school with _ who is
currently slipping up on 60, same as I am _ says he's thinking
about retiring in a couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   I've had similar thoughts from time to time. Then I ask myself,
``Retire from what?''
</P>
<P>
   But he's got a different deal, getting up before the sun's up
most mornings, being the first person at the office, maintaining a
strict schedule of working hard, helping others and doing good.
</P>
<P>
   One time, with the idea of encouraging him to slow down a bit, I
suggested he ought to stop by my house on his way to work for a cup
of coffee.
</P>
<P>
   He said fine, that I could look for him about 5:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   I allowed that I was suddenly having second thoughts about the
extent of my hospitality, and that in fact if he came knocking on
my door at such an hour, I would sic the dogs on him.
</P>
<P>
   Entertaining a good friend is one thing. Interrupting a good
night's sleep is something else.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, he now tells me he may be able to alter his
schedule more to my liking in the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   That'll be a big change for him, seeing as how he's had a job
since he was in the third grade. I asked him what he planned to do
once he quit working himself night and day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not anything for the first year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Good thinking. I read recently that Tom Dewey gave Richard Nixon
much the same advice when Nixon found himself in early retirement
as a result of the 1960 presidential election: Don't make any
important decisions for at least six months. Best to let your brain
calm itself down first.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon, who may or may not have ever got his brain calmed down,
similarly advised George Bush when he lost out to Bill Clinton in
1992. So it was that Bush waited awhile before he started jumping
out of airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Getting back to my friend, he did mention, more than once, that
one thing he'd like to do is cultivate the habit of having a
leisurely breakfast, meeting with friends at the coffee shops,
catching up on the local gossip.
</P>
<P>
   What with his work schedule, that's something he's missed out on
all these years. Just opposite for me. It was always part of my
job.
</P>
<P>
   As a young reporter, sitting in coffee shops, I could get more
news from a back booth than I could the front page. Never mind that
most of it you couldn't print.
</P>
<P>
   That's how I got to be so well-rounded, more especially with a
regular diet of fried eggs and ham, pancakes and grits, biscuits
and gravy.
</P>
<P>
   I wish my friend all the best in his impending retirement. He
can even have my old spot at the back booth.
</P>
<P>
   This word of advice for him on entering small town cafe society:
Don't believe everything you hear or tell everything you know, and
you'll do just fine.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(AT)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
