<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Finding someone other than Haider to blame
 &HT;    (Eds: Palaces cq in 2nd graf. For release May 24, 2000.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA _ What was it that Virgil warned us about almost 2,000
years ago; oh, yes: ``Whatever it is, I fear Greeks even when they
bring gifts.'' I should have known better than to accept the offer
of coffee from Neco; there was a price to pay, a double price _ one
in coin, the other in inference.
</P>
<P>
   Neco Karakas is a roly-poly guy who emigrated from Greece to
Austria and has an upscale souvenir shop just across from Vienna's
Belvedere Palaces. It was while we were having a light breakfast at
a coffee shop next door that Neco came into my life, marching into
the room, proclaiming his recognition of the American visitors and
offering to buy us a cup of coffee ``just from my heart,'' as he
clutched his fist to his chest.
</P>
<P>
   I accepted because he seemed like an interesting person with
whom to discuss Austria's political arsonist Joerg Haider, Neco
being an immigrant, and Haider's Freedom Party riding into the
nation's parliament on an anti-immigration platform (in addition to
Haider's sympathy with things Hitlerian).
</P>
<P>
   That's where I got fooled.
</P>
<P>
   Even scapegoats have to have scapegoats _ and Neco has his.
</P>
<P>
   Before he drew us into his shop for repayment of the cup of
coffee (purchased: a decent print of Gustav Klimt's ``The Kiss,''
the real thing on display just across the street at the Upper
Palace), Neco had astonished me.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner had I asked him about Haider's impact on Austria _
expecting a diatribe against the man and his party that blames the
nation's problems on the influx of immigrants such as he _ than
Neco targeted what he said was the real problem: Jews.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long to get there. I asked Neco how business was
doing since so many nations imposed sanctions on Austria after
Haider's troops were elected and accepted into the government. It
was bad compared to last year, he said, but he added that it was
all the fault of the Israelis and ``the American Jewish
what-do-you-call-it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The American Jewish lobby?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, the lobby. None of this (the sanctions) would have
happened if it wasn't for the Jews. They made a big thing of
this.''
</P>
<P>
   I hadn't realized that. I don't think too many others had too. I
also don't believe it. I believe much of the rest of the world felt
strongly about the Austrian government's acquiescence to Haiderism.
</P>
<P>
   What I realized about Neco, however, is that when things go bad,
there has to be someone to blame and who else is handier than the
Jews?
</P>
<P>
   This, I decided, was not the time or place to reveal my
religious affiliation, better to just listen to the man who
apparently has yet to realize that he, an immigrant, is the target
of a turbulent reaction that is agitating not only Austria but all
of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration, particularly illegal immigration, is a flashpoint
across the continent as it is elsewhere, but moreso; it has given
succor to extremists such as Haider.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps with Neco, things are a little different. Likely, he has
become part of the establishment _ an immigrant, yes, but one who
has been around long enough to buy his own place and defend it
against the hordes of others who would enter the country and want
it also.
</P>
<P>
   But his ledger book has been assaulted by international
sanctions and Neco needs a specific culprit.
</P>
<P>
   So the ``Jewish lobby'' came in handy, as it has so many times
before.
</P>
<P>
   The conversation didn't venture much past that, Neco wanted to
sell us something after his gift of coffee. So my wife and I
entered his shop and, despite his misplaced acrimony, purchased the
print of ``The Kiss.''
</P>
<P>
   Likely, the only customers he had that day were a couple of
Jews. Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
