<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Unions' narrow interests threaten China bill
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   All that congressional Democrats are being asked to do this week
is to vote in the manifest national interest, but with the AFL-CIO
pulling them the other way it is unclear how many will approve
permanent trade with China.
</P>
<P>
   With business lobbying hard for a yes vote, this is a no-brainer
for most Republicans. It comes naturally to them. And the pitch for
support from a cohort of China's own dissidents has given cover
even to the GOPers who have been grandstanding against China's
lousy human rights record.
</P>
<P>
   (Interestingly, many in Congress who fulminate against political
oppression, party-line justice and authoritarianism in China have
shrugged off comparable and worse flaws in right-wing regimes as
mere imperfections.)
</P>
<P>
   But asking Democrats to go against labor's passionate, and
well-heeled, opposition to the bill is like asking a dog to walk on
its hind legs. The act is unnatural and even the ones with a little
practice are awkward at it.
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO has a long and honorable tradition of supporting the
rights of workers in repressive countries. That was especially so
of its solidarity with the straining reformist movements in the
East Bloc countries under the Soviet thumb.
</P>
<P>
   But labor's opposition to permanent trade status for China is
part of its more recent, broad-brush antagonism to international
trade in general, and that antagonism is, at its core, merely
protectionist _ a self-interested recoil from economic competition
that could swipe some U.S. jobs from older production industries
even as it creates more and often better-paying jobs in fields
outside labor's historic base.
</P>
<P>
   Chronically second-best to Republicans in political
money-grubbing, Democratic candidates are disproportionately
dependent upon, and beholden to, union largess. A vote to back
President Clinton's pitch for trade menaces a Democratic
representative's or senator's re-election funding with no prospect
of offsetting votes from a largely indifferent electorate.
</P>
<P>
   More than a little pious blather has been hooted on behalf of
the bill. No, bringing China fully into the international trade
system will not start a momentum toward inevitable democracy or
seed a flowering garden of dissent.
</P>
<P>
   It will, however, push China toward the development of
predictable, politically independent business law, potentially a
start on other at least marginal reforms. It will involve China in
a commercial network in which China's own interests will favor
international stability over international mischief.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, reliable trade with China will be good for U.S.
businesses, especially agriculture. That may weigh lightly in any
elegant moral assay of the issue, but it is no bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   With any unilateral U.S. attempt to marginalize and harry China
over trade unlikely to force Beijing to see the human rights light,
there is simply no good reason to cede the territory to
unhesitating Japanese and European competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is a columnist for Cox Newspapers. He is based in
Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
