<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PHARMACY-TOBACCO (San Francisco) _ California's top health
official last year tried to head off an anti-smoking media blitz
targeting a drugstore chain that had donated $130,000 to Gov. Gray
Davis. By LANCE WILLIAMS.
</P>
<P>
   PRIEST-ABUSE (San Francisco) _ On the verge of an embarrassing
civil trial, the Archdiocese of San Francisco has reached a
settlement in the case prompted by a teenage rectory worker who
accused his pastor of physical and mental abuse. By ELIZABETH
FERNANDEZ.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-COLUMN (San Antonio) _ Many General Motors and Ford cars
and trucks are equipped with a device similar to an airliner's
flight data recorder, which automatically records the vehicle's
speed and other information for the five seconds leading to an
air-bag deployment. Until now, it was difficult to extract that
information. A California company is selling a device that connects
a car's onboard computer to a police officer's laptop computer to
quickly extract information from a crashed vehicle. By G. CHAMBERS
WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-PT-CRUISER (Undated) _ The 2001 Chrysler PT Cruiser is just
about the coolest-looking car to come along since, probably, the
Plymouth Prowler in 1997. Granted, it's not quite as cool as the
Prowler, and not nearly as exciting, from a purely performance
standpoint. But it's a lot more practical than the Prowler. By G.
CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BAY-TO-BREAKERS (San Francisco) _ Reuben Cheruiyot messed around
for a couple of miles _ at least by his lofty standards. He was
content to poke along with the pack in the early stages of the 89th
Examiner Bay to Breakers on Sunday, in a race that seemed to be
stuck in cement. The pace was so slow that unseeded runners and
guys jumping into the action from off the curbs along Sixth Street
actually managed to keep up with the top-rated men for more than a
moment or two. Then the 26-year-old Cheruiyot, another in that
seemingly endless cookie-cutter line of Kenyans, decided to get
serious. By DWIGHT CHAPIN.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTRIC-BIKE (Undated) _ Welcome to the latest twist in the
environmentally friendly, politically correct commute: the electric
bicycle, a product of a company founded and owned by automotive
icon Lee Iacocca. EV Global Motors Co. of Los Angeles manufactures
the E-bike, a retro-looking bicycle similar to the Schwinns of the
'50s, has regular pedals and seven gears, so it can go almost
anywhere on human power, with virtually no limitations. By G.
CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   AEROBIC-EXERCISES (Albany, N.Y.) _ Experts say low-impact
exercises, such as water aerobics, cycling and walking, are as
effective over the long term as running and weight-lifting. These
lower-impact sports build fitness and bones without a higher risk
of injury. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   BOY-TOYS (San Antonio) _ Boys have baseball cards. Now girls
have their own set of trading cards and the subject is _ boys. A
Norfolk, Va., company's Boy Crazy! CARDS feature young men from all
over the country, and according to a toy industry trade
association, sales are sizzling. By ELAINE ARADILLAS.
</P>
<P>
   ANCIENT-POTTERY (Undated) _ Majolica is a type of glazed
jewel-toned pottery associated with Spain, Italy and Mexico. This
decorative pottery fell from fashion in the early 1900s, but it has
been making a comeback since the 1960s. Many potters are making
majolica today, but collectors covet early pieces. By FRANCES
INGRAHAM HEINS.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERATHLETES (Dallas) _ History tells of breakthrough moments
that set the world on its ear, such as the day in 1928 when Sir
Alexander Fleming discovered that mold could be used as medicine,
or in 1492, when Christopher Columbus stumbled upon the Americas.
Here's another one -- the day in June 1997 when Angel Munoz, Puerto
Rican immigrant and retired investment broker, figured out how to
make money off computer geeks doing what they do normally. By ROY
BRAGG.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ It's spring training for
bears, campers and hikers at Yosemite National Park, and so far the
bears are winning the game. In the past week in Yosemite Valley,
bears broke into eight more vehicles and there were another 12
damage reports from campgrounds. So far this spring there have been
117 bear incidents already at Yosemite, resulting in $32,871 in
property damage, most of it to cars. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   SKATER-AIDS (San Francisco) _ Last month, skater Rudy Galindo
announced that he is HIV positive. Since then he says he's been
barraged with support from inside and out of the skating world.
Galindo, a Hispanic American, said he hopes he can send a message
to other men of color, who are at risk for AIDS. ``Safe sex is not
an empty slogan,'' he said. ``I'm living proof that you can't make
mistakes.'' By ERIC McCORMICK.
</P>
<P>
   FISHING-WEATHER (Rockport, Texas) _ The best-laid plans of mice
and fishermen often go astray. That's what Scottish poet Robert
Burns would have written if he'd ever anticipated an angling trip
for months only to arrive at the coast at the same time as a storm.
By JOHN GOODSPEED.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (`k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ For some reason, people who would
never admit to being yuppies, dot-commies and other things ending
in ``-ies'' are proud to say they're foodies. Such is the elevated
status of the alimentary tract in the Bay Area. But if you think
you're a foodie because you get to the hottest restaurants before
the critics do, think again. You're a restaurant victim. By ROB
MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-AFRICA (San Francisco) _ Thabo Mbeki, the president of
South Africa, is visiting the United States this week. He has been
the subject of great controversy since the publication of a letter
he wrote last month which raised questions about the nature of the
AIDS epidemic sweeping Africa and the efficacy of applying Western
treatment models there. By JEFF SHEEHY and TOM COATES.
</P>
