<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 12:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2211 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-HEALTH-SUMMER-LIFEBEA     05-22 1271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-SUMMER-LIFEBEAT-973&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET READY FOR SUMMER'S BUMPS, BITES AND BRUISES
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text. 
 (tlk) 
 &HT;    Dr. Weil, a pioneer in the field of integrative medicine,
recently authored ``Eating Well for Optimum Health.''
 &HT;    
 By DR. ANDREW WEIL 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc. 
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features
<P>
   Warm weather's here, and your days off are likely to be spent in
the woods and on the beach. Although the living can be easy, the
season has its own set of health concerns, from hay fever to
black-and-blue knees. Be prepared by assembling a first aid kit
filled with natural, all-purpose remedies before you head outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   Repel mosquitoes and reduce the itch: The best way to steer
clear of mosquito bites is to know when the pesky insects are most
likely to be around. Mosquitoes generally feed around dusk, so if
you can't stay indoors during this time, wear long-sleeved,
loose-fitting clothing and tuck your pants into your socks. You may
want to wear such neutral colors as beige and khaki, which don't
seem to attract bugs.
</P>
<P>
   Also consider taking B-complex vitamins regularly _ mosquitoes
find human blood unpalatable when people are on this supplement.
Take 100 milligrams three times a day starting a few weeks before
mosquito season, which kicks in around April and peaks in July and
August.
</P>
<P>
   If these precautions don't work, try applying neem oil
(Azadirachta indica), which can provide significant protection for
up to 12 hours. Extracted from an Indian tree, this oil is
available in health-foods stores.
</P>
<P>
   In the event that a mosquito does snack on you, dab Tiger Balm
or aloe vera gel on the bite to relieve the itching.
</P>
<P>
   Get the better of bee stings: Whether you're gardening or
hiking, you may brush up against a bee or happen to disturb a hive.
If you do get stung, attempt to remove the stinger before it
releases all the bee's venom; you'll end up with a smaller, less
painful welt. To ease the pain and inflammation, ice the area
immediately, then apply a paste made with baking soda and water.
You can also treat the bite site with full-strength tea tree oil
(Melaleuca alternifolia) or peppermint oil (Mentha piperita),
effective topical antiseptics, or the homeopathic gel StingStop,
which contains an infinitesimal amount of stinging nettle.
</P>
<P>
   Stave off summer sickness: Don't assume you're immune to colds
Simply because it's not winter. At the first sign of a summer bug,
take echinacea (Echinacea purpurea), a natural antibiotic and
immune-system enhancer. Try A freeze-dried supplement or a
standardized extract. Follow directions on the package and halve
the dose for children.
</P>
<P>
   Ease sore summer muscles: If those first few sunny-weather
outings leave your lately hibernating muscles aching, try rubbing
tincture of Arnica (Arnica montana) on the injured area. This
bright-yellow daisy-like flower, a popular healing plant among
Native Americans, speeds the healing of bruises, sprains, soreness
and swelling; it also relieves arthritis, and muscle and cartilage
pain.
</P>
<P>
   Arnica comes in a variety of other topical forms _ cream, salve,
ointment, gel and oil _ but I like the tincture. Never apply it to
broken skin or an open wound: It can be toxic if it gets inside the
body.
</P>
<P>
   Take the ``ouch'' out of poisonous plants: Recognition is the
first line of defense when it comes to dealing with poison ivy,
oak, and sumac. Learn to identify these plants and then avoid them.
If you do touch one, wash off the allergenic resin with soap and
water within 20 to 30 minutes of contact and slather the affected
area with aloe vera gel, to help soothe the itch if a rash does
develop.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best poison-ivy treatments I know is to get in as hot
a shower as you can stand for 5 to 10 minutes. This will increase
the itching _ but only for a few minutes. That's when the
nervous-system circuits seem to get overloaded, stopping the
discomfort for several hours.
</P>
<P>
   Beat motion sickness: There's nothing worse than embarking on a
well-deserved holiday and becoming dizzy or nauseated before you
even hit the interstate. Fortunately, there are a number of
remedies that may make it possible for you to enjoy your journey.
</P>
<P>
   While traveling, try wearing acupressure wristbands, which have
a plastic peg that presses against the nausea controlling acupoint
on the inside of your wrists. The bands are available at most drug-
and health-food stores.
</P>
<P>
   Taking ginger (Zingiber officinale) also prevents and treats
motion sickness. Twenty minutes before travel, mix a half teaspoon
of ginger powder in a glass of water and drink it. Or take two to
four capsules of powdered ginger. Ginger snaps, ginger ale and
candied ginger can help with mild nausea, too.
</P>
<P>
   Soothe sunburn: Think prevention. Always use a sunscreen with an
SPF of 15 or higher that contains Parsol 1789, zinc oxide, or
titanium dioxide. These ingredients block almost the entire
spectrum of the sun's damaging rays. Slather sunscreen on every
exposed part of your body each time you work up a sweat or get out
of the water. Wear a broad-brimmed hat, lightweight pants or skirt,
and cover your shoulders and chest.
</P>
<P>
   If you do get sunburned, your skin will appreciate the cooling
and healing effects of aloe vera. Scrape out the gel from inside an
aloe leaf or buy a lotion whose primary ingredient is aloe, then
apply a generous amount to the affected area. You can also soothe
sunburn with cooled black tea (the tannins are what do the trick).
</P>
<P>
   Heal hay fever: I have found stinging nettle (Urtica dioica) to
be a highly effective treatment for hay-fever symptoms, minus the
side effects _ drowsiness and dry mouth _ of conventional allergy
medicines. Use a freeze-dried extract of the leaves, sold in
capsule form, and take one to two capsules every two to four hours
as needed.
</P>
<P>
   I also like quercetin, a bioflavonoid found in buckwheat and
citrus fruit, as an allergy preventive. Quercetin appears to
stabilize the immune-system cells that release histamine, the
mediator of allergic reactions. Take 400 milligrams twice a day
between meals. Give it a few weeks to show its full effect.
</P>
<P>
   Dr.Weil's summer first-aid Kit Stave off the season's troubles
with herbs, supplements and essential oils, all of which are
available at health-foods stores. What to have on hand:
</P>
<P>
   _ Acupressure wristbands
</P>
<P>
   _ Aloe vera gel
</P>
<P>
   _ Arnica
</P>
<P>
   _ B-complex vitamins (specifically B2)
</P>
<P>
   _ Baking soda
</P>
<P>
   _ Black tea
</P>
<P>
   _ Echinacea
</P>
<P>
   _ Ginger powder
</P>
<P>
   _ Neem oil
</P>
<P>
   _ Peppermint oil
</P>
<P>
   _ Quercetin capsules
</P>
<P>
   _ Stinging-nettle capsules
</P>
<P>
   _ StingStop
</P>
<P>
   _ Sunscreen with SPF IS+
</P>
<P>
   _ Tea tree oil
</P>
<P>
   _ Tiger Balm
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
