<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 12:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2213 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-BASEBALL-SALARY-HUMOR     05-22 2043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEBALL-SALARY-HUMOR-LIFEBEAT-1842-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET OUT YOUR HANKY: HERE ARE THE NOMINEES FOR BASEBALL'S
ALL-UNDERPAID TEAM
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text. 
 (tlk) 
 &HT;    Andrew Postman is the author of four books, most recently
``What's in an Age? Who Did What When, from Age 1 to 100.'' &HT;    
 &HT;    
 By ANDREW POSTMAN 
 c.2000 Andrew Postman
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features
<P>
   As you may have heard by now, ex-Toronto Blue Jay, now Los
Angeles Dodger right fielder Shawn Green, with only one All-Star
appearance under his belt, is getting $14 million a year for six
years. Is he worth it? We think not.
</P>
<P>
   Far worse, there's Bobby Bonilla. For his $5.9 million salary in
1999, he gave the New York Mets the following as a return on their
investment: He ate and didn't work out in an apparently desperate
attempt to win inclusion on the post-season roster of Macy's
Thanksgiving Day parade balloons; he challenged his manager to a
fight; and, during the final innings of Game 6 of the National
League Championship Series against the Atlanta Braves, the
culmination of arguably the most exciting baseball playoff series
in years, he decided to play cards in the clubhouse with fellow Met
malcontent Rickey Henderson (who, though also a Bonilla-like
loafer, was still a relative bargain, and far more useful to the
team, at his paltry sub-$2 million per year).
</P>
<P>
   We could field an ``All-Overpaid Team'' 10 times over. But there
are a lot of very good players who don't get nearly as much money
as they deserve. Here are our nominations for baseball's
``All-Underpaid Team.''
</P>
<P>
   FIRST BASE: MARK MCGWIRE, St. LOUIS CARDINALS What? Underpaid at
just shy of $9 million? Absolutely. We don't doubt that McGwire has
earned tons in endorsements, and that he will continue to do so
until (and beyond) the end of his career. But what his home-run
light show (an astounding 135 over the past two seasons) did for
league attendance, TV baseball ratings and national esprit de corps
cannot be quantified. If and when McGwire is reevaluated, he will
be worth way more than nine mil. Remember: When McGwire came to St.
Louis, he was a slugger, but an often injured slugger, and no one
could reasonably have expected that at Busch Stadium _ no one's
idea of a home-run park _ he would not only break Roger Maris'
single-season home-run record two years in a row but obliterate it.
</P>
<P>
   SECOND BASE: POKEY REESE, CINCINNATI REDS We couldn't help
picking Pokey for a few reasons (not the least of which is being
able to say ``picking Pokey''). He was a steal at $270,000; his
fielding range is ridiculous (it earned him his first Gold Glove);
and he appears to be on a rocket going straight up, and fast (in
his rookie year he hit .219; the next year, .256; last year, .285).
He's also saddled, at least for now, with what was certainly the
league's All-Overachieving, All-Underpaid Team. How about Sean
Casey, fourth in the league in batting, at $220,000? How about
Scott Williamson (12-7, 2.41 ERA, 19 saves, more than a strikeout
per inning) at $200,000? How about Manager of the Year Jack McKeon
being asked back with only a slight increase to his 1999 salary of
roughly $500,000?
</P>
<P>
   SHORTSTOP: REY ORDONEZ, NEW YORK METS Undoubtedly, many will
disagree with this choice. Ordonez is, after all, one of the least
effective offensive players in the history _ this is not a misprint
_ in the history of Major League Baseball. But hear me out: It is
not merely that Ordonez is without question the best-fielding
shortstop in at least a quarter century. (And please, tiresome
Cardinals fans, look in the mirror before you make that face about
Ozzie Smith, because he was never this good a fielder, and he
played more than half his games on the easier-to-negotiate
artificial surface.) And it is not just that Ordonez's range and
arm allow him to turn hits into outs, and force-outs into double
plays. It is that Ordonez is so reliable (a staggering major league
record of 100 consecutive errorless games, and counting, through
the end of last season) that he allows his pitchers to throw more
of the notoriously hard-to-predict, but ultimately very effective,
sinkers and splitters that turn into ground-ball outs. In short, he
makes his entire pitching staff calmer and better. Finally, if
we're going on highlight-reel appeal, Ordonez produces as many
moments annually as (and of greater breadth than) your
garden-variety All-Star slugger. At $1.65 million in 1999, he was a
GM's dream come true.
</P>
<P>
   THIRD BASE: TONY FERNANDEZ, TORONTO BLUE JAYS Fernandez toyed
with .400 for the first half of the season and ended up at .328,
the highest average of his 17-year career. Indeed, his is a case of
either great perseverance and batterly autodidacticism (ouch) or
really bad timing. In what should be the autumn of his career,
Fernandez has flourished in the past two seasons as he never has
before. Word to Tony (at $2.2 million): The way to do it is to
start hot, sign a fat contract, then tail off _ not the other way
around.
</P>
<P>
   CATCHER: JASON KENDALL, PITTSBURGH PIRATES It's hard to find
guys who are badly underpaid at this position, because the
brutality of playing catcher leaves so few catchers able to walk
without a limp, much less contribute both offensively and
defensively. But had Kendall not suffered a gruesome broken ankle
halfway through a very productive season, he might have established
himself as worthy of being considered in the next breath after
cream-of-the-crop catchers like Ivan Rodriguez and Mike Piazza. A
durable player and career .312 hitter, Kendall makes $1.25 million
with the Bucs. If he's healthy for the 2000 season and beyond,
he'll soon make his way out of All-Underpaid status, though he'll
probably have to leave small-market Pittsburgh to do it.
</P>
<P>
   LEFT FIELD: LUIS GONZALEZ, ARIZONA DIAMONDBACKS Here is the
classic case of a player, seemingly out of nowhere, having the year
of his life. In his tenth full year in the big leagues, Gonzalez
hit 36 points higher, knocked in 32 more runs, rapped 44 more hits
and scored 28 more runs than he had in any other season. He also
had a 30-game hitting streak, the second-longest in the National
League since 1987. So why did it happen now? Was it having Buck
Showalter as manager? Playing on a playoff-caliber club? Breathing
the Phoenix night air? Whatever the reason, Gonzalez was arguably
the veteran steal of the year, at $2 million, and he has a good
enough swing to make his second All-Star team.
</P>
<P>
   CENTER FIELD: TIE BETWEEN KEN GRIFFEY JR., CINCINNATI REDS, AND
ANDRUW JONES, ATLANTA BRAVES Griffey? Look at it this way: In his
last years, the best basketball player of the nineties,
what's-his-name Jordan, was paid $30-plus million in annual salary.
The best baseball player of the nineties topped out at $8.5 million
_ and he had to play a lot more games. It's nutty, we know. But in
today's sports market, that's a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, at a paltry $330,000, hasn't been around long enough to
demand big money. But in the four years he's been with the Braves,
they've won four division championships and two National League
pennants. What's more, Jones is not only a fabulous center fielder
but perhaps the most graceful outfielder ever to step on grass. (We
hear you, Willie Mays supporters; give us a break, DiMaggio
acolytes. Enough with the nostalgia: Use your eyes.) He's not yet
(and may never be) a great offensive player, but Jones is a good
one (.275, 26 HRs, 84 RBIs) who'll be covering 65 percent of the
outfield for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   RIGHT FIELD: TONY GWYNN, SAN DIEGO PADRES There is no position
in baseball that comes close to having such a plethora of great
players not making what they should (Vladimir ``Best Outfield Arm
in Baseball'' Guerrero, Montreal Expos, at $1 million; Larry ``Best
All-Around Player in the National League'' Walker, Colorado
Rockies, at $5.2 million; Manny ``Most RBI in 61 Years'' Ramirez,
Cleveland Indians, at $4.1 million; Sammy Sosa of the Cubs; Bobby
Abreu of the Phillies; Matt Stairs of the A's...)
</P>
<P>
   But Tony Gwynn, at $4.3 million and one of the greatest hitters
of all time, takes this one. Want to hear what Gwynn has hit in the
seven seasons since he turned 33, what for anyone else would be the
slippery downside of one's career? .358, .394, .368, .353, .372,
.321 and .338.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn could have made many more millions signing with a
bigger-market club but stayed true to the only team he's known.
There are very, very few players who've been in the league more
than 10 years and who have similarly stayed put (Cal Ripken Jr.
with the Orioles, Barry Larkin with the Reds, Tom Glavine with the
Braves). Anyway, Tony will have the last laugh the day he's
enshrined in Cooperstown.
</P>
<P>
   RIGHT-HANDED STARTING PITCHER: JOSE LIMA, HOUSTON ASTROS Lima
($1.95 million) blossomed in 1998, going 16-8 (the first time in
his career he didn't have a losing record) and, to show it wasn't a
fluke, followed up that effort with an even better 21-10 record and
a lower ERA. His strikeout-to-walks ratio in the past two years is
just silly _ an unbelievable 9: 1 _ and he's shown himself to be a
money pitcher, too. Lima's days of being underpaid should fast be
coming to an end.
</P>
<P>
   LEFT-HANDED STARTING PITCHER: JOSE ROSADO, KANSAS CITY ROYALS A
guy who was 10-14 last year is underpaid? Who has lost eight more
games in his career than he's won? Whose ERA was just a tad under
4? You got it (though he didn't). Rosado toiled for the woefully
under-budgeted, though young and talented, Royals. That 3.85 ERA of
his? Believe it or not, that was good enough for fifth best last
year in the ludicrously offensive-biased American League (from the
DH to smaller parks to minuscule strike zones to expansion,
pitchers have no chance). And who, you ask, are the four hurlers
ahead of Rosado? A guy named Pedro Martinez, one named David Cone,
one named Mike Mussina, and one named Brad Radke. Those four
combined earned almost $28 million in 1999. Rosado made $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE RELIEVER JOHN JOHNSTONE, SAN FRANCISCO GIANTS This is the
quintessential underpaid, under-appreciated position. After all, a
pitcher becomes a middle reliever ``because he's not good enough to
do anything else.'' That said, middle relievers have become
increasingly important; not coincidentally, playoff teams,
including the Mets, Yanks, and Braves, tend to boast the deepest
corps of middle relievers (a.k.a. ``relief specialists'').
Johnstone, whom no one outside of his family and the Bay Area has
ever heard of (and even the Bay Area we're not sure about), made
just under $700,000 last year. He had a minuscule ERA of 2.60, and
he led the major leagues in ``holds'' (keeping a lead) _ which
means that if not for him, the Giants closer would have had nothing
to save.
</P>
<P>
   CLOSER: BILLY WAGNER, HOUSTON ASTROS Not only does this guy
throw 100 mph, it is conceivable, given the trajectory of his
brilliant career, that he will soon be averaging two strikeouts per
inning. That's correct: We said two, not one. Last year, his ERA
was a this-has-to-be-a-misprint 1.57. While closers are often,
almost by definition, underpaid (after all, they tend to burn out
almost as quickly as they emerge), Wagner, at a hair over $2
million, makes far less than the few equals he has among dominant,
ice-water-in-the-veins short relievers (Mariano Rivera, Trevor
Hoffman).
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LIFEBEAT
and other features. &QL;
</P>
