<HEADER>
A2214 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CHILDCARE-SLEEP-LIFEB     05-22 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-SLEEP-LIFEBEAT-943-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLEEP-DEPRIVED NEW MOTHER FINDS ``THE BOOK''
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text. 
 (tlk) 
 &HT;    Megan McNamer, a freelance writer from Missoula, Montana is the
mother of two boys.
 &HT;     &HT;    
 By MEGAN MCNAMER 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc. 
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features
<P>
   Suffering from the nightly baby-induced sleep deprivation that
all new parents seem to go through, I could never decide if we
humans are meant to sleep alone, in pairs, or what. It seemed
unfair to make a tiny baby sleep all by himself or to try to pawn
off a ``cuddly'' of some sort to approximate companionship when we,
clearly, each had a big, living cuddly we could latch onto. Plus,
it can be so comforting to sleep with babies. They sleep with such
complete devotion, such brow-furrowed concentration, when they do
sleep.
</P>
<P>
   True, they practice their art at odd hours, having spurts of
inspiration, then long periods of frustration. They might even
become blocked on sleeping. And that's when babies, and their
parents, need an operating system, a book on sleeping _ they need
The Book.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't find The Book on my own, heavens no. I was one of those
natural, instinctive mothers who was convinced that she intuited
mothering in such an innately motherly way that it didn't cross my
mind that I might need any book. Or so I thought, before I hit the
wall, literally, in the sheets-and-towels section of Sears, utterly
exhausted from what had felt like an all-night hostage situation.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, I was discovered stumbling about there, sighing deeply,
by my friend Maeta, a no-nonsense, peripatetic mother of a baby six
months older than mine, which, from my inexperienced point of view,
might as well have meant mother of an Oxford don.
</P>
<P>
   Maeta's cheeks looked flushed from the brisk outdoors and her
eyes were fully open. She was probably shopping for clearance sale
sheets to make apostle robes in her capacity as assistant director
at the community theater. (She was both mother of an Oxford don and
able to get 50 schoolkids to wave their palm branches in the right
direction during ``Jesus Christ Superstar.'') I'll never forget the
way she took one look at the slumbering baby on my back and my own
ravaged state and then said it: ``You need The Book.'' I could have
sworn she said, ``Let there be light.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Solve Your Child's Sleep Problems'' is revelatory, yet simple.
It is a plan laid out by Dr. Richard Ferber for teaching your baby
to fall asleep. Alone. If he learns to fall asleep alone at
bedtime, down the road he can learn to fall asleep in the middle of
the night. Without you. That's the idea. Looking back, I am amazed
at the simplicity of the process compared to the turmoil it tapped
in my heart.
</P>
<P>
   There is REM and non-REM sleep, and Stages I through IV, and
``hypnagogic hallucinations,'' and ``circadian rhythms'' to know
about, but, in my own particular Book, what Parents of the
Sleepless (the gothic terminology of one reviewer) are advised to
do goes something like the following scenario.
</P>
<P>
   You put baby to bed, awake. He starts to howl.
</P>
<P>
   You look at your watch. After one minute (you select the
starting increment), you go in and comfort him without picking him
up. He beams at you in instant relief. You leave. He howls.
</P>
<P>
   You look at your watch. After five minutes you go in to comfort
him without picking him up. He twists his red, wet face toward you
beseechingly. You leave. He howls.
</P>
<P>
   You look at your watch again. After 10 minutes you go in to
comfort him without picking him up. He draws shuddering breaths,
hiccuping mightily. You leave. There is a stunned moment of
disbelief And then he howls.
</P>
<P>
   You look at your watch, grab fistfuls of your hair and yank.
After 15 minutes you go in and comfort him without picking him up.
His crying is so loud and dense that you swear it is a form of
solo-polyphonic ritual chant. You don't want to know what he is
chanting. You leave. He continues to howl.
</P>
<P>
   You look at your watch. And after 20 minutes you go in. Your
baby nails you with a look of such withering rancor through his
tears that you don't even try to comfort him but instead beat a
hasty retreat. He continues to howl; the pitch rises in a
methodical step fashion.
</P>
<P>
   You look at your watch, nonstop, for 30 minutes. You go in. He
does not acknowledge your presence in any way. He is utterly
focused on his crying and does not want to be distracted. You
leave, feeling numb in all your extremities.
</P>
<P>
   You are unable to look at your watch. You stand motionless in
the middle of the living room as if in the eye of a hurricane. You
draw one quivering breath and feel as if you are in labor again. It
is not going well. You curse the fact that you decided to start
this program when your husband was out of town. You curse the
program. You curse all books on baby rearing. You curse the fact
that you ever learned to read.
</P>
<P>
   And then: He stops.
</P>
<P>
   Your baby stops his crying. But he is actually awake, you can
sense it. He is awake and alive. He is alone and intact. You both
are listening, riveted, to the silence of the other. And then he
starts making that squishing, sputtering mouth sound he makes when
he's talking to Curious George (his cuddly).
</P>
<P>
   You just stand there frozen, a statue. You know that he is
pointing out to George that he, George, has an eye here, and
another there, and a nose just below, and a mouth right here. After
he points that out, repeatedly, to George, you hear some rustling
sounds. The crib slats shake once, twice. You stand rigid, a pillar
of salt. You know that he is lying on his back and kicking his feet
just to see them go up and down. He is considering his feet.
</P>
<P>
   And then: There is a long, long significant pause ....
</P>
<P>
   He is sailing away from you. He is sailing away. You stand
fixed, chiseled, still. You gaze over the river of crystal light.
You start to sense it. The deep, deep, ocean-deep breathing
of...sleep.
</P>
<P>
   A new day is born.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LIFEBEAT
and other features. &QL;
</P>
