<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 12:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2215 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-SEATTLE-TRAVEL-LIFEBE     05-22 1920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEATTLE-TRAVEL-LIFEBEAT-1570&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIP SEATTLE WOOS THE HEALTH-CONSCIOUS TRAVELER
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text. 
 (tlk) 
 &HT;    Leslie Martin was formerly travel editor of ``Country Living''
magazine and of ``Country Living's Healthy Living'' magazine.
 &HT;     &HT;    
 By LESLIE MARTIN 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc. 
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features
<P>
   Seattle _ hip, environmentally aware and holistically minded _
figures high on annual lists of America's most livable cities. No
wonder: It's flanked by the snowclad Olympic and Cascade mountain
ranges _ with 14,411-foot-high Mount Rainier in dramatic view to
the southeast _ and rimmed by the scenic shores of Lake Washington,
Lake Union, Elliott Bay and Puget Sound. And this sprawling
metropolis of 3 million hasn't sacrificed its outdoor lifestyle (at
least not yet) to the demands of urban culture. Yes, there are too
many cars. But 8,000 commuters bike to their offices, and some
18,000 others float to work on ferries. Ecological and political
passions still run high here, as evidenced by last fall's
demonstrations against the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Dubbed the ``Emerald City of the Pacific Northwest'' for its
generous green spaces, Seattle also boasts an appealing array of
residential neighborhoods, each with a distinctive personality. In
north Seattle alone, there's funky, free-style Fremont; yuppie
Wallingford; and traditional, working-class Ballard.
</P>
<P>
   In the northeast, you'll find wooded Ravenna and University
District, home of the University of Washington. East Seattle is
comprised of trendy Capitol Hill, upscale Madison Park and
ethnically rich Madrona. Youthful Alki sits in the southwest; in
the west, affluent Magnolia perches on a peninsula and chic Queen
Anne towers above downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Country in the city
</P>
<P>
   From Peregrine falcons to stately cedars, wildlife and
wilderness abound in Seattle. There are more than 6,000 acres of
parkland in the city alone. You might spy bald eagles somewhere in
the 500 rustic acres of Magnolia's Discovery Park and will
certainly come upon honking Canadian geese at Lake Union's shores.
</P>
<P>
   Watch sockeye salmon run at the Hiram Chittenden Locks (June
through August; 315 N.W. 54th St.), and if you ride the ferries to
Bainbridge and Vashon Islands, you can often spot orcas cavorting
in Puget Sound (The trip to 48-square-mile Bainbridge Island takes
35 minutes. Call Washington State Ferries, 800-843-3779, for
schedules).
</P>
<P>
   For the best viewing of old-growth trees, visit Schmitz Park,
part of West Seattle, and Lake Washington's Seward Park. Capitol
Hill's Volunteer Park is one of the city's most accessible open
spaces. The landscaping, which includes fountains, promenades and
formal gardens was the work of the Olmsted brothers, whose father
and step-father, (the family relationship was complicated)
Frederick Law Olmsted, was one of the pioneers of American
landscape architecture. An observatory in Volunteer Park offers
panoramic views of the city. In the heart of downtown's bustling
Pioneer Square, don't miss the sweet, small-scale waterfall in
Waterfall Park.
</P>
<P>
   Fitness frontiers
</P>
<P>
   If exploring neighborhoods on foot and wandering along park
trails doesn't satisfy your need for exercise, get your heart
pumping with tennis, bike-riding, or paddling, to name just a few
of the activities available in this athletic town. The waterfront
and 2.8-mile trail around Green Lake are joggers' favorites. The
city maintains 155 tennis courts, awarded on a first-come,
first-served basis or reserved in advance at Seattle Parks and
Recreation (5201 Green Lake Way N.; for reservations, phone
684-4077). (Note: Unless otherwise listed, the area code is 206.)
</P>
<P>
   To pedal your way through Seattle's streets, rent bikes equipped
with a computerized mapping system at Blazing Saddles Bike Rentals
(1230 Western Ave.; 341-9994). Cycle along the 12-mile Burke Gilman
Trail, which skirts Lake Washington's shores, or try some
island-pedaling by taking your bicycle on the Vashon or Bainbridge
ferries (just pay the foot-passenger toll).
</P>
<P>
   Vashon Island is tranquil and rural; Bainbridge is flatter, but
you'll have to contend with more cars. And the city's Engineering
Department can provide you with a free map of other scenic bike
routes and loops (684-7583).
</P>
<P>
   If plying the waters strikes your fancy, start by renting a
rowboat, kayak, or sailboat at Green Lake Boat Rentals (7351 E.
Green Lake Dr. N.; 527-0171). How about a sea-kayak tour? Check out
Pacific Water Sports (16055 Pacific Hwy. S.; 246-9385). Can you
canoe? Get equipped for an excursion on Lake Washington's tranquil
bayous at the University of Washington Waterfront Activity Center
(20 minutes north of downtown; 543-9433). For information about
swimming, river-rafting, skiing, horseback-riding, golf, or scuba
diving, contact the Seattle-King County Visitors Bureau (Washington
State Convention &AMP; Trade Center, 800 Convention Place, Seattle, WA
98101; 461-5840).
</P>
<P>
   Places that pamper
</P>
<P>
   Spas and salons proliferate both in the heart of the city and in
residential neighborhoods. Unwind with a warm-oil massage at
Ummelina, a downtown gem with a dry sauna that re-creates the
healing environment of the desert (1525 4th Ave.; 624-1370).
Jaroslava specializes in such treatments as seaweed body wraps and
almond loofah scrubs (1413 4th Ave.; 623-3336). In the same
building as the Alexis Hotel, Aveda Lifestyle Store &AMP; Spa features
treatments that include aromatherapy massage and Dead Sea-salt
exfoliation with the company's well-known, plant-based products
(1015 First Ave.; 628-9605). Robert Leonard specializes in facials
(2033 6th Ave., Suite 151; 441-9900). Habitude, which offers herbal
body masks and facials, has locations in both Ballard (5350 Ballard
Ave. N.W; 782-2898) and Fremont (513 N. 36th St.; 633-1339).
</P>
<P>
   Spirited reading
</P>
<P>
   With more bookstores per capita than any other American city,
Seattle is a bookworm's delight. Spend an afternoon of enlightened
browsing at the Elliott Bay Book Company in Pioneer Square; this
literary landmark features an extensive general-interest inventory
and hosts one of the most respected reading series in the country
(101 S. Main St.; 624-6600). Beyond the Closet focuses on
alternative lifestyles, with extensive offerings from small presses
(518 E. Pike St.; 322-4609). East West Book Shop is a popular
Ravenna haven with an enormous selection of Jungian-psychology
books (6500 Roosevelt; 523-3726). Nearby, Mandata covers
spirituality and metaphysics (918 N.E. 64th St.; 527-2979). A
favorite in grassroots Fremont, the Fremont Place Book Company (621
N. 35th St.; 547-5970) accents gender studies. Check out Left Bank
Books, a cooperatively run bookstore with an emphasis on radical
politics, philosophy and poetry (92 Pike St.; 622-0195). Upstairs
from Seattle's largest Asian food store, Kinokuniya Bookstore
includes a fine alternative medicine section (519 6th Ave. S.;
587-2477). For an extensive complementary-health bookstore, head to
Bastyr University, just 40 minutes from downtown Seattle in Kenmore
(14500 Juanita Dr. N.E., Kenmore, WA 98028-4966; 425-823-1300).
</P>
<P>
   Healthy dining
</P>
<P>
   Seattle offers far more than just java joints. The city's
restaurants excel in seafood and Pacific Rim cuisine, with organic,
locally grown products a highlight; the Painted Table in the Alexis
Hotel is a prime example (92 Madison St.; 624-3646). Refined and
full- flavored, the vegetarian fare at Cafe Flora is first-rate
(2901 E. Madison St.; 325-9100). Whether you're in the mood to sip
a tamarind-ginger lemonade or to savor a vegetarian snack,
Carmelita will not disappoint (7314 Greenwood Ave. N.; 706-7703).
In Capitol Hill, Gravity Bar is a classy, slick vegetarian
restaurant with an Asian accent (415 Broadway E.; 325-7186). The
friendly Still Life in the Fremont Coffeehouse will transport you
back to the 1960s; its homemade fare, much of it vegetarian _ is
delectable (709 N. 35th St.; 547-9850). Out-of-towners should visit
Ray's Boathouse, for its stunning views of the Olympic Mountains
and its extensive fish offerings (6049 Seaview Ave. N.W.;
789-3770). In Green Lake, don't miss Ed's Juice and Java, just
below the Compounding Apothecary, for organic everything _ from
wheatgrass to rice plates (7900 E. Greenlake Dr. N.; 524-7570).
Nearby, the Urban Bakery serves up meatless soups and terrific
breads (7850 E. Greenlake Dr. N.; 524-7951).
</P>
<P>
   Rest for the weary
</P>
<P>
   Set on a quiet street in lovely Capitol Hill, the turn-of
the-century Salisbury House _ graced with welcoming fireplaces and
elegant beamed ceilings _ makes a great home base (750 16th Ave.
E.; 328-8682; rooms start at $85 per night). Downtown, between Pike
Place Market and Pioneer Square, the stately Alexis Hotel is
conveniently located next to the Aveda spa (1007 First Ave.;
800-426-7033; www.alexishotel.com; rooms start at $165).
Overlooking the flower stalls of Pike Place Market, Inn at the
Market opens onto expansive Elliott Bay views (86 Pine St.;
443-3600; www.innatthemarket.com; rooms start at $145). Pike Place
Market, the country's oldest continuously operating farmers'
market, is a treasured Seattle landmark where, among other things,
you can buy organic produce and all manner of fresh fish, linger in
a tearoom or lunch in a kosher deli.
</P>
<P>
   For a quintessential Seattle experience, try a floating home on
Lake Union; the restored 1944 U.S. Army Tugboat M.V. Challenger
Bunk &AMP; Breakfast will set you up in one of its eight rooms on the
water (1001 Fairview Avenue N., 1600; 340-1201 or 877-340-1201;
www.challengerboat.com; rates start at $100).
</P>
<P>
   More tips
</P>
<P>
   When touring downtown, save money and time by walking or using
public transportation (from 7 a.m. to 7 p.m. there's a
21-block-long free-ride bus zone). To venture out into the
neighborhoods, however, you'll need to drive, hop on a bus (call
206-553-3000 for info), or bike. Once you get there, though,
explore on foot _ it's the best way to absorb the flavor and rhythm
of each district.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the rumors of incessant downpours, Seattle's annual
rainfall is 36 inches _ less than that of Manhattan or Atlanta. The
city is often misty, though, so a waterproof jacket is a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   To learn about local politics and concerns, tune in to 94.9
KUOW, the University of Washington's National Public Radio
affiliate, or check out the free alternative weeklies widely
distributed downtown: ``The Stranger,'' creative and courageous,
and ``Seattle Weekly,'' the city's answer to New York's Village
Voice.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
