<HEADER>
A2224 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-22 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FOODOBSESSION.COM 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For some reason, people who would never admit to
being yuppies, dot-commies and other things ending in ``-ies'' are
proud to say they're foodies. Such is the elevated status of the
alimentary tract in the San Francisco Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   But if you think you're a foodie because you get to the hottest
restaurants before the critics do, think again. You're a restaurant
victim.
</P>
<P>
   You're just eating restaurant food, and most restaurants can't
find help and can't keep chefs. San Francisco has two gossip
columns devoted to chefs' comings and goings, and they are
well-read. It's hard to keep up with who's stealing the great chefs
of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants are booming, but it hardly matters what the food
tastes like. A little buzz, a lot of decor, some showy
presentation, and the restaurants fill up with young beneficiaries
of computer wealth who can't cook and think the world's best food
is in restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   They don't know that great cuisines come from the world's homes.
I have one young friend who has opinions about all the latest
restaurants, yet can't make anything more complicated than a
grilled cheese sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   When she cooks at home for company, she tries to prepare
restaurant food from great chefs' cookbooks, using recipes with 21
steps that somewhere in the middle say, ``Last week make a stock.''
</P>
<P>
   It's no wonder young people eat all their meals in restaurants,
and let someone else make the stock last week.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how you really know if you're a foodie, a food victim of
very sophisticated pretensions: How many kinds of salt do you have
in your cupboard?
</P>
<P>
   The salt craze hit my home hard. Our cupboard contains red
Hawaiian tidal crystals, gray Celtic sea salt, damp French fleur de
sel, Aigues-Mortes salt, Sicilian salt, coarse Portuguese sea salt,
ultra-fine Japanese salt, kosher salt and rock salt. That's not
even counting salt from the Sea of Iodized.
</P>
<P>
   We have enough sea salt to start a sea. It would be
international waters.
</P>
<P>
   We even have the ``Salt &AMP; Pepper'' cookbook by Bay Area food
writer Michele Anna Jordan, and it's a good book about all the
newly revealed mysteries of the shaker and grinder. Salt is
``flavor's midwife,'' as Jordan puts it, and different salts give
birth to different flavors.
</P>
<P>
   This is getting serious. I'm not just a foodie. I'm a saltie.
</P>
<P>
   Having a cookbook collection isn't enough anymore. Your
collection has to include antique cookbooks, anthropological
cookbooks and trendy single-subject cookbooks like Jordan's ``Salt
&AMP; Pepper.'' That's technically a two-subject cookbook, I suppose,
but not on most tables.
</P>
<P>
   Currently on bookstore shelves are such single-subject tomes as
``The Rice Bible,'' ``The Complete Meat Cookbook'' and ``The Good
Egg.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the great cholesterol panic is over, eggs are over easy
and served up every other conceivable way. San Francisco restaurant
consultants Gayle Pirie and John Clark have a reassuringly slim
cookbook called ``Country Egg, City Egg,'' on the foodstuff so
often taken for granted, and massacred since the invention of the
pan, to use M.F.K. Fisher's imagery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our whole M.O. is that you can find six eggs in your
refrigerator, a little balsamic vinegar, a beer, and you can make a
feast,'' Pirie says.
</P>
<P>
   You have to break some eggs to make an omelet, so you might as
well crack a book about the simplest food in the most confusing
department in the supermarket. Now I know why some eggs are white
and others brown, but it's better to have blue.
</P>
<P>
   If young restaurant addicts can't face cooking at home yet,
Pirie and Clark will be cooking their bread-crumb fried eggs and
other egg dishes as guest chefs at Berkeley's Cafe Rouge at
lunchtime Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   So goes the life of the palate in Berkeley, formerly the home of
the life of the mind. Naturally, the salt on the eggs won't be the
nasty iodized kind, but strictly kosher.
</P>
<P>
   If single-subject cookbooks are all the rage, I should be able
to get a piece of the action, too. I was going to write ``The Water
Cookbook,'' but got stuck on the difference between hard and soft
water.
</P>
<P>
   Boiling I'm not so sure about, but I've got freezing down cold.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
