<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-GAYS-GAIN-BENEFITS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAYS AND LESBIANS MAKE STRIDES IN HEALTH-BENEFITS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By CHUCK COLBERT  
 &HT;    Gains in workplace equality for gay and lesbian Americans have
been ``rapid and remarkable,'' says Kim Mills, education director
of the Human Rights Campaign, the nation's largest political
organization.
 &HT;    ``The progress shows no signs of abating,'' she says. ``In many
workplaces we've gone beyond the basics of a nondiscrimination
policy, domestic-partners health-insurance benefits and a
sanctioned employee resource group to diversity training at all
levels of the corporation, including sexual orientation and gender
identity. This includes respectful and appropriate marketing to our
community and financial commitments to our organizations.''
 &HT;    Mills, the author of HRC's published report, ``The State of the
Workplace,'' visited Boston to address a monthly dinner meeting of
the Greater Boston Business Council, or GBBC.
 &HT;    GBBC, a gay and lesbian professional and business organization,
promotes visibility of gays in the workforce, providing positive
images.
 &HT;    Mills heads up WorkNet, an HRC project that collects, analyzes
and distributes _ free of charge _ information to assist employees
and employers in implementing and tracking policies that ensure
equal treatment of gay, lesbian, bisexual and transgender workers.
WorkNet includes the most extensive database of U.S. employers who
implement nondiscrimination policies that cover sexual orientation
and domestic-partnership benefits.
 &HT;    Mills' statement that ``progress has been rapid and
remarkable,'' is no exaggeration. In March, WorkNet documented an
impressive 3,402 U.S. employers who offer domestic-partner health
insurance.
 &HT;    ``From the end of last year until mid-March, 117 companies
started providing health-insurance benefits,'' Mills says. ``That's
a rate of about nine a week.''
 &HT;    There are currently 70 ``Fortune 500'' companies that provide
health insurance for domestic-partners. Employers offering
equal-benefits include American Airlines, American Express, Apple
Computer, AT&AMP;T, Eastman Kodak, General Mills, IBM, Marriott,
Mattel, Walt Disney and Xerox.
 &HT;    ``One of the incredible things about workplace advocacy is
seeing the progress, the quantifiable data that show how far we've
come,'' Mills says.
 &HT;    In 1982, the New York City-based Village Voice newspaper became
the first employer to offer domestic-partner health-insurance
benefits. For most of the 1980s, however, only a handful of
employers followed suit. By 1990, fewer than two dozen employers
implemented such a policy.
 &HT;    In 1991, however, the Cambridge-based Lotus Development Corp.,
then an independent company, raised the stakes in the information
technology sector, becoming the first publicly held corporation to
add domestic-partner benefits.
 &HT;    Fast forward to late 1999. Since then, here's been a virtual
explosion in the numbers of employers in 40 states who offering
domestic-partner health insurance. California, Massachusetts and
New York _ each with more than 100 employers _ lead the way. The
District of Columbia, Illinois and Pennsylvania are not far behind,
according to HRC's database.
 &HT;    Today, domestic-partner benefits are rated the most effective
recruitment tool for executives and the third most effective for
managers and line workers, according to a 1999 survey by the
Society for Human Resource Management.
 &HT;    Behind these impressive gains is the city of San Francisco. In
1996, San Francisco passed an equal-benefits ordinance _ the
nation's first _ which mandated that any contractor doing business
with the city or county must offer equal-benefits.
 &HT;    Employers tracked by the San Francisco Human Rights Commission
accounted for 76 percent of all the identified employers nationwide
offering domestic-partner benefits, according to the report. The
commission shares its data with the WorkNet project, enabling HRC
to advocate progressive changes in policy nationwide.
 &HT;    ``We can help companies do the right thing in advising employees
and employers on the value of workplace diversity, which includes
sexual orientation along with gender, race, and ethnicity,'' Mills
says. ``We've helped to educate executives all the way to the top
of major corporations on diversity issues.''
 &HT;    HRC's WorkNet project can't achieve workplace equality alone.
That requires an effort by all gay and lesbian Americans to make
the case company by company, asking for the equal treatment at work
that we deserve.
 &HT;    For a complete list of employers who offer domestic-partner
health insurance, see the HRC WorkNet Web site at
www.hrc.org/worknet. 
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Chuck Colbert serves on the board of the National Lesbian and
Gay Journalists Association.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 CHUCK COLBERT 
