</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-HOT-JOBS-2000-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT JOBS FOR 2000  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By ISIS ARTZE  
 &HT;    Increasingly, traditional careers are being replaced with
careers of the 21st century, whether it's broadband architecture,
fuel-cell engineering or gerontological counseling. Consider these
examples:
 &HT;    _ Auto manufacturers say that by 2010 many gasoline engines may
be replaced by small electric motors that run on fuel cells. The
result is that future fuel-cell engineers will create vehicles that
are more fuel-efficient.
 &HT;    _ Law, a favorite career area for Latinos, will see many
changes. The new millennium calls for multidisciplinary lawyers,
who will combine their skills with those of accountants and
consultants.
 &HT;    In an article titled ``Top Careers for 2000 and Beyond,'' (on
CareerPlanner.com), career reporter Mike Robinson explains that the
key to understanding future career prospects is to become aware of
the long-term trends that are taking place. One of these is an
aging population and longer life spans, Robinson says. It's a trend
that will lead to a high demand in products and services tailored
to the elderly, including healthcare and nursing facilities.
 &HT;    ``With the ranks of those 65 and over set to swell from 33
million to 80 million over the next 40 years,'' according to U.S.
News Online, the demand for individuals specializing in the
concerns of the senior citizens is already huge and will only grow.
 &HT;    Pat Gleason-Wynn, a gerontological counselor, is one such
individual. Visiting private homes and nursing facilities,
Gleason-Wynn handles anything _ from a woman recovering from a
broken hip who needs help making her home easier to navigate to a
widower having trouble with his social life.
 &HT;    Another career identified by U.S. News as a hot job is that of
an intensivist. This is a physician who tries to prevent medical
complications by evaluating medical histories, surgeries and
diseases, then consults with surgeons, cardiologists and other
specialists to coordinate the complex care of the critically ill.
 &HT;    Ronald L. Krannich, author of ``The Best Jobs for the 21st
Century'' (Impact, 1998) agrees that healthcare careers will
abound. He says that, in addition to favorable demographics, the
healthcare industry will grow due to advances in medical technology
and the likelihood that financing healthcare will become easier.
 &HT;    While these traditional careers are being revamped, everyone
agrees that information technology is the fastest-growing field in
the new decade. Jobs related to the Internet may seem intimidating,
but, as Krannich says, ``information technology tends to service
all industries.''
 &HT;    It is also important to remember that there is much division of
labor in Web jobs. Some individuals produce content, the area that
requires the least amount of technical expertise. It entails, among
other duties, writing copy for Web sites, and often creating the
graphics.
 &HT;    In the area of Web design, individuals must have HTML and
graphic design experience, and are often responsible for sound,
animated graphics, page layouts and site architecture.
 &HT;    Web developers are probably highest in demand. These jobs
require knowledge of a variety of current database and business
applications, as well as standard programming languages such as
Java and C++.
 &HT;    Web sites also need managers, individuals who plan and budget,
and are responsible for site development and maintenance. And, like
all other businesses, Web sites offer careers in traditional jobs
such as sales and marketing.
 &HT;    The Web has also created a new breed of broker. Besides
traditional financial and analytical skills, online brokers must be
able to answer technical questions as easily as questions about
stock splits and industry statistics, and have good customer
service skills.
 &HT;    But Web jobs aren't the only fast-growth opportunities. Another
hot field is travel, according to Krannich, who says it is probably
the second-fastest growing industry after information technology.
Krannich says that careers in hospitality, rental cars and hotels
will boom because people have more spare time. And, Krannich adds,
those who hold these jobs have a high level of job satisfaction.
 &HT;    CareerPlanner.com's Robinson agrees that increased leisure time
is characteristic of the new millennium.
 &HT;    ``With longer lives and an increase in leisure time,'' he says,
``expect the entertainment industry to boom. There will be more
time for books, concerts, movies and television.''
 &HT;    One final long-term trend that will have an impact on future
careers is cocooning, a phenomenon in which people will want to
stay inside the safety, security and comfort of their homes, cars,
offices and gated communities. The result is that people will do
more from their homes, and that careers involving home
entertainment systems and home remodeling will grow, according to
Robinson.
 &HT;    And, if more and more people will be staying home, the success
of broadband, a new technological breakthrough, seems imminent.
Broadband is a technology that merges the computer and the
television set. Goldman Sachs Group Inc. estimates that 73 million
homes will have access by 2008. Information architects will be
needed to organize and present its content. The training is similar
to that of online information design.
 &HT;    Krannich points out the obvious: ``Although technical skills
will not be required in every twenty-first century career, jobs
will be very technologically oriented.''
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Isis Artze is a free-lance writer.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Hispanic Business magazine 
