<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-NATIVE-AMERICAN-VOTE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POWER OF THE NATIVE-AMERICAN VOTE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By KAREN LINCOLN MICHEL 
 &HT;    Albuquerque, the city that many Southwest Indians call home, was
the place presidential candidates were invited to speak last month
about their stand on Native-American issues.
 &HT;    The American Indian Chamber of Commerce of New Mexico publicized
the forum nationally and persuaded CBS correspondent Hattie Kaufman
_ the highest profile Native broadcast journalist _ to moderate.
 &HT;    Everything was set. But the only candidate who traveled to
Albuquerque for the event was Green Party candidate Ralph Nader,
who appeared with his running mate, Winona LaDuke, a Native-rights
activist, and White Earth Chippewa from northern Minnesota.
 &HT;    In Indian Country, that's like holding a special ceremony for
faraway dignitaries and only your family shows up.
 &HT;    Ouch.
 &HT;    Before it turned into a platform for the Green Party, the forum
raised the question of why politicians continue to ignore
Native-America.
 &HT;    The small voting block certainly plays into it. In a population
of more than 2 million, where the median age is 26, more than half
of American-Indians and Alaska Natives are of voting age. A
potential block of 1 million-plus votes seems to be considered
nothing by Al Gore and George W. Bush. But if they expect to
represent all of America, the native vote is nothing to overlook _
even if only a fraction of them are registered voters.
 &HT;    In Arizona, 56,946 Americans-Indians registered to vote as
Democrats in 1998, according to the Democratic National Committee.
There are no comparisons for American-Indians voting Republican by
the Republican National Committee.
 &HT;    Some American-Indian politicos say American-Indians made all the
difference in the outcome of the 1996 presidential election in
Arizona. Clinton and Gore narrowly defeated Republican candidates
Bob Dole and Jack Kemp by 2 percent, or by 31,215 votes, of the
1.38 million ballots cast.
 &HT;    Although voting records do not distinguish race or ethnicity, a
tally of precincts within the Navajo Reservation _ the largest of
Arizona's 20 Indian tribes _ showed the Clinton-Gore ticket won 51
percent of the 24,907 votes cast as compared to Dole-Kemp's 37
percent.
 &HT;    It seems Al Gore should have remembered that before snubbing the
American-Indian business community in one of the largest urban
Indian centers in the Southwest.
 &HT;    It is no secret that American-Indians historically have aligned
themselves with the Democratic Party. Although the number of
Native-American Republicans is slowly on the rise, Native-American
Democrats far outnumber them.
 &HT;    Since gaining the right to vote with the 1924 Indian Citizenship
Act _ and later for some tribes, while still others refuse U.S.
citizenship _ American Indians as a group have favored Democrats.
 &HT;    The DNC says that over the past 20 years, roughly 85 percent of
American-Indian voters have cast ballots for Democrats in national
elections. And when tribes contribute financially to political
parties, most of those dollars wind up in the coffers of the
Democratic Party and its candidates.
 &HT;    But if Gore and other Democrats continue to take that loyalty
for granted, we could see a shift in support at a time when tribes
are becoming politically astute.
 &HT;    The growth of Indian gaming has allowed ``gaming tribes'' to
contribute monetarily to the political process. And tribes
nationwide have banded together in some cases to lobby Congress on
certain bills.
 &HT;    The Center for Responsive Politics, a Washington, D.C.-based
independent research company that tracks campaign contributions,
considers American-Indians successful in their ability to make
their political donations pay off.
 &HT;    A spokeswoman for the center said they have noticed a steady
increase in lobbying efforts in recent years and an increase in
overall involvement by tribes that engage in gaming.
 &HT;    When I looked closely into this subject in 1998, tribes had
rallied congressional support to defeat measures that would have
undermined tribal sovereignty.
 &HT;    Among the proposals that died were efforts to tax revenues of
tribes, require tribes to waive sovereign immunity against law
suits in exchange for federal funds, and require legal actions
against tribal governments to be heard in federal courts rather
than tribal courts.
 &HT;    Statistics gathered by the center show that gaming tribes
contributed more than $1.9 million to political campaigns and
parties in the 1995-1996 election cycle. Of that total, 85 percent
benefited Democrats.
 &HT;    The 1995-1996 total was more than 2.5 times greater than that
during the 1993-1994 election cycle, when gaming tribes anted up
$585,400 in hard and soft money contributions and Political Action
Committee donations. Nearly 79 percent of the total combined
contributions went to Democrats.
 &HT;    That doesn't sound like a lot of money in American politics. But
tribes appear to be making their contributions work for them.
 &HT;    Generations ago, a war party might have been sent out to track
down Gore and Bush for insulting and humiliating the Southwest
tribes. We're more civilized today. We'll take a stand at the polls
and, in the meantime, try to lobby them to death.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Karen Lincoln Michel, past president of the Native-American
Journalists Association, is co-owner of News from Indian Country.) 
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Karen Lincoln Michel 
