<HEADER>
A2228 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-NEW-AMERICA-VIEQUES-F     05-22 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-VIEQUES-FIRESTORM-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FATE OF VIEQUES  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By JAMES E. GARCIA  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    It used to be known as ``Crab Island.'' Some local residents
even recall having to shut their doors to keep crabs from crawling
into their living rooms.
 &HT;    Most of the crabs are gone now from the tiny island of Vieques,
Puerto Rico. Why? Because of the toxic, destructive effects of
bombs blasted there over the last 60 years _ bombs sent by the U.S.
military, which uses the land for practice.
 &HT;    Environmentalists say Vieques' delicate coral reefs have been
largely obliterated. Long stretches of its once-pristine beaches
now stand littered with tons of shrapnel, unexploded shells,
discarded military hardware and even the radioactive debris of
bombs that the U.S. Defense Department now admits were tipped with
depleted uranium. Using uranium-tipped weapons is a direct
violation of Pentagon rules.
 &HT;    Carlos Zenon, a local fisherman and activist, says the job of
supporting his family in the poor, remote community has been made
far more difficult by the island's six-decade ``military
occupation.''
 &HT;    Like most of the island's 9,600 residents, Zenon wants the
bombing range shut down. And he vehemently opposed U.S. Attorney
General Janet Reno's decision to order federal agents to expel more
than 200 protesters from Camp Garcia on Vieques on May 4.
 &HT;    Some of the protesters had been camping there for nearly a year
in a stubborn show of civil disobedience against the U.S.
military's use of a 33,000-acre swath on the island.
 &HT;    Protests increased after the death of David Sanes Rodriguez, a
civilian guard at the base, who was killed about a year ago when a
fighter pilot accidentally dropped a bomb on him.
 &HT;    In a recent interview, Zenon repeated the longstanding
complaints of Vieques' residents _ that the bombing has crippled
the local fishing industry and stymied tourism and other economic
development. Unemployment hovers around 50 percent.
 &HT;    Many locals also complain of health problems, including higher
cancer rates, which they believe are linked to the island's
environmental degradation.
 &HT;    But David Sanes Rodriguez's death was the last straw.
 &HT;    Even though Reno has cleared the beaches and sent the protesters
packing, the island's dispute with the Defense Department is still
not resolved _ and it's far from over.
 &HT;    Soon after the expulsion of the protesters from Camp Garcia,
Zenon told me that his sons, Cacimar and Pedro, protested the
conditions by hiding in secret camouflaged shelters somewhere
inside the boundaries of the bombing range.
 &HT;    Later, a federal magistrate issued arrest warrants for the
brothers _ even as the Navy's destroyer USS Stump and Navy A-4
Skyhawks began shelling Vieques with non-exploding ``dummy'' bombs.
 &HT;    Immediately after Reno raided the beaches, a broad coalition of
Puerto Rican church officials, activists and political leaders
vowed to continue fighting until they kick the Navy out of Vieques.
 &HT;    Since then, dozens of protesters have been arrested for
trespassing on the bombing range. Federal authorities say the
protesters could face stiff fines and up to 10 years in prison.
 &HT;    Recently, the bombing range's opponents lost a key ally. Pedro
Rossello, the governor of Puerto Rico, is being roundly criticized
for backing a decision by President Clinton in January to permit
the resumption of limited bombing exercises on Vieques.
 &HT;    According to Clinton's plan, no live ammunition will be used _
at least not unless local residents vote in a referendum to allow
that to happen.
 &HT;    To help persuade the residents that it was a good idea to allow
the bombing to resume, Clinton promised about $90 million in
special economic assistance to the island.
 &HT;    The first $40 million installment could come this year or next,
depending on congressional approval. The remaining $50 million is
contingent upon a ``yes'' vote to let the Navy stay. Seems like a
fair bribe.
 &HT;    According to the White House plan, Vieques' voter referendum on
the issue is supposed to take place sometime in the next two or
three years. Opponents of the bombing range shouldn't count on it.
Clinton wants the issue to just go away.
 &HT;    Meanwhile, the Republican leadership in Congress is already
pressing for ``live ammunition'' bombing to resume immediately.
 &HT;    In the meantime, some have labeled Rossello a ``traitor'' for
backing Clinton's proposal and for also enforcing the removal of
the protesters. It was Rossello who, during a U.S. Senate hearing
last fall, said that ``not one more bomb'' would fall on Vieques.
 &HT;    Rossello did betray the cause. It seems that when it served his
desire to boost his national reputation, Rossello was with the
Puerto Rican people, most of whom want the Navy out. But when he
began to ponder his immediate political future _ Rossello cannot
seek re-election as governor _ he buckled to political pressure
from the White House. If Gore wins the White House, Rossello will
most likely be rewarded.
 &HT;    In the meantime, Zenon says he and his family plan to keep
protesting.
 &HT;    ``As a father, I'm concerned about what may happen to my sons,''
he said. ``Yet there are so many Vieques families who have already
suffered that we're willing to pay the price.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (James E. Garcia is editor-in-chief of Politico magazine, a
monthly publication covering U.S. Latino politics. E-mail
Politico1(AT)aol.com or visit www.politicomagazine.com.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 James E. Garcia 
<TEXT>
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on NEW
AMERICA NEWS SERVICE and other features. &QL;
