<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AEROBIC-EXERCISES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HOW TO GET GOOD AEROBIC EXERCISE WITHOUT ACHES, PAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SYLVIA WOOD  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Tom Fox jogged for more than a decade before his
knees and feet gave out. For the past six months, the retired state
educational administrator has opted for a less jarring type of
exercise _ water aerobics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like this much better,'' said Fox, 63. ``It's a good workout
and the impact on the joints is much less.''
</P>
<P>
   More people are turning to the water as a way to stay in shape
without the aches and pains that go along with traditional types of
exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big benefit is, it's low-impact,'' said Rorie Kerns, a
water and fitness instructor in the Albany area.
</P>
<P>
   Some people, however, still associate low impact with little
effort and little reward. Think again.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say low-impact exercises, such as water aerobics,
cycling and walking are as effective over the long term as some
other kinds of exercises at building fitness and preventing
osteoporosis, a problem of bone-loss, especially among older women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any type of exercise that stresses the skeleton in some way is
beneficial,'' said Dr. J. David Abraham of Northeast Orthopaedics
in Albany. ``Some exercises just give you more bang for your
buck.''
</P>
<P>
   Running and weight-lifting are good examples of high-impact
exercises that put a lot of strain on the skeleton and,
consequently, help build the bone density that prevents
osteoporosis.
</P>
<P>
   Yet such exercises often increase the potential for injuries,
including stress fractures and tendinitis, problems that can derail
a fitness plan for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a trade-off that way,'' said Dr. Shankar Das of
the Orthopaedic Group, also in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   That is one of the reasons physicians are increasingly steering
people toward the water, especially those with arthritis or those
who are new to exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get a lot fewer injuries in the water,'' said Dr. Robert
Cooley, the chief of orthopedics at Ellis Hospital in Schenectady.
``It's a great alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Joba, 83, attributes her good health in part to a
regimen that includes at least one pool session a week. On other
days, she enjoys walking in her hometown of Saratoga Springs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do arms, legs and weights,'' she said. ``We're huffing and
puffing. We feel great afterward. It's tiring but you feel
energized.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerns, 34, believes many younger people continue to look at
water aerobics as something for senior citizens or injured
athletes. But fitness classes in the water have become more
challenging in recent years with more of an emphasis on resistance
and weights, using specially designed dumbbells and flotation
devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say, `Oh, it's in the water, you're not going to get a
workout,''' she said. ``A lot of people don't realize what a great
workout it is.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The key to reaping the fitness and bone-building benefits from
any exercise program is consistency. ``The problem most people have
when they start an exercise program is they don't stick with it,''
Das said.
</P>
<P>
   Add the potential for injury and pain, as is the case with some
high-impact exercises, and you have another reason to quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``For people who haven't exercised previously, water exercise
allows them to participate and minimize the risk of injury. This
allows them to get hooked without injury or pain,'' Abraham said.
</P>
<P>
   Because water aerobics puts less strain on the skeleton than
jogging or walking, Cooley likes to see people mix in other
activities, like walking, to maximize fitness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pushing a lot more cross-training,'' he said. ``It keeps
people healthy if you do a variety of activities. You're less apt
to injure yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that he has tried water aerobics, Fox said he doesn't miss
the pain from jogging. And he believes his weekly pool classes have
helped keep him healthy enough to exercise regularly, both at the
local YMCA and at home in his yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me it's better,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Sylvia Wood can be reached at 518-454-5445 or by electronic
mail at swood(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
