<P>
   WORLD-BRIEFS (Undated) _ World news in brief.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNITED STATES &LR;  _  &UR; General &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' news category)
</P>
<P>
   HARVARD-PRESIDENT (Cambridge, Mass.) _ Neil Rudenstine, a
scholar of Renaissance poetry who led the largest fund-raising
campaign in the history of higher education, plans to step down
next spring after a decade as president of Harvard, the United
State's oldest and most prestigious university. By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   NY-CHILD-STARS (New York) _ The Professional Children's School,
offstage home to actors, concert pianists, ballerinas and other
child performers, has long suffered a reputation as a place where
pushy stage mothers and chain smoking managers send their child
stars so they can continue their careers without having to crack a
book. But now the school is boasting of astonishing success in
getting its students into the nation's premier colleges. By Kate
Zernike.
</P>
<P>
   (This article is tentative and may be eliminated later.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNITED STATES &LR;  _  &UR; Washington  &LR;  (Will move in `w' news category)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-FEDERALISM (Washington) _ The U.S. Supreme Court has
decided the two remaining federalism cases of the term without
coming down strongly on one side or another. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   IMMIG-SECRETS (Washington) _ The U.S. Congress is weighing
whether to outlaw the use of secret evidence in immigration courts.
This practice has led to years of imprisonment for suspects who
cannot see the charges against them or know the reasons they are
jailed. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-MIDEAST (Washington) _ Gov. George W. Bush is scheduled to
speak about the Mideast at an address in Washington on Monday. By
Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `p' category)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `f' news category)
</P>
<P>
   ASIA-INTERNET-TYCOONS (Hong Kong) _ From Taiwan to Thailand,
some of Asia's most powerful families have started online ventures.
But some critics say that despite their chameleon-like
adaptability, Asia's tycoons may have trouble making the leap into
cyberspace because the Internet's emphasis on speed, openness and
collaboration challenges traditional Asian values of prudence,
financial opacity and family control. By Mark Landler. (With
graphics)
</P>
<P>
   (This article is tentative and may be eliminated later.)
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-SATELLITES (Alcantara, Brazil) _ In the satellite
launching business, location is everything. Because Alcantara is
two degrees south of the equator, rockets launched here can achieve
orbit faster and carry heavier payloads than those launched
elsewhere. Built by the Brazilian military two decades ago, the
Alcantara Launch Center has become the focal point for what is
perhaps the most ambitious space program in any developing country.
By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   POLAND-TELEKOM (Undated) _ A consortium led by France Telecom
has won the exclusive right to bid for a 35 percent stake in the
sale of Poland's state-run telecommunications company,
Telekomunikacja Polska. The deal is Eastern Europe's largest
telecommunications privatization. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `e' news category or as indicated)
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-GIELGUD (Undated) _ Sir John Gielgud, one of the great
actors of the English stage who enthralled audiences for more than
60 years with his eloquent voice and consummate artistry, died
Sunday at his home in Aylesbury, west of London. By Mel Gussow.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   (An early version of this story will move by 3 p.m. EDT.)
</P>
<P>
   CHECHEN-CULTURE (Moscow) _ Although he is living in Moscow, Topa
Elimbayev has not abandoned his homeland but is fighting to save
Chechen culture and break the stereotype of his people as bandits
and terrorists. By Sonia Kishkovsky.
</P>
<P>
   AMIS-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Experience,'' Martin Amis'
remarkable new memoir, is an entertainingly footnoted volume that
loops back and forth in time to chronicle the author's coming of
age with becoming earnestness and humor. By Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-FASHION (Dateline to come) _ Fashion from the streets of
Tokyo. By Guy Trebay.
</P>
