<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2238 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-AIDS-AFRICA-HNS &LR;      05-22 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-AFRICA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AFRICA NEEDS AMERICA'S HELP TO COMBAT AIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (EDS: Note optional trim)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JEFF SHEEHY AND TOM COATES  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ South African President Thabo Mbeki is scheduled
to travel to San Francisco later in the week after wrapping up his
state visit to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   He has been the subject of great controversy since the
publication of a letter he wrote last month that raises questions
about the nature of the AIDS epidemic sweeping Africa and the
efficacy of applying Western treatment models there.
</P>
<P>
   Because of this letter, many have suggested Mbeki does not
believe that the human immunodeficiency syndrome, or HIV, causes
AIDS. However, that's not what he says.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he charts a journey toward truth that Africa must
undertake in its response to HIV. Mbeki contrasts the nature of the
AIDS epidemic in the West to that in Africa. In the West, he says,
exposure to HIV has resulted largely through homosexual contact. In
Africa, HIV/AIDS is transmitted predominantly through heterosexual
intercourse.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations reports that about 2 million Africans died of
AIDS, the acquired immune deficiency syndrome, in 1998 and that 23
million Africans are carriers of HIV. Death rates from AIDS are
declining in the West, yet rising in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki draws certain conclusions from these facts.
</P>
<P>
   First, ``whatever lessons we . . . may draw from the West . . .
a simple superimposition of Western experience on African reality
would be absurd and illogical.''
</P>
<P>
   Second, ``our urgent task is to respond to the specific threat
that faces us as Africans.''
</P>
<P>
   Third, ``We will not, ourselves, condemn our own people to death
by giving up the search for specific and targeted responses to the
specifically African incidence of HIV/AIDS.''
</P>
<P>
   Is this controversial? Perhaps, but Mbeki's willingness to
educate himself and his government and to consider tailored
responses to the epidemic does not deserve the near hysterical
avalanche of criticism it has received.
</P>
<P>
   Have we forgotten our own history? How grateful would Americans
confronted with AIDS have been if previous presidents had
approached the epidemic with the same intensity and seriousness?
</P>
<P>
   Some of what Mbeki says is of great concern. He has decided that
his government will not provide, at this time, AZT to HIV-positive
pregnant women.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, he is sympathetic to the dissidents who say HIV
does not cause AIDS. It is understandable that, as a former
dissident, Mbeki is sympathetic to those who challenge authority.
And some of his choices are dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   However, we know needle exchange programs halt the spread of
AIDS and do not encourage illicit drug use. Still, senior American
policymakers refuse to support needle exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Note the American experience. Dissidents in the streets, in
government and in the medical establishment propelled the battle
against AIDS. It took the active cooperation of the affected
communities to stem the spread of the virus.
</P>
<P>
   Communities and individuals self-regulated their sexual
practices. The medical establishment underwent unprecedented
changes as the affected communities and individuals demanded a
partnership with health care providers.
</P>
<P>
   The National Institutes of Health now includes AIDS activists on
its councils and peer review groups, and other disease-related
research reviews now include relevant community activists. The
message was clear: Business as usual could not be tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   A significant part of our success has come by empowering those
affected by HIV/AIDS. Yet this attempt by an African leader to
articulate a uniquely African response is damned. A democratically
elected leader of a people whose struggle for freedom is rightly
celebrated is now treated with disrespect bordering on contempt.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has just declared AIDS a national and global
security threat. Our total spending on HIV/AIDS in 2000 is
approximately $11 billion. Yet only $254 million has been proposed
to fight AIDS in the developing world. Pharmaceutical companies are
pledging $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   When Mbeki compares these dollar figures with the estimated
numbers of people with HIV/AIDS in the United States versus the
numbers in Africa, is he wrong to be skeptical?
</P>
<P>
   The tragedy is that the savage spread of HIV in Africa is
avoidable. The United Nations estimates that an annual expenditure
of $2.5 billion on prevention would cut the number of new
infections by 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   We could be making condoms, sex education, explicit
advertisements and inexpensive STD drugs available now.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the commitment of $1.5 billion to train the Colombian
army to chase drug runners? Let us not get frustrated with Mbeki.
He has a right to be frustrated with us.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Africa must find its own way. We must support leaders like Mbeki
who have the vision and courage to confront the grim challenge
facing them.
</P>
<P>
   Those in the Western scientific establishment who wish to become
engaged in the politics of AIDS in Africa should push their
countries to accept their responsibility toward our fellow
residents of this planet.
</P>
<P>
   During the Cold War, both East and West poured resources into
Africa to support friendly regimes. Can we not demand our societies
show the same interest in supporting African governments, many of
them now democracies, in their struggle to find a way to avert this
catastrophe?
</P>
<P>
   Since President Mbeki wrote his letter, the Clinton
administration has responded in several ways: declaring AIDS a
security threat, allowing patented drugs to be manufactured by
African countries and boosting spending are all important actions.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki's letter succeeded in getting our attention. All the same,
these measures only feebly begin to address the horrifying reality
that Mbeki and all of Africa face.
</P>
<P>
   When HIV has gone the way of smallpox and the World Health
Organization is deciding what to do with the last vial of this
lethal virus, historians will be writing about all of the good
things that the United States has done in the fight against
HIV/AIDS. America's research is unparalleled. We have made a
commitment to the care of people with HIV/AIDS. Nevertheless,
future historians will rightly take us to task for the genocide
that we are allowing to happen in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Sheehy is deputy director for communications for the AIDS
Research Institute at the University of California at San
Francisco. Tom Coates is a professor of medicine and director of
the institute.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
