<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2243 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-BOY-TOYS-HNS &LR;      05-22 0522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOY-TOYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GIRLS GOING CRAZY OVER TRADING CARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ELAINE ARADILLAS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ A new trading card game on the market has
adolescent girls going crazy. Boy crazy.
</P>
<P>
   Card magnate Decipher Inc. has tapped a nerve in the young male
market with games inspired by ``Star Wars,'' and now, girls who
want to have a little fun can trade Chris from California for Kevin
in Minnesota with the Boy Crazy! game cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys get whatever they want, like WWF or sports trading cards,
and girls are supposed to get games about math, women in history
and role models,'' said Leslie Hellerman, marketing and public
relations manager for Boy Crazy!, based in Norfolk, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Hellerman said young people should be learning about subjects
that are educational and good for them _ referred to as ``spinach''
in the marketing industry _ but sometimes girls need to feel good
about other things they are interested in, like boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is providing what they want, and that's why Boy Crazy!
is going through the roof,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Not every girl is insane about Boy Crazy! cards. San Antonio
middle school student Brenda Donahue, 12, was at North Star Mall
recently when Decipher held a casting call for young Texans to
appear on next year's gaming cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have better things to spend my money on,'' Donahue said,
rolling her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is so sixth-grade,'' added her friend Michelle Franco, a
seventh-grader.
</P>
<P>
   Boy Crazy!, featuring boys from all over the country, was
launched on Valentine's Day 1999, but has really taken off in the
past two months.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Toy Manufacturers of America, an industry trade
association, the trading card industry shipped $820 million worth
of cards to retail stores in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pokemon sort of opened the door for girls to begin trading.
Boy Crazy! has filled that next step for them,'' Hellerman said.
</P>
<P>
   The cards are sold in packs of nine for a retail cost of $3.99.
Each card showcases a particular boy, with his photo and personal
information, and what he sees as ideal traits in a girl. There are
363 boys featured on the cards. The game is intended for girls 10
and older.
</P>
<P>
   The object of the game has one girl secretly choosing the guy
she would most like to go out with, based on the information listed
on the cards. Her friends try to guess which boy she picked and
explain why.
</P>
<P>
   If a girl doesn't find the boy of her dreams in her pack of
cards, she can go online at www.boycrazy.com and peruse more than
300 virtual cards featuring boys from all over the country. The
interactive site receives more than a million visits a day.
</P>
<P>
   Decipher Inc. has decided to expand its boundaries and is
searching globally for its next edition of boy cards. In the
upcoming months, Hellerman and her public relations team will be
searching for boys in Toronto, Paris and London.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter what language you speak or where you live.
It's an international stage that girls go through _ that stage of
boy-craziness,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 1315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
