<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-ADVISORY </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   Here is MONDAY'S package of Medical News Today health-news
stories and features prepared by HealthScout.com and distributed by
The New York Times Syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   To purchase any of these articles separately, please contact
syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480.
</P>
<P>
   For information on how to subscribe to the daily package of
Medical News Today stories, call your New York Times Syndicate
sales executive at 888-269-8796.
</P>
<P>
   TAKING THE SEDATION OUT OF VALIUM-LIKE DRUGS
</P>
<P>
   Valium without the drowsy side effects? Separating the calming
effect from the dulling one may pave the way to a more refined
drug, says new research.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-anxiety drugs from the Valium family (benzodiazepine) are
some of the most commonly prescribed drugs in the world. When they
came on the market in the 1950s, they were a vast improvement over
barbiturates, which could be habit-forming and had other side
effects.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, benzodiazepines are far from perfect, and patients
still face side effects like sedation, motor coordination problems
and the risk of dependence. But now researchers have managed to
lower the anxiety level of mice without dulling their senses. They
hope to use similar techniques to develop anti-anxiety drugs for
humans without the undesirable side effects. (500 words. Slugged
VALIUM-REFINE-MED)
</P>
<P>
   VIBRATING TOOLS AND SMOKING DON'T MIX
</P>
<P>
   A disease suffered by people who frequently use vibrating tools
seems to be made worse by smoking, says a new U.S. study.
</P>
<P>
   The disease -- called vibration-induced white finger, or
occupational Raynaud's phenomenon -- occurs when the vibration of
tools like chainsaws and jackhammers make the user's hands
oversensitive to cool temperatures. (600 words. Slugged
SMOKING-VIBRATE-MED)
</P>
<P>
   CONTAMINANT LEVELS LOWER IN FARM-RAISED FISH
</P>
<P>
   Picking out fish from a supermarket display is certainly a
comedown from hooking them in rushing, wild waters. On the other
hand, it's probably safer.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at Purdue University tested farm-raised catfish,
crayfish and rainbow trout for a variety of pesticides and
discovered that the vast majority contained levels that were lower
than those for fish caught in the wild. (600 words. Slugged
FARM-FISH-MED)
</P>
<P>
   PATIENT-FRIENDLY VERSION OF COLON CANCER GUIDELINES DEVELOPED
</P>
<P>
   As if hearing a diagnosis of colon cancer wasn't hard enough,
people typically find themselves baffled when trying to understand
the complexities of the disease and the treatment options.
</P>
<P>
   But a new reader-friendly publication aims to change that. The
publication takes the medical information used by oncologists in
treating colon and rectal cancer and translates it into
easy-to-understand language. This should allow people to take a
greater role in and make better-informed decisions about their own
treatment. (450 words. Slugged COLON-CANCER-GUIDELINES-MED)
</P>
<P>
   MORE PEOPLE FACE THROAT CANCER RISK
</P>
<P>
   Significantly more people who suffer from a precancerous
condition known as Barrett's esophagus face the risk of developing
cancer than previously thought, American researchers now say.
</P>
<P>
   Associated with chronic heartburn, Barrett's esophagus affects
about 2 million people in the United States. It develops when the
regurgitation of stomach contents stimulates changes in the lining
of the esophagus -- the tube that carries food from the mouth to
the stomach -- so that it resembles the lining of the intestines.
(600 words. Slugged THROAT-CANCER-MED)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT HEALTHSCOUT:
</P>
<P>
   HealthScout (http://www.healthscout.com) is a service of Rx
Remedy, Inc., a leader in the field of health information and
publisher of REMEDY Magazine, a prize-winning health publication
read in 2.2 American homes.
</P>
<P>
   -- All of HealthScout's original stories are based on primary
sources: reports in refereed medical journals and interviews with
the medical researchers who authored them. Fact-checkers
independently confirm reporters' work on sensitive stories.
</P>
<P>
   -- HealthScout's medical writers and editors have previously
worked at many of the nation's most respected newspapers and
magazines.
</P>
<P>
   -- HealthScout's Scientific Advisory Board includes leading
authorities in more than a dozen disciplines.
</P>
