<HEADER>
A2257 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN     05-22 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LEGACY OF JOHN WESLEY, THE INADVERTENT FOUNDER OF METHODISM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ While controversial issues were being debated last week
at the United Methodist General Conference in Cleveland, I was in
London looking for the heart of Methodism.
</P>
<P>
   My goal was to worship at Wesley's Chapel, the most famous of
the churches established by John Wesley, the inadvertent founder of
Methodism in the 1700s.
</P>
<P>
   I say inadvertent because Wesley, a 5-foot-4 cleric who
alienated church powers by fervently preaching to coal miners and
other English working people, never intended to start a new
denomination.
</P>
<P>
   He remained a priest in the Church of England throughout his 88
years. But English leaders gradually closed their church doors to
him. So, he began preaching outdoors under trees and in fields and
eventually built his own chapels.
</P>
<P>
   Wesley's actions coincided with a spiritual awakening in England
and the United States and resulted in the creation of Methodist
churches around the world.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to attend church where it all began.
</P>
<P>
   I was due to arrive in London early Sunday, but my flight was
more than an hour late, meaning I would have a hard time getting
into London in time for worship at Wesley's Chapel.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I decided to give it a try. It was almost noon by the
time I arrived by underground train at the Old Street station, near
Wesley's Chapel. I walked the few hundred yards to the church, sure
the worship would be concluded.
</P>
<P>
   I was surprised to find the historic chapel filled with people
singing hymns and preparing to celebrate Communion. I slipped into
a back pew and was greeted by a man who handed me a hymn book.
</P>
<P>
   Male voices dominated the hymns, including some written by
Charles Wesley, brother of John. Charles wrote more than 5,500
hymns, including ``Hark the Herald Angels, Sing.'' On the Sunday I
attended, parishioners sang ``Just As I Am,'' ``Amazing Grace'' and
``Up From the Grave He Arose.''
</P>
<P>
   Twelve young people in white robes were baptized by the pastor,
the Rev. Leslie J. Griffiths, a former president of the British
Methodist Conference who has been pastor for four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has brought us alive,'' longtime member David Tee said
after the service.
</P>
<P>
   While smiling and hugging parishioners after church, Griffiths
refused to take full credit for the church's resurgence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Energies were just waiting to be tapped,'' said Griffiths,
who, coincidentally, will be in Texas on Sept. 17 to speak at the
First United Methodist Church of Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Griffiths has reached out to people of all nationalities who
live in inner-city London. They include natives of the Caribbean,
South Africa, Japan, Zimbabwe, Sierra Leone, Ghana, Bolivia and the
Philippines; some wear the traditional dress of their native lands.
</P>
<P>
   Times haven't always been so good to Wesley's Chapel. Back in
the 1970s, some even suggested boarding up the church, which was in
disrepair. One bizarre plan called for selling the church brick by
brick, perhaps to someone in the United States interested in the
historic place, said Tee, who also is church treasurer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans already have the old London Bridge (now in Lake
Havasu City, Ariz.), and the old Queen Mary cruise ship (docked in
Long Beach, Calif.), so buying Wesley's Chapel didn't seem too
far-fetched,'' Tee said.
</P>
<P>
   But other Englishmen _ and many Americans, Australians and
people from other nations _ were outraged by such a thought. More
than 1 million pounds was raised to refurbish the historic chapel
and John Wesley's home next door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Queen Elizabeth came here for the first time in 1978 to
celebrate our improvements,'' Tee said.
</P>
<P>
   During a London twilight, I also visited another special place
for Methodists. It is on Aldersgate Street where Wesley, on May 24,
1738, had a spiritual rebirth.
</P>
<P>
   In his journal, Wesley writes about ``very unwillingly'' going
to a nighttime society meeting on Aldersgate Street and listening
to a reading from Martin Luther's Preface to the Epistle to the
Romans ``describing the change which God works in the heart through
faith in Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt my heart strangely warmed,'' Wesley wrote. ``I felt I
did trust in Christ, Christ alone for salvation, and an assurance
was given me that he had taken away my sins, even mine, and saved
me from the law of sin and death.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the place is marked by a flame-shaped plaque standing 10
feet high on an upper-level walkway of the huge Barbican Centre;
the walkway has been named John Wesley Way.
</P>
<P>
   As I stood there, my heart was strangely warmed, too, as I
realized that despite the excessive secularization of society, John
Wesley's dream of reaching out to all of God's people still is very
much alive.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
