<SLUG> BC-ELECTRIC-BIKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BIKE GIVES RIDERS SOME EXTRA JUICE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's as quiet as a whisper, emits zero pollutants and transports
one person from Point A to Point B in relative comfort _ as long as
it's not raining outside and the weather is neither too hot nor too
cold.
</P>
<P>
   Forget gasoline, tune-ups and oil changes, but don't forget to
bring along an extension cord.
</P>
<P>
   That's because after you have ridden your new E-bike to work,
you will need to hook it up to the nearest electrical outlet to
recharge its battery for the ride home.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the latest twist in the environmentally friendly,
politically correct commute: the electric bicycle, a product of a
company founded and owned by automotive icon Lee Iacocca.
</P>
<P>
   After a failed attempt to buy the Chrysler Corp. after his 1993
retirement as the automaker's chairman, Iacocca turned to
alternative transportation as his newest business endeavor,
founding EV Global Motors Co. in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The E-bike, a retro-looking bicycle similar to the Schwinns of
the '50s, has regular pedals and seven gears, so it can go almost
anywhere on human power, with virtually no limitations.
</P>
<P>
   But it comes with something extra: a 400-watt electric motor
built into the hub of the rear wheel, which allows the bike to
coast along at speeds up to 15 mph with the rider doing nothing but
steering and maintaining balance. And it even has cruise control.
</P>
<P>
   Iacocca's company believes that more people will turn to the
E-bike for at least some of their transportation needs. And the
bikes are good for more than just campground use, the company
insists. In fact, the company is developing an entire line of small
electric vehicles, including a scooter, similar to a Vespa, a
three-wheel bike, a ``pedicab,'' with a bike seat for the driver
and two covered seats for passengers, and an ``NEV,'' which is
short for ``neighborhood electric vehicle,'' which looks like a
miniature sports car and seats two people.
</P>
<P>
   Prices start at $995 (plus $49 destination charge) for the
E-bike's standard model. There are two other versions: the Comfort
model, which includes a suspension seat, rear cargo rack with tote
bag and curved handle bars for $1,109 plus destination charge; and
the top-of-the-line Touring model, with disc brakes and more cargo
capacity, for $1,345 plus destination fee.
</P>
<P>
   If that seems pricey for a bicycle, remember that this one helps
you along on those grueling hill-climbs, and it's still not as
expensive as some of the mountain bicycles that have become popular
with sport riders. Those can cost $3,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   The E-bike operates from a 24-volt battery pack built into the
frame. The pack has a built-in charger that needs only to be
plugged into any standard electrical outlet for recharging _ which
takes 4.5 hours. The range on a charge is just under 20 miles for a
200-pound rider averaging 10 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Helping the bike by doing some pedaling can extend that range
quite a bit.
</P>
<P>
   The bike can be used in one of three modes: all electric power
with no pedaling; motor and pedaling together; or just pedaling
alone. Even with the 23-pound battery pack installed, the bike
weighs just 67 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   It has a headlight and taillight for night riding, and there
also is a horn. Using these electrical accessories heavily can
decrease the range between charges, however. They are powered by
the same battery that the motor uses.
</P>
<P>
   For indoor charging, the battery pack can be lifted quickly out
of the bike and carried by its own handle.
</P>
<P>
   The battery pack is good for about 350 recharges, or about 7,000
miles, the company says. Replacement batteries cost $100 each.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact G. Chambers Williams III by telephone at 210-250-3236
or by e-mail chambers(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
