r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     05-22 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET'S ABOLISH EFFORT TO HALT EXECUTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The anti-capital-punishment crowd is spinning its wheels again.
When they tire of mourning the state-imposed deaths of serial
killers and other homicidal maniacs, it seems, death-penalty
opponents enjoy dabbling in politics.
</P>
<P>
   So. The New Hampshire Senate approved a bill last week that
would ban capital punishment in the Granite State. The House passed
the ban in March.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately (for the future of civilized society as well as for
the people of New Hampshire), Gov. Jeanne Shaheen supports capital
punishment and has promised to veto this preposterous piece of
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is apparently academic, anyway, seeing as how there are
no prisoners residing on New Hampshire's Death Row, and the
population is not expected to increase in the near future.
According to news reports, New Hampshire had the lowest homicide
rate in the United States in 1998 _ and hasn't executed anyone
since 1939.
</P>
<P>
   Since the bill isn't needed and the governor will refuse to sign
it, why in the world did New Hampshire lawmakers waste the public's
time and money enacting it? Just to make a point, perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   This is the state, after all, where voters handed
flash-in-the-pan presidential candidate John McCain a victory in
the Republican primary _ for no apparent reason except to make a
point.
</P>
<P>
   The point in this case might be found in the reaction of Richard
C. Dieter, executive director of the Death Penalty Information
Center in Washington. Dieter was quoted by The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
   ``For a state to take a totally different direction and vote to
abolish it is an indication of legislative and popular change.
There's a longer road ahead, but New Hampshire might be a
bellwether of where the country is going.''
</P>
<P>
   A bellwether? That would mean that New Hampshire is ahead of the
curve _ that state after state will be rushing to abolish capital
punishment, and everyone will look back one day and say, ``Wow, New
Hampshire was really on top of that one.''
</P>
<P>
   Why, the next thing New Hampshire's legislators might want to do
is change the state's nickname from the ``Granite State'' to the
``Bellwether State.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's first-in-the-nation presidential primary certainly
has been a bellwether over the years. Remember President Gary Hart?
President Paul Tsongas? President Pat Buchanan?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he didn't mean to say ``bellwether''; maybe he meant to
say ``death knell.''
</P>
<P>
   How wonderful it would be for the cause of justice in this
country if chronically out-of-step New Hampshire's attack on the
death penalty were to actually signal the beginning of the end for
the anti-capital-punishment movement. We don't need to abolish
capital punishment in America; we need to abolish the notion that
it ought to be abolished.
</P>
<P>
   Right-thinking Americans whose hearts bleed not for killers but
for victims of killers have no interest whatsoever in doing away
with the ultimate punishment for those who commit the ultimate
crime.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press quoted New Hampshire's governor:
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some murders so heinous that the death penalty is an
appropriate punishment and, accordingly, I will veto this
legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's hear it for Shaheen, a Democrat _ as opposed to, let's
say, the Republican governor of Illinois, George Ryan, who declared
a moratorium on executions after some Death Row inmates in his
state were able to raise doubts about their convictions.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a news flash, folks: The purpose of the appeals process
in the criminal justice system is to give persons found guilty of a
crime the opportunity to prove their innocence _ and Death Row
inmates all across America get plenty of chances to do exactly
that.
</P>
<P>
   If criminal suspects are being unfairly convicted, then let's
take a look at the process that leads to conviction, not at the
punishment imposed on the guilty.
</P>
<P>
   There is no evidence that innocent people are being executed in
this country. And there's no reason to pass laws dealing with a
problem that does not exist.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com.) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
