<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000522.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2284 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-AUTO-PT-CRUISER-HNS &LR;      05-22 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-PT-CRUISER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CHRYSLER'S COOL CRUISER HAS BROAD APPEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OK, I'll have to admit it.
</P>
<P>
   The 2001 Chrysler PT Cruiser is just about the coolest-looking
car to come along since, probably, the Plymouth Prowler in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, it's not quite as cool as the Prowler, and not nearly
as exciting, from a purely performance standpoint.
</P>
<P>
   But hey, it's a lot more practical than the Prowler.
</P>
<P>
   And above all, it's affordable, something that the Prowler will
never be. It's much cooler-looking than a lot of cars that you
would pay several thousand dollars more for, such as the Honda
Accord or Toyota Camry.
</P>
<P>
   We tested the entry-level automatic-transmission model, whose
bottom line was just $17,790, including $550 transportation. When
you consider that the average cost of a new car is more than
$20,000, the PT Cruiser rings up as a real bargain, especially when
you get such a large measure of coolness in the package.
</P>
<P>
   Even though this was not the top-of-the-line special edition
that lists for about $22,000, our test car was fairly
well-equipped. Besides the four-speed automatic transmission, it
came with air-conditioning, power windows, and an AM/FM/cassette
audio system, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   There were a couple of items I would have added to make it a bit
more practical: power door locks (preferably with remote control)
and cruise control.
</P>
<P>
   Those items are available _ DaimlerChrysler just didn't put them
on the car they provided us for the test drive. But this little
baby did draw crowds and turn heads everywhere I drove it. The
styling is a mix of street rod (a la the Prowler) and '40s panel
truck.
</P>
<P>
   The car's broad appeal reaches all ages, from children and teens
to aging baby boomers and even to their parents.
</P>
<P>
   That's the charm of the PT Cruiser, and why it will be a
resounding success.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a great car from a mechanical or performance
standpoint; it's really only a Dodge Neon underneath, and it comes
with just a 2.4-liter, 150-horsepower four-cylinder engine.
</P>
<P>
   That is enough power to satisfy most everyday driving needs, but
it won't be enough to win many races. Still, the PT Cruiser can
seat up to five adults (four comfortably) and provide room in the
rear for stuff, such as luggage or sports equipment.
</P>
<P>
   For practical matters, it is a cross between a sport-utility
vehicle and a minivan, but there is no four-wheel drive available;
just like the Neon and most of the Dodge/Chrysler minivans, the PT
comes with front-wheel drive.
</P>
<P>
   An associate who drove our test car as we went to lunch one day
summed it up in one sentence: ``It's really a neat-looking vehicle,
but it reminds me of driving my minivan.''
</P>
<P>
   You could do worse, of course. There are a whole lot of us
driving our minivans around every day, but when was the last time
you saw someone's head spin around to take another look at a
minivan?
</P>
<P>
   Consumers are flocking to the PT Cruiser like nothing that has
come before it except, perhaps, the 1964-1/2 Ford Mustang. Not even
did Volkswagen's New Beetle, introduced a couple of years ago,
cause this much excitement in the automotive world. Dealers aren't
even taking orders right now because orders have outstripped
manufacturing capacity for the calendar year, even though the PT
was introduced only about a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   But whether consumers will continue to clamor for the PT Cruiser
in the years to come remains to be seen, and will depend on how
well these first few hundred-thousand hold up in real-world use. If
they start falling apart after a few thousand miles and owners have
to spend lots of time shuffling their vehicles back to dealers for
repairs, no manner of coolness will sustain today's runaway sales.
</P>
<P>
   I'm betting the Cruiser is built well enough to keep its owners
happy, and that sales will continue to be brisk enough to keep
supplies low and demand high. And it will still be cool to own a PT
Cruiser _ unless, of course, everyone on your street has one, and
all of a sudden we get tired of seeing these cars everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicle is compact outside. Overall length is just over 14
feet _ 5.3 inches shorter than the Ford Focus compact sedan. But
inside there is 120 cubic feet of space, nearly as much as a
full-size sedan. There are two bucket seats up front, and a
60/40-split two-section rear seat that can be folded or removed in
sections to accommodate more cargo.
</P>
<P>
   Standard equipment, besides the air conditioning and audio
system, includes five-speed manual transmission, power
rack-and-pinion steering, power front disc/rear drum brakes, tilt
steering wheel, rear-window defroster, floor mats, 15-inch wheels
with bolt-on wheel covers, and manual side mirrors. There are dual
air bags in the front.
</P>
<P>
   Base price for our test vehicle was $15,450 plus transportation.
Extras included the automatic transmission ($625), side air bags
for the front occupants ($350), and four-wheel antilock disc brakes
($790).
</P>
<P>
   EPA fuel-economy ratings are 20 miles per gallon in the city and
25 mpg on the highway. The tank holds 15 gallons of gasoline, and
unleaded regular is recommended.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact G. Chambers Williams III by telephone at 210-250-3236
or by e-mail chambers(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
