<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A0523 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service AUSTIN, Texas _
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I make stuffed animals with a college theme and want to
market them. The pattern I use is copyrighted. Does that mean the
finished product is also? Do I need permission from a college to
sell something with its logo? How about if I use the college colors
and include a manufactured pin or what-not? Do I need to copyright
my finished product?
</P>
<P>
   _ L. J
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Purchasing the pattern undoubtedly gives you a license to
make, use or sell items made from it,'' says Andrew Dillon, patent
attorney at Felsman, Bradley, Vaden, Gunter &AMP; Dillon. Generally the
logos, colors, etc. of colleges are copyrighted and licensed to
others for commercial use. So yes, you need permission for an
official product. Simply making an animal of the school colors and
then putting on a licensed school pin or clip would be OK, adds
Dillon. Registering a copyright is not necessary. Put an
appropriate copyright notice (''copyright'' or the circled ``c'',
the year of first publication and your name) in order to avoid
someone alleging that they are an ``innocent infringer.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: An over-friendly bird spends hours each day flying directly
into a window. The noise is heard throughout the house. Can you
help us save this bird and our window?
</P>
<P>
   _ Felicity M.
</P>
<P>
   A: This bird sees its own reflection, and either thinks this
other bird is competition or a conceivable mate. It is defending
territory or trying to meet a possible prom date. Cover the window
with cardboard to eliminate the reflection or place a rubber snake
or plastic owl on the ledge.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Recently, a funeral procession was on a small two-lane road
leading to the cemetery. What is the proper thing to do when a
procession passes?
</P>
<P>
   _ Debra T.
</P>
<P>
   A: Pull over, stop and let the cortege pass in an unbroken line.
This shows respect for the family and the occasion. In addition,
out-of-town attendees may get lost unless they stay with the
procession. What's the harm in a few idle moments?
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have always stored my mink coat with a professional, but a
friend told me I don't need to. She said as long as I keep the
house cool, the coat would be fine. I certainly don't want to
damage my fur in any way, but saving this money and time would be
nice. Is this correct? Can I store the coat at home, and if so,
what room temperature would be safe? Other tips?
</P>
<P>
   _ R.K.
</P>
<P>
   A: Really want to keep your home at 45 degrees, 50 percent
humidity this summer? Nippy and expensive. That is the recommended
climate for fur storage, according to the Fur Information Council.
Remember, closets are usually 10 degrees warmer than the rest of
the house. Improper storage will shorten the life of your fur by
drying out the natural oils in the leather. In addition,
professional storage is an opportunity to have your fur cleaned and
mended if necessary. Furs should be stored on a broad-shouldered
hanger out of direct sunlight (not in a cedar chest).
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have shredded years of old records _ paid bills, bank
statements, etc. _ as I don't want everybody to know our account
numbers and business. I put two of the large brown paper bags (used
for lawn clippings) full of shredded paper and the recycling guys
never took them. Can you advise me what to do to get rid of this
paper?
</P>
<P>
   _ Pat D.
</P>
<P>
   A: Write ``recycled paper'' on the front or top of the bag.
Perhaps the recyclers weren't sure what the bags contained. More
recycling questions? Contact Solid Waste Services at 499-2111.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My back yard is full of snails. Some are bigger than a
half-dollar. What kind of snails are they? What do they eat besides
my aloe vera plant?
</P>
<P>
   _ B.P.
</P>
<P>
   A: Probably the brown garden snail, says entomologist John
Jackman, of Texas A&AMP;M Extension Service. They eat almost anything
and love humidity. Baits work to control them, but so does a saucer
of beer (they sip, then drown). Copper strips are sometimes used as
snail barriers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Every time we travel to Europe we run into different
holidays. That puts a damper on shopping as the stores are all
closed! Is there a list of foreign holidays?
</P>
<P>
   _ J.M.
</P>
<P>
   A: Shopkeepers in European countries often have a fairly
cavalier attitude about hours. So, verify museum and shop hours
with the concierge when you arrive. In general, museums are closed
on Monday, and many shops close daily for a long lunch break. Visit
tyzo.com for info on scheduled holidays. Tyzo.com also offers
information on time zones, dialing codes and currency for world
travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a pair of vintage Levi's that I would like hemmed.
Vintage Levi's have a special hem stitch called a chain stitch. Do
you know of anyone that can do it? I would really like to keep
these authentic.
</P>
<P>
   _ P.M. A: You need Denim Doctors. Holes to hems are repaired
with strict attention to authenticity. Send your Levis to Denim
Doctors Repairs, 8044 West Third St., Los Angeles, Calif. 90048.
Include your name, return address and telephone number. Want to
discuss your beloved jeans? Call (800) JEANSDR. Q: My son and I are
at odds, and hopefully you can settle things. I say Haley Joel
Osment, the great young actor who played Cole in ``The Sixth
Sense,'' is the same kid who leads the classroom uprising in the
Pizza Hut commercial where he rallies his classmates to ``The
Edge.'' Nothing but family honor riding on this, but it's driving
me NUTS!
</P>
<P>
   _ Jeff R.
</P>
<P>
   A: Your son wins. Pizza Hut's spokeswoman Patty Sullivan says
``The Edge'' ad features ``just a child actor, not Osment.'' But I
understand your confusion. The 12-year-old is ubiquitous _
``Forrest Gump'' (the child) to the ``Jeff Foxworthy Show'' (Matt),
and at the tender age of 4 appeared in a 1992 series of Pizza Hut
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Our entire new deck was built with treated wood. Now I worry
that the whole family and pets are tracking toxins (I know they use
a percentage of arsenic, etc., in the treatment), into our home and
carpets and beds from our bare feet, etc. Can you find out for me?
</P>
<P>
   _ Loree G,
</P>
<P>
   A: The wood has probably been treated with chromated copper
arsenate (CCA), which does not present a problem to your family
through direct contact, says Texas Department of Health's John F.
Villanacci. CCA can leach into the soil. Unless your pets or
children ingest substantial amounts of the soil, CCA will not cause
a problem. The major concern surrounding CCA-treated lumber is its
disposal. Such wood should not be burned. Concerns about landfill
disposal of this lumber (will the chemicals leach into the
groundwater?) also exist.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for a poem along the lines of the ``Last Leaf on
the Tree.'' I think it's about growing old and losing all your
friends over the years until you are the last leaf left. Ever heard
of it?
</P>
<P>
   _ Ali T.
</P>
<P>
   A: ``The Last Leaf,'' by Oliver Wendell Holmes (1809-1894) _
Harvard Medical School anatomy professor and father of the Supreme
Court justice who penned the phrase ``clear and present danger.''
Written around 1831, this poem is a salute to Maj. Thomas Melville,
grandfather of Herman Melville, author of ``Moby Dick.'' The last
leaf (line) refers to Melville's interactions with a younger
generation: ``And if I should live to be, The last leaf upon the
tree, In the spring, Let them smile, as I do now, At the old
forsaken bough, Where I cling.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is hard money? Soft money?
</P>
<P>
   _ Louis P.
</P>
<P>
   A: Hard money is money raised and spent according to federal
regulations and restrictions. This money is used to advocate a
specific candidacy. Unions and corporations cannot contribute to a
hard-money fund. In addition, federal law limits contributions to
$1,000 per voter and $5,000 a year per political action committee
per election.
</P>
<P>
   Soft money is essentially everything else. Soft money
contributions are to be used for generic party-building activities
as well as local and state political activities (e.g.
get-out-the-vote drives), notes the Center for Responsible
Politics.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin, TX, 78767; (512)
445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
