<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH0523-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Many browsing Web before heading to mall
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``No, thanks. Just looking.''
</P>
<P>
   How many times have you uttered or sneered or snapped that
phrase at some well-meaning salesperson at the mall determined to
separate you from your money? While you may make a purchase
eventually, first you have to decide which set of lawn furniture
will look best on your deck or if you really need a new teakettle
that whistles when the water's boiling.
</P>
<P>
   Or how about this: you want to buy a car but you have no idea if
the window sticker or the salesman are giving you the information
you need to make an informed decision.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet and electronic commerce have turned on the lights
for uneducated consumers, giving us access to product information
we never had. Millions of wired users have gone online, many to
make purchases but many more just to look at manufacturers' Web
sites and product comparison sites like MySimon (www.mysimon.com)
or Bottom Dollar (www.bottomdollar.com) to research before they
buy.
</P>
<P>
   A new study from Internet research firm Jupiter Communications
suggests that e-commerce is not limited to online purchases, which
Jupiter estimates will hit about $200 billion by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   In its most interesting finding, the study also says consumers
will spend three times that amount offline in brick-and-mortar
retail outlets, catalogs or other traditional shopping outlets
armed with the research they have done on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The study suggests that e-commerce isn't just about selling
merchandise online, it's about educating consumers. Jupiter says
there is no doubt the Web will generate millions in sales in the
years to come, but the actual transaction could come from any
established retail channel _ the Web, the mall or even the catalog
that just came in the mail.
</P>
<P>
   An Atlanta start-up company called Figleaves.com sells men's and
women's undergarments online but also plans to open a
brick-and-mortar store in New York later this year. The company
says users shouldn't be limited to having just one outlet to
purchase its products.
</P>
<P>
   Upscale retailer Neiman Marcus is working with another Atlanta
company to bring a multidimensional approach to the online shopping
experience. Users will be able to visit a virtual Manolo Blahnik
shoe salon and examine the pricey footwear from a variety of
angles. But it's the rare customer who will spend upwards of $500
for a product only seen online, although online ordering is
possible. Many shoe lovers will head directly to the nearest
Neiman's and request the shoes they admired on the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter says the Web offers a world of opportunity to display
products and educate users, thus generating sales. Jupiter's study
says the Web actually exerts a tremendous influence over purchases
made in the real world as well as online.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, Jupiter uses Royal Caribbean Cruise Lines as a
prime example of Web browsing. Users may visit the cruise line's
site to research a trip to Alaska and decide when they want to go
and what type of cabin they would like, based on factors such as
availability and price.
</P>
<P>
   While the user may not make an online reservation, Jupiter says
the customer has practically completed the ``buying cycle'' and
that the travel agent or telephone representative who does make the
reservation will complete the sale much more quickly as a result.
The actual purchase of items could be called ``the last mile'' of
electronic commerce. If all the work is done online, where the
actual dollars change hands isn't that important in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Browsers'' is the term Jupiter applies to consumers who do
extensive research on products and services online but have yet to
make an online purchase, and most browsers will spend money on the
items they are researching.
</P>
<P>
   I know several people who have spent weeks researching
everything from Saturn automobiles to Oriental rugs online. None of
them plan to make online purchases of those items, but they say the
knowledge they've gained from their research has been invaluable.
</P>
<P>
   One walked into the car dealership armed with the ``blue book''
price of her current car and the exact location and price of the
car she wanted. Another says she now knows what a good Oriental rug
should cost and how to distinguish quality. Another acquaintance
has been spending hours online researching the perfect home theater
system.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to making an actual purchase, all three say
they will go to a traditional real-world retailer.
</P>
<P>
   And Jupiter's study would agree with comic Jerry Seinfeld's
line: ``Not that there's anything wrong with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
