<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NON-SPORT-GAMES0523-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Jet Grind Radio' among console games that will be hot this year
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At the Sega booth during the E3Expo in Los Angeles
recently, the line to play ``Jet Grind Radio'' was so long company
officials sometimes had to ask enthusiasts to stop so others could
play the new video game.
</P>
<P>
   The highly anticipated game is for the Sega Dreamcast and will
be released this fall. Here are 10 of the top non-sports games on
all the consoles _ PlayStation 2, PlayStation, Nintendo 64 and
Dreamcast _ that will go on sale before the holiday season:
</P>
<P>
   ``Conker's Bad Fur Day'' (N64): This was the biggest surprise
for Nintendo at the convention. Story line: Conker the squirrel had
a bad night and, equipped with only a frying pan and hangover, is
about to experience the worst day of his life. The cute little
animal shows his dark side by doing his best to ruin the daily
activities of others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dark Cloud'' (PS2): Many journalists studied this game at the
E3Expo to fully comprehend the graphic capabilities of Sony's new
system. In this role-playing game, young hero Toran finds that an
evil spirit has wreaked destruction on all living things. The
beauty and detail of the landscapes are mind-boggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dead or Alive 2'' (DC, PS2): Even though the game has been out
for a month on Sega, it has been almost impossible to find a copy
in stores. The Tecmo-produced fighting game has been No. 1 in
Dreamcast sales for the past three weeks. The reason? Graphically
rich fighting locations, ranging from a lush opera house to a
moving elevator cage and more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marvel vs. Capcom 2'' (DC): Capcom Entertainment is releasing
its No. 1 arcade hit to the console market. The game features a
record number of playable characters (more than 50) for pure action
fighting, including special three-on-three battles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gorkamorka'' (DC): Ripcord Games recently formed a partnership
with Sega and unveiled four upcoming games for the system,
including this one. The game is a rarity, as it combines
combat-style action with racing. It's best in the two-player mode,
where one can race the vehicle while the partner focuses on blowing
up the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jet Grind Radio'' (DC): Based on its popularity at the E3Expo,
this might be Sega's best-selling game of the fall. The plot is
simple: The city government has set forth a plan to keep kids from
expressing themselves in any way, shape or form. The kids rally
behind special skating shoes and spray paint to design their own
graffiti art. The colorful graphics are amazing, with characters in
full 3-D and everything else in 2-D.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perfect Dark'' (N64): It's tough to follow the classic
``Golden Eye 007,'' but Rare far exceeded expectations with this
sequel. James Bond is no longer the central character, but rather
Joanna Perfect Dark _ who was the perfect student at spy school and
now has to face real-life espionage. The most fun part of game is
the four-player matchups.
</P>
<P>
   ``SimTheme Park'' (PS2): Using the power of Sony's new system,
Electronic Arts takes this game great strides past the PlayStation
version. Players can wander through theme parks they create and
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spyro: Year of the Dragon'' (PS): Spyro and Sparx are back in
a new adventure, faced with the challenge of defeating an evil
sorceress who has kidnapped all the dragon eggs. Skills required
include boxing, skateboarding, sharpshooting and more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Wants to be a Millionaire'' (PS): Everyone's favorite
television game show set records for sales on the PC, and host
Regis Philbin was at the E3Expo to personally introduce the console
version.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
