<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2325 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TECH-CENTERPIECE0523-     05-22 1755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-CENTERPIECE0523-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cell phones expand users opportunities
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Remember that famous line from the old ``Saturday
Night Live'' skit: It's a floor wax and a dessert topping. Only in
this case it's a telephone and a Web browser all rolled up in the
same neat package.
</P>
<P>
   If you've got a wireless Web cellular phone, you can order a
book, check sports scores or get the latest news from CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and if you want to make a phone call, you can do that, too.
</P>
<P>
   The newest generation of cellular phones has matchbook-sized
screens and built-in Internet browsers that let users access
everything from CNN to Yahoo to Amazon.com. Industry analysts
expect that most cellular phones will be Web-ready by the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   Users of wireless Web cell phone service can check e-mail, make
travel arrangements, get the latest stock quotes and even make a
phone call. Unlike personal digital assistants, interactive pagers
or other wireless devices, the wireless Web phone lets you do all
that without having a plethora of interactive devices strapped to
your belt or tucked into your purse.
</P>
<P>
   A Web phone is a handy thing to have. While sitting at an
airport, for example, you can log on to the Delta Air Lines Web
site, enter your flight number, discover that your plane has been
delayed by 45 minutes and either book another flight or just sit
back and have another cup of coffee in the lounge. While you're at
it, you can call your family and friends and tell them not to rush
to the airport to pick you up.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as you wait patiently for your plane, you can do
everything from buy books at Amazon.com to check your e-mail.
Americans are now finding out what the folks in Scandinavia have
known for quite some time. Being able to go online from your phone,
your pager or any other hand-held device is pretty cool.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can use your Web phone to go shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's Deanna Sanford said one of her colleagues went
shopping with a list his wife e-mailed to his Hotmail account. He
was able to wander the supermarket aisles while consulting the
e-mail message he retrieved on his cell phone to tell him which
groceries to buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wireless technologies are the next Internet,'' said Debora
Wilson, president and chief executive of Weather.com, the online
offering by the Weather Channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get the same feeling about wireless that I had five years
ago about the Internet. The ability to receive information on
devices you carry around with you all day is the next wave of
things. It's like history repeating itself,'' she said. ``A year
ago, everyone wondered what would happen with wireless. It's been
so slow, because the Internet is such a force, but it's the next
wave.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much potential (with wireless Web phones), but most
customers really haven't gotten into using their phones for data
yet,'' said EarthLink's vice president of product management, Tom
Andrus. He said educating consumers is the next step in the
development of the wireless Web phones and other wireless products.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to education, there are other problems with this
early generation of Web phones. Even though there are people
happily devoted to Web phones, there are others who gripe that the
two- to five-line text-only messages most Web phones can handle are
hard to read and often useless.
</P>
<P>
   To compound the problem, many popular Web sites are not yet
optimized for Web phone users. For example, if you type in the Web
address for Salon using a Web phone, you will receive an error
message telling you the site isn't yet phone-ready. Similarly, if
you want to send e-mail, you'll have to do it over the Web-based
application that comes with your phone, typically Yahoo Mail or
Microsoft's Hotmail.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the problem are the extra buttons, toggle switches
and other gizmos added to cellular phones to give them Web
capability. The wireless Web is a handy add-on to a cellular phone,
but already there are plenty of users who can't figure out how to
make a local phone call, never mind surf the Web with their phones.
</P>
<P>
   Xcelerate, a Fort Lauderdale, Fla.-based company, operates a
``usability center'' in Atlanta where groups of experienced and
novice users are brought in to test the newest cellular
innovations.
</P>
<P>
   Fawad Ahmad, managing director for wireless services at the
center, said the usability lab tries to find out how easy or
complicated it is for users to actually use the Web via the cell
phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically, we ask them to perform eight to 15 different
tests,'' he said. ``Let's say we are doing a test for Amazon.com.
We'll ask users to buy a book, and we'll tell them the title of the
book they're going to buy,'' he said. ``Then we see which phone
it's easiest to do it on.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahmad said Xcelerate watches every move the testers make and
examines virtually every button on every phone. ``We observe their
body language, and we look at the screens on the phones and how
friendly they are to a Web-based application. It's pretty extensive
testing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahmad said Web phone users must be comfortable using the Web via
a wireless device, and that it can take some time. He recommends
newer phones, which have larger screens than some of the earliest
models.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some newer phones have a separate keypad or three to four
buttons to use (to access the Web) and are much more
user-friendly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmad believes the biggest problem now is that the tiny
telephone screen isn't big enough for most people who are used to a
17-inch color monitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key assumption,'' Ahmad said, ``is that screen is not wide
enough or not long enough and you can't do Web browsing on a
two-line display. That drives people crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   While new cell phone technology is making it easier for users to
navigate their way around the Web, Internet companies developing
services for the wireless Web should keep several things in mind,
according to Ahmad.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are going to be a leader in the wireless space, you
have to be innovative,'' he said. ``Your top three lines are your
best real estate. Put the stuff you know users want at the top so
people can read it without scrolling. You won't have as much
information as you have on the Web site, but people just want to
get to your site to use it. Don't give them ads, because then they
won't be able to do the actual task. ``
</P>
<P>
   One of the most active companies in the wireless area today is
Microsoft. It rolled out MSN Mobile 2.0 service in March as part of
its ``Everyday Web'' strategy. The thinking is that users of the
Microsoft Network and its family of Web sites aren't chained to
their PCs all day and will look to other devices for Internet
access.
</P>
<P>
   The MSN Mobile service allows users to access most of the MSN
Web sites including Hotmail, MoneyCentral, Expedia travel
information and even horoscopes.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's Sanford said MSN's mobile initiatives, including the
MSN Mobile 2.0 cell phone product, are part of the company's
Internet strategy to provide users a satisfying MSN experience on a
variety of devices. She said it's a strategy that's been in the
works for a long time. ``This isn't something you can do
overnight,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's investment with wireless phone provider Nextel in
February 1999 got the MSN team thinking about the best way to
deliver MSN content to cellular phones.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a real challenge,'' Sanford said. ``There is limited
screen space, and people use their phones differently from how they
use the PC-based Web. People don't want to just surf. They want a
more focused experience. We approach it from making things really
timely and really relevant to make things right for the right
devices.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the first things MSN did when developing products for
wireless devices was to make sure users could keep the passwords
they already use on the Web. Sanford said the key to a positive
wireless Web phone experience is to develop products that are
relevant for the phone, such as travel, maps and e-mail, some of
the most popular wireless Web services.
</P>
<P>
   Sanford said getting Web-based information to customers quickly
is one of the biggest challenges so far. She said Microsoft uses
XML technology to strip the data from the Web pages and put it into
a format that mobile phone users can access quickly and easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people think the data network on the phone is slow,''
she said. ``But a lot of the lag time depends on how fast the site
can deliver information across the wireless network. You have to
employ the same kind of technology that Web sites already use to
optimize their pages so they'll load faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the rest of the Internet companies, Microsoft is trying to
develop applications for the Web phones that make sense for users.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're thinking about a lot of things when we think about the
future of MSN Mobile,'' Sanford said. And she echoes the rest of
the industry that's still trying to tame a new technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all so new,'' she said. ``We're all trying to figure out
what people want when they choose to stay connected with these
devices. We still don't know what people really want because the
phones are just coming out. We are trying to get at what people
would want to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been around for a year, so we have a slight advantage.
We know the Web phone should be able to give people things they can
use when they are out and about. We want to give them the ability
to get things done on the run.''
</P>
<P>
   EarthLink Vice President Erika Jolly, who heads up EarthLink's
wireless Web phone efforts, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have to think differently, because it's a totally
different environment. People are used to pictures and colors, so
we have to work to develop something that's still visually
appealing to the customer,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may not want a stock chart, but you may want to see the
stock price for that day. You may not want to see all your e-mail,
but maybe you'll want to flag e-mail from your boss or some of your
friends,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jolly said wireless Web users want information that's useful and
accessible, but that there's still a long way to go in terms of
development and ease of use. ``It's like the 9,600-baud modems when
they first came out,'' she said. ``Everyone thought they were lame.
There are some limitations on the phones right now, but we have to
be patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
