<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEOGAME0523-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta to get preview of PlayStation 2
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Millions of video game gearheads are twiddling
their thumbs until October waiting for Sony's PlayStation 2. But
Atlanta gamers will get a hands-on test drive by early summer.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a $10 million promotional blitz for the sleek device
_ which has an upgraded video processor, DVD drive and expansion
slots for a broadband modem and hard drive _ Sony will bring the
game to Atlanta for Major League Baseball's Fan Fest 2000, July
7-11.
</P>
<P>
   Those who get a sneak peek of PS2 may be disappointed at first.
It's not much to look at. With a minimalist vertical design, it
looks like a nondescript black book sitting upright on a shelf.
</P>
<P>
   But the new game platform has already become a media darling and
emerged as the Holy Grail for consumer electronic enthusiasts known
as ``early adopters'' who are already lining up to buy it. PS2 will
retail for about $300.
</P>
<P>
   The console has already been released in Japan, where it sold a
million units in the first week. It was also among the hottest new
products unveiled at the Electronic Entertainment Expo held here
recently.
</P>
<P>
   PS2 promises to merge the features of a game console, a DVD
player and a desktop computer. But the computer features _ an
optional add-on broadband modem and hard drive _ won't be available
in October. Sony says peripherals will be available by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The hard drive will allow gamers to more easily play software
that requires more than one disc. The modem will permit players to
compete over the Net _ and maybe more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't outlined all the uses yet,'' said Ryan Bowling, a
spokesman for Sony. ``A lot of what we're going to do is still in
the works.''
</P>
<P>
   There are doubts the PS2 can live up to pre-release hype. Rick
Mears, an editor for a magazine called Gamefan, said he was
disappointed after paying $700 _ his own funds, not the magazine's
_ to get an early Japanese version.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're telling everybody it's this super gaming platform, but
it's not,'' Mears said. ``They'll probably sell a million of them,
but I already sold mine to someone else. It's not even better than
Sega Dreamcast, and that's been out for a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Mears added that while Sony is using PS2's expandability as a
major selling point, consumers may not be willing to wait or pay
extra money to use the additional features.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to understand that Sony releases the (crummy) stuff
in Japan, but by the time it gets to America they will have fixed
all the bugs and flaws,'' Burney said. ``In the next year, it will
blow all the other game platforms away.''
</P>
<P>
   The original Sony PlayStation, which only played video games,
ranks as one of the biggest success stories in the $6.1 billion
video game industry. Since it was introduced in 1994, more than 26
million PlayStation units have been sold in North America. The new
unit will be able to play games designed for the older console.
</P>
<P>
   In a breathless, two-hour news conference in Los Angeles,
executives from Sony Computer Entertainment America announced their
plans for launching PS2 in North America in late October.
</P>
<P>
   ``PlayStation 2 is not the future of video game entertainment,''
said Kazuo Hirai, president and chief operating officer of the
company. ``It's the future of entertainment. Period.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hirai may not have the last word. Industry rival Nintendo is
also developing a new entertainment console called Dolphin. And by
next year Microsoft is expected to release its X-box, yet another
high-powered gaming device with Internet capability.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
