r l BC-NETKIDS0523-COX     05-22 1958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETKIDS0523-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What is technology doing to kids' minds? It's creating a new way
of thinking
 &HT;    By Omar L. Gallaga
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ These children, they used to call them nerds.
</P>
<P>
   As they tap-tap-tapped on midget keyboards, eyesight weakened
from pre-EPA-approved, radiation-spewing monitors, the kids spoke
of their love of computers in secret. They joined computer clubs
that met after class, a refuge from the after-school-bell bullies _
because what they were doing didn't remotely approach a state of
acceptable coolness.
</P>
<P>
   They wore corduroy. They might have liked it.
</P>
<P>
   And then the revolution came, quietly in the '80s, then loudly
through the '90s, making a lot of people rich, and putting the
hobby tools of their youth into every home, every low-rent hotel,
on the counters of gas stations, until the computers were
everywhere. Until it was OK.
</P>
<P>
   Computers and modems and the mighty Web are as ubiquitous in a
child's vocabulary as the multiplication table. The geeks did
inherit the Earth. The archaic DOS became the unstable Windows, and
every barely computer-literate person who wasn't a gifted and
talented child could shove a mouse around and feel wired. Now
parents fret about digital divides and computers in the classroom.
Are they learning online? Will they know enough?
</P>
<P>
   Experts say that computers, and more importantly, the Internet,
are changing the way children learn, develop and think. Today's
technotykes will be tomorrow's information wranglers. They'll work
in real-time, though hopefully not by speaking in useless info-age
buzzwords. They will think in multidimensions, incorporating
hyperlinks, sound and video into their everyday communication. The
adults of tomorrow will learn to work as teams, pushing gigabytes
of information around like scraps of Post-It notes. No, forget
tomorrow. They're doing it now.
</P>
<P>
   GALS AND THEIR WEB SITES
</P>
<P>
   Amanda Stanley had a computer in her home even when her family
chose not to keep a TV or radio in the house. ``I've been around
computers all my life,'' she said. The 13-year-old, who comes from
a family of computer enthusiasts, learned how to paint jeans at a
camp last summer. Now she wants to sell her wearable art online.
</P>
<P>
   Amanda's curious eyes and chatty conversation belie a mind built
for multitasking. She is enrolled in Giga Gals, a program that
started at the Austin Children's Museum in February. Web designers
help 9- to 18-year-olds get online and start their own sites, from
Web diaries to e-commerce ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Evans, co-owner of Austin's Digital Voodoo, a Web
design firm, has been helping Amanda get her site up and running.
And, it turns out, they were perfectly matched. ``I used to paint
jeans in college,'' Evans said. ``It's a total coincidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans said she's been surprised by the pace of Amanda's work.
While Evans gets a crash course in pop culture from the teenager,
her student is picking up Web skills at a rate much faster than
most adults could, Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has no fear,'' Evans said. ``Kids are faster at absorbing
the technology. The interest level is higher and they're closer to
the technology. Some adults don't want to be a part of the
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Kids and young adults coming of age just as Internet access has
become cheap and commonly available may have an advantage in the
information age over adults who approach new technologies as if
they're learning a new language.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Sams, who coordinates Giga Gals, said that's because kids
have become accustomed to a time when information is available at
their fingertips. Instead of cracking dusty encyclopedias, they
consult CD-ROMs and search engines. ``I'm always shocked,'' Sams
said. ``They have a whole world of information and it's made their
world a lot smaller than ours. I think it's really changing them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sams, who with her nose ring and bright flower-shaped hair clips
looks like an enthusiastic teenager herself, says she doesn't think
today's kids are any smarter. ``They're still beating the hell out
of each other and running wild,'' she said. But they are savvier.
``There's the opportunity for them to be more creative as
technology becomes more affordable. There are just more things to
stimulate how smart they are.''
</P>
<P>
   And what about the digital divide that sociologists fear will
keep that technology away from kids who need it most?
</P>
<P>
   Sams once taught a class of Spanish-speaking students who had
had little or no contact with the Net. Given the opportunity, they
quickly caught up, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids could hardly speak English,'' she said, ``but they
knew how to get around the Internet. We communicated that way.''
</P>
<P>
   THE WEB _ 'IT JUST IS'
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Human Code, an Austin multimedia company, hosted a
forum on the future of education that aired locally on KLRU. Titled
``Class of 2012,'' the show brought together four experts,
including Brenda Laurel, co-founder of Purple Moon, a now-defunct
kids' software developer, and Elliot Soloway of the University of
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Discussing the role of teachers, computers and privatization for
the future of education, the talk came back again and again to the
subject of kids and technology. Will computers and the Web act as
substitutes for teachers, or will they aid students in learning
necessary skills for a quickly changing world?
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, one panelist concluded, ``It's not a question of (if
technology is) good or bad,'' said Milton Glick, a provost at
Arizona State University. ``It just is.''
</P>
<P>
   Children, the panelists said, are becoming gatherers of
information, sometimes beating teachers to the punch and bringing
their own research and data to the classroom. And while the
Internet may not give them the humanistic skills they need _
communication with others and work ethics, for instance _
technology may help amplify the skills they will need for the jobs
they take on, many of which haven't been invented yet. In a world
where even the most trivial bit of data is available with a mouse
click, will kids need memorization skills?
</P>
<P>
   A surprising side-effect of the Internet's growth may be on
basic learning. Sue Cole, a computer class teacher at Mendez Middle
School and instructor at River City Youth Foundation's after-school
computer lab, said kids are suddenly becoming interested in good
spelling. ``One of the first things I saw was that the Internet
requires students to focus on their spelling. If you don't spell it
right, you don't get there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Cole has watched her students embrace the Net, and that has
changed their relationships with friends, parents and relatives.
``They're finding new ways to communicate with each other using the
written expression,'' she said. ``They're searching the Net and
looking for lost relatives and the origins of their names.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest problems, she finds, is the one that's been
around since the Web took off _ shielding kids from pornography and
hate sites. But almost as bad, she said, is that kids have to be
weaned from quick-developing addictions to the Internet. ``Once
they find out how exciting it is, that's all they want to do. We
have to remind students that they have a life outside the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the increasing presence of computers and the Internet at
schools, traditional teaching may not harness the power of the new
technology, some say. Arthur VanderVeen, chief executive of
Austin-based ActiveInk Corp., believes children can learn best by
solving real-world problems and becoming active participants in
what they study.
</P>
<P>
   His company produces Internet educational software for
kindergarten through 12th grades. While the firm doesn't yet sell
its services to the Austin Independent School District, VanderVeer
said ActiveInk is working with 22 other school districts in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Using ActiveInk, students take on projects, working in teams and
using spreadsheets, databases and computer simulations to create
plans of action. If it sounds like the inner workings of a
high-tech firm, that's intentional.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to create an environment, replicating the
processes that come up in work environments,'' he said. ``We've
gone to the corporate environment to find out 'what are the skills
students need to succeed in the new economy?' Traditional education
is not preparing students for those skills.''
</P>
<P>
   John Wright, who with his wife, Aletha Houston, runs the
University of Texas Center for Research for the Influences of
Television on Children, has been turning his attention to
interactive entertainment. Teaching kids using models of real-world
events can help them engage in non-linear thinking, he said. And
computers are helping.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be a wonderful educational thing,'' Wright said.
``It facilitates thinking in larger concepts and bigger language.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wright is not so optimistic for kids who don't have
computers or Internet access. ``Can you take kids from an
environment where the parents didn't have any interactive
electronic experience and have them, in a single generation, join
the digital world? For children of color, the lag is getting worse,
but only because others are advancing.''
</P>
<P>
   BRIDGING THE MATH GAP
</P>
<P>
   On a Saturday morning, in a cheery house near the University of
Texas, a group of mothers and their daughters are looking at a
dismantled computer, learning the difference between RAM and a hard
drive after a snack of powdered donuts and orange juice.
</P>
<P>
   An hour later, they're putting together their own Web pages,
coding background colors and choosing clip art. It's part of a
program begun by Girlstart, a local non-profit group aimed at
helping another kind of digital divide _ the one that founder
Rachel Muir says is widening between girls and boys.
</P>
<P>
   Muir, a 26-year-old who began Girlstart as Smartgirls two years
ago, said research suggests girls often lose interest in technology
during middle school, veering off from possible careers in math and
computer sciences. That's why, she said, a major gender gap exists
in the mostly male high-tech industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Girls start off with a strong sense of entitlement, but we see
that diminish substantially between sixth and seventh grade,'' Muir
said. ``If a girl doesn't select a path in math or science in
middle school, she won't have the building blocks to pursue it in
college.''
</P>
<P>
   So, using weekend courses and summer camps, Girlstart has tried
to bridge that gap, a few students at a time. Kids by nature are
curious and want to take apart technology and learn how it works,
Muir said. ``We teach girls not to be afraid to take things apart
and break stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Like another Austin stalwart, software company Girl Games, Inc.,
the group is trying to educate girls and make technology more
accessible to them.
</P>
<P>
   The real-world implications are quickly apparent. The girls
learn desktop publishing and immediately see the results of their
work when their Web pages go live on the Internet or when they can
see a piece of video they've digitally edited.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're teaching them to master their physical world,'' Muir
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Overton, a 9-year-old at the Saturday class, wanted to
publish a Web page after months of using the Web on her Dell home
computer and listening to Internet radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, Shirley Overton, said she is constantly surprised by
the information absorbed by her daughters, including Sarah's older
sister, a Web designer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime she needs to know anything, if I don't have an answer,
she goes to the Internet,'' Overton said. ``It's opened up the
whole world.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
