<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSCENE0523-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plenty of sites profess to track your lucky stars
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Most of you almost certainly use the Web for scholarly
pursuits _ happily researching the gross national product for
Brazil, or finding a great vendor for epoxy cement, or perhaps
gauging the influence of epic poems on modern literature.
</P>
<P>
   But some people use the Web to check their horoscopes. If you
think that's in the stars for you, then today you'll find enough
sites to preserve your peace of mind. The notion is this: If you
don't like the horoscope you find on one site, simply continue down
the list until you find a prediction that suits you.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best horoscope sites on the Web _ there seems little
argument to the contrary _ is the product of an astrologer called
Jonathan Cainer who writes for a London newspaper. His Web site at
www.bubble.com/webstars/ is often a bit slow because of that
popularity. That's why you might want to note a ``mirror site''
that offers the same Web pages at www.cainer.com/.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find the expected daily and weekly horoscopes here, as
well as predictions for the year; general information about each
astrological sign; a way to check for astrological compatibility
with other signs; and RealAudio files that deliver a longer audio
version of your horoscope.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the content on this page _ including everything listed
above _ is free, but Cainer does sell some astrological reports.
The commercial content here isn't blatant and, if you just come to
check your horoscope, you'll never notice it (which probably would
dismay Cainer).
</P>
<P>
   AstroNet, at www.astronet.com/, is one of the slickest horoscope
sites on the Web. Again, you'll find free daily and weekly
horoscopes and other standard features. And that's probably what
most people are looking for.
</P>
<P>
   But for those who are truly interested in astrology, this site
has articles that discuss various trends in depth. You'll find
links to these articles on the opening page.
</P>
<P>
   There's a good Australian site for astrology called Blackstump
Horoscope Leader at www.blackstump.com.au/horo.htm. It's a fun stop
since, once you've checked out your stars, you can also find the
latest scores for Australian Rules Football or just browse the
headlines from Australia.
</P>
<P>
   The actual horoscope information is a collection of links to
other sites, including Cainer's. But there are some unusual links
here, including one to a Chinese astrology site.
</P>
<P>
   Many people, of course, follow their horoscopes using the daily
newspaper. And Sydney Omarr is a popular columnist in many papers.
If you're away from the newspaper but still want to see that
horoscope, you can find Omarr's predictions at
washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/ style/columns/horoscope.htm.
</P>
<P>
   As at many of the sites, you'll also be able to check out your
compatibility _ at least where astrology is concerned _ with a
potential mate. And you'll get advice on choosing a real-world
astrologer as well as health tips based on your sign.
</P>
<P>
   Kelli Fox, another well-known astrologer, runs a site called
Astrology.com, which is located, logically enough, at
www.astrology.com. You'll find fairly detailed astrological
forecasts here and _ just as is true with Cainer's site _ also find
a commercial section where you can buy full-blown charts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
