<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2339 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-TECH-GAMER0523-COX     05-22 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-GAMER0523-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flash back to the '60s with Beetle Buggin
 &HT;    By Omar L. Gallaga
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE DESKTOP
</P>
<P>
   Offering instant gratification appeal with its ease of play,
decent price point and rock solid arcade racing action, Beetle
Buggin ($20; www.infogrames. com; for the PC) is a hit. Add to that
a variety of fantastically fun play modes and the fact that you
really can't go wrong with those cuddly/funky cool Volkswagen
go-buggies, and you've got a must-have title. Targeted at the
``casual gamer,'' Beetle Buggin is all about fun in a '60s laden,
dope-smokin', love child world and less about complicated submenus,
upgrades and reward systems of driving ``simulations.'' Just hip,
groovy, romping and racing, baby. Lots of it. Go nuts.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE CONSOLE
</P>
<P>
   Extending an elemental law of physics to include ``what goes up
must pull off a Varial before it comes down,'' Tony Hawk's Pro
Skater ($50; www.activision.com; for the Nintendo 64) brings all
the superlative joyousness from the outstanding Playstation game to
the N64. Essentially a direct port, world skate champ Tony Hawk and
nine of his cronies do the virtual vert and street skate thing with
unsurpassed fluidity and style. Faithful to its Playstation
counterpart, Tony 64 includes the same nine fully interactive
sprawling 3-D levels and a challenging reward system promising
long-term gameplay, especially in Career Mode. Control
configuration is deceptively sparse with an exponentially varied
number of moves and combos making for a long, steep learning curve.
It's novice friendly, nonetheless, as each rider comes complete
with the essential balance and trick skills of the real pros. The
gamer must learn to utilize said skills to their fullest in order
to earn points and capture pick-ups. Sadly softened, this N64
version has neither the thud-piddle-piddle skull smacks nor the
smatter of blood accompanied by a virtual crash and bail _and the
soundtrack is incomplete, stymied by the cartridge's limitation to
looped musical samples. But if you're really into excellent extreme
sports games such as this, you probably own a Playstation anywy.
</P>
<P>
   For all of its hardware power, one of the best games currently
available for the Sega Dreamcast is a simple 2-D game that is as
addictive as ``Tetris.'' Chu Chu Rocket ($30, www.sega.com) is a
fast and frenetic party game in which you try to corral many
wandering mice into your home base rocket by placing arrows on a
simple grid while marauding cats try to attack . It sounds simple,
but in multi-player mode, you're fighting for real estate and mice
against up to three other players. When the game is in full swing,
you'll be cursing those orange cats and your devious fellow
players. Chu Chu is also the first game you can play over Sega's
network. Simple and fun, it's the year's best console party game.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
