</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-SAVVY0523-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Quick View offers virus protection
 &HT;    By Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sue and Jacki:
</P>
<P>
   When the Love Bug dominated the news, there was an article in
the paper suggesting protections. Something called Quick View was
mentioned, which allows you to view e-mail without launching a worm
or virus. What is Quickview?
</P>
<P>
   _ Stephen Wiesner, Parma, Ohio
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Quick View Plus is a robust file-viewing utility for the
PC, with a neat little twist. It gained popularity as a shield
against viruses during the outbreak of Melissa in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Besides saving the frustration and time spent converting
files or fretting over files you can't open at all, Quick View Plus
is a great safety net against those nasty little intruders. By
using the utility to view file attachments, you can access contents
of a file without triggering a virus that might be lurking.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: It packs a lot of muscle for $59, considering you can view
files downloaded from the Web and e-mail attachments, including
photos and graphics, in a heartbeat. Text, spreadsheets, database
files, presentations, compressed files, HTML. You name it. The
utility supports more than 200 file formats.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Mac and PC file-type incompatibilities don't get in its
way either. Plus, you don't spend big bucks on multiple software
packages. Surf to jasc.com and click the Products link.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sue and Jacki:
</P>
<P>
   I'm looking for a Web site that gives the names and addresses of
people living on the same street. I know the site exists because
I've been there before, but I don't remember how I got there. Can
you help?
</P>
<P>
   _ John Koval, Lorain, Ohio
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Try out AT&AMP;T AnyWho Info at anywho.com or InfoSpace at
infospace.com.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: What a great way to get to know your neighbors and
organize a block party. Both sites were easy to use, but navigation
came easier with AnyWho. You can type the info on the first page
and get a pretty good listing. According to Alice, none of these
sites has comprehensive lists. Getting accurate lists depends on
where the site is getting its info and how often it's updated.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: InfoSpace requires a couple of extra clicks. Once you
navigate to InfoSpace, click on the White Pages link. At the bottom
of the page, click on Reverse Lookup for Address. Type in the
street name, city and state and get a listing.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Of course, if someone's personal information is unlisted,
you won't find them anywhere. Also, if you are attempting an e-mail
search for someone who is using AOL, they will not be listed
either.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd write for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. E-mail questions to techsavvy(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
