r e BC-HOLLOWAY-TV-COLUMN052     05-22 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLOWAY-TV-COLUMN0523 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This week, TV says goodbye to a towering talent
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ We shouldn't get all misty and maudlin. He is,
after all, just a funny guy on a medium-rated TV show. And he's
stepping down, not crawling off to die.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, I'm compelled to pause and pay tribute to Michael
J. Fox, who takes his final bow on ``Spin City'' this week. As the
world surely knows by now, Fox is battling Parkinson's disease and
has decided the weekly grind of a TV series is not the best use of
his depleted energy. He wants to spend more time with his family
and speak out about his disease. He may also do some acting or
directing from time to time, but that's uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   The hourlong ``Spin City'' finale Wednesday is not Fox's best
work. The episode moves too slowly and lingers too long with too
many goodbyes and not enough of the guffaw-producing scenes that
have been this gifted funnyman's trademark. It was a nice touch
having Michael Gross, who played Fox's father on ``Family Ties,''
pop in as the deputy mayor's shrink. But the story line that has
Mike resigning after taking the fall for a mob scandal involving
the mayor is lame.
</P>
<P>
   But so what? Not even a lackluster farewell can tarnish Fox's
distinguished comedic career. He's proof-positive that Randy
Newman's claim that ``short people got no reason to live'' is
stupid. It's a testimony to the gigantic appeal of tiny Fox (5 feet
4 inches officially, but that may be stretching it) that movies
like ``Doc Hollywood'' and ``Life with Mikey'' didn't blot out the
good films like ``Back to the Future'' and ``Teen Wolf.''
</P>
<P>
   He made only two TV series _ ``Family Ties'' and ``Spin City'' _
but Fox left his mark on both as a quick wit and fearless
pratfaller. He couId romp through complicated dialogue at a
breakneck pace, whether espousing Reaganomics as the button-down
Alex P. Keaton or spewing liberal New York politics as spinmeister
Michael Flaherty. In the grown-up role of Flaherty, Fox relished
zinging sexual banter and double entendres. That innocent face made
them seem even funnier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the aforementioned constituent could be polled over
lunch,'' said Nikki, Mike's love interest last season, in a scene
that fairly dripped with lust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sounds great,'' Mike replied, licking his lips. ``I'm gonna
get on the horn and make the arrangements. You prepare the, uh,
spreadsheets.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyishly handsome at 38, Fox has always used his looks and
diminutive size to his advantage. He was happy to let Tracy Pollan
(now his wife) tower over him when she played his girlfriend on
``Family Ties'' and has been known to jump into the arms of the
mayor, played by 6-feet, 6-inch tall Barry Bostwick, on ``Spin
City.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox's fearless instinct for slapstick is legendary. Long after
he was diagnosed with Parkinson's, he joyfully jumped into the
Hudson River for a scene with Bostwick, and zoomed around the
office on in-line skates. Even in this week's swan song, he bounds
around in boxer shorts, panting after Heather Locklear like a rabid
puppy.
</P>
<P>
   A Canadian-born hockey fanatic, Fox came to Hollywood at 18 and
landed ``Family Ties'' (1982-89) at 20. The sitcom was conceived by
Gary David Goldberg as a generational clash between hippie parents,
played by Meredith Baxter and Gross, and their Reaganite son Alex,
who had a poster of William F. Buckley over his bed.
</P>
<P>
   Fox was such a hit in the role that the focus shifted to him by
the end of the first season. He became a brand-new golden boy,
respected in Hollywood and beloved everywhere else. When movie
offers started pouring in, Fox could have weaseled out of his
seven-year contract, but he told Goldberg and the cast he had no
intention of leaving. He stayed on and made a graceful exit with
his colleagues at the show's end.
</P>
<P>
   My guess is Fox is loved as much for his core values as for his
talent. He is a devoted husband and father who has faced illness
with courage, humor and determination. OK, he's not perfect. He
still smokes like a chimney, but that's about the only dirt anyone
can dig up on him. To avoid years of pity, he chose not to reveal
his illness until last year, although he was diagnosed more than
six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   After going public, Fox testified before Congress on the need
for increased funding for Parkinson's research, and he intends to
become an activist after his TV retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do firmly believe that there will be a cure by the time I am
50,'' he told Diane Sawyers in an interview last week on ``20/20.''
``If I'm not cured, it's a personal disappointment, but you really
get past the personal agenda when you make this step (becoming a
spokesman).''
</P>
<P>
   Although he may no longer be at the top of his acting game, he's
still got game, as viewers know from this season's fast-paced
episodes. It came as a surprise when he told the cast, crew and ABC
that this would be his last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't so much what I couldn't do on the show,'' Fox told
Sawyer. ``It's what I couldn't do outside of it, because I was
tired. I loved it very much, but it was just too much energy to
spend in one place.''
</P>
<P>
   In a stunningly bad move, ABC has decided to continue ``Spin
City'' next year with Charlie Sheen as the new deputy mayor. Sheen
is clean and sober these days but doesn't have a track record in
smart comedy. (``Hot Shots'' and ``Major League'' don't count.)
Besides, he's got enormous (about a size 7, actually) shoes to
fill. Since Fox is probably irreplaceable, ABC should let the show
bow out along with its star.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
