<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN0523-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trendies ruin Hawaiian-shirt mystique
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ I am no slave to fashion. I am not even
its lawn-guy. Yet every spring, clothing catalogs sprout in my
mailbox. They are sent to me by sophisticated retailers.
Sophisticated retailers who have used sophisticated marketing
techniques and sophisticated database creation to determine that I
am the sort of person who is now fretting over his summer wardrobe.
It cracks me up every time. Lately, though, some of the catalogue
photos have alarmed me.
</P>
<P>
   For eons, my off-duty summer wardrobe has consisted largely of
clunky sandals of the kind that scuff the floors in health-food
stores, jeans that still have another year in them if I watch the
beer, and ugly Hawaiian shirts. A timeless leisurewear ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   This is a tourist-town look exempt from the vagaries and
stresses of fashion.
</P>
<P>
   But now I open these catalogues, and what do I see? Broad-
shouldered men with jaws like Dick Tracy wearing _ it pains me to
say this _ ugly Hawaiian shirts.
</P>
<P>
   These are tasteful catalogues geared to people who have real
jobs. They show men with their willowy cotton-clad, blunt-cut
blonde counterparts on rocky New England shorelines and in the
shade of graceful summer home verandahs. These are not the people
for whom ugly Hawaiian shirts were intended.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, fashion has a nasty way of overtaking the
fashion-resistant. These catalogue people are trying to pretend
they are one of us. And I don't like it one little bit.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few guidelines for separating the faux
Hawaiian-shirt wearer from people who live the way people in ugly
Hawaiian shirts are supposed to:
</P>
<P>
   _ An ugly Hawaiian shirt should not cost more than $20. A $50
shirt is, by definition, formal wear. You wouldn't use the
shirttail of a $50 shirt to wipe melted ice cream off a car seat,
so why wear it on a Saturday?
</P>
<P>
   _ An ugly Hawaiian shirt is not forever. It is rayon or thin
cotton. An object that lasts no longer than a summer romance.
That's part of its mystique. (And a reason for the $20 rule.)
</P>
<P>
   _ An ugly Hawaiian shirt cannot be ironed except when worn as
evening wear.
</P>
<P>
   _ An ugly Hawaiian shirt must be busy enough that the casual
observer would assume any stain to be part of the shirt's design.
</P>
<P>
   _ An ugly Hawaiian shirt should be in a pattern you cannot
imagine on any other manner of textile or life-form.
</P>
<P>
   _ But an ugly Hawaiian shirt does not cross the line into self-
parody. A shirt that mocks the venerable conventions of Hawaiian
shirt design marks the wearer as a poser, a tourist, a mere
wannabe. Someone trying to look retro-cool.
</P>
<P>
   To combat the creeping trendiness of ugly Hawaiian shirts, I've
tried buying progressively cheaper and uglier Hawaiian shirts. I
thought I could combat this fashion shift by example. No luck. It's
a losing battle.
</P>
<P>
   More's the pity.
</P>
<P>
   Many people who advocate buying less to live better _
``voluntary simplicity'' as the magazines call it _ seem to
describe a dreary monochrome T-shirt-and-bandanna existence. A
cheap Hawaiian shirt, however, is an attractive alternative.
Voluntary simplicity with cheap panache.
</P>
<P>
   This is not mere cheapness. It is a life-choice.
</P>
<P>
   Gertrude Stein, when showing off her impressive art collection
to a young Earnest Hemingway told him: ``You can either buy clothes
or buy pictures. It's that simple.''
</P>
<P>
   She dressed in ``strange steerage clothes'' Hemingway said, and
she owned the great names in big frames.
</P>
<P>
   From the photographs I've seen, the writer took her advice on
clothing, but didn't get around to the paintings. He collected ex-
wives, instead.
</P>
<P>
   I don't own Picassos. But I also suspect you can either buy
clothes or buy computers and books. It works the same way.
</P>
<P>
   For this reason, I like to imagine my weekend wear suggests a
wearer who possess A Rich Inner Life.
</P>
<P>
   Or it did until it started turning up in all the catalogues.
</P>
<P>
   What will Tracy-jawed models spoil next? Please not the bowling
shirts and guayaberas.
</P>
<P>
   Anything but them.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for The Daytona Beach (Fla.) News-
Journal. He may be reached at mark.lane(at)news-jrnl.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
