<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    2 charged in '63 bombing
 &HT;    By By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two former Ku Klux Klansmen were jailed last week over
the bombing of a Birmingham church 37 years ago. The dynamite blast
on Sept. 15, 1963, killed four black girls.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas E. Blanton Jr. and Bobby Frank Cherry were charged with
first-degree murder by an Alabama grand jury. Through lawyers, the
men said they are innocent.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation has been opened and closed several times since
the bombing. One suspect was convicted of murder in the 1970s, and
another suspect has died.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Langford, former FBI special agent in charge of the
Birmingham bureau, said agents were able to gather new information
on the crime recently. ``There were witnesses who would talk now
who wouldn't talk back then,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Blanton and Cherry, who are in their 60s, could
face life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   TEACHERS TO RATE PARENTS
</P>
<P>
   Are your parents helping you become a good student?
</P>
<P>
   Parents in Chicago will be graded next year on whether they're
assisting their kids enough with homework, getting them to school
on time and making sure they are rested for the day ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The parents won't receive a letter grade from teachers. Instead,
every five weeks they'll receive a checklist. Parents with low
marks could be referred to a parent training academy.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say schools should be focusing on the performance of
teachers _ not parents. Requests for information such as a child's
bedtime are seen as an invasion of privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ANIMALS' HOMES EXPAND
</P>
<P>
   Three African governments plan to team up to create the largest
wildlife park in the world. South Africa, Mozambique and Zimbabwe
are to sign a formal agreement next month.
</P>
<P>
   The park will link South Africa's Kruger National Park with the
Gaza province in Mozambique and Gonarezhou National Park in
Zimbabwe. Animals and visitors will be allowed to roam free in the
7.5 million-acre area.
</P>
<P>
   A smaller African park opened last week in South Africa and
Botswana.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
