<HEADER>
A2350 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0523-CO     05-22 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0523-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What people do all day
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ It's sunny and 60-degrees outside. Not a
cloud in sight. Trees and grass are storybook green from all the
rain we've had this week. There's still a puddle beside the curb
across the street, and no matter how many times Kevin and his
village helpers clean it out, it grows to small-lake proportion
after a rain, tempting youngsters and, on occasion a grownup or
two, in for a wade.
</P>
<P>
   Birds are swinging on feeders in the side yard while three
squirrels compete for sole rights to the two terra cotta saucers
filled with sunflower seeds. A fourth is trying to bring down a
suet cage. The shiny green birdbath I lugged home from the nursery
glistens in a newly-planted flower bed.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like perfection, doesn't it? A real Shangri-La.
</P>
<P>
   Not quite.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, the rest of my yard looks a whole lot like an
illustration from the Richard Scarry book I used to read to my son,
Kristofor _ ``What Do People Do All Day?'' They're all out there _
just like the folks in the book. And I'm sure Lowly Worm is mucking
about in the mulch as well.
</P>
<P>
   For readers who were at a different time in their lives and not
reading Scarry to their kids, Lowly Worm appeared, although rather
obscurely, on every page in the book and before I could read the
text to him, Kristofor had to find the worm. His rule. Our delight.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, that's how my yard looks today. BUSY.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Druckenmiller is out front with a shrieking drill that's
chewing its way into the ancient mortar, or what's left of it, that
holds up the bricks in the pillar at the sidewalk edge of the long,
low wall that surrounds my yard. It didn't make it through last
winter's freezes and thaws.
</P>
<P>
   Little kids have been walking that wall since 1916, and it's my
solemn responsibility to maintain the tradition. Besides, I've
walked it a few times myself just so I wouldn't forget how much fun
they're having. Lucky for all of us wall-walkers Mr. D. is around
to save the day _ and the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Tom Younker is out back _ I can hear his extension
ladder bumping against the upstairs back porch roof where he's busy
mending a downspout that was shoved away from its gutter by winter
ice. When he's finished, he'll move on around the house, and
eventually out to the garage, scraping, patching, and painting.
</P>
<P>
   The gutters and downspouts are original to the house _ 84 years
old. The alternative to the annual spring restoration would be new
ones, but they wouldn't match the graceful, half-barrel shapes of
the old ones, so we've nixed that idea.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Bryan Reynolds is churning up an old flower
bed with his roto-tiller. A friend in the country supplies us with
all the manure we need _ free for the hauling _ and when she's not
out carrying brides to the church in her horse-drawn surrey, she
even helps load.
</P>
<P>
   Around back, another friend with an old pickup truck has just
dropped one-and-a-third cubic yards of hardwood mulch onto the
driveway _ the second load in two days. And there's more to go.
Now, it's holes to dig and flowers to plant _ a regular Midwestern
spring frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   This is my storybook _ kind of a homegrown response to Mr.
Scarry's question. This is what people do all day _ if they're
lucky like me.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
