<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER'S SPELL WEARS OFF ALL TOO QUICKLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whoopee! This is the last week of school. I won't have any more
homework to do. I can spend my evenings reading a book or watching
television or just doing nothing.
</P>
<P>
   I can talk with my husband, take long baths and actually sit
long enough to enjoy my dinner. I can talk to my daughters or
stroll through the mall or both.
</P>
<P>
   I won't have to add or subtract or multiply. I won't have to
read another confusing history or science text. There will be no
more book reports or science projects, the latter of which always
gave me nightmares. Best of all, I won't have to worry that my
daughters will come home at the end of yet another long, hard day
and tell me how inept I am.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mommy, you changed it and it was wrong,'' one of them would
say with the disgust glaring from their big brown eyes. ``I thought
you were a genius.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am,'' I'd say.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you got it wrong,'' one of them would say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, let me see that,'' I'd demand. ``No, I didn't. That can't
be right. It's your teacher. She got it wrong. Is this her first
teaching job? She'll get better.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, somewhere between late August and this week, the
teacher has gained stature in my daughters' eyes and displaced me
as the know-it-all in their lives. You have to wonder if this
happened by accident or whether my daughters had a part in
dethroning me.
</P>
<P>
   I've gone from exemplary cool mom to merely an acceptable
dimwit. And in just nine months. I don't like it.
</P>
<P>
   After this week, I'll start to deprogram them, to have my little
darlings back, drinking from my head, so to speak. Yes, mark my
words. Solomon's wisdom will seem like mere horse sense compared
with my learning.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever I tell my daughters between now and the next August
will be gospel. That system of checks and balances that sometimes
seems to divide my home will have shut down. The windows and the
books will be closed. For two whole months.
</P>
<P>
   Just the thought makes me tingle all the way from the top of my
empty head to the bottom of my feet.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings me to a whole other matter. My empty bank account.
By summer's end, that little jingle in my pocket will have been
completely silenced, compliments of TXU and summer camp.
</P>
<P>
   A hundred dollars a week, they want for the pleasure of having
my girls. That's the low bid. The high looks something like $185 a
week. That alone will make you rethink your feelings about
homework, make you want to beg for it.
</P>
<P>
   So will the $300 a month TXU will demand for keeping my home
air-conditioned. Next to suffocating from the heat, helping my
daughters with their homework seems like a breath of fresh air, a
walk in the park, a piece of my cake.
</P>
<P>
   I can see myself now, longing for the end of summer and the
sight of that big yellow school bus rumbling through the
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The very things I hated, I will think of lovingly. Days like
``muffins with mom'' and ``doughnuts for dad'' will seem like sheer
pleasure. So will the school carnival and teacher-parent
conferences. I'll learn to live again with my daughters' fondness
for the teacher. And I'll tolerate the homework.
</P>
<P>
   Did I say that?  suppose I should be honest.
</P>
<P>
   On curriculum night, I'll be the parent in the back of the room
making the futile plea for a little less homework.
</P>
<P>
   I know I made the same pitiful pitch last year, but you never
know when you might get lucky.
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7400, or e-mail:
gstaples(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
