<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2360 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-BAY-TO-BREAKERS-HNS &LR;      05-22 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAY-TO-BREAKERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     KENYAN RUNNER TAKES HIS TIME WINNING BAY RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: Filed in ``l'' and ``s'' categories.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DWIGHT CHAPIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Reuben Cheruiyot messed around for a couple of
miles, at least by his lofty standards.
</P>
<P>
   He was content to poke along with the pack in the early stages
of the 89th Examiner Bay to Breakers on Sunday, in a race that
seemed to be stuck in cement.
</P>
<P>
   The pace was so slow that unseeded runners and guys jumping into
the action from off the curbs along Sixth Street actually managed
to keep up with the top-rated men for more than a moment or two.
</P>
<P>
   Then the 26-year-old Cheruiyot, another in that seemingly
endless cookie-cutter line of Kenyans, decided to get serious.
</P>
<P>
   He chose the most challenging spot on the 7.46-mile city to the
sea course _ Hayes Street hill _ to make his move.
</P>
<P>
   And what a move it was.
</P>
<P>
   Cheruiyot roared up the hill, quickly distancing himself from
everyone in the field except countryman Dominic Kirui, then, going
down the hill, he quickly dispatched Kirui, too.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the way it was Cheruiyot, running all alone into
history as he became the 10th straight Kenyan male to win the race.
</P>
<P>
   His time wasn't impressive. His clocking of 34:54, in fact, was
the slowest since Arturo Barrios' 34:57 in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   But, considering that the runners were practically walking the
first two miles (4:57 and 4:43, respectively), and that Cheruiyot's
journey was strictly a solo act after Hayes Street hill, his time
was more than commendable.
</P>
<P>
   Even if it was way off Kenyan Ismail Kirui's Breakers record of
33:42 and the world 12K best of 33:31 set by Kenyan Joseph Kimani,
and was the second-slowest Breakers clocking since the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Cheruiyot, who had won five straight road races coming into
Sunday's competition, was well aware of the record talk preceding
the Breakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt strong, and I was trying to push it,'' Cheruiyot said,
``but it was too hot for a record pace. I'm very happy to have won
the race the way I did. I like to run alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheruiyot's agent, Australian Peter Stubbs _ himself a
world-class half miler _ said, ``To break records, Reuben would
have needed to have three or four guys pushing him seriously, right
from the start, and that didn't happen. Most of the way, he was
just coasting.''
</P>
<P>
   Stubbs said he was surprised Cheruiyot handled the field as
easily as he did, especially after the slow early fractions.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Hayes Street hill,'' Stubbs said, ``I think he just decided
it was time to go to work. He was feeling good at that point, so
why not just drop the hammer? Which is exactly what he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the Breakers, much is always made of the rigors of Hayes
Street hill, about how tough it will prove for first timers in the
race, like Cheruiyot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at it,'' Stubbs said, ``and Reuben said to me,
`What's the problem? It's just a hill.'''
</P>
<P>
   Easy for him to say. Not so easy for his nonplussed rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Kirui, who was second in 35:25 _ a fat 31 seconds behind
Cheruiyot _ said, ``I tried to stay with Reuben, but I was feeling
tired today, and he is very strong right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Third-place finisher Armando Quintanilla (35:30) of Mexico said,
``It was very difficult. Cheruiyot was going down the hill (Hayes
Street) when I was still going up. I would need to train very hard
to run beside him because he is in great form right now. The heat
wasn't a problem, but Reuben was.''
</P>
<P>
   Quintanilla's countryman Joel Hernandez, a sub-seeded runner,
finished ahead of the other two elite runners in the race, Jon
Brown of the United Kingdom and Josphat Machuka of Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   In seventh spot, behind the veteran Machuka, was the top Bay
Area finisher, Kalid Abdalah, a 20-year-old Somalian now living in
Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was displeased with the pokey pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy about it,'' Brown said. ``It suited me just fine.
But I'm just not in shape at the moment. This was the first time
I've done anything more than an easy run in two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sensed that when Cheruiyot made his move on the hill, he'd
had enough of hanging around with the rest of us. He just wanted to
get on with it, so he accelerated really hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found getting up the hill difficult. I didn't recover for
two miles.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By then, of course, Brown was merely a spectator. Along with all
the other supposedly elite men, if they could even see Cheruiyot,
that is.
</P>
<P>
   After the race, Cheruiyot, who honed his skills by running 16
miles a day to and from school when he was a youngster, was as
elusive verbally as he had been on the course.
</P>
<P>
   As good as Cheruiyot is, he'll be a longshot to make the Kenyan
Olympic 10,000-meter team _ his next goal _ as will Kirui. Both of
them live and train in Colorado now. The Kenyan stars already are
in training back home, getting ready for their country's Olympic
trials in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of becoming a champion,'' Cheruiyot said. ``An Olympic
champion? Maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   More likely, however, Cheruiyot will keep trying to become king
of the roads rather than king of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's come up with such a great series of races this year,''
Stubbs said, ``but I don't think he's peaked. He's kind of gotten
the hunger for the roads here in America. He's starting to build
his confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   When he's finished building it, the rest of the road racers
might well be advised to take up another line of work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
