<HEADLINE>
SHOPPING AROUND: SUMMERTIME IN LONDON  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----- ONE COLOR SLIDE IS AVAILABLE FREE OF CHARGE! -----
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By EVERETT POTTER  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    London is booming. It's a city where West End matinees, tea at
Brown's Hotel and noontime concerts at St. Martin-in-the-Fields are
still star attractions. But it's also Tony Blair's ``Cool
Britannia,'' with a lively restaurant scene, a controversial
first-ever mayor, Ken Livingston, and the much-debated Millennium
Dome.
 &HT;    What will visiting Americans find in the capital this summer?
 &HT;    The new British Airways London Eye (44-20870-800-0600;
www.ba-londoneye.com), a giant Ferris wheel with enclosed cars that
rises slowly above the Thames for a bird's-eye view of the city.
Not to mention the newly opened Tate Modern (25 Sumner St. London.
SE1; 44-20-7887-8008; www.tate.org.uk) in the old Bankside Power
Station.
 &HT;    Located on the Thames and looking across at St. Paul's
Cathedral, the building was designed by Sir Giles Gilbert Scott,
who gave England its red phone box.
 &HT;    The vast 500-foot-long Turbine Hall and the river views very
nearly distract from the national collection of modern art, which
includes major works by Duchamp, Hockney and Warhol. More than 2
million visitors are expected to visit the free museum this year.
 &HT;    In fact, the only downside to London this summer is that it can
cost a small fortune to vacation there. But here are some tips to
do it without courting bankruptcy.
 &HT;    Flights to London in summertime can be sky high. These are
months when's it also tough to use frequent flier miles. To get the
best fares, try to avoid flying on Fridays and Sundays.
 &HT;    If flights to Heathrow seem expensive, look to Gatwick and even
Birmingham, for example, which is just 90 minutes by train from
London.
 &HT;    Consolidator fares to London often undercut the major carriers'
summer fares. One of the fastest ways to access them is through
Internet sites such as Expedia.com (www.expedia.com),
Travelocity.com (www.travelocity.com), LowestFare.com
(www.lowestfare.com) and the Travel Site.Com
(www.thetravelsite.com).
 &HT;    Another way around high fares is a classic airline package.
Round-trip airfare, accommodations and transfers are included for a
single price, along with other perks, such as a sightseeing tour.
 &HT;    British Airways (Holiday Desk, 75-20 Astoria Blvd., Jackson
Heights, N.Y. 11370; 877-428-2228;
www.britishairways.com/regional/USA), Virgin Atlantic (747 Belden
Ave., Norwalk, Conn. 06850; 888-YES-VIRGIN; www.virginatlantic.com)
and American Airlines (P.O. Box 619688, DFW Airport, Texas 75261;
800-882-8880; www.aa.com) all offer a range of packages to London.
 &HT;    For example, Virgin's ``London Experience'' is a six-night
package that includes round-trip airfare, transfers, hotel, daily
continental breakfast, a theater ticket, one afternoon tea, a
sightseeing tour and other perks starting at $819 per person, based
on double occupancy. Not bad, considering that airfares alone
between New York and London can run higher than that in summer.
 &HT;    Package prices are fixed throughout the season, and they're
usually available with as little as seven days' advance notice. The
two variables, of course, are hotel choice and availability. Since
there may be 20 or more hotels offered at different prices, it's
smart to check them out independently via the Internet or with a
London guidebook.
 &HT;    Yet for some Americans, going to London isn't the same without
staying at one of London's best hotels, places that have redefined
the luxury-hotel experience. But London sticker shock is most
apparent at these fabled hotels where chintz, afternoon tea and
discreet service reign.
 &HT;    For London's top properties, it's not uncommon to spend in
excess of $400 per night, with daily breakfast at such hotels
easily adding $40 or more to the bill.
 &HT;    But here's a little secret. Smack in the middle of summertime
high season, when there are more pairs of white sneakers than
pigeons in Trafalgar Square, there are deals to be found at some of
London's finest hotels. That's because the highflying European
business travelers who are normally in residence are on vacation.
 &HT;    For example, look at One Aldwych (One Aldwych, WC2;
800-223-6800; www.onealdwych.co.uk), a chic, minimalist palace just
a stone's throw from Covent Garden. Rooms boast down comforters,
fresh fruit and flowers as well as CD players, and the hotel has a
59-foot lap pool where Mozart is piped underwater.
 &HT;    The average nightly rate is 300 pounds (about $474). But from
July 29 to September 10, ``Summer Vacation Rates'' at the hotel
come in at 195 pounds per night ($308) for the first two nights and
97 pounds ($153) for the third night. What's more, a full English
breakfast is included.
 &HT;    For those who like the idea of bed &AMP; breakfast but don't want to
stay in the suburbs, consider Uptown Reservations (41 Paradise
Walk, Chelsea; 44 020 7351 3445; www.fenet.co.uk/uptown). These bed
&AMP; breakfast accommodations are in private houses in such tony
neighborhoods as Chelsea, Knightsbridge or Kensington. Rooms have
either an ensuite bathroom or a private bathroom. Rates run 85
pounds ($134) and, naturally, include breakfast.
 &HT;    For those intent upon saving money, the British Tourist
Authority (551 Fifth Ave., New York, N.Y. 10176; 800-462-2748;
www.visitbritain.com) is a good source for finding bed &AMP; breakfasts
and affordable hotel suggestions. They also offer a wealth of
information on cost-saving museum and transportation passes.
 &HT;    No one said that London is cheap. But with a little forethought,
it can be affordable.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Everett Potter is a New York City-based free-lance travel
writer.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Everett Potter 
