<HEADLINE>
THE MATURE TRAVELER: BEST MEMORIES OF CHINA ARE ONE-ON-ONE
ENCOUNTERS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----- ONE COLOR SLIDE IS AVAILABLE FREE OF CHARGE -----
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ADELE MALOTT  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    Planning a tour of China may not be easy, but it is worth the
effort, says Romaine Wismer of Ellenton, Fla., and her daughter,
Shelley Wismer, of Salt Lake City. In preparing for their trip,
they poured over brochures for hours, read books like Fodor's
``Exploring China,'' checked National Geographic and AAA files and
then visited www.China.com.
 &HT;    ``We wanted to cover as much as possible,'' they said, ``but did
not want to spend four or five days on a ship in the Yangtze River,
which is part of many popular tours of China.''
 &HT;    The Wismers settled on BestTours of River Vale, N.J.,
(800-688-3288; www.bestour.com) because this company allowed them
to swap unwanted cruise days for stops in Shaoxing and Hangzhou _
two cities in the wine-, tea- and silk-producing areas. Their
18-day itinerary included visits to Shanghai, Shaoxing, Hangzhou,
Suzhou, Beijing, Xian, Guilan, Guangzhou (Canton) and Hong Kong.
The cost: $4,000, which covered transportation, lodging and most
meals.
 &HT;    Although the schedule was busy and sometimes tiring, Romaine
Wismer, an active 74-year-old traveler, didn't find it impossible.
``Getting there was the most grueling part of the journey since the
17-hour flight covered 7,000 miles from Salt Lake City,'' she said.
 &HT;    While the Wismers admit that they were fascinated by the Great
Wall, Terracotta Warriors and the beauty of Guili, they remember
with greatest enthusiasm their close encounters with the locals and
their unique culture.
 &HT;    On an early-morning walk their first day in Shanghai, they saw
many groups of people engaged in activities _ some were absorbed in
Tai Chi, others were involved in an exercise class, and still
others followed prescribed dance routines and waved long red fabric
ribbons to form patterns. The Wismers learned that these dances are
performed at public celebrations and that the red fabric symbolizes
Communism.
 &HT;    Most interesting to the Wismer duo were the 20 or 30 people who
were dancing to a popular tune. When the Wismers asked their
permission to take a snapshot, they were greeted by collective
smiles and nods.
 &HT;    Romaine Wismer said, ``One small, older man stopped, bowed and
motioned to us to join the group. `Tango?' he asked. We shook our
heads to indicate that we had not mastered that dance, but he held
his arms open and again said, `Tango,' while beckoning us to join.
We smiled, bowed and continued on our way.''
 &HT;    
 WHIRLING ME AROUND  
 &HT;    ``The next morning, The same man was in the same spot,'' Romaine
Wismer said. ``This time when he issued his invitation, I stepped
forward while Shelley held up her camera. The man took my hand and
whirled me around while he smiled for the picture. What a wonderful
way to begin our journey through his country!''
 &HT;    The Wismers left Shanghai on the train going to Shaoxing, a much
smaller town that is famous for producing rice wine and is
reputedly one of the oldest villages in the country.
 &HT;    When they arrived, the Wismers and two other tourists were the
only passengers to leave the train. After lunch, the
mother-and-daughter team were on their own until dinner, so they
decided to take a short walk to the downtown area. Road workers
stopped their digging to stare, making the Wismers reflect on how
it feels to be a minority. They saw no other Caucasians.
 &HT;    A small van took Romaine and Shelley Wismer to Hangzhou, the
heart of the tea-producing area that celebrates the Mid-Autumn
Festival or Festival of the Mooncake. During the celebration, it is
customary for families to gather in the many parks to picnic, dance
or play games.
 &HT;    
 A SMALL CONFECTION  
 &HT;    A mooncake is a small confection, usually 2.5 inches in diameter
and an inch tall. It looks like a pale version of our Christmas
fruitcake and, according to Romaine Wismer, tastes a lot like it.
Mooncakes are sold in bakeries, hotel lobbies and, sometimes, at
street corner booths.
 &HT;    The Wismers enjoyed the dancers, even though they couldn't
understand a word of what the master of ceremonies said. They
watched in awe as a giant mooncake on a table three feet wide was
wheeled onto the stage, causing audience members to file up to the
stage to cut sections of the cake to eat after dinner.
 &HT;    Romaine Wismer says, ``After a little urging from me, Shelley
went to get a share of the mooncake for our party. The Chinese
people smiled and nodded their approval.''
 &HT;    
 OUR BEST INSIGHT  
 &HT;    The Wismers said they got their greatest insight into life in
China when they toured Beijing. ``We were always aware that our
guides were government employees who would only show us those
things that the government allows foreign tourists to see,''
Romaine Wismer said. But, she added, ``In Hutong we were introduced
to a family consisting of an older woman, her daughter and
granddaughter.
 &HT;    ``Their living quarters would be considered very poor in our
country, but this family was proud of the large-screen TV,
refrigerator and running water. All 13 of us crowded into one small
room. The grandmother didn't speak any English, but she smiled as
our guide explained that while she no longer worked, her daughter
and son-in-law both had good jobs. The daughter worked in a
restaurant, but we were not told what the son did. The grandmother,
whose name was Anna, offered us candy with much smiling and
bowing.''
 &HT;    On the way to Tiananmen Square, the Wismers were startled to see
a portable barber's chair on the sidewalk. In it sat a man who was
in the process of getting his hair cut in the open air.
 &HT;    ``The local people showed no surprise,'' Romaine Wismer said.
``They just walked around the chair.''
 &HT;    As the Wismers approached Tiananmen Square, a guide gave a long
talk about the events that took place in this historic location.
His description: ``The accident was caused by misguided students
who were influenced by outside agitators in 1989.''
 &HT;    Since her return, Romaine Wismer remembers the monuments and
beautiful spots of this enormous land. But most of all, she
remembers the one-on-one encounters with the people of China.
 &HT;    In addition to Bestours, other travel packages to China are
offered by Saga Holidays, a company that specializes in trips for
those ages 50 and older. Their 19-night tour, which includes a
Yangtze River cruise, is priced at $3,899, double occupancy.
Departures dates are available through September. For more
information, call (800) 432-1432, or visit www.sagaholidays.com on
the Web.
 &HT;    Orient Flexi-Pax Tours, which operates out of New York, has an
18-day Yangtze River Splendors trip that costs $3,739 plus taxes
for a fall departure. For more information, call (800) 545-5540, or
visit www.orientflexipax.com on the Web. 
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    Adele Malott is the publisher of THE MATURE TRAVELER: Travel
Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus, a newsletter for mature travelers.
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 The Mature Traveler Newsletter 
