<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2379 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      05-22 1308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, May 23:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-LEBANON (Jerusalem) _ Developing: Southern Lebanon was
chaotic Monday as the Israel-affiliated militia, the South Lebanon
Army, abandoned villages and Hezbollah fighters and civilians moved
in; Israeli gunships killed at least two civilians. The West Bank
and Gaza quiet, however. By William A. Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT7.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-WOMEN (Jerusalem) _ In a landmark ruling, the Israeli
Supreme Court said Monday that women can pray in groups, read aloud
from the Torah and wear prayer shawls at the Western Wall,
practices that had been forbidden by law in keeping with Orthodox
practice. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-POLITICS (Taipei) _ Officials in Taiwan react to recent
political developments. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-NONPROFITS (United Nations) _ U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan is scheduled to speak Monday on the value of non-governmental
organizations, at a time when several countries are trying to bar
some of those organizations from the United Nations to reduce their
influence on issues like Tibet, Kashmir and Chechnya. By Barbara
Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Dateline to come) _ A child was killed Monday by a
NATO bomb left from the war last year, increasing criticism of NATO
for not dealing better with the problem of unexploded bombs. By
Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-POLITICS (Belgrade) _ Political developments in
Serbia. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-GIELGUD (Undated) _ Sir John Gielgud, one of the great
actors of the English stage who enthralled audiences for more than
60 years with his eloquent voice and consummate artistry, died
Sunday at his home in Aylesbury, west of London. By Mel Gussow.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT1,2.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-FEDERALISM (Washington) _ The Supreme Court decided the
two remaining federalism cases of the term, without coming down
strongly on one side or another. In an arson case, the court ruled
about the intent of Congress, not the authority of Congress. In a
false claims case, the court held that Congress never meant to
apply the act to states. The high court also agreed to take a
migratory bird case for next term, which raises other federalism
issue: the authority of Congress under the interstate commerce
clause. By Linda Greenhouse. (1350 words)
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-CLEANAIR (Washington) _ The Supreme Court took an
important clean air case that raises the issue of how much power
Congress can delegate to a federal regulatory agency. By Linda
Greenhouse. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ A roundup of other court action, including
a decision in the Playboy case. By Linda Greenhouse. (1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-MIDEAST (Washington) _ Gov. George W. Bush is scheduled to
speak about the Mideast at an address in Washington on Monday. By
Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   GORE (Washington) _ Al Gore talks with union workers and then
meets with South African President Mbeki. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News and notes on politics.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FLA-TOBACCO-SUIT (Miami) _ Opening arguments possible in the
punitive damage portion of a class-action tobacco lawsuit. The jury
already has ruled against the industry twice, deciding the nation's
five biggest cigarette makers conspired to produce a deadly product
and awarding $12.7 million in compensatory damages to three smokers
representing the half million smokers. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   PA-PLANE-CRASH (Washington) _ Developments in the investigation
of the charter plane crash in Pennsylvania that killed 19. By
Mattew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   HARVARD-PRESIDENT (Undated) _ Neil Rudenstine, a scholar of
Renaissance poetry who led the largest fundraising campaign in the
history of higher education, plans to step down next spring after a
decade as president of Harvard, the nation's oldest and most
prestigious university. After startling his colleagues with an
abrupt three-month leave of absence due to exhaustion early in his
tenure, Rudenstine has won wide praise for uniting Harvard's
historically disparate deans, and has been a leading national
spokesman supporting multiculturalism and affirmative action. By
Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Nasdaq stocks tumble in early trading,
driving the Nasdaq composite index below its April 14 low. At 11:10
a.m., the Nasdaq is down 5.34 percent, at 3,209.36, the Dow Jones
industrial average is down 1.89 percent the S&AMP;P 500 is down 2.22
percent. Treasury prices are higher. European stock markets are
lower. London is down 0.47 percent and Frankfurt is down 1.46
percent. The Nikkei closed down 2.80 percent, to a one-year low.
The Hang Seng index ended down 2.33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-SATELLITES (Alcantara, Brazil) _ In the satellite
launching business, location is everything. Because Alcantara is
two degrees south of the equator, rockets launched here can achieve
orbit faster and carry heavier payloads than those launched
elsewhere. Built by the Brazilian military two decades ago, the
Alcantara Launch Center has become the focal point for what is
perhaps the most ambitious space program in any developing country.
A boom in telecommunications satellites _ most of them for American
companies _ is likely to assure Alcantara a prosperous future. By
Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-MERGERS () _ Two big deals involving companies that market
software for business-to-business uses are announced. Vignette is
acquiring OnDisplay in a $1.7 billion stock swap, while WebMethods
is buying Active Software in a stock deal valued at $1.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   POLAND-TELEKOM (Undated) _ A consortium led by France Telecom
has won the exclusive right to bid for a 35 percent stake in the
sale of Poland's state-run telecommunications company,
Telekomunikacja Polska. The deal is Eastern Europe's largest
telecommunications privatization. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
