<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2393 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-WHITECOLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-22 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DR. LAURA DOESN'T NEED HELP FAILING 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Dr. Laura Schlessinger's new syndicated television program
bombs, and it will, it won't be her fault.
</P>
<P>
   When Dr. Laura's show tanks, it will be because a vast left-wing
conspiracy _ gays, feminists, tree huggers, free-lovers, prochoice
advocates, child haters, atheists, journalists, academics, assorted
libertines and moral bankrupts _ has been working day and night to
keep her message off television.
</P>
<P>
   When her show fails it will be all their fault.
</P>
<P>
   Because you can be sure that it won't be Dr. Laura's.
</P>
<P>
   Even if she is about as telegenic as a dried codfish.
</P>
<P>
   Even if her TV persona gives new meaning to the word stiff.
</P>
<P>
   So I have mixed feelings about the tactics of gay activists who
are urging WCVB-TV (Ch. 5) not to air Dr. Laura's show. I
sympathize, but if they succeed it will give her another excuse to
play the martyr, a role she relishes, and knows how to exploit.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I'd rather watch her fail.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Dr. Laura said her remarks about gays had been
distorted, taken out of ``clinical'' context. She says she doesn't
condemn homosexuals, she condemns homosexuality. She hates the sin
but loves the sinner.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure in which clinical context she referred to gays as
``deviants.'' The word doesn't sound clinical, i.e., objective,
analytical, devoid of emotion. It sounds loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe she thinks of her radio show as a clinic, although there
doesn't seem to be much about it that's clinical in the medical
sense. It's not what you'd call therapeutic, unless you believe in
old-fashioned wall-to-wall therapy, and a lot of her callers do,
apparently. Hit me again, Dr. Laura! Harder! Thanks. I needed that.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, driving to work, I listen to Dr. Laura just to get my
dander up. It never fails. She has the same effect on my nervous
system as four or five cups of coffee. Between Dr. Laura and Boston
traffic, I arrive at work with my eyes bugging out of my head.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Laura's radio show reaches 20 million listeners. It's
probably safe to say that most of them don't tune in, as I do, to
get their blood roiled. Her success says a great deal about how
desperate people are for guidance, for someone to tell them what's
right and what's wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Into the slough of moral relativism steps a woman wrapped in a
cloak of sanctimony.
</P>
<P>
   She natters on as if she were without sin, free to cast the
first stone.
</P>
<P>
   She acts as though she personally carried the tablets down from
Mount Sinai.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't give advice, she issues orders.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Laura's act may play on radio, but it won't go over on
televison. The only way to make her program a hit is to turn it
into a quiz show. ``For 1 million dollars, list the following
groups in the order in which Dr. Laura insulted and abused them on
yesterday's show: 1) Gays 2) Single mothers 3) Atheists or 4)
Mothers who work outside the home.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Post reported last week that rehearsals for her
television program have not been going well. The paper quoted an
anonymous observer who said Dr. Laura was having a dificult time
mastering the TV talk-show form. The spy added, ``The worst part
is, she won't listen to anybody's advice.''
</P>
<P>
   Kind of makes you want to go take on the day, doesn't it?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 1440EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
