<HEADER>
A2402 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-JAPAN-YOUTH-VIOLENCE-     05-22 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-YOUTH-VIOLENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAVE OF VIOLENCE BY TEENS LEADS TO HAND-WRINGING IN JAPAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHARON MOSHAVI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ A young woman is stalked and murdered. An elderly woman
is knifed to death by her neighbor. Another is killed during a bus
hijacking.
</P>
<P>
   This might read like a New York police blotter, but all the
crimes were committed in Japan in the space of a few weeks. Most
startling, all were committed by Japanese teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   Japan is racked by a growing wave of teen violence, and that has
led to a lot of hand-wringing, as Japan wonders what is going wrong
with its youth.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's violent crime rate is the highest it has been in 23
years, but the fastest-growing category is crimes committed by
those under 18 years old. Specialists cite a combination of factors
to explain why so many of this generation are lashing out: economic
hard times, smaller families, an increased sense of isolation due
to technology, and school pressures.
</P>
<P>
   Most Japanese youth, of course, aren't killing anybody, and the
crime rate remains much lower than in the United States, but
specialists said the assailants are merely extreme examples of a
surging number of dysfunctional Japanese youth known as
``hikikomori,'' or socially withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   The average hikikomori might refuse to go to school, hole up in
a bedroom, sleep during the day, stay up at night, and act
violently toward family members.
</P>
<P>
   They are also characterized by a lack of self-esteem, and
according to adolescent psychiatrist Hidehiko Kuramoto, ``an
inability to separate the real world from the world of their
imagination.'' That's one reason why a hikikomori teenager can
become violent, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics on juvenile crime in Japan are sketchy, but it has
been rising steadily since 1994, and today more than half of all
violent offenses are committed by teens. In 1998, the most recent
year for which statistics are available, incidents of school
violence rose 25 percent, and experts say it most certainly rose
again in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Japan last experienced a wave of teen violence in the early
1980s, but most of the crime was committed by gangs and it wasn't
quite so brutal. Today, most of the violence is done by
individuals, and it can be cruel and cold.
</P>
<P>
   In the case this month of a 17-year-old boy who stabbed his
64-year-old neighbor to death, the boy reportedly told police that
he wanted to have the experience of killing someone.
</P>
<P>
   Japan became aware of just how cruel a child can be in 1997,
when a 14-year-old in Kobe strangled and dismembered an
11-year-old, shocking the nation. Not only has youth violence
continued to grow, but the offenders are getting younger, officials
say.
</P>
<P>
   Youth violence in Japan is still nothing compared with the that
in the United States, which over the past year has had a rash of
school shootings, starting with the deaths at Columbine High School
in Colorado. But Yoshinao Hirano, an education professor at Shinshu
University, said Japanese youth are, in their hearts, as capable of
violence as their American peers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just that America has guns, and Japan does not,'' he
said. Japan has some of the strictest gun-control laws in the
world. To get a handgun _ all other guns are illegal _ one must
undergo a year of background checks.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the recent rash of teen violence, Japan's
parliament is working to change its juvenile crime statute, which
hasn't been altered since 1949. A draft bill would lower the age of
prosecution from 16 to 14, and would automatically place serious
crimes in the hands of prosecutors rather than family court.
</P>
<P>
   At age 14, Seiichi Ishii's daughter refused to go to school. She
became sullen and withdrawn, and wouldn't go out of the house. She
vented her rage at her mother. Ishii, a computer executive, is
trying to understand what happened. He said he thinks maybe the
problem is that his daughter is an only child, and didn't have a
sibling to interact with. He also said she was getting bullied at
school because she was a bit unusual, a sin at conformist Japanese
schools.
</P>
<P>
   A year and a half later his daughter is back in school, but
nothing has been solved. She's still violent at home, and directs
most of the behavior toward her mother. ``I'm afraid she might
snap, become a kireru,'' said Ishii, using a term that means to
commit a sudden violent act.
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon of social withdrawal is not exclusive to Japan,
but experts say one of the reasons it may be especially prevalent
is that Japan is a reserved society. It is the kind of behavior a
child can sink in to and no one might notice at first.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's peculiarly Japanese. These kids are being too passive.
It's a kind of passive aggression,'' said Hidehiko Sekizawa,
executive director of the Hakuhodo Institute of Life and Living,
which monitors Japanese lifestyles.
</P>
<P>
   Two recent surveys funded by the Ministry of Education point
much of the blame at parents. ``Japanese kids are lacking a moral
education,'' said Hirano, who was commissioned to conduct the
surveys.
</P>
<P>
   According to Hirano's studies, Japanese children have less
parental instruction and discipline than their counterparts in
Korea, Britain, Germany, and the United States. For example, 71
percent of Japanese youth have never been told by their fathers not
to lie _ three times more than youth in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese youth are also less likely than teenagers in other
countries to do good deeds, like stopping a friend from doing
something wrong, or helping an elderly person, according to one
study, a sharp contrast to their parents' reputation for
politeness.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts also attribute youth violence to video games and
television. But while critics in the United States object to video
games and movies with violence, the Japanese are worried about the
isolating nature of computers and television. A survey by the
Hakuhodo Institute found that children 10 to 14 ``thought of video
games as friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, schools must share in the blame, specialists say. Though
life in Japan is changing rapidly and becoming less traditional and
conformist, the schools are not. ``That gap can be difficult for
some students to handle,'' said Kuramoto. Bullying, for example, is
a consistent problem that schools do little to address. The
17-year-old boy who hijacked a bus and killed one passenger was the
victim of bullying in school.
</P>
<P>
   Even with his daughter undergoing massive trauma, Ishii found it
difficult to seek professional help. The family went to see a
psychiatrist only once, and his daughter made only occasional
visits to a counseling center. Ishii's wife ended up becoming
housebound, too. ``She was too ashamed to face anybody, so she
stayed inside all the time, just like our daughter,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
