<HEADER>
A2409 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS &LR;      05-22 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AUNTIE' COMES UNDER FIRE   FOR SPURNING QUEEN MUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ When the British Broadcasting Corp. announced last week
that it would not cover the July 19 pageant honoring the Queen
Mother on her 100th birthday, all hell broke loose.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives were apoplectic, saying the BBC's decision to snub
the Queen Mum, as the mother of Queen Elizabeth II is fondly known,
was proof that the network is a bastion of self-loathing Brits who
hate the monarchy and everything it stands for.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, the Tories said, it proved the BBC is run by a bunch of
left-wing, chablis-swigging, sushi-chomping liberals who are so
biased in favor of Prime Minister Tony Blair and his Labor Party
that the national broadcast service is undermining democracy.
</P>
<P>
   If you believe the Tories, the BBC stands for Biased British
Communists.
</P>
<P>
   But before dismissing this as Tory hyperbole, one might note
that no less a thoughtful magazine than The Economist has compared
the BBC to a communist regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``The corporation has a byzantine bureaucracy, an all-powerful
leader, and has long been in a state of permanent revolution,'' an
editorial opines. ``Most important, however, it has a creed _ that
public-service broadcasting must be funded by the taxpayer _ which
informs all its actions and which cannot publicly be questioned.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tory assault on the BBC is part of a wider attack on
``Auntie,'' as the British refer to their nationally subsidized
network. Every household in Britain pays about $160 a year _ about
$4 billion overall _ for the privilege of watching costume dramas
and the Teletubbies. Part of the bargain includes some of the best
radio and television journalism in the world.
</P>
<P>
   But the BBC is at a crossroads. Facing aggressive competition
from independent stations, which outbid ``the Beeb'' for popular US
imports like ``Friends'' and ``Frasier,'' and as digital and
satellite TV offer Britons unprecedented choice, the BBC has tried
to inject some energy and innovation into its sometimes stodgy
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Tories claim ``the Beeb'' is in Labor's pocket,
even some Labor stalwarts are turning up their noses at the BBC's
efforts to make itself less stuffy. Two weeks ago, Margaret
Beckett, a Labor member of Parliament, refused to go on the BBC's
premier public affairs show, ``Question Time,'' because Boy George
was a panelist.
</P>
<P>
   Boy George, the front man for 1980s pop group Culture Club,
accused Beckett of being a homophobic snob. Beckett replied that,
while tolerant of homosexuals, she was less so of the BBC going
down-market in search of ratings.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over the Queen Mum's parade, meanwhile, has led
many viewers to question just whose network this is, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the BBC provided live coverage of the opening of the
Tate Modern gallery, which houses modern art, deeming it one of the
most important cultural events in the nation's recent history.
</P>
<P>
   But, like many British people, Ron and Marge Dunbobbin say they
would rather watch a parade honoring the Queen Mum, whose
morale-boosting visits to victims of the Blitz made her a national
treasure 60 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the people who run the BBC think we'd rather watch a
bunch of rich celebrities talk about modern art, but I'll tell you,
most people want to see the Queen Mum,'' said Ron Dunbobbin, who,
with his wife, runs the Dryfesdale Hotel, a quaint hostelry in
Lockerbie, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   With the BBC taking a pass on the Queen Mum's parade, ITV, the
rival independent commercial network, gladly scooped up the rights.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial stations have been running circles around the BBC of
late, outbidding it for the rights to broadcast soccer, which is
the closest thing to a national religion here. Des Lynam, the BBC's
longtime, unflappable chief sportscaster, went over to ITV.
</P>
<P>
   Back to the Tories, whose inability to mount serious opposition
to Blair is probably more of a threat to democracy than a bunch of
supposed limousine liberals at the Beeb. The Conservatives insist
that the BBC's choice of Andrew Marr as its political editor was
proof positive that the network is irredeemably biased.
</P>
<P>
   Marr, it seems, was once the editor of a liberal newspaper, The
Independent, and as a columnist has written opinion pieces that
have sometimes _ hold onto your hats _ endorsed Blair's policies.
</P>
<P>
   Right. Well. That proves it then, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   All right. Enough of that bother. Back to the great issues of
the day: When are the Teletubbies on again?
</P>
<P>
   (Kevin Cullen is the London bureau chief of the Globe).
</P>
</TEXT>
