<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CANCER (New Orleans) _ Developments at the cancer
conference: Three new studies suggest that small doses of
antidepressants can help relieve hot flashes in cancer patients. By
Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MANDRILLS (Undated) _ Primatologists are discovering new and
exciting elements in the life of the mandrills of Gabon: they dwell
in vast colonies of females and offspring. A group of 800 mandrills
is a tightknit and stable society, traveling, foraging, breeding,
playing, nuzzling and bickering together year after year. And
except when females are in estrus, the males are solitary dwelling
creatures, who all but kill one another when the females are in
season. By Natalie Angier. (2150 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT3.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-RUSSIA-MIR (Undated) _ By some plans, it should have been
long dead. With most of its structure disintegrated by a fiery
reentry through the Earth's atmosphere, the remains of the giant
spacecraft should be resting on the bottom of the Pacific Ocean.
Instead, the Russian Mir space station remains in orbit, staffed by
two astronauts busily repairing worn components and readying it for
future visits. Previously abandoned, battered and showing all the
effects of its sometimes troubled 14 years in space, the Mir just
keeps going on and on. By Warren E. Leary. (1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT4.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LYME-DEBATE (Undated) _ A furious debate rages among doctors
over the value of expensive antibiotics used to term Lyme disease.
So say nothing more can be done after the original treatments,
while others contend the rigid, expensive regimen may be needed for
months. Now members of Congress are determined to find out which
side is right and have ordered a Congressional investigation. By
Holcomb B. Noble. (2150 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT5,6.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FLUORESCENT-MOLECULE (Undated) _ A glowing point at the tip
of an optical fiber could someday be the torch that lights the
world of DNA, proteins and other molecules. Writing in Nature,
researchers at the University of Konstanz in Germany report that
they had created a microscope that used a single fluorescent
molecule as its light source. Some scientists are calling it a
breakthrough in optical imaging. By Kenneth Chang. (680 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENE (Undated) _ In a culmination of concerted efforts
initiated by one determined family, three groups of researchers are
reporting that they have found the gene mutation that causes a rare
disorder known as pseudoxanthoma elasticum. Now that they have
identified the gene, they say, they can begin figuring out how it
contributes to disease, diagnose it prenatally, test for it in
people whose symptoms are ambiguous and look for ways to treat the
disease. By Gina Kolata. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DAEDALUS (Undated) _ An imaginative and irreverent English
scientist who writes under the pen name Daedalus has been tweaking
scientific orthodoxy in weekly columns for the last 36 years. A
self-described ``court jester in the Palace of Science,'' he is an
expert in chemical spectroscopy and other sober subjects, and since
1988 his column has been published weekly by the serious journal
Nature. But his research projects have sometimes flown wildly off
the track of mainstream science. One of his achievements was the
construction of a fraudulent perpetual motion machine. By Malcolm
Browne. (1525 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ALBATROSS (Undated) _ Researchers in Massachusetts
unexpectedly discovered an albatross, whose internal compass had
gone haywire. But it was just one of several extraordinary bird
finds on Penikese. 1215 words w/photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: Items on the
nonexistent love life of bdelloids, the rediscovered asteroid
Albert and the missing comet K2. By Henry Fountain. (685 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MADCOW-DISEASE (Undated) _ Now, six years after young people
in Britain started dying from a human strain of mad cow disease,
scientists are still struggling to understand how the disease
spreads to humans, how many more will die from it and if a similar
epidemic could start in the United States spread by infected deer
and elk. While there are no firm answers, clues are being
discovered on an almost weekly basis as scientists explore the
nature of a mysterious infectious agent called the prion. By Sandra
Blakeslee. (1050 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BOWELS (Undated) _ An obsession with the bowels was more
than a mad moment in the history of medicine. It went on for a
century or more, and it is not over yet, according to a book
published in March, ``Inner Hygiene.'' The book is exhaustive and
scholarly, but it is also a merry chronicle. Constipation may be
common and unpleasant, but the notion that it is the root of every
illness is nonsense. The idea, however, had been around for
centuries, and it was truly embraced by doctors and the public in
the United States and Europe in the 1800s. It kept its hold on
medicine until well into the 20th century. By Denise Grady. (890
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MEDICAL-CONSUMERISM (Undated) _ In quitting the United
States Senate race last week, Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani discovered
that choosing a therapy for prostate cancer was a far more daunting
effort than he had expected. Giuliani said he had to focus entirely
on the decision, letting his immediate political future fall by the
wayside. Giuliani's difficulties spring largely from a radical
change in the relationship between patients and their doctors.
Americans have traded in paternalism for medical consumerism after
fighting for a greater voice in making critical decisions about
their care, and that has not come without cost. By Lawrence K.
Altman. (1125 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Personal Health column: High-fiber
diets may not prevent cancer, as recent studies suggest. But they
have tons of other benefits. By Jane E. Brody. (790 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENE-WAGER (Undated) _ How many human genes are there?
Recent estimates have ranged from 60,000 to 140,000 and might be
expected to narrow sharply as the human genome nears completion. In
fact the range has widened, suggesting that gene-counting remains
at least as much art as science. Faced with estimates that are all
over the lot, genome scientists have contrived a simpler way of
settling the question, at least for the present. At a meeting this
month at the Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory they opened a sweepstake
for bets on the number of human genes. The winner will be chosen
based on the most likely number decreed at the same annual meeting
in 2003. By Nicholas Wade. (585 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ News and notes on health and
fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ For children who need medical attention at a hospital, the
danger may not end when they are placed in an ambulance. A recent
study found by researches at Johns Hopkins Children's Center found
that it was not uncommon for patients and medical equipment to be
unsecured as ambulances sped them to the hospital. (300 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Reducing medical costs has become a major goal in the age of
managed care, but a new study finds that can be trickier to
accomplish than it may seem. Money saved at the hospital often is
spent for other care, including later hospitalizations. (200 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ A researcher warns people with pacemakers not to sleep with
magnets, but apparently they can safely be worn as long as they're
kept at least six inches away from the devices. (306 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Researchers say that deaths from sudden infant death syndrome
could be cut back even further if doctors would merely tell their
new mothers to put the babies to bed on their backs. (265 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Through genetic engineering, scientists have bred a mouse that
can drink much more alcohol that other mice, and that even recovers
from its hangovers fasters. They hope their findings will be
significant in treating alcoholics. (225 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ A science question answered: Why does fish
start smelling awful in the garbage pail so much sooner than meat
does? By C. Claiborne Ray. (290 words)
</P>
