<SLUG> BC-CORNING-STREET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORNING TO BUY REST OF INTELLISENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds, prices in final 3 grafs do not reflect market close)  
 By JUSTIN DINI   
 c. 2000 NYTimes.com/TheStreet.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fiber optics giant Corning (GLW:NYSE) said it will acquire the
67 percent of closely held IntelliSense it doesn't already own for
some $500 million in Corning stock, one of three deals in the
high-tech space unveiled Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, semiconductor maker LSI Logic (LSI:NYSE) said it
would buy privately held DataPath Systems, a Los Gatos,
Calif.-based maker of chips for communications applications, in an
all-stock deal valued at $420 million. And Sunnyvale, Calif.-based
Advanced Micro Devices (AMD:NYSE) said it would sell 90 percent of
its communications products unit to Silicon Valley-based tech
buyout firm Francisco Partners for about $375 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Corning, the Corning, N.Y.-based company which acquired its
initial stake in Wilmington, Mass.-based IntelliSense in June, said
IntelliSense will operate as a wholly owned subsidiary when the
deal closes, which is expected some time in the second quarter. A
big chunk of the purchase price will be recorded as goodwill and
intangible assets that are expected to be amortized over periods of
five to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Milpitas, Calif.-based LSI, meanwhile, said its acquisition of
DataPath ``will immediately bolsters LSI Logic's portfolio of
communications standard products as well as its library of
communications-specific building blocks.''
</P>
<P>
   AMD, the second-biggest chip maker after Intel (INTC:Nasdaq),
will retain a 10 percent stake in the unit, with a warrant to
acquire approximately an additional 10 percent. The companies
anticipate completing the transaction in the third quarter. After
it closes, AMD will provide wafer fabrication, manufacturing and
related services to the new company under multi-year service
agreements. Financial terms were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   AMD shares fell 5 5/8, or 7 percent, to 78 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   Corning shares declined 6 3/16, or 3 percent, to 176 1/4 in
midday trading Monday.
</P>
<P>
   LSI shares fell 2 3/4, or 6 percent, to 43 1/2 in midday
trading.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
</TEXT>
