<SLUG> BC-HERBALIFE-FOUNDER-STREET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUNDER OF HERBALIFE DEAD AT 44 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds, stock price does not reflect market close)  
 By JENNIFER FRIEDLIN   
 c. 2000 NYTimes.com/TheStreet.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Herbalife International (HERBA:NASDAQ) said Monday that its
chairman and chief executive, Mark Reynolds Hughes, died on Sunday
in his sleep at his home in Malibu, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Los Angeles Sheriff's Department said the
case had been turned over to the Los Angeles Coroner's office,
adding that Hughes' death appeared to be the result of natural
causes.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes, who was 44, founded Herbalife, a maker of nutritional
and weight-loss products, in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles-based company said that it would continue to
operate according to ``the spirit and vitality'' of Hughes' vision.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Herbalife announced that Hughes had shelved a plan to
buy out the company. He had offered to buy Herbalife in September
through a company he set up, MH Millennium Acquisition Corp., for
$510 million, or $17 a share, but then canceled the deal after
failing to arrange financing.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said at the time that he was making the offer because he
was unhappy about the company's sagging stock price. When the bid
was made, Herbalife's stock jumped 26 percent, to about 15. It
tumbled after the canceled bid and was trading down 1 1/4, or 13
percent, at 8 5/8 around midday Monday after hitting a 52-week low
of 8 earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   A company representative would not comment on Herbalife's
current plans, saying only that company executives were ``moving
forward with their current strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's Internet homepage said Hughes decided to found
Herbalife after his mother's death from an accidental overdose of
prescription diet pills when he was 18.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
