<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2445 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-PHILLIPS-BOS &LR;      05-22 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-PHILLIPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ESSENTIAL MYSTERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
MOTHERKIND 
By Jayne Anne Phillips. Knopf. 292 pp. $24. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The world of heat and shadows depicted in Jayne Anne Phillips's
fiction is a high-risk place of close-focus intensity _ a universe
rendered, then made bearable, by the brick and mortar of language.
Her early works offered breathtaking heights of alienation: The
chameleonic, hipster voices of the stories in ``Black Tickets''
contained a trance-like ferocity Raymond Carver might have envied,
while ``Machine Dreams,'' her first novel, delivered the fractured
cruelties of the Vietnam age through its intimate, first-person
narrators, all of them on shifting sands. Hers is a language-laden
domain of both precision and nuance; ``Shelter,'' her most recent
novel, managed to convey a murderous story through the prismatic
lens of girlhood memories. In ``MotherKind,'' she has turned this
interior vision onto a year of birth and death _ both primordial
states that promise to strip away everything but the fire within.
</P>
<P>
   It's a crash course in the essential mysteries, in other words,
and one that seems in keeping with Phillips's affinity for the
white-hot center. But ``MotherKind'' is altogether different from
her previous fiction: softer, slower, less reliant upon either
external travails or mutable perspectives. In focusing on the story
of a new mother named Kate; her physician husband, Matt, and his
two sons; and the impending death of her mother from lung cancer,
Phillips has constructed a world of thick description _ of layered
emotion, cottony insularity, odyssean walks to the corner and back.
And while this subject matter has its obvious precedents, from
Proustian sweets to Mrs. Dalloway's perfect flowers, it requires a
particularity of depth and higher meaning that few writers can
accomplish. Phillips does so only erratically: There are moments of
great emotion in ``MotherKind,'' beautiful passages that convey the
woozy, secret center of early motherhood or the final symphonic
chords of loss. But far too much in between is simply concerned
with the detritus of waiting, without benefit of the exalted
language or symbolism that could contain it.
</P>
<P>
   We know from the outset what the stakes are here: ``one ending,
with variations,'' as Kate thinks, closing in on her mother's
death. When the novel opens, Kate, a 31-year-old editor and poet,
is pregnant; she is flying to her mother's small Appalachian town,
where Katherine Tatemen, at only 59, has been given a year to live.
Through several brief, retrospective narratives, we see the months
and events leading up to Kate's taking her mother to live with her
in Boston: Katherine's diagnosis, Kate's return from a solo
pilgrimage in Katmandu, the mother's happy acceptance of her
daughter's pregnancy, which precedes Kate's marriage to Matt by
several months. By the time Katherine has moved into Matt and
Kate's house, hoping that chemotherapy will give her the extra
months to get to know her grandson, we have a deepening sense of
the profound bond between the two women: universal in its
mother-daughter themes, particular in its kindness and empathic
reach.
</P>
<P>
   But if death is a main character from the beginning of
``MotherKind,'' that inexorable silhouette still leaves room for
the exuberance of the infant Alexander: his first minnow flutter in
Kate's womb; his ubiquitous demands, suggesting a perfect blend of
tyranny and innocence. Struggling to stay alive, Katherine caresses
her grandson, clings to her ancient poodle who is also staving off
death, watches Kate marry Matt amid magician's doves and a backyard
garden of eternal hope. And Kate moves ceaselessly from one
interior space to another, cradle to sickroom, in the middle of the
night _ exchanging a nursing child or a breast pump for the spoon
that measures her mother's morphine.
</P>
<P>
   Those crashing sounds you hear in the hallways, disrupting this
eternal arc, belong to Sam and Jonah, Matt's boys from a
just-finished marriage _ two unstoppable, typical dervishes of 8
and 6 who provide the only truly unpredictable action of
``MotherKind.'' One of the best scenes in the novel involves
Jonah's floating out to sea in an inflatable rowboat _ and yet even
this passage, frighteningly evoked, is stopped short, then
delivered by characters' recall and dialogue a few weeks later.
That circumspection suggests some of the problem with the novel.
There is a tentativeness to Phillips's writing here that is
unfamiliar; seeking to navigate the murky shoals of Kate's year of
firsts-and-lasts, her prose is too often cautious instead of
careful, lethargic or numbingly detailed rather than deliberate.
It's one thing to capture with elegant concision the contents of a
dying woman's medicine table; it's another entirely to belabor the
design shortcomings of a baby's windup swing.
</P>
<P>
   And yet ``MotherKind'' contains occasional cloudbursts of
emotion that are masterful as well as moving, from Kate's discovery
of a new mother's loss of self to her terrifying glimpse at ``the
free fall of time'' that she must now witness at such an
accelerated pace. Katherine, of course, has an intrepid presence in
this story that will begin and end in twilight; it is here, in the
power shift between mother and daughter, that death exacts, where
the novel achieves a finely rendered luminescence of grief.
</P>
<P>
   Its arrow aimed toward the nameless territory we call home,
``MotherKind'' charts its passage by the changing of seasons: the
stifling timelessness of an urban summer, the treacherous allure of
New England in its winter cave. Testifying in all its transient
sadness to the tenuousness of things _ to the death of loved ones,
the relentless losses and paybacks of the past _ it stands instead,
in its best moments, as a tribute to endurance. And Kate, whose
sojourns to the East primed her for the willy-nilly surrender both
of motherhood and of grief, would surely comprehend that enigmatic
center: a world of riderless horses and one-way streets, where a
pilgrimage can dead-end in the dark enclosure of a shrine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
