<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2448 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-22 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSAULT IS NOT INNOCENT PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN MCNAMARA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can we agree that four 9-year-olds pinning a classmate to the
playground while a fifth boy mounts her and makes ``humping''
motions is, for lack of a better word, wrong?
</P>
<P>
   Why, then, is the debate in West Bath, Maine, fixating on how to
describe the assault on the little girl rather than focusing on the
assault itself?
</P>
<P>
   Ever since news surfaced last week that five third-grade boys
had been suspended from the West Bath School for repeatedly
physically and verbally abusing some of their female classmates,
the public debate has centered on whether the boys' actions
constitute sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   How could it be sexual harassment? scoff the critics. The boys
aren't even old enough to understand the concept.
</P>
<P>
   How could it not be? responds the other side. The boys were
simulating an act of gang rape.
</P>
<P>
   Call it sexual harassment or don't, if the phrase offends you,
but don't pretend that what happened in that schoolyard was simple
schoolboy horseplay. It was not, as the father of one of the
suspended boys insisted, equivalent to the innocent games of jailer
that he played as a boy. It was not, as others have suggested,
similar to the incident in 1996 when a first-grader in North
Carolina was disciplined for kissing a girl on the cheek because he
liked her.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of that much-ridiculed kissing scandal, the US
Department of Education issued guidelines calling on school
officials to use their ``judgment and common sense'' in these
cases. To constitute sexual harassment, it said, an act ``must be
sufficiently severe, persistent, or pervasive that it adversely
affect a student's education or creates a hostile or abusive
educational environment. For a one-time incident to rise to the
level of harassment it must be severe.''
</P>
<P>
   This incident would seem to qualify, but it didn't happen just
once. The little girl in West Bath was pinned to the ground on at
least two occasions. Complaints about the boys' behavior toward
several girls at school were lodged over several weeks before any
action was taken. The first time the little girl was thrown to the
ground during recess, she did as she had been told: She reported
the incident to the playground supervisor. The supervisor did
nothing, effectively giving the boys the green light to assault the
girls again and sending the girls the clear message that adults
cannot be trusted to protect them.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder they did not tell their parents about the harassment.
The boys had warned them of physical retaliation if they did, and
the refusal of the playground monitor to intervene on their behalf
must have made them feel even more vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Today's schoolyard is not the place we remember; the teasing can
be meaner and more sexual than anything we experienced as children.
``Hostile Hallways,'' a study by the American Association of
University Women almost a decade ago, reported that 70 percent of
girls experience verbal sexual abuse and 50 percent suffer unwanted
sexual contact in school.
</P>
<P>
   Cultural influences don't help. Parents may tell their children
that sex is a scared act between beloved partners, but music lyrics
and videos, television shows, and movies sell them sex as a crude,
casual, often brutal exchange between two people of unequal power.
Boys rule; girls drool. ``Bitch'' is among the milder epithets used
to describe women in the songs 9-year-olds hear blasting from their
big brothers' CD players every night.
</P>
<P>
   Parents, teachers, and school administrators need to talk to
children about gender stereotyping without fear of being labeled
``politically correct'' by those who would have us believe that
this incident was no more than boyhood antics. We teach children
how to behave respectfully at the dinner table; surely we can teach
them how to conduct themselves appropriately with classmates of the
opposite sex.
</P>
<P>
   No little girl should experience the terror that child did, and
no little boys should be ignored who have so clearly internalized a
dangerous cultural message about male power and its use to
intimidate. Whatever else those boys in West Bath thought they were
doing, they were not starry-eyed innocents sharing a tender moment
of affection with a female classmate because they liked her.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eileen McNamara's e-mail address is mcnamara(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
