<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WALTERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 39 YEARS, SHE'S THE GRANDE DAME OF TV NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ All in all, the morning taping of ``The View'' had
been rather . . . eclectic.
</P>
<P>
   First, a retired plumber sprang from the audience during the
preshow warm-up and proceeded to shake his booty with alarming
gusto. Then TV trashman Jerry Springer made an innuendo-laden
appearance, cheered on by a studio audience hooting ``Jerry!
Jerry!'' Finally, a guest chef cooked up a batch of bugs, insisted
on sampling his delicacies, and offered one to Barbara Walters.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Walters wore an expression America knows well,
her eloquent face fixed somewhere between bemusement and
incredulity. It was the look she wore when Monica Lewinsky blithely
discussed having sex with the president of the United States.
Discussed it in front of nearly 50 million viewers. (``Everybody
said `I'm not interested, I don't care,' and then the whole country
watched,'' Walters remarked dryly in an interview after the
``View'' taping). While watching Walters watch others, the thought
occurs: By now, what has this woman not seen and, especially,
heard? She
</P>
<P>
   WALTERS, Page C6 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   is, after all, the virtuoso of the revelatory interview, able to
coax confessions (and tears) out of just about anybody, making it
an Event whenever she sits down with a newsmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Yet she is still capable of surprise, or at least of feigning
surprise. It puts the audience on her side, as do deft displays of
empathy. Before taping began on a second episode of ABC's ``The
View,'' Walters commiserated with spectators about hunger pangs.
``Now that the network has `Millionaire,' you'd think they'd give
you a cup of soup or something,'' Walters crooned sympathetically.
</P>
<P>
   The audience loved it and, seemingly, her. In the front row sat
70-year-old Mollie Goldstein of Queens. ``We just came from `Regis
and Kathie Lee,' but I like this better,'' Goldstein confided.
``We're crazy about Barbara. I remember her from way back, so I
watch everything she's in.''
</P>
<P>
   The same cannot be said, so far, of Walters's birthplace,
Boston, when it comes to ``The View.'' The talk show, which
features freewheeling, topical chat, and celebrity interviews by
five women of different age groups, has been slow to build an
audience in the two months since WCVB-TV (Channel 5) began airing
it at 11 a.m. In recent weeks, viewership has started to climb, but
it still lags far behind ``The Price Is Right'' on WBZ-TV (Channel
4).
</P>
<P>
   A vivid presence on TV, Walters is surprisingly diminutive and
soft-spoken in person. Spectators inside the ``View'' studio on
Manhattan's West Side, even those seated 15 feet from her,
sometimes had to strain to hear her words. Yet since she's the
show's resident legend _ and co-producer _ there's no question as
to who's in charge. She firmly deflected a query about her personal
life from the youngest ``View'' panelist, Lisa Ling; later, when
the discussion began to wander aimlessly, Walters firmly
interjected ``To put a button on this. . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   Walters had 20 minutes between shows, which she spent in her
dressing room picking at Chinese food, making and taking phone
calls, and going over the guest list for the second ``View'' to be
taped that day. Affixed to one wall was a cartoon portrait of
Walters seated on the moon interviewing the title character of her
favorite book, ``The Little Prince,'' by Antoine de Saint-Exupery. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mania as usual &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was another hectic day for the 68-year-old Walters: After
wrapping up the second show, she was scheduled to tape two segments
of her newsmagazine, ``20/20,'' while making preparations to fly to
Texas to interview Republican presidential candidate George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   There were nearly a dozen others in the room: ``View'' costars
Ling, Star Jones, and Joy Behar (the other panelist, Meredith
Vieira, was away closing on a new house), plus a covey of
20-something assistants who weren't even born when Walters became a
household name on the ``Today'' show. They were all sitting down,
slumped into chairs and couches _ all except Walters. She remained
standing throughout the lunch break. If you sit, you stop, and
Barbara Walters doesn't stop.
</P>
<P>
   There are times, however, when she feels like cutting back, and
this day in late April seems to be one of those days. After noting
that her contract with ABC will be up in August, Walters picked up
a fortune cookie and asked: ``Is this going to tell me whether I
should renew my contract?'' She opened it and intoned dramatically:
``You should not renew!''
</P>
<P>
   Later, more seriously, Walters opened up about the demands of
her schedule. In addition to co-producing and appearing on ``The
View'' a couple of days a week, she anchors the weekly newsmagazine
``20/20,'' does four editions of ``The Barbara Walters Special''
per year, plus her annual ``Ten Most Fascinating People'' program.
And of course, there is the pressure of landing the big ``get,''
the interview everyone else covets. Just as people expect Mark
McGwire to hit a homer each time he comes up to the plate, so too
do they expect Walters to land the big gets, even though the
competition has never been stiffer (Diane Sawyer, Katie Couric,
Oprah Winfrey, Ted Koppel, Mike Wallace, Connie Chung,
``Entertainment Tonight,'' ``Access Hollywood.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``It's harder and harder to do because there is so much
competition,'' said Walters. ``It is very hard now, and I really
don't know how much longer I'm going to do specials.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When my contract was signed, I didn't have `The View,' '' she
added. ``So I have to really start thinking about just what it is
that I can give up, that I want to give up. And I don't want to
climb another mountain. I'm not a workaholic. I have a very strong
social life, and many friends. My work is not my entire life.''
</P>
<P>
   Words spoken defiantly, as if to convince herself. Indeed, the
high point of Walters's day seems to be the phone call she gets
from her daughter, Jackie, during which the two laugh at a risque
cartoon Jackie had mailed to her mother. Walters lit up again when
she was told that CNN correspondent Christiane Amanpour, who
recently had a baby, was on the phone. ``Hello, mama,'' Walters
trilled into the phone. ``I'll give you 30 seconds to tell me he's
the most wonderful baby in the whole world.'' She promised to offer
Amanpour some pointers on juggling a demanding TV career and
motherhood. Was Walters just making friendly conversation with a
celebrity, or was she reeling in an interview subject? With her,
one suspects, the two often merge. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Longing to pause &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that explains the distinct longing for some downtime. As
Walters zipped from subject to subject with her assistants _ her
upcoming interview with Bush, her desire to return to Brookline
(where she grew up) to film a segment for ``The View,'' a dozen
other details _ Walters suddenly sighed: ``Wouldn't it be fun to go
shopping? I haven't been shopping in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Duty called, though. That second show loomed, with actress
Heather Graham on tap. ``What's Heather Graham talking about?''
Walters asked. An aide suggested that conversational fodder might
be found in Graham's attempt with boyfriend Ed Burns to buy the
apartment of the late John F. Kennedy Jr. Walters shook her head:
``Let's stay away from that. It's such a downer.''
</P>
<P>
   The paradox of being Barbara Walters at this stage of her
39-year career is that she is far more famous than either Graham or
Burns, and many others she interviews. She waved away the
observation. ``Listen, you sell chickens on television now and
you're famous,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fine, but she's no chicken vendor. She's a walking piece of TV
history, with a resume studded with firsts: first female cohost of
the ``Today'' show, first woman to coanchor a network newscast,
first woman in television news to earn a salary of $1 million (it's
now reportedly closer to $10 million). She did not invent the
celebrity interview on TV, but she made it into an art form, and
turned ``the Barbara Walters interview'' into a genre with its own
distinct hallmarks. She was one of the pioneers of the TV
newsmagazine, and she, more than anyone else, built a bridge
between news and entertainment _ a bridge that is well-traveled in
television today.
</P>
<P>
   And consider this: Who else has remained well-known and au
courant enough that she's been the subject of impersonations on
both the ``Saturday Night Live'' of the 1970s (Gilda Radner as
``Baba Wawa'') and on the ``SNL'' of the year 2000 (Cheri Oteri)?
No one does Gerry Ford impersonations anymore, but Barbara Walters
still generates a cultural buzz.
</P>
<P>
   ``She may be the most influential person in the history of TV,''
says Steven D. Stark, an NPR commentator who wrote ``Glued to the
Set: The 60 Television Shows and Events That Made Us Who We Are
Today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People often think of Edward R. Murrow as the patron saint of
TV news,'' adds Stark. ``No, Barbara Walters is the patron saint of
TV news. For better or worse, she created what we now think of as
television news. She's a genius of a sort. If Mike Wallace were to
leave `60 Minutes,' `60 Minutes' would go on the same way. But `The
Barbara Walters Specials' are Barbara Walters; there's nobody else.
She's irreplaceable in a way that no one else is.''
</P>
<P>
   Told of Stark's assessment of her influence, Walters's eyes
widened. Was this real surprise, or merely the mock? ``I don't feel
that way,'' she said, then assumed an attitude of
mock-imperiousness as she nodded toward her staff. ``I should ask
them to treat me with more respect. A little more respect,
please!'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
A diligent reporter &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Within the TV industry, Walters is known for doggedly pursuing
interview subjects herself rather than leaving it to producers, yet
she frets about the public perception that ``I just sit around and
everybody comes to me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's harder and harder to get the big interview, and I hate
it,'' she said. ``Also, every murderer has an agent and a lawyer.
They want to know your ratings, they want to know how much time
you're going to give them. If you put them on, how much promotion?
I mean, it's just amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, if you're Barbara Walters, what interview coups are
left?
</P>
<P>
   ``People always say to me: `Who would you like to get?' '' said
Walters. ``But the people who are left do not do interviews. The
queen of England does not do interviews. The pope does not do
interviews. So far Prince Charles and Camilla Parker-Bowles and the
young princes do not do interviews. The time that heads of state
mattered has passed. I think with the exception of Saddam Hussein,
there's no head of state that people would say: `I really want to
see him.' Maybe Fidel Castro now, but certainly not a year ago. And
people are not interested in foreign policy. They're not even that
interested in politics. You have to make George W. interesting to a
prime-time audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps in search of another challenge, Walters teamed up with
Bill Geddies, her longtime producer for ``The Barbara Walters
Specials,'' to found ``The View'' three years ago. Walters said she
envisioned it as a cross between ``Regis &AMP; Kathie Lee'' and the
last part of ABC's ``This Week,'' where journalists indulge in some
give-and-take with each other.
</P>
</TEXT>
