<HEADLINE>
BOOKS RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Pastoralia'' by George Saunders (Riverhead, $22.95). A second
striking collection finds personal stories, and occasional grace,
in the schlocky sprawl of the American dream. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Human Stain'' by Philip Roth (Houghton Mifflin, $26). An
eloquently imagined American tragedy, with a good man undone by his
desire to be ``just on his own and free.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``At End of Day'' by George V. Higgins (Harcourt, $24). Artful
and uncompromising as always, this final novel by the vernacular
master tells a story right out of the crime-news headlines. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Anil's Ghost'' by Michael Ondaatje (Knopf, $25), like ``The
English Patient,'' sets up a collision of history and imagination,
this one in Sri Lanka. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``White Teeth'' by Zadie Smith (Random House, $24.95).
Incandescently inventive, insouciantly multicultural, this debut
novel shows off the new English and the new London. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Way Out There in the Blue'' by Frances FitzGerald (Simon &AMP;
Schuster, $30) reframes the achievements of the Reagan presidency
through the prism of his pursuit of ``Star Wars.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
