<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-HENLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON HENLEY IS BACK IN THE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eleven years between albums is a pop-culture eternity, but not
for Don Henley. First he toured behind his last solo album, ``The
End of the Innocence,'' then he founded the Walden Woods Project
and published a book about the environment, then fought with Geffen
Records and sued them for his release, then reunited and toured
with the Eagles, then fathered three children in the last five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Life in the fast lane, to quote an Eagles song.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes ``Inside Job,'' a new solo album, due out Tuesday.
It's worth the wait, as Henley combines graceful acoustic ballads
with simmering funk and drum-looped rock tracks, all girded with
articulate, rapier-wit lyrics about social issues and his new
family-man status.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always said that I'd rather make a few good albums than a
whole lot of mediocre ones,'' says Henley, now 52. ``The
experiences that I had during those 11 years made it possible for
me to write these songs. So I don't worry about how much time has
gone by.''
</P>
<P>
   Henley also has no illusions about the target audience for the
new album, which will be backed by his appearance at the
FleetBoston Pavilion June 5. (It's a Walden Woods benefit, with
tickets $44 to $89.50)
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 78 million baby boomers who don't really have a
whole lot to listen to, and I'm hoping that I can at least
partially fill that void,'' he says. ``I think that this album
speaks to concerns that members of my generation deal with on a
daily basis, including the environment, parenthood, and the
inhumanity and coldness pervasive in a corporatized world.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pollution to parenthood &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Henley deals with environmental pollution in the piano ballad
``Goodbye to a River'' (with the line ``the captains of industry
are killing everything''), with parenthood in the tranquil ``Taking
You Home'' (about bringing home a newborn daughter, with the verse,
``In this love I found strength I never knew I had''), and abusive
corporations in ``Inside Job.'' In the latter, he sings, ``While
you were sleeping they came and took it all away/ It was an inside
job, it always is/ Chalk it up to business as usual.''
</P>
<P>
   Cynical? Yes _ and that's always been part of Henley's world
view. But that is countered more than ever by the sensitive songs
(including the acoustic ``For My Wedding'') that address the love
of family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the album is an example of yin and yang. It deals with
light and darkness,'' says Henley. ``I try to achieve a balance
because I think there's more of a balance in my life now. People
have used words like cynical and negative to describe me, which I
don't necessarily agree with. I've always been skeptical about
certain things and outspoken. . . . But I'm now finding a great
deal of solace in my family.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I tried to say in some of these songs is that in an
illogical world, in a world where reason does not necessarily
prevail, solace can be found in the family, in nature, and in the
spiritual life which encompasses those two things. Nature has
always been my refuge, but now my family is my refuge as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Henley is not as sympathetic, of course, to the corporate world,
which he attacks with even more venom than usual on the album. In
``Workin' It,'' he offers a Dylanesque rap and this tart assessment
of some corporate executives: ``We're running out of everything,
but we can't afford to quit/ Before this binge is over, we've got
to squeeze out one more hit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The corporate climate, and not just in the record industry, is
frightening,'' says Henley. ``They're gobbling up everything. And
it's just not good for art, it's not good for culture, it's not
good for diversity, it's not good for the truth, it's not good for
fairness. And the government seems to have refined the art of
looking the other way. It's a completely laissez-faire climate now
in Washington. You can get as big and as voracious as you want.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for Microsoft, Henley is reminded. A federal judge
recently ruled that the software giant violated antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Media monopolies &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the one token sacrificial lamb,'' he says. ``But there
are anticompetitive practices going on all over the place. And it's
all in the name of commerce. Every logical argument now that can be
made on behalf of sustaining this planet has to take a back seat to
commerce. I know about this first-hand because I'm from Texas, the
most polluted state in the union.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm also disturbed by the formation of monopolies of various
kinds within the media industry. They tend to use nice euphemisms
like globalization, multinationalism, merger, and conglomerate _
but these are all euphemisms for monopoly. Back in Teddy
Roosevelt's time, none of this would have been allowed. He would
have been trustbusting up a storm.''
</P>
<P>
   Henley also takes some shots at the Internet in ``Workin' It,''
with the biting line, ``We've got the software, hardware, CD-ROM,
we've got the exploitation.com.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is a double-edged sword,'' he says. ``It's a bit
like television. It can be a wonderful tool for good, for
education, and communication. Or it can be a repository for all our
cultural garbage. There's a lot of litter alongside the information
highway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't go on the Internet. If the Internet has some
information that I need, I ask someone else to do it for me. And I
don't use e-mail, largely as a matter of privacy. There are serious
privacy issues with regard to the Internet. Large corporations are
gathering information on each and every one of us, which I deal
with on the song `Inside Job.' Big Brother is here. And he's
workin' it.''
</P>
<P>
   Henley is clearly back in harness and ready to go. He even has a
new band, save for holdover guitarist Frank Simes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted people who were a little bit younger and more
enthusiastic,'' he says of the changes. ``I was looking for a
little hunger, so to speak. Not that some of my previous band
members weren't great musicians, but I think some of them had
gotten tired of going on the road and wanted to stay put. I don't
blame them for that and we all remain friends. But I just thought
it was time for a change. New faces, fresh start.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
