<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   !!! 1/2 ``Dinosaur'' Dinosaurs are natural movie stars, and
Disney's computer-generated tribe of them, set against real
landscapes, is a virtual triumph, moving movies (and Disney
animation) another step forward. This fable about a young orphan
dino struggling to survive with his surrogate family echoes
``Bambi,'' ``Tarzan,'' and ``The Lion King'' thematically, but has
a fresh look all its own. (PG) &QL; 
 &QL; 
(FR) !!! ``Hamlet'' This contemporary ```Hamlet,'' starring Ethan
Hawke, has a raw, fresh street energy that moves with vitality
through a Manhattan world of corporate takeovers, youthful angst,
and media overload. Even when its conceits only seem conceits,
Michael Almereyda's reworking persuasively plugs Shakespeare's
existentialism into today's ephemera. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
! 1/2 ``Road Trip'' Labored gross-out stuff, set in motion when a
guy at college in Ithaca, cheating on his girlfriend at college in
Austin, hits the road to head off a compromising video before she
gets it in the mail. Its masturbatory fantasies go after the
``American Pie'' set with jokes about anal probes, sperm banks, a
wacko roommate who has a white-mouse moment, and a French-toast gag
that will put you off breakfast for days. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! ``Small Time Crooks'' Woody Allen is in a comfortable comic
groove as an ex-con dishwasher who strikes it rich when his wife's
cookie shop, fronting his latest larcenous scheme, becomes a wild
success in its own right. Allen has all he can do to avoid being
eclipsed by Tracey Ullman, as the stripper turned manicurist turned
cookie mogul, and by Elaine May, who's no less hilarious as her
dim-bulb cousin. (PG)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
