<HEADER>
A2460 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MONEY-GRADS-BOS &LR;      05-22 1573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-GRADS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE GRADUATES NEED ADVICE ON HANDLING MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT BERNARD NELSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It doesn't take long for reality to edge out revelry in
the minds of new college graduates.
</P>
<P>
   Before the mortarboard and gown are packed away, decisions have
to be made about where to live and work, what to drive, and how to
pay for it on a graduate's piddling starting salary. Within a few
months, coupon clipping replaces bar hopping.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's how it used to work.
</P>
<P>
   Things look different for the class of 2000. Many of this year's
grads have another problem entirely: what to do with all their
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an insignificant question,'' said Mark Podolsky,
president of the Financial Planning Association of Massachusetts.
``In today's world, grads need to understand that decisions they
make right off the bat can have quite an impact later in life.''
</P>
<P>
   What everyone understands is that the hot economy and lack of
available workers make the landscape for this generation of
graduates different from any before it.
</P>
<P>
   Average starting salaries reported by this year's graduating
class are as much as 12 percent higher than those of a year ago,
according to an April survey by the National Association of
Colleges and Employers. Inflation has risen 3 percent over the same
period, and workers' wages overall have gained 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Those gains put new work-force entrants at pay scales their
parents didn't see for decades, if ever. Many graduates, especially
in high-tech fields, will garner a starting salary of $50,000 or
more this year _ on top of a $5,000 to $10,000 signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   The good times extend beyond Web design and computer science _
and beyond elite schools such as Harvard and MIT. Even liberal arts
majors from small colleges are seeing their worth rise, thanks to
the labor shortage in many fields.
</P>
<P>
   There have been similar wage hikes every year since 1993. Over
the past seven hiring seasons, starting salaries have jumped almost
60 percent for computer science majors and almost 40 percent for
those in electrical engineering, according to the association of
colleges and employers.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer prices, meanwhile, are 19 percent higher than they were
in spring 1993, according to the Bureau of Labor Statistics. And
incomes for all workers are roughly 30 percent higher, the American
Compensation Association estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ``A decade ago, students had to chase after recruiters for
interviews,'' said Dom DeLeo, director of the career center at
Boston College. ``These days, as often as not, it's the recruiters
working to make themselves attractive to the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Camille Luckenbaugh, director of the National Association
of Colleges and Employers salary survey, ``Everyone is benefiting,
even majors you wouldn't associate with the new economy. The past
three years have marked the . . . best time to come out of college
that I know of.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd Myatt, who graduated Friday from Babson College in
Wellesley, knows about the recruiting frenzy firsthand.
</P>
<P>
   The 22-year-old from Salem, N.H., who acknowledges he got his
degree in management and management information systems ``without
the highest GPA in school,'' said he was bowled over when virtually
every company he chatted up at fall job fairs wanted to interview
him. Another called Myatt after a chance encounter with one of the
firm's executives on the MBTA.
</P>
<P>
   He narrowed his choices to a trio of high-tech companies. By
early January, he had offers from all three that included starting
salaries approaching $50,000, stock options, tuition reimbursement,
and other perks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely wasn't trying to play one company against
another, but the recruiters kept calling and asking if there was
anything they could do'' to influence my decision, Myatt said.
``They were really good offers, and I'm still amazed they were all
coming after me.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he accepted a job as a consultant at Boston-based
Zefer Corp., the company whose executive he had met on the train.
</P>
<P>
   Myatt won't be rich overnight, but he is making more money and
earning more stock options than he thought possible even a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all pretty unexpected,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not all graduates are surprised by the process, though.
</P>
<P>
   Brandeis University senior Daniel Lieberman, who graduated
Saturday, said he expected to find a job without too much trouble.
But he was still thrilled when his two top picks came through with
offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not many places do the kind of work I'm interested in,'' said
Lieberman, a 21-year-old New Yorker who majored in economics with a
focus on environmental studies. ``I was worried about finding a job
that I really wanted to do, that I liked.''
</P>
<P>
   That didn't turn out to be a problem. Two months after he sent
out his first resume, Lieberman landed a $35,000 job ``with really,
really great benefits'' as an environmental researcher at ICF
Consulting in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But Lieberman acknowledges that the new economy doesn't treat
all majors equally.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who had studied economics, like me, did pretty well,''
he said. ``A lot of other people I know in the social sciences or
humanities are still looking.''
</P>
<P>
   That's hardly news to Sara Ramsey, who graduated from Simmons
College with a degree in communications. Ramsey knows she would
have fared better with a business or high-tech focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a friend who double-majored in communications and
computer science, and she landed a great job paying $49,500 plus a
signing bonus,'' she said. ``The rest of us are wondering whether
we should have done the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Ramsey is not too concerned about finding a job. And she
knows that when she does, it'll probably pay more than the liberal
arts grads of yesteryear first earned.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring there were plenty of positions to be had, she focused
on academics rather than an intense job search during the school
year. This summer, she will earn $10 to $15 an hour doing marketing
work at Pangaea Multimedia in Cambridge, Mass., where she interned
during the spring semester.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the market is right now, jobs are popping up here and
there,'' said the 22-year-old Maine native. ``I'll find something
by the end of the summer and, if I don't like it, I always have the
option to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Deciding how to handle good fortune is an enviable problem, said
Beth Kobliner, author of ``Get a Financial Life: Personal Finance
in Your Twenties and Thirties.'' But it's still a problem, she
said, especially in a world that forces an increasing amount of
financial self-responsibility on young workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost a cliche at this point, but you're entirely on
your own when it comes to saving for retirement and taking care of
your long-term financial security,'' Kobliner said. ``And the scary
part is that you can't make up for this time if you miss it.''
</P>
<P>
   Graduates seem to be getting the message.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Iowa State University survey found that half of college
students start worrying about their finances before they graduate.
Among people ages 20 to 39, the survey found 87 percent fretting
over money.
</P>
<P>
   Podolsky, of the Financial Planning Association, and president
of Financial Solutions Associates in Dedham, said the key for new
graduates is assessing their financial priorities and how to
address them. They can't just use their parents or grandparents as
models, either.
</P>
<P>
   Graduates ``have different issues and different time frames at
that age,'' Podolsky said. ``It really is a unique time,
financially speaking.''
</P>
<P>
   The first thing to address, Podolsky, Kobliner, and others
agree, is how to use an employer's benefits package. Some benefits
are limited or unavailable if you don't sign up for them at the
start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stock options are great, but realize that they won't
necessarily pan out,'' Kobliner said. ``Just in case they don't
make you filthy rich, make sure you cover the basics through other
benefits,'' including disability insurance and a 401(k) plan.
</P>
<P>
   But you also need to do some things on your own, said Debra
Neiman, a certified financial planner with the Neiman-Maloy
Financial Group in Wakefield.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not `politically correct' for grads who feel flush to
talk about budgeting, but it's critical that they learn to live
within their means,'' Neiman said. ``Call it a spending plan, if
you have to, but do it.''
</P>
<P>
   She recommends financial software, such as Quicken or Microsoft
Money. Such products combine the discipline of a budget with the
flexibility and high-tech appeal of a computer program.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you come out with a relatively high starting salary,
you'll probably think the sky's the limit,'' Neiman said. ``At
least putting numbers into the software or on paper forces you to
see the limitations and tradeoffs associated with your decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, financial professionals agree, is to do all
things in moderation. No matter how moneyed you feel as a new
graduate with a healthy salary, avoid the temptation to rush out
and buy the flashiest car or rent the ritziest apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``As crazy as it sounds right now, buy a Toyota instead of a
Lexus and live in Allston instead of Beacon Hill,'' Podolsky said.
``Invest the rest, so you can take advantage of this super
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't, you'll regret it when you're older.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 1529EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
