<HEADLINE>
$90,000 INHERITANCE CAN MAKE RETIREMENT COMFORTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Q. We will be inheriting $90,000 and are interested in Roth
IRAs and mutual funds. We feel we can add $12,000 a year to our
retirement savings over the next 20 to 25 years. What is our
retirement outlook?
</P>
<P>
   K.B., Arlington, Texas &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; A. If you devote the entire inheritance to your retirement
accounts, you would be in marginal shape to retire after 20 years,
and in solid shape in 25 years. If you don't devote the inheritance
to retirement savings, you certainly would have to wait 25 years
before retiring.
</P>
<P>
   If you add the $90,000 to retirement savings and add $1,000 a
month for 25 years, you would have an accumulation of $1,671,630
after 20 years, presuming 10 percent average annual investment
returns. The pool would grow to $2,827,324 after 25 years. But if
you fall prey to the many other attractions that $90,000 can buy,
your retirement accounts (including the taxable holding in Janus
Worldwide) would amount to only $1,012,107 after 20 years, and
$1,8742,379 after 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   So what's so shabby about $1 million plus? Consider the
ever-present bugbear of retirees: inflation. In 20 years, you will
need $159,183 to buy what $80,000 buys today if inflation averages
3.5 percent annually; the figure would be $189,059 after 25 years.
Even if you presume that you can live in retirement on 65 percent
of your current income, you would still need $103,469 after 20
years and $122,888 after 25 years to support a standard of living
equivalent to what $52,000 a year buys today.
</P>
<P>
   So, suddenly that $1 million doesn't loom so large.
</P>
<P>
   My suggestion is to put the inheritance in a stock mutual fund,
then withdraw $4,000 a year to fully fund Roth IRAs for both
yourself and your wife. After 25 years, you could expect to have
$683,774 in your taxable accounts, $441,719 in the tax-free Roth
IRAs, and $1,701,995 in the tax-deferred 403(b), a nice balance
that would allow you to manage your tax liabilities well.
</P>
<P>
   As for investments, I'd suggest putting $50,000 of the
inheritance in a fund such as Vanguard Index 500 or USAA S&AMP;P 500,
and $10,000 each in funds such as Vanguard Mid-Cap Index, Vanguard
Small-Cap Index, Vanguard Health Care, and USAA Science and
Technology. When you move money from the taxable fund accounts to
the Roth IRAs, you can simply move to the same funds but with a
different tax status.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I will leave the Navy in June and start working toward a
graduate degree in journalism. The two-year program will cost
$41,000 after a small fellowship; I might be able to earn an
additional $2,600 a year as a teaching assistant. I am not eligible
for need-based financial aid but can take student loans. I am
considering putting the savings account money in a CD or money
market fund and taking student loans to avoid dipping into stock
funds.
</P>
<P>
   D.D., San Diego, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. So you've heard journalism isn't a racket with fancy
salaries, and you figure you had better hang onto that $66,926 you
saved? A pretty good idea _ especially if the student loans are the
type that accrue interest only after you complete your studies.
Taking the loans gives you the option of paying them off two years
hence, just at the point that you would have to begin paying
interest.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, with any luck, your portfolio should have achieved
some gains. You should also be in a position to figure out your
likely budget once you begin working, and to decide whether you
will be able to bear the cost of the loans from your earnings, and
thus allow your stock funds to remain in your portfolio. Either
way, you'd have had a two-year interest-free loan.
</P>
<P>
   If you adopt that strategy, though, I'd suggest you move to a
less aggressive fund than PBHG Emerging Growth fund, which holds a
pretty risky portfolio. If you encounter a couple of tough years
with this fund while you are in graduate school, you could find
your options might not be as attractive upon graduation. Even with
the American Century Ultra fund, you would have the risk that your
returns over those two years would be negative, but I would view
that as a smaller risk.
</P>
<P>
   You could, of course, decide to park the money in the stock
funds in CDs or money markets during those two years, but you would
also doubtless pay an unpleasant tax bill if you did that. I'd be
comfortable if you decided to move from PBHG Emerging Growth to one
of the many Standard and Poor's Index 500 funds, which would at
least somewhat reduce the chance that a sizable part of your stock
savings might evaporate while you are cracking the books.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Ours is a single-income family, and I woke up about a year
ago and realized I was not putting nearly enough aside for
retirement and was not being aggressive enough with my 401(k)
investments. At the time, I had 80 percent of my money in a stable
value fund, and 10 percent each in Vanguard Institutional Index 500
and Vanguard Primecap. I contribute $450 a month to the 401(k) and
my employer matches with $160. Would you say the moves I have made
are too aggressive or not aggressive enough, and what more do I
need to do to be able to retire at 59 1/2?
</P>
<P>
   D.H., Beaumont, Texas &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Unless you make some pretty dramatic changes, retirement at
59 1/2 seems pretty problematical. If you save at the current rate
for 13 1/2 years and achieve average annual investment returns of
10 percent, you would accumulate $489,435, which will be nowhere
close to enough to support you in retirement, even at a somewhat
reduced standard of living.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, you are saving a little more than 8.5 percent of your
earnings, a respectable rate for a person who starts saving early
and invests well. I think you were right to change your 401(k)
allocations, but because you've probably been saving for only about
10 years and have had low investment returns for most of that
period, you need to catch up. I don't know enough about your costs
to suggest how much you might be able to add to your savings, but I
do suggest you try to save more.
</P>
<P>
   Also, move the credit union IRA to a more aggressive investment.
I'd move the entire account to the Vanguard Health Care fund, and
try to supplement the account with ongoing contributions. (But if
you have not reached the maximum for your potential employer match
to contributions to your 401(k), you should favor investments there
until you get to the maximum match.)
</P>
<P>
   You are not being too aggressive or too tame in your investment
choicess. You have a good mix. What you need is not better
investments, but to save more or retire later.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
______ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A last-minute prediction: Next weekend at the latest, Vanguard's
Index 500 fund will probably take over from Fidelity Magellan as
the world's largest mutual fund. Although Index 500 had been
creeping up on Magellan in terms of assets under management in
recent years, its ascendancy just became a matter of time when
Magellan closed to new investors. Entering last week, Index 500 was
just $193 million behind Magellan, whose assets stood at $104,799
million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, Box 2378,
Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
