<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 15:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2466 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MONEY-TRAUSCH-BOS &LR;      05-22 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-TRAUSCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME BOMBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN TRAUSCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; It's not about money. It's about time. One seems to be
devouring the other. The times are good, sure, but time? Forget it.
We are temporal paupers in this economy that is roaring like a
hungry lion and swallowing the clock whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need a vacation,'' we groan in the deepening Sunday twilight
of another pathetically short and overprogrammed weekend. How can
it be Monday morning again? Didn't we just do that? Nobody leaves
the house until we find Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The ``downsize now'' gurus pontificate about simplicity from the
radio, TV, and bookstore windows. Yet another beatific author is
being interviewed about the joys of blowing the whistle on stress
and making cookies with the kids.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right. But who's got time to look for the whistle in this
mess? Pass the Oreos, kid, and pour your own milk.
</P>
<P>
   Connie Glaser understands.
</P>
<P>
   She's an imperfect guru, in town to speak at a recent Simmons
College executive women's conference. She lets her hair flop at the
end of a long humid day. When she reaches into her purse for press
information and discovers she brought the wrong bag down from her
hotel room, she shrugs and laughs. She doesn't have all the
answers, but she does have two teenage sons and so juggles her
lecture and consulting schedule to spend no more than one or two
nights in a row away from her home in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   She's the coauthor of ``When Money Isn't Enough: How Women Are
Finding the Soul of Success,'' written with Barbara Smalley _ a
book that could easily be about men, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Increments,'' she says to the interviewer, who is frazzled
from a slow ride in Boston's Friday traffic and pressing the guru
for the secret formula that will defuse the time bomb. ``It starts
with recognizing stress.''
</P>
<P>
   No problem. But then what? And how long does it take to reach
nirvana in rush hour?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like you ever get there,'' she says. ``It's a
process. You can't stay sedentary in life. It's about choices,
always about redefining success and making choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Her book is full of people who walked out of the executive suite
to a home business, or who decided to ``plateau'' on a comfortable
career ladder rung and not climb anymore, or who went back to the
old job when the impressive promotion fried the brain and soul.
</P>
<P>
   Inspirations all, but a reader wants to hear more about that
first step _ the second step, really, after recognizing stress. How
does a person break through the inertia of success and start fixing
what, by most standards, is working beautifully?
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to figure out what you want,'' Glaser says. Never as
easy as it sounds, and a career coach or counselor can help. ``You
start with baby steps. Maybe you work at home a couple mornings a
week. Then you might look at job sharing, flex time, a part-time
position, or a leave of absence.''
</P>
<P>
   The boss won't laugh either, she says. The economy that's
creating those high-powered jobs and the attendant stress is also
creating a shortage of workers. So companies are scrambling to hang
on to good people.
</P>
<P>
   She knows a partner of a top accounting firm who is working part
time. Companies offer concierge services, laundry and dry cleaning
shops, minisupermarkets in the cafeteria, day care, some on-site
schooling, and a lactation room for nursing mothers. ``Unheard of a
few years ago,'' she says. ``Time is the currency of the new
millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   Her book is the outgrowth of two earlier volumes on women in the
workplace, also written with Smalley _ one on communication called
``More Power to You,'' and one on surviving in the macho corporate
culture, titled ``Swim With The Dolphins.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Women tell me they're more successful than they ever thought
they'd be, but that something is missing,'' notes Glaser. ``They
say, `This is why I made all those sacrifices _ Hello?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The book focuses on women because they still often have primary
responsibility for children and home, and ``the issue of balance is
more in their face.''
</P>
<P>
   But she says the quest for time ``is much more than a woman's
midlife crisis. There's a shift in perception about what work is.
Our parents' generation were willing to work for the paycheck. Now
people want more.''
</P>
<P>
   Or less.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Susan Trausch is a member of the Globe staff. She can be reached
by e-mail at trausch(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
