<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 15:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2468 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-HILTON-BOS &LR;      05-22 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-HILTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ECHOING MOMENTS OF A FADING TIBET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE SEARCH FOR THE PANCHEN LAMA 
By Isabel Hilton. Norton. 336 pp. Illustrated. $25.95. 
 
VIRTUAL TIBET 
Searching for Shangri-La from the Himalayas to Hollywood 
By Orville Schell. Metropolitan. 340 pp. $26. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Traveling in Tibet two years ago, I chanced upon the summer
palace built by the Chinese for the 10th Panchen Lama in Shigatse
in the 1950s. It was a cavernous place, shuttered and rarely
visited. But one upstairs room was comfortably furnished, and on a
shelf were a half-dozen children's toys _ an airplane, a car, a few
stuffed animals.
</P>
<P>
   I motioned to the elderly monk who was leading us around. ``They
are here for him when he comes,'' he said, smiling _ meaning the
little boy the Chinese government had then recognized as the
reincarnation of the 10th Panchen Lama.
</P>
<P>
   Several years before that, while in Dharamsala to interview the
Dalai Lama for the BBC, journalist Isabel Hilton ``became gripped''
by the hints she picked up about the reincarnation search that was
then underway, five years after the death of the 10th Panchen Lama.
</P>
<P>
   Over the following year, as one child was recognized as the 11th
Panchen Lama by the Dalai Lama, then supplanted by a second boy
chosen by the Chinese government _ the little boy of the toys _
Hilton's unusual access to the Dalai Lama involved her to the point
where she became an accomplice in his efforts to have his chosen
boy recognized by Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   It is to Hilton's credit that she has not let her role
overshadow the drama and significance of the story of the search
itself. And she has surrounded that account with a rich, even
entertaining, account of Tibetan history and religion focused on
the traditional role of the Panchen Lama as the spiritual
counterpart to the Dalai Lama as political leader.
</P>
<P>
   Overshadowed in the West by the extraordinary appeal of the
present (14th) Dalai Lama, the 10th Panchen Lama emerges in
Hilton's account as a tragic and sympathetic figure who supported
needed social and political reforms but fell victim to the turmoil
of Maoist China.
</P>
<P>
   In the present situation, the Buddhist belief in reincarnation
has great political significance because after the death of either
the Dalai Lama or the Panchen Lama, the other must recognize his
reincarnation. The implications of the search for a reincarnated
Panchen Lama, writes Hilton, were thus ``clear to a regime in
Beijing which had spent decades seeking the key to the pacification
of Tibet.'' For if the newly reincarnated Panchen Lama was under
Beijing's control, then acting through him, Beijing could control
the selection of a 15th Dalai Lama when that time should come.
</P>
<P>
   (The value of this strategy, of course, seems diminished after
the flight earlier this year to India of the Karmapa, the
14-year-old lama who was the leading religious figure still in
Tibet and was widely believed to be loyal to Beijing.)
</P>
<P>
   As for the search, Hilton's account is as close to being an
``authorized version'' as there is likely to be, and is supported
by details that could only be known to an insider. One that neatly
captures the shifting line between the sacred and the profane in
contemporary Tibet concerns the visit by senior lamas to the sacred
Lhamo Latso lake in October 1994, as the search was in its final
stages.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing ceremonial cloaks and reciting mantras, they sat on a
high ridge above the lake, looking for some sign in the water to
help them identify the reincarnated Panchen Lama, Hilton writes.
``They held bells and dorjes of tantric ritual, and from time to
time picked up a pair of binoculars to scan the surface. Behind
them, serving monks made tea and prepared food, while one filmed
the ceremony on a video camera.''
</P>
<P>
   Hilton's role in all this was to enable the Dalai Lama to
identify _ on camera _ his chosen child and convey the name to the
leader of the search inside Tibet, who would then conclude the
search so as to win Beijing's unwitting approval of the Dalai
Lama's choice. This ``innocent subterfuge'' fell apart when the
Dalai Lama announced the choice prematurely. The Chinese reacted by
scooping up the chosen boy _ his present whereabouts are unknown _
and anointing their own choice.
</P>
<P>
   The Tibet of which Hilton writes _ binoculars and video camera
aside _ is a Tibet closer to medieval Europe, with its ``close
association'' of the spiritual and the temporal, than ``a kind of
religious Disneyland.'' That land of Western imagination is the
``Virtual Tibet'' chronicled by China scholar Orville Schell, whose
insider's view of the filming of ``Seven Years in Tibet'' is a
mirror image of Hilton's view of the search for the Panchen Lama.
</P>
<P>
   It's a lively and vastly entertaining account in which Tibetan
monks transplanted to a mock-up Lhasa in the mountains of Argentina
mingle with a Hollywood film crew with everything focused on a
single mythic figure _ except that it's actor Brad Pitt, not the
Dalai Lama.
</P>
<P>
   But as Schell notes, the Tibet of tradition is likely to survive
only as a ``virtual Tibet'' because ``so many vestiges of
`mysterious' (or, in Chinese parlance, `feudal') Tibet have been
expunged from the face of that occupied land.''
</P>
<P>
   This same sense of what is disappearing comes through when
Hilton adds to a discussion of a future search for the
reincarnation of the present Dalai Lama the caveat, ``if, indeed,
there will be a 15th Dalai Lama.'' It may well be that Hilton has
seen _ and participated in _ one of the final moments of a lost
Tibet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 1535EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
