<DOCNO> NYT20000522.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2469 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-FRIEDMAN-BOS &LR;      05-22 1258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-FRIEDMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVE OVER, LA COSA NOSTRA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DICK LEHR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
RED MAFIYA 
How the Russian Mob Has Invaded America 
By Robert I. Friedman. Little, Brown. 296 pp. $25.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Friedman, you are a bad man, a liar!''
</P>
<P>
   That's the reception freelance journalist Robert I. Friedman
received when he arrived unannounced two years ago at the home of a
Russian mobster living outside Denver. The crime boss, posing as a
businessman, wanted nothing to do with Friedman's request to talk
about the Red Mafiya's explosive growth in the United States. He
slammed the door in the writer's face.
</P>
<P>
   In the decade that Friedman has been tracking the Russian mob,
he has faced far worse. There was the death threat he received from
one of the most powerful Russian mobsters in this country,
Vyacheslav Kirillovich Ivankov. The Valentine's Day card that
Ivankov mailed Friedman was certainly heartfelt: It contained a
passionate promise to torture and kill the writer, as Friedman
recounts it.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman has had to go into hiding at times, and he came to
possess a bulletproof vest in the course of his reporting on the
new, big thing in the nation's underworld, the Russian mob. He's
out there, occupying a no man's land of sorts _ ahead of most of
the nation's mainstream press in covering the Russians and even
ahead of much of law enforcement, particularly the FBI. The new
mobsters came of age in a lawless Russia and now do business here
with little regard for the customs that have long defined the
playing field for the cops, the mobsters, and the journalists who
cover both.
</P>
<P>
   ``We Italians will kill you,'' Friedman writes, quoting from a
government wiretap of a conversation between a John Gotti associate
and another Italian underworld figure. ``But the Russians are crazy
_ they'll kill your whole family.'' Friedman says a retired New
York City policeman warned him the Russian mobsters will ``shoot
you just to see if their gun works.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedman's new book, ``Red Mafiya: How the Russian Mob Has
Invaded America,'' is the culmination of his groundbreaking work to
date, parts of which have appeared in articles in the magazines New
York, Vanity Fair, and Details, and in The Village Voice. Mixing in
his own experiences trying to uncover the story, Friedman provides
a lucid and important overview of the Red Mafiya's US expansion
from its original beachhead in the Brooklyn neighborhood of
Brighton Beach. ``In North America alone,'' he writes, ``there are
now thirty Russian crime syndicates operating in at least seventeen
US cities, most notably New York, Miami, San Francisco, Los Angeles
and Denver.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Mafiya, Friedman has found, does it all, and does it
well. Extortion, drugs, murder, money laundering that has ensnared
some of the largest US banks, and even international arms deals
involving submarines, helicopters, and other weapons plundered from
the former Soviet Union's military arsenals.
</P>
<P>
   Hockey fans also need to take note. Friedman describes Russian
mobsters shaking down some of the Russian-born hockey stars now
playing in the National Hockey League. ``Alexander Mogilny of the
Vancouver Canucks, Alexei Zhitnik of the Buffalo Sabres, and
Vladimir Malakhov of the Montreal Canadiens have all been targets
of extortion. Even Detroit Red Wings superstar Sergei Federov was
rumored to have had to pay gangsters to be left alone when he first
came to America.''
</P>
<P>
   The book documents how a number of players maintain close ties
to several of the Russian crime bosses operating here and, most
troubling, how the NHL brass has largely turned a blind eye to the
risk this poses to the game's integrity. ``The real question is why
the NHL tolerates its presence,'' says Friedman. For anyone who
cares about the game, the disclosures are shocking and deeply
troubling.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, an important theme of Friedman's work is the slow
reaction to the growing menace displayed not only by the NHL but by
just about every sector of society _ the politicians, the press,
the public and, perhaps most important, law enforcement. The FBI,
addicted to the Italian La Cosa Nostra, has been slow to respond to
the Russian mob. ``If not for its (the FBI's) own sluggishness in
addressing the problem, the Russian mob in the United States would
never had become as powerful as it is today,'' Friedman says.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the FBI's stubborn fixation with La Cosa Nostra,
Friedman cites a second critical reason for law enforcement's delay
_ Jewish politics. ``Because the Russian mob was mostly Jewish, it
was a political hot potato, especially in the New York area, where
the vast majority of refugees were being resettled by Jewish
welfare agencies.''
</P>
<P>
   By far, the strength of this book is its reporting. Friedman
explains the influx of Russian mobsters, which accelerated after
the breakup of the Soviet Union, actually began in the early 1970s,
``when Soviet leader Leonid Brezhnev had agreed to allow the
limited emigration of Soviet Jews, (and) thousands of hard-core
criminals, many of them released from the Soviet Gulags by the KGB,
took advantage of their nominal Jewish status to swarm into the
United States.'' He first got onto the story a decade ago while
reporting on the Italian Mafia and, ``I was introduced by a
Genovese organized crime family source in New York to several of
his Russian criminal colleagues, a meeting that opened a door to me
into this little-known, nearly impenetrable ethnic underworld.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the book is organized as a kind of rogues' gallery _ set
pieces on key Russians, such as Ivankov, the boss who Friedman says
threatened to kill him, or the gangster ``Tarzan'' (Ludwig
Fainberg) who operated mainly out of a Miami strip joint, Porky's.
Each piece tends to unfold similarly: The figure is introduced in
his US locale, then his Russian roots are explored and, finally,
the narrative returns to present criminal activity. I would have
preferred a bit more variation; as strange as it may sound given
their frightening lawlessness, the gangsters began to run together.
(Too often, for example, a new mob figure is introduced as ``one of
the most feared.'') It is clear that in the past decade there have
been several successful prosecutions of Russian mobsters, and
perhaps the book's flow would have benefited by switching to the
point of view of one of the investigators and going deep inside the
probe.
</P>
<P>
   I also wish Friedman had included notes on each chapter. To his
credit, he has won the confidence of many investigators and
underworld figures and obtained reams of classified documents. But
I often found myself wanting to know more about a particular
investigation, information as basic as a case's docket number. It's
the staple of back-of-the-book notes; unfortunately, there are none
here.
</P>
<P>
   But these are nit-picks. This is gumshoe reporting at its best.
Friedman has succeeded reportorially in ways writers about
organized crime usually don't: namely, obtaining many face-to-face
interviews with the actual crime figures. And he's done it all
while flying virtually solo, without the powerful institutional
backing journalists working for the top newspapers can expect.
Ivankov has threatened him, another gangster sued him for libel,
and another tried to bribe him. Fending off the bids to silence him
are apparently part of the turf that comes with exposing the Red
Mafiya, ``a brutal, innovative, multi-billion-dollar-a-year
criminal enterprise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
