<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2474 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-POLITICS-BOOKS-1100(2     05-22 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICS-BOOKS-1100(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE AGAIN THE CAMPAIGN TRAIL LEADS TO THE BOOKSTORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Campaign 2000 books began arriving even before many
candidates had officially started running. Some 12 months ago we
got our first spate of so-called ``definitive'' biographies of the
candidates, including one wild, soon-discredited George W. Bush
tome by an ex-con. John McCain got the jump on would-be chroniclers
by putting out a well-received memoir; Bush put out a
not-so-well-received autobiography himself.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the second wave. This time around we get
quasi-objective commentary in the form of biography (''Inventing Al
Gore,'' by Bill Turque), essays (''The Case Against Hillary
Clinton,'' by former Reagan speechwriter Peggy Noonan), and
sharp-edged fiction (''The Running Mate,'' by Joe Klein). Each
approach is clearly intended to sway reader-voters, though Turque
and Klein would probably argue they're trying to play everything
down the middle. Noonan is openly trying to convince Americans in
general, and New Yorkers in particular, that it's time to bid
Hillary and Bill farewell.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Inventing Al Gore,'' Turque, a longtime Washington
correspondent for Newsweek, revisits old scandals and suggests some
new ones. Far from being the well-rounded son of caring parents,
Vice President Gore was, Turque suggests, molded for a successful
political future by an ambitious mother and father (himself a U.S.
senator). When Albert Gore Sr. lost his last Senate election in
Tennessee because voters there perceived him as too liberal, mostly
on Vietnam, son Al took the lesson to heart and determined he would
avoid controversial positions when possible.
</P>
<P>
   (This was certainly not true regarding environmental issues. In
his book ``Earth in the Balance,'' Gore wrote, ``The voice of
caution whispers persuasively in the ear of every politician, often
with good reason. ... The integrity of the environment is not just
another issue to be used in political games ... and the time has
come to take more political risks _ and endure much more political
criticism _ by proposing tougher, more effective solutions and
fighting hard for their enactment.'')
</P>
<P>
   Turque makes a strong case that powerful Albert Gore Sr. eased
his only son's upwardly mobile path _ first by gaining him cushy
duty during the Vietnam conflict (Al Jr. was unaware of this,
Turque notes) and, later, giving him a necessary financial base for
a political career by cutting the then-twentysomething in on
lucrative land deals.
</P>
<P>
   From there, the son made his own cautious way, heading off drug
accusations by admitting he inhaled, though not often (Turque
thinks Gore puffed a lot more than he publicly lets on) and molding
himself into the sort of conservative Democratic candidate
Tennessee voters eventually sent to the House of Representatives,
then the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Turque devastates Gore by contrasting many of his public
comments with his private actions _ any Republicans who believe
Molly Ivins was too tough on George W. Bush in ``Shrub'' ought to
read ``Inventing Al Gore.'' Without resorting to hyperbole, simply
by quoting Gore and then examining records, Turque skewers the vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding Gore's 1996 public lambasting of the tobacco industry
_ and his tearful invoking of the 1984 death of his sister, Nancy,
from lung cancer _ Turque notes that ``seven years after Nancy's
death, (Gore) continued to take contributions from cigarette
manufacturers and grew tobacco on his farm.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch!
</P>
<P>
   In all, Turque concludes, Al Gore is ``a man who at critical
moments has proclaimed independence and then retreated from it,
stood on principle and then deferred it to political ambition.''
Far from inventing the Internet, the Al Gore presented to readers
by Bill Turque has continually re-invented himself to suit
prevailing political winds. Especially because Turque has presented
his themes so objectively, based on facts rather than innuendo,
it's a chilling picture, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Equally scary is Peggy Noonan's ``The Case Against Hillary
Clinton,'' but for a much different reason. No one would expect
arch-conservative Noonan to write a book praising the first lady
and senator-wanna-be, and she hasn't. We assume that Noonan, the
writer who crafted many of Ronald Reagan's speeches, will be quite
persuasive presenting an anti-Hillary case, and she is:
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton ``does not seem as big as the emotions she
engenders ... to me she seems more like an odd thing that happened
to us, a person of average insights, above-average intelligence,
and below-average character who somehow has come to fasten our
gaze.''
</P>
<P>
   On page after page, Noonan effectively eviscerates her subject.
Hannibal Lecter never carved a victim more completely than Noonan
slices and dices Hillary Clinton. Every reported scandal is
reiterated, and every Clinton response delineated:
</P>
<P>
   ``With a consistency that would be called heroic if it were
applied to a high purpose, she will keep her smile on, hug
children, speak in airy phrases no one could disagree with (`Our
children are our future'), stick to the script, and try very hard
not to answer questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Noonan blows it _ monumentally.
</P>
<P>
   Around the middle of her 181-page book, Noonan describes
``something you probably do not know about, something (Hillary) did
that astonished me because it really did take nerve.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   A few months after the Columbine school shootings, Noonan
reports, Hillary Clinton met secretly with all the top TV and film
industry moguls ``at the beautiful hillside home of Michael Eisner,
the famous CEO of Disney.'' There, Noonan relates, Clinton
castigated the bigwigs for producing material that not only
depicted but somehow encouraged violence, and warned them frankly
that unless they mended their ways she would openly oppose them,
even though she and husband Bill had always counted on their deep
pockets for campaign support.
</P>
<P>
   ``If nothing changes I'll try to make your lives difficult,''
Clinton declares. ``I'll lead the charge; I'll lead a boycott, and
this one you'll feel. Because if I turn on you, it's like Nixon to
China: People will notice.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Noonan admits the reason we wouldn't know about this
meeting is because there was no such meeting: ``It never happened,
and, really, it never will, because Hillary Clinton doesn't feel
she can put her country's needs before her need for campaign
money.''
</P>
<P>
   How unfortunate. Noonan had plenty of ammunition without having
to make more up. Even Edmund Morris' fictional additions to his
Reagan biography, ``Dutch,'' weren't this awful, since Morris was
trying to gild the Gipper legend, not destroy it. If Noonan wanted
to publish anti-Clinton fiction, she should have written a novel.
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, is what Joe Klein did in 1996 with ``Primary
Colors,'' a thinly-disguised depiction of Bill Clinton's rocky,
colorful presidential campaign of 1992. The book got most of its
attention because the author was listed as ``Anonymous.'' Media
types took plenty of guesses regarding his/her real identity _
surely it had to be a journalist covering the campaign, or perhaps
someone from the Clinton camp. Mandy Grunwald and George
Stephanopoulos were early favorites. Klein only 'fessed up when
writing experts pegged him as the prohibitive favorite. ``Primary
Colors'' became a bestseller, then a movie starring John Travolta.
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad so many people paid attention to who wrote the
book, rather than how he wrote it. ``Primary Colors'' really worked
because Klein _ currently a Washington correspondent for The New
Yorker _ was so masterful at providing small, telling details about
daily political life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Running Mate'' proves ``Primary Colors'' was no fluke.
Once again, Klein reveals the bone marrow of politics through
fiction _ though readers can, of course, spend happy moments
deciding who is based on whom.
</P>
<P>
   Protagonist Charlie Martin, a maimed Vietnam
veteran-turned-senator from an unnamed Midwestern state is, no
doubt, a mix of Nebraska's Bob Kerrey and Arizona's John McCain,
among others. Charlie, coming off a failed presidential try _
beaten in the Democratic primaries by Jack Stanton, the Clinton
doppelganger introduced by Klein in ``Primary Colors'' _ wants to
reorganize his staff, get an old pal a prominent position in the
Stanton administration, grow close to a just-discovered
illegitimate son, marry a New York businesswoman after too many
years as an eligible bachelor and, just maybe, have Stanton pick
him as running mate.
</P>
<P>
   This lengthy to-do list comes together as Charlie fights a
fraudulent claim of sexual assault (the alleged victim's father
decks the one-handed Charlie in front of the media), faces a Senate
challenge from a colorful conservative opponent and, in general,
has to decide whether he is first a human being or a politician,
since it is apparent, despite Charlie's best efforts, that it's
impossible to be both at the same time. (Of special note is Klein's
hilarious rendering of Charlie's inability to convince Stanton he
is vice-presidential material: ``... though Stanton was making a
visible effort not to pay attention, he was reading every tea leaf,
aware that Charlie was attempting the limited, qualified suck-up
route, and thinking less of him for that. Sucking up is an art; it
has to be effortless, seamless _ anything less than totally
convincing is a disaster.'')
</P>
<P>
   Charlie is, if anything, too dedicated to his job. His
character, and Klein's convoluted story, really pick up reader
interest as the author inserts priceless insights into the
necessary trivia of political life. Charlie shuffles the paintings
and sculpture in his Senate office every month to represent artwork
from different voter groups back home; he drives a Chrysler minivan
on campaign trips because the Chrysler plant in his state has 850
more workers than the Ford plant. These are the lines that
resonate, far more than Charlie's predictable attempt to run one
final, clean Senate race, and his equally predictable failure to do
so.
</P>
<P>
   A prophecy, here: Where, a generation ago, Teddy White's
magnificent nonfiction ``The Making of the President'' series
taught readers how American politics really worked, Klein's
``Primary Colors'' and ``The Running Mate'' will serve the same
purpose for current voters. As Jessamyn West observed, ``Fiction
reveals truths that reality obscures'' _ and ``The Running Mate''
is certainly among the best fiction published so far this year,
about politics or anything else.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Inventing Al Gore''
</P>
<P>
   By Bill Turque
</P>
<P>
   Political biography
</P>
<P>
   Houghton Mifflin, $25
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Case Against Hillary Clinton''
</P>
<P>
   By Peggy Noonan
</P>
<P>
   Political commentary
</P>
<P>
   HarperCollins, $24
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Running Mate''
</P>
<P>
   By Joe Klein, aka ``Anonymous''
</P>
<P>
   Political fiction
</P>
<P>
   The Dial Press, $26.95
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
