<SLUG> BC-SCI-FLOURESCENT-MOLECULE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BEACON INTO MOLECULAR WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Germany)   (The Science Times)  
 By KENNETH CHANG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A glowing point at the tip of an optical fiber could someday be
the torch that lights the world of DNA, proteins and other
molecules.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in the current issue of the journal Nature, researchers
at the University of Konstanz in Germany report that they have
created a microscope that uses a single fluorescent molecule as its
light source.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line of this idea,'' said Dr. Vahid Sandoghdar, a
physicist at the University of Konstanz and the paper's senior
author, ``is if you can bring our molecule to an arbitrarily close
distance, then we should get molecular resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   As microscopes using this light source are refined, they may
allow scientists to observe the receptors and channels at the
surface of a cell or how particles of light interact with
molecules.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fabulous,'' said Dr. Shimon Weiss, a staff scientist at
Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory in California. ``I definitely
think this is a breakthrough in optical imaging.''
</P>
<P>
   The new microscope is a variation of an earlier device known as
a near-field scanning optical microscope, where laser light passed
through a tiny metal pinhole at the end of an optical fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, optical microscopes cannot make out details smaller
than half the wavelength of light, or about one-100,000th of an
inch, a constraint known as the diffraction limit. One way to get
around the diffraction limit is to stick a tiny light source very
close to the sample. In that case the light beam does not have a
chance to spread, or diffract, and the resolution is limited by the
width of the light source instead of the wavelength of the light.
</P>
<P>
   This allows near-field scanning optical microscopes to make out
details as small as one-millionth of inch in width, but light
leakages through the edges of the pinhole prevented finer
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Sandoghdar and his collaborators have replaced the pinhole with
a crystal embedded with fluorescent molecules known as terrylene.
By adjusting the frequency of the laser beam shining down the
optical fiber, they can light up a single terrylene molecule. ``We
demonstrate it is possible to manipulate a single molecule and use
it as a light source,'' Sandoghdar said.
</P>
<P>
   The objects examined so far with the microscope are relative
behemoths _ triangular aluminum pyramids one-50,000th of an inch on
a side _ and the images are fuzzy compared with those taken by an
atomic force microscope, which measures the topology of a surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have done is a first demonstration,'' Sandoghdar said.
``We still have a lot of work to do to do this molecule
resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandoghdar's group still needs to figure out how to place the
fluorescent terrylene exactly at the tip of the crystal so that
they can place it right next to the object they are looking at.
</P>
<P>
   At present, the microscope also operates at minus 457 degrees
Fahrenheit, or 2.6 degrees above absolute zero. Most fluorescent
molecules stop working within a few minutes at room temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   These constraints will for now limit potential applications and
the number of scientists who will be able to use it. ``It's a tour
de force to get this,'' said Dr. Calvin F. Quate, a research
professor in electrical engineering at Stanford University, ``and I
don't think it will be as widespread as other probes are.''
</P>
<P>
   For this microscope to be of use to biologists, more stable
fluorescent molecules need to be found. ``If you don't have that,
you don't have your microscopy,'' Weiss said. ``You want this
flashlight to be on. The question is how far it can be pushed. Can
this or something like this be pushed to room temperature?''
</P>
<P>
   Even at the ultracold temperatures, the new microscope could be
used to see how photons scatter off molecules or shuffle between
two fluorescent molecules. ``You would be doing
nano-photochemistry,'' Sandoghdar said, ``how one molecule reacts
with another.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
