<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-PLAYBOY (Washington) _ The Supreme Court strikes down a
federal law designed to shield children from accidental exposure to
erotic cable programs that their parents have not chosen to
receive. In a 5-4 decision, which is a victory for Playboy
Enterprises Inc., the court agrees with the firm that the law was
too broad and violated the First Amendment rights of cable TV
viewers to receive explicit programs. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-POLLUTION (Washington) _ Taking up one of the biggest
environmental cases in years, the Supreme Court agrees to decide
whether the Environmental Protection Agency can drastically cut
smog and soot levels nationwide over the next decade. The court
will review a lower court's decision to block EPA rules designed to
cut air pollution by 10 percent. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE (Washington) _ With the House scheduled to vote this
week on normalizing trade relations with China, lawmakers weigh the
options in an issue that is both complicated and volatile. By GREG
McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CAMPAIGN (Washington) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush storms
the nation's capital, staging a high-profile campaign visit to
address the National Association of Realtors, the American Israel
Public Affairs Committee and a fund-raising reception. Bush also
plans a news conference here Tuesday. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   LAZIO-PROFILE (Washington) _ Rep. Rick Lazio, R-N.Y., who is
running for the U.S. Senate against Hillary Rodham Clinton, is a
moderate on gun control, abortion and the environment. But he also
pushed legislation that put a conservative imprint on the nation's
public housing system, winning favor with House Republican leaders.
We profile Lazio's seven years on Capitol Hill. By DAN FREDMAN and
JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   CONVENTION-CHIEF (Undated) _ Lydia Camarillo, an El Paso native
and former director of Southwest Voter Registration Project in San
Antonio, is chief executive of the upcoming Democratic National
Convention in Los Angeles. She is the first Hispanic to run a major
party convention. By LORI RODRIGUEZ.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SPACE-STATION (Houston) _ After completing repairs to the
exterior of the fledgling international space station, the crew of
the shuttle Atlantis prepares for 3 1/2 days of work on the
interior of the orbiting module. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-SHOOTING (Brownsville, Texas) _ U.S. officials say a
Border Patrol agent shot and killed a Mexican man who had just
crawled out of the brush after wading across the Rio Grande into
Texas. BY JAMES PINKERTON.
</P>
<P>
   RAILWAY KILLER (Houston) _ Testimony is under way in the
punishment phase of Angel Maturino Resendiz's capital murder trial.
The Mexican drifter, who has told the court he prefers execution to
life in prison, was convicted of killing a Houston physician and
has told the authorities that he killed eight people in other
states. By STEVE BREWER.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ To make the 2004 presidential
election more exciting and encourage broader voter participation, a
Republican panel proposes to tinker with the present front-loaded
primary system, which nobody likes very much. But the proposed
alternative and other ideas such as a national primary have their
own problems. Maybe it is not necessary to change. By MARIANNE
MEANS.
</P>
