<HEADER>
A2486 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT &LR;      05-22 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PREVENTION: For Children, a Safer Race to the Hospital
</P>
<P>
   For children who need medical attention at hospitals, the danger
may not end when they are placed in ambulances.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by researchers at Johns Hopkins Children's Center
found that it was not uncommon for patients and medical equipment
to be unsecured as ambulances sped to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The findings, part of an effort to improve ambulance safety,
were presented this month in Boston at a meeting of the Pediatric
Academic Societies and the American Academy of Pediatrics.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Nadine Levick, an emergency medical specialist at Johns
Hopkins, emphasized that the findings were not an indictment of
ambulance safety. The goal of the study, she said, was to assess
conditions in the typical ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   With that information in hand, a team of doctors and engineers,
supported by the federal government, intend to design tests,
complete with crash-test dummies, similar to those used to assess
the safety of passenger vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling is, anything we can do to make this a safer
environment is a plus,'' Levick said.
</P>
<P>
   Ambulances have a high crash rate per mile traveled, but the
crashes tend to be minor, Levick said.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, researchers observed 200 ambulance arrivals at an
unidentified urban hospital involving 206 patients and 636 other
occupants. The observers found that in 11 percent of the cases,
patients on gurneys were not strapped in at all. Ten percent
traveled on a parent's lap. And many types of emergency medical
service equipment were found to be either poorly secured or not
tied down at all.
</P>
<P>
   Rx MONEY: Save at One End, Spend at the Other
</P>
<P>
   Reducing medical costs has become a major goal in the age of
managed care, but a new study finds that can be trickier to
accomplish than it may seem.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main ways to reduce costs is by shortening as much as
possible the amount of time people are hospitalized. They are now
told to come in as close to surgery as possible, for example, and
discharged far earlier than was the practice in the past.
</P>
<P>
   When surgeons at the Boston University School of Medicine took a
look at the savings associated with the early discharge of patients
who had had heart bypass surgery, they found that in many cases the
medical costs were simply shifted elsewhere, including to nursing
services in the home or extended-care facilities. And in some
cases, when problems arose, the patients had to be quickly
readmitted to hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The findings were presented earlier this month by Dr. Harold
Lazar, a cardiothoracic surgeon, at a meeting of the American
Association for Thoracic Surgery.
</P>
<P>
   According to the university, researchers compared bypass
patients from 1990 with those from 1998, when patients spent an
average of 3.8 fewer days in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   HAZARDS: When Magnets Make a Heart Go Bonkers
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Thomas A. Mattioni treats patients for heart disease, so he
takes no position on whether the alternative-medical practice of
sleeping on magnets has any effect on arthritis or other joint
diseases.
</P>
<P>
   But Mattioni does have a warning for those using the magnets who
also have implantable pacemakers or similar devices called
cardioverter defibrillator: be careful. The magnets, usually placed
in mattress pads, can change the settings on the pacemakers and
turn off the defibrillators _ with potentially fatal results.
</P>
<P>
   Mattioni, director of electrophysiology at the Arizona Heart
Institute in Phoenix, presented his findings at a conference this
month of the North American Society of Pacing and
Electrophysiology.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, he said he had known nothing about the use of
the magnets until several patients asked him about them. Mattioni
and colleagues then began ordering the products on the Internet and
trying to gauge their effect.
</P>
<P>
   The magnets are placed not just in mattress pads but worn around
the arms, legs and waist. The researchers found that as long as the
magnets were kept six or more inches from the heart devices _
usually implanted in the upper arm _ there was no problem. So for
people who use wearable forms of the magnets, there is generally no
problem.
</P>
<P>
   But people who sleep on mattress pads with magnets have a much
higher risk of being affected, the researchers found. If someone
using a defibrillator gets too close to a magnet in the pad, for
example, the device may fail to deliver the needed jolt of
electricity if the heart fails.
</P>
<P>
   Mattioni said he had no way of knowing how many people used the
magnets. About two million people in the United States use
pacemakers, and 250,000 have the defibrillators.
</P>
<P>
   PATTERNS: Words of Warning to Help Stop SIDS
</P>
<P>
   Putting infants on their backs when they go to sleep is a widely
accepted technique for reducing the risk of sudden infant death
syndrome, but doctors need to do a lot more to get the word out, a
new study finds.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-one percent of parents and baby sitters surveyed reported
that their babies' doctors had not told them how to put the
children down to sleep, say researchers for the National Institute
of Child Health and Human Development.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, writing in The Journal of the American Medical
Association, also found progress in the fight against SIDS. Deaths
have gone down almost 40 percent since a campaign emphasizing
having children sleep on their backs or sides began in 1994. About
3,000 babies a year die from the syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   But the researchers said a significant disparity remained
between whites and blacks. From 1994 to 1998, they said, stomach
placement decreased to 17 percent from 44 percent among white
infants; for blacks during the same period, the rate was 32
percent, down from 53 percent. (Black infants are 2.2 times as
likely to dies of SIDS as are white ones.) The researchers urged a
greater effort to educate black parents.
</P>
<P>
   When doctors did make recommendations, the study found, parents
and others were more likely to place babies on their backs. ``I
think that if they're not doing it, then they should be,'' said
Marian Willinger, a SIDS specialist at the health institute,
referring to doctors. The key, she said, is consistency, so that
babies get used to the position.
</P>
<P>
   IN THE LAB: A Mouse Made for Heavy Drinking
</P>
<P>
   First it was mice that could eat to their hearts' content
without getting fat. Now it's mice that can hold their alcohol
better and recover from it faster.
</P>
<P>
   First, scientists at the University of Medicine and Dentistry of
New Jersey reported that they had created a genetically modified
mouse that could eat with abandon. The long-term objective is
better understanding of human obesity.
</P>
<P>
   Now, scientists at the University of Washington report creating
a mouse that drinks much more alcohol than it would ordinarily. The
goal here is more insight into alcoholism.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers say they have bred mice missing a gene that
bears instructions for making an important brain protein. The mice,
they say, drink twice as much alcohol as do mice with the protein.
</P>
<P>
   And, given injections of alcohol raising blood-alcohol level to
almost three times the driving limit, the mice recovered in about
65 minutes. (Ordinary mice needed about 90.) The findings were
reported in a recent issue of The Journal of Neuroscience.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
