<HEADER>
A2496 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCIENCE-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      05-22 0262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE QUESTION AND ANSWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By C. CLAIBORNE RAY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rotten Fish
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why does fish start smelling awful in the garbage pail so
much sooner than meat does?
</P>
<P>
   A. Fish contains quite a bit of a substance that gives rise to
two chemicals that make the rotten-fish smell, while red meat has
hardly any, said Dr. Joseph Hotchkiss, a professor of food science
at Cornell University.
</P>
<P>
   The two chemicals are trimethylamine and dimethylamine, both
derived from trimethylamine oxide, which is particularly common in
the flesh of fin fish, especially cold-water, surface-dwelling
ocean fish like the cod. Ocean fish start to smell faster than,
say, catfish, Hotchkiss said.
</P>
<P>
   When the fish is killed and exposed to the action of air, its
own enzymes and bacteria, Hotchkiss explained, that causes the
trimethylamine oxide to undergo a chemical process called
carboxylation. The products are amines, which are volatile and
quite odoriferous.
</P>
<P>
   Fish dealers test for the amount of amines to determine how
fresh fish is, ``and the consumer's nose knows, too,'' Hotchkiss
said. ``But those who do not eat fish find it more objectionable
than others.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I pass around a vial with the chemicals that cause fish
to stink in a beginning food science class, the reactions differ,''
Hotchkiss said. ``Students from inland northern countries find it
obnoxious; those from southern marine areas, with different
cultural backgrounds and food habits, find it much less
offensive.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
