<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRLAURA-1100(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DR. LAURA BERATES, LECTURES AND INSULTS AUDIENCE IN HER BEST
BEDSIDE MANNER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So Dr. Laura Schlessinger is cutting someone else off in
midsentence, berating her caller, and it makes you think _ people
actually listen to this?
</P>
<P>
   Every day?
</P>
<P>
   Without a gun to their head?
</P>
<P>
   In less than an hour on one recent afternoon, the acid-tongued
and holier-than-thou California-based radio personality/pseudo
shrink:
</P>
<P>
   _ Suggests that a woman pretend she is adopted as a way to deal
with a family problem.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tells a woman not to marry a boyfriend because her son doesn't
like the guy _ without asking how long the two have been dating or
if they're already engaged.
</P>
<P>
   _ Browbeats a woman for ``whining and complaining'' about her
father's role in her life as her wedding approaches.
</P>
<P>
   _ Turns an innocuous question about explaining sex to a child
into a shrill, rambling diatribe against the feminist movement,
abortion and bad parents, which she says are legion. The feminist
movement, to paraphrase Dr. Laura, has made women unpaid
prostitutes and men bums.
</P>
<P>
   _ Interrupts everyone who calls in. Often.
</P>
<P>
   And this is mild compared to what Schlessinger says about
homosexuals: She has called them ``deviants'' and ``biological
errors,'' thus incurring the wrath of gay-rights groups around the
country _ as well as a group of Canadian broadcasters who want her
banned from the airwaves. Schlessinger later issued an apology for
her comments, but her critics are unforgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Laura makes Rush Limbaugh sound good natured and open
minded. And this will likely get worse before it gets better. With
two new books in publication and a talk show debuting next fall on
CBS, she's going to be grating on our ears more than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some things you should know right off about Dr. Laura:
She did not earn a Ph.D in psychology or psychiatry; she got her
doctorate in physiology, which is the study of the functions of the
body. She does have a license as a counselor from the University of
Southern California in 1980. She also was an adjunct professor at
Pepperdine University. But, overall, she has fewer credentials than
television's Dr. Frasier Crane.
</P>
<P>
   Schlessinger, 53, is in fact, a talk-show shock jock, in love
with the sound of her own opinions, delivered in a self-righteous
screeching tone that makes a New York City subway train sound
soothing. But don't say any of that to her face _ she has a black
belt in karate.
</P>
<P>
   OK, on occasion she makes some good points (see the list below).
But she spews them in an abrupt, unpleasant manner, with an air of
unbridled disgust and dislike for the world around her _ the real
world, where people get divorced, where both spouses in many
families have to work to make ends meet, and where stuff happens.
</P>
<P>
   Her tone is summed up by the tag line repeated before her
commercials: ``I'm Dr. Laura Schlessinger _ now go do the right
thing!'' delivered in an authoritative clean-your-room-this-instant
tone. Compassion is not one of her strong suits.
</P>
<P>
   She is somewhat hypocritical as well. She rails against the
feminist movement, which sowed the seeds that enabled women like
her to become successful. She cautions against two-income families
raising children while being part of one herself. She is married
and has a son, Deryk. Her husband, Lewis Bishop, is a former
biology teacher who manages her career.
</P>
<P>
   And there is her bedside manner _ or lack of one. Chiding and
intimidating callers hardly sounds like the best way of helping
people with their problems, which she says is her objective.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the louder and more objectionable she gets, the more
successful she becomes. So it's time we take a closer look at this
one-woman wrecking crew.
</P>
<P>
   DR. LAURA DOES DALLAS: In Big D, they still talk about
Schlessinger's behavior at a 1997 Jewish Federation of Dallas
fund-raiser. According to several sources, Schlessinger behaved
horribly from beginning to end.
</P>
<P>
   First, she refused three suites at the Grand Kempinski (she
finally deigned to stay at The Mansion on Turtle Creek), and then
refused to ride in a car with the three women who arrived to take
her to the event because they wore perfume.
</P>
<P>
   At the event, Schlessinger (despite being paid $30,000) mingled
with guests for only five minutes. She then, according to columnist
Maryln Schwartz of The Dallas Morning News, ``berated everyone and
said that anyone who was not as Orthodox as she is wasn't a Jew.''
Guests were astounded, and several hundred walked out. ``She was
just very nasty and insulting. She also got up and walked out
without taking several gifts given to her,'' Schwartz says.
</P>
<P>
   DR. LAURA DOES TV: ``Dr. Laura,'' her one-hour TV talk show,
debuts Sept. 11 on CBS on 175 stations (95 percent of the country),
despite numerous protests by gay rights groups.
</P>
<P>
   In Fort Worth-Dallas, the show will be on KTVT/Channel 11,
despite protests from about 100 people on April 15 at the station's
Dallas studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're contractually obligated to carry the show, as are CBS
stations around the country,'' says station vice president and
general manager Brian Jones. Jones says ``Dr. Laura'' is
tentatively scheduled to air from 4 to 5 p.m. Monday through
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will have a studio audience and live guests and phone-in
elements,'' he says. ``The show will feature a balanced perspective
of a variety of issues and that's what we know. It doesn't exist
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   Jones says he met with the leaders of several organizations at
the protest. ``It's the beginning of an ongoing dialogue,'' he
says. ``We all now have open channels. I anticipate more feedback
and conversations.''
</P>
<P>
   Count on it, says Steve Atkinson, activism chair of the Dallas
Gay and Lesbian Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fully expect there will be more protests if the show airs,''
Atkinson says. ``We want the show not to air and that's what we're
going to keep working toward. I don't think anybody could tell us
with a straight face that if she put forth negative stereotypes
about any other group of people _ Jews or blacks or Hispanics _ she
would be given a TV show.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's feeding into fear and hatred, and I firmly believe we
have to hold people accountable when they contribute to a climate
of hatred.''
</P>
<P>
   We don't hate ``everything'' Dr. Laura says _ heck no. Here are
10 points she's made that most people would agree with:
</P>
<P>
   _ It's good to donate stuff you don't want anymore to the less
fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   _ Children should not demand presents and throw fits in stores.
</P>
<P>
   _ Narcissism can kick your behind.
</P>
<P>
   _ Men and women do dumb things that mess up their lives.
</P>
<P>
   _ Think before you have children. And then think again.
</P>
<P>
   _ You can't have everything you want.
</P>
<P>
   _ It's good for families to spend time together.
</P>
<P>
   _ It's better to take control of your life than whine about
being a victim.
</P>
<P>
   _ Children are not commodities.
</P>
<P>
   _ Having a conscience and using it are important.
</P>
<P>
   SCHLESSINGER ON THE SHELVES: Dr. Laura has published six books;
the two most recent ones are:
</P>
<P>
   ``Parenthood by Proxy'' (Cliff Street Books; $24 hardcover) and
``But I Waaannt It!'' (Cliff Street Books; $15.95 hardcover).
</P>
<P>
   The first is a pro-family/pro-stay-at-home-mom tome in which
Schlessinger lashes out against mothers working outside the home,
calls day care ``a symptom of feminist paranoia,'' takes women to
task for ``prioritizing'' career over kids, and warns all parents
about wanting to be their kids' friends instead of disciplining
them and setting boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parenthood'' also rails against the ``movement'' for same-sex
marriages, saying said the movement is ``to satisfy adult desires,
and to hell with the children, if there are any.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I Waaannt It!'' is Dr. Laura's second children's book _
one that takes children to task for whining and not appreciating
what they have. Sammy and his mom go to the toy store to buy
presents for cousin Rachel. But Sammy demands toys, throwing an
in-store kicking-and-screaming fit until he gets his way. He can't
sleep, though, and soon realizes that it's his beat-up old toy, Mr.
Cat, that makes him happy. The new toys he no longer wants are
donated to a children's home.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   DR. LAURA _ AND OTHERS _ ON DR. LAURA: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jewish perspective is, God created the world and it is our
job to help perfect it. Just like God created the Earth and the
wheat, but we are the ones that take the wheat and make bread. We
each have the obligation and the responsibility to live our lives
in a way that helps perfect the world. I take that very
seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Dr. Laura, when asked about her mission, in Broadcasting &AMP;
Cable
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the lone voice out there standing up for Judeo-Christian
principles.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Dr. Laura on her March 7 show
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope all her kids turn out gay.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Elton John in US Weekly
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``You probably know who Dr. Laura Schlessinger is. That doesn't
mean you necessarily listen to her: really, who enjoys listening to
some know it all tell hapless people across the country that
they're all whiners who just need to get a backbone and a copy of
the Old Testament, stop having sex and talk to their mothers?''
</P>
<P>
   _ From the 10 Things You Can Do to Mess With Stupid Dr. Laura
Web site
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Laura has no patience with self-described victims (she's
likely to call them cowards or door mats), psychobabble of any
stripe, or ladies who want to dwell excessively on their feelings.
She is, in short, the complete antidote to modern pop culture.''
</P>
<P>
   _ syndicated columnist Mona Charen
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a pretty gentle people. So it'll probably be something
more creative, like putting her in a bad dress or something.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Elizabeth Birch, executive director of the Human Rights
Campaign Foundation, when asked if Dr. Laura would be burned in
