A2504 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-PHARMACY-TOBACCO-HNS &LR;      05-22 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHARMACY-TOBACCO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STATE POSTPONED ANTI-SMOKING ADS TARGETING POLITICAL DONOR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LANCE WILLIAMS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ California's top health official last year tried
to head off an anti-smoking media blitz targeting a drugstore chain
that had donated $130,000 to Gov. Gray Davis.
</P>
<P>
   According to documents and interviews, state health Director
Diana Bonta took unusual steps to block the California Medical
Association Foundation from using a state health grant to fund a
1999 advertising campaign criticizing the Rite Aid pharmacy chain
for selling cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   The medical foundation said it targeted Rite Aid because the
company is California's biggest drugstore chain, and because its
executives had refused to limit cigarette sales in stores that are
otherwise devoted to selling medicine and health products.
</P>
<P>
   But Rite Aid also is a player in California politics, having
donated $235,000 to candidates in the 1998 state elections,
including $80,000 to Davis, who at the time was running for
governor. On July 30, 1999, shortly after the CMA Foundation says
it told Rite Aid of its planned advertising campaign, Rite Aid gave
the Democrat another $50,000, state records show.
</P>
<P>
   And after that, even though the Department of Health Services
had already signed off on the Rite Aid ads, Bonta's aides began
scrutinizing the foundation's grant contract, said Carol A. Lee,
the CMA Foundation director. No irregularities were found.
</P>
<P>
   Bonta later appealed to the foundation to shelve its ads so she
could personally mediate with Rite Aid, according to an Oct. 29
letter from the foundation responding to the idea.
</P>
<P>
   But the foundation's Pharmacy Partnership went ahead with its
campaign, and on Nov. 10 hit Rite Aid with a tough full-page ad in
the New York Times (``No company should profit from healing us and
harming us at the same time,'' it said) and a televised news
conference featuring a throat cancer victim.
</P>
<P>
   The medical foundation declined the health director's plea to
put off the campaign because at prior meetings Rite Aid executives
``absolutely refused'' to consider removing cigarettes from their
stores, Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview Friday, Bonta said she had questioned
the Rite Aid campaign because it seemed ethically inconsistent to
single out one pharmacy for selling tobacco when others do the
same.
</P>
<P>
   She also wanted to make sure that the company's management had
been given a chance to respond to the criticism before the ads were
launched. Finally, she said she had only recently been appointed to
her post, and wanted to make sure proper procedures had been
followed.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign donations had nothing to do with it, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no conversation with the governor,'' she said. ``I don't
know about the donation. That was not a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a brand-new person coming into the job, saying, `Hey,
what is this? How does it fit into the grand scheme . . . in terms
of targeting this company?''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, anti-smoking activists said it was unusual, and
troubling, for the health director herself to become involved in an
effort to scotch anti-tobacco ads, which are funded from the state
cigarette tax.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stanton Glantz, a professor at the University of California
at San Francisco, called Bonta's action ``unprecedented'' and
``intrusive'' and said it made him question the Davis
administration's professed commitment to combating smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is shocking that the health director in the administration
of a governor who campaigned against tobacco to get elected would
stand in the way of an effort to get cigarettes out of pharmacies,
no matter how big the campaign donation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Drugstores ``should not be out selling a product that is killing
people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rite Aid public relations director Sarah Datz said the Camp
Hill, Pa.-based company sells cigarettes because customers want to
buy them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a retail business, and our job is giving our
customers a choice,'' she said. While Rite Aid complies with all
California laws regarding tobacco sales, she said, the company also
believes that ``it's important for customers to make their own
lifestyle and product choices.''
</P>
<P>
   She declined to comment on the company's political donations.
</P>
<P>
   California's anti-smoking campaign is funded by a tax of 25
cents per pack on cigarettes imposed by the Proposition 99
initiative in 1988. The taxes, more than $40 million last year, are
earmarked to fund a wide range of anti-smoking measures, including
anti-smoking education efforts administered by the state Health
Department.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the effort, the state has funded a series of print,
billboard and TV ads that portray the hazards of smoking in the
harshest terms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
