<HEADLINE>
AND THE WINNER IS...
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY LIPSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The best wine of the Los Angeles County Fair's Wines of the
Americas Competition, which was named Friday, might be difficult to
find.
</P>
<P>
   Announced as Best Wine of the Competition, a 1996 cabernet
sauvignon from California's Beaulieu Vineyard, Rutherford, titled
Clone 6 and priced at around $110 a bottle edged out a $12 Amador
County, California, syrah from Montevina Winery and a 1997 Pezzi
King Californian reserve zinfandel from Dry Creek that sells for
around $30.
</P>
<P>
   But the best deal of the most honored wines picked by the 60
judges from around the globe, who sipped and spat for three days at
the Millard Sheets Gallery at Fairplex in Pomona, may be the Best
in Class chardonnay, a 1998 Gallo of Sonoma bargain priced at $10 a
bottle.
</P>
<P>
   There were 2,662 entries from 500 wineries at this year's
competition, regarded by many as the most important of the nation's
elite county fair wine competitions and often the largest.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles County Fair wine competition began in 1935.
</P>
<P>
   This year there were two added competitions, one for extra
virgin olive oils which drew 28 entries and a wine package design
competition. Separate judging panels examined the olive oils and
wine bottle labels.
</P>
<P>
   The public will be able to taste many of the entries (wines and
olive oils) and many of the the winning wines at a fund-raising
event today at the Millard Sheets Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   As in previous years, the wines will also be available for
tasting at the County Fair, Sept. 14-Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   For ticket information call (909) 865-4231 or (909) 865-4233. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
