r e BC-MACY-GRAY-PREVIEW-LAD     05-22 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACY-GRAY-PREVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHADES OF GRAY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
The hottest breakthrough artist of 1999 sounded hot, tired and
ready to make a breakthough into a long afternoon nap.
</P>
<P>
   Macy Gray was in the midst of her second day of filming a new
video somewhere in the Valley and the steaming weather and rigid
schedule had turned her normally raspy voice even more smoky than
usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hectic, yeah,'' she whispered. ``We've been doing this
shoot nonstop and I feel like I could crawl into a cave right about
now. I haven't had a minute to do anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray's life has been nonstop nearly from the moment her enticing
debut album, ``On How Life Is'' (Clean Slate/Epic), surfaced last
summer. The disc's savvy mix of hip-hop, old-school soul and rock
caught the ear of r&AMP;b fans and radio programmers who made ``Do
Something'' a hit, turning Gray into one of the year's most
celebrated new acts. The album ended up on a host of best-of lists
and Gray was nominated for a best new artist Grammy Award in a
field dominated by teen sensations. ``Do Something,'' meanwhile,
was nominated in the best female r&AMP;b vocal category.
</P>
<P>
   It brought Gray even more exposure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect to win, especially for new artist,'' Gray, 30,
said. ``It was a kick going to the awards and everything, anyway.
But you kind of knew who would probably win.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the winners in Gray's categories were Christina
Aguilera and Whitney Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Gray, though, is one of those rare performers with a distinctive
sound. Her tone has been compared to Miles Davis' otherworldly
speaking voice while others hear smoky shades of Nina Simone,
Eartha Kitt and Tina Turner.
</P>
<P>
   And Gray's fans range from Neil Young to 'N Sync's Chris
Kirkpatrick to dance-pop maven Fatboy Slim, with whom she recently
cut two tracks for his forthcoming album.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing else like Macy Gray and that's the appeal of
her as an artist,'' said Chris Patyk, music director at local hot
adult contemporary station KYSR-FM (98.7) _ Star 98. ``There's no
one else like her at a time with so much prepackaged, homogenized
stuff. The vibe here at the station started in the hallways. When
we were talking about playing her before Christmas we put the
record on and it just lit up the phones. Her album got huge quickly
and started outselling things we were playing pretty heavily.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray, who appears Wednesday at the Greek Theatre and then heads
out with Carlos Santana at the end of July, almost didn't become a
singer at all.
</P>
<P>
   Born Natalie McIntyre in Canton, Ohio, to a steelworker dad and
a mom who taught eighth-grade math, she was regularly teased by
neighborhood kids who made such fun of her unusual voice that she
stopped talking at one point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Singing was the last thing I ever imagined I could do,'' said
Gray, whose stage name was borrowed from a beloved neighbor in
Canton. ``I loved music but I never ever saw myself as a
performer.''
</P>
<P>
   At home, Gray soaked up her parents' record collection, which
was full of old-school soul by Aretha Franklin, Donny Hathaway, Sly
Stone, Stevie Wonder and Marvin Gaye. At the same time, Gray was
studying classical piano, remaining so self-conscious about her
voice that she never attempted to sing a note.
</P>
<P>
   Everything changed in 1992 when she moved to Los Angeles to
study screenwriting at the University of Southern California.
Hooking up with some musician friends, Gray penned lyrics and cut
guide vocals for another vocalist. When it was time to record, the
singer didn't show and Gray filled in.
</P>
<P>
   The tape began to circulate and Gray's voice was noticed by the
leader of a hotel jazz band who asked her to join.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was crazy because it was a good money gig,'' she
recalled. ``I was singing standards and Sinatra tunes for a hundred
bucks an hour. Easy money.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Gray _ a divorced mother of three who lives in Encino _
and some pals opened an after-hours Hollywood coffee shop called
the We Ours, where the Roots, Tricky, and the Black Eyed Peas
stopped by to hang out and sometimes jam.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a word-of-mouth thing but the place was so small you
knew everybody,'' Gray said. ``It was a good scene to get a sound
together, to see what was working and what wasn't. It wasn't like a
big Hollywood hang-out. It was a ghetto superstar thing. We'd play
there every week but because the place could fit only 100 people,
we stripped down our 12-piece band to a four-piece.''
</P>
<P>
   The club's sizzling, all-night open-mike jams and Gray's
reputation as a singer made Andrew Slater, manager of Fiona Apple
and the Wallflowers, notice. Slater hooked her up with hot
producer-musician Jon Brion, who added unusual instrumental touches
such as vibes and the strange-sounding proto-synthesizer, the
chamberlin.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting album, ``On How Life Is,'' which has since sold
more than 2 million copies, came at the perfect time. Lauryn Hill's
album, ``The Education of Lauryn Hill'' had opened the door for a
more musical brand of rap and hip-hop while old-school soul and
funk were making a periodic comeback.
</P>
<P>
   The album's initial radio hit, ``Do Something,'' led listeners
to sample such standout material as the funk-inflected ``Why Didn't
You Call Me,'' the frank ``Sex-o-Matic Venus Freak,'' the affecting
breakup song ``I Try,'' and the poignant disc-closer, ``The
Letter.''
</P>
<P>
   Musicians on the record include Gray's longtime writing
partners, programmer Darryl Swann and keyboardist Jeremy Ruzumna,
plus Arik Marshall, who played guitar with the Red Hot Chili
Peppers, and such seasoned veterans as Funkadelic guitarist
Blackbird McKnight, Tower of Power percussionist Lenny Castro and
Apple drummer Matt Chamberlain. The string arrangements were
courtesy of Beck's dad, David Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   Gray, who won two statuettes at the recent Brit Awards,
Britain's answer to the Grammys, performs ``I Try'' on Fox-TV's
(Channel 11) Essence Awards at 8 p.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Even with her high media profile, Gray says her sometimes gritty
lyrics are deeply personal tales from her life. And she's surprised
they have such apparently universal appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're snippets of things that have happened to me, that
inspired me to write,'' she says. ``It's just my life. It's all
pretty personal. It's not like I'm speaking for the whole world. I
really don't have some big message. It's just what I've gone
through and I hope people can relate.'' &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
Who: Macy Gray with Black Eyed Peas. &QL; 
Where: Greek Theatre, 2700 N. Vermont Ave., Los Angeles. &QL; 
When: 7:30 p.m. Wednesday. &QL; 
Tickets: $23 to $38.50. &QL; 
Information: (213) 480-3232. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
