<HEADER>
A2520 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-ALBATROSS-ART-NYT     05-22 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ALBATROSS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS IT A PLANE? NO, IT'S A BIRD AND A VERY RARE BIRD INDEED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Maine)   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By E. VERNON LAUX   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PENIKESE ISLAND, Mass. _ The weather was hot and sunny with a
stiff southwest wind blowing at about 30 knots on Tuesday, May 9,
when a large seabird, an albatross, came flying in off Buzzard's
Bay at 11:45 a.m. and buzzed researchers hunkered down in a blind
here.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, Gina Reppucci of North Chelmsford, Mass., and
Carolyn Mostello of West Kingston, R.I., were on the island to
study terns and gulls for the Massachusetts Division of Fisheries
and Wildlife. The last thing they expected to see was an albatross.
</P>
<P>
   But both had prior experience with albatrosses in the Pacific
Ocean and had spent time observing these birds on Midway Island, a
major breeding area for laysan (Phoebastria immutabilis) and
black-footed (Phoebastria nigripes) albatrosses, two widespread
Pacific Ocean species.
</P>
<P>
   Mostello has even seen the rarest species of albatross in the
world, the short-tailed albatross (Phoebastria albatrus), at
Midway.
</P>
<P>
   So they were well aware that these large, soaring birds, whose
wingspans reach six or seven feet, were virtual strangers _
accidentals, in the language of ornithology _ in the North Atlantic
Ocean. One can scarcely hope to see a member of this family in a
lifetime of venturing offshore in this part of the world.
</P>
<P>
   As Reppucci recalled, they were ``hysterical, our eyes popping
out of our heads,'' when this adult yellow-nosed albatross
(Thalassarche chlororhyncos) came soaring in off the bay and zoomed
by their blind, passing about 15 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   They were so awestruck when they realized what it was that they
did not even grab their binoculars on the bird's first pass. They
did not need them as it came in at eye level, then flared up and
over the blind. The black bill with yellow upper ridge, underwing
pattern, the exquisite eye shadow and overall pattern and
coloration of this fabulous bird were etched into instant memory.
``It was the most exciting thing we had ever seen,'' Mostello said.
</P>
<P>
   While observing endangered terns is worthwhile and satisfying,
there is nothing like a big-time rarity, a bona fide off-the-wall
vagrant seabird.
</P>
<P>
   Penikese Island is a small grass-covered island in the sparsely
inhabited Elizabeth Island chain that juts westward into Buzzard's
Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers are camping here from April through August,
monitoring a federally endangered species, the roseate tern (Sterna
dougallii). There are large numbers of nesting herring gulls (Larus
argentatus) and great black-backed gulls (Larus marinus) on the
island and a small rookery of black-crowned night-herons
(Nycticorax nycticorax) and a few snowy egrets (Egretta thula).
</P>
<P>
   For a small island, Penikese has its share of ornithological
items of note. The first breeding record of the manx shearwater
(Puffinus puffinus) in North America was discovered when a nest
containing a chick was found here in 1973, the first time this
species had been found nesting on the western side of the North
Atlantic. It has not been found breeding in Massachusetts since.
</P>
<P>
   Penikese is also the southernmost known nesting location for a
small seabird called the Leach's storm-petrel (Oceanodroma
leucorhoa) in the Atlantic Ocean. These nocturnal birds arrive in
the middle of the night to return to nesting burrows in old stone
walls on the island. There are only a handful of pairs on the
island.
</P>
<P>
   But the albatross was an even rarer bird. The ``gooney'' bird
made several passes over the grassy island hillsides at relatively
slow speed, treating the researchers to great views at close range.
</P>
<P>
   The nesting great black-backed gulls took offense at its
presence and three or four adults gave chase. The beleaguered
albatross headed back to the north into Buzzard's Bay with several
``angry'' great black-backs in pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   Albatrosses come to land for only one reason: to find a mate,
lay an egg and raise another albatross. Were Penikese Island
located in the southern Atlantic Ocean, it would be ideal albatross
nesting habitat. It fills the bill nicely with strong winds and
wide open grassy hillsides to serve as runways for these heavy
birds to take off on. Most important, it is free of mammalian
predators. The bird was in all probability prospecting for a nest
site.
</P>
<P>
   But it was 180 degrees out of sync from the Southern Hemisphere.
While it is spring here, it is fall where the rest of its species
lives. It seems the bird's compass and internal clocks have all
been reset for the Northern Hemisphere. If it could only find a
mate, there could be a staggering range expansion into a whole new
hemisphere. This kind of thing could happen _ the Penikese
albatross is not the first to turn up in the wrong place at the
wrong time.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer an adult yellow-nosed albatross visited Matinicus
Rock in Maine on July 6. The bird remained for about two hours, was
photographed and then it flew off never to be seen again, unless
the bird that visited Penikese was the same individual. The
sighting in Maine last summer was the third for this species in
Maine ornithological history.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the North Atlantic, there have been some
remarkable albatross sightings. A black-browed albatross
(Thalassarche melanophris) returned to the same huge Northern
Gannet (Morus bassanus) rookery on Hermaness Island in the Outer
Hebrides from 1967 until 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The albatross courted these large, seagoing gannets to no avail.
It built a nest each year from 1972 until 1987 but never attracted
a mate as the rest of its species were well south of the equator.
This bird exhibited extreme site fidelity, but it was the only one
of its kind, so its efforts were genetically in vain.
</P>
<P>
   There are two other records for this species in Massachusetts.
Amazingly, the first record was of a bird on almost the exact same
date, on May 7, 1971, seen over Bird Island, off of Marion, Mass.,
also in Buzzard's Bay. This bird was spotted by Dr. Ian Nisbet, an
authority on roseate terns who has been active in research and
conservation efforts on their behalf for more than 40 years. Bird
Island is really no distance at all as the albatross flies from
Penikese across Buzzard's Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Yellow-nosed albatrosses have also been spotted from the Gulf of
St. Lawrence in Quebec, the Bay of Fundy in New Brunswick, twice in
New York state, once in Freeport on Long Island and one was seen
flying up the Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   As more and more birders go afield armed with excellent optics
and first-rate field guides, the species is being detected more
frequently. But the birds are still very rare.
</P>
<P>
   Albatrosses are extraordinarily long-lived. This is known from
recoveries of birds wearing bands or rings that were attached at a
known time and place. The longevity record is of a giant royal
albatross (Diomedea epomohora) banded in New Zealand and recovered
as a breeding adult 58 years later. Theoretically they could live
to be more than 80 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the recently sighted bird has not reappeared at
Penikese Island or been seen anywhere else for that matter. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 1707EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000522.0240 </DOCNO>
