<SLUG> BC-OPED-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSPECTIVES ON GIULIANI'S EXIT AND HILLARY CLINTON'S CHANCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for use Sunday, May 21, or thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by OPED clients. Nonsubscribers can use this
article only by special arrangement. For purchase information, see
end of text. 
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rudolph Giuliani has pulled out of the New York Senate race,
leaving his successor months behind in fund-raising, planning and
glad-handing. How do you beat Hillary Clinton from a standing
start? Here are a few words from some experts.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Nachman, a former editor of The New York Post, is
executive producer of ``Politically Incorrect with Bill Maher'':
</P>
<P>
   So you're some no-name Republican suddenly thrust into
prominence and about to launch a campaign against someone with name
recognition equal to Evita Peron's. As my mother would say, what
could be bad? With no Rudy Giuliani baggage to carry, your
``unfavorable'' ratings are already hugely better than the ones for
the woman who calls herself ``HILLARY!''
</P>
<P>
   Remember, it's not your police department you have to defend.
You never kicked any little old ladies off the welfare rolls, or
ticketed a jaywalker, or banished a hot-dog peddler or arrested
some hapless cabbie. Or dumped your wife on live TV. There's your
slogan: It Wasn't Me!
</P>
<P>
   That means your only opponent is Hillary, not yourself. And
since she won't have Rudy to kick around anymore, she'll be
required to defend herself. And thanks to your being nobody, she'll
have nothing to attack. Until Friday, the race was going to be won
by the candidate the voters disliked least. Now that's you. This is
good, yes? Why didn't we think of this before?
</P>
<P>
   Frank Luntz has been Rudolph Giuliani's pollster since 1993:
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it: this election was never really about Rudy
Giuliani. It has always been about Hillary Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Most pollsters will tell you that attitudes toward Hillary were
more important in determining voter preferences than their feelings
toward Rudy. That being said, the reason why Rudy Guiliani was able
to weather the past few weeks without any drop in public opinion
was his incredible record of success in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton just doesn't have that record _ and that may
prove to be the key weapon in Rick Lazio's political arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   The one question that Rick Lazio needs to present to the people
of New York is, ``Can you name one thing Hillary Clinton has done
for the people of New York?'' It's short, sweet, to the point and
in my focus groups throughout the state, no one could answer it.
Even her own advisers have trouble answering.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Wilentz is director of the American studies program at
Princeton.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of their candidate, Republicans will try to paint
Hillary Clinton as an outsider, the carpetbagger without a record.
But I'm not so sure this will work. Clinton represents a distinct
New York tradition, one that actually predates the ethnic pol _ the
ambitious and talented arriviste.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with the other great eastern states _ Massachusetts
with its Brahmins and River Gods, Pennsylvania with its inbred
Quaker elite _ New York has always been remarkably open to upstarts
_ socially as well as politically.
</P>
<P>
   The first outstanding New Yorker in the new nation's politics,
Alexander Hamilton, was the West Indies-born son of an unremarkable
Scottish peddler. After Hamilton came George Clinton, the
Jeffersonian Democrat, and his nephew, DeWitt. Descendants of
moderately prosperous immigrant farmers from Ulster County, they
both served auspicious terms as New York's governor. Then came
Martin Van Buren, the cunning, self-made son of a tavernkeeper from
Kinderhook. After two Senate terms, he became the first New Yorker
to win the White House.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers have welcomed out-of-staters, particularly, it
seems, when it comes to choosing their Senate candidates. Not only
the oft-mentioned Robert Kennedy of Massachusetts and James Buckley
of Connecticut, but also Ramsey Clark of Texas, the Democratic
senatorial nominee in 1972. Indeed, New York's very first senator,
Rufus King, began his political career as a delegate to the
Continental Congress _ from Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   So while Republicans may try to make the carpetbagger charge
stick, I'm not so sure it will work.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Bond is a former Republican National Committee chairman:
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton lost a formidable opponent in Rudy Giuliani. He
had a proven record of attracting crossover Democrats, and a
Republican Senate candidate has to have that appeal. While the
dynamics of the race have changed, however, Clinton's uphill battle
to win this Senate seat hasn't.
</P>
<P>
   First, there is no such thing as a standing start for any
Republican running against her, even in New York. Polls showed her
support at a steady 44 percent, and despite Giuliani's troubles
over the past two weeks, her support has barely moved.
</P>
<P>
   Second, a recent decision by the 10th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals tossed out Federal Election Commission restrictions on
party contributions to congressional candidates. Although this
court has jurisdiction only over six Western states, both parties
have indicated that they will apply it nationally. Thus,
fund-raising will not be an issue for the New York Senate
candidate. The party could legally write out a multimillion-dollar
check tomorrow to provide financial parity.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell L. Moss is director of the Taub Urban Research Center
at New York University.
</P>
<P>
   Without Rudy Giuliani in the race, Clinton will have to work
much harder to mobilize minority groups in New York City.
African-American voters are enthusiastic supporters of Bill
Clinton, but it's not clear that the president's popularity is
automatically transferred to his wife. Clinton was counting on
anti-Giuliani sentiment to bring out her voters in minority areas.
More important, Republicans can now nominate a candidate with
suburban roots who will carry the Conservative Party imprimatur, a
clone of genial George Pataki. Furthermore, Hillary Clinton cannot
rely on upstate voters to instinctively oppose a politician from
New York City. Without the mayor, Republicans will do better
upstate and in the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Rothenberg is the editor of Rothenberg Political Report:
</P>
<P>
   Rick Lazio could actually turn out to be a stronger opponent
than Rudy Giuliani. He is a moderate who voted for family and
medical leave; he backs gun control and has been supported by
environmental groups. Even more important, the four-term
congressman from Suffolk County doesn't carry the mayor's personal
or political baggage. He's more personable and unthreatening than
Giuliani, and he doesn't have to worry that a shooting, racial
incident or City Hall scandal will derail his Senate bid. Lazio
could re-create the same coalition of upstate and suburban voters
that helped George Pataki oust another political celebrity, Mario
Cuomo, in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Trump, the real estate developer, is author, with Dave
Shiflett, of ``The America We Deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Hillary has proved over a long period of time that she is very
tough, tenacious and smart. Whoever runs against her will have to
have those qualities in even greater abundance because her name
recognition and celebrity are so very high.
</P>
<P>
   Stick to the issues and work very hard _ and the anti-Hillary
vote may just be a big surprise in November.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
