A2528 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-RADIO-SITE-OF-WEEK &LR;      05-22 0290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADIO-SITE-OF-WEEK </SLUG>
  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Weekly box) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
 
``Uncle Joe's Morning Show'' Album-rock radio vet ``Uncle Joe''
Benson, joined by sidekick Sioux-Z Jessup and sports anchor Scott
St. James, spins classic rock and offers nuggets on each artist. A
daily featured artist segment takes place at a quarter past the
hours 6 to 8 a.m. 
Where: KCBS-FM (93.1) _ Arrow 93. 
When: 6 to 10 a.m. weekdays. 
Typical segment: ``Hotel California,'' Eagles; ``Break On Through
(To the Other Side),'' Doors; ``Fire,'' Jimi Hendrix; ``Mysterious
Ways,'' U2. 
Quote: ``I take great pleasure in pointing out little-known facets
of the music.'' 
Off the air: A Glendale resident, Benson mixes his love for music
with auto racing and on Memorial Day weekend will participate in a
three-hour endurance contest near Bakersfield. His syndicated ``Off
the Record'' program is broadcast on 118 stations across the
country, including Arrow at 10 p.m. Sundays. He has also penned
seven volumes of discographies titled ``Uncle Joe's Record
Guides,'' with editions on prog-rock and the '80s due this fall. 
Background: Benson started in radio in 1968, moving to Los Angeles
in 1980. He spent 15 years at KLOS-FM (95.5) where he held down
afternoons and evenings, and hosted Sunday night's ``7th Day,''
which highlighted a specific year and artist each week. He has been
at Arrow for three years. 
Taking a stand:! ``People who've heard me know who I am. I have a
passion for music and racing and those are the biggest things in my
life. And people know it.'' 
Website: www.unclejoe.com. 
You'll like this if: ... you like oldies KRTH-FM (101.1) and
active-rock KLOS. 

