<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2533 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-PRIEST-ABUSE-HNS &LR;      05-22 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIEST-ABUSE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CHURCH SETTLES CASE OF ALLEGED ABUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Averting a potentially embarrassing civil trial,
the Archdiocese of San Francisco has reached a settlement in the
case of a teen-age rectory worker who accused his Burlingame pastor
of physical and mental abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Financial terms were not disclosed, but the lawyer for the young
man, whose lawsuit claimed damages of more than $50,000, said the
amount was ``very significant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It clearly indicates the archdiocese recognizes the validity
of the allegations,'' said Justine Durrell, the San Francisco
lawyer representing the plaintiff, identified in court documents as
John Doe. ``They probably had concerns about going to trial.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial was to start Monday in San Francisco Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   Church spokesman Maurice Healy said the archdiocese's insurance
company paid the settlement, describing it as ``a standard release
of all claims.''
</P>
<P>
   The priest's attorney did not return a call seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   In a case that stunned parishioners at St. Catherine of Siena
Church, the Rev. James Aylward was spotted in November 1997,
wrestling in a darkened rectory room with a 16-year-old former
altar boy. Another priest, the Rev. John Conley, happened upon the
encounter.
</P>
<P>
   After crawling out the room, leaving the teen to face Conley
alone, Aylward later insisted the nocturnal encounter was a
one-time incident of ``horseplay and wrestling,'' and publicly
apologized for his ``foolishness and imprudence.''
</P>
<P>
   The police and the San Mateo County district attorney's office
investigated, finding insufficient evidence to file criminal
charges.
</P>
<P>
   The archdiocese conducted an internal review, concluding that
Aylward's conduct was inappropriate but not sexual. The archdiocese
said it strongly disapproved of priests wrestling with youths, but
termed Aylward's conduct a lapse in judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Aylward, ordained in 1964, remained as pastor for about seven
months, then resigned to later serve as parochial vicar at Our Lady
of Mount Carmel Church in Mill Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, the former altar boy sued, alleging he had been
``physically and mentally abused'' by Aylward for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aylward would force Doe to wrestle with him, forcing him to
the ground and getting on top of him,'' the lawsuit contended.
``Aylward would secure Doe in positions from which (he) could not
escape and not release him until Doe would groan from pain. Aylward
while engaged in these acts would grunt and groan and saliva would
drip from his mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit accused the archdiocese of sanctioning the
misconduct by failing to discipline or remove the priest from the
parish.
</P>
<P>
   The archdiocese denied the allegations. ``Nothing happened,''
said Paul Gaspari, the lawyer representing the church.
</P>
<P>
   But in February, Aylward admitted to a history of inappropriate
touching of boys for his own sexual gratification.
</P>
<P>
   Under oath, the 61-year-old priest confessed to multiple
incidents of inappropriate physical contact with minors, over at
least 12 years at several parishes.
</P>
<P>
   In his deposition, Aylward described the physical interaction he
had with boys as ``wrestling'' and admitted that some of the
encounters were for his own sexual pleasure, according to Ronald
Schwartz, co-counsel in the lawsuit against Aylward.
</P>
<P>
   During his deposition, Aylward also said archdiocesan officials,
during their internal investigation, never asked whether he had
engaged in such conduct with other minors. He testified that had
his religious superiors probed further, he would have told them the
truth.
</P>
<P>
   Archdiocesan officials said they ``specifically asked (Aylward)
whether he had any sexual contact of any kind with any minors at
any time, and he denied having done so. . . . (H)e never wavered
from that position.''
</P>
<P>
   Aylward was immediately placed on administrative leave and
remains in that status today.
</P>
<P>
   His revelations startled even his staunchest supporters. In
mid-March, more than 100 St. Catherine parishioners gathered in the
parish auditorium to discuss the case. Much anger was voiced, not
only at their former pastor but also toward the archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the oddest twists in the case involved Conley, the parish
priest who stumbled upon the nighttime ``wrestling'' and reported
it to both law enforcement and his religious superiors. Before his
ordination in 1993, Conley had worked as a federal prosecutor,
serving for a time as chief of the criminal division in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after exposing the wrestling incident, Conley was placed
on administrative leave, where he remains to this day.
</P>
<P>
   In a highly unusual move, he filed a lawsuit against his
religious superiors, maintaining that he was defamed and penalized
for reporting suspected child abuse. The suit for infliction of
emotional distress and defamation was dismissed in San Francisco
and is on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully this case will encourage the church to reinstate
Father Conley,'' Durrell said. ``It would make a real statement in
terms of their willingness to encourage whistle-blowers instead of
the cloak and dagger approach.''
</P>
<P>
   The archdiocese has insisted Conley was put on leave not because
he reported the incident but for unrelated actions and behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Church spokesman Maurice Healy was cryptic about the priest's
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are probably certain actions the archdiocese would want
done before we get out of the administrative leave mode,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Conley declined to be interviewed because of his appeal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
