<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT RAISES FRESH ANTITRUST CHALLENGE
 &HT;    Moving in the (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With a long-awaited date before a federal judge
only days away, Microsoft Corp. argued yet again Monday that the
company should be kept intact even if it broke the antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the three previous sets of briefs on what remedies would
best cure the company's antitrust faults, the latest Microsoft
offering was unsolicited by U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Jackson is to preside at a hearing here at which
both the government and the company will air their remedy views and
contrasting legal timetables.
</P>
<P>
   After Jackson last month ruled that Microsoft had illegally
sought to retain its monopoly power over operating systems for
personal computers, the government called on the judge to break the
company into two parts.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft contended Monday that in an earlier Justice
Department action, ``the government has already admitted that the
breakup of Microsoft would be 'dangerous to the economy's welfare'
and 'against the public interest.' ``
</P>
<P>
   ``The government had it right in 1995: the (antitrust) law does
not countenance the dismemberment of Microsoft, a remedy that would
clearly 'act against the public interest.' ``
</P>
<P>
   The 1995 case ended in a settlement and consent decree _ one
which the government later accused Microsoft of having broken. The
dispute led directly to the current suit, brought on behalf of the
Justice Department and 19 state attorneys general.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the government contends Microsoft's new arguments
don't wash because they are based on the situation that prevailed
before Jackson issued his wide-ranging decision.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also noted that in the earlier case both Jackson and
the Justice Department admitted there was no way of knowing whether
competing technologies, such as the Netscape Navigator Web browser
or Sun Microsystems' Java platform, could eventually have replaced
its dominant Windows software.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without such a finding, the government's request for
structural relief must fail,'' Microsoft said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Microsoft contends that the U.S. Court of Appeals found
in 1998 that technological tying _ the inclusion of
once-independent software into an operating system _ was within
bounds, as long as it creates some demonstrable benefit to
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson's verdict failed to take into account that appeals'
court finding, Microsoft claims.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: microsoft.com/presspass/trial/
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
