<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Tuesday, May 23, 2000, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   CABLE-SEX _ WASHINGTON _ What the Supreme Court's ruling Monday
striking down a federal law that sought to protect children from
sex-oriented cable TV channels means to viewers, regulators and the
industry. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ In an unexpected court filing,
Microsoft Corp. submitted a short brief Monday attacking the
government's response to its response to the government's breakup
proposal. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   E-PRIVACY _ WASHINGTON _ The Federal Trade Commission briefs
Congress members on its proposal to regulate consumer privacy
protections on e-commerce sites. Details and reaction. (Geewax, Cox
News Service). 22.
</P>
<P>
   BIZMAGS _ A rundown of the week's financial press. (Walker,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WESTPOINT _Shares of WestPoint Stevens were off more than 30
percent in the wake of an announcement that the textile maker was
dropping plans to go private. The bed and bath products company
said it was squashing the effort because of higher interest rates,
which increases the cost of borrrowing. Looking at what this means
for WestPoint. (Bond, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DOW _ It's beginning to sink in that the Federal Reserve's rate
increases are not only likely to continue, but will have the
desired effect of slowing the economy. Even the technology sectoro
once regarded as immune to rate increases will be affected since
the client companies that invest in high tech equipment are
affected. (Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   EARTHLINK _ Earthlink will make for Sprint a suite of
applications to make the ISP's services available across Sprint's
broadband wireless network. Sprint owns 1/4 of Earthlink. (Kanell,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   COXNET PTECH PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet PTECH page for the current week.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET PTECH 0523 _ A high-tech vision of a flat panel future is
the gospel for thousands of physicists and engineers around the
world. They are racing to perfect new display technologies just as
the Internet and more advanced microprocessors give the flat panel
seemingly endless real-life applications. (Gee, Austin
American-Statesman) Art includes a 4-column color illustration and
a 18-pica color photo of an IBM flat panel screen.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ARTIST SCREEN _ Zvi Yaniv isn't the typical artist. He's not the
typical physicist either. He envisions a world with wall-sized
video displays and spends his days in a mostly windowless office
perfecting a prototype that he hopes will make his dream a reality.
(Gee, Austin American-Statesman) Art includes a 1-column color
photo of the artist's work and a 6-pica color mug of the artist.
</P>
<P>
   GAME CORNER _ MadCatz has taken the deficient Sega Dreamcast
controller and corrected its flaws. (Staff, Austin
American-Statesman) Art includes a 1-column color photo of the
MadCatz controller.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY _ When I was a young man, way too much of my time
was spent trying to get more speed and louder exhaust noises out of
a car that began life as a rather ordinary Chevrolet Chevelle.
Nowadays cars aren't that big of a deal to me. Instead, I spend
just as much childish zeal and grown-up money hopping up my home
PC. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) Art includes 1 column
color sig of columnist.
</P>
<P>
   NON-SPORT-GAMES _ At the Sega booth during the E3Expo in Los
Angeles recently, the line to play ``Jet Grind Radio'' was so long
company officials sometimes had to ask enthusiasts to stop so
others could play the new video game. The highly anticipated game
is for the Sega Dreamcast and will be released this fall. Here's 10
of the top non-sports games on all the consoles _ PlayStation 2,
PlayStation, Nintendo 64 and Dreamcast _ that will go on sale
before the holiday season. (Carvell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   VIDEOGAME _ LOS ANGELES _ Millions of video game gearheads are
twiddling their thumbs until October waiting for Sony's PlayStation
2. But Atlanta gamers will get a hands-on test drive by early
summer. As part of a $10 million promotional blitz for the sleek
device _ which has an upgraded video processor, DVD drive and
expansion slots for a broadband modem and hard drive _ Sony will
bring the game to Atlanta for Major League Baseball's Fan Fest
2000, July 7-11. (Harris, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   GADGETS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ A new fax machine from Sharp Document
and Network Systems of America can cut the cost of running a home
business by finding the cheapest available phone company to handle
any fax or telephone call to another state. (Cummings, Dayton Daily
News). WITH PHOTO. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-GEAR _ The latest in digital technology gear. This week:
Iolo Technologies' System Mechanic 3.2. (Austin
American-Statesman). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-PLAYGEAR _ The latest in digital entertainment gear. This
week: eMedia Guitar Method CD-ROM. (Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-LINK _ Your link to some of the best and most interesting
sites on the Web. This week: Neostream Interactive. (Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-KIDGEAR _ Games for children. This week: Kids Tetris.
(Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-WEEWEB _ Web sites for kids. This week: Global
Show-'n-Tell. (Austin American-Statesman). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-GAMER _ Games for the console and desktop aimed at the
moderate to advanced gamer. This week: Beetle Buggin. (Austin
American-Statesman) . MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-CENTERPIECE _ Remember that famous line from the old
``Saturday Night Live'' skit: It's a floor wax and a desert
topping. Only in this case it's a telephone and a Web browser all
rolled up in the same neat package. If you've got a wireless Web
cellular phone, you can order a book or check the sports scores, or
get the latest news from CNN. Oh, and if you want to make a phone
call, you can do that, too. The next and newest generation of
cellular phones have matchbook-sized screens and built-in Internet
browsers that let users access everything from CNN to Yahoo and
Amazon.com. Industry analysts expect that most cellular phones will
be Web-ready by the end of the year. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY_ Popular column about personal computing written for
the average user. This week: Palm-sized computers. (Husted, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-TOOLS _ Software reviews. This week: Combatting viruses on
the Web. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ What's new on the Web. This week: Browsing the Web to
make informed purchases. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ What's new on the Web. This week: Astrology sites.
(Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   READ-ONWEB _ A rundown of interesting finds on the Net.
(Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TECH-SAVVY _ Question and answer column focusing on using
computers and other technology as tools to get jobs done.
(Cleere/Rudd, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVEDNETKIDS _ When
children of the pre-Internet generation grew up, they were taught
to solve problems methodically, in a linear way, the first steps to
an A to B to C mindset. Today's kids learn to think in three
dimensions, using computers and the Internet to manipulate text,
images, sound and video, creating their own language unhindered by
geography or a lack of information resources. How is the Internet
and today's computer technology changing the way Austin children
develop? We'll find the brightest Austin kids see if learning to
have such skills create a generation that will be that much smarter
than their parents? (Gallaga, Austin American-Statesman). 45. WITH
PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
