<P>
   These sports stories for release Tuesday, May 23, 2000, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL
</P>
<P>
   BBN-BRAVES-ROAD _ Braves story of the day advancing nine-game
road trip, which begins with a three-game series starting Tuesday
in Milwaukee. A look at chances of Rafael Furcal winning rookie of
the year. Only two other players have hit over .300 as
19-year-olds, Mel Ott and Cesar Cedeno. Also compare his stats to
other top rookies this year. (Stinson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-TRIAL _ ATLANTA _ Opening arguments expected to begin in
lewis case Tuesday. We talk importance of openings, some of the
players in the trial. Strategies if the defendants turn on each
other. (Torpy, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (s) Sports categories.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-SCENE _ BALTIMORE _ They don't think he's guilty, they're
leery of ``cracker justice'' and they want him back home. Football
fan or not, most here say Ray Lewis - hometown favorite and
linebacking terror - is innocent. From Mother's Federal Hill Grille
(home of Free Ray Lewis t-shirts) to Severn (home of infamous limo)
to Owings Mill (home of Ray and Ravens), the message is clear: Ray
is innocent. A recent poll confirms. But the city - and the team -
prepare for life without Ray. A scene-setter for trial's first day.
(Chapman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (s) Sports categories.
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPICS
</P>
<P>
   OLY-WEIGHTLIFTER _ SAVANNAH, Ga. _ Profile of Cheryl Haworth of
Savannah. She is a sure bet to win a medal in the Sydney Games in
weighlifting. She's also an accomplished artist. (Tierney, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 60. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   The following stories are from an Olympic preview section Austin
published Saturday. All stories are available via a budget tool
search with a run date of 0520.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SWM-WALKER _ AUSTIN _ Mark Spitz. Matt Biondi. Neil Walker?
At first glance it seems odd to pair Walker's name with those of
some of the greatest swimmers in U.S. history. This March at the
short-course world championships in Athens, Greece, Walker joined
Spitz and Biondi as the only men ever to cop seven medals at a
major international competition. Five of the medals were gold and
the other two silver. In the process of collecting that haul,
Walker set not one, not two, but five world records. (Maher, Austin
American-Statesman). 25. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-DIV-WALKER _ AUSTIN _ Dumais has been called America's next
big hope indiving. His stunning success as a young diver earned him
quick comparisons to Greg Louganis, a double gold-medal winner in
the 1984 and1988 Olympics. The 2000 Olympics are fast approaching,
and Dumais is still be out there playing pickup basketball at the
University of Texas, trying to show people on the rec courts that
he's got some game. (Maher, Austin American-Statesman). 20.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-CYC-MCRAE _ AUSTIN _ A cyclist from Plano and Austin is back
in Europe and keeping an eye on Sydney, Australia, for the upcoming
Olympic Games. We're talking Chann McRae, not Lance Armstrong, the
reigning Tour de France champion. McRae, a boyhood friend of
Armstrong, is poised to make more of a name for himself this year.
(Maher, Austin American-Statesman). 17.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-DIV-WILKINSON _ AUSTIN _ Texas All-American Laura Wilkenson
is diving again after breaking a foot. (Maher, Austin
American-Statesman). 20.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-FORTNER _ AUSTIN _Lately, when it comes to the USA in the
Olympic Games, there is always pressure for gold and nothing else.
It's UT Nell Fortner's turn in the hot seat as she will be one of
the coaches for the women's team. (Maher, Austin
American-Statesman). 15-18.
</P>
<P>
   GOLF
</P>
<P>
   GLF-OPEN-QUALIFYING _ With visions of ``Tin Cup'' dancing in
their heads, more than 140 golfers gathered at Braelinn Golf Club
in Peachtree City on Monday to begin their quest for a berth in the
U.S. Open. They came in all shapes and sizes, from all walks of
life, with shared dreams -- shoot four good rounds of golf to
qualify for the opportunity to tee it up with the pros at Pebble
Beach in mid-June. That's the unique thing about the U.S. Open. If
your handicap is inside a 2, you plop down $150 and take your shot
at advancing from one of the hundreds of pre-qualifying sites. Four
survived at Braelinn. . . with regional qualifying tests to come.
(Manasso, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   MISCELLANEOUS
</P>
<P>
   HANDICAP-PLAYER _ Salem high school senior Mandy Young suffers
from an immune-deficiency disorder so rare that she is the only
person who has been diagnosed with it. It cost her her left leg.
But neither the loss of the leg nor the possibility that a minor
injury like a cut could become life-threatening has kept her from
playing softball. She is one of the best hitters on her Atlanta
area recreation league team and maintains a radiant outlook on life
regardless of her circumstances. (Hildreth, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION FOR SUBSCRIBERS OF THE NYT NEWS
SERVICE
