<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2568 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-DEBATE-0523-CO     05-22 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-DEBATE-0523-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICAN ELECTION GETS WILDER AS PRESIDENTIAL DEBATE PLAN FLOPS
 &HT;    (450&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The most competitive presidential race in Mexico's
modern history turned wilder with the sudden cancellation of a
pivotal debate that was scheduled for Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The debate was expected to feature the top three candidates, but
was called off late Saturday night after negotiators failed to
agree on a format.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday representatives of the candidates met again to see if
they could salvage the event, which would have been the second
televised debate held during this country's contentious race for
president.
</P>
<P>
   But the meeting _ whose outcome was unknown as of Monday evening
_ was convened only after the candidates publicly labeled one
another as cowards who foiled the debate.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of the debate was another example of the tense,
unpredictable nature of this high-stakes campaign. This is the
first time in 71 years that Mexico's ruling Revolutionary
Institutional Party, or PRI, is behind in some opinion polls and
could lose the presidential election, scheduled for July 2.
</P>
<P>
   Observers appear divided on who had the most to lose by backing
out of a debate.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI and its candidate Francisco Labastida Ochoa ``are the
ones that are chicken,'' said Federico Estevez, political analyst
with Mexico's nonpartisan Center for Research and Development.
</P>
<P>
   But Labastida tried to pin blame on Vicente Fox Quesada, a
former Coca-Cola executive and candidate of Mexico's conservative
National Action Party, or PAN. Fox is ahead in some polls and poses
a very real threat to Labastida, and the PRI's seven-decade
dominance.
</P>
<P>
   Fox insisted on having a U.S.-style debate with three
interviewers asking questions during the 90-minute encounter. He
also objected to a plan by Mexico's television networks to air the
debate on stations with the least number of viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida, who rejected the idea of a panel, accused Fox of
wanting close friends of his to be included as interviewers and
said a panel format wouldn't be a traditional debate.
</P>
<P>
   Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the candidate of Mexico's leftist
Democratic Revolutionary Party, or PRD, also blamed Fox for being
inflexible. He too rejected the idea of a panel.
</P>
<P>
   Javier Trevino, a Labastida adviser, called Fox ``two-faced''
and ``ridiculous'' and suggested Fox wanted to sabotage the debate
so he wouldn't have to face attacks as the campaign heads toward
the final stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``His clear intention was not to have the debate,'' Trevino
said. ``He thinks he's running for president of his high school.''
</P>
<P>
   Estevez , however, said Fox's terms for the debate _ especially
a bigger audience _ made sense given his momentum as a leading
challenger.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the frontrunner now. Why should he expose himself? He
should at least get better channels or a better format,'' Estevez
said.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference on Sunday, Fox accused Labastida of being
afraid.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want to confront questions from various
interviewers because they can't defend 70 years of corruption,
crime and poverty,'' he said. ``They don't want the freedom of
spontaneous questions for the candidates because they are afraid
they won't know any answers. They want questions to be sent to them
ahead of time.''
</P>
<P>
   On a Sunday night broadcast on Mexico's Television Azteca, the
country's second largest network, Fox jeered at Labastida while
both were being questioned about the debate's collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida, blaming Fox, said in a statement: ``I'm going to
fulfill my promise that the debate happens. The debate is not an
obligation for candidates, but it is a right that the people have.
I'm going to defend that right.''
</P>
<P>
   The candidates held their first debate in April. Fox was widely
judged in Mexico City to be the winner of that encounter, which
included Labastida, Cardenas and three other minor candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts agree that in a second three-way debate Labastida and
Cardenas would have both reserved most of their attacks for Fox.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Ferriss' E-mail address is: susanf(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.wola.org for the Washington Office on Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
