<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2572 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AP-KOREA-MEDIA-2NDTAK     05-22 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP-KOREA-MEDIA-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: Gun Ri.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bowman; Joseph L. Galloway, the writer of the U.S. News article;
and Ed Offley, the Washington bureau chief of the stripes.com Web
site discovered personnel records flatly contradicting Daily's
assertions about his military service: that he was a prisoner of
war, that he had received certain decorations, and, most important,
that he served with H Company, the unit of the 7th Cavalry Regiment
directly involved in the No Gun Ri incident.
</P>
<P>
   How solid is the new evidence?
</P>
<P>
   It has raised serious doubts among some reporters who trusted
Daily. He has responded to very few questioners. When Galloway
reached him, Daily raised the possibility that his memory had been
affected by emotional trauma or his anti-depressant medication.
</P>
<P>
   Charles J. Hanley, one of the AP reporters, said he originally
found Daily's accounts of events convincing, and trusted his
documentary evidence: a driver's license placing him with the
company in March 1950, a letter home naming his company commander,
and an H Company ceremonial Christmas dinner menu from Dec. 25,
1949. Not until recently did Hanley get documentation of the
conflicting personnel records.
</P>
<P>
   Hanley said this past weekend: ``There is a discrepancy in the
sketchy military record of one of our more than 40 sources. We are
trying to get to the bottom of it. But this source provided no
essential information for our report on No Gun Ri.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no question, however, that the newly discovered
personnel records cast doubt on Daily's claims, not only about No
Gun Ri but about his entire military career.
</P>
<P>
   How important is Daily? AP's executive editor, Jonathan Wolman,
said in a statement last week: ``Serious questions involve veteran
Ed Daily. We spoke to soldiers who put him at the scene and have
reviewed the documentation he offered for his role.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``If it turns out that he and those records deceived
us, we will be extremely regretful, and saddened for him. But the
tale of No Gun Ri does not fall on the words of Daily.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanley points out that Daily is not quoted until the 56th
paragraph of the original account. And he said that several other
veterans confirmed the basic fact of the killing before Daily did.
</P>
<P>
   However, Stephen G. Smith, the editor of U.S. News, describes
Daily as ``the linchpin'' of the wire service's original report.
``He's the one who ties it all together,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Because the AP account depends on what Smith calls ``a mosaic of
partial quotes,'' the fact that Daily's three quotes were vivid,
full sentences dealing with the event, the orders and the veterans'
feelings of guilt made him more crucial than the other veterans
interviewed, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Few of those skeptical of the overall report mention the South
Korean witnesses, who are also quoted at some length.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these South Koreans are seeking reparations, a fact
mentioned with some irritation by two veterans interviewed by The
New York Times last week. Few journalists have reinterviewed the
South Koreans.
</P>
<P>
   But Hanley bristles at the idea that their quest for reparations
casts doubt on their memories. ``Frankly,'' he said, ``it is
analogous to questioning the right of Holocaust victims to seek
some token of reparation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rules
</P>
<P>
   Amid Fear, Were There Orders to Kill?
</P>
<P>
   Aside from being the public face of No Gun Ri, Daily is also one
of three former soldiers who tell the AP _ either in the original
report or in a video on the wire service's Web site _ that their
commanders on the scene ordered them to fire. He told the AP: ``The
command looked at it as getting rid of the problem in the easier
way. That was to shoot them in a a group.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of orders is crucial to determining whether the
killings were simply lethal overreaction by young soldiers scared
that enemy troops were hidden among the civilians, or whether they
constituted a war crime.
</P>
<P>
   A second soldier from H Company, Eugene Hesselman, was quoted as
saying that the company commander, Capt. Melbourne C. Chandler, had
said: ``To hell with all those people. Let's get rid of all of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. News points out that H Company's morning report for July
27, the summary of a unit's activity the day before, listed
Hesselman as having been wounded on July 26. But its attempts to
reach Hesselman proved unsuccessful. Hesselman, in an interview
long before the name of No Gun Ri was widely known, had told the AP
that he had a small shrapnel wound and declined to be evacuated.
</P>
<P>
   Galloway, however, said that the medical battalion's morning
reports indicated that Hesselman had been evacuated to the medical
unit on July 26, the day of the massacre. However, the morning
report of July 27 does not indicate when that transfer occurred _
before or after the shooting, before or after any order might have
been given.
</P>
<P>
   The third veteran to mention orders, George Preece, does so in a
videotaped interview with Hanley. In an interview with The
Lexington (Ky.) Herald-Leader days after the AP released its
original report on Sept. 29, Preece retracted the statement, and he
has since denied that any orders were given.
</P>
<P>
   But Hanley said on Friday that he now has interviews with 10
former GIs confirming that there were direct orders. As for the
retractions and rollbacks of some veterans on the details and even
the existence of the killings, Hanley said he believed that the
former GIs had come under pressure from fellow veterans, or were
worried about possible war-crimes charges.
</P>
<P>
   Hanley also points out that no veteran came to AP volunteering
information for the original article.
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``These guys were called cold,'' and remembered details
of the events that in many cases matched the details the South
Koreans had given.
</P>
<P>
   Hanley also says that arguments about on-the-scene orders
overlook two general orders from top commanders. The 1st Cavalry
Division headquarters on July 24 had issued an order saying: ``No
refugees to cross the front line. Fire everyone trying to cross
lines. Use discretion in case of women and children.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. News made no reference to these general orders.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he would frame his account differently if he had
to do it again, Galloway replied: ``If I had time to do the other
interviews and sit back and ponder, I might have written it
differently. But still, as it stands, not bad. I think we did a
good job in the time that we had. I stand behind it. I think in the
end, when the investigation is over and done, there will be a lot
more holes shot in the AP story.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he meant by ``in the time we had,'' Galloway said he
was trying to get his piece published before Offley and Bowman.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, the crucial centerpiece of the AP report, the
American soldiers killed at least 100 Korean civilians _ possibly
under direct orders _ has been chipped but hardly shattered by the
latest revelations.
</P>
<P>
   Herman Patterson, a rifleman in the 2nd Battalion, said in an
interview with The New York Times last week: ``Unfortunately, the
incident took place. Numbers are not known exactly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
