<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2577 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-COURT-PLAYBOY-HNS &LR;      05-22 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-PLAYBOY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COURT STRIKES DOWN TIME LIMIT ON CABLE SEX SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court, siding with Playboy
Entertainment Group, on Monday struck down a federal law designed
to shield children from accidental exposure to erotic cable
programs that their parents have not chosen to receive.
</P>
<P>
   In a 5-4 decision, the court agreed with Playboy that the law
was too broad and violated the First Amendment rights of cable
viewers to receive sexually explicit programs.
</P>
<P>
   The law required cable operators that don't fully scramble, or
block, sex-oriented networks for nonsubscribers to limit those
channels' ``indecent'' programs _ even to paying subscribers _ to
the hours between 10 p.m. and 6 a.m. when children are probably not
watching television.``Basic speech principles are at stake in this
cases,'' Justice Anthony M. Kennedy wrote for the court. ``The
history of the law of free expression is one of vindication in
cases involving speech that many citizens may find shabby,
offensive, or even ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said that the broadcasting of indecent material into
homes was an area the government could ``address'' but that it
needed to do so in ``a way consistent with the First Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's opinion was joined by Justices John Paul Stevens,
David H. Souter, Clarence Thomas and Ruth Bader Ginsburg.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, ending a dispute over regulating cable systems
</P>
<P>
   that fail to fully scramble signals for nonsubscribers, was
hailed as a victory over government censorship and attacked as an
</P>
<P>
   abandonment of impressionable youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   Playboy Chairwoman Christie Hefner said, ``We have maintained
all along that (the law) was unconstitutional, unnecessary and
impractical. We felt it was an intrusion on individual choice by
the federal government.''Daniel Brenner of the National Cable
Television Association, added that the ruling ``takes into account
the needs of viewers who want this programming and those who do
not. Both can be
</P>
<P>
   accommodated, and cable is committed to making sure such
channels
</P>
<P>
   are blocked for viewers who don't want them,''
</P>
<P>
   But Janet LaRue, an attorney with the conservative Family
Research Council, called the ruling an ``outrage'' and added,
``It's a sad day when the protection of children takes a back
</P>
<P>
   seat to the profits of pornographers.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress passed the law, the Communications Decency Act, in 1996
to address the concerns of parents who complained that a technical
problem known as ``signal bleed''_ in which sound and distorted
images from sexually explicit channels are not completely blocked
electronically _ was allowing their children to view adult
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Later that year, Playboy Entertainment Group, a cable TV spinoff
of the magazine, challenged the law. The company argued that it was
regulatory overkill and restricted adults' access to
constitutionally protected speech.
</P>
<P>
   Playboy also contended that the problem of signal bleed was
present only in some areas of the country and that the cable
operators had offered subscribers a free special box that fully
blocked adult programming. Therefore, the company said, a blanket,
across-the-board ban on those types of channels during daytime and
early evening hours was inappropriate and unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 a special three-judge federal district court in
Wilmington, Del., agreed with Playboy, saying that less restrictive
alternatives _ the free blocking boxes _ were available to address
the issue. Therefore, the panel said, the law's requirement that
cable operators limit the viewing time of indecent shows was
``overly burdensome'' and therefore unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The court said giving adequate notice of the blocking-box
alternative would be less restrictive than barring adult-oriented
programs in the daytime.
</P>
<P>
   In its direct appeal of that decision to the Supreme Court, the
Clinton administration argued that without the law, children whose
parents did not subscribe to such channels would often be able to
see and hear raunchy programs that haven't been properly scrambled.
</P>
<P>
   The government's brief included testimony from a Florida woman
who said she found her 7- and 8-year-old children and a playmate
one afternoon watching the Spice channel, with scenes of a couple
seemingly having sex.
</P>
<P>
   The problem occurs in as many as 39 million homes with 29
million children, a Justice Department lawyer told the court during
arguments last November.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Supreme Court affirmed the lower court's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cable systems have the capacity to block unwanted channels on
a household-by-household basis,'' Kennedy said. ``Targeted blocking
is less restrictive than banning, and the government cannot ban
speech if blocking is a feasible and effective means of furthering
its compelling interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the dissenters, Justice Stephen Breyer said the
majority's decision ``threatens to leave Congress without power to
help the millions of parents who do not want to expose their
children to commercial pornography.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Sandra Day
O'Connor, Antonin Scalia joined Breyer.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bruce Fein, a constitutional law scholar here, said the close
5-4 decision showed that the court is struggling with how to deal
with new technologies, such as the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology makes it difficult protect children without
blocking out material constitutionally protected to the parents,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the Supreme Court declared unconstitutional a federal
law making it a crime to send or display indecent material on the
Internet in a way available to minors. The unanimous decision
marked the court's first effort to extend the principles of the
First Amendment into cyberspace and to confront the nature of a
new, and an unfamiliar medium.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
