<HEADER>
A2584 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FISHING-WEATHER-HNS &LR;      05-22 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHING-WEATHER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SUDDEN GULF STORMS DON'T DISSUADE FISHING ENTHUSIASTS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN GOODSPEED  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKPORT, Texas _ The best-laid plans of mice and fishermen
often go astray.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Scottish poet Robert Burns would have written if he
had ever anticipated an angling trip for months only to arrive at
the Gulf coast at the same time as a storm.
</P>
<P>
   But fishing guides can be as determined as the proverbial
postman: Neither rain, nor sleet, nor wind ... If the client wants
to go fishing badly enough, four Rockport guides agree they're
ready to brave rain and rough seas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fish are already wet anyway,'' said Phillip Durst of Just
One More Guide Service. ``This is a popular spot for people from
San Antonio, Austin and Houston, and they've been planning their
trip for months. If it's raining or bad weather is on the way, I'll
ask them at the dock if they want to go or wait for another day.
Most of them say, `Let's go get it' _ unless it's lightning.''
</P>
<P>
   It's usually tough to get guides to agree on some matters, but
they're united on lightning _ it's a bad thing. Sometimes, however,
it's difficult to convince clients to call it a day when they're
catching fish between crashes of thunder, said Rocky Rouquette of
Tecolote Charter Services.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing that some people don't understand,'' Rouquette
said. ``But what's there to understand? You have a graphite rod in
your hand and your foot in saltwater. You can get over being wet,
but you're not going to get over being struck by lightning.''
</P>
<P>
   Storms can build quickly on the Gulf of Mexico and put a damper
on a trip _ or even force a run for safety. No guide wants to put
himself or clients into dangerous situations and all pay close
attention to the weather.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, even quiet clouds can offer warning signs.
</P>
<P>
   Hector Saucedo of Bahia Rica Adventures recalls taking a doctor,
his wife and two sons out last Father's Day after the rain stopped.
They started catching fish immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I looked over and saw the lines up off the water,''
Saucedo says, explaining that static electricity will build before
a thunderstorm. ``I looked at the father, and his hair was standing
straight up. I said, `We've got to get out of here. It's ready to
start bolting.' He didn't want to go, so I pulled my hat off and my
hair stood up. He said, `Is that bad?' And this guy's a surgeon. I
said, `What do you think?'''
</P>
<P>
   They raced back to the dock just as sky broke open with wind,
rain and lightning.
</P>
<P>
   Graphite fishing rods also can let you know that something is in
the air, said Larry Ebest of Backwater Safari Guide Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's enough static electricity in the air, you can put a
graphite rod up to your ear and hear it creaking,'' Ebest said.
``The pole becomes a lightning rod. You know something is about to
happen, and it would be best to head on in.''
</P>
<P>
   Guides set their own policies for what to do if a trip is
canceled because of weather. Some will refund the deposit, but most
would rather reschedule the trip.
</P>
<P>
   They all agree that going ahead with a trip in foul weather is a
judgment call between the guide and client. If it's just raining
and the wind is not too high, they'll tough it out if the client
wants to. If a trip is cut short because of weather, then the guide
must decide whether to charge or reschedule, and most understand
that a client does not want to feel cheated.
</P>
<P>
   Bad weather is like walking a tightrope, though, Saucedo said.
If the guide says no, some clients might feel that he doesn't want
to go. If he says yes, they could think he just wants to drive them
around, let them get so miserable they'll call it off and the guide
will still keep the money, knowing they were not really going to
fish in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   That brings up the biggest question _ do fish still bite in the
rain?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's usually not a good day when it's raining,'' Durst said.
But it's still possible to get a limit of reds or specks, he added.
</P>
<P>
   A hard rain will push the baitfish down so you'll have to fish
deeper. If there was a thunderstorm the night before, the fishing
might shut down until midafternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't think fish will bite if it's raining,''
Ebest said. ``But if you're not fishing, it's impossible to know if
they're biting.''
</P>
<P>
   Saucedo agreed, adding that wind and rough water will make it
harder to reach certain sweet spots, but they'll still be biting.
</P>
<P>
   So if you've canceled your best-laid plans and you're pacing
like a rat in a trap in your hotel room when your stomach starts
growling, just remember: You're not the only one who's hungry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fish are going to eat every day, even in the rain,'' Saucedo
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
