<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SCI-MEDICAL-CONSUMERISM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO EASY DECISIONS FOR A MAN OF DECISION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeats to fix byline.)   (The Science Times)  
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In quitting the Senate race last week, New York Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani discovered that choosing a therapy for prostate cancer was
a far more daunting effort than he had expected. Giuliani said he
had to focus entirely on the decision, letting his immediate
political future fall by the wayside.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's difficulties spring largely from a radical change in
the relationship between patients and their doctors. Americans have
traded in paternalism for medical consumerism after fighting for a
greater voice in making critical decisions about their care. That
has not come without cost.
</P>
<P>
   Making crucial decisions in one's own care has become
increasingly complex. Tests now detect certain diseases like
prostate cancer earlier, increasing chances for cure. Treatment
choices are wider. Yet, for prostate cancer, doctors may not know
which treatment is best.
</P>
<P>
   The changes are forcing many people to assume a degree of
responsibility for their care unknown to their parents, and many
younger people are unprepared for the difficulties in making the
choices.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's is a case in point. His father died in 1981 at 73 of
prostate cancer. The full facts in the elder Giuliani's case are
not known. But in that era, prostate cancer was usually not
detected until it had spread and was well beyond any hope of cure.
It also was an era when doctors decided the treatment, and few
patients questioned them.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, doctors rarely told patients that they had
cancer. In this new era of medical consumerism, most cancer
patients are told they have the disease.
</P>
<P>
   A blood test known as PSA, for prostate specific antigen, led to
the detection of Giuliani's prostate cancer at an early stage. The
test did not exist in his father's lifetime. Thus, its use has
forced Giuliani to make decisions his father never had to consider.
</P>
<P>
   Prostate cancer patients like Joe Torre, the New York Yankees
manager, have told Giuliani about their experiences. With his
take-charge personality, Giuliani has sought medical advice from a
number of doctors throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani found that urologists and radiation oncologists tend to
champion their specialties and present medical information in
subtle ways intended to sway patients to their fields. Those
circumstances made the effort of becoming an informed patient
complex, frustrating and overwhelming, Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   Patients differ in how they make medical decisions. Many
prostate cancer patients who wish to start treatment immediately
settle on one within days of learning the diagnosis. Many others,
over their heads in the morass of medical nuance, need more time.
</P>
<P>
   When Giuliani learned he had prostate cancer he was caught up in
crucial political and personal decisions. He found himself
simultaneously tackling four jobs _ mayor, unofficial candidate for
the Senate, dealing with marital difficulties, and being a cancer
patient.
</P>
<P>
   Three or so weeks would be enough time to choose a treatment and
judge how it would affect his campaigning, Giuliani thought in his
initial timetable. But his other problems distracted him from
focusing on the medical decision, he said. In confronting his
mortality, he found making medical decisions much tougher than
making budgetary or legal decisions and the most difficult and
painful of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not prostate cancer was the sole reason for his
dropping out of the race, there is no question about the difficult
choices Giuliani confronted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't understand the impact of this,'' Giuliani said.
Unanswered Questions
</P>
<P>
   Prostate cancer ranks second to skin cancer as the most common
malignancy among men. It usually grows slowly and can take years
before proving fatal. The problem is that doctors do not know how
to tell which patient most needs early aggressive treatment and
which can wait. Thus, many more men are treated for prostate cancer
than would die from it had they not been treated at all. Under such
circumstances, doctors do not consider it risky for patients to
spend several weeks choosing a therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, choosing a therapy for prostate cancer is particularly
difficult because the crucial head-to-head studies that could
provide important answers have not been carried out. Instead,
patients have to rely on broad statistics that many feel may not
apply to them.
</P>
<P>
   Men with prostate cancer find themselves in a position similar
to the situation women with breast cancer faced a few years ago.
Decisions eased only when crucial studies were completed to show
that lumpectomy plus adjuvant drugs and radiation was an effective
alternative to radical mastectomy for early breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   2 POSSIBLE TREATMENTS
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani is considering two main treatments: surgery to remove
the prostate or radiation therapy. Until last Friday, Giuliani had
to speculate about which therapy would get him back on the
senatorial campaign trail fastest and with fewest complications.
</P>
<P>
   Many men can do some routine desk work a few days after prostate
surgery. But it takes at least three weeks before they can travel,
and then many must deal with urinary incontinence and frequent
diaper changes. Adding to the complexity is that after surgeons
remove a prostate, pathologists look at it through a microscope for
malignant cells. If they find the cancer has spread, radiation
therapy may also be needed.
</P>
<P>
   There are two types of radiation for prostate cancer, and
neither would seriously interfere with Giuliani's work as mayor.
Yet each would have posed problems for campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   In one form of radiation, doctors use needles for permanently
implanting radioactive ``seeds'' into the prostate. Radiation wears
off after several months. Because such patients emit tiny amounts
of radiation, they are warned to avoid continued close contact with
pregnant women and children. That is not a major problem for most
people. The amount of radiation in a fleeting exposure can be less
than the amount of radiation in the environment. Nevertheless, if
blown out of proportion, it could become a liability for a
hand-shaking, baby-kissing politician in a campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The second form is external radiation. For prostate cancer, it
is usually given five days a week for eight weeks. During that
time, a patient can work regular hours. But the patient is confined
to the geographic area in which he is being treated.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, Giuliani weighed such factors heavily as a
prospective senatorial candidate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
