<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Outlook gives birth to new lists of stocks to own
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that the bull market has turned decidedly bearish, business
and personal finance magazines are offering advice on which stocks
to buy in a down market.
</P>
<P>
   Smart Money (June), The Wall Street Journal's personal finance
magazine, recommends ``the magnificent seven,'' a group of ``small,
fast-growing companies that, thanks to this spring's market
meltdown, happen to be selling at big discounts.''
</P>
<P>
   They are Allaire (ticker symbol ALLR), Global Industries (GLBL),
Globix (GBIX), Inhale Therapeutic (INHL), Medicis Pharmaceutical
(MRX), Pinnacle Systems (PCLE) and Zoran (ZRAN).
</P>
<P>
   Kiplinger's Personal Finance (June) says the market's spring
gyrations proved once again the value of diversification. The
magazine lists 35 stocks in three portfolios designed to suit an
investor's personal style: aggressive (mostly small, fast-growing
tech companies); patient (established blue chip stocks); or
conservative (utilities and other high-yielding stocks).
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg Personal Finance (June) recommends that investors look
to ``business to business'' stocks, usually referred to simply as
B2B. These are companies with names like i2 Technologies (ITWO), a
company that designs software for inventory control. Others buy and
sell raw materials, parts, goods and services using the worldwide
Web.
</P>
<P>
   `Hot growth companies'
</P>
<P>
   Three metro Atlanta companies are on the latest Business Week
(May 29) list of 100 ``hot growth companies.''
</P>
<P>
   They are LHS Group, number 46, an Atlanta company that supplies
support software to phone companies, and which is being acquired;
Theragenics, number 73, a Buford company that makes radioactive
seeds used to treat prostate cancer; and Optio Software, number 78,
an Alpharetta company whose software customizes information for
delivery by fax, printer or e-mail. The No. 1 company is Direct
Focus, a Vancouver direct marketing retailer of sports equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Business Week said this year's diverse list of small businesses
proves ``you don't have to be a dot-com to be a dynamo.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Red Herring (June), which targets the technology
market, is out with its annual list of ``the 100 most important
companies in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   United Parcel Service, the only Georgia company on this list,
was cited because of the company's huge investment in technology.
Unlike most other lists, Red Herring doesn't rank the companies but
lists them in alphabetical order based on criteria ``borrowed from
venture capitalists and investment bankers.''
</P>
<P>
   Worth mentioning...
</P>
<P>
   Fortune (May 29) alerts business firms to the ``invasion of the
body snatchers,'' as headhunters and executive search firms are
called these days. If you're the boss, the body snatchers want your
best workers ``and they'll do anything to get what they're after.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Business Review (May/June) sees a disturbing trend in
corporate America: CEO churning. ``Top executives are rapidly
coming and going, keeping their jobs for shorter periods of time.
The reason? Most boards simply don't know what leadership means,
and thus they pick the wrong people to run companies,'' the
magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
