<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2608 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CABLE-SEX23-COX     05-22 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CABLE-SEX23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COURT, STRIKING SCHEDULE LIMITS, SAYS PARENTS CAN BLOCK SEXY TV
 &HT;    460&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It's up to parents to block sexually explicit cable
TV programming from their homes, the Supreme Court ruled Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Congress had restricted the hours of such programming to
late-night hours in order to protect children from ``signal
bleed,'' in which non-subscribers can see and hear snippets from a
supposedly scrambled X-rated channel.
</P>
<P>
   By a 5-4 vote, the justices ruled that the law was an
unconstitutional infringement of free speech. Parents can keep such
programming out of their homes simply by calling their cable
companies, Justice Anthony M. Kennedy wrote in the majority
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simply put, targeted blocking is less restrictive than
banning, and the government cannot ban speech if targeted blocking
is a feasible and effective means of furthering its compelling
interests,'' Kennedy wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, cable operators are required to comply to a
customer's request to completely block _ rather than just scramble
_ a signal. New televisions are also equipped with ``V-chips'' so
parents can eliminate channels or programs they find objectionable.
</P>
<P>
   As a practical matter, the decision means that more parents will
rely on these other remedies, predicted Eliot Mincberg, a legal
analyst for People for the American Way, a civil liberties advocacy
group.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are doing it already,'' said Dave Beckwith, a
spokesman for the National Cable Television Association. ``This
trap blocks out the signal entirely.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the cable company sends an installer to the
subscriber's house to put in the blocking device. Sometimes it can
be done through a phone call to the central office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on the system,'' said Beckwith. In either case, the
service is free to the subscriber.
</P>
<P>
   Beckwith said there would be some financial impact on cable
companies if large numbers of subscribers requested channel
blocking, since it costs more to block a signal than scramble one.
</P>
<P>
   Janet LaRue, an attorney for the Family Research Council, said
she is urging families to quickly call their cable companies for a
blocking device.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm deeply disappointed with this decision, which makes
protection of children take a back seat to the profits of cable
pornographers,'' she said. ``It's going to get worse. They let that
signal bleed for no other reason than to attract new customers.
It's free advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court decision upholds a lower court ruling, so
cable subscribers will see no difference in their service. The law
under question, part of the 1996 Communications Decency Act, has
been largely thwarted by legal challenges since its enactment. It
was enforced only from May 1997 to March 1998.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   William Kennard, chairman of the Federal Communications
Commission, said in a statement, ``In reviewing today's Supreme
Court decision, parents should remember that current law
specifically provides that cable customers can contact their local
cable companies and request that channels they find objectionable
be blocked from their homes at no cost.''
</P>
<P>
   The V-chip also gives ``parents the ability to block television
programming that is not fit for their kids to watch,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the court implied that this is an action better left to
parents than to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is no response that voluntary blocking requires a consumer
to take action, or may be inconvenient, or may not go perfectly
every time,'' wrote Kennedy. ``A court should not presume parents,
given full information, will fail to act.''
</P>
<P>
   However, in his dissenting opinion, Justice Stephen G. Breyer
said Congress was right to act because the availability of
voluntary blocking devices has failed to adequately protect
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``By finding 'adequate alternatives' where there are none, the
court reduces Congress' protective power to the vanishing point,''
Breyer wrote. ``This is not what the First Amendment demands.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy was joined in the majority by Justices John Paul
Stevens, David H. Souter, Clarence Thomas and Ruth Bader Ginsburg.
Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Sandra Day O'Connor
and Antonin Scalia sided with Breyer in the dissent.
</P>
<P>
   Because the court was so evenly split, and with moderates and
conservatives on both sides, there will few political
ramifications, Mincberg predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conservatives can't say, 'look what those liberal justices
have done,' and liberals can't say, 'look what those conservative
justices have done, ' `` he said.
</P>
<P>
   The case is U.S. v. Playboy Entertainment Group.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Supreme Court: www.supremecourtus.gov
</P>
<P>
   Federal Communications Commission: www.fcc.gov
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
