<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Tuesday, May 23 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-CABLE-TV (Washington) _ Declaring for the first time that
programming on cable television is entitled to the highest level of
First Amendment protection, the Supreme Court on Monday struck down
a federal law that required many cable systems to limit sexually
explicit channels to the late-night hours. The vote was 5-4, with
an unusual lineup of justices that reflected differing views both
on the extent of the problem the 1996 law was passed to address _
the unwanted ``bleed'' of signals from cable channels that a
household had not ordered _ and on the degree of constitutional
``flexibility'' the government should receive in its effort to
shield children from exposure to graphic sexual images. By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-LEBANON (Jerusalem) _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak's
long-planned withdrawal from southern Lebanon seemed to be suddenly
accelerating out of control Monday, with Hezbollah guerrillas
driving Israeli-allied militias out of border command posts and
northern Israeli residents fleeing south in fear of Hezbollah
rocket attacks. Israeli warplanes repeatedly bombed Hezbollah
followers moving into the border zone, killing five civilians and
wounding another 25, according to reports from Lebanon. Fearing
Hezbollah reprisals, the Israeli army ordered frontier residents
into bomb shelters, but hundreds chose instead to leave and drive
far out of Katyusha rocket range. By William A. Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE-ADS (Washington) _ With just two days to go before
Congress decides whether to upgrade economic ties with China, both
camps launched the final phase of one of the most intensive and
expensive political campaigns in years to recruit three dozen
undecided lawmakers who hold the key to victory or defeat. By
Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   DOCTORS-HEALTH (Washington) _ A look at the lobbying efforts by
doctors and drug companies concerning legislation on increasing
collective bargaining rights for physicians. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-GIELGUD (Undated) _ Sir John Gielgud, one of the great
actors of the English stage who enthralled audiences for more than
60 years with his eloquent voice and consummate artistry, died
Sunday at his home in Aylesbury, west of London. By Mel Gussow.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT1,2.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-DAVIS-JUSTICE (Sacramento, Calif.) _ In the 1998 campaign,
Gov. Gray Davis said he would be tougher on crime than his
Republican opponent. No one took that remark literally. But these
days, Democratic lawmakers say it sometimes seems as though Davis
was only slightly exaggerating. Halfway into his second year in
office, the governor is establishing himself as more of a
tight-fisted conservative on criminal justice issues than his
Republican predecessors, or any other elected official in
California _ if not the nation. The governor has essentially
removed the incentive that makes inmates model prisoners by
refusing any recommendation the parole board has made to grant a
release. He has announced that any judge he appoints should reflect
his sentiments ``or resign.'' He has blocked efforts to reform the
state's notorious ``three strikes'' law, which can put someone in
prison for life for stealing a bicycle if it is their third felony
conviction. And he has vetoed a modest bill that would grant the
press greater access to inmates in the state's notoriously
closed-door prison system, which has been rocked in recent years by
corruption scandals. By Evelyn Nieves. (1800 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT17.
</P>
</TEXT>
