<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2611 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-CANCER-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      05-22 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CANCER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN MTV PRANKSTER GETS (MOSTLY) SERIOUS ABOUT HIS CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Broadcast notes are at end of the review. Time, channel are
for New York area. Check local listings.) 
 By CARYN JAMES  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is so different from ``E.R.'' In fact, though ``The Tom
Green Cancer Special'' takes place largely in a hospital, following
its star as he is treated for testicular cancer, this
stomach-churning, affecting, original special is different from
anything that has ever been on television.
</P>
<P>
   The cult star of his MTV series, in which his camera captures
reactions to practical jokes that delight 15-year-olds, Green is
just beginning to emerge as a mainstream personality. Last week on
``The Tonight Show'' he put a squirming white mouse in his mouth,
re-enacting a scene from his current movie, ``Road Trip,'' and
horrifying Judge Judy, sitting next to him on the couch. With a
wide-eyed gaze and a goatee, he looks both innocent and devilish, a
style that perfectly expresses his personality.
</P>
<P>
   However adolescent his humor, though, it can be serious and
revealing as it shatters cultural assumptions. He turned a corner
with his recent special in which he took Monica Lewinsky to Canada,
where he grew up, ostensibly to buy fabric for her line of
handbags. He took her to dinner with his parents, the beleaguered
victims of so many of his pranks. The tone was poignant simply
because he was nice to her, neither fawning nor rude. (Think of how
different that attitude is.) Gradually, deeper resonances emerged:
Of course he was making fun of her, but they were both making more
fun of the people who came out to gawk at her; and it was a bit sad
to see how willing she was to go along.
</P>
<P>
   His ``Cancer Special'' is another breakthrough. It deserves its
viewer's warning; the show is excruciating to sit though because it
includes a long, unflinching look at the operation (no one except a
surgeon should ever get that close to human intestines) and a visit
to the pathology lab where we see the mashed-up testicle that had
been removed in a previous operation. Yet beyond its shock value,
the show is also a bizarre television landmark, willfully erasing
all boundaries between narcissism and art, black humor and
gross-out comedy, private and public lives, good taste and bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to live this secret life with one testicle,'' he
says here, explaining his reaction after the cancerous testicle was
removed. When he needed a second operation to remove and test lymph
nodes in his abdomen, he decided to take the cameras along. His
special is the video generation's equivalent of the confessional
memoir, a kind of public therapy in which self-revelation becomes a
survival strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Green is so known for pranks that the immediate reaction to the
news he had cancer was that he must be joking. The special is no
joke. A large part was filmed at the University of Southern
California, where he was treated. The chairman of the urology
department explains that while testicular cancer accounts for only
1 percent to 2 percent of male cancers, it is the most common form
among 15- to 35-year-old men. (Green is 28.)
</P>
<P>
   Such informative moments are not the point, though. The special
is shaped by nervous laughter. Green recruits those closest to him
and they gamely try to adopt his defensive, mocking attitude. He
goes to dinner with his parents, his girlfriend Drew Barrymore and
his two regular sidekicks from his show, Glenn Humplick and Phil
Giroux. He gives the waitress an elaborate, uncomfortable
explanation of his disease, and she replies, ``You want to see a
wine list?''
</P>
<P>
   This particular kind of cancer gives him plenty of opportunities
for jokes that would never make it on network television. Yet there
are also moments that seem unintentionally touching. Being fitted
for what he calls his burial suit (actually the suit he wore to the
Oscars), he asks for ``a last picture of me alive with my mother,
in a nice suit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom, you're going to live,'' his mother says, sweetly and as
cheerfully as she can, kissing him on the cheek. ``What did the
doctor tell you today? He said, `Tom, you're going to be fine.'''
</P>
<P>
   He looks close to tears, though he recovers by saying, ``You're
wrinkling my suit, Mom.''
</P>
<P>
   In the hospital he asks the doctor, ``Is it possible I'm going
to wake up screaming?''
</P>
<P>
   Seeing the operation is the price viewers pay for the rest of
the special. Even Green says, with his deadpan delivery, ``I was
kind of hoping it would have been funnier inside my body.''
</P>
<P>
   After that, there are some genuinely funny moments, including a
singalong ditty about the value of self-examination, complete with
lyrics on screen and a bouncing testicle over the words. Appearing
to a cheering crowd at the University of Florida, he has turned his
terrifying experience into comedy, helped by the fact that the
doctors found no trace of cancer during the second operation.
Still, he ends the special by saying, ``Hopefully, my cancer won't
come back and I won't die.'' Performers are rarely so chilling,
blunt or honest.
</P>
<P>
   To flip back and forth between the taboo-shattering Tom Green
and the staid ``Frontline'' would be to invite an extreme case of
cultural whiplash. Despite its eye-glazing title, though, ``The
Battle Over School Choice'' turns out to be a smooth, humanizing
primer on an issue that is both central to the presidential
campaign and deadly dull in the abstract. The main subject is
vouchers, with which the government pays for students to attend
private schools.
</P>
<P>
   Focusing on Cleveland, the evenhanded special presents voucher
students whose futures have been salvaged by the opportunity, as
well as others who attended a school whose founders absconded with
the government's money. There are interviews with Vice President Al
Gore, who opposes vouchers, and Gov. George W. Bush, who supports
them, but the documentary makes the point that there is less
difference between the candidates' views than their ads contend.
(And really, who is against higher standards and better education?)
</P>
<P>
   The failure of this otherwise lucid, engaging documentary is in
its modest ambition: It offers only glancing references to a
profound, underlying issue it is easier to ignore: how much the
battle over school choice is really about race and class.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE TOM GREEN CANCER SPECIAL
</P>
<P>
   10 p.m. ET Tuesday on MTV &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `FRONTLINE'
</P>
<P>
   `The Battle Over School Choice'
</P>
<P>
   10 p.m. ET Tuesday on PBS (Channel 13 in New York) &QL;
</P>
