<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2612 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-SYRIA-ARCHEO-ART-     05-22 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SYRIA-ARCHEO-ART-(1300)2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUINS ALTER IDEAS OF HOW CIVILIZATION SPREAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 (The Science Times)  
  
By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the northeastern corner of Syria, near the Iraqi border and
within sight of southern Turkey's Taurus Mountains, archaeologists
have begun excavations of an ancient settlement that lay on a major
trade route from Nineveh to Aleppo. The ruins from more than 5,500
years ago are telling them that previous ideas about the spread of
early civilization were more than likely wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The first trenches cut into the large 500-acre site, Tell
Hamoukar, have yielded strong evidence that centrally administered
complex societies in northern regions of the Middle East apparently
arose simultaneously but independently of the more celebrated
city-states of southern Mesopotamia, in what is now southern Iraq.
In the conventional view, civilization was thought to begin solely
in the south and then move north through trade and colonization.
</P>
<P>
   In an announcement of the new finds, Dr. McGuire Gibson, an
archaeologist at the Oriental Institute of the University of
Chicago, said, ``We need to reconsider our ideas about the
beginnings of civilization, pushing the time further back.''
</P>
<P>
   Other archaeologists familiar with the research agreed in
interviews last week that the Tell Hamoukar excavations confirmed
and should elaborate on a consensus that has emerged among scholars
in the last decade about the role of northern settlements in Syria
and Iraq and in southeastern Turkey in the development of
civilization. These settlements exhibited many of the attributes of
civilization _ monumental architecture, division of labor, social
stratification _ apparently before they had any significant contact
with people in the lower valleys of the Tigris and Euphrates
rivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very important excavation,'' said Dr. Gil J. Stein, an
archaeologist at Northwestern University. ``It fits in really
nicely with a picture that's been emerging, based on several other
excavation sites.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Dr. Guillermo Algaze, an archaeologist at the University of
California at San Diego, who had argued for a south-to-north
transplantation of early civilization, said that he now generally
agreed with the new interpretation. ``I've been eating a lot of
crow lately,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Excavations at Tell Hamoukar were started last summer by a joint
expedition of the Oriental Institute and the Syrian Directorate
General of Antiquities. Work will resume next month and will
probably continue for many years. The site promises an abundance of
artifacts, archaeologists said, not only because of its large size
but also because most of the material seems to be close to the
surface.
</P>
<P>
   Digging into the oldest layer of ruins uncovered so far,
archaeologists found traces of people living in villages at the
site as early as 4000 B.C. Within 300 years, the settlement had
grown into a prosperous town of at least 32 acres with ample
evidence of a well-organized society of the kind associated with
the early stages of civilization.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Gibson said, the town appeared to be enclosed by
a defensive wall 10 feet high and 13 feet wide. Such walls came
with civilization.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the walls the archaeologists dug up the remains of fine
pottery and several large ovens, shaped like igloos, evidence of
food preparation on an institutional scale. The same areas held
pieces of large cooking pots and animal bones and traces of wheat,
barley and oats for what must have been a bakery and also probably
a brewery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Preparing bread and food on such a scale is evidence of a
society in which somebody is organizing people and resources,''
Gibson said. ``You are building up a hierarchy, a social structure
that's a mark of civilization.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most telling evidence for an organized, stratified
society, archaeologists said, were the seals the people probably
used to mark containers of food and other goods. Some of the seals
are small, with only simple incisions or cross-hatching. Others are
larger, presumably for higher officials to stamp more valuable
goods. One of these stamping seals was in the form of a leopard
with 13 spots, and others were in the shape of deer, bears and
ducks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would propose that the larger, more elaborate seals with
figurative scenes were held only by the few people who had greater
authority, while the smaller, simply incised seals were used by
many more people with less authority,'' Gibson said. ``The
difference would be something like the signature of the regional
director of customs of Chicago compared to the rubber stamps that
say only `U.S. Customs.'''
</P>
<P>
   In southern Mesopotamia at this time, an expanding population
and increased food production from irrigation were changing the
social landscape even more drastically. Economies were being run by
increasingly centralized leadership. Agricultural villages grew
into urban centers, some of which were in time ruled by local
kings. This became known to scholars as the Uruk period, after one
of the more prominent of these southern city-states, more than 400
miles south of Tell Hamoukar, and it was the period that
established Mesopotamia as ``the cradle of civilization.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago archaeologists said they had found no pottery or
other evidence of Uruk influences on the Tell Hamoukar settlement
in the 3700-3500 B.C. period. Some Uruk-type pottery shows up
around 3200, by which time there was perhaps a substantial southern
Mesopotamian presence at the site.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Other excavations at Tell Brak, also in northeast Syria, and
Hacinebi and Arslantepe, in southeast Turkey, have also revealed
that complex societies had developed before any significant contact
with the Uruk people, Stein said.
</P>
<P>
   So when southern Mesopotamians did expand into the north in the
middle to late fourth millennium, Stein concluded, they ``came into
contact with northern polities that were already quite advanced
chiefdoms, even though they were not as large in scale as the
urbanized states of the south.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he now agrees with this view, Algaze cautioned that it
would be a mistake to allow ``the pendulum of thinking to swing too
far in the other direction'' and conclude that the northern
societies were comparable in their scale of development with those
in the south. Since the first writing presumably developed to
handle record-keeping for a centralized economy, he said, the fact
that writing originated in Sumer, in southern Mesopotamia,
indicated a more advanced society there.
</P>
<P>
   In a publication of the Oriental Institute, Gibson noted that a
few scholars were even suggesting that perhaps civilization began
not in southern Mesopotamia, but in the north, and that it
gradually made its way south.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we start revising our textbooks, however, we should
remember that there was an even earlier contact with people who had
come from southern Mesopotamia,'' he wrote, referring to a southern
culture in the Ubaid period, extending from 5500 to about 4000 BC
Some Ubaid pottery and other artifacts have been found scattered
throughout the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Richard Zettler, a University of Pennsylvania archaeologist
with extensive experience in Syria, said: ``I'm convinced that our
real focus now should not be on the Uruk period, but the Ubaid.
It's not a terribly well-known period.''
</P>
<P>
   For one reason, he said, remains from the Ubaid period are hard
to find in southern Mesopotamia. They are presumably buried deep
beneath Uruk sites or covered by river silt. Archaeologists may
have more luck looking for an earlier transition to complex
societies at sites in the north, perhaps including Tell Hamoukar.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson would make no promises. ``It's a very big site and it's
going to take a lot of digging,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
