<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2620 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-COURT-POLLUTION-HNS &LR;      05-22 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-POLLUTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SUPREME COURT ENTERS FRAY OVER SMOG RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Wading into one of the biggest environmental cases
in years, the Supreme Court agreed Monday to decide whether the
federal government can drastically cut smog and soot levels over
the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   The justices will review a lower court's decision to block the
Environmental Protection Agency from enforcing regulations it
adopted in 1997 to cut air pollution by 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Vickie Patton, the senior attorney at Environmental Defense, a
Washington-based lobbying group, said the court's decision _
expected sometime next year _ would end one of the most
controversial clean air cases in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lower court decision turned back EPA's clean air health
standards by disregarding more than 30 years of national clean air
policy,'' Patton said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   But Thomas Donohue, president of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce,
one of several business groups that sued the EPA over the rules,
said only Congress has the right to impose such ``wide-reaching''
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once and for all, the Supreme Court can put an end to EPA's
unconstitutional attempt to extend their regulatory power and
ignore the will of Congress,'' said Donohue, whose Washington-based
federation represents more than three million businesses.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the clean air rules in 1997, EPA Administrator
Carol Browner said the stricter standards would ``provide new
health protections to 125 million Americans, including 35 million
children.''
</P>
<P>
   If put into effect, the EPA's rules would have an immediate
economic impact in places _ mostly in the Midwest _ where old power
plants still burn coal. At the same time, Eastern states _ such as
New York, New Jersey and Connecticut _ that have complained for
years about drifting pollution from the Midwest could see
improvement in air quality after several years.
</P>
<P>
   The revised air standards limited the allowable level of ozone,
a component of smog, to 0.08 parts per million, instead of the 0.12
parts per million under the old requirement. And states for the
first time were required to regulate microscopic particulates, or
soot, from power plants, cars and other sources down to 2.5 microns
_ 28 times smaller than the width of a human hair.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA estimated that as many as 15,000 lives would be saved
annually by the cleaner air and that hundreds of thousands of cases
of asthma and respiratory ailments would be avoided.
</P>
<P>
   But the anti-pollution rules were fiercely opposed by a broad
coalition of businesses, from auto and steel manufacturers to
truckers and power plant operators. These groups said it would cost
$46 billion a year to comply with the new standards, and they
questioned whether the improvement in air would have much effect on
health.
</P>
<P>
   After lobbying efforts with the Clinton administration failed,
the business groups turned to the courts to block the standards. In
1998, a coalition of industry groups and three states _ Michigan,
Ohio and West Virginia _ sued the EPA in the U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a three-judge panel in that court ruled 2-1 that the
agency overstepped its authority. The appeals court panel said the
EPA had interpreted the 1990 Clean Air Act ``so loosely'' that it
unlawfully usurped Congress' legislative power. In October, the
full appeals court voted 6-5 against reviewing the decision,
leaving the ruling intact.
</P>
<P>
   The Clean Air Act authorizes the EPA to issue air quality
standards to protect human health. The law says the agency may set
pollution limits that ``accurately reflect the latest scientific
knowledge useful in indicating the kind and extent of all
identifiable effects on public health or welfare which may be
expected from the presence of a pollutant.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, the Clinton administration asked the Supreme Court
to take up the case. Solicitor General Seth Waxman called the lower
court ruling ``a radical departure from settled law'' and said that
loss of the clean air standards ``unnecessarily prolongs the
exposure of millions of Americans to unhealthy pollutant levels.''
</P>
<P>
   The court's last major environmental case was in 1997 when it
unanimously interpreted the Endangered Species Act to permit
lawsuits not only by people who think the government is doing too
little to protect threatened species, but also by those who think
that federal regulations have gone too far. The decision opened the
door to suits against regulators by businesses and property owners.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
