<DOCNO> NYT20000522.0285 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2622 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-E-PRIVACY23-COX     05-22 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-PRIVACY23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LAWS NEEDED TO PROTECT ONLINE PRIVACY, FTC SAYS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ So many Internet merchants are violating the
privacy of consumers that Congress must pass legislation to stop
the abuses, the Federal Trade Commission said Monday in a report to
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   For four years, the federal agency has monitoring privacy and
hoping businesses would curb themselves, but ``progress in
self-regulation has been disappointing,'' FTC Chairman Robert
Pitofsky said in a statement submitted with the report.
</P>
<P>
   Without regulations, companies are ``unlikely to provide online
consumers with the level of protection they seek and deserve,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pitofsky said that while nearly 90 percent of popular Web sites
offer some type of privacy disclosure, safeguards are weak.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we probe beneath the surface and assess compliance with
(recommended guidelines), a less-than-encouraging picture
emerges,'' he said. ``Only one in five of the busiest commercial
Web sites provides basic privacy protections.''
</P>
<P>
   The FTC's stinging report will be presented to the Senate
Commerce Committee on Thursday. But many Republican leaders believe
regulation would be premature in the young world of electronic
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quickest way to kill the Internet is to regulate it to
death,'' said Ken Johnson, a spokesman for Rep. W.J. ``Billy''
Tauzin, R-La., chairman of the House Commerce subcommittee on trade
and consumer protection. In general, GOP leaders ``believe we need
to move cautiously'' on legislation, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   But a group of Democrats, led by Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C.,
ranking member of the Senate Commerce Committee, Monday announced
they would introduce comprehensive privacy legislation to keep
companies from profiting from the sale of personal data gleaned
from unwitting consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ensuring privacy is good business, and establishing a federal
standard for these protections will allow us to address consumers'
concerns before they pass up the growing Internet marketplace
altogether,'' Hollings said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether such legislation could get traction in Congress this
year appears doubtful. Lawmakers already have a full plate of
technology-related legislation awaiting action. Moreover, Congress
plans a long summer recess during the political party conventions.
Then, with the fall elections coming up, lawmakers hope to end this
Congress by Oct. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Delaying a consumer protection bill for another year would
please electronic commerce companies, which have been lobbying
against regulations since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Pitofsky, who previously had supported self-regulation, now
wants the power to penalize companies that violate privacy
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Catlett, president of Junkbusters Corp., a New
Jersey-based group that promotes privacy legislation, said
legislative action is ``long overdue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a market failure,'' he said. ``The idea that the free
market will cure all privacy problems is no more plausible than the
idea that the market will cure all environmental problems.'' Only
the force of law can enforce privacy protections, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But industry trade groups reacted negatively to the FTC report.
``We believe the recommendations are overbroad, premature,
impractical and unnecessary,'' said the Online Privacy Alliance, a
trade group representing companies engage in electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Hollings proposal, companies operating on the Internet
would have to provide consumers with:
</P>
<P>
   _ Notice. Companies must clearly indicate how they collect
personal information and how they intend to use it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Consent. They must get the consumer's consent before
collecting or using consumers' personally identifiable information.
</P>
<P>
   _ Access. They must provide consumers with access to personal
information collected about them, and offer the opportunity to
correct, deny or supplement that information.
</P>
<P>
   _ Security. They must establish procedures to protect the
security and confidentiality of the information.
</P>
<P>
   For more information: www.ftc.gov
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
