</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000522.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2624 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-LIVER-COX     05-22 1306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New treatment, new hope
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   XENIA, Ohio _ The worst moment in Doug Yaus' ordeal might have
been the diagnosis of pancreatic cancer two years ago. As he sat on
the doctor's examining table, the words made him light-headed. He
had done enough research by then. ``You're history,'' was what he
heard, although the doctor didn't say quite that.
</P>
<P>
   ``That and the exploratory surgery,'' the 44-year-old Xenia man
says now. ``Those were scary.''
</P>
<P>
   The exploratory surgery could have ended his chance for a
life-saving liver transplant. It turned out that cancer in the bile
duct, the kind he really had, didn't offer much better prospects
than cancer in the pancreas. But Yaus beat those long odds by
qualifying for a clinical trial that might cure it. The catch was,
if so much as one tiny tumor migrated from his liver, Yaus was out
of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   So after getting zapped with radiation for about two weeks,
after nearly another week of radiation through a tube that snaked
down his throat all the way to his liver, after some low-dose
chemotherapy and 2 1/2 months of thinking he might actually be the
one in 100 to beat this disease, it would all come down to what the
surgeon found inside Yaus' abdomen.
</P>
<P>
   And you thought it was hard to wait for an exam grade or the bid
on the sale of your house? ``That was intense,'' Yaus says. ``You
know you might find out that not too far down the road, you're
going to meet your maker.''
</P>
<P>
   For 42 percent of the patients in the Mayo Clinic trial, the
hope ended there. The cancer went beyond their livers and they went
off the transplant list. But Yaus and 10 others in the experimental
protocol received transplants and they're all alive today. It has
been only a year for Yaus, but the average survival span is 44
months.
</P>
<P>
   Where most cancer treatments attack the tumor after surgery, Dr.
Gregory Gores decided to zap the bile-duct tumors before surgery.
It appears to work ``for a highly selected group of patients'' with
early-stage cancer, says Gores, who published his research in this
month's issue of the Liver Transplantation journal. ``Before this
point, no treatment options were available for this group of
patients.''
</P>
<P>
   As it happened, the misdiagnosis of pancreatic cancer was the
first step Yaus took toward medical history. He wasn't even in any
pain when he first went to his doctor. The whites of his eyes were
kind of yellow, his urine looked more like coffee and some
heartburn was wrecking his appetite, but he was still working
eight-hour days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt well enough to where you can shrug it off,'' he says.
The one thing that did bother him was the result he kept getting on
his ``Family Doctor'' software, a computer program that matched
symptoms with suggested diagnoses. Yaus kept varying the symptoms a
little, ``just in case I was being a hypochondriac,'' but the
answer on his computer stayed the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always came up, `See your doctor immediately,''' he says.
``You want to know the answers, but you're afraid of the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   His family doctor took blood tests and sent him to a liver
specialist, who took a variety of scans and samples and saw his
pancreas was enlarged. That typically happens when a tumor clogging
the bile duct causes bile to back up like an overflowing sink, but
all Yaus knew at the time was a doctor with degrees on his wall was
calling it pancreatic cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Right away he called Dr. Ken Smithson, a Dallas
gastroenterologist who was married to Yaus' cousin. Smithson told
him how to hook up with Baylor University in Texas or the Mayo
Clinic in Rochester, Minn. By the end of the day, a Wednesday, he
had an appointment at Mayo for Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The bile duct is a small tube connecting the liver to the small
intestine, enabling bile produced in the liver to facilitate
digestion in the intestine. It's about the width of a disposable
pen, so it doesn't take a very big tumor to block the duct and back
the bile up into the bloodstream. But by the time that excess bile
starts causing jaundiced skin, it's almost always impossible to
remove the cancer without ruining the liver and requiring a
transplant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is, even though you think you have removed all the
cancer, you can't get all the microscopic tumors,'' Gores says. The
cancer there is so aggressive that it can overrun the new liver or
other organs within weeks of a transplant. Because there aren't
enough donor livers for the people who could live a long time with
a new one, almost no one with bile-duct cancer is eligible for a
transplant.
</P>
<P>
   So the average person with bile-duct cancer lives for 13 months
after diagnosis, Gores says. It's not a common cancer, but it kills
nearly all of the 2,000 to 5,000 Americans it strikes each year.
Usually it's the byproduct of another liver disease, as it was for
pro football Hall of Famer Walter Payton, one of Gores' patients,
who died last fall.
</P>
<P>
   In order to make transplants feasible and extend that lifespan,
someone had to find a way to keep the cancer from returning.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer therapy usually takes place after surgery to remove the
cancer, says Gores, because, ``Most of the time, the surgeons can't
wait to do anything before surgery.'' That wasn't working for
bile-duct cancer because the cancer returned so quickly. By the
time a transplant patient recovered enough to withstand harsh
treatment, it was too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we started thinking, `What's the most rational thing we can
do before surgery?''' Gores says. ``For this particular tumor, it's
radiation.''
</P>
<P>
   Yaus was diagnosed in the first week of June 1998. Twice a day
for 15 days he had radiation beams fired at his tumor, and then
came the agony of having a wire-sized tube fished through his nose
and throat and stomach and intestine until it reached his bile
duct. For three days on each lobe of the bile duct, the tumor was
pelted with radioactive beads the size of a pencil lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It still amazes me today that they can do that,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the weeks of radiation, accompanied by low doses of
chemotherapy, nobody mentioned the fateful exploratory surgery to
come. Yaus had beaten big odds just to get this far. From 1993
through 1998, only 19 of the 918 Mayo patients with bile-duct
cancer were enrolled in the clinical trial.
</P>
<P>
   The operation was that August. Dr. Charles Rosen, the surgeon,
told Yaus, ``We could not see the tumor at all.'' It had been the
size of a golf ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't coherent enough to jump up and down and celebrate,''
Yaus says. ``But I knew what he was saying. I felt like I'd made
that final hurdle.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it took nine months to cross the finish line, weakened by
his damaged liver until he reached the top of the transplant
waiting list. ``You realize how important your family is in times
like those when you can't even get around by yourself,'' Yaus says
of his wife, Evelyn, and parents, Jack and Bonnie. When he spent
the last three months waiting at Mayo, someone was there nearly
every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of anxiety when that phone rings at 6 in the
morning and they say, `We've got a liver for you,''' he says. The
time had come. ``I thought, `Let's get it on.'''
</P>
<P>
   He noticed a difference right away. He didn't feel sickly when
he woke up. He wasn't so worn out. ``I just felt normal.'' He was
back working part time at Clarklift of Ohio, the Dayton forklift
manufacturer, three months after the transplant on May 14, 1999.
He's been full time since November.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty vibrant, isn't he?'' Gores says.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the man,'' Yaus says. ``He's the one who invented this
treatment. He made it all possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Contact Kevin Lamb e-mail at kevinlamb(at)coxohio.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
