<DOCNO> NYT20000522.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2628 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-22 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     IT'S BROKEN, BUT CAN IT BE FIXED? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ To make the 2004 presidential election more
exciting and encourage broader voter participation, a Republican
panel boldly proposes to tinker with the present front-loaded
primary system, which nobody likes very much.
</P>
<P>
   The party nomination contests this year were over by the March 7
primary round, eliminating all viable candidates but Vice President
Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush before half the states had
held primaries or caucuses. The compressed timetable gave the two
men with the biggest names and the most money an unfair advantage
over lesser-known rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Disenfranchising a huge chunk of the country is not the
democratic way.
</P>
<P>
   But the proposed alternative and other reforms that have been
periodically floated come with their own problems. For openers,
state legislatures that set the actual primary dates have their own
ideas about their importance in the electoral process and resist
being pushed around by national party do-gooders.
</P>
<P>
   A special Republican National Committee panel recently endorsed
a scheme to balance the primary calendar by letting the smallest
states hold their contests in March, confining middle-size states
to April and May and holding off the 12 largest states until June.
The GOP would try to enforce the new rules by slashing the size of
the convention delegation of any state that refused to cooperate.
This, however, would not be a good omen for party harmony in
affected states in the coming general election.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats are also unhappy with the present primary system
but are skittish about the proposed reform. They will stay away
from the issue for a while until they see how much turmoil it
causes in the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   The big states won't like being pushed to the back of the pack,
where their influence could be minimized by the earlier returns.
That's why the big guys moved up this year's primary dates in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   But other solutions that might be fair to all the states are not
necessarily the answer either.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious alternative is a shift to a national primary,
in which every state would vote for party candidates on the same
day. But this would make it even more difficult for lesser-known
candidates to gain traction, money and media exposure against the
giants. It would give every individual running only one shot at a
victory, not several chances in several states.
</P>
<P>
   The demands of campaigning nationwide should be saved for the
general election.
</P>
<P>
   And we can predict that the parties would still have to deal
with the stubborn insistence of Iowa and New Hampshire to go first.
That would retain their inflated influence over the presidential
contests despite their relatively unrepresentative constituencies
and size. But this is not a bad thing. These states offer upstart
candidates an opportunity to prove their merit through one-on-one
campaigning, which would not be possible in a truly national
primary, where the media and money would matter most.
</P>
<P>
   Controlled regional primaries, spread out over four months in a
rotating sequence every four years, might be a logical compromise.
It would allow the campaign to progress at an orderly pace.
However, directly pitting the political and economic interests of
one region against another is likely to be more divisive than
unifying. The candidates may divvy up the regions, hoping to make a
big impact where they are strongest. This is a formula for trouble.
The competitive strains between South and North, East and West are
traditional and natural. Codifying them can only further polarize
the country.
</P>
<P>
   The major push to revise the current crammed-together electoral
process comes from concern about voter apathy, which afflicts both
parties. The theory is that giving more people a chance to take
part in meaningful primaries or caucuses will make politics more
representative and less dominated by big donors and special
interests.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps it is not the primary system that is at fault.
Perhaps the candidates do not inspire enthusiastic support. Perhaps
the lack of an overriding emotional issue this year dampens public
interest. Perhaps campaigns in general go on too long. Perhaps the
excessive sums of money involved have turned us off. Perhaps in
this information age we are overloaded with charges and
countercharges that we cannot accurately assess.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps campaign finance reform is really the answer.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, just maybe, it is not necessary to change the primary
schedule. If that is so, it is necessary not to change it.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 1832EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000522.0292 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2631 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-HEAT-CHOKED-COX     05-22 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEAT-CHOKED-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Under pressure, Heat squeezed
 &HT;    By Greg Stoda
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ They can't take this anymore, and the stress of it all _
three playoff-deciding games in three years on their own court and
three losses to the same opponent _ is now, finally and absolutely,
as clear as a Miami Heat meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   It happened again Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Only this time, the Heat cracked not only at the end of the game
but beyond it.
</P>
<P>
   They cracked in going more than three minutes without scoring,
holding a six-point lead near the end of a game they needed to win
as desperately as they have ever needed anything on a basketball
floor.
</P>
<P>
   And then they cracked in the aftermath of an 83-82 loss to the
New York Knicks, who own Miami's mind and soul and heart, by
chasing and cursing officials Dick Bavetta, Dan Crawford and
Bennett Salvatore and blaming them for the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   The officials weren't responsible for Jamal Mashburn (3-of-15)
and Tim Hardaway (6-of-20) shooting miserably.
</P>
<P>
   The officials weren't responsible for the Heat missing 10 free
throws _ including the first five they attempted in the fourth
quarter _ or being outrebounded.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, the officials weren't responsible for the Heat
lying to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely,'' said Miami center Alonzo Mourning, ``we are the
better team.''
</P>
<P>
   That's denial.
</P>
<P>
   That's ignoring reality at a time of high stress.
</P>
<P>
   That's the Heat ... that's all that's left of and for them.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the Knicks have done to them.
</P>
<P>
   A wonderful rivalry _ probably the best in professional sport
right now _ should come to end with this Miami surrender. No one
should require further proof of New York's supremacy. Four
consecutive playoff series have been stretched to the limit by the
two opponents, and the Knicks have won the past three in Miami's
home.
</P>
<P>
   They have won big (by 17 points) and small (twice by one).
</P>
<P>
   They have won when a ball bounced in for them (Allan Houston
last year) and away for the Heat (Clarence Weatherspoon this year).
But it's over.
</P>
<P>
   The Heat were fragile before losing the final two games of this
series. Now, they're broken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been in 13 world championships,'' said Miami head coach
Pat Riley, ``and I have never been in a Finals series that has as
much intensity and as much effort as this series.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why the Heat's ranting about officials so diminishes
the competition and so defines their own submission to the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them dressed quickly and departed the funeral parlor of
a locker room. Others lingered to complain in vituperative diatribe
against the officials _ Hardaway in a no-questions statement about
``making them accountable'' or Mashburn, after leaving the court
spewing obscenities, in long and cathartic explanations about the
unfairness of having ``put in more work than any other NBA team
would ever think about'' and feeling somehow cheated.
</P>
<P>
   But the enduring picture will be of Mourning, around whom a new
Heat team almost certainly will soon begin to be constructed,
slumped in his cubicle or bent over holding his head in his hands.
He pushed Miami to a 25-16 lead by scoring almost as many points
(14) as the Knicks on baseline floater, a dunk, a rebound, another
dunk, a short jumper, a rebound and a long jumper.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, his 29 points and 13 rebounds and five
blocked shots weren't enough to save the Heat from a disaster that
will consume them.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Mourning was forced to pass the ball to Mashburn
with the game in the balance and forced to watch Mashburn, who he
said was ``wide open'' on the catch, swing it to Weatherspoon.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, he watched the rebound of Weatherspoon's miss go to
New York's Latrell Sprewell teetering almost out of bounds as the
Knicks screamed for a timeout that allowed them to then bite off
the last 2.1 seconds of Miami's season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think,'' Mourning said, ``we put more into this than they
did.''
</P>
<P>
   The Heat did no such thing, of course.
</P>
<P>
   They did something else ... something they have done time and
time and time again against the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   They cracked.
</P>
<P>
   gregstoda(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 1834EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000522.0293 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2633 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV28-NY     05-22 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DASH IT ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 28)  
(Eds: The misspelling of ``indispensable'' at the beginning of the
second-last graf is deliberate.) 
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics.) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The stately colon, the confiding parenthesis and the gently
pausing comma demand to know: What's behind today's big dash to the
dash? Why has this  &UR; lingua interruptus &LR;  _ expressing uncertainty,
jerking the reader around, setting up startling conclusions,
imitating patterns of speech _ come to dominate our prose?
</P>
<P>
   In the preceding paragraph, I used a pair of dashes to interrupt
a sentence and insert supplementary material that gave the question
meaning or _ to writers, at least _ urgency. I could as easily have
used a pair of parentheses, specifically designed for the purpose
of graceful interjection of useful explication.
</P>
<P>
   In the sentence beginning the previous paragraph, I could again
have used parentheses (``parens'' to friends) or even commas to
separate the mild interjection of ``to writers, at least,'' but I
didn't. Why not? Because I have fallen into the habit of trying too
often to make writing read like speaking.
</P>
<P>
   The spoken sentence is filled with uttered second thoughts,
changes of direction, lurches off on tangents and similar twists.
That's because we say what we think as we think it, and thoughts
have a way of tumbling over one another, and we stick them in our
flow of words as each notion comes to us.
</P>
<P>
   In this age of raw transcription, art strains to imitate life,
and artful writers feel the pressure to mirror the speech patterns
of yammering people by imitating their higgledy-piggledy outpouring
of unedited thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   That transcribed-speech technique is fine for writers of fiction
and is especially apt for playwrights and screenwriters who reveal
their characters' characters realistically through their speech.
Some characters blurt their thoughts, showing honesty; others
weasel their words, showing duplicity; yet others expostulate
grammatically but endlessly, showing off.
</P>
<P>
   Writers of drama must write speech, not writing, because real
people do not speak writing. Hence we have pauses, delays _ you get
my drift? _ half-stops, restarts, stammering and exclamatory grunts
(ugh!) and drifting off into pre-dot-com ellipses .... To put this
speech in written form _ that is, to transcribe it _ we have seen
the powerful punch _ pow! right in the kisser _ of illustrative
punctuation.
</P>
<P>
   Good dramatic writers are in favor of whatever turns the reader
on. In an 1863 poem, the poet Emily Dickinson, writing in the
halting voice of a woman dying, used the dash to signify gasping
for breath: ``I am alive _ I guess _/The Branches on my Hand/Are
full of Morning Glory _ And at my finger's end _/The Carmine _
tingles warm _/And if I hold a Glass/Across my Mouth _ it blurs it
_/Physician's _ proof of Breath _/I am alive.''
</P>
<P>
   In our time, the writing of Tom Wolfe has made stylish use of
the dash; he combines it with italics and the midsentence
exclamation point to indicate herky-jerkiness or panic in thinking.
</P>
<P>
   In an article in the current Harper's deriding the critics of
American ``triumphalism,'' the iconoclastic Wolfe steps into their
shoes to write, ``After the Soviet archives were opened up _ I
mean, damn! _ it looks like Hiss and the Rosenbergs actually  &UR; were &LR; 
Soviet agents _ and even the Witch Hunt, which was one of the
bedrocks of our beliefs _ damn again! _.'' That's the use of
fictional internal monologue in a nonfiction article, and the dash
does its job of chopping up the speech.
</P>
<P>
   But writers of narrative and exposition, as well as those who
present fiction in the third person, choose to use the language in
the voice of the writer and not of a character.
</P>
<P>
   The written sentence, which is not to be confused with the
spoken sentence that has been transcribed, gives its creator a
chance to rethink the ideas that have come off the top of the head,
to reassemble them in an orderly series, to snip off the
stupidities and shoot the strays, thereby to marshal a cogent
argument or paint a striking image.
</P>
<P>
   On Punctuation Highway, the writer-as-speaker is a dasher, only
half-braking at every stop sign; the writer-as-writer measures
every pause, uses a comma for the speed bump and a semicolon to
proceed with caution at the balancing of closely related complete
thoughts, as in this sentence. The colon, a strict setter-up of
things to follow, is like an arrow that says ``Now watch this'' to
the reader, but it is too often replaced by the do-anything dash.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Veit of the University of North Carolina at Wilmington
disagrees with me about the danger of the  &UR; em &LR; , which is the
typographer's term for the length of the dash: It's as long as the
letter  &UR; M &LR;  in the same font.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technically, no function of the  &UR; em &LR;  couldn't be handled by
other punctuation _ comma, colon, semicolon, period or
parentheses,'' he notes. ``The impact of the  &UR; em &LR;  is not syntactic
but visual. Its shape and length demand a pause and impart drama.
It sets up a punch line in a way a colon cannot. Arthur Wallace
Calhoun put a code of the Old South into words in 1918: `A woman's
name should appear in print but twice _ when she marries and when
she dies.'''
</P>
<P>
   That was then; now, just as women appear in print a lot, the
dash appears too often. I acknowledge that dashes can be useful _
say, to add an example _ and are surely more emphatic than
parentheses (without the sly sharing of confidence with the
reader).
</P>
<P>
   And the dash is indispensible for surrounding a list that
already contains commas _ weakly beginning a sentence with a
conjunction, misspelling  &UR; indispensable &LR; , and incorrectly using a
comma before the  &UR; and &LR;  preceding the final item in a series _ but
undiluted dashiness has become the mark of the slapdash writer who
fails to take the trouble to differentiate among the pauses of
punctuation.
</P>
<P>
   Writing is different from speaking. Organize your written
thoughts so that you don't have to stud your sentences with asides,
sudden additions, curses or last-minute entries. Limit your use of
the dash to its indisp _ to those functions where it beats the
other punctuation pauses _ or else.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
