<HEADLINE>
A VOTE FOR REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Members of the House of Representatives ought to vote this week
to grant China permanent normal trade relations.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that Beijing's record on human rights is
acceptable or that American workers and their unions are wrong to
worry about jobs in textiles and some other industries going
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   But a vote against permanent normal trade relations for China
would not improve human rights in China and would not preserve
American jobs.
</P>
<P>
   House members are not voting on China's entry into the World
Trade Organization. China's accession to the WTO is practically
certain. They are deciding whether or not they will terminate the
annual farce of voting to bestow normal trade relations on Beijing
one year at a time. And since WTO rules require that each member
confer permanent status on other members, a House vote in the
negative would mean that the United States would be in violation of
WTO rules, isolating itself rather than China.
</P>
<P>
   The primary consequence of such a self-punishing exercise would
be to permit China to deny to American goods and services the
lowered tariffs and expunged quotas that competitors such as
Germany and Japan will enjoy. American exporters of soy beans, cell
phones, and Hollywood movies would then forfeit the considerable
concessions that US trade negotiators have wrung from the Chinese
over years of hard bargaining.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of a yes vote in the House often exagerate the
benefits enhanced free trade may have on human and civil rights in
China. As long as the Communist Party maintains its grip on the
world's most populous nation, the best that can be expected is a
continued expansion of choices in the private lives of Chinese
citizens and in the economic sphere.
</P>
<P>
   Opening Chinese markets to US imports may do little, in the near
term, to alleviate political repression within China or to end
China's colonization of Tibet. But free-market reformers in the
party would suffer a serious setback if the House voted to
perpetuate the pointless yearly vote on normal trade relations.
That is why the Dalai Lama has said that a yes vote will serve the
cause of reform in China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
