<HEADER>
A2636 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-MOSCOW-$ADV28-     05-22 1274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MOSCOW-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSCOW'S VILLIANS AREN'T WHAT THEY USED TO BE 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARILYN STASIO    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I went to Russia not too long ago and it wasn't there _ at
least, not the sinister, Soviet-era Russia that writers of Cold War
spy thrillers had prepared me to find behind the Iron Curtain. For
that matter, the Iron Curtain wasn't there. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Where was the cold air of menace that hung over Moscow in Martin
Cruz Smith's ``Gorky Park,'' smothering a politically sensitive
murder investigation in an oppressive landscape of ``white breath,
white trees, white snow, white sky''? What ever happened to Karla,
the implacable chief of Soviet espionage (``so self-possessed that
he could allow, if need be, 10 years for an operation to bear
fruit'') who relentlessly pursued the British agent George Smiley
in ``Quest for Karla,'' the trilogy of cerebral thrillers that John
Le Carre wrote in the 1970s? Where, oh where, among the spring buds
of a new political climate, were the bitter snows of yesteryear?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gone, gone, gone. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nobody reads that stuff anymore, my Russian hosts gently
informed me, as they hustled me into the smart shops, fancy
restaurants and gleamingly refurbished landmarks of modern Moscow.
Actually, they don't even write that stuff anymore. The great spy
masters are either abandoning the old Russia and striking out for
new frontiers or repudiating the genre entirely. Martin Cruz
Smith's latest novel was set in Cuba, and Frederick Forsyth's last
book, a sequel to ``The Phantom of the Opera,'' was set in a Coney
Island fish factory. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Having had a glimpse of the new Russia, I can understand the
disenchantment of the genre masters. Compared with the subtle chess
players in Cold War thrillers, those black-booted Mafia gangsters
who gun their BMW motorbikes on the cobbled side streets of the
Tverskaya while making their shakedown rounds are drugstore
cowboys. The millionaire bankers, oil tycoons, media moguls and
industry barons who make up Russia's new oligarchy might prove to
be more cunning villains. But don't ask these greedy biznizmeni
(stout men who ostentatiously park their big Bentleys on public
sidewalks) to adapt their crass style to the classic spy thriller,
with its reflective foreign agents, its byzantine games of intrigue
and agonizing moral dilemmas.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The buy-or-die spirit of Russia's new market economy doesn't
adapt any better to the atmosphere of bleak despair in these
novels. Pleasant as it may be, shopping in the fashionable
boutiques of the Arbat and Manezh Square will never replace the old
thrill of being herded through the GUM department store by a glum
Intourist guide. Luckily, my reading matter on this trip took the
edge off the unnerving civility that dollar-bearing foreigners now
encounter.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lenin was still rotting decorously in his tomb on the morning
that I went to Red Square, and the Tsarskaya _ the wooden tower
where Ivan the Terrible stood gloating over the protracted
executions of state criminals _ was still good for a heartfelt
shudder. But the sun was shining, tourists were gamboling, and the
little army of fuzz-faced soldiers who marched up to me only wanted
to have their pictures taken to send home to their mothers in
Gdansk.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So, it was with some relief that I buried my nose in ``The
Forbidden Zone,'' a political thriller by Michael Hetzer. Hetzer
was the founding editor of The Moscow Times, the English-language
newspaper in Moscow, and a survivor of the fusillade of gunfire
that ripped up the newspaper's offices (and killed four people) in
the chaotic street fighting of 1993. In the eyes of his heroine, an
American astronomer named Katherine Sears, Moscow in 1984 was still
a ``gloomy, oppressive and sinister'' place for a woman traveling
alone. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although I encountered no hostility on my own trip (beyond the
supercilious sneer of a waiter at the ever-so-trendy Boyarsky
restaurant), poor Katherine fares otherwise when she tries to find
out the fate of a dissident astrophysicist. Pegged as a spy, she is
dragged from her room at the huge and hideous Ukraine Hotel (``the
city's largest foreigner ghetto'') by KGB agents and hounded into
hiding by a senior member of the Politburo. Happily, the chase
takes her to the very landmarks I was headed for that day: the
magnificent Cathedral of the Assumption (where she's torn away from
the splendid icons and pursued to the bell tower by a hooded monk);
the medieval enclosure of Novodevushi Convent (where a woman in a
red scarf slips her a cryptic message); the swank Moskva Restaurant
(where she catches the same awful floor show I did).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While Katherine's jaunty Perils-of-Pauline adventures are fine
for sightseeing, Robert Harris' ``Archangel'' is a book best taken
out after dark. The hero is a British scholar named Fluke Kelso who
has come to Moscow to attend an international symposium marking the
reopening of the Soviet archives only to discover that the cult of
Stalinism is still very much alive in Russia. Caught up in the
``charge of history,'' he wanders the city like a traveler in a
time warp. ``That was what always drew him back,'' he says, ``the
way history hung in the air between the blackened buildings like
sulfur after a lightning strike.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When night falls on the city in ``Gorky Park'' _ ``the evening a
maternal black, windows small and bright, the faces on the street
bright as windows'' _ Martin Cruz Smith's police inspector, Arkady
Renko, experiences the same sensation of being adrift in time.
Standing alone in the winter twilight, ``he felt he could have been
in any Moscow of the past five centuries, and he wouldn't have been
surprised by the sound of hooves in mud.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the paranoid world of the espionage novel, the hovering past
is always alive with menace. In ``Archangel'' Robert Harris makes
the present seem as malevolent as the past. I never made it to
Robotnik, a fictional Mafia-run nightclub where Fluke Kelso
observes rich Russians at sexual play and learns the going rate for
a ``respectable'' prostitute ($300). But the stark night scenes of
a place where the ``serious money'' goes to sin, where ``teeth and
eyes and nails and banknotes flashed in the gloom like knives,''
elicits the kind of shiver that you just don't get from going to
the Bolshoi.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Any Westerner in Moscow on business should find John Le Carre's
``Single &AMP; Single'' sobering reading, especially after staggering
back to the hotel from a jovial trade dinner. The idealistic hero,
Oliver Single, is the junior partner in a London investment house
that used to launder dirty money for members of the old Politburo.
Now the merchant bankers are back in town to cut some deals with a
new breed of crook. After meeting his clients _ a thuggish family
of Georgian drug dealers who want to use their illicit profits to
corner the international market in human blood _ Oliver is whisked
off to one of those glitzy hotel casinos that have sprung up around
Red Square (the sort of place where ``plainclothesmen guard the
swing doors, pink-stained fountains play,'' and the wheels are spun
by ``women croupiers in low-cut dresses.'') Then it's off to the
family digs, where Oliver and his new associates sit in chairs once
owned by Catherine the Great, puff on Cuban cigars, and toast their
business venture from silver-chased ram's horns. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sipping tea in the lobby of the Metropol and eavesdropping on a
thin-lipped Danish businessman ``in phones'' struggling to
negotiate a contract with two beefy Muscovites in black leather
jackets, I could appreciate Oliver's culture shock.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 1839EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
