<HEADER>
A2637 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-ERITREA-BOS     05-22 0363
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-ERITREA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETHIOPIA'S MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ethiopia's unwarranted attack into Eritrea has greatly escalated
the war between these two impoverished nations. Despite its
military success, Ethiopia ought to withdraw and accept the peace
agreement that has been on the table for months.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia and Eritrea are fighting over an inconsequential piece
of real estate. But it is highly charged with symbolism as the two
nations sort out their relationship after a 20-year war that ended
with Eritrea breaking off from the larger nation.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton before the war hailed President Isaias
Afewerki of Eritrea and Prime Minister Meles Zenawi of Ethiopia as
exemplars of new African leadership. The conflict suggests they are
run-of-the-mill strongmen who fight to advance their domestic
agendas.
</P>
<P>
   Meles came to power because the Eritrean war of independence
weakened the dictator then in power. He is a member of the minority
Tigray group, and the latest offensive gives him an opportunity to
solidify his standing among the Amhara people, who dominate Addis
Ababa, the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Lake, Clinton's former national security adviser, and
other administration figures have gone back and forth between the
two countries to persuade them to accept a peace plan proposed by
the Organization of African Unity. This low-key diplomacy did
nothing to avert the latest offensive. The administration needs to
get tougher.
</P>
<P>
   It has supported a boycott of arms sales to both countries, but
this supposed evenhandedness benefits Ethiopia, given its recent
success and the huge population imbalance (58.4 million to 3.8
million).
</P>
<P>
   Isaias and the other Eritreans are intent on affirming their
independence from their recent masters. But they had no right to
seize the border land in 1998, an act that precipitated war.
Nonetheless, they have volunteered to withdraw pending an impartial
border demarcation, while Ethiopia has raised spurious objections
to the deal. The United States and other western nations must make
it clear to the Ethiopians that they are now in the wrong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
