<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-HARVARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUDENSTINE'S LEGACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once, college and university presidents shook the halls of
American thought. Today, their intellectual leadership is
overshadowed by two of higher education's watchwords: capital
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Rudenstine stepped into this river in 1991 when he became
president of Harvard University. Understated and known for working
behind the scenes, Rudenstine has struck a pragmatic balance
between fiscal and academic excellence, even if he may never have
his name on a Harvard building. His plan to step down as president,
announced Monday, means Harvard must hammer out a new future.
</P>
<P>
   Even critics praise Rudenstine's impressive fund-raising
ability. Harvard has exceeded its $2.1 billion campaign goal. A
scholar of Renaissance literature, Rudenstine champions the
sciences. He has pushed Washington to spend more on research and
has addressed pressing new issues facing Harvard's medical school
and teaching hospitals. Hires such as law professor Lani Guinier
and government professor William Julius Wilson have helped
diversify the faculty. Rudenstine's historic legacy may well be
starting an effort to get Harvard's fiercely independent schools to
work more closely together.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Law School professor Charles Ogletree calls Rudenstine
``an extraordinary president and an ordinary guy,'' pointing to his
involvement in details great and small, from academic appointments
to office-hour talks with undergraduates. In 1994, this retail
presidency looked all too human when Rudenstine took a medical
leave, saying he was exhausted. He seemed overwhelmed, but three
months later he was back.
</P>
<P>
   In a search that may take a year, Harvard would do well to find
a new president who combines Rudenstine's fund-raising and
managerial attributes with an ability to use the office as a bully
pulpit. Ever-faster developments in such fields as medicine,
communications, and biotechnology are raising ethical questions
that cry out for answers. The sweet reason once offered by college
presidents is in demand again. The next president must protect the
traditional core of academic excellence and its modern variations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 1841EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
