<HEADER>
A2648 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-CALIF-DAVIS-JUSTICE-A     05-22 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-DAVIS-JUSTICE-ART-2TAKES(960)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS MAKES `TOUGH ON CRIME' A HALLMARK OF HIS ADMINISTRATION
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ It was the height of the bitterly fought
1998 campaign for governor of California, and Democrat Gray Davis
was trying hard to prove that he would be tougher on crime than the
Republican attorney general, Dan Lungren, running against him on a
record of two decades in law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   As governor, Davis insisted, he would be tougher on crime than
anybody. He would give judges discretion to sentence 14-year-olds
to death and consider supporting nonunanimous jury verdicts.
Indeed, he said in a televised debate, on issues of law and order,
he considered Singapore _ a country that executes drug offenders _
``a good starting point.''
</P>
<P>
   No one took that remark literally. But these days, Democratic
lawmakers say it sometimes seems as though Davis was only slightly
exaggerating. Halfway into his second year in office, the governor
is establishing himself as more of a conservative on criminal
justice issues than his Republican predecessors, or any other
elected official in California _ if not the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has essentially removed the incentive that makes
inmates model prisoners by refusing any recommendation the parole
board has made to grant a release. He has announced that any judge
he appoints should reflect his sentiments ``or resign.'' He has
blocked efforts to soften the state's ``three strikes'' law, which
can put someone in prison for life for stealing a bicycle if it is
their third felony conviction. He has vetoed a modest bill that
would grant the press greater access to inmates in the state's
closed-door prison system, which has been rocked in recent years by
corruption scandals, and has indicated that he will veto a similar
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the governor, who broke with the Democratic Party and
endorsed Proposition 21, the youth crime initiative that allows
14-year-olds convicted of felonies to be locked up in adult
prisons, has stocked the parole board and other posts with ex-law
enforcement officials who are considered hard-liners, very much
like his predecessor, Pete Wilson, had done. He has also sided with
police groups over civil rights organizations in refusing to
approve a bill that would track racial profiling, or the practice
of stopping motorists based on the color of their skin.
</P>
<P>
   California, already in a class by itself in terms of crime and
punishment because of its ``three strikes law,'' continues its lead
as one of the strictest states in the nation, if not the strictest,
on law and order, said Frank Zimring, director of the Earl Warren
Legal Institute at the University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, through a spokesman, has declined repeated requests, over
several weeks, for an interview, saying he was too busy. But the
governor has continually pointed to polls that give his approval
rating at more than 65 percent as proof that voters endorse his
stance on law and order. His spokesman, Michael Bustamante, says
that the governor campaigned as a centrist, made moderation a theme
of his first two State of the State speeches and told Democrats at
last year's state convention exactly how he planned to lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Davis laid out how he intended to govern from the
center,'' Bustamante has said.
</P>
<P>
   As a political calculation, moving far right on crime and
punishment to show the electorate that he is a moderate Democrat is
a safe bet, political observers say. California is rather
conservative when it comes to crime issues, with voters
consistently approving initiatives that toughen laws against
offenders. In fact, California, which has the biggest court and
prison system in the country, led the prison-building boom, and
Davis is expanding it.
</P>
<P>
   But to the state's Democratic leaders, who were eager for change
after 16 years of Republican governors who made hard lines on law
and order the benchmarks of their administrations, the governor's
inflexibility on criminal justice issues _ largely seen by both his
supporters and critics as a political buffer against potential
challengers who might fault him for being soft on crime _ is
becoming the defining characteristic of his administration.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who authored the youth crime initiative that Davis has
endorsed, praised his successor as ``a pleasant surprise on the
stance he has taken on criminal justice, both in terms of his
appointments and his support of tough standards as well as
prevention.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor's critics, almost all of them from within his own
party, say that in these good times, when the public is content and
the state coffers are flush, any governor would receive similar
ratings. In fact, they say, it is precisely during these times that
the governor can afford to show some independence rather than plod
along the politically safe path to a second term.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that has been somewhat surprising is the kind of
iron-clad approach he has,'' state Sen. Tom Hayden said.
``Absolutism is something that you expect from an ayatollah, but
it's surprising in a governor in a state that's very complex and
diverse. It's okay to lay down the rules, but there's been any
number of occasions when flexibility is called for. I've seen any
number of his appointees who share the same approach, but who
display routine flexibility. He's not bending to them. He's the
hard-liner in their ranks.''
</P>
<P>
   After a honeymoon year in which the governor's stance on crime
caused barely a ripple of attention (except for regular scoldings
in newspaper editorials), his stance has received greater scrutiny
and political disapproval in recent weeks. Or, as an editorial in
The Los Angeles Times put it, ``the honeymoon is over, brought to
an end partly by his prickly, controlling style and partly by his
aversion to taking political risk.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In March, the governor suffered his first major political defeat
when the state Senate blocked a conservative Republican from
serving another term as chairman on the state parole board because
of a federal court ruling that the board violated the Americans
with Disabilities Act.
</P>
<P>
   James Nielsen, a former three-term Republican state senator, had
been appointed to the board of prison terms, as the parole board is
called, by Wilson in 1991 and re-appointed in 1995. Davis
re-appointed him to fill out the remaining nine months of a term
last May and tried to extend it.
</P>
<P>
   But the Senate leader, John Burton, a Democrat from San
Francisco who is considered the most powerful legislator in
California, refused to hold a confirmation hearing on the
appointment. Burton, who has become increasingly vocal about his
disagreements with the governor over law and order, said that he
was outraged by a federal judge's ruling criticizing Nielsen (who
actively campaigned against Davis in 1998) as ``callous'' to the
rights of disabled prisoners seeking full access to parole
hearings. Some prisoners who used wheelchairs had to crawl up
stairs to get to the hearings and deaf prisoners who used sign
language had their hands shackled at hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Davis turned the political defeat into a victory by turning
around and appointing Nielsen to head the state youth parole board.
</P>
<P>
   Burton, in a recent interview, said that Davis' inflexibility
``because he thinks a Democrat becomes a moderate by being tough on
crime'' ignores the possibility that people can be ``redeemed.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Critics point to the high-profile parole case of Robert
Rosenkrantz, who has served 15 years in prison for second-degree
murder. In June 1985, Rosenkrantz, now 34, killed the man who told
his father at a high school graduation party that he was gay; he
was sentenced to 17 years to life. Prison officials say he is a
model inmate and numerous psychologists, as well as the
prosecutors, trial judge and detective who worked on the case all
recommended that he be released.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, an appeals court took the unprecedented step of
ruling that the parole board had abused its discretion when it
found Rosenkrantz unsuitable for parole. The parole board had set a
release date for Rosenkrantz last year, but the governor had
stepped in and rejected the parole, saying Rosenkrantz ``was not
currently suitable'' for release.
</P>
<P>
   The case is jeopardizing another appointment Davis has
recommended to the parole board, because the appointee, Leonard
Munoz, a former Los Angeles police officer was part of the group
that rejected Rosenkrantz's bid for release.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the state Senate Public Safety Committee, John
Vasconcellos, a Democrat from San Jose, said that the parole board,
under the governor's edict to never approve the release of anyone
convicted of murder, ``have held Kafkaesque hearings in which
conclusions have nothing to do with the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor, through a spokeswoman, Hilary McLean, has declined
to comment on the Rosenkrantz case.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, the governor has had to confront reporters who
want to know why he continues to reject a bill that would grant
journalists greater access to inmates. The bill, similar to one the
governor rejected last year, would restore the ability to conduct
interviews with inmates, a policy that was changed in 1995 by the
California Corrections Department after a series of scathing
articles in The Orange County Register.
</P>
<P>
   Carole Migden, a Democratic Assemblywoman who authored both
bills, said she thought it was important to keep the issue alive
even if the governor vetoed it again. Migden added that although
she was disappointed, she did not think the governor's stance on
law and order was out of line with the voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he wants to get re-elected,'' she said, ``just as you
want to keep your job. Everybody wants to keep their job.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A politician, especially a Democrat, loses nothing in gaining a
reputation as an unyielding hard-liner on law and order, said
Zimring of the University of California. ``He loses nothing except
if someone were writing the next `Profiles in Courage,''' he said.
``I don't think Davis would make it into that. But politically?
There is no serious downside.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 1850EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
