<HEADER>
A2650 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV28-     05-22 1288
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., May 28) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   City of Light Makes a Claim to Music, Too
</P>
<P>
   Vienna, Austria, has long been called the City of Music, but
Nigel Simeone, a lecturer in the department of music at the
University of Wales in Bangor, makes a case for sharing the
distinction with Paris. His book ``Paris _ A Musical Gazetteer,''
scheduled to be published by Yale University Press on May 30,
suggests hundreds of sites associated with composers and performers
who have lived in Paris in the last 400 years, including such
non-Frenchmen as Chopin, Donizetti, Liszt, Mozart, Prokofiev,
Rossini, Stravinsky, Verdi and Wagner.
</P>
<P>
   Landmarks include houses, monuments, graves, churches and
concert halls, with directions. The armchair traveler may
appreciate such arcane details as the fact that the Palais Garnier,
which houses the Opera, has 2,531 doors and 7,593 keys.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the book is devoted to brief biographies,
enumerating the places where composers and musicians lived or
stayed.
</P>
<P>
   The author outlines four separate walks, including a circular
walk from Les Invalides; the neighborhood of Passy; from the Opera
to Montmartre Cemetery; and from Place de l'Alma to the Etoile.
</P>
<P>
   Sites noted in the book include 12, place Vendome, Chopin's last
home; 4, avenue Carnot, Ravel's apartment; La Trinite, the church
where Messiaen was organist for 61 years; the Opera and the
Opera--Comique, the Theatre des Champs-Elysees, the Musee de la
Musique and various cemeteries, especially Pere-Lachaise and
Montmartre.
</P>
<P>
   The book costs $40 in hardcover, $18.95 in paperback. It can be
ordered by calling (800) 987-7323 or at www.yale.edu/yup.
</P>
<P>
   Roman Luxury in a Renovated Hotel
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its opulent furnishings and enviable location
just off the majestic Piazza del Popolo, Rome's recently reopened
Hotel de Russie vaunts a special attraction for a hotel in the
center of the city: a garden, three-quarters of an acre with
towering palms, magnolias, orange trees, rosebushes, a small grotto
and fountain.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel reopened last month after a two-year restoration.
Situated in an early 19th-century palazzo, it was for many years a
haunt of Russian dignitaries _ hence its name. It was also a
favorite among cultural celebrities: Picasso, Cocteau and
Stravinsky are among those who have signed the guest book.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II the palazzo was taken over by the Italian
military secret service and used as their center of operations. It
then became the headquarters of RAI, Italy's state television and
radio, until seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel, part of the RF Hotels chain, was overhauled in the
$18 million renovation. There are 129 bedrooms including 27 suites,
each with two-line telephones, voice mail and satellite television.
The decor combines diverse styles: Baroque headboards coexist with
minimalist television stands and photographs of flowers by Robert
Mapplethorpe.
</P>
<P>
   In summer, the restaurant and bar service spills into the
garden, whose terraced slopes climb to join the Pincio Hill and the
Villa Borghese, Rome's liveliest public park. Next month a spa with
a Turkish bath, sauna, gym and beauty salon is set to open.
</P>
<P>
   Room prices start at $269 for a single, based on 2,190 lire to
the dollar, and go up to $1,461 for the Picasso suite, which has
lithographs by the artist. Prices do not include VAT or breakfast,
which ranges between $17 and $25 a person. Hotel de Russie, 9 Via
del Babuino, 00187 Rome; (39-06) 328881; fax (39-06) 32888888.
</P>
<P>
   A D-Day Museum Opens in New Orleans
</P>
<P>
   The historian Stephen E. Ambrose is not the first writer to
devote much of his career to a war. But Ambrose, the author of
``D-Day, June 6, 1944: the Climactic Battle of World War II,'' may
be the first to found a museum devoted to an amphibious invasion.
</P>
<P>
   The National D-Day Museum will open next month in a 19th-century
former brewery and an adjoining four-story glass-fronted pavilion
in the Warehouse District of downtown New Orleans.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans was the home of Higgins Industries, which built
landing craft that carried infantry platoons through rough seas
from ships to shore, allowing men and equipment to land on open
beaches, as they did in Normandy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the displays in the 70,500-square-foot museum will be a
reproduction of the boat designed by Andrew Higgins, the company
owner, whom General Eisenhower, in a conversation with Ambrose,
credited with winning the war. Other exhibits will include film
footage of the invasion at Normandy and battle artifacts from the
beaches, a vintage glider that is part of a scene recreating a
crash in a Normandy field, and a simulated hedgerow to show why
combat beyond the shore was so difficult. Nine oral history
stations will recount a variety of personal experiences.
</P>
<P>
   The National D-Day Museum, 945 Magazine St., at the corner of
Howard Avenue, (504) 527-6012, was developed at a cost of $25
million, a mix of federal, state and private funds. Ambrose
conceived of the project and played a major role in the
fund-raising. In 2001 the museum plans to open a section focusing
on the Pacific invasions.
</P>
<P>
   From June 2 to 9, the museum will be open only for those holding
preview tickets sold through the mail; it expects to open its doors
to walk-in visitors on June 10.
</P>
<P>
   Hours are 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. daily. Tickets cost $7, $5 for ages 5
to 17.
</P>
<P>
   Newfoundland Celebrates the Vikings
</P>
<P>
   A thousand years ago, Leif Ericson and his crew of Vikings rowed
their longships to the rocky shores of Newfoundland, where they
founded the first European settlement of North America. This
summer, Newfoundland is host to ``Vikings! 1,000 Years,'' a
provincewide festival centered around L'Anse aux Meadows, the only
authenticated Norse settlement in North America.
</P>
<P>
   At the tip of Newfoundland's Northern Peninsula, a coastal
region famous for icebergs and seabird colonies, L'Anse aux Meadows
will welcome a flotilla of longships in a re-enactment of Ericson's
landing on July 28.
</P>
<P>
   At Norstead, a newly created ``port of trade'' near the remains
of the original sod and timber huts, visitors can watch Viking
battles and weddings and learn about ironworking and boat-building
from July 17 to Sept. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Farther down the coast, the pristine fjords and volcanic
mountains of Gros Morne National Park look much as they did in
Viking times. Travelers can drive between Gros Morne and L'Anse aux
Meadows along the scenic Viking Trail, a seaside highway dotted
with tiny fishing villages.
</P>
<P>
   Cities and towns across Newfoundland will join the festivities
with a range of cultural events. The exhibition ``Full Circle:
First Contact'' will explore the interaction between the Viking
newcomers and the aboriginal people they called Skraelings (St.
John's Arts and Culture Centre, June 2 to Aug. 6; Corner Brook
Museum and Archives, Aug. 25 to Oct. 9). ``The Spiritual World of
the Vikings'' is the title of an exhibition July 16 to Aug. 17 at
the Resource Center for the Arts Gallery in St. John's.
</P>
<P>
   Viking-style longships, including the Snorri, a U.S.-built
vessel that re-created Ericson's journey from Greenland to
Newfoundland in 1998, will also stop at ports throughout the
province in July.
</P>
<P>
   Maxxim Vacations of St. John's is offering 7- and 10-night
packages including flight, hotel and rental car. Tours from New
York or Boston start at $969 a person double occupancy.
Information: Maxxim Vacations, (800) 567-6666.
</P>
<P>
   Details about the ``Vikings! 1,000 Years'' celebration can be
found on the Tourism Newfoundland and Labrador Internet site,
www.gov.nf.ca/vikings, or by calling (800) 563-6353.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
