<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH VOWS TO MOVE U.S. EMBASSY TO JERUSALEM 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush promised Monday that if
elected president he would station the U.S. ambassador to Israel in
the contested city of Jerusalem rather than await the outcome of
delicate Israeli-Palestinian peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Bush made the commitment in remarks to 1,500 applauding
participants at a conference sponsored by the American Israel
Public Affairs Committee (AIPAC), an influential lobbying
organization founded in 1951 to support Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore is scheduled to address the organization
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's pledge that ``as soon as'' he takes office as president
he would ``begin the process of moving the United States ambassador
to the city Israel has chosen as its capital'' represents a break
with Clinton administration policy.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. embassy is currently located in Tel Aviv, with only an
American consulate located in Jerusalem. Israel has designated
Jerusalem as its national capital and wants the U.S. embassy to be
moved to Jerusalem. Supporters of the Palestinian cause oppose
Israel's claim on Jerusalem, asserting that the divided city ought
to serve the capital of a future Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who has helped broker a series of landmark
Israeli-Palestinian peace agreements since 1993, says the U.S.
embassy should move from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem only as part of
``final status'' peace negotiations between Israel and the
Palestinian Authority, representing Palestinians living on the West
Bank and in the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
   ``My support for Israel is not conditional on the outcome of the
peace process,'' Bush declared. Israel's five-decade-long ``special
relationship'' with the United States will continue during a Bush
presidency even if Israel's Arab ``adversaries cannot bring
themselves to make true peace with the Jewish state,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign issued a statement that criticized Bush for
``irresponsibly'' attempting to ``politicize'' the Middle East
peace process. Bush seems ``confused about the Middle East peace
process,'' said Gore press secretary Chris Lehane, adding that Bush
is `` suffering from an antiquated analysis, reminiscent of the
Republican approach of the 1980s.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's appearance before the American Jewish lobbying
organization was part of a 36-hour whirlwind visit to the nation's
capital by the presumptive GOP presidential nominee who will cap
his visit with a rare Washington, D.C., news conference on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush initially planned to meet with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak on Tuesday during Barak's scheduled visit to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   But Barak cancelled his plans to visit the United States and
meet with Clinton, Bush and Gore after fighting broke out amid the
planned withdrawal of Israeli security forces from a 22-year-old
security buffer zone in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks, Bush criticized the Clinton administration for
pressuring Israel to ``conform'' to U.S. timetables and blueprints
for peace and for an alleged ``attempt to take sides'' in Israeli's
most recent parliamentary elections to support Barak and his
pro-peace negotiations platform.
</P>
<P>
   ``America should not interfere in Israel's democratic process,''
Bush declared. ``And America will not interfere in Israeli
elections when I am president.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak, campaigning on a pro-peace negotiations platform for the
Labor Party, defeated Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and
his Likud-led government last May 17 in a landslide.
</P>
<P>
   In earlier remarks to the National Association of Realtors, Bush
hit upon contested domestic issues in his rivalry with Gore,
defending his proposal for a $483 billion federal income tax cut,
in part to help single mothers with two children who earn $22,000 a
year. Bush, decrying the tax code as a ``toll booth on the road to
the middle class,'' said such taxpayers are saddled with higher
rate of federal taxes on additional income than individuals earning
$220,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it is conservative to cut taxes and it is
compassionate to trust people with their own money so she can save
and so she can dream and so she can build for her family,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to counter criticism leveled by Gore that his proposal
for a tax cut and Social Security rescue are ``risky,'' Bush
replied: ``They say it is risky to cut taxes. What is risky is
leaving unspent surpluses in Washington, D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com )
</P>
