<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIT-TRAINS-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERVICE SLIPS, FARES BAFFLE ON BRITISH TRAINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., May 28) 
 By ALAN COWELL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In old movies and some rose-tinted memories, rail
travel in Britain is an idyll of charm and predictability. Puffing
Billy steam trains chuff their way through bucolic villages.
Salt-of-the-earth families head with noisy cheer for outings in
third class. And, in first, silent toffs take shelter behind copies
of The Times of London to ignore one another.
</P>
<P>
   These days, rail travel in Britain boasts little charm and a lot
of unpredictability. The onetime gentility of first class has been
replaced by the competing cacophonies of cell phones ringing and
conversations that begin with sentences like: ``I can't hear you.
We're in a tunnel.''
</P>
<P>
   In standard _ as the lower class is now called _ and sometimes
in first, rail travel is no more than a scrimmage to find a seat,
or face a journey standing. Arrival times are hit or miss; trains
sometimes do not move at all for lengthy periods.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most baffling aspect of British rail travel is
the price. Since the old British Rail was privatized in 1996, an
inefficient, unprofitable state monopoly has been replaced by
inefficient but generally profitable private operators that
preclude competition by maintaining regional monopolies.
</P>
<P>
   Fare structures have become a tangle of elusive discounts and
incentives for early booking that have widened the gap between
standard and first class passengers _ but probably united them in
complaining about poor service. Last month, for instance, hundreds
of people on a train from London to Manchester became so incensed
when it broke down _ twice _ that they refused to leave the
stricken carriages to board other, equally crowded trains on the
same route. Instead, they staged a sit-in until their train was
towed into Manchester three hours late.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the public outcry that one British newspaper, The Sunday
Independent, has launched a campaign to protest what it calls the
sense that ``We the consumers often seem to have less and less
power and less and less choice.''
</P>
<P>
   For their parts, the rail companies, which still receive some
state subsidies in addition to large profits, insist that the
railways were in such bad shape under British Rail that years of
investment will be needed to lift them to a better standard. But
that doesn't explain the complexities of ticket prices.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for instance, one of the busiest routes between London and
Manchester, operated exclusively by Virgin Trains, a part of
Richard Branson's Virgin Group, which made its mark with cheap
trans-Atlantic flights. Here a traveler may pay anything from $32
(at $1.60 to the pound) round trip for a standard-class ticket
booked seven days in advance, to a staggering $345 for the top
first-class ticket, which actually exceeds some of Virgin's
round-trip fares between London and New York.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the only complication. A discounted first-class
ticket for off-peak travel on this route can cost $96. And, on
weekends, people with ordinary standard-class tickets may upgrade
to first for a modest $8. Yet a flexible, standard-class ticket
without restrictions on when it may be used is $240.
</P>
<P>
   Rail groups offer five different special travel cards (not
counting the Britrail Flexipass discount cards that afford
Americans and other foreigners unlimited travel on the entire
system within a designated time frame). Thus, anyone under the age
of 26, or a full-time student, may pay $28.80 a year for a Young
Person's Railcard, offering a 34 percent discount on trains outside
peak commuting times. There's a similar card for the over-60s. But,
unlike in Germany and other European countries, there's no such
program for the 26-through-60-year-old business traveler.
</P>
<P>
   Cross-Channel Eurostar trains and London's Underground are not
integrated into most of the above arrangements and require separate
booking.
</P>
<P>
   Technology offers a way through these thickets of confusion,
provided the traveler knows what to ask for and has Internet
access.
</P>
<P>
   An American, for example, may contact Britrail on
www.britrail.com to buy a Flexipass discount card before leaving
the United States for a British vacation. The cards are available
only outside Britain and may be purchased from the Britrail Web
site, from travel agents or at (888) 422-2748 or (877) 677-1066.
Unlike the Classic Railpass, which is good for consecutive days of
travel, the Flexipass affords passengers the chance to choose 4, 8
or 15 days of travel within a two-month period. Prices range from a
four-day standard-class pass for $235 to a 15-day first-class pass
for $770.
</P>
<P>
   Britrail also offers a variety of links to other free sites,
such as www.railtrack.co.uk for British timetable information, and
www.raileurope.co.uk for Eurostar services to the continent.
Additionally, Virgin's Trainline (www.thetrainline.com) offers a
relatively simple system of planning journeys and purchasing
tickets online.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not everyone travels with a laptop to make those
connections on the road. Britain's National Rail telephone service,
(44-345) 484950, is a useful source of information. The caller
speaks to a real person, but the real person does not always offer
full discount fare details unless asked specifically for the best
bargains.
</P>
<P>
   For travel in London _ with its bewildering mix of commuter
train, underground and bus services _ an equally useful service is
London Travel Information, (44-171) 222 1234, which offers
solutions to arcane questions such as: which is the best way to get
from Kentish Town to Wimbledon, say, or Shooter's Hill to Notting
Hill?
</P>
<P>
   However you travel, though, don't expect it to be cheap, and the
only real toffs you're likely to see will be those you glimpse in
chauffeured cars who abandoned the indignities of the railroads a
long time ago.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
