<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2656 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-FLYFISHING-$AD     05-22 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-FLYFISHING-$ADV28-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: the riverbed.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ethic at Clearwater and at most other fly fishing schools is
``catch and release.'' This means no trout dinners. More important,
it means that the tiny hooks on the flies have no barbs, making it
imperative that one keep the line taut once a fish finds the end of
it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My own experience was that the rare, hooked trout liked to swim
frantically in all directions. This generally prompted shouts from
the nearest guide about proper positioning, and I usually responded
to this instruction by joining my fish in a wild, thrashing dance
that must have looked something like Joe Cocker on speed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Our guides would not have passed central casting. I had expected
weathered older men in goofy, fly-blown hats, spooning out fish
wisdom like cough syrup. Instead we got Mike Peters, an erstwhile
ski-racing coach from Mammoth, Calif., and Scott Saiki, a
27-year-old Hawaiian-born surfer and snowboarder whose command of
fly fishing technique was impressive even to his fellow guides.
Both were as patient as they were knowledgeable (and our second
visit to Clearwater last summer suggested that they were by no
means the exception). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clearwater's owner, Dick Galland, was a pioneer in some of the
early Outward Bound programs in Colorado and Texas, and one of his
earliest ventures in fishing instruction was a course he taught in
San Francisco in the late 1970s called Zen and the Art of Fly
Fishing. There is nothing too touchy-feely about Clearwater's
approach these days, but the emphasis remains clearly on how one
learns to fly-fish rather than on how many one might catch. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This began to make clearer sense to me on the third day of our
``mastering'' class. We set off for a lower section of the Pit
River, a place that our guides referred to portentously as the Pit.
The fish beckoned to us from about 300 feet below the road, in
water that cut through a canyon spread with brilliant fall colors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wading slowly through the strong current, fighting to keep our
balance, it seemed that fly fishing had become a contact sport.
Then, wherever we stopped, it was as though we were meeting the
fish all over again, this time with the proper introductions. Our
nymphing began to look less awkward, and most of us actually caught
a few fish. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next afternoon we found ourselves in an even more
spectacular setting, a spot along Hat Creek called Carbon Flats.
Iridescent grasses glowed in the clear water, and even from the
banks above we could see big silvery shapes working their way
lazily upstream. These trout, it turned out, were some of the most
famously coy fish in the west. But by then we were all casting well
enough to be satisfied just to stand in the slow current, soak in
the sun, and practice. When a few fish began to strike, we shared
the thrill. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carbon was no less compelling when my father and I returned on
our second trip to Clearwater early last summer. This time we took
a couple of old friends who had been fly fishing for years, and the
four of us shared the wisdom and humor of two of the lodge's most
experienced guides, Tom Peppas and Art Teter.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As spectacular as it had been to see this swatch of northern
California at the peak of its autumn foliage, June was even better.
The days were warm and long and we switched from neoprene waders to
lighter, more comfortable Gore-Tex versions from the Clearwater
rental shop. We returned to the Pit to do some more full-impact
nymphing, and then spent a quiet, enjoyable day learning to fish
from skiffs on the Fall River. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Almost from the start I wished that I had put in a little
practice on my casting and knot-tying in the interim. But part of
the joy of fishing with guides was that we could brush up as we
went. If anything, Tom and Art were too accommodating, helping us
out of so many tangles (literal and figurative) that I was afraid
we weren't working hard enough. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the end, we felt that our mastering course had given us
enough confidence to go on fishing. The knots no longer felt so
complex, and we could start thinking about finer points like when
to change from one type of fly to another. But none of that seemed
to matter much when we went back to Carbon Flats. The setting was
again magnificent, and even on a Saturday morning, we had the
crystalline river all to ourselves. The trout, however, seemed to
see me coming. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This time, summoning all the delicacy I could, I cast again and
again to what seemed like a perfect spot, just ahead of my fat
prize. And the fish rose once again to taunt me, eating every bug
in sight save mine. (BBOX) &QR; 
How to be outsmarted by a trout &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ARRANGING AN EXPEDITION &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For information about Clearwater Trout Tours, contact the
company at Clearwater, Box 90, Cassel, Calif. 96016 or call (415)
381-1173 (especially in the winter months) or (530) 335-5500. The
lodge is open for guided fishing from the beginning of the trout
season in late April until it ends in November. Classes usually run
from early May until October. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clearwater can be reached from San Francisco (just under six
hours by car), from Sacramento (about five hours) and from Reno
(slightly less than three hours). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CLASSES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The basic ``mastering'' class costs $995 a person for four
nights' lodging, all meals, equipment rental and instruction. There
are also intermediate and expert-level courses for both men and
women, as well as three courses designed for women, including a
women-only ``mastering'' course. Students must buy their own flies
and some of their own tackle and fishing licenses, at an added cost
of about $100 for the course. Tips to the lodge staff (10 percent
of meal and accommodation charges per guest) and the guides ($50 to
$90 per guest) are customary but optional. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Private guiding packages are available throughout the season for
$315 a person, including all meals and overnight lodging (double
occupancy). Intermediate and expert courses are taught every other
month. In winter the company frequently runs fishing tours to such
places as New Zealand's South Island, which is famous for its brown
trout, and Christmas Island in the south Pacific, a mecca for
bonefishing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EQUIPMENT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fly fishing is the gift that keeps on costing. Expect to pay in
the $500 range for a good rod and about $200 for a good reel. Not
to mention the vest, the waders (neoprene or Gore-Tex, depending on
the water temperature and the season), the wading boots and the
tackle. The lodge sells fine equipment in its store, but neither
the guides nor anyone else made any perceptible push to sell it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
