<HEADER>
A2657 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$A     05-22 1567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRACKING DOWN AN OUTFITTER FOR THE LEWIS-AND-CLARK WILDERNESS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  By BETSY WADE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A college classmate living in Arizona said he was going to
Montana in July to canoe along Lewis and Clark's route on the Upper
Missouri River. Though I had heard only part of the tape of Stephen
E. Ambrose's best-selling biography of Meriwether Lewis,
``Undaunted Courage,'' I was envious.
</P>
<P>
   My classmate is not alone in heading for the Lewis and Clark
wilderness: Lee V. Larson, a spokesman for the Federal Bureau of
Land Management, which is responsible for the portion protected as
the Upper Missouri Wild and Scenic River, said that Ambrose's book
had stimulated trips on the 149-mile stretch. Whether the
Lewis-and-Clark boom is big enough to make the charts or not,
canoeing, rafting and kayaking are in a major surge.
</P>
<P>
   Try this: In Alaska there will be midnight rafting down the
Nenana River at the edge of Denali National Park from June 17 to
23. The moon will be full on the 16th, but no matter: close to the
North Pole at the solstice, the sun will be above the horizon for
nearly 21 hours. In the weird dusk, those on the rafts will glimpse
rapids and canyons on a two-hour trip before a very early breakfast
at the McKinley Chalet Resort along the Nenana.
</P>
<P>
   And Butterfield &AMP; Robinson of Toronto, a noted operator of
bicycling and walking trips with luxury accommodations, has a new
venture, Rivers and Oceans, which is offering six river and hiking
trips in remote parts of the Canadian Northwest. Some enter areas
where only this company has permission to go.
</P>
<P>
   The Alaska midnight rafting is offered by the concession holder
at the park, Denali Park Resorts; Butterfield &AMP; Robinson is
likewise well established. But most people who want to kayak or
canoe far from home start from scratch in finding an outfitter
unless they have a friend's recommendation. Twice, I have called
upon outfitters and have not taken the trip because the employees
seemed vague on pick-up timing or I objected to something in the
documents I was to sign. More than is the case with a hotel or a
cruise, travelers entrust their lives to outfitters.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RIVER SURFING  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My college friend, Dr. Richard Oliver, is using a small
family-owned company in Anaconda, Mont., Upper Missouri River
Guides, that he learned about through its Web page,
www.uppermissouri.com. Glenn Monahan, the owner, is a retired
teacher who focuses on geology and elects to pitch some camps at
Lewis and Clark's historic campsites. As an additional
qualification, Monahan has written a guide to the river keyed to
the Bureau of Land Management maps.
</P>
<P>
   The Web is increasingly used to find small companies, but the
electronic woods are filled with rogues. In the case of outfitters
that operate in federal lands or waters, like Monahan's, there is
at least minimal protection: federal areas under the direction of
any of eight agencies, including the National Park Service, the
Forest Service and the Bureau of Land Management, have to get
permits annually.
</P>
<P>
   Larson of the Bureau of Land Management said: ``We have a fairly
comprehensive list of stipulations _ safety requirements, food
handling, credentials of the boatmen.'' Three broad goals are
involved, he said: safety of the participants, preservation of
public health and protection of natural resources.
</P>
<P>
   A list of recreation areas on federal lands is available at
www.recreation.gov. This does not list operators, although camping
reservations links are provided.
</P>
<P>
   Most states license guides and outfitters, and shoppers should
ask companies if they have licenses. A small book, ``Top Rated
River Adventures: Canoeing, Kayaking and Rafting in North
America,'' (Picked-by-You Guides, $18.95, www.topguides.com) notes
any licensing requirements in the 14 states it includes, and gives
addresses for agencies or associations. (Entries in this book are
written by the outfitters themselves; the explanation of the
editor's selection method should be examined.)
</P>
<P>
   Some semiofficial agencies provide a list small enough to check
out by phone. In Fort Benton, Mont., at the first section of the
Wild and Scenic Upper Missouri, for example, the visitor center,
(406) 622-3864, maintains a list of only six river outfitters.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, experienced kayakers or canoers simply want to rent
boats in a remote state. Outfitters may have arrangements for this,
but of necessity the rental is probably also going to involve being
dropped off and picked up, so costs and schedules should be
discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all outfitters want participants to sign agreements
acknowledging the ``inherent dangers'' in their activities. The
Butterfield &AMP; Robinson Rivers and Oceans catalogue is blunt: ``All
of the trips in this brochure . . . entail risk of personal injury
or death from accident, illness or the conduct of other persons. .
. . Medical facilities may not be easily accessible and may not be
sophisticated.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WATCH FOR WAIVERS  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, outfitters also ask clients to sign a waiver
asserting that the operator may not be sued even in the event of
gross negligence. Cindy Orlando, chief of concessions for the
National Park Service in Washington, said such waivers were legally
unenforceable and not consistent with National Park policy. She
said that permit holders had to carry liability insurance
appropriate for the type of activity and the number of clients, and
that where boating was involved, Coast Guard regulations applied.
</P>
<P>
   America Outdoors, an association of 500 outfitters with
headquarters in Knoxville, Tenn., maintains its membership list on
the Web at &QL; 
www.americaoutdoors.org. David L. Brown, the executive director,
said that its group has a code of ethics, but that when complaints
were received, it referred them to the agencies or states that
licensed the operators. Brown said his organization did not have a
standard waiver of liability and that most waivers used by
operators were created by insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   The group's membership list is free from (865) 558-3597, or
America Outdoors, P.O. Box 10847, Knoxville, Tenn. 37939. The Web
list is updated regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-five operators organized as the Colorado River Outfitters
Association maintain their list at www.croa.org. John Rice,
president of the group, said members paid dues and subscribed to a
code of ethics. He said that there were 150 outfitters licensed by
the state, but that some were very small. A members' list leaflet
is available from Post Office Box 1662, Buena Vista, Colo. 81211.
</P>
<P>
   A more sophisticated step is represented by
www.adventureseek.com. This Web site of 230 operators includes many
big names, including Mountain Travel-Sobek, OARS and Backroads.
According to Jeff Kinder, a founder and vice president,
adventureseek works on the travel agent system: it gets a
commission for each booking. Client evaluations will be carried on
the site. Reservations can be made on line, by e-mail, on a
hypertext link or by phone.
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of other adventure travel sites, but the
content is vast and the material overlaps. For example, Tim Gordon
of Gordons-guide in Fresno, Calif., says that www.gordonsguide.com,
has 800 outfitters listed, who pay an annual fee to be included.
Other big sites are www.away.com, &QL; 
www.greatoutdoors.com, www.iexplore.com; and www.gorp.com, which is
short for Great Outdoor Recreation Pages. Activities like camping,
canoeing or fishing can be searched on www.gorp, which seems to
include almost everything.
</P>
<P>
   The night whitewater trip in Alaska, offered this year for the
first time by Denali Park Resorts, a division of Aramark, will be
able to accommodate 32 people nightly in four rafts, with a guide
in each. The trip is described as quite wet; the 11-mile course
includes stretches labeled Splatter Rock and the Narrows. The
minimum age is 10, and the cost is $72 a person, including
breakfast. For reservations, call (800) 276-7234; for information,
visit www.denalinationalpark.com.
</P>
<P>
   The new Butterfield &AMP; Robinson trips, on largely uninhabited
water systems like the Klinaklini in British Columbia, require a
lot of logistics, including helicopter lifts. For all the rugged
surroundings, Butterfield &AMP; Robinson continues its emphasis on
supersoft nights: wine, tents you can stand in, towels and real
glasses are shipped ahead on cargo rafts, the company says.
</P>
<P>
   Rivers and Oceans Unlimited Expeditions merged with Butterfield
&AMP; Robinson to set up these new trips, which travel through
provincial parks and private lands that cannot accommodate vehicles
</P>
<P>
   The trips range from $2,350 to $4,950 a person for six nights.
Information and catalogues: 70 Bond St., Toronto, Ontario, Canada
M5B 1X3; (800) 678-1147; www.butterfield.com.
</P>
<P>
   Upper Missouri River Guides can be reached at 315 West Fourth
St., Anaconda, Mont. 59711 and (406) 563-2770, as well as at
www.uppermissouri.com. The 46-mile, three-night White Cliffs Tour,
by canoe from Coal Banks to Judith Landing, Mont., costs $735 a
person, meals included.
</P>
<P>
   Float trips like this one on Class I rivers, with no rapids, are
safe enough for young children, but parents should discuss any
river trip carefully with an outfitter, and appraise their
children's tolerance for being confined for hours at a time in what
they may consider boring circumstances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 1902EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
