<P>
   SIERRA-LEONE-U.N. (United Nations) _ Nearly half the
peacekeepers seized in Sierra Leone earlier this month have now
been released, the United Nations said Monday. Officials hope that
releases will continue in coming days. By Barbara Crossette. (475
words)
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-BLAIRS (London) _ Prime Minister Tony Blair, nudged in
public by his wife, Cherie, to take some of the paternity leave his
government has just authorized for British parents, is canceling
his public appearances this week to spend time with her and Leo,
their baby son. By Warren Hoge. (350 words)
</P>
<P>
   ETHIOPIA-ERITREA (Addis Ababa, Ethiopia) _ As envoys arrived
here to try to end the outbreak of war between Ethiopia and
Eritrea, the Ethiopian prime minister said Monday that he was
willing to talk _ but will not stop fighting as the talks go on. By
Ian Fisher. (475 words)
</P>
<P>
   HAITI-ELECTION (Port au Prince, Haiti) _ The results of an
undetermined number of legislative races from Sunday's election may
have to be canceled because ballots were either damaged, lost or
left susceptible to fraud when tired and poorly trained poll
workers dumped huge piles of ballot boxes in a jumble outside of
electoral offices. Officials at several Communal Electoral Offices,
known by the French acronym BEC, arrived at work Monday to discover
that hundreds of ballot boxes had been left there overnight because
poll workers could find no room for them inside. Some boxes were
open, with thousands of ballots and other official documents
scattered on the sidewalk or street. By David Gonzalez. (400 words)
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-PILOTS (Roissy, France) _ There is calm once again inside
the control towers here at Charles de Gaulle airport just outside
Paris. Air France's bold decision to do what was once unthinkable _
make its pilots speak English to the control towers _ lasted a mere
15 days. The airline had the idea that linguistic pride should be
put aside for safety considerations. Rather than having bilingual
airwaves that frequently confuse and infuriate pilots from other
countries, the goal was to have everyone speak English, as happens
at many European airports already. But it wasn't so easy. Last
month, the airline was forced to admit that it had underestimated
both the difficulties of such a conversion and the stubborn Gallic
pride that still persists among French pilots and air controllers.
By Suzanne Daley. (1075 words)
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE-IMPACT (Shanghai, China) _ Sun Guomin, a poor farmer
in a village west of here, represents an example of why American
business executives and government officials may be disappointed
once China enters the World Trade Organization. While American
businesses have been dreaming of the vast potential markets for
their goods and services in China, the government is unlikely to
allow the West the kind of access those dreams are made of. For if
Beijing immediately did everything the trade organization requires,
Mr. Sun and millions like him could be driven out of business. A
news analysis by Craig S. Smith. (1450 words)
</P>
