<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2664 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-LAZIO-PROFILE-HNS &LR;      05-22 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAZIO-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LAZIO IS A LINK BETWEEN HOUSE CONSERVATIVES AND MODERATES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     and JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Rick Lazio, R-N.Y., navigated his way to
political prominence in Congress through a most unlikely route:
Getting Republican conservatives and moderates and even some
Democrats to like him.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, the likely Republican to face Hillary Rodham Clinton for
the U.S. Senate seat in New York, spent seven years in the House
developing political antennae that won him praise from former House
Speaker Newt Gingrich (on the right) and Housing Secretary Andrew
Cuomo (on the left).
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, 42, is ``light-hearted and very informal and relaxed,''
and prone to flipping coins in a back room of the House chamber to
ease tensions, said Rep. Rob Portman, R-Ohio, a close friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not your typical stuffy senator,'' Portman said.
</P>
<P>
   Portman and Lazio have a running practical joke in which one of
them secretly slips an ugly green fruit from New Zealand to the
other, usually during public speaking engagements, to test the
other's grace under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The green fruit, which he says looks a little like a Kiwi fruit,
</P>
<P>
   has surfaced at unexpected times in Lazio's coat pocket and in a
box containing an award.
</P>
<P>
   After New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani cleared the way for
Lazio's Senate bid by withdrawing from the race last Friday,
Portman said Lazio told him: ``There will be plenty of
opportunities to get me with the green fruit.''
</P>
<P>
   Portman said Lazio's sense of humor has helped him forge
connections between conservative and moderate Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets along with everybody in the (Republican) conference,''
Portman said. ``He comes in with a self-deprecating joke and puts
people at ease. People know if they work with him, he's not going
to be hogging all the limelight.''
</P>
<P>
   Ideologically, Lazio is also well positioned to bridge
differences within his party. While he is a fiscal conservative and
was a supporter of the failed balanced budget amendment, he is more
moderate on social issues.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, who grew up in West Islip, N.Y. and graduated from Vassar
College in 1980 and American University law school in 1983, started
his career in Congress in 1993 as an unpredictable maverick.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of 40 Republicans voting for President Clinton's
family medical leave measure, and he was one of 51 Republicans
voting with the Clinton administration to overturn the ``gag rule''
which had made it illegal for medical personnel at federally funded
family planning clinics to discuss abortion with patients.
</P>
<P>
   By 1994, Lazio was voting with Clinton and the Democrats 72
percent of the time, according to a Congressional Quarterly study.
Partly because of the highly publicized 1993 incident on a Long
Island commuter train in which a gunman killed six and wounded 19,
Lazio voted with the Democrats to ban certain kinds of
semiautomatic weapons and for the ``Brady Bill,'' requiring a
five-day wait for handgun purchases.
</P>
<P>
   His pro-environmental voting record was enough for him to win
endorsement from the usually pro-Democratic Sierra Club and the
League of Conservation Voters.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio opposed Clinton's efforts to lift the ban on gays in the
military.
</P>
<P>
   And although he favors maintaining the legal framework of
abortion contained in the U.S. Supreme Court's 1973 Roe v. Wade
decision, he voted to continue the ban on federal funding for
abortion and also to ban late-term abortions.
</P>
<P>
   By 1995 with Republicans in control of Capitol Hill, Lazio was
voting 82 percent of the time with Gingrich. His pro-Clinton voting
that year dropped to 34 percent, according to Congressional
Quarterly.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio was there for Gingrich on important votes. He voted for
term limits for House members, the balanced budget constitutional
amendment,and school vouchers. In 1996, he voted to permit states
to bar illegal immigrants from public education.
</P>
<P>
   But it was in the public housing arena that Lazio made his mark
in the Gingrich revolution.
</P>
<P>
   With so-called Section 8 rental subsidies and 1.5 million units
of housing, the federal Department of Housing and Urban Development
underwrites the shelter needs of 3 million impoverished Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have long viewed the HUD system as breeding
dependency on government, turning mostly urban public housing
projects into islands of entrenched poverty, crime and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in 1995 with his appointment as chair of the House
Banking and Financial Services housing subcommittee, Lazio labored
to remake that system.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio picked his target issue with care. New York leads the
nation in public housing units with 196,949. Illinois is second
with 75,302 and California is third with 45,262.
</P>
<P>
   Three years of defeat, compromise and negotiation ultimately
ended with victory in 1998 when President Clinton signed the HUD
spending bill for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Under the legislation, public housing would no longer be the
reserve of the poorest of the poor. Units would be open to a
greater percentage of the working poor, those just a rung or two up
from the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio pushed for the mix, arguing that it would diminish the
sense of despair and isolation the poorest of the poor feel in huge
blocks of public housing apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Low-income housing advocates countered that without public
housing, those at the lowest end of the poverty scale would have
nowhere to go.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the law required able-bodied, non-working adults in public
housing to perform eight hours of community service a month. But to
get the bill past Clinton's veto pen, Lazio and others on the GOP
negotiating team acceded to several Democratic wishes. Chief among
these was the inclusion of 90,000 new rental vouchers under the
Section 8 subsidy program.
</P>
<P>
   The final legislative product won praise from across the
political spectrum. ``This bill completely overhauls America's
indefensible current public housing system,'' said Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is only a change for the better,'' Cuomo said. ``It
fundamentally transforms public housing.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman and Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920.)
</P>
