   &UR; TOP: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lead story: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-CABLE-TV (Washington) _ Declaring for the first time that
programming on cable television is entitled to the highest level of
First Amendment protection, the Supreme Court on Monday struck down
a federal law that required many cable systems to limit sexually
explicit channels to the late-night hours. The vote was 5-4, with
an unusual lineup of justices that reflected differing views both
on the extent of the problem the 1996 law was passed to address _
the unwanted ``bleed'' of signals from cable channels that a
household had not ordered _ and on the degree of constitutional
``flexibility'' the government should receive in its effort to
shield children from exposure to graphic sexual images. By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   1-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 9 p.m. ET in `w' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Top center: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   3-column photo with ISRAEL-LEBANON; story on FOLD (skedline
below).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-LAW-LICENSE (Washington) _ An Arkansas disciplinary
committee recommended on Monday that President Clinton be disbarred
because of ``serious misconduct'' in the Paula Jones sexual
harassment case. A majority of the panelists who met on Friday to
consider two complaints against the president found that he should
be disciplined for false testimony about his relationship with
Monica Lewinsky, the state Supreme Court said in releasing the
committee recommendation. The recommendation goes to a Pulaski
County Circuit Court judge in Little Rock for disbarment
proceedings. If the judge disbars Clinton, the president can appeal
to the state Supreme Court. By Don Van Natta.
</P>
