   CALIF-DAVIS-JUSTICE (Sacramento, Calif.) _ In the 1998 campaign,
Gov. Gray Davis said he would be tougher on crime than his
Republican opponent. No one took that remark literally. But these
days, Democratic lawmakers say it sometimes seems as though Davis
was only slightly exaggerating. Halfway into his second year in
office, the governor is establishing himself as more of a
tight-fisted conservative on criminal justice issues than his
Republican predecessors, or any other elected official in
California _ if not the nation. The governor has essentially
removed the incentive that makes inmates model prisoners by
refusing any recommendation the parole board has made to grant a
release. He has announced that any judge he appoints should reflect
his sentiments ``or resign.'' He has blocked efforts to reform the
state's notorious ``three strikes'' law, which can put someone in
prison for life for stealing a bicycle if it is their third felony
conviction. And he has vetoed a modest bill that would grant the
press greater access to inmates in the state's notoriously
closed-door prison system, which has been rocked in recent years by
corruption scandals. By Evelyn Nieves. (1800 words)
