<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2668 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LEWIS23-TRIAL-COX     05-22 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS23-TRIAL-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Much is riding on statement by DA today
</P>
<P>
   By Bill Torpy
</P>
<P>
   and Bill Rankin
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After a four-year absence from trying a case, Fulton
County District Attorney Paul Howard today will stand before a jury
and a national audience to argue why football star Ray Lewis should
be found guilty of murder.
</P>
<P>
   In opening arguments, Howard and his team will contend that
Lewis and co-defendants Joseph Sweeting and Reginald Oakley, in
Atlanta for some Super Bowl partying, rushed from Lewis' rented
limousine and stabbed two Decatur men to death.
</P>
<P>
   Howard knows how much is riding today, knowing strong first
impressions often win cases. Defense attorneys can swoop in and win
over jurors with emotional closing arguments. Prosecutors must to
build a foundation with a solid opening and then legitimize their
case, witness by witness.
</P>
<P>
   Howard's case was bolstered Monday when Judge Alice D. Bonner
said the prosecution can use a statement Lewis gave police the
morning of the slayings. Howard is sure to contend Lewis lied to
protect himself and his codefendants.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers had told Bonner that Lt. Michael Smith
threatened to ruin Lewis' career if he didn't speak to police. But
the judge ruled that Lewis' statement was freely and voluntarily
given.
</P>
<P>
   A lengthy trial is anticipated and Howard must unveil a verbal
road map in the hour-long opening to show jurors where they are
being taken in the upcoming weeks. Howard, an accomplished trial
attorney, hasn't tried a case since being elected in 1996, having
played the role as administrator.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest shining moment is the opening for the
prosecution,'' said former Cobb County District Attorney Tom
Charron, who now trains prosecutors at the National Advocacy Center
in Columbia, S.C. ``The opening argument is crucial, especially in
a lengthy case. At the beginning, jurors are the most open they are
going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard's quick murder indictments of Lewis and two friends were
roundly derided as a ``rush to judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   And Lewis' high-priced legal team then quickly upped the ante by
filing a speedy-trial request, thereby telling Howard to prove his
case _ and prove it fast. The defense move pushed prosecutors into
a legal two-minute drill, forcing them to quickly gather evidence
and round up reluctant witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after less than four months of investigation, Fulton
prosecutors say they are ready to go. Observers say it's one of the
fastest murder cases on record.
</P>
<P>
   Former DeKalb County District Attorney Bob Wilson disagreed with
the quick indictment, saying Howard, who is up for re-election this
year, had to rush his investigation and trial preparation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe Paul did a bang-up job; we'll find out soon,'' Wilson
said. ``The eyes of the public are on (Howard). If he doesn't win
against Ray Lewis, then in the eyes of the public, it's a loss.''
</P>
<P>
   The Buckhead stabbing case, in many ways, is a simple crime:
early-morning trash talk turns into deadly street brawl.
</P>
<P>
   The scene was a powder keg awaiting a spark. Both Lewis' party
and the victims' party were drinking. Both sides were armed. Both
had members with criminal records. Both even had a rapper who
reveled in tales of the mean streets.
</P>
<P>
   But the case becomes very complicated with witnesses at the
frenzied scene telling conflicting stories of men with knives and
punches thrown.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in gobs of blood, three defendants, dozens more witnesses,
some DNA testing and things can get pretty confusing.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's what the defense hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys will sometimes trumpet sketchy and conflicting
witness testimony. Other times, they will try to paint the victims
_ Jacinth Baker and Richard Lollar, in this case _ as troublemakers
who threatened the Lewis party into defending themselves. Lewis'
lawyers will portray him as a ``peacemaker'' who tried to defuse
the angry scene.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives and friends of the victims have bristled at the
defense accusations, saying they are being victimized again. Also,
they think the dead men have become forgotten by the blaring
celebrity of the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't need to be OK for someone to have money and get
off; that's telling society it's OK to do these things,'' said
Kellye Smith, Lollar's fiance when he died. Smith and Lollar's
daughter, India, was born several weeks after her father was
killed.
</P>
<P>
   Capturing a sense of the victims will be important to
prosecutors Howard, Clint Rucker and Sheila Ross Finley.
</P>
<P>
   Rucker, 35, and Finley, 29, two of Howard's young rising stars,
were set to try the case alone until recently when the DA stepped
in, he said, to even the odds against a cast of venerable defense
attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   In court, Rucker, a former high school quarterback, switches
between head-on rushes and a gentle bedside manner.
</P>
<P>
   Finley is intense and direct. Prosecutors are generally in the
driver's seat in a criminal case, usually outgunning defenses with
time invested, investigation and evidence.
</P>
<P>
   This case may be different. With the time crunch, the cast of
defense attorneys and the facts of the case _ no witnesses have
placed a knife in Lewis' hand _ anything can happen.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
