u f BC-POLAND-TELEKOM-NYT &LR;      05-22 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLAND-TELEKOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE TELECOM AND PARTNER NEGOTIATE FOR OLD POLISH PHONE SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ France Telecom and a Polish partner, Kulczyk Holding,
received exclusive rights Monday to negotiate the acquisition of a
35 percent stake in the former Polish phone monopoly,
Telekomunikacja Polska, for roughly $4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The deal ushers in what will presumably be the final steps in
the sale of Poland's state phone company to private investors, one
of the largest privatizations in the formerly Communist-ruled
Eastern Europe. The award brings with it the right to raise the
ownership stake to 51 percent by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also opens up Eastern Europe to France Telecom, which
has been struggling to regain momentum after stumbling badly this
year in its international expansion plans.
</P>
<P>
   The pace is expected to accelerate, because France Telecom is
now also considered the front-runner to acquire Orange PLC,
Britain's third-largest cellular phone provider, which Vodafone
AirTouch agreed to sell when it reached a deal to acquire
Mannesmann of Germany in February.
</P>
<P>
   Emil Wasacz, the Polish treasury minister, told a news
conference in Warsaw that the deal provided Telekomunikacja Polska
with a partner capable of supplying ``the knowledge, know-how and
technology necessary to assume a leading market position.''
</P>
<P>
   If France Telecom and Kulczyk, which is controlled by the Polish
entrepreneur Jan Kulczyk, complete the negotiations by June, they
will have an option to acquire a further 16 percent later, giving
them full control of the Polish phone company.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the Polish treasury sold 15 percent of Telekomunikacja
Polska on the stock market and another 15 percent to company
employees. It plans to retain 45 percent of the company after the
full entry of France Telecom and Kulczyk.
</P>
<P>
   The move is a gamble for France Telecom because Telekomunikacja
Polska remains a lumbering dinosaur in a market rapidly shifting to
wireless phones and the Internet. Telekomunikacja, stymied for
decades by Poland's former Communist rulers, has 71,000 employees
and faces growing competition from an array of fresh and nimble
wireless phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   But the Polish government, fearful of heavy job reductions and
eager to preserve a Polish national phone business, has shielded
the giant former monopoly by taking a slow path toward
deregulation, issuing licenses that allow only a single rival in
each of Poland's major cities and reserving lucrative long-distance
lines to Telekomunikacja Polska until 2002 and international
service until a year later.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the government has assured Telekomunikacja Polska
one of four potentially lucrative licenses for a new generation of
wireless phones that will provide users with basic Internet
services.
</P>
<P>
   Still, because of government hesitation over the sale,
overhauling Telekomunikacja Polska has proceeded fitfully, and only
recently has it begun major investments to enhance its wireless and
Internet services. On Friday, it announced a $1 billion bond
offering to help accelerate the financing of those investments.
</P>
<P>
   France Telecom's sole competitor in the bidding was the Italian
carrier, Telecom Italia. Michel Bon, the chief executive of France
Telecom, has been trying to hasten development of international
activities ever since France Telecom abandoned a partnership with
Deutsche Telekom, its German counterpart, early this year in a
venture known as Global One. Deutsche Telekom already owns a 51
percent share of the Hungarian phone company, Matav, and a 22
percent share in Poland's No. 2 cell phone provider.
</P>
<P>
   Based in Warsaw, Telekomunikacja Polska says it has roughly 9
million customers in a country of 42 million people. In the first
quarter, it said net profit rose 450 percent, to the equivalent of
$109 million, on a 25 percent revenue increase, to $760 million. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
