<SLUG> BC-WESTPOINT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bedding maker's planned buyout folds
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shares of WestPoint Stevens fell as much as 36 percent Monday
after it called off a proposed management buyout.
</P>
<P>
   The West Point-based towel and bedding maker announced late
Friday that high financing costs killed a buyout offer of $22 a
share from a group led by Chairman Holcombe Green Jr. The news
pushed the stock to a 52-week low of $11.50 Monday. WestPoint
Stevens closed at $13.25, down $4.75.
</P>
<P>
   The canceled bid followed the Federal Reserve's move to raise
the overnight bank-lending rate by half a point to 6.5 percent, the
highest in nine years. That prompted a major investor to withdraw,
WestPoint Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   The company also said it has abandoned its plan to seek a
buyout, merger or recapitalization.
</P>
<P>
   Fed up with its lagging stock, WestPoint Stevens hired Merrill
Lynch &AMP; Co. in November to help it consider options. Green's group
raised the price of the buyout from $21 a share in March after a
group of shareholders sued the company, charging that the original
offer undervalued their stock.
</P>
<P>
   On a conference call with investors Monday, WestPoint Stevens
said it will now look for acquisition candidates while it tries to
increase sales with new products, said Tim Ghriskey, senior
portfolio manager at Dreyfus Corp.
</P>
<P>
   WestPoint Stevens said during the call that it plans to cut
costs by consolidating operations at some mills and by outsourcing
some of its manufacturing, said analyst Kenneth Smith of
Robinson-Humphrey Co.
</P>
<P>
   Company executives could not be reached for comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have an ambitious plan that requires a significant change
from the way they've been doing things,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking a wait-and-see approach,'' said Smith, who
downgraded the shares to ``underperform'' from ``outperform.''
</P>
<P>
   Lower demand for WestPoint Stevens' products have hurt sales and
profit in recent quarters.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan analyst Noelle Grainger noted several risks for
current earnings estimates, such as a lack of management guidance
over the past six months, weak business trends and possible
downtime at mills.
</P>
<P>
   Grainger is holding estimates at $2.17 a share for the year but
cut the stock to ``market performer'' from ``long-term buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
