u f BC-ONLINE-TOYS-BOS &LR;      05-22 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-TOYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOYSMART.COM WILL CLOSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Toysmart Inc., a once-hot Internet retailer that captured the
eye _ and the money _ of the Walt Disney Co., said Monday that it
has instead closed its online doors after failing to drum up
investor support.
</P>
<P>
   The company collapsed Friday, after negotiations over new
funding crumbled and its board _ mostly Disney employees _ opted to
shut everything down. Toysmart.com will close its headquarters and
shop in Waltham, Mass., and a distribution center in Worcester,
Mass. Disney had invested $45 million in the company since August.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the retailer's 170 employees were packing boxes Monday,
and a few sadly joked that they might sell themselves on eBay's
auction site as a prepackaged team of high-tech workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did the best we could,'' Toysmart.com chief executive David
Lord said Monday. ``I'm trying the best I can to help our
employees. That's my only concern right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Toysmart.com had hoped to carve out a niche in a competitive
marketplace by offering safe, educational toys to parents. Its
now-closed Web site had offered plenty of plush Disney toys,
puzzles, and games _ but no plastic toy weapons.
</P>
<P>
   But the company stumbled as the ranks of Internet toy stores
grew, investors began snubbing dot-coms, and Disney reconsidered
its Internet strategy, Lord said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any one of those you can probably overcome,'' he said. ``But
all three _ it's too great a challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past month, Toysmart.com has been trying to reorganize
its operations to please Disney and other investors. It laid off 55
employees and mapped a new strategy of selling to businesses and
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   But after negotiations over the new investment broke down,
Toysmart.com's board voted to shutter the company. ``Everyone said,
`Well, that's it then,' '' Lord said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Lord purchased the online toy business he had developed
for the Holt family, which retained a 1 percent equity stake in
Toysmart.com.
</P>
<P>
   Under Lord, Toysmart.com grew to to approximately $10 million in
revenue in 1998, according to corporate research by Hoover's Inc.
The closely held retailer did not release its annual sales last
year.
</P>
<P>
   In the graveyard of dot-com companies, Toysmart.com will not be
alone. Gift shop Violet.com and education toy retailer Red Rocket
have closed ther Web sites, and last week, British apparel merchant
Boo.com announced its imminent demise after failing to attract
much-needed investment.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Craftshop.com, an Internet arts and crafts retailer
backed by Andover-based CMGI Inc., filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy
protection in Wilmington, Del. The Connecticut retailer hopes to
sell off its assets, including its domain name and Web store.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts believe the dot-com failures have only begun. In a
report last month, Forrester Research predicted that financial
performances, heavy ad spending, and competitive pressures will
drive most online retailers out of business by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of traditional stores are taking their spin at the
Internet game, (and) much more emphatically,'' said David
Cooperstein, an analyst with Forrester in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Internet-only merchants, retail giants like Wal-Mart
Stores Inc. and Toys ``R'' Us Inc. have such recognized names that
they do not have to dig deeply into their pockets to advertise
their Web stores.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester also sounded a warning after Disney paid $20 million
in August for a controlling stake in Toysmart.com. ``Beware of the
mouse's appetite,'' its analysts wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Disney, it was a good move,'' Cooperstein said. ``For
Toysmart.com, it was a dangerous game. It wasn't like this was a
venture capitalist in Silicon Valley willing to focus on potential.
Disney is very concerned when things don't pan out the way it
anticipated.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Disney chief executive Michael Eisner said
his company's Internet holdings were in no danger of failing. ``Not
only will Disney's Internet assets survive, they will thrive,''
Eisner said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   But his company's Go.com Internet unit, which includes
Toysmart.com and Disney Online, is grappling with employee turnover
and slower-than-anticipated growth. And now, Toysmart.com is being
eliminated from Disney's Internet roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I can't talk (as) to what Michael Eisner is speaking
of,'' said Lord, Toysmart.com's chief executive. ``I only know that
Go.com has stated that it's changing and is being redefined. I
guess we're a part of that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 1947EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
