<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2686 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-EARTHLINK-COX     05-22 0290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARTHLINK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EarthLink to provide Internet access for Sprint
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EarthLink Inc. will be the Internet service provider for
Sprint's new high-speed wireless service, the companies announced
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based EarthLink, which merged several months ago with
MindSpring Enterprises, will provide the ``core set of Internet
tools'' that Sprint will use in providing broadband _ that is, the
connection capable of handling massive amounts of data rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of high-speed link is considered necessary for
transmitting video, audio and graphics, as well as for passing
along huge amounts of data without forcing an endless wait upon the
recipient. Sprint will provide the service by transmitting from a
tower to a 13.5-inch by 13.5-inch digital transceiver on the home
or business of the customer.
</P>
<P>
   EarthLink already has software available for broadband provided
via cable modems and digital subscriber lines, and the deal with
Sprint adds a wireless option, said EarthLink spokesman Kurt Rahn.
</P>
<P>
   EarthLink's technology is already in use in Phoenix as part of
Sprint's first trial of the wireless service, he said. Sprint says
the service allows Internet download speeds up to 5 mbps.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint, which owns 26.7 percent of EarthLink, plans to expand
the service to other cities later this year. In Atlanta, the
license for fixed wireless is owned by WorldCom, which has an
agreement to buy Sprint _ subject to regulatory approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, one of us will roll it out,'' said Sprint
spokesman Robert Hoskins. ``Atlanta is a pretty big market.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
