<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2687 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-BROADBAND-RURAL-BOS &LR;      05-22 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROADBAND-RURAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATOR KERRY PLANS LEGISLATION TO NARROW `DIGITAL DIVIDE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOWELL, Mass. _ Taking aim at the ``digital divide,'' US Senator
John F. Kerry of Massachusetts on Monday said he and Senator Daniel
Patrick Moynihan of New York will introduce legislation offering
tax credits to phone and cable companies for rolling out
broadband-speed Internet access in poor and hard-to-serve rural
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a hearing on broadband availability, Kerry said he
and Moynihan, both Democrats, are working out the final details on
the tax credit plan and hope to file their bill, with Republican
support, no later than next week.
</P>
<P>
   The tax credit, if adopted, might have its biggest impact in
rural parts of the South and West. But it could have at least some
impact in Massachusetts, where 151 of the 351 cities and towns _
mostly west of Worcester _ reported no cable modem or telephone
digital subscriber line offerings in a mid-April survey by the
quasi-public Massachusetts Technology Collaborative in Westborough.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry's proposal came at the New England edition of a series of
national hearings sponsored by the Federal Communications
Commission and state utility regulators. The goal is to get ideas
on how to accelerate the development of broadband-speed Net access,
which by most estimates is currently available to fewer than 4
million American homes.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry said he, Moynihan and Senate Finance Committee staffers
have still to determine how much of a tax credit companies would
get. But he said in an interview, ``It will be generous. We want to
get it out there fast. I think there is definitely bipartisan
support for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry said the proposed measure has raised a host of issues,
including questions of what level of subsidy phone companies should
get relative to cable companies and those offering fixed wireless
services for high-speed Net access. ``The minute you get into
starting talking about this credit, you get into all sorts of
issues of what is qualifying and what is not,'' Kerry said.
</P>
<P>
   Some participants at Monday's hearing at Middlesex Community
College said a plan like Kerry's could prove crucial to bringing
high-speed access to poor or rural parts of the country where big
carriers otherwise might have little incentive to invest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rural areas are going to get left out unless there are
some pretty strong incentives put into place by policymakers,''
said Tod A. Jacobs, a telecommunications strategist and managing
director with J.P. Morgan in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs said cable companies can roll out 1.5-megabit-per-second
broadband access at a cost of about $143 per home in the 10 percent
of neighborhoods that are most densely settled. But he said the
service to sparsely populated areas easily can cost $1,000 per
subscriber, making it prohibitively expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, barely 50 percent of customers of Bell Atlantic and
GTE, which are merging this summer, are in neighborhoods that are
both close enough to switching facilities and have average
household income of $75,000, the two conditions likeliest to
determine where phone companies offer DSL.
</P>
<P>
   Only 34 percent of customers meet such criteria in US West's
Rocky Mountain/High Plains service territory, and only 29 percent
in the Bell South region.
</P>
<P>
   However, David Gabel, a Newton-based professor at Queens College
in New York who is credited with some of the country's most
far-reaching studies of broadband access availability, cautioned
that Kerry's plan could be fiendishly complex to implement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just figuring out a way to do this for phone service was
difficult enough,'' Gabel said, referring to federal subsidies for
rural telephone service. Gabel cautioned that the complexities of
sorting out how much of a subsidy should be offered for cable
modems, various types of DSL and multiple fixed-wireless schemes,
in many geographies and markets, could be fatally complicated for
Congress to resolve.
</P>
<P>
   And Victor Glass, executive director of the National Exchange
Carrier Association, which represents 1,100 independent, mostly
rural phone companies, said all evidence shows that ``rural phone
companies are rapidly deploying a broadband network,'' taking
advantage of newer technologies that are cheaper and easier to use
in areas that may have only 10 or 20 phone lines per square mile.
At least 150 of his group's members are now offering the services.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
