<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2688 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LEWIS-JURY-COX     05-22 0426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-JURY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lewis jury satisfies prosecution, defense
 &HT;    By Bill Torpy and Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Four of the jurors have sat on juries before. Another
two said they didn't think they were up to the daunting task. Yet,
here they are.
</P>
<P>
   A jury dominated by nine black women was chosen Monday to sit in
judgment over the Buckhead stabbings case. It is composed of 10
women and two men, 10 black people and two white people. Five
alternates also were selected for the anticipated monthlong trial.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors have had family members arrested and have been crime
victims. Some teach Sunday school, some watch Jerry Springer and
``The Practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the prosecution and the defense both said they liked what
they got.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very happy with the jury,'' said David Wolfe, a lawyer
for defendant Reginald Oakley. ``It's a group of people that will
be attentive and responsive to their obligations under the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulton County District Attorney Paul Howard said he was pleased
to have all the women jurors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They provide the conscience and soul of this community,'' he
said. ``I couldn't be happier.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard then added, ``I'd take 12 Martians to hear it.''
</P>
<P>
   With his six strikes, Howard made sure at least some jurors
would not serve. These included a man who called half of Atlanta's
police officers ``dirty'' and a civil defense lawyer who provided
free legal help to indigent defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 12 chosen, all admitted to having heard something about
the case. The limo stood out the most. Other than that, things were
kind of sketchy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We discussed he might have did it or he might not,'' said
Juror 56 of water cooler discussions on the case. She has served on
a jury. It was a good experience, she said.
</P>
<P>
   During five days of jury selection, it became apparent that
jurors have big-city sensibilities, yet several retained a
small-town familiarity.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about her initial reaction to reports of the Buckhead
stabbings, Juror 31 shrugged and said: ``To me, it's nothing new.
There's always someone getting hurt. Same old same old.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the 30-something woman, like many others on the original
pool, knows a fellow juror _ a finance account manager who was an
old high school chum. Out-of-town journalists were struck by how
many in the pool knew each other, demonstrating that no matter how
big the metro area gets, Atlanta, the city, remains small in many
respects.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
