<HEADER>
A2691 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-22 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HEAT ARE FEELING THE PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is a time to be charitable. The Miami Heat are in pain, and
cannot be held fully responsible for the things they are saying.
</P>
<P>
   The problem starts with the top man, of course, and that means
president/coach/strongman Pat Riley, as opposed to owner Mickey
Arrison. Riley works his teams hard _ so hard, in fact, that the
players develop a sense of entitlement. The reasoning goes
something like this: No one works harder than us; therefore, we
deserve to win.
</P>
<P>
   And when, for the third straight year, it does not work out to
their satisfaction when playing the hated New York Knicks, both
coach and players search for a reason other than their own
fallibility. On Sunday, the convenient scapegoats were referees
Dick Bavetta, Danny Crawford, and Bennett Salvatore.
</P>
<P>
   New York shot 31 free throws to our 21 . . . Too many touch
fouls in the final four minutes . . . Some of our guys took it to
the hoop and couldn't get to the line . . . It shouldn't have been
a jump ball in the final 12 seconds; Zo should have been at the
line . . . Majerle never fouled Houston at the end of Game 6 . . .
Sprewell never called that final timeout . . . The league and NBC
both want New York and LA in the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Et cetera, et cetera, et cetera, as the monarch says in ``The
King And I.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley began his postgame press conference lamenting the
officiating. Tim Hardaway refused to speak of anything else,
basically accusing the officiating trio of cheating. Alonzo
Mourning insisted repeatedly that Miami was the better team and had
been done in by the referees. The truth is that the Heat are in
understandable denial.
</P>
<P>
   Both Games 6 and 7 were as much lost as they were won, and in
the sober light of some future day the coaching staff undoubtedly
will acknowledge Miami's culpability. Right now, the loss is too
painful to analyze properly, but when Riley &AMP; Co. examine the
evidence, they will admit the truth. They are too smart not to do
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so how did Miami twice snatch defeat from the jaws of
victory? Let us count the ways.
</P>
<P>
   1. By losing an 18-point second-quarter lead in Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   2. By scoring 25 points in the second half of Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   3. By Mourning allowing 37-year-old Patrick Ewing to slip inside
him for a crucial follow-up dunk with 1:57 remaining in Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   4. By P.J. Brown fouling Chris Childs in the backcourt with 1:31
remaining in Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   5. By Dan Majerle missing a technical foul shot in the second
quarter of Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   6. By allowing the Knicks _ the Knicks! _ to score 9 points in a
second-quarter stretch of 45 seconds in Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   7. By failing to hold a 6-point lead with 4:44 remaining in Game
7.
</P>
<P>
   8. By the 6-9 Mourning's inability to exploit the 6-6 Larry
Johnson in the fourth period of Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   9. By no one other than Hardaway scoring a basket in the final
seven minutes of Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   10. By Mourning foolishly attempting to steal a Johnson entry
pass to Ewing, said transgression (carrying about 10 percent chance
of success) leading to an open Ewing dunk that became the winning
basket with 1:20 remaining in Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   11. By Jamal Mashburn's combined 6-for-27 shooting in Games 6
and 7, culminating in his passing up the final shot he absolutely
should have taken and allowing his team's fate to be decided by sub
Clarence Weatherspoon.
</P>
<P>
   12. By Anthony Carter and Weatherspoon each missing makeable
shots that could have (a) tied and (b) won Games 6 and 7,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   13. By shooting a Shaq-like 11 for 21 from the foul line in Game
7.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yeah, the refs beat 'em, all right.
</P>
<P>
   As much as it is ever possible to even use the term in a heated
matchup such as this, the sad reality is that Miami really did have
control of both Games 6 and 7 with four minutes to go. And Game 7
was at home. But whether New York found a way to win or Miami found
a way to lose _ take your pick, but I'm opting for the latter _ New
York took both games, and that's that.
</P>
<P>
   The flip side is that New York deserved to win because the
Knicks had more people turning in big individual performances and
making more big plays when the last two games were being decided.
Ewing turned in 15-18 and 20-10 games and had the aforementioned
monster put-back in Game 6 and the winner in Game 7. Latrell
Sprewell had a huge 20-point first half in Game 7. Chris Childs
scored 13 consecutive New York points in a second-half stretch.
Most of all, the entire New York team played exemplary team defense
when it was most needed. Miami can squawk and moan from now till
the Twelfth of Never, but the record will show that in the final
combined 7:02 of Games 6 and 7, with 6-point leads at the
four-minute mark of each game, it was outscored, 16-3.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, indeed, the Heat work hard for Riley. They might be right.
They really might be the hardest-working team in a league of
across-the-board hard workers. They work hard, and no one doubts
how badly they want to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have empathy for any coach, or any team, that puts as much
into it as they do,'' saluted New York coach Jeff Van Gundy, a
former Riley assistant and a great Riley admirer.
</P>
<P>
   That's very nice, but in the crucible of professional sport,
perceived virtue is not its own reward. You've got to make shots
and you've got to think clearly, too, and in the biggest moments of
Games 6 and 7, the Heat did neither.
</P>
<P>
   The brainwashed Heat are like members of a Doomsday Cult who are
slowly learning that their most cherished beliefs are just so much
propaganda. They were convinced they would win because they were
worthy. It's always hard to accept the fact that you lost because
you just weren't good enough.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 1951EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000522.0337 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2692 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LEWIS-SCENE-COX     05-22 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-SCENE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Few in Baltimore believe Lewis is guilty
 &HT;    By Dan Chapman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Mother's Federal Hill Grille, in a gentrifying
section of red-brick row houses within walking distance of the
Baltimore Ravens shiny new stadium, no longer offers ``Free Ray
Lewis'' T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   They're sold out.
</P>
<P>
   The infamous black Navigator limousine, recently
blood-splattered and bullet-riddled, doesn't spend much time parked
on its lot out near the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Its service is requested virtually every night.
</P>
<P>
   And talk-show fans in west Baltimore, where the row houses
aren't as tidy, can't escape the Ray Lewis-is-innocent drumbeat
coming from their radios.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt about it,'' says Larry Young, whose morning show on
WOLB-AM attracts nary an anti-Lewis caller, ``it's still the talk
in barber shops, beauty salons, restaurants, bus corners, cabs.
That's about all people are talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   With Lewis' murder trial set to start today in Atlanta, the
outpouring of interest and opinion in Baltimore soon could reach
Super Bowl-esque levels of fervor. The feeling here is that the
hometown hero needs to win the judicial equivalent of an away game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baltimore sees it as a big influencing factor in the way the
community is looked at,'' says architect Darryl Hawkins over eggs,
pancakes and coffee at the Federal Hill bar. ``Baltimore has enough
bad press right now, what with the incredible proliferation of
killings. And heroin is crippling Baltimore. This trial is just
another black eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins, like virtually everybody else interviewed across
Baltimore the past few days, says Lewis is guilty _ of bad
judgment. Few believe he actually stabbed Jacinth Baker or Richard
Lollar. ``Wrong place, wrong time, wrong crowd,'' is the phrase
repeated almost mantra-like throughout this port town.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's guilty of stupidity and hanging out with stupid people,''
says Bill Richards, a semi-retiree sipping rum at the Windsor Inn
Crab House, a favorite Monday night haunt of Lewis and other
Ravens. ``You make $6 million a year, you ought to be hanging
around the yacht club or the country club.''
</P>
<P>
   The regulars at the Windsor Inn speak of Lewis mainly as a
football player, and what the most-feared middle linebacker in the
game means to a team _ and a town _ that hasn't had much sports
cheer of late.
</P>
<P>
   This, after all, is the city where Johnny Unitas and Cal Ripken
ruled. Talent-wise, Ray Lewis might be their equal. And with the
Colts finally replaced by the unproven Ravens, and with the Orioles
enduring yet another sorry season, fans here dream of football
glory this fall.
</P>
<P>
   John Ziemann compares Lewis to Unitas _ the ultimate Baltimore
compliment _ an old-school, nails-tough player who willingly signs
autographs. A guilty verdict would leave a gaping hole in the
Ravens' defense, Ziemann says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would not be a critical blow. It would not be a crucial
blow. It would be a great wound,'' says Ziemann, president of
Baltimore's Marching Ravens, the 400-member team band. ``But wounds
do heal.''
</P>
<P>
   Some more easily than others. The Lewis saga highlights parts of
the city's underbelly that won't stay hidden. Beyond the glittering
new football and baseball stadia, the Inner Harbor's
revitalization, and its progressive political leadership, Baltimore
can't shake its drugs and crime. Roughly 115 people have been
murdered in Baltimore this year, a pace likely to continue the
city's decade-long, 300-plus-murder-a-year average.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are 29 or so (murders) ahead of the pace of last year,''
says Young, the radio host who served more than two decades in the
Maryland Legislature. ``We are at the point where enough is
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Young's audience is predominantly black, and their opinions
mirror a recent Baltimore Sun poll. Fifty-four percent of black
people say Lewis is innocent; 33 percent of white people agree. Yet
only 5 percent of black people believe Lewis is guilty, compared to
30 percent of white people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blacks are probably saying, `He's one of ours,''' says
Hawkins, the black architect. ``Conversely, maybe whites are taking
the approach that he's another spoiled, rich, catered-to athlete
again in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   LLOYD FOX / Staff
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion: This T-shirt is a hot item in Baltimore, where
most black people say Ray Lewis is innocent.
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE,MD--FEBRUARY 7, 2000--Free Ray Lewis tee-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   RAY LEWIS TRIAL
</P>
