<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-SCENE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Few in Baltimore believe Lewis is guilty
 &HT;    By Dan Chapman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Mother's Federal Hill Grille, in a gentrifying
section of red-brick row houses within walking distance of the
Baltimore Ravens shiny new stadium, no longer offers ``Free Ray
Lewis'' T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   They're sold out.
</P>
<P>
   The infamous black Navigator limousine, recently
blood-splattered and bullet-riddled, doesn't spend much time parked
on its lot out near the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Its service is requested virtually every night.
</P>
<P>
   And talk-show fans in west Baltimore, where the row houses
aren't as tidy, can't escape the Ray Lewis-is-innocent drumbeat
coming from their radios.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt about it,'' says Larry Young, whose morning show on
WOLB-AM attracts nary an anti-Lewis caller, ``it's still the talk
in barber shops, beauty salons, restaurants, bus corners, cabs.
That's about all people are talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   With Lewis' murder trial set to start today in Atlanta, the
outpouring of interest and opinion in Baltimore soon could reach
Super Bowl-esque levels of fervor. The feeling here is that the
hometown hero needs to win the judicial equivalent of an away game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baltimore sees it as a big influencing factor in the way the
community is looked at,'' says architect Darryl Hawkins over eggs,
pancakes and coffee at the Federal Hill bar. ``Baltimore has enough
bad press right now, what with the incredible proliferation of
killings. And heroin is crippling Baltimore. This trial is just
another black eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins, like virtually everybody else interviewed across
Baltimore the past few days, says Lewis is guilty _ of bad
judgment. Few believe he actually stabbed Jacinth Baker or Richard
Lollar. ``Wrong place, wrong time, wrong crowd,'' is the phrase
repeated almost mantra-like throughout this port town.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's guilty of stupidity and hanging out with stupid people,''
says Bill Richards, a semi-retiree sipping rum at the Windsor Inn
Crab House, a favorite Monday night haunt of Lewis and other
Ravens. ``You make $6 million a year, you ought to be hanging
around the yacht club or the country club.''
</P>
<P>
   The regulars at the Windsor Inn speak of Lewis mainly as a
football player, and what the most-feared middle linebacker in the
game means to a team _ and a town _ that hasn't had much sports
cheer of late.
</P>
<P>
   This, after all, is the city where Johnny Unitas and Cal Ripken
ruled. Talent-wise, Ray Lewis might be their equal. And with the
Colts finally replaced by the unproven Ravens, and with the Orioles
enduring yet another sorry season, fans here dream of football
glory this fall.
</P>
<P>
   John Ziemann compares Lewis to Unitas _ the ultimate Baltimore
compliment _ an old-school, nails-tough player who willingly signs
autographs. A guilty verdict would leave a gaping hole in the
Ravens' defense, Ziemann says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would not be a critical blow. It would not be a crucial
blow. It would be a great wound,'' says Ziemann, president of
Baltimore's Marching Ravens, the 400-member team band. ``But wounds
do heal.''
</P>
<P>
   Some more easily than others. The Lewis saga highlights parts of
the city's underbelly that won't stay hidden. Beyond the glittering
new football and baseball stadia, the Inner Harbor's
revitalization, and its progressive political leadership, Baltimore
can't shake its drugs and crime. Roughly 115 people have been
murdered in Baltimore this year, a pace likely to continue the
city's decade-long, 300-plus-murder-a-year average.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are 29 or so (murders) ahead of the pace of last year,''
says Young, the radio host who served more than two decades in the
Maryland Legislature. ``We are at the point where enough is
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Young's audience is predominantly black, and their opinions
mirror a recent Baltimore Sun poll. Fifty-four percent of black
people say Lewis is innocent; 33 percent of white people agree. Yet
only 5 percent of black people believe Lewis is guilty, compared to
30 percent of white people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blacks are probably saying, `He's one of ours,''' says
Hawkins, the black architect. ``Conversely, maybe whites are taking
the approach that he's another spoiled, rich, catered-to athlete
again in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   LLOYD FOX / Staff
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion: This T-shirt is a hot item in Baltimore, where
most black people say Ray Lewis is innocent.
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE,MD--FEBRUARY 7, 2000--Free Ray Lewis tee-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   RAY LEWIS TRIAL
</P>
