u a BC-SCI-DAEDALUS-2TAKES-N     05-22 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DAEDALUS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAEDALUS, THE COURT JESTER IN THE PALACE OF SCIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By MALCOLM W. BROWNE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   By fighting mock battles with its siblings a lion cub masters
skills useful for bringing down zebras, and a child learns tactics
helpful for survival in a competitive human society.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists, like cubs and children, also play, in more
sophisticated ways.
</P>
<P>
   Einstein's ``thought experiments,'' for example, were a form of
intellectual play that helped him understand the implications of
relativity.
</P>
<P>
   When the celebrated popularizer of science Carl Sagan wrote his
novel ``Contact'' (in the movie adaptation of which Jodie Foster
travels almost instantly to a distant star system), Sagan needed to
consult his friend Kip Thorne for technical help.
</P>
<P>
   Thorne, a relativity expert at the California Institute of
Technology, undertook the playful task of analyzing Sagan's
fictional scheme for traveling through black holes and discovered a
fundamental error. Thorne went on to devise a remotely plausible
alternative travel plan exploiting ``worm holes'' instead of black
holes to communicate with distant parts of a spatially folded
universe.
</P>
<P>
   Thorne's idea not only lent credibility to Sagan's novel but
gave rise to a half dozen serious scientific papers dealing with
the possibility of time travel. It also played a major role in
Thorne's best-selling book for science fans called ``Black Holes
and Time Warps: Einstein's Outrageous Legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   In similar spirit, an imaginative and irreverent English
scientist who writes under the pen name Daedalus has been tweaking
scientific orthodoxy in weekly columns for the last 36 years.
Daedalus' true identity is Dr. David E.H. Jones, a physical chemist
on the faculty of the University of Newcastle upon Tyne in England.
</P>
<P>
   To the delight of his fans _ scientists and scientifically
literate readers _102 of Daedalus' columns have been anthologized
by Oxford University Press as ``The Further Inventions of
Daedalus.'' (The first compilation of his columns, ``The Inventions
of Daedalus,'' was published by W.H. Freeman &AMP; Co. in 1982.)
</P>
<P>
   A self-described ``court jester in the Palace of Science,''
Jones is an expert in chemical spectroscopy and other sober
subjects, and since 1988 his column has been published weekly by
the impeccably serious scientific journal Nature. But his research
projects have sometimes flown wildly off the track of mainstream
science.
</P>
<P>
   One of his achievements was the construction of a fraudulent
perpetual motion machine, for which he offered a small prize to
anyone able to deduce what made it keep turning with no evident
source of power.
</P>
<P>
   After some two decades the machine still operates, he said,
``and although one scientist came close to guessing its secret, no
one has won the prize.'' Perpetual motion, of course, is prohibited
by the second law of thermodynamics.
</P>
<P>
   Another of his projects led to the discovery of arsenic in a
lock of Napoleon Bonaparte's hair and the consequent suspicion that
the French emperor had been poisoned by his English captors on the
island of St. Helena, where he spent his final days. It turned out,
however, that the wallpaper in Napoleon's St. Helena bedroom was
colored with an arsenic-based green dye, and poisonous arsenic
fumes were inadvertently released from the paper by mold. If
Napoleon died of poisoning, it was apparently accidental.
</P>
<P>
   One of Jones' engineering successes was the construction of a
bicycle so unstable as to be unridable. Useless as a vehicle, the
bicycle became the basis of an article by Jones in a publication of
the Massachusetts Institute of Technology called Bicycle Science.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bicycle itself is long gone,'' he said, ``but I am now
celebrated as the founder of modern bicycle theory.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of Daedalus' ideas begin as jokes and end up as serious
contributions to science; some 21 percent of his published ideas
(which have appeared in New Scientist, The Guardian and Nature), he
says, have turned out to have at least some basis in reality.
</P>
<P>
   Jones regards Daedalus' crowning achievement as the prediction
of buckminsterfullerene _ a chemical family of hollow carbon
molecules. In its issue of Nov. 3, 1966, the British magazine New
Scientist published a column by Jnes titled ``Hollow Molecules''
that said: Daedalus ``has conceived the hollow molecule.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' it continues, ``would be a closed spherical shell of a
sheet polymer like graphite, whose basic molecule is a flat sheet
of carbon atoms bonded hexagonally rather like chicken wire.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1985 two Americans and one Briton discovered just such a
molecule, giving birth to an entirely new branch of organic
chemistry. In 1996 the discoverers were awarded a Nobel Prize in
Chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are one or two columns in my new book likely to have
equally illustrious futures,'' Jones said, ``but I'm not going to
tell you which ones they are.''
</P>
<P>
   They are not likely to be the Daedalus nuclear pogo stick or the
black hole garbage disposal machine or a scheme, based on recent
findings in molecular biology, to hasten the sentences of prisoners
by aging them artificially.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
