<HEADER>
A2701 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS     05-22 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     UPGRADING TO WINDOWS 2000 INCLUDES MAJOR REINSTALLATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DWIGHT SILVERMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I am interested in trying out Windows 2000, but I don't want
to lose my Windows 98 setup. I understand you can dual-boot with
both operating systems, but would I have to reinstall all my
applications to get them to work in Windows 2000?
</P>
<P>
   A: This question comes up each time Microsoft releases a new
operating system, and the answer is always the same.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you will need to reinstall the programs you want to use
with both Windows 98 and 2000 in a dual-boot setup. This is because
Windows 2000 and Windows 98 do not share the same Registry, or
master configuration file, and in a sense do not know about each
other.
</P>
<P>
   When you install a Windows program, it tells the operating
system key information about itself by adding information to the
Registry. Often, the program cannot run without accessing the
information stored in the Registry.
</P>
<P>
   So long as both operating systems are using the File Allocation
Table, or FAT, file system, you can find the folders for your
applications in either Windows 98 and Windows 2000. But if you try
to click on a program installed in Windows 98 and you're running
Windows 2000, it probably won't launch. And if it does, it may
behave strangely.
</P>
<P>
   If you choose to install the program again in Windows 2000, you
can usually use the same installation path. However, some Windows
programs have their configuration files separate from the Registry,
and these files may include pointers to the operating system. So,
when you reinstall under Windows 2000, it may change the pointers
so they no longer work with your Windows 98 setup.
</P>
<P>
   If so, you will probably need two installations in two separate
folders _ one for Windows 2000 and one for Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   The situation gets even more tricky if you want to use the High
Performance File System, or HPFS, available with Windows 2000.
Here, you will almost certainly need separate installations of all
software, and you will need to set Windows 2000 up in its own
partition on your hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 2000 is a business operating system, and given its
complexity, if you don't need it for business purposes, you may
want to stay away and keep your computing life simple.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a notebook computer that is three years old. I
recently had to buy another battery because the old one began to
need charging more frequently. When I first got it, it would go
three hours without a charge. When I finally replaced it, it was
down to 30 minutes. What happened?
</P>
<P>
   A: Certain types of batteries develop what is known as the
``memory effect.'' It is caused by not letting the battery
completely discharge before you begin recharging it.
</P>
<P>
   The battery basically develops a kind of floor for recharging.
Let's say your battery started with three hours of life, but you
started charging it when it had used up only two. Do that enough,
and the battery will only take a two-hour charge. If you notice
it's only getting two hours and you decide to play it safe by
recharging after 90 minutes, that will become your new starting
point.
</P>
<P>
   This happens primarily to older nickel-cadmium batteries, and to
a lesser extent to nickel-metal-hydride batteries. More modern
lithium ion batteries are relatively resistant to it.
</P>
<P>
   There is some controversy as to whether the memory effect really
exists.
</P>
<P>
   But millions of home videocam owners who have replaced $80
batteries can attest to its existence!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
