<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2703 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-ROAD-COX     05-22 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-ROAD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Furcal's flair turns heads around NL
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ He will begin seeing more curveballs now and feel a
greater effort to move him off the plate. And more pickoff attempts
once he reaches first, if just to make him feel the dirt.
</P>
<P>
   The National League will get serious about Rafael Furcal now,
probing for what the Atlanta rookie cannot do.
</P>
<P>
   The answer thus far: not much.
</P>
<P>
   With the season one-quarter done, Furcal, at 19 the youngest
player in the major leagues, has gone from spring training curio to
Opening Day gamble to Rookie of the Year candidate. Batting .324 as
Atlanta opens a nine-game road trip tonight in Milwaukee, he is
vying to become just the third 19-year-old in major league history
to hit .300. The others were Mel Ott and Cesar Cedeno.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, as flabbergasted as anyone, have seen nothing like
this.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one. Never,'' said first baseman Andres Galarraga, a
major-leaguer since 1985. ``The way he talks, the way he acts, the
way he plays, everything, he's like no one.''
</P>
<P>
   Furcal leads all major-league rookies in average, on-base
percentage (.405) and walks (15) and is tied with Anaheim rookie
Adam Kennedy with 10 stolen bases. Only Kennedy and Texas' Ruben
Mateo have more hits. While Houston catcher Mitch Meluskey has
superior power numbers among first-year NL players, Furcal has
reached base (51 times in 36 games) and scored more times (26 runs)
than any of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never dealt with a kid who was so far advanced at such an
early age,'' said Pat Corrales, the dugout coach, who is in his
41st year of professional baseball. ``There was no doubt in his
mind from Day 1 that he could play here. He had to convince some
other people, but not in his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Handicappers breaking down candidates for Rookie of the Year
might place Furcal above Meluskey and San Francisco's Calvin Murray
among NL position players. But St. Louis left-hander Rick Ankiel
(3-2, 3.94) has drawn raves for his polish at just 20 years old; he
is 13 months older than Furcal. Cincinnati's Rob Bell, dealt away
by Atlanta two winters ago in the Bret Boone-Mike Remlinger deal,
is right behind Ankiel.
</P>
<P>
   If it is too early for such flattery, no one realizes it better
than Furcal, who gave a incredulous grin when someone suggested he
might win the award.
</P>
<P>
   ``The season is too long,'' he said. ``I'm not thinking about
anything except right now. We have 120 more games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have been thunderstruck by his early performance.
Skeptical early, hitting coach Merv Rettenmund concluded in spring
camp that Furcal swung a stronger bat from the left side, which
would make for a good platoon mix with shortstop Walt Weiss, who is
stronger from the right.
</P>
<P>
   But seven weeks have convinced Rettenmund that he was 100
percent wrong. Furcal is better right-handed (.333, with a .395
slugging percentage) than as a lefty (.300).
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked up the other day and he was hitting .337,''
Rettenmund said. ``And I just said to myself, 'What if? What if he
wins a batting title?' I mean, I don't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might have a time when it goes bad. But I can't compare him
to another Rookie of the Year because I've never seen a 19-year-old
play in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing time for Weiss and Furcal has become a sensitive issue.
Manager Bobby Cox's original concern was to make sure Furcal got
his two or three starts a week at short or second. Now, the concern
is why keep such a force on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll work out,'' Cox said. ``I don't want to make any comment
until I talk to Walt.''
</P>
<P>
   But Weiss understands the impact of a young player. He was the
AL Rookie of the Year in Oakland in 1988 when the Bash Brothers A's
came together. Weiss had played three years at North Carolina
andlus three seasons in the minors before winning the award at age
24.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's gotten better and better already,'' Weiss said.
``I've seen improvement from spring training to now. He brings a
dimension to the club that they haven't had in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Furcal's fielding is as uneven as advertised. After a 34-error
season at Class A, he has seven misplays already, fourth most among
NL shortstops. His .948 fielding percentage does not compare
favorably with the .971 rate from Weiss, Ozzie Guillen and Jose
Hernandez last year.
</P>
<P>
   The concensus in the organization is that Furcal's fielding will
improve steadily. However, no evidence exists that Furcal can
maintain this offensive pace. He hit just .293 against the Class A
Carolina last summer. Scouts have noted that he has proved himself
against the major league fastball and will even drive, not punch,
the outside pitch to the opposite field. The next response should
come in curves and sliders, as well as increased traffic inside.
Furcal has yet to be hit by a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The Baseball Writers' Association of America has voted just
three Atlanta players as its rookies of the year Earl Williams in
1971, Bob Horner in 1978 and David Justice in 1990. The Sporting
News, on a ballot of managers and coaches, voted its rookie award
to Chipper Jones in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   None of them hit .300. None of them was 19. And surely, none of
them stirred the ghost of Mel Ott.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
