<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACCOUNTING-705&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOLCKER TO HEAD PANEL PUSHING FOR INTERNATIONAL ACCOUNTING RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The long-range goal of worldwide accounting standards _ making
it possible for companies to compile one set of books for investors
everywhere _ may be moving closer to reality with new efforts to
put together an international standards setter that will be
accepted in both the United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Paul A. Volcker, the former Federal Reserve chairman, was named
Monday to head a new body that will choose the people who will set
the international standards. The 14 people they select will replace
the current International Accounting Standards Committee, which has
been dominated by accounting professionals.
</P>
<P>
   The path to truly international accounting standards has been a
rocky one because standards vary widely among nations and because
the United States, with the most comprehensive standards and in
some ways the most restrictive, has been loath to accept
international standards.
</P>
<P>
   But that has begun to change as American regulators conclude
that their principal advantage in forcing large companies to comply
with American standards may lose its effectiveness in coming years.
That weapon is the requirement that any foreign company that wants
to list its stock on an American market, like the New York Stock
Exchange or Nasdaq, must reconcile its books to American accounting
rules.
</P>
<P>
   New technology has opened the possibility of international stock
markets that span national boundaries and make it easy for an
investor in the United States to buy shares in a foreign company
that has no American listing. ``I worry about what happens in an
electronic market, where the value of a listing is likely to be
diminished,'' Arthur Levitt, the chairman of the Securities and
Exchange Commission, said in an interview Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In a round of international negotiations last year and early
this year, Levitt held out the prospect of possible American
acceptance of international standards to prompt a change in the way
those standards are set. He became the chairman of a body that
chose Volcker and 16 other trustees of the new organization. The
trustees' job will be to pick the standard setters and then raise
money to keep the body in business.
</P>
<P>
   Volcker said he hoped the board would be appointed by the end of
this year.
</P>
<P>
   The 14 people are to be chosen based on technical expertise,
without quotas on where they are from. At least five of them are to
have experience as practicing auditors and at least three are to
have been preparers of financial statements in jobs like chief
financial officers. At least three others are to have experience as
users of such statements, like investment analysts, and one is to
have an academic background. Of the 14, seven are to be liaisons
with national accounting standards bodies, including the Financial
Accounting Standards Board in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   There is still no assurance that the SEC or any other country's
market regulator will accept international standards. But the
progress makes it more likely that the SEC will at least gradually
move toward international standards, possibly by certifying that
accounts that comply with a particular international standard will
not have to reconcile that part of the books with U.S. standards,
even though other parts must be so reconciled.
</P>
<P>
   The politics of accepting international standards in the United
States have shifted somewhat in recent years. A few years ago, much
of corporate America was pushing for it, in some cases because they
hoped international standards would be looser than American ones.
But some of that support has vanished because more recent
international standards have been more rigorous.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most emotional battles in accounting covers merger
accounting rules. The FASB, citing in part the fact that
international standards do not allow a form of merger accounting
known as pooling, has proposed ending that type of accounting. That
move, which would hurt reported profits of many companies that make
acquisitions, has touched off complaints to Congress and could lead
to legislation aimed at reversing the FASB decision.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In addition to Volcker, the other members of the trustees for
the International Accounting Standards Committee are: Roy Andersen,
chief executive of Liberty Life, a South African company; John H.
Biggs, the chairman of TIAA-CREF, an American money management
firm; Andrew Crockett, general manager of the Bank for
International Settlements; Roberto Teixeira Da Costa, former
chairman of the Comissao de Valores Mobiliarios of Brazil; Guido A.
Ferrarini, a law professor at the University of Genoa in Italy; L.
Yves Fortier, chairman of Ogilvy Renault, a Canadian law firm;
Toshikatsu Fukuma, chief financial officer of Mitsui &AMP; Co.;
Cornelius Herkstroter, former president of Royal Dutch Petroleum;
Hilmar Kopper, chairman of the supervisory board of Deutsche Bank;
Philip A. Laskawy, the chairman of Ernst &AMP; Young International;
Charles Yeh Kwong Lee, chairman of Hong Kong Exchange and Clearing
Ltd.; Sir Sydney Lipworth, the chairman of the U.K. Financial
Reporting Council; Didier Pineau-Valencienne, chairman of
Association Francaise des Enterprises Privees; Jens Roder, a senior
partner of PricewaterhouseCoopers; David S. Ruder, a former
chairman of the SEC; Kenneth H. Spencer, the chairman of the
Australian Accounting Standards Board; William C. Steere Jr.,
chairman and chief executive of Pfizer Inc.; and Koji Tajika,
co-chairman of Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu.
</P>
</TEXT>
