<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERALL, SOX PITCHING A SUCCESS SO FAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Give Ramon Martinez some regular work, some warmer weather, and
a healthy hamstring, and his days as the weak link in the Red Sox
rotation will be over, perhaps as soon as Friday night in Yankee
Stadium, when he begins a three-game set that will be bookended by
Martinez brothers, as Pedro goes Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox are a quarter of the way through the season, and despite
an early exit by Ramon the Elder in Sunday's 7-5 loss to Detroit _
he lasted just 2 1/3 innings after a 10-day layoff because of a
sore left leg _ the team's pitching has been the unqualified
success story of the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the Sox' offseason moves _ the trade for Carl Everett,
the signing of free agent lefty Jeff Fassero, the pickup of the
released Pete Schourek _ the best thing that happened to this team
may have been pitching coach Joe Kerrigan failing to persuade the
Cleveland Indians to hire him as their manager last November.
</P>
<P>
   Every season, general manager Dan Duquette places different
pitchers on Kerrigan's palette _ from Bret Saberhagen and Steve
Avery in '98 to Mark Portugal and Pat Rapp and Kent Mercker last
year to Schourek and Fassero this spring _ and every year Kerrigan
responds artfully. The bullpen has thrived, too, despite three
closers in three seasons: Tom Gordon in '98, Tim Wakefield last
season, and now Derek Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't about Pedro and four paupers, either, though it's a
comforting thought for the Sox that Pedro the Younger, who opens
the Toronto series Tuesday night, is 5-0 this season after a Boston
loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got depth,'' Kerrigan said. ``That's what got us through
last year, and we've got depth again this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we're going to go through probably 15-18 pitchers. It
never fails. I don't like to think about it, but that's the reality
of the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, 25 men threw at least one pitch for the Sox.
Thirteen made starts. Last season, the Sox opened with a rotation
of Pedro Martinez, Saberhagen, Rapp, Portugal, and Wakefield. This
season, it's Pedro and four other guys, and the results have been
splendid. There are two constants _ Martinez and Kerrigan _ that
have had as great an impact on the culture of this town as Keith
Lockhart, and without the baton.
</P>
<P>
   Let the rest of the baseball world play 17-16 games. Here, it's
Pitching First. And when has that ever been the case?
</P>
<P>
   In their first 40 games, the Sox have held the opposition to
three runs or fewer 23 times. That's more than any other team in
baseball, including the Maddux-Glavine-Millwood Braves (20) and the
Big Unit D-Backs (17). The Sox are 19-4 in those games, which
include two 1-0 losses and Saturday's 2-1 setback to the last-place
Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   Three Sox pitchers _ Pedro Martinez, Schourek, and Fassero _
rank among the AL top seven in earned run average. The Sox have
walked fewer batters than any other team in baseball, have allowed
fewer home runs, and are second in the American League in
strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids have done a heck of a job,'' manager Jimy Williams
said. ``They really have. They should feel pretty darn good about
themselves _ their deliveries, their execution, making pitches,
getting out in front of hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassero, after stepping into Kerrigan's garage and retooling his
mechanics, already has as many wins (5) as he had all of last
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``With each start, his old habits fade more and more,'' Kerrigan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Schourek hasn't had similar results, with just two wins in his
eight starts, but his .240 batting average against is second to
Pedro's .157 among Sox starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a power-oriented guy _ power fastball, power curve _
and he's made the transition to a ground ball-efficient pitcher,''
Kerrigan said. ``He's getting hitters early in the count on his
sinker, and his changeup now is almost as good as his curveball.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to give the credit to him, because he had to make
that transition in his own mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Rose, whose next start will come on national TV Saturday
against the Yankees, weathered some early jolts and has pitched
well, both as a spot starter and out of the pen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's adapted very well to the traditional fifth-man role,''
Kerrigan said.
</P>
<P>
   While the Sox starters rank first in the league, the bullpen is
a close second to the Yankees. Kerrigan said the unsung hero of the
month is Wakefield. By starting the first game of a recent trip in
Baltimore, after throwing in relief the night before, Wakefield
kept the Sox from having to place Ramon Martinez on the DL and
spared the bullpen from being overtaxed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anybody in the big leagues who could have done
that,'' said Kerrigan. Those are words that Wakefield should take
to Duquette when he pushes for the Duke to pick up his contract
extension.
</P>
<P>
   Rod Beck and Bryce Florie are getting closer to arriving as
reinforcements. Hipolito Pichardo, the former Royal, is also being
groomed for a relief role as he makes his way back from elbow and
shoulder injuries. Saberhagen insists he has enough comeback left
in him.
</P>
<P>
   From time to time, Kerrigan hauls out a mannequin to serve as a
batter during tutorials. He used one with a young Pedro Martinez in
Montreal, when he helped him perfect the art of pitching inside. He
calls his dummy the Pitcher's Pal.
</P>
<P>
   But on the Sox, there's no question who ranks as a pitcher's
best friend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
