<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-PEDRO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN ON THE FIELD, ALL EYES ON PEDRO MARTINEZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   His initial stretching and maybe a rubdown and light bike work
out of the way, Pedro Martinez will take to the Fenway Park field
at 6:35 p.m. sharp Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He'll do a little more stretching and a little light jogging,
moving forward and backward. He'll play long toss deep on the
outfield grass for 5-7 minutes, starting close to the catcher and
then backing up until he is throwing the ball 200 to 250 feet, and
then moving back in again. Then it's into the bullpen for 48-54
warmup pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Introductions will be made over the PA system. The national
anthem will be performed. Martinez will take the mound against
Chris Carpenter and go after his eighth win of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But the 30,000-plus cramming the park, plus the hundreds of
thousands tuning in on NESN, won't be the only ones anticipating
Martinez Magic.
</P>
<P>
   It happens on the field and in the clubhouse, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Pedro takes the mound, there's always that chance that
that's the day,'' said catcher Jason Varitek. ``He's that good of a
pitcher. That could be the day that he does something perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   The guys on the field behind the Red Sox ace talk of wanting to
make the plays for every pitcher. They talk of knowing the hitters
and playing a couple of steps this way or a couple of steps that
way, depending on what the hitter does against a power pitcher, not
just what he does against Pedro. They talk of preparing just as
thoroughly, whether it's Pete Schourek on the mound or Pedro
Martinez. They talk of playing just as hard whether it's Ramon or
his little brother.
</P>
<P>
   Some talk of a Pedro game as another day at the office.
Certainly, they want to make all the plays and play as hard for one
pitcher as they do for another. But business as usual?
</P>
<P>
   Don't believe it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to miss anything, cause he's as exciting as you
can get,'' said first baseman Mike Stanley. ``He's the best in the
game of baseball right now and maybe in a long time. Any time could
be a special time. He's had 17 strikeouts before and he's certainly
capable of doing 20.''
</P>
<P>
   They watch. They learn. They anticipate.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan Ryan had a similar effect on the Texas Rangers when
Stanley was with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was another guy, too, where if you were on the bench, you
weren't up in the clubhouse messing around because any given night
could have been a special night,'' Stanley said. ``You're not
sitting there doing idle things like you would be on the bench if
someone else were pitching, because of the whole atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley saw several of Ryan's special moments. He caught a
no-hitter. He was on the bench for another. He saw Ryan take a few
more into the late innings.
</P>
<P>
   The excitement in the park spreads across the field. And it can
work a couple of ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get excited and see him striking out 15 and just not
really be in the game and be more of a fan,'' said third baseman
John Valentin. ``That can happen. And it's not good.''
</P>
<P>
   It can get tough when Martinez is mowing down hitters and the
fielders don't have to field much, said Valentin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played behind Roger (Clemens) and I played behind Pedro and
it's very similar,'' Valentin said. ``When Roger was here, he was
very dominant, and as a defensive player, when not too many balls
are hit to you, it's not a real good thing. When a ball is hit to
you, you can get caught on your heels a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Varitek is one player who doesn't have that problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm probably the exact opposite,'' said the catcher. ``His
ball is pretty explosive. His ball can take off on you in a
heartbeat and he's got a lot of movement on a lot of his pitches.
My level is probably raised even more when he's on the mound.''
</P>
<P>
   It's important to be ready from the start, said shortstop Donnie
Sadler.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know he's going to get around the plate and you know the
hitters are up there hacking because they don't want to fall behind
in the count because he has four dominant pitches,'' Sadler said.
``You have to be on your toes at all times.''
</P>
<P>
   Every time Pedro walks out of the dugout, the crowd stirs, said
Stanley, ``and each time a guy gets two strikes, they start waving
the K cards.''
</P>
<P>
   The intensity level rises.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not distracting. It elevates your awareness a little
bit,'' Stanley said. ``It elevates your excitement level to make a
great play if he needs it because you hate to waste any of his
starts. You want to go out there and get the big hit if you can, to
make the defensive play if the ball comes to you, to make sure you
keep him going.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez has been going, and going, and going.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers are mind-numbing. The one earned run in his last
four starts and 0.90 earned run average overall. The 7-1 record.
The 88 strikeouts and only 11 walks. The opponents' batting average
of .157.
</P>
<P>
   Teammates aren't the only ones who marvel at Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro is in the heart of his career,'' Stanley said. ``I
didn't see Nolan when he was younger. But I've talked to guys who
have been in the league, like a Harold Baines. I talked to him the
other day at first base and he's been in the league 20 years, maybe
21, and he hasn't seen anybody better.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's not just players.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox pitching coach Joe Kerrigan tries to enjoy it all as a
coach. As a fan. As a student.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he does for me and for the rest of the staff is he really
exposes holes of the hitters,'' Kerrigan said. ``Maybe it's some
way of getting a hitter out you haven't thought of, or you haven't
seen in the past. Whether it be something that the hitter chases in
the dirt or something he swings at high out of the strike zone, he
just exposes the hitters' weaknesses.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a skill, the coach said, that Martinez keeps improving. He
studies batters against other Red Sox pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a combination of physical skills and the intellect he
has,'' Kerrigan said. ``I think that's something he has learned and
gotten smarter with every year. He really pays attention to
previous swings and previous at-bats and what he does with a guy.
He'll get a certain hitter out one way _ he might throw him four
straight curveballs and then the next at-bat he might not see a
curveball.''
</P>
<P>
   Such an approach differs from that of Atlanta's Greg Maddux,
another Kerrigan favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maddux will get you out a certain way all the time until he
sees that you can make an adjustment to that, and then Maddux will
make an adjustment,'' Kerrigan said. ``If you can't hit a
particular spot or particular pitch or particular speed he's going
to go to that until you prove otherwise. Pedro doesn't like a
hitter to get a read off him.''
</P>
<P>
   Different folks. Different strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Same results.
</P>
<P>
   And fun to watch. From the living room. The stands. The dugout.
The field.
</P>
<P>
   ``You sit there and you're in awe watching this guy,'' Kerrigan
said. ``If you're not a fan while you're watching him pitch, even
though you're supposed to be the pitching coach, you're not
enjoying the whole baseball experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 2002EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
