u i BC-ISRAEL-WOMEN-ART-NYT &LR;      05-22 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-WOMEN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI HIGH COURT ALLOWS WOMEN TO CONDUCT SERVICES AT WESTERN
WALL
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT 7 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The Israeli Supreme Court changed the rules of
worship at Judaism's most revered shrine when it ruled Monday that
women can have group services at the Western Wall, can wear prayer
shawls and read aloud from Torah scrolls.
</P>
<P>
   A legal ban on women's services at the shrine, in keeping with
strict Orthodox Jewish tradition, was challenged in court by Women
of the Wall, a group that demanded the right to have services in
the same way men worship at the site.
</P>
<P>
   Under the rules in force at the Western Wall, which follow
Orthodox custom, men and women worship in separate areas divided by
a partition, and only the men have services while the women worship
individually. Monday the court gave the government six months to
arrange for group services for women at the shrine, complete with
prayer shawls and chanting from the Torah.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've come out of the Middle Ages,'' said Anat Hoffman, a
leader of the women's group. ``Today the Western Wall became part
of the state of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling was roundly condemned by Orthodox officials and
rabbis, who called the decision a divisive assault on Jewish law
and practice at Judaism's most sacred shrine. It was the latest in
a series of Supreme Court rulings on matters of religion and state
that have been criticized by Orthodox leaders as anti-religious.
</P>
<P>
   The deputy religious affairs minister, Yigal Bibi, a member of
the National Religious Party, said the Supreme Court had issued yet
another ruling that would ``nullify the state of Israel as a Jewish
state and turn it into a state of all its citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   The case, thrashed out over 11 years in the courts and in three
government committees, raised the question whether the Western Wall
is a religious site where worship must follow strict Orthodox
practice, or a national place of pilgrimage where Jews of all
persuasions can have services in different ways.
</P>
<P>
   The shrine of massive stones, venerated by Jews for centuries,
is a remnant of a wall that surrounded a plateau where the ancient
Jewish temple stood before it was destroyed by the Romans in A.D.
70.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts by Women of the Wall to have prayer services there, and
by Conservative and Reform Jews to have mixed services of men and
women, have drawn verbal abuse and sometimes violence by strictly
Orthodox Jews who consider such gatherings an affront to their
religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Women of the Wall, made up of more than 100 liberal Orthodox,
Conservative and Reform women backed by a few hundred women abroad,
did not challenge the segregation of men and women but sought to
have traditional services in the women's prayer area, wearing
prayer shawls and reading aloud from the Torah.
</P>
<P>
   Such group worship was outlawed by a regulation governing Jewish
holy places that barred ``holding a religious ceremony that is not
according to local custom.'' That was interpreted by the Chief
Rabbinate and the Religious Affairs Ministry, which oversee prayer
arrangements at the Western Wall, as Orthodox custom. Violating the
regulation carried a penalty of up to six months in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Government committees that examined the case ruled against
changing standing practice on the ground that it might provoke
violence, and suggested alternative sites for women to have
services adjacent to the Western Wall.
</P>
<P>
   But in Monday's ruling, a three-judge panel rejected such
alternatives, asserting that they failed to uphold the women's
right to prayer at the shrine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The petitioners have the right to pray according to their
custom in the Western Wall plaza as well,'' Judge Eliahu Matza
wrote in his opinion, endorsed by the two other judges. ``It is
unacceptable that concern about a violent reaction by any sector of
the public will lead to denial of the exercise by another sector of
its right.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman, who is a Jerusalem city council member from the leftist
Meretz Party, said the ruling ``is moving the Western Wall out of
the complete monopoly of the ultra-Orthodox,'' and will make it
possible for the first time to have bat mitzvah services there for
girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The voices of women, who are half of the Jewish people, were
silenced in the holiest place to Jews,'' she said. ``This was a
stain on the state of Israel and Jerusalem. Monday that stain has
been removed.''
</P>
<P>
   But Moshe Gafni, a legislator form the strictly Orthodox United
Torah Judaism Party, called the court decision a ``shocking blow to
observant and traditional Jews around the world, and a stab in
their back.''
</P>
<P>
   He warned that the ruling would ``turn the holiest place to the
Jewish people into a place where none of us will be able to pray,
because it will be the site of the worst kind of sacrilege, against
all the rules of Jewish law and the entire Jewish tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   The religious affairs minister, Yitzhak Cohen, from the strictly
Orthodox Shas Party, said he would submit a bill to Parliament that
would counter Monday's ruling by specifying what forms of worship
are permitted at the Western Wall.
</P>
<P>
   A religious moderate, Rabbi Michael Melchior, the minister of
diaspora affairs, also criticized the ruling, warning that it could
lead to ``terrible and violent dispute'' if it was carried out. He
urged a compromise. ``We can't resolve the central problems of our
society by one side bending the other,'' he said, ``only through
dialogue and agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   The Conservative movement in Israel, which reached its own
compromise with the government on mixed prayers by men and women at
a site adjacent to the Western Wall, welcomed Monday's ruling as
``a great day in the struggle for religious pluralism in Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   But it caused hardly a ripple Monday morning at the Western
Wall, where hundreds of worshipers paid no attention to Hoffman and
four other women who arrived from the Supreme Court to celebrate
their victory.
</P>
<P>
   As they draped arms around each other and read a psalm of
thanksgiving from a prayer book, Rivka David, an Orthodox school
principal from Tel Aviv, looked at them as if they were from
another planet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prayer is a personal thing,'' she said. ``This is a show.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 2005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
