u i BC-CHINA-TRADE-BOS &LR;      05-22 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE DEFINE HUMAN RIGHTS IN THEIR OWN WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI _ Like many Chinese, Y.M. Zhou thinks the United States
has a warped and hypocritical view of human rights in his country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We already have human rights,'' declared Zhou, 33, an employee
of a foreign bank in Shanghai. ``The US doesn't have the right to
criticize us. The US has problems of its own _ killings in the
schools and that poor Cuban boy,'' he added, referring to the raid
that returned Elian Gonzalez to his father, an incident that was
portrayed in China as armed government agents bursting into an
innocent family's home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The US uses one standard to judge countries in other stages of
development. But we are like the US 100 years ago,'' Zhou asserted.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights and labor conditions in China have been at the
center of a rancorous Washington debate that culminates Wednesday
with the US congressional vote over granting China permanent normal
trade status. American labor unions and some victims of persecution
in China have banded together against the legislation, arguing that
the United States should retain the little leverage it has annually
to influence Beijing over its suppression of political and
religious dissent.
</P>
<P>
   Zhou's views reflect a much different concept of human rights
than that of most Americans. The Chinese government says human
rights mean access to food, shelter, medical care, education, and
equal opportunity. And for nearly 50 years, few people in China
have questioned that definition. Yet here in Shanghai, China's most
Westernized city and its wealthy, commercial capital, there is a
small, but growing number of middle-class people with access to the
Internet and foreign travel who are beginning to think of human
rights in a different way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our government is mixing the concept, changing the definition
of human rights and trying to confuse people,'' complained Huang, a
42-year-old former government worker who declined to give his first
name for fear of reprisals. ``There's an international standard of
human rights and it's not eating! Food is just a basic need, and if
a government can't provide people with food, it has no right to
exist.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if Chinese have human rights, Chen Jie, a 24-year-old
pianist, was blunt. ``Not at all! Prisoners are treated like pigs .
. . and even I feel I don't have any human rights. Every leader
should be elected. But as long as we have only the Communist Party,
it will never be done. We need other parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the Chinese government has issued a steady
diet of media reports on the perceived unfairness of US criticisms
of China, and dark threats about how relations and commerce with
the United States would suffer if Congress does not pass the trade
deal. China recently released a report denouncing human rights in
the United States, and a separate booklet hailing advances in human
rights in China under communist rule.
</P>
<P>
   To most Americans, human rights include freedom of speech,
religion, press and assembly, the right to a fair trial, and the
right to form political parties and contest free elections.
</P>
<P>
   But one look at ``Fifty Years of Progress in China's Human
Rights,'' a recent Chinese government report, underscores that the
leadership here defines human rights as a ``people's democratic
political system,'' land reform, the education of women, the
probihition of prostitution, drugs and gambling, the elimination of
ethnic discrimination, and economic advancement.
</P>
<P>
   There is no denying that living conditions, literacy, and the
wealth and gender gap have vastly improved since 1949, when the
Communist Party took charge. But the report makes no mention of the
times when government policies went awry. China suffered the worst
famine in history in the late 1950s, which claimed an estimated 30
million lives. Many Chinese suffered or extreme political and
cultural persecution during the 1966-76 Cultural Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the report praises the goverment for feeding 22 percent
of the world's population on 7 percent of its arable land, raising
incomes dramatically, providing health care, and coping with
natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
   The report notes that the Chinese constitution ensures freedom
of speech, assembly, press, and religion. But it fails to mention
that all those rights are overriden by Article 51, which says
freedoms ``may not infringe upon the interests of the state, of
society or of the collective.'' That clause has justified the
imprisonment of countless political and religious dissidents.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, another recent official report, ``US Human Rights
Record in 1999,'' paints ``A Clockwork Orange''-like vision of an
ultraviolent America filled with trigger-happy police and
out-of-control gangs. The 10-page Chinese report condemns the
United States for having the world's highest rate of deaths by gun
violence, the world's highest per capita prison population, prison
labor, police brutality, judicial corruption, racial
discrimination, gaping income inequities, long working hours,
domestic violence, and poverty.
</P>
<P>
   The examples of US defects are attributed to US media, including
The Boston Globe, whose Web sites are often blocked here to prevent
Chinese from reading them. And even as it quotes American press
articles that criticize US authorities, the report condemns the US
media as ``a propaganda machine used by authorities to manipulate
public opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   The report concludes that ``the US government needs to keep an
eye on its own human rights problems, mind its own business and
stop interfering in the internal affairs of other countries.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no mention in the reports or in the Chinese press of
the frequent arrests of political dissidents and members of banned
religious sects, such as Falun Gong, or of the long prison terms
meted out in closed hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The US is not perfect. I also question their purpose for
criticizing us; it's not about human rights, but political gain,''
said Lu Qing, 26, who works for an export company. Even so, she
acknowledged ``we do not have enough human rights here. . . . Our
biggest problem is low salaries. If people don't have enough money,
they don't have enough energy to change society.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen Linxin, 28, said the first step to improving human rights
would be a free media ``so we can hear different voices and judge
for ourselves what we want. The government controls everything, so
even when people are oppressed, the public doesn't know about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet like other critic of China's human rights record, Chen urged
Washington to normalize trade relations, not only for commercial
reasons, but also to speed China's political liberalization.
</P>
<P>
   Normal trade ``will make China more open, more free, and . . .
it will help our human rights situation by improving living
standards and helping us develop a middle class,'' he reasoned.
``Because if we have enough middle-class people, that more than
anything will help force democratization.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
