<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-BLAIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUALITY TIME (AND DIAPERS) AT 10 DOWNING 
</HEADLINE>
   By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Prime Minister Tony Blair, nudged in public by his
wife, Cherie, to take some of the paternity leave his government
has just authorized for British parents, is canceling his public
appearances this week to spend time with her and Leo, their baby
son.
</P>
<P>
   A 10 Downing Street spokesman said the only appointment Blair
would keep was his weekly session with Queen Elizabeth II on
Tuesday. He will leave the handling of prime minister's questions
in the House of Commons on Wednesday and the chairing of the
Thursday cabinet meeting to his deputy, John Prescott. Mother,
father and newborn son will leave London at midweek for Chequers,
the official country retreat in Buckinghamshire where they will be
joined for the weekend by the couple's three other children, Euan,
16, Nicky, 14 and Kathryn, 12.
</P>
<P>
   Downing Street, which has kept a tight lid on publicity
surrounding the birth at the Blairs' insistence, released the first
picture of the couple and Leo, who was born early Saturday morning.
Fourteen more photographs were offered for sale through a London
agency with proceeds to go to charities supporting children's and
breast cancers. The photos were taken by Mary McCartney, 30, the
daughter of the former Beatle, Paul McCartney. Her mother, Linda,
who was well known for her photography, died of breast cancer in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Mrs. Blair, 45, a noted employment rights lawyer, had
praised the Finnish prime minister, Paavo Lipponen, 59, for taking
a week off that month to be with his newborn daughter, and she had
pointedly urged the ``widespread adoption of his fine example.''
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister, 47, said he could not abandon his job, but
he promised to devote as much time as he could to the baby and
specifically to take up night diaper duty. Noting that pledge, his
press spokesman, Alastair Campbell, said the decision did not
reflect a big shift in attitude. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
