<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2732 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-CABLE-TV-2TAKE     05-22 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-CABLE-TV-2TAKES(875)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT STRIKES DOWN LIMITS ON EXPLICIT CABLE TV SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Del.)   By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Declaring for the first time that programming on
cable television is entitled to the highest level of First
Amendment protection, the Supreme Court on Monday struck down a
federal law that required many cable systems to limit sexually
explicit channels to late-night hours.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was 5-4, with an unusual lineup of justices. Both sides
agreed that shielding children from sexually explicit material, the
purpose of the law, was a legitimate goal, but differed on the
extent of the problem the 1996 law was passed to address and on the
degree of constitutional ``flexibility'' the court should give the
government in its effort to protect children.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy wrote the majority opinion, joined by
Justices John Paul Stevens, David H. Souter, Clarence Thomas and
Ruth Bader Ginsburg. Kennedy's opinion discussed the ``basic speech
principles'' that he said were at stake in the case, a challenge
brought by Playboy Magazine's cable operations, which include
Spice, AdulTVision, Adam &AMP; Eve and the Playboy channel. All came
within the law's definition of being ``primarily dedicated to
sexually-oriented programming.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The history of the law of free expression is one of
vindication in cases involving speech that many citizens may find
shabby, offensive or even ugly,'' Kennedy said. He added: ``The
citizen is entitled to seek out or reject certain ideas or
influences without government interference or control.''
</P>
<P>
   The dissenters were Justices Stephen G. Breyer and Antonin
Scalia, both of whom wrote dissenting opinions, and Chief Justice
William H. Rehnquist and Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, both of whom
signed Breyer's dissent. ``Our prior cases recognize that where the
protection of children is at issue, the First Amendment poses a
barrier that properly is high, but not insurmountable,'' Breyer
said.
</P>
<P>
   At issue in the case, U.S. vs. Playboy Entertainment Group, No.
98-1682, was the validity of Section 505 of the Telecommunications
Act of 1996. Adopted as a floor amendment with little debate, the
section was intended to address the problem of ``signal bleed,''
caused by a cable system's failure to scramble a signal well enough
to avoid a fuzzy image or some sound from coming through to those
subscribers who have not paid for a particular channel and do not
want it.
</P>
<P>
   Section 505 required that for a channel ``primarily dedicated to
sexually-oriented programming,'' a cable system that lacked the
technology to block the signal completely had to limit the channel
to hours when children were unlikely to be watching. A Federal
Communications Commission regulation set the time as between 10
p.m. and 6 a.m., and many cable systems chose that ``safe harbor''
option rather than investing in the technology needed for complete
blocking.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the law contained another approach in a
separate section, Section 504, under which cable operators had to
provide an effective blocking device for any subscriber who wanted
one.
</P>
<P>
   A special three-judge federal District Court in Wilmington,
Del., ruling in 1998 in Playboy's challenge to the law, held that
Section 504 could protect customers just as well without being as
intrusive as the systemwide time segregation required by Section
505.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, the district court said, Section 505 was not the
``least restrictive means'' to achieve the government's goal, and
was unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   In his opinion affirming that decision, Kennedy made several
points that could significantly limit the government's ability to
regulate content in new communications technologies.
</P>
<P>
   In applying ``strict scrutiny,'' the highest level of First
Amendment protection, to cable programming, Kennedy identified what
he called a ``key difference'' between cable and broadcast
television and radio, for which the court has applied a lower level
of scrutiny and permitted more regulatory leeway.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the broadcast media, cable systems have the capacity for
``target blocking,'' he said, adding: ``Technology expands the
capacity to choose; and it denies the potential of this revolution
if we assume the government is best positioned to make these
choices for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Corn-Revere, a lawyer who represented Playboy, said in an
interview Monday that this analysis would also apply to the
Internet and could prove important in turning back efforts to
regulate speech in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of judges Monday also rejected the Clinton
administration's defense of Section 505 as necessary because
parents could not be counted on to request individual blocking
devices from their cable company. That was an unwarranted
assumption, Kennedy said, adding: ``Even upon the assumption that
the government has an interest in substituting itself for informed
and empowered parents, its interest is not sufficiently compelling
to justify this widespread restriction on speech.''
</P>
<P>
   In his dissenting opinion, Breyer said that by not depending on
individual parental action, Section 505 ``offers independent
protection for a large number of families.'' He said the government
had an ``independent interest in offering such protection''
regardless of choices made by individual parents about monitoring
what their children watch.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL TAKE FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There were also these other developments Monday on a busy day at
the court.
</P>
<P>
   Air Bag Suits
</P>
<P>
   Dividing 5-4, the court ruled that manufacturers of cars made
before federal law required air bags cannot be sued under state
negligence laws for failing to have the passive safety devices.
</P>
<P>
   The case, Geier vs. American Honda Motor Co., No. 98-1811, was
the latest in a particularly contentious and unpredictable area of
the court's docket, federal pre-emption of various state court
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Breyer wrote the majority decision, which upheld a ruling last
year by the federal appeals court here that a suit against Honda
for failing to include an air bag in a 1987 Accord was pre-empted
by the federal regulation in effect at that time that permitted a
gradual phase-in of passive restraints.
</P>
<P>
   For 1987 models, manufacturers were required under a 1984
regulation to equip only 10 percent of their models with either air
bags or automatic seat belts. All cars manufactured after Sept. 1,
1989, had to have passive restraints, and all cars beginning with
the 1998 model year were specifically required to have air bags for
both the driver and front-seat passenger.
</P>
<P>
   Breyer said the Department of Transportation had deliberately
chosen a gradual approach, to promote public acceptance and give
manufacturers time to develop better systems. Permitting state
negligence suits created an unacceptable conflict with the state
regulatory approach, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the dissenting opinion, Stevens charged the majority with an
``unprecedent extension of the doctrine of pre-emeption that failed
to treat state court systems with proper respect.
</P>
<P>
   While the regulation at issue is no longer in effect, there are
millions of cars still on the road from the period in question.
</P>
<P>
   The majority opinion was joined by Rehnquist, O'Connor, Scalia
and Kennedy. Souter, Thomas and Ginsburg joined the dissent.
</P>
<P>
   Employment Disputes
</P>
<P>
   Stepping into an issue of growing importance in labor-management
relations, the court agreed to decide whether employers can enforce
binding arbitration agreements that employees are increasingly
required to sign as a condition of being hired.
</P>
<P>
   The question in Circuit City Stores vs. Adams, No. 99-1379, is
whether the federal Arbitration Act, a 1925 law that excludes
certain employment contracts from its coverage, applies to ordinary
labor agreements of this type. The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals, in San Francisco, held in this case that arbitration as
part of an ordinary employment contract could not be enforced. All
other federal courts to address the issue have found such
agreements enforceable. Nearly 10 percent of the American work
force is covered by mandatory arbitration agreements, according to
a brief from the National Academy of Arbitrators.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
