<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2735 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-AUTHORS-BAXTER-SPI &LR;      05-22 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHORS-BAXTER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAKOUT NOVEL LIKELY TO TAKE CHARLES BAXTER BEYOND `WRITER'S
WRITER'  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MARSHALL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are certainly worse things to be called, even for a
writer. But being tabbed ``a writer's writer'' has slowly and
steadily been woven into a hair shirt for Charles Baxter.
</P>
<P>
   There were times when it seemed a worthy accolade, this notion
that his fine work, both novels and short stories, had won great
admiration from his fellow writers. But there were times lately
when being ``a writer's writer'' seemed much less of an accolade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It starts as a compliment,'' Baxter said in an interview,
``but it soon becomes a kind of backhanded compliment. For being `a
writer's writer' is also a way of saying your work is out of touch
with readers. So I have very mixed feelings about that
description.''
</P>
<P>
   Baxter's days as ``a writer's writer'' seem to be coming to an
abrupt end. Popularity, even best-selling popularity, may be next
for the 53-year-old writer because of his exceptional new novel,
``The Feast of Love'' (Pantheon, 308 pages, $24).
</P>
<P>
   This is an inspired look at love in its many permutations, a
jazz-riff version of ``A Midsummer Night's Dream'' transported to
Ann Arbor, Mich., and the new millennium. ``The Feast of Love''
manages to be heartfelt and erotic, hilarious and poignant,
scathing and bittersweet. And it is as irresistible as a
Valentine's Day box of truffles.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, a Baxter novel is getting reviews filled with
superlatives. Suddenly, a Baxter novel is the lead recommendation
of Amazon.com. Suddenly, a Baxter novel is receiving a push from
independent booksellers. And suddenly Baxter, a soft-spoken and wry
academic from the University of Michigan, is on an extensive
cross-country book tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all very heartening to a writer,'' Baxter said. ``But
I have also tried to cultivate a steely Zen detachment about it. Of
course, I hope people like the novel and recommend it to their
friends. But there are limits to how much I can intervene on the
book's behalf at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A writer's writer'' has been replaced by a new phrase attached
to Baxter _ ``author of a break-out book.'' This is the phenomenon
when a literary writer bursts into the spotlight with a novel that
greatly expands his readership.
</P>
<P>
   Cormac McCarthy had this happen to him when his terse
masterpiece, ``All the Pretty Horses,'' ended his many years of
writing obscurity. The most recent phenomenon was Kent Haruf, with
his understated Colorado elegy, ``Plainsong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Feast of Love'' bears more than passing similarity to
``Plainsong.'' Both novels celebrate the daily lives and dreams of
``ordinary'' people, their stories spun forth in their plainspoken
voices in alternating chapters. Both novels build toward a
conclusion where menace and tragedy must be confronted in hopes of
approaching redemption.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Feast of Love,'' however, is firmly grounded upon the most
universal of human longings.
</P>
<P>
   As the character Chloe muses, ``When people are staring off into
their neighborhood infinity ... what are they thinking about?
That's what I'm trying to grasp. I think they're stupefied,
thinking about love, mostly, how they once had it, how they got it,
how they lost it, and all the people they loved or didn't love, how
they ended up royally hating somebody, like, the weirdness and
wetness of it. Bradley says they're thinking about money, but I
know they're not. Love comes first.''
</P>
<P>
   Chloe and Bradley play signal roles in Baxter's ode to love.
These two, as different as pierced tongues and baggy chinos,
demonstrate Baxter's wondrous dexterity as a writer, his ability to
concoct fully realized characters and authentic voices. These
people leap off the page and into the memory.
</P>
<P>
   Chloe is a punk Madonna, impulsive, trusting, tart, wise beyond
her education and years. She works as a waitress in a coffee
emporium at the mall, is in love with a reformed drug addict named
Oscar, dabbles briefly in porn to make ends meet, consults a
psychic and firmly believes: ``You can't always get what you want
but sometimes you get what you need _ truer words than that have
been spoken, but not much truer, and for sure not in my lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is a lumpy toad of a fellow, trustworthy, solid,
forlorn, often encountered walking his dog (also named Bradley). He
is the owner of the coffee emporium at the mall, but also a visual
artist of some talent, if muddled vision, an unfortunate at love,
having lost his first wife to another woman, his second wife to
another man. But Bradley still keeps questing for companionship
because he firmly believes ``In truth, there are only two
realities: the one for people who are in love or love each other,
and the one for people who are standing outside all that.''
</P>
<P>
   Chloe and Bradley are joined in the novel by an aging
philosopher/professor and his wife; a tough-nut, me-first female
attorney and her fierce married lover. All are somehow persuaded to
share their tales of love and loss with a plot-stuck, insomniac
novelist named Charles Baxter.
</P>
<P>
   This opening gambit in the novel seems fraught with danger
because of its self-consciousness. In fact, one of Baxter's writing
compatriots warned against using himself as a minor character,
arguing that it was ``like pushing a wheelbarrow across a tightrope
above Niagara Falls.'' Baxter was undeterred.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to ground the story in somebody who seems to exist,''
he said, ``somebody who writes novels in Ann Arbor, before all
these characters take off in their speculations, their anecdotes,
their fantasies.''
</P>
<P>
   The marvelous collage of characters sprung from Baxter's
imagination without any real research. The younger ones were
probably shaped by his writing students and his 21-year-old son,
the middle-age ones by his wife of 25 years and their friends. What
amazed him was how freely the voices all flowed forth.
</P>
<P>
   After six books of fiction, including two novels, Baxter spent
four years writing ``The Feast of Love,'' with some real rewards.
But what happens in the marketplace still remains uncertain so soon
after publication. If his ninth book, with all its building buzz,
does not crest on the best-seller list, then so be it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as if Stalin just said that this was not
literature,'' Baxter emphasized, ``and it's not as if my life is in
danger. In America, we worry too much about being a hit or making
the big score. That is not to say I wouldn't be delighted if a lot
of readers enjoyed my book. But I'm not about to let it drive me
crazy either.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
