<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2741 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-HARVARD-PRESIDENT-ART     05-22 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-PRESIDENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUDENSTINE, RECORD FUND-RAISER, RESIGNS AS PRESIDENT OF HARVARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT8 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Neil L. Rudenstine, a scholar of Renaissance poetry who recently
led the largest fund-raising campaign in the history of higher
education, announced Monday that he will step down next spring
after a decade as president of Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   After startling his colleagues in 1994 with a three-month leave
of absence because of exhaustion, Rudenstine won wide praise on the
Cambridge, Mass., campus for uniting its historically disparate
deans and has been a fervent supporter of affirmative action.
Undergraduates, however, often found him remote, and some in higher
education believe he failed to fully exploit the platform afforded
the steward of the nation's oldest and most prestigious university.
</P>
<P>
   Rudenstine, 65, said he is unsure of his plans, but sees this as
an apt moment to retire, as the institution of 18,000 students and
2,000 professors embarks on a new era of strategic planning and,
inevitably, another capital campaign.
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, Rudenstine believes the information technology
revolution and globalization of the economy herald a tectonic shift
in the academy, akin to the switch from small colleges to large
research universities at the turn of the century, and the vastly
expanded access to higher education after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``The totality of the institution will be a different
configuration,'' he said Saturday in an interview in the library of
the president's mansion, about a mile off Harvard Square. ``That
ought to be a challenge for some people.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudenstine is a rare combination of prodigious fund-raiser and
scholar. From the poetry and music performed at his 1991
inauguration to his personal oversight of more than 250 tenure
appointments, his intellectual acuity was always on display. Yet
his legacy is most clearly etched in Harvard's bank accounts,
having raised $2.6 billion _ more than $1 million a day _ over six
years from some 175,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Many believe it was his earnest commitment to Harvard's academic
future that pushed so many donors' hands deeper into their pockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the strongest factors in philanthropy in general is
that people give to people, as well as institutions,'' said William
H. Boardman, a top Harvard administrator who traveled with
Rudenstine as he met one-on-one with more than 500 potential
donors. Typical, Boardman said, was the reaction of the late John
Loeb, who said after meeting the president in the early 1990s, ``I
spent a half hour with Neil Rudenstine and I felt like I've known
him all my life.'' ( Loeb gave $72 million in the campaign.)
</P>
<P>
   On campus, Rudenstine installed the first provost, or
university-wide academic officer, in Harvard's modern history,
attempting to overcome the traditional autonomy of its 12 schools.
Through monthly meetings of a council of deans, he encouraged
unified approaches to institutional issues and cross-fertilization
among the faculty on topics like the environment, the brain, Latin
America and East Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harvard has this tradition of every tub on its own bottom,''
said Joseph Nye, dean of the Kennedy School of Government. ``In the
past, that has meant that the sum of the university is not greater
than its parts. What Neil has been good at is getting the parts to
work together so the sum total is greater.''
</P>
<P>
   Renowned for prolific handwritten notes, Rudenstine has a
humble, often rumpled persona, and often ran late for appointments
(his leave, in 1994, began when he slept through a series of
appointments in New York). While he counts among his most memorable
moments encounters with students, undergraduates said they rarely
saw him between a welcome handshake during freshman year and
commencement.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could go through the rest of your time here and never see
him in the yard,'' said Fentrice Driskell, a junior who is
president of the undergraduate council. Alan Wirzbicki, president
of The Crimson, the school newspaper, said Rudenstine ``was clearly
a brilliant fund-raiser, but to most students, that's all he was,
Harvard's fund-raiser.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, Rudenstine has been a quiet leader among his peers,
though he has spoken boldly about the importance of affirmative
action, first through a 62-page report in defense of diversity,
and, in 1997, gathering a coalition of university presidents to
sign an advertisement in major newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Harvard doubled the number of women on its faculty,
from 85 to 183, and assembled a dream team of scholars in its
Afro-American Studies Department.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Louis Gates Jr., the department chairman, recalled when
Rudenstine was first appointed and, over lunch, urged him to write
a list of his ``ideal department _ even if they're impossible to
recruit.'' Gates jotted William Julius Wilson, Cornel West, Lani
Gunier, Jamaica Kincaid, Anthony Appiah. ``He looked at me and said
go for it _ and we hired all these people,'' Gates said. ``There
were all these people who theorized about multiculturalism _ there
were very few administrators who were able to envision that theory
and to implement it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
