 PERSONALS: Now, Everything Is Perfectly Clear 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle news
file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Both  &UR; Liv Tyler &LR; 's ``ears and her large high eyes are of different
sizes,'' writes  &UR; Cheryl Lee Terry  &LR; of Us Weekly. ``This explains
her sudden rise to fame and fortune.''
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to the Richmond (Va.) Bar Association last week,
Supreme Court Justice  &UR; Clarence Thomas  &LR; said he would reduce his
speaking schedule because public speaking comes close to
``compromising'' his actions as a judge.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he believes his colleagues on the court ask too
many questions. ``The court was a fairly quiet court when I
arrived,'' he said. ``Now we look like `Family Feud.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WHY PIZZA FLIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Fremont's  &UR; Tony Gemignani &LR; , four-time winner of the Pizza
Olympics in Rome, guest on  &UR; Jay Leno &LR; 's ``Tonight'' show and winner
of first prize at the World Pizza Games in Las Vegas, has shared
the secret of why he's a great pizza-tosser and you're probably
not.
</P>
<P>
   It's all in ``how you make the dough,'' said Gemignani, who
plies his craft professionally at Pyzano's in Castro Valley. ``A
lot of it has to do with pizza flour. The higher the protein count,
the more stretchy it is.'' Pizza flour has a 13 to 14 percent
protein count, he said, but most baking flour has only 5 to 6
percent protein, which causes it to tear when tossed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; THANKS, BUT NO THANKS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   On the occasion of its 150th birthday, Harper's magazine's June
issue includes a congratulatory letter from  &UR; President Clinton &LR;  and
a proclamation from New York Mayor  &UR; Rudolph Giuliani &LR;  that June is
Harper's 150th anniversary month in New York. Also included are a
selection of oldies but goodies that includes a somewhat
politically incorrect snippet from a  &UR; George Plimpton &LR;  interview
with  &UR; Eudora Welty &LR;  in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Plimpton asks Welty about the time  &UR; Henry Miller &LR;  came to visit
her home in Jackson, Miss. ``He was so dull,'' she says. ``He never
looked at anything. I guess he was bored by being in Mississippi.
During his visit, they were going to move the hospital for the
insane down on North State Street to the next county, to a bigger
place. The patients were helping move themselves. I thought that
would be a funny sight for Mr. Miller. . . . It meant absolutely
nothing to him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's hard to believe,'' said Plimpton, no slouch at
flattery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought so, too,'' said Welty. ``It's not every day there's
something like that in Jackson to offer anyone. Those poor old
crazy people carrying their own beds out and putting them in a
truck and driving away. . . . I thought it was a gift I could offer
as a hostess.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; GOODS AND SERVICES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Gloria Vanderbilt &LR; , New York glamour girl and heiress, is
auctioning some of her stuff _ shoes, purses, scarves and jewelry _
on eBay ( &LR; ebay.com &LR; , seller name is aml58). Each item comes with a
photograph of a portrait of the seller by  &UR; Aaron Shikler &LR; , says a
note from the seller to buyers, whose ``official portraits of
President  &UR; John F. Kennedy &LR; ,  &UR; Jacqueline Kennedy  &LR; and  &UR; Nancy &LR; 
 &UR; Reagan &LR;  are in the White House.'' Furthermore, the portrait will be
``signed personally by Ms. Vanderbilt.'' Oh, and the shoes are size
8.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Marla Maples &LR;  is auctioning off the 7.45-carat diamond
engagement ring that  &UR; Donald Trump  &LR; gave her (when he was still
married to  &UR; Ivana Trump &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   _ An ad in last week's Los Angeles Times, forwarded to Personals
by  &UR; Larry Maxcy &LR; , touted the bridal registry for the 99-Cent Only
Stores, which prides itself on ``over 9,999 exciting choices
(Nothing over 99 cents EVER).''
</P>
