<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2750 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-22 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVING CREDIT FOR IMPROVED TEXAS SCHOOL SCORES &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   &QL; 
AUSTIN, Texas _ I have heard the political line on TAAS often
enough.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling with Texas Gov. George W. Bush throughout much of the
country, I have listened to him brag repeatedly about the
improvements in student test scores in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   And in Austin last week, Jim Nelson, Bush's hand-picked state
education commissioner, was elated as he announced that this
spring's statewide TAAS results had reached new heights.
</P>
<P>
   It was more good news for state bureaucrats and the would-be
president in their command posts and for thousands of students and
teachers on the front lines.
</P>
<P>
   Battlefield terms come to mind because the educational process
has become almost a war in our increasingly competitive world. In
the emerging global economy, we are told, our children aren't
merely competing against classmates for the best grades and the
best colleges, they are competing with kids on the other side of
the world for tomorrow's best jobs.
</P>
<P>
   It is a level of competition with which I am not totally
comfortable, because I fear our children may be sacrificing too
much of their childhoods for the sake of their futures. But I don't
pretend to be an educational expert.
</P>
<P>
   With so much at stake, public education also is enshrouded in
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential candidates duel over educational records and
policy. Principals and teachers are under fire to improve student
performance _ and their campus report cards _ so that taxpayers can
be assured that they are getting their money's worth.
</P>
<P>
   And, from an early age, Texas students are drilled on the
importance of our state's primary academic measuring stick, the
Texas Assessment of Academic Skills (or TAAS) test, which they
begin taking in the third grade.
</P>
<P>
   The closest stretch of the front lines to my house is Kiker
Elementary School in suburban, southwest Austin, and the soldier I
know best is my 10-year-old daughter, Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Although seriously crowded, Kiker is a good school, thanks to
dedicated teachers and a large dose of parental involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, who completes the fourth grade this week, is a good
student. And, fortunately, she is blissfully ignorant of how
important her test scores are to politicians, great and small.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you worry much about the TAAS test?'' I asked her the
other day. ``Nah,'' she replied.
</P>
<P>
   She passed TAAS without any trouble in the third grade, and she
most likely passed this year, although we haven't seen her latest
scores yet.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor did have the distinction of being the last of Kiker's 200
fourth-graders to finish the math section of the TAAS when it was
administered last month. But that didn't seem to bother her.
</P>
<P>
   Her favorite part was the writing test. Most of her friends
thought the writing exam was ``boring and hard,'' but she thought
it was ``fun and easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Whichever it was, 98 percent of Kiker's fourth-graders passed
the writing test, one of Taylor's teachers announced after an
awards ceremony last week. She said the overall TAAS results at
Kiker were ``phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   Kiker is an above-average school in a wealthier-than-average
school district. But improvements in TAAS scores were widespread
this spring. Test scores of minority students still lag behind
Anglos, but they continue to close the gap.
</P>
<P>
   The TAAS scores are less important to Taylor than they will be
to her younger brother, Adrian, who will have to pass the state's
standardized tests each year to be promoted to the next grade. That
law, which the Legislature enacted last year at Bush's urging, went
into effect with this year's kindergarten class.
</P>
<P>
   At present, the only TAAS test that students have to pass is the
exit-level test given in high school. They have to pass that test
to graduate.
</P>
<P>
   TAAS will be replaced within a few years with new standardized
exams covering more subjects, and there may be a rough inaugural
period.
</P>
<P>
   But the improving TAAS scores are good news _ and not simply
because students are scoring higher on standardized tests. More
importantly, let us hope, they reflect improvements in our public
education system.
</P>
<P>
   If that is the case, students, teachers, principals, parents _
and even some politicians _ deserve credit.
</P>
<P>
   Clay Robison is chief of the Houston Chronicle's Austin Bureau.
(clay.robison (a)chron.com) &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
