<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-M:I-2-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO CRUISE CONTROL IN M:I-2?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Embargoed until after May 24, 2000) 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Turning ``Mission: Impossible'' into a viable movie franchise
was, to paraphrase a line from the espionage action attraction's
new sequel ``M:I-2,'' a mission very difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The film faced agonizing delays at every step. Just getting off
the ground, to start with; for some two years following the 1996
``M:I's'' release, producer-star Tom Cruise was tied up working on
Stanley Kubrick's ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' one of the longest-running
productions in film history. And even after perfectionist Cruise
found the time to focus his attention exclusively on ``M:I-2,'' a
satisfying script for the picture proved frustratingly elusive. And
once the massive logistical task of filming the sequel finally got
under way, the production's main locations in and around Sydney,
Australia were hit with a plethora of problems both man-made and
beyond human control.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the main concern overriding all of the individual
development, scheduling and production difficulties was the driving
desire to make a better movie. Although it was a blockbuster
international hit, Brian De Palma's first ``Mission'' film was
widely criticized for being incomprehensible, poorly paced and, by
some fans, a betrayal of the popular 1960s television show from
which it was derived. Profitable as it was, the film was viewed in
many quarters as the epitome of soulless commercialism; the kind of
thing that made Cruise a superstar in the likes of ``Top Gun'' and
``Cocktail,'' but which the more mature star of ``Jerry Maguire,''
the Kubrick film and ``Magnolia'' is evidently striving to
transcend.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise placed his hopes for a better second ``Mission'' on John
Woo, the Chinese director who made an international splash with the
balletically violent Hong Kong crime melodramas ``A Better
Tomorrow,'' ``The Killer'' and ``Hard Boiled.'' Since coming to
Hollywood, Woo has gradually worked his hyper-aestheticized,
bullet-riddled style into what would otherwise have been
standard-issue action pictures such as ``Broken Arrow'' and
``Face/Off.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When Tom offered this project to me, I was a little surprised
because I'd never dreamed of making a `Mission: Impossible,'''
notes the 54-year-old Woo in broken yet somehow precise English.
``But he said that this would be a totally different movie, no need
to connect it to the first one. He wanted every episode to have a
different style from a different director; he wanted this one to be
John Woo's `Mission: Impossible.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him I was not good at special effects, that I'm
computer-blind,'' Woo adds with a throaty laugh. ``I like the real
thing and my style is more about the character, that people would
care more for him than they would about a computer. Tom agreed, and
he also wanted to make a classic, romantic spy movie, which I
thought was great.''
</P>
<P>
   The plotline that was settled on resembled the best example of
that particular approach: Alfred Hitchcock's 1946 ``Notorious,''
written by the esteemed Ben Hecht.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty much something that I wanted to play with,''
notes screenwriter Robert Towne, who came up with the ``Notorious''
gambit. ``You can actually use a love triangle to both generate
suspense and evolve the characters emotionally, while revealing
plot.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``M:I-2,'' Cruise's Ethan Hunt is assigned by the Impossible
Missions chief (Anthony Hopkins in a flavorful cameo) to convince
international jewel thief Nyah Hall (British actress Thandie
Newton) to re-enter the life of a former lover, Sean Ambrose
(Dougray Scott), a more ruthless master thief. Ambrose has stolen
an experimental virus antidote from an Australian pharmaceutical
manufacturer, and must be stopped by any means necessary from
obtaining and unleashing the killer bug it was tested against.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating matters is the fact Hunt and Hall fall in love
before he sends her off to seduce Ambrose.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were inspired by the movie `Notorious,' '' Woo confirms.
``We just took the spirit of it, though. The idea was to have good
and evil both in love with the same woman. Tom and Robert Towne
came up with that whole structure for this movie, just try to make
it modern.''
</P>
<P>
   Towne, the widely revered screenwriter of some classic '70s
films himself (``Chinatown,'' ``Shampoo''), has been Cruise's
favorite script doctor for years. He tried, with mixed results, to
add a little narrative sense to ``Days of Thunder,'' ``The Firm''
and the first ``Mission,'' but the assignment he chose to accept
this time around was probably the most daunting yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were other writers involved with this before I was,''
Towne explains. ``And John had been on it for some six to eight
months. He had developed some flashy action sequences in his own
unique way and preproduction had gone rather far down the line to
implement them. So I based my story on what he presented me. It was
certainly different, but let me put it this way: unless you're
deeply masochistic, it's not something that you'd want to do very
often.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, having said that, it was great fun to do. The challenge
was to fit a story into that `Mission: Impossible' world, and make
that world and story as credible as possible. In a word, I tried to
seek the right tone. It's never going to be gritty realism, but
within its own fantastical framework, it had to have a certain
demanding discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   Demanding was the operating adjective once production finally
got under way in Australia last May. Rain washed out entire
shooting days and curtailed others. A major hailstorm even damaged
a number of expensive vehicles _ before Woo, a cinematic master of
mechanized mayhem, was prepared to wreck them.
</P>
<P>
   ``John and I were looking at some casting tapes when we heard,
virtually, this explosion,'' recalls Paula Wagner, Cruise's
producing partner. ``We looked up, and hail the size of baseballs
was coming from everywhere at terminal velocity. And we had 40 days
of rain.''
</P>
<P>
   Other complications included a local cinematographer, Andrew
Lesnie (``Babe''), who had never shot a film in anamorphic
widescreen before and had to be replaced with American ``Top Gun''
shooter Jeffrey Kimball. Though Woo insists the change was made
solely to help speed up the already behind-schedule production _
and he heartily recommended Lesnie to his next employer, ``Lord of
the Rings'' director Peter Jackson _ the move did not endear the
above-the-line bosses to the Australian crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a little difficulty because of the union thing, too,''
Woo adds. ``They had just started, so they made so many rules, and
there's only one union for everything _ actors, stuntmen, crew. But
we were able to compromise, and they turned out to be very
dedicated and talented people.''
</P>
<P>
   Other problems arose. Scott hurt his back during one of the
film's numerous, ridiculous motorcycle stunts, prompting another
weeklong delay. Even worse, permits to film an elaborate climactic
chase through the streets of Sydney were refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that they couldn't afford to block the traffic
for four weeks while we shot the scene,'' Woo says,
characteristically polite but still perturbed. ``But we had to stop
the whole production again and redesign all the action.''
</P>
<P>
   But the worst moments for Woo were on a mesa in Utah. That's
where Ethan Hunt's introductory scene, a rock climbing vacation,
was filmed; and where Cruise insisted on doing all of his own
stunts.
</P>
<P>
   Two thousand feet up. With only a single, thin cable to hold
him, and nothing to catch him on the ground or prevent him from
smashing into the cliff face during harrowing jumps.
</P>
<P>
   Through seven nail-biting takes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was up on top of the mesa, praying for him and sweating and
panicking,'' Woo admits. ``I couldn't even watch the monitor, I was
so worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Post-production rumors have made it seem like Cruise was even
more worrisome in the editing room, as pressure mounted to ensure
the over- budget (more than $100 million, originally priced at $80
million) and past due (first slated for release last Christmas)
film achieved a commercially crucial PG-13 rating. Top Hollywood
action editor Stuart Baird was brought in to assist with the
cutting, some believe to tone down Woo's trademark ballistic
overindulgence.
</P>
<P>
   But while acknowledging that creative conflicts occurred at
various stages of the long, tortured production, Woo insists Cruise
never tried to hijack the final cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom gave me a lot of great respect,'' Woo says. ``Arguments
happen in every movie; they just draw attention. But he listened to
me all the time. Even when he had different ideas, in the end he
always wanted my approval.''
</P>
<P>
   Now it's time to see whether a worldwide audience feels
``M:I-2'' is as improved as its makers hoped.
</P>
<P>
   But for Woo, typically, success will be judged in personal
rather than economic terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to make a rich and romantic film,'' he says, ``And I
feel like so many people understand me now and encourage me. I hope
this makes them want me to make more good movies for them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
