<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-LEONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBELS FREE HALF OF FORCE FROM THE U.N. IN AFRICA WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Nearly half the peacekeepers seized in Sierra
Leone this month have been released, the United Nations said
Monday. Officials added that they hoped that releases would
continue in coming days.
</P>
<P>
   With the freeing of 29 additional troops Monday, 233 of the 500
hostages have now been turned over, United Nations officials said
here.
</P>
<P>
   But as more hostages have been released, rebels have also been
calling for their leader, Foday Sankoh, to be freed, raising
concerns that the rebels may continue to hold the troops while
bargaining for their leader's freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, Secretary-General Kofi Annan proposed strengthening
the United Nations force, to 16,500 from the authorized 13,000. He
also said in a report to the Security Council that even more
soldiers might be needed later.
</P>
<P>
   In his report and in comments to reporters, Annan blamed Sankoh,
who is in the custody of the Sierra Leone government, for the
crisis in the country. Annan recommended that the council consider
imposing new sanctions on Sankoh and his Revolutionary United
Front, adding that the guerrilla leader had no future role in
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe by his behavior he has excluded himself from the
process,'' Annan said. The secretary-general said Sierra Leone's
diamonds, which financed Sankoh, should be taken out of rebel hands
and turned over to the government and people of the country. The
diamonds are one of Sierra Leone's few natural resources.
</P>
<P>
   In Freetown on Monday morning, two Nigerians on duty were killed
when armed men described as former Sierra Leone army soldiers
entered the Nigerians' barracks and demanded the release of a
fellow soldier who was apparently being detained there.
</P>
<P>
   A gun battle erupted, and the Nigerians and a former soldier
died. Several former Sierra Leone soldiers were reportedly injured.
</P>
<P>
   In another incident, about six mutilated bodies wearing
peacekeepers' uniforms were found northeast of Freetown. U.N.
officials said they did not have enough information to know
victims' identities.
</P>
<P>
   Jordanian soldiers were sent to the area to examine the site and
the bodies. But the group does not have a forensic expert,
according to a spokeswoman for the United Nations here, Marie
Okabe. Uniforms of Nigerian and Zambian troops were stolen a few
weeks ago, so the presence of just uniforms would not necessarily
identify the men, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The victims appear to have been shot in the head at close range.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
