<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Murderously melodic: Eminem raps everything
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What will really bother mainstream America about this album is
that it contains every off-putting scenario a sick mind could
conjure up. But then it has the nerve to be a melodic nightmare.
Something the kids can sing along to.
</P>
<P>
   Eminem (producer Dr. Dre's most gifted protege since Snoop Dogg)
spins incredibly twisted tales of murder, makes fun of Christopher
Reeve and sings a death threat (``Kill You''). Then, in his nasal,
smart-aleck tone, the Grammy-winning rapper born Marshall Mathers
continues to fire away at every boy band, nosy reporter and suing
relative in sight. Leaving in his wake a second album so well-done
it earns its parental advisory sticker and accolades at the same
time.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on Eminem: www.slimshadyworld.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``The Marshall Mathers LP''
</P>
<P>
   Eminem. Aftermath/Interscope.
</P>
<P>
   18 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
