<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2762 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MATCHBOX-JANSMITH23-C     05-22 1582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATCHBOX-JANSMITH23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Though her dream of singing stardom has yet to come true, Jan
Smith of Snellville, Ga., has found her calling as a vocal teacher
for the rock set
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With her motherly eyes, Southern accent and T-shirt and jeans,
Jan Smith, 43, of Snellville, Ga., doesn't seem at first glance
like someone who'd have a triple platinum rock album hanging on the
wall.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in her sunny office _ in a converted grammar school
building just down the road from Emory University _ she looks more
like a hip schoolteacher waiting at a utilitarian metal desk for a
conference with a student. But there it is, the glamorous trophy,
tucked in a frame like a photo of a favored child.
</P>
<P>
   The plaque is from MTV supergroup matchbox twenty, the scruffy
Orlando rock band that has sold a phenomenal 10 million copies of
its 1996 debut album, ``Yourself or Someone Like You,'' with the
radio hits ``Push,'' ``3am,'' ``Real World'' and ``Back to Good.''
Smith's big voice, honed through years fronting Atlanta rock bands,
isn't on the album. But her imprint is everywhere. She is lead
singer Rob Thomas's vocal coach.
</P>
<P>
   When the baby-faced rock star was at the studio microphone
bouncing out the lyric ``well I will, well I will,'' Smith was by
his side, talking to him like a trainer in the corner of a boxing
match: ``Slow down. Go with me. Reach for it.'' She listened to
playback for hours, helping producer Matt Serletic pick the best
tracks, the ones where Thomas' passionate bar-band vocals nailed
the songs. When the band began its tour of clubs, Smith was there
too, hanging with kids in sock caps and flannel shirts during smoky
sound checks. And at this year's Grammy Awards, the tough vocal
maestro was backstage in Thomas' dressing room, helping him warm up
before performing the record and song of the year, ``Smooth,'' with
Carlos Santana.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving in stores today is the new matchbox twenty CD ``mad
season,'' on which Smith directed vocals. And lead singer Thomas
doesn't hesitate to give her mountains of credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the bomb. She has done amazing things for me,'' he says
on the eve of his highly anticipated follow-up's release. ``Get a
hold of the last matchbox twenty album and listen to this one. They
are testaments to Jan. She's really taught me the subtleties of
singing. Since I met her, I have gained two octaves on my voice.
I'm from the school of `I can sing and I don't need anybody to show
me.' But Jan has made all the difference in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The international stage of the Grammys is a long way from the
modest house in Forest Park, Ga., where Smith grew up, watching the
awards show each year plopped in front of her parents' television
set. She remembers the moment in 1974 when her idol, Joni Mitchell,
picked up the Grammy for ``Down to You'' from ``Court and Spark.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There just weren't a lot of girls with guitars back then,''
Smith recalls. ``I knew right then that these were the people who
were it. The Grammy became an icon for me. It is everything I grew
up believing in.''
</P>
<P>
   While other girls at Forest Park Senior High were trying out for
cheerleading, Smith sat in her room hunched over a microphone
recording four-part harmonies into a Sony reel-to-reel. Her father,
the songleader at McDonough, Ga., Heights Baptist Church, fueled
her passion by taking her to gospel shows at Atlanta's old
Municipal Auditorium. At 15, she joined a rock band called Messiah,
playing local dances and clubs. By 1979, when her friends began
flashing engagement rings, Smith was one of Atlanta's barefoot Rock
Chicks, tossing her long blonde hair while screaming into the
microphone at clubs such as Alex Cooley's Electric Ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her instincts for vocal interpretation are uncanny,'' recalls
Mike Greene, the old friend and Atlanta musician who went on to
become president of the National Academy of Recording Arts and
Sciences (the Grammy folks). ``She is a straight shooter who leads
by example and lives life very large.''
</P>
<P>
   Being a member of the boys' club took its toll. By age 17, Smith
found herself in drug rehab.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was that whole hippie thing. The music was infested with
drugs,'' she recalls. ``I tell people, `Hey, the real Woodstock
happened in my lifetime.'''
</P>
<P>
   To avoid the excesses of the world of rock, Smith enrolled at
Georgia College in Milledgeville and earned a degree in psychology.
For eight years, she worked in a DeKalb County, Ga., day program
for disturbed adolescents. But her muse kept tugging at her sleeve.
She went back to singing at nights, with the dream of making it as
a rock star.
</P>
<P>
   Success as a singer was elusive _ no major recording contracts,
no hit records. Then something completely unexpected happened: She
found her life's work as a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   During a 1986 visit to the old Clark Music store in Atlanta, she
ran into the owner of the Atlanta School of Rock, who asked Smith
if she would be willing to give voice lessons to the lead singer of
a local band, the Torpedos. Almost by accident, she discovered that
she could take the elements of classical vocal training _
breathing, intonation, reaching for the diaphragm _ and apply it to
the often reckless and free-form world of rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most instructors are classically trained and don't consider
rock legitimate,'' she says. ``In classical music, you are trained
to reflect what the composer wants. Rock is such an individual
thumbprint for a vocalist, and you don't want to change that. Think
about Bonnie Raitt or Eddie Vedder. When you turn on the radio, you
can recognize their sound immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1989, Smith had so many clients in her Rolodex that she was
able to quit her day job. Eventually she opened a small studio,
where she worked with local acts such as Kristin Hall and
Collective Soul. It was through her relationship with that
Stockbridge band that she met 15-year-old Serletic, a Stone
Mountain prodigy who was then playing in the studio with the group.
As his star rose in the early 1990s, Serletic often turned to Smith
for help in getting the best out of the young vocalists he had
begun producing.
</P>
<P>
   Such as Rob Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Serletic sent the high school dropout _ with his torn
jeans and a sock hat pulled over his head _ to Smith's Decatur,
Ga., office for some advice. At the time, Thomas' voice was
powerful but raw. Like many rock stars, he wasn't sure he needed
anyone (especially a tough, middle-aged woman) to tell him what to
do.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the one hand, it's all about attaching to the emotional
side and feeling what you're singing,'' Thomas explains. ``But on
the technical side, it's about breath control and opening up your
throat. That was the hardest part at first.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith stood by Thomas' side at Tree Sound, the Norcross, Ga.,
recording studio where matchbox twenty's first album was recorded.
He found that she was no pushover, her clipped voice putting him
through the paces like a horse trainer with a whip.
</P>
<P>
   The visibility, which Smith describes as ``an incredible ride,''
has been more than she ever imagined. She has a waiting list of
people clamoring for her services and plans to open a division of
Jan Smith Studios in Nashville this summer. Underneath the crisp,
professional exterior, however, she often relaxes into the
starstruck teenager who dreamed of having her own Grammy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest part,'' she says, ``is to be at the prime of my
career and know it may never happen for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith still wants to be a star in her own right. But at 43, with
years of knocking on doors be-
</P>
<P>
   hind her, is that still a possibility?
</P>
<P>
   ``Why hasn't she made it as an artist herself? Who the hell
knows,'' says Eddie Owen, owner of the Decatur club Eddie's Attic.
``Anybody who works in this business knows being at the right place
at the right time is one ingredient you can't muster up on your
own. ... If you're an artist and ever feel you've lost your
chances, it's all over. I believe it takes keeping a mystical eye
on the grand prize to make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith seems to have that covered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we are here for two things: To help each other, and
to have a good time,'' she says. ``We are each doing here what the
spirit has called us to do. You don't take money with you, or fame.
Elvis is dead. He's still dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Music) is the language of the heart. The closest I know I can
be to God is when I'm singing.''
</P>
<P>
   THE JAN SMITH FILE
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Home: Ten acres in Snellville, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Family: Father is James Smith, a retired salesman with Quaker
State Oil. Mother is Betty Smith, retired administrative assistant
with the Talon Zipper Corporation. Two older brothers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rock life: Wrote first tune, ``I Will Sing You a Song,'' when
she was 9. Joined first band, Messiah, at 15, playing high school
dances and local clubs. Fronted the Southern rock band Jan Smith &AMP;
the Eclectic Cowboys from 1990 to 1994. Released a solo album
called ``Rain'' in 1995 and ``Nonstop Thrill,'' with the Jan Band
in 1997. Served as president of the Atlanta chapter of NARAS from
1998 to 2000, and is an alternate trustee.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Catch her live: June 9 at Eddie's Attic (515-B N. McDonough
St., Decatur, Ga. 404-377-4976; www.eddiesattic.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : Visit the Jan Smith Web site:
www.jansmith.com
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
