<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Book excerpt sets stage for city's 1913 brush with anarchy
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Infamous Leo Frank lynching case revisited in Atlanta magazine.
</P>
<P>
   A painful chapter of Atlanta's history will be spotlighted June
13 when Alfred Uhry's Tony Award-winning musical ``Parade'' debuts
at the Fox Theatre. It's the story of the city's most infamous
homicide case _ the murder of 13-year-old Mary Phagan and the
conviction and lynching of Jewish businessman Leo Frank more than
80 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It is a case that has obsessed former Atlanta writer Steve Oney.
Now, after a dozen years of research, Oney has finished what is
touted as the definitive book about the episode, with several
explosive revelations. To be published next winter, the
as-yet-untitled book is excerpted in the June issue of Atlanta
($3.50).
</P>
<P>
   In the two-chapter excerpt, Oney sets the scene for the tragic
events of April 26, 1913, and points out the chasm that existed
between the haves and have-nots, as well as a growing
anti-Semitism.
</P>
<P>
   While elegantly attired Atlantans attended a touring performance
of the New York Metropolitan Opera Company (Arturo Toscanini was
conducting and Enrico Caruso was singing), children as young as 10
were laboring 11 hours a day in mills and factories. One of them
was Mary Phagan, who was found dead the next morning at the
National Pencil Co. As Atlanta Editor in Chief Lee Walburn notes in
his column, the subsequent trial and lynching would be as close as
the city has ever come to anarchy.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  FINAL WORDS: In a fitting Memorial Day issue, Time ($3.50)
pays tribute to American veterans with a selection of last letters
from soldiers who were killed in action in both world wars, Korea
and Vietnam. Eloquent and heartbreaking in their simplicity, these
are the final words from ordinary men to their loved ones. ``These
epistles haunt the soul the same way the best war poems do,''
writes historian Douglas Brinkley, ``perhaps even more poignantly,
because we know what their authors didn't. ...''
</P>
<P>
   In one note, a soldier stationed in India writes his girlfriend
a marriage proposal and describes a rainbow he had seen an hour
after sundown. His sweetheart wrote back saying she'd marry him,
but he never got the reply.
</P>
<P>
   Selected from Andrew Carroll's Legacy Project, a nonprofit
initiative that seeks out historically significant wartime letters,
these final notes will be published as a book next May.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE GREAT OUTDOORS: The premiere issue of Wildlife Journal
($3.95) hits the stands this week, with informative and
well-written articles ranging from a profile of former ``Wild
Kingdom'' star Jim Fowler to an update on the Endangered Species
Act. Published by Emmis Communications and edited by Marietta-based
Steve Walburn, son of Atlanta magazine editor Lee Walburn, the
quarterly is devoted to covering all aspects of wildlife and the
natural environment.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  QUICK READS: Atlanta Citymag ($3.95) offers a summer guide to
what's hot, from fashions to travel. Also of note is a profile of
TV and movie casting queen Shay Bentley-Griffin, who has supplied
local talent for projects such as TNT's ``Andersonville'' and
``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil.''
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
