<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2764 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-PEABODY-AWARDS23-COX     05-22 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEABODY-AWARDS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barry Sherman's legacy of excellence
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A bittersweet mood hung over Monday's luncheon for
the 59th Peabody Awards.
</P>
<P>
   The elation of those winning what's widely considered to be
broadcast journalism's highest honor was undercut by the absence of
Barry Sherman, the University of Georgia professor and longtime
Peabody director who died from a sudden heart attack three weeks
ago at the age of 47.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still disbelieving Barry's dead,'' said Peabody board
member Ed Bark, echoing many of those at the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel,
where the luncheon was held. ``I was walking by the hotel the other
night and saw someone who looked just like Barry _ it was like in
`The Sixth Sense.' I keep half expecting him to show up.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Roy Barnes talked about the standard of excellence Sherman
set for the awards, which are administered annually by the UGA
school of journalism and mass communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was wondering what is an appropriate tribute,'' Barnes told
an opulent, opera-house-style room packed with such notable
journalists and celebrities as Peter Jennings, Tom Wolfe and
Lorraine Bracco. ``But being here and seeing all of you here, what
(he would have wanted) is to continue this great work.''
</P>
<P>
   A film tribute of Sherman was shown. Later, Sheila Nevins, while
accepting a 15th Peabody for her work in original programming at
HBO, said that ``the Peabodys were Barry Sherman'' and that she now
thinks of her award as the ``George Foster Peabody Barry Sherman
Award.''
</P>
<P>
   Reporter Dale Russell accepted a Peabody for the investigative
team from Atlanta's WAGA-TV, which won for its series on racial
profiling by U.S. Customs agents at Hartsfield International
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's humbling,'' Russell said of the event, which was hosted
by NBC's Matt Lauer. ``I look around this room and see Bud
Greenspan, Aaron Sorkin (creator of `West Wing') _ I wanted to ask
him who got shot in that last episode.''
</P>
<P>
   WAGA news director Budd McEntee called the Peabody ``the
ultimate,'' and said that, at a time when many local news
organizations are cutting back on investigative reporting, winning
such an award helps keep a unit like the I-Team together.
</P>
<P>
   ``It confirms why we do what we do, and reaffirms the mission,''
he said. ``These awards confirm the need for more investigative
reporting.'' Other winners echoed that thought. Jennings said that
ABC's Peabody for its 24-hour, globe-trotting coverage of the new
millennium ``confirms for me Americans are interested in the rest
of the world.'' CBS's Bob Simon, who won for international
reporting, said, ``It's reassuring to know that if you do bad
things in Cincinnati or the Philippines or Bosnia, you're going to
wind up on this screen,'' referring to the film montage of winners
that preceded the awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why we're here, when I see all these other
winners,'' said David Chase, creator of HBO's ``The Sopranos.'' ``I
never expected to be anywhere near this award, because of the
nature of our show.''
</P>
<P>
   Also winning were the producers of the PBS ``Frontline''
documentary ``The Lost Children of Rockdale County,'' which was the
highest rated show on GPTV last year and has been repeated numerous
times.
</P>
<P>
   Co-producer Rachel Dretzin, who spent five months in Georgia
filming teenagers whose widespread sexual activities led to a 1996
syphilis outbreak in suburban Atlanta, said she was ``astonished''
by the reaction to the film. Co-producer and husband Barak Goodman
added, ``We expected a certain amount of resistance, and we got
some of that. But the community also took responsibility for what
happened. We got them to do something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was the memory of Sherman that continued throughout the
ceremony. As HBO's Nevins put it, ``Everybody's saying `Barry would
have liked this,' or `Barry would have liked that.' But you know
what Barry would have liked? He would have liked to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Drew Jubera writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
