u a BC-HARVARD-RUDENSTINE-BO     05-22 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-RUDENSTINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD PRESIDENT TO STEP DOWN NEXT YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALICE DEMBNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ After nine years at the pinnacle of higher
education, Harvard University president Neil L. Rudenstine said
Monday that he plans to step down in June 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Rudenstine, 65, will leave Harvard far wealthier and stronger
than at any time in its history, both friends and foes agreed. Many
called him a local and national leader among his peers. Even those
who fault him for failing to take full advantage of the bully
pulpit that is Harvard praise his national leadership on the issue
of diversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a good run, and it's time for someone else,''
Rudenstine said. ``The institution is strong enough financially
where someone else ought to be willing to step forward and do some
bold things.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time he departs, Rudenstine will have served a decade,
three years longer than the national average for college
presidents. He came back from a three-month medical leave in
1994-1995 to raise the largest sum ever for an institution of
higher learning _ $2.6 billion _ to resolve the question of
Radcliffe's future, and to begin a long process of unifying a
balkanized campus. Observers on and off campus said he will be
remembered most for those three efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He leaves the institution in the strongest financial postion
it's been in in its whole life,'' said Rudenstine's predecessor,
Derek Bok.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harvard today is more inclusive, more cohesive, more
interdisciplinary and more engaged with the larger world,'' added
Robert G. Stone Jr., who heads Harvard's governing board. Stone and
other members of the Harvard Corporation will likely begin the
process of searching for Rudenstine's successor this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Rudenstine said he is proudest of his work developing the
Afro-American Studies Department into the preeminent such program
in the nation, with such academic superstars as Henry Louis Gates
Jr., Cornell West and William Julius Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Gates, the department chairman, in turn, joined others in
praising Rudenstine's national leadership on diversity, the one
issue on which he abandoned his typical behind-the-scenes approach
to take a public stand. Rudenstine organized other presidents to
fight efforts to gut affirmative action and published evidence of
the benefits of a diverse campus to society.
</P>
<P>
   He was not as successful in bringing diversity to all aspects of
campus, however. While three of the five Harvard vice presidents
are women, up from one when he arrived, all eight of the deans he
appointed are white males.
</P>
<P>
   His presidency is marked by some other contradictions. He
recruited top faculty in many fields, including professor Lani
Guinier in the Law School and Laurel T. Ulrich, a Pulitzer Prize
winner, in history, but made little dent in Harvard's
student-faculty ratio, which at 8 to 1 is higher than some
comparable institutions. Harvard College expects to add more
faculty in the near future, however, with funds from the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He more than doubled the number of senior women faculty from 85
to 183, but acknowledges that the percentage of women in the
faculty remains low.
</P>
<P>
   He began the process of breaking down the independent tradition
of Harvard's professional schools, reinstating the position of
provost to help set university-wide academic policy and
establishing high-profile interdisciplinary programs on the
environment, and cognitive science among others.
</P>
<P>
   But the schools remain independent fiefdoms for the most part.
``Neil was too nice a guy'' to make a lot of progress in that area,
said a former university faculty member.
</P>
<P>
   Rudenstine defends his efforts in that arena, saying, ``It took
more than a century to create the current system. I think it would
be odd if you could change all of that in a decade _ and I'm not
sure you want to change it all. Besides, I don't think banging
heads in a university is a way to make progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudenstine was a Rhodes Scholar who graduated from Princeton and
studied for three years at Oxford. With an expertise in Renaissance
literature, he received a doctorate from Harvard, where he later
taught, then left for Princeton where he was a faculty member and
senior administrator. He served as Princeton's provost from 1977 to
1988.
</P>
<P>
   Over his tenure as Harvard president, some have faulted him for
taking too soft a stance on internal matters, or taking too long to
make decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neil is adverse to conflict, so he finds hard decisions harder
than some. He is so nice, he hates to hurt people,'' said a
colleague.
</P>
<P>
   But he is also revered for his thoughtfulness, his strength of
intellect and deep commitment to liberal arts education in an
increasingly specialized world.
</P>
<P>
   ``His administration will be remembered for its integrity and
authenticity,'' said Stanley Ikenberry, president of the American
Council on Education. ``He was successful in moving the university
to a new level. And he is viewed by his peers as a moral and
intellectual leader and mentor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Neil's style is not prone to exhibitionism. But within the
academic community, he has been a strong voice,'' Ikenberry said.
</P>
<P>
   The demands of the job also proved draining at times. In 1994,
Rudenstine surprised the faculty and administration by taking a
three month medical leave, saying he was exhausted. He said upon
his return in early 1995 that he spent much of the time reading and
writing, something that the job as president didn't allow him to
do.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy said Rudenstine had been an effective
advocate for research funding and student financial aid. Much of
that work was one-on-one, according to Ikenberry.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept his sights _ and ours _ on what we are here for _ the
intellectual and academic matters,'' Jeremy Knowles, dean of the
faculty of arts and sciences.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, Rudenstine also served as a unifying force
among disparate colleges and universities, according to Tufts
president John DiBiaggio.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's called us together to talk about issues of mutual
concern,'' said DiBiaggio. Rudenstine, he said, hosted several
dinners for local presidents from both public and private
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Rudenstine said his biggest regret is mishandling the purchase
and planned development of 52 acres of land in Allston. The
university stirred Mayor Thomas M. Menino's ire for its secret
purchase of the land over many years. But Rudenstine squared the
matter with the city last year, by agreeing to pay $40 million in
lieu of taxes to the city over the next 40 years and to build new
student housing there.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Harvard University also announced a $20 million
loan project to renovate or build housing for low to middle-income
residents in Boston and Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe we are where we want to be but Harvard,
stepping up its commitment, was moving to the right direction and I
think Neil had a lot to do with it,'' said Cambridge Mayor Anthony
Galluccio. ``We are a little disappointed to hear the news because
I think he is someone we could have worked with to strengthen the
town-gown relationship.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
