u w BC-SCOTUS-FEDERALISM-NYT     05-22 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-FEDERALISM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT SIDESTEPS CONSTITUTIONALITY IN ARSON AND FALSE CLAIMS
RULINGS 
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Ill., Ind., Vt.) (See also SCOTUS-CABLE-TV, SCOTUS-CLEANAIR) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court took a step back Monday from its
ongoing confrontation with Congress over the boundaries of federal
authority, interpreting two federal laws in a manner that avoided
the need to rule on challenges to the statutes' constitutionality.
</P>
<P>
   The court unanimously interpreted the federal arson law as not
applying to a house used solely as a private residence. Dewey J.
Jones, sentenced to 35 years in federal prison for throwing a
molotov cocktail into a cousin's house, had challenged his
conviction on the ground that Congress' power to regulate
interstate commerce did not extend to making such an act a federal
crime. The justices Monday vacated the conviction on the narrower,
purely statutory ground that the law ``does not reach an
owner-occupied residence that is not used for any commercial
purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   In a second case, the court ruled that Congress did not intend
to make the states liable to suit by private plaintiffs under the
False Claims Act, a federal law that allows individuals to sue on
the government's behalf for claims of fraud in government
contracting.
</P>
<P>
   This 7-2 decision avoided the deeper constitutional issue of
whether states are immune from such suits under the 11th Amendment,
which the court has invoked several times recently to shield state
governments from the application of federal law.
</P>
<P>
   However, in a sign that the justices are by no means finished
with their examination of the limits of congressional authority,
the court accepted a new and potentially far-reaching case about
federal authority for decision in its next term.
</P>
<P>
   The new case is a challenge to federal jurisdiction under the
Clean Water Act over isolated wetlands, including seasonal ponds
and small lakes that are not connected to navigable, interstate
waterways but serve as habitats for migratory birds. A regional
solid waste agency in Cook County, Ill., which was denied a permit
from the Army Corps of Engineers to fill in such a wetland for use
as a waste disposal site, is arguing that Congress lacks authority
under the Commerce Clause to regulate such areas.
</P>
<P>
   According to a brief filed in the case by the National
Association of Homebuilders, there are 8.3 million isolated
wetlands in the country. Under its regulations, the Army Corps of
Engineers, which has the authority to issue permits under the Clean
Water Act, broadly defines the waters under its jurisdiction to
include ``intrastate lakes, rivers, streams'' as well as prairie
potholes, wet meadows and ponds, and including waters used by
migratory birds that cross state lines.
</P>
<P>
   In denying the Solid Waste Agency of Northern Cook County
permission to fill 17.6 acres, which included seasonally wet
depressions left from a former strip mining operation, the Army
Corps of Engineers said there were numerous migratory birds nesting
at or using the site, including a large colony of great blue
herons.
</P>
<P>
   The 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in Chicago, upheld the
corps' position in a ruling last year that noted the cumulative
effect on the economy of the ``millions of people'' who hunt, trap,
or observe migratory birds. Even if there is no effect on commerce
from the destruction of a particular isolated habitat, the court
said, ``the aggregate effect is clear, and that is all the Commerce
Clause requires.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the soundness of that analysis is in fact far from
clear following the Supreme Court's decision last week that struck
down the civil remedy provision of the Violence Against Women Act
on the ground that violence against women lacked a sufficient
connection with commerce. The justices received appeal in the new
case, Solid Waste Agency vs. U.S. Army Corps of Engineers, No.
99-1178, in January but deferred acting on it until after deciding
the Violence Against Women Act case.
</P>
<P>
   Of the two federalism cases the court decided Monday, the result
in the False Claims Act case was the more surprising because the
court itself, in an unexpected order on the eve of argument last
November, had greatly raised the constitutional stakes. The court
asked the lawyers to address the question of whether a private
individual has standing to pursue a False Claims Act suit on behalf
of the government. Had the answer been no, the heart of a law that
Congress first passed in 1863 to curb fraud against the government
by Civil War contractors would have been eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   But having opened the door to that prospect, the court shut it
firmly Monday. The court was unanimous in ruling that private
plaintiffs do have standing, both because of the long historic
pedigree of what are known as ``qui tam'' actions and because the
plaintiff is standing in the shoes of the government, which has
suffered an actual injury.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia wrote the court's opinion in this case,
Vermont Agency of Natural Resources vs. Stevens, No. 98-1828. A
former employee of the Vermont state agency had brought a False
Claims Act suit charging that the agency had mishandled a federal
grant. In response, Vermont argued that under the 11th Amendment,
which the court has interpreted as barring suits in federal court
against states, the state was immune from suit. Both the federal
District Court in Vermont and the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals, in New York, rejected the state's position.
</P>
<P>
   The court Monday avoided the 11th Amendment issue, ruling
instead that the act's reference to the liability of ``any person''
who commits fraud against the government does not refer to states,
at least when the plaintiff is a private individual. The government
has the authority to take over the prosecuting role in a False
Claims Act case, and the decision Monday left open the prospect
that the government itself could still sue a state. The decision
also raised the possibility that the False Claims Act could be open
to other constitutional challenges based on the separation of
powers.
</P>
<P>
   In a dissenting opinion, Justice John Paul Stevens, joined by
Justice David H. Souter, said the law's text ``makes it perfectly
clear'' that Congress intended the word ``person'' to include
states.
</P>
<P>
   Both in this case and in the arson case, Jones vs. United
States, No. 99-5739, the court applied a longstanding rule that
laws of dubious constitutionality should be interpreted, if
possible, in a way that avoids the constitutional issue.
</P>
<P>
   In applying that rule in the arson case, Justice Ruth Bader
Ginsburg's unanimous opinion said that ``arson is a paradigmatic
common-law state crime'' that Congress could not casually have
meant to federalize without saying so explicitly. The law ``is not
soundly read to make virtually every arson in the country a federal
offense,'' Ginsburg said.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration defended the law's broad application
on the ground that private homes were connected to interstate
commerce through their receipt of natural gas through interstate
lines as well as through the interstate mortgage and insurance
markets. The 7th Circuit accepted this analysis when it upheld .
Jones' conviction. But Ginsburg said the analysis defied the
``common perception'' of what it means to ``use'' something in
interstate commerce. Here, the owner simply ``used the property as
his home, the center of his family life,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 2052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
