<SLUG> BC-AMAZON-SHORT-STORY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMAZON RESCINDS HONOR IN SHORT STORY CONTEST 
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Okla.)  By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last Monday, the first PEN/Amazon.com Short Story Award was
announced and Meera Nair of Brooklyn won the $10,000 prize. It was
one of the largest prizes for an undiscovered writer _ for her work
entitled ``Video,'' about the havoc wrought on a young Indian
couple's marriage by the sexually explicit culture of the West.
With a disclaimer, Amazon is running the full text of the story
despite some complaints over the graphic descriptions of sex _ and
despite the fact that the story was found to be ineligible for the
award.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Amazon and PEN rescinded the prize, which includes
publication on Amazon and in The Boston Book Review, and gave it to
someone else when it was discovered that Nair had been published
previously in a national magazine, which technically meant she was
not a beginner.
</P>
<P>
   The judges gave the prize instead to one of the runners-up,
Marlene Reed Wetzel, of Bixby, Okla., for ``A Map of Tripoli,
1967,'' a love story about an American woman and a Jewish-Italian
man, set in Libya just before the Six-Day War. It is the first
published work of fiction for Wetzel, who is 63, and has lived and
worked in the Middle East. Up to now, Wetzel has published articles
only in local papers in the Oklahoma area, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com ruled Nair ineligible because one of her previous
stories had appeared in The Threepenny Review, which violated the
competition's rules that entrants must not have published a work of
fiction in a nationally distributed magazine with a circulation of
over 5,000. Nair had told Amazon about the Threepenny Review story,
but neither she nor Amazon initially realized that the magazine had
such a large circulation. The decision was made after someone
called Amazon's attention to The Review's circulation figures. The
judges for the prize were Sherman Alexie, David Guterson and
Jamaica Kincaid.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Nair will be allowed to keep the $10,000 and her story
remains on the Amazon Web site, said Patty Smith, an Amazon
spokeswoman. In the story, an Indian husband watches a pornographic
video and tries to persuade his wife to perform the acts he sees.
``Some of them did object to the sexual nature'' of the piece,
Smith said of the customers. ``Some people did not share the
judges' enthusiasm for this wonderful story.''
</P>
<P>
   But the customers' reaction had nothing to do with the prize's
withdrawal, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Amazon was very fair,'' Nair said. ``I don't think
they had any qualms'' about publishing the story.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon said 12,000 people entered the contest. The submissions
ranged from apocalyptic fantasies to stories about children and
horses. The other runners-up are Thomas Cockrell, Holiday Reinhorn
and Paul Rusconi, whose stories are available on Amazon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 2052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000522.0383 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2770 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-FOX-PARKINSONS-790&AMP;AD     05-22 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOX-PARKINSONS-790&AMP;ADD-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX LENDS NAME, CLOUT TO PARKINSON'S ADVOCACY GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ The office of the Parkinson's Action
Network here is now answering the phone with a Hollywood name:
``Michael J. Fox Foundation for Parkinson's Research.''
</P>
<P>
   And on Tuesday, founder Joan Samuelson will be in Washington for
a news conference with Fox, the star of the television show ``Spin
City, to announce the formation of the new research and advocacy
effort the two will team up on.
</P>
<P>
   Both consider it a perfect match. Fox provides the celebrity
clout and fund-raising ability that Parkinson's advocates have long
wished for. And Samuelson brings expertise as a longtime lobbyist
for Parkinson's funding and research.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm sitting at the feet of a master,'' Fox said in
a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do the two have a mutual admiration, they both have the
disease, a neurological disorder that causes tremors and restricts
mobility.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Parkinson's, you're off and you're on,'' Fox said, adding
that he had lived with the disease for about 10 years, while
Samuelson had had it for about a dozen. Their symptoms are alike,
he said, as is their dependence on medicine to control their
shaking, though the medicine takes time to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes Joan and I have morning meetings together before our
meds have kicked in,'' Fox said. ``We're like a couple of Keystone
Cops. One or both of us can't open our bottles of water or pick up
papers. It's a comedy of errors.''
</P>
<P>
   Samuelson, who formed her Santa Rosa-based organization in 1991,
will become the president and CEO of the Michael J. Fox Foundation.
The popular actor, whose last ``Spin City'' segment airs Wednesday,
will be chairman of the board.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said he decided to join the Parkinson's organization because
of Samuelson. ``You sit in a room with Joan and she starts to talk
and she is the most compelling person,'' he said. ``She has a sense
of purpose and commitment and she has a huge stake in this, as do
I.''
</P>
<P>
   About 1 million Americans have Parkinson's, 40 percent of them
under age 60. They include former boxing champ Muhammad Ali, writer
Pauline Kael and Attorney General Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said that after meeting Samuelson he looked into the
Parkinson's Action Network, which is one of four major Parkinson's
groups but the only lobbying one. ``It's a quality organization
with a good reputation and track record,'' Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of ``Spin City's'' one-hour finale Wednesday, viewers
will be invited to call a toll-free number, which will link them to
the Santa Rosa operation for donations. Samuelson's office has put
together a phone bank to handle the calls.
</P>
<P>
   These are heady times for Samuelson, who has tried to recruit
Fox to Parkinson advocacy since the actor announced in November
1998 that he had the degenerative neurological disorder.
Samuelson's first coup was to persuade Fox to appear in September
before Congress, and help her plead for more research money.
</P>
<P>
   The National Institutes of Health paid for about $78 million in
Parkinson's research last year.
</P>
<P>
   Samuelson, 50, a lawyer, learned she had the disease when she
was 37. She founded Parkinson's Action Network chiefly to boost
awareness of the disease and lobby for a greater share of the
government research pie.
</P>
<P>
   She spends about a third of each year in Washington, and other
time on the road giving speeches and attending brain research
conferences. But there's never been enough focus on raising private
money for brain research, she said, and this is where working with
Fox will make the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants to help,'' Samuelson said. ``Mike will call me
and say, `Oh, I was talking to James Taylor ... or Elton John ...
or Sting and they want to know what they can do. Oprah wants to
know what she can do.'''
</P>
<P>
   Samuelson said when the two talked in Washington last fall, Fox
told her to let him know what more he could do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took that as a pretty clear invitation,'' Samuelson said.
``I broached the idea of combining his private fund-raising effort
in collaboration with our advocacy stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox, 38, said he and Samuelson have a lot in common. ``Neither
one of us are administrative types but we're terrible at
delegating. We both tend to want to do it all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're both workaholics,'' agreed Samuelson, who said that
beyond their professional connection is a growing personal one.
``He's a friend. I watch him on the TV interviews and I think about
the guy behind the celebrity. This is a real passage for him.''
</P>
<P>
   She attended the final taping of ``Spin City,'' and said, ``I
felt almost like a traitor with people being so sad that he was
quitting the show, because it's almost like their loss is our
gain.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The actor said he would put his energies into working on the
foundation's Web site (michaeljfox.org), which won't be operating
until Wednesday, and ``being part of the national conversation''
about Parkinson's, which he refers to as ``PD.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fox foundation became a new organization by absorbing the
Parkinson Action Network. Samuelson sees her relationship with Fox
as a ``partnership'' and said her organization smoothly became the
Fox foundation by board action.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no point in going out and creating a new nonprofit
organization,'' she said. ``We already are one. So the board met
and we added Mike to the board and officially changed the name.''
</P>
<P>
   Samuelson said the group would grow from its current seven
employees, and create both an executive board and a science board
to award research grants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a lot of the nitty-gritty to work out,'' she
said, including her salary, which with Parkinson's Action Network
is $76,000. She said the new board probably would combine some of
Fox's big-name friends with existing Parkinson's Action board
members.
</P>
<P>
   For now the foundation will continue in Santa Rosa, but the
headquarters eventually will be in New York with separate offices
in Washington and probably Sonoma County.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
