<SLUG> BC-HAITI-ELECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUMPED BALLOTS RAISE WORRIES IN HAITI VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti _ The results of an undetermined number of
legislative races from the election on Sunday may have to be voided
because ballots were either damaged, lost or left susceptible to
fraud when tired and poorly trained poll workers dumped hundreds of
ballot boxes in a jumble outside electoral offices.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at several Communal Electoral Offices, known by the
French acronym BEC, arrived at work Monday to discover that the
ballot boxes had been left there overnight because poll workers
could not find room for them inside. Some boxes were open, and
thousands of ballots and other documents were found scattered on
the sidewalk or street.
</P>
<P>
   International election observers said that the chaotic delivery
of ballots could make recounts impossible in some areas if there
were close margins or if the official tally sheets, which were
supposed to have been delivered separately, were contested because
of irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The votes cannot be recounted because everybody is treading on
them,'' said Mary Durran, the spokeswoman for the observer mission
from the Organization of American States. ``It seems the vote will
have to be canceled in a number of polling stations in the BEC's of
Port-au-Prince.''
</P>
<P>
   Workers outside the electoral office in the Delmas neighborhood
spent the morning piling up ballot boxes into a 6-foot mound.
Handwritten lists were scattered about in some places, while
workers scooped up handfuls of scattered ballots and put them back
into boxes. ``There was no place to store them in the building, and
it was late in the night when they brought the boxes here,'' said
Jean-Louis Fritz, the lawyer for the Provisional Electoral Council,
which organized the elections, the country's first in three years.
``The police helped them to do their job, but they were very busy.
They put them here and left.''
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of fraud has always been a worry in a cumbersome
electoral process where votes are tallied by hand. Some opposition
parties had expressed fears that Family Lavalas, the party of
former President Jean-Bertrand Aristide, would try to manipulate
the vote. But election observers found no evidence of that, noting
that in some cases damaged Lavalas ballots were clearly visible on
the street.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
