</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETHIOPIA-ERITREA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETHIOPIA WILLING TO NEGOTIATE BUT REFUSES TO STOP FIGHTING 
</HEADLINE>
   By IAN FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia _ As envoys arrived here to try to end the
outbreak of war between Ethiopia and Eritrea, the Ethiopian prime
minister said Monday he was willing to talk but would not stop
fighting as the talks go on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shall negotiate while fighting,'' the leader, Meles Zenawi,
told diplomats from other African nations Monday. ``We shall fight
while negotiating. Both roads lead to peace. Whichever road leads
us to peace quicker, that will be the road we follow in the final
analysis.''
</P>
<P>
   Fighting reignited 10 days ago, when Ethiopia mounted an
offensive it says is aimed at ending the costly two-year war over a
disputed border. Monday, Zenawi spoke from a position of strength:
Ethiopia has pressed deeply into Eritrean territory, saying it will
not leave until Eritrea abandons territory it captured in the last
two years.
</P>
<P>
   Reno Serri, the European Union's special envoy to the Horn of
Africa, came here Monday after three hours of talks with the
president of Eritrea, Isaias Afwerki. Also, Ahmed Ouyahia, the
special envoy of the chairman of the Organization for African
Unity, is meeting with Ethiopia's leaders. Both diplomats support a
peace plan brokered by the OAU but neither said a breakthrough was
imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This mission's work has only just begun,'' Serri, an
undersecretary in the Italian Foreign Ministry, told reporters in
the Eritrean capital, Asmara. ``I don't think situations always
stay the same. I think they move and I am here to move it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yemane Gebremeskel, a spokesman for the Eritrean government,
said they too were willing to resume talks, which broke off earlier
this month in Algeria. But, despite what appear to be severe
setbacks on the battlefield, he said Eritrea was willing to settle
the dispute militarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any problem with diplomacy,'' he said in a
telephone interview Monday night from Asmara. But he added: ``The
war will continue and we will see who will prevail at the end of
the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the U.S. World Food Program said Monday it would sent
the first shipment of food into Eritrea, in an effort to feed
hundreds of thousands of Eritreans who have fled fighting in the
western part of the nation. Officials said they would fly 40 tons
of high-energy biscuits into Asmara on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Both nations have agreed in principle on a peace document.
Eritrea has said it wants a cease-fire first, but Ethiopia wants
the details nailed down before the fighting ends.
</P>
<P>
   With most of the fighting over in western Eritrea, a battle was
shaping up at the town of Areza, according to a military analyst
here from a western nation. That battle could be decisive
militarily and extraordinarily fierce, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
