<DOCNO> NYT20000522.0387 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2774 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HANDICAP-PLAYER-COX     05-22 1590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDICAP-PLAYER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mandy's gift
 &HT;    By Jenn Hildreth
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Mandy Young woke up from a coma nine years ago, big tears
started rolling down her face when she felt around in the hospital
bed for where her left leg should have been.
</P>
<P>
   She looked up at her parents and asked, ``Will God let me grow a
new leg, like trees grow new branches?''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Young will never forget that moment in her daughter's life,
even as she now brims with joy watching Mandy _ a bright, happy
18-year-old about to graduate from Salem High School _ inspire
onlookers on the softball field.
</P>
<P>
   Mandy survived the amputation against great odds, just as she
has survived a string of other life-threatening illnesses related
to a rare immune-deficiency disease that she has had since birth.
It is named ``Mandy's Disease,'' for her. ``Other people see this
girl who only has one leg and is just playing softball, and they
think about how they gripe and they groan. Then they see me out
there working as hard as I can just to be like them,'' Mandy said.
``People ask, `How do you do it?' and I say, `How do I not do it?'
When you grow up in this type of environment, you don't ask
questions; you just live it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandy does not have a prosthetic leg, but she joined the
Sluggers, a team coached by her parents in the Rockdale County
recreation league, in 1995. She uses a crutch to help her play
third base and a designated runner when she steps up to bat. Last
fall, she was named captain of the Salem varsity slow-pitch team.
She has played two years with a traveling team (1996 and 1997), and
has repeatedly earned All-Star honors with the Sluggers. She'll
play in three All-Star games, beginning June 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``She isn't afraid, she will dive for balls,'' said Lisa, who
watched in awe as Mandy dropped her crutch and dived to catch
game-ending line drives in consecutive games a few weeks ago.
``She's going to make every effort to get the out, and I can't
think of anybody else that I would feel more comfortable with at
third base.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandy also is a force at the plate, where she bats by balancing
on her right leg and twisting her torso into her swing. In a
regular season that ended last week, she was one of the Sluggers'
top four batters with a .540 average and .612 on-base percentage.
</P>
<P>
   She played catcher for the Salem team, the only position she
could play, because she was not allowed to use a crutch. Linda
Rice, Salem's slow-pitch coach, said Mandy's attitude, skill and
knowledge earned her one of 16 spots on a team that drew more than
40 girls to tryouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the type of person that has a command about her,'' said
Rice, who lauded Mandy's leadership behind the plate and her
ability to drive in runs. ``She looked like this was all familiar
to her, and it was just another day on the playing field.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet there were many times in Mandy's life that doctors told Lisa
and her husband, Speed, that their daughter probably would not live
to see another day, much less play in a softball game.
</P>
<P>
   Mandy's body cannot detect or fight off infection the way that
most people's do. The condition is so rare that Mandy is the only
person in the world who has been diagnosed with it, according to
Dr. Bruce Beeber at Children's Healthcare of Atlanta at Egleston
hospital. She makes the 12-hour drive to the National Institutes of
Health in Bethesda, Md., at least twice a year for tests and
examinations, to monitor her situation and to further the study of
the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her difficulty is in germ-killing power,'' Beeber said. ``She
might start with what would be for another person a rather simple
skin wound, but infection would end up spreading very rapidly,
causing tissue damage that could end in something like
meningitis.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandy has had spinal meningitis _ a life-threatening bacterial
infection that affects the fluid surrounding the spinal cord and
the brain _ three times. Most stricken are lucky to survive it even
once. She once had a cold that turned into double pneumonia by the
next morning, and as a 3-year-old had a stomach abscess that caused
her weight to drop to 17 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Mandy willingly talks about her disease; she has described it to
television audiences on the ``Montel Williams Show'' and ``Extra''
_ and many regard her story as amazing.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my end, I think `miracle' is not the wrong word to use
for her,'' Beeber said.
</P>
<P>
   Not long before her ninth birthday, Mandy and her younger
sister, Alex, were jumping around in the bedroom of their home in
Conyers. Mandy slipped and cut her left leg on the corner of the
bed. The cut didn't bleed, but Lisa still put antibiotic cream over
it and wrapped it in a bandage. The next day, the skin had rolled
back from the abrasion, and Lisa immediately took Mandy to the
hospital because the wound ``looked like raw meat,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the following weeks, Mandy became very sick. She was put on
intravenous medicine for a week and was sent home from the hospital
on antibiotics, but something still was desperately wrong. One
doctor suggested that it was a reaction to a virus picked up from a
classmate on the bus, and another thought the sickness might be
related to a severe case of homesickness; the Youngs recently had
moved from Hickory, N.C. So the family visited Mandy's
grandparents' home in North Carolina, but on the trip back, her
condition got worse.
</P>
<P>
   Mandy started moaning from the throbbing, cramp-like pain in her
left leg, and Speed stopped at a rest area near Suwanee, so they
could call Mandy's doctors. As Lisa talked on a pay phone outside
of a McDonald's, she glanced back over at her family's mini-van,
and her eyes widened in fear.
</P>
<P>
   Speed was holding Mandy in his arms, and Lisa saw a rainbow of
pink streaks forming on the back of Mandy's leg. They decided to
take Mandy back to Egleston, where doctors had treated her before.
By the time they arrived, Mandy was screaming in pain and begging
the nurse to put her in a hot bath, a ``cure-all for our family,''
Lisa said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Mandy's toes had started to turn black, and the
blackness was creeping up her left foot and onto her leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``You better prepare yourself now,'' Speed told his anxious
wife, ``because they're going to have to amputate.''
</P>
<P>
   After the hot water in the bath brought out quarter-sized black
blisters all over Mandy's leg, doctors diagnosed the condition as
gas gangrene _ which started from the small cut Mandy had gotten
from her bed _ and she was transferred to Crawford Long Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The gangrene spread so fast that, when Lisa asked the doctors
how much they were going to have to amputate, they told her that it
wasn't important _ Mandy probably was not going to live through it,
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Mandy's blood pressure dropped so low that doctors called the
Youngs in to say a final goodbye to their unconscious daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, Mandy pulled through, and a month later, instead of
saying goodbye, Lisa and Speed were explaining to Mandy why she no
longer had a left leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything you've prepared at that point just goes out the
window,'' Lisa said. ``We said to her, `God gave us a choice to
make: We could either let you die and go to heaven right now, or we
could keep you, but the doctors would have to take one of your
legs.'''
</P>
<P>
   When the Youngs returned home after the amputation, Lisa said,
she lay down on top of Mandy's pairs of shoes and cried. But
Mandy's attitude was _ and remains _ so positive, that Speed said
it was tough for anyone else to get down.
</P>
<P>
   Mandy decided that she wanted to try gymnastics, so she did. She
learned how to ride a bicycle with a special pedal. She shoots
baskets in the driveway, swims, plays volleyball and walks with the
rest of the students in her physical education classes.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Mandy would practice softball with Speed and Alex in
the back yard, and she just loved diving for the ball. Yet when
Mandy told Lisa that she wanted to play for a team in 1995, Lisa
was a little apprehensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, we were really taken (aback) by it, and we didn't
think it would happen,'' Lisa said. She went before the Rockdale
Girls Softball Association board and was happily surprised when the
board accepted her proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Kathi Smith, who was president of the board at the time, said
that her biggest concern was for Mandy's safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted it to be a positive experience for her, and it
worked out really well,'' Smith said. ``I think that it inspired a
lot of people. Sometimes in sports, people tend to get too caught
up in winning and losing, and it maybe put some focus on what we're
really out there doing. ... It allowed (Mandy) to participate in
something that she had never done before, and it was like she
wasn't handicapped. For a little while, she was just a normal kid
doing a normal thing.''
</P>
<P>
   And that, essentially, is what Mandy wants out of her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``My big thing is, I want to be just like everybody else,'' said
Mandy, who plans to commute to Clayton State and major in education
next year. ``I don't want to be outcast or looked at differently
just because I only have one leg or because I have a disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith doesn't look at her differently, but she can't help but
marvel. When Mandy is playing, Smith said, ``Time doesn't matter.
Things don't matter. There's the game, and you can be a part of
something that maybe can be bigger than you are for a little
while.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
