<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYPICAL DAY ON WALL STREET: STOCKS PLUNGE, THEN REBOUND
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The stock market plunged early Monday as jittery
investors dumped the technology stocks that many already agreed
were overpriced and also sold some of the so-called old economy
stocks that had actually been doing reasonably well recently.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time the market closed, the major indexes had done
what has become normal recently, rebounded, leaving the market down
only moderately. Enough investors, apparently, are still looking to
buy on the dips, despite the Federal Reserve's clear warning last
week of higher interest rates in the months ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the old economy stocks did not recover very much,
however. Among these was General Motors, which disappointed
investors by limiting the exchange of its stock for shares in its
Hughes Electronics subsidiary. GM finished down 9 3/8, or about 11
percent, at 77 5/8. It fell as low as 76 5/16.
</P>
<P>
   The morning sell-off sent the technology-heavy Nasdaq index down
217 points, or 6.4 percent. That left it below the 3,321.29 it
closed at on April 14, after a week in which the index fell a
record 25.3 percent. The Dow Jones industrial average dropped 257
points, or 2.4 percent, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
fell 38 points, or 2.7 percent. Both remained just above their
April 14 closes.
</P>
<P>
   But at the close, after investors bought up stocks from Intel
and Yahoo to Cisco Systems and eBay, the Nasdaq index finished down
just 26.19 points, or 0.77 percent, at 3,364.21.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the late rally, Monday became only the third day
in the last six weeks in which the Nasdaq composite closed with a
daily change of less than 1 percentage point. As recently as 1995,
less than one day in five ended with a change of more than 1
percent, but volatility has been rising since then.
</P>
<P>
   Led by late rallies in J.P. Morgan and IBM, the Dow Jones
industrial average closed down just 84.30 points, or 0.79 percent,
to 10,542.55. And the S&AMP;P 500, led back by AT&AMP;T and Intel, was off
6.23 points, or 0.44 percent, at 1,400.72.
</P>
<P>
   In the bond market, prices rose a little and yields, which move
in the opposite direction, slipped as some investors shifted their
money from stocks to bonds. The yield on the Treasury's 10-year
note fell to 6.44 percent, from 6.48 percent on Friday. The price,
which moves in the opposite direction from the yield, rose 12/32,
to 100 14/32. The yield on the 30-year bond fell to 6.19 percent
from 6.20 percent on Friday, while the price rose 8/32, to 100
28/32.
</P>
<P>
   And the price of crude oil for June delivery, which had popped
above $30 a barrel last week, fell $1.28, or 4.3 percent, to $28.61
a barrel after the president of OPEC said the organization of oil
producers would pump more oil to keep its price within its desired
range of $22 to $28 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the slump in all the major stock indexes was a
continuation of the selling that began last week after the Federal
Reserve raised its short-term interest rate target half a
percentage point to 6.5 percent and signaled that more rate
increases were likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are realizing that higher interest rates won't be good
for high multiple technology stocks; that technology stocks may be
sensitive to the economy,'' said Richard McCabe, chief market
analyst at Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   As the threat of higher interest rates has sunk in, analysts are
also beginning to reconsider their outlook for corporate earnings
for the S&AMP;P 500, which were spectacular in the first quarter of
this year, rising 23.5 percent from a year earlier, and are
forecast to be strong this quarter, up 18.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas McManus, the equity strategist at Banc of America
Securities, said Monday that he was cutting his forecast of S&AMP;P 500
earnings growth for this year to 12 percent from 13.7 percent. ``By
the second half of this year we expect to see far fewer positive
revisions and far more negative revisions in earnings,'' he said.
``And I don't know if the market is prepared for that.''
</P>
<P>
   McManus, a stock market bull who just four weeks ago was
recommending that investors put 80 percent of their portfolio into
equities, cut that recommendation back to 70 percent, while he
raised his bond recommendation to 30 percent and has nothing in
cash. ``Our 70/30/0 allocation is still moderately optimistic,
compared with `normal' recommendations'' of 60 percent to 65
percent of a portfolio in stocks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   What may make earnings disappointments harder for investors to
take is that earnings forecasts for the current quarter and this
year have been rising recently. According to First Call/Thomson
Financial, which collects analysts' forecasts, the earnings growth
rate forecast for the companies in the S&AMP;P 500 index has risen to
18.8 percent for the second quarter from a 16 percent prediction at
the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
   More significantly, the forecast for the second quarter has
actually climbed from 17.6 percent on March 1. Usually, analysts
trim their current-quarter earnings predictions during that quarter
by 2 percentage to 3 percentage points, as the companies give
clearer guidance on what to expect.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Barbera, the chief economist at Hoenig &AMP; Co., said,
``What people are just beginning to realize is that a second shoe
is going to drop; technology companies will have their fair share
of earnings disappointments.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbera said that some investors and analysts had argued that
the technology sector would be relatively immune to higher interest
rates because these companies had been raising their money in the
stock market, through new stock issues, or have bought other
companies using their own stock.
</P>
<P>
   But he argues that the Fed's ability to slow economic growth
will put pressure on stocks, and therefore, make it difficult for
technology companies to raise new funds or buy new companies. And
that will hurt their earnings.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although he is bullish on the near-term earnings outlook,
Richard Bernstein, director of quantitative research at Merrill
Lynch, agrees. ``I think you are going to see a lot of
disappointments soon'' in the technology sector, he said. ``What if
your strategy was growth through acquisitions and nobody wants your
stock anymore?'' he asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
