<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THIS REPEAT IS REPLETE WITH DRAMA 
</HEADLINE>
   By IRA BERKOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Miami Heat sounded like the hiss from a radiator
when it's over-steamed. Jamal Mashburn, Tim Hardaway, Alonzo
Mourning, et. al. were complaining, after an 83-82 loss in the
deciding Game 7 of their playoff series against the Knicks on
Sunday. They were charging that there was ``a conspiracy'' by the
referees and the league to make sure that the Knicks won. They
imagined that a Los Angeles-New York final series would be a
TV-ratings bonanza, a commercial aspect surely not lost on David
Stern and his minions.
</P>
<P>
   It is highly plausible that Stern, sultan of the National
Basketball Association, indeed went to bed in Westchester with a
smile on his face. But the outcome of the game had profoundly less
to do with the refereeing than it did with Miami's shooting free
throws as if heaving a medicine ball _ hitting 11 of 21 overall
from the foul line (to the Knicks' 28 for 31); or the fact that two
of its best shooters, Mashburn and Hardaway, connected on just 9 of
35 shots from the field; or that Mourning did an unfortunate
impersonation of Willie Sutton, missing a dunderheaded steal
attempt to allow his man, Patrick Ewing, a clear getaway to the
basket for the winning jam. Consider also that Pat Riley, the glass
of fashion and a basketball brain to match, called two timeouts
with 26 and 12 seconds to go and 1 point down, and was unable to
concoct a good shot for his team either time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed in their reaction,'' Jeff Van Gundy, the
Knicks' coach, said Monday of the Heat. ``They're attacking the
credibility of the league. I can understand their disappointment,
and I have a lot of respect for the Heat, but it's not right. I
think what they're saying may have a subconscious effect on the
league and the officials in our upcoming series.''
</P>
<P>
   The series beginning Tuesday night against the Pacers, that is.
It is a coach's job to clear out any mental viruses that may affect
not only his team, but those who would have influence over its
fortunes. Namely, the referees.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy doesn't want the referees bending over backward to be
nice to people like Reggie Miller (just imagine for a moment, Knick
fans, anyone trying to be nice to Reggie), and Van Gundy is taking
no chances. Referees are more or less people, Van Gundy
understands, and they don't want to be perceived as soft on the
Knicks. So he reacts to the reaction, to ward off any evil eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard for people to give credit to another team after
a loss,'' said Van Gundy. ``It's always some external force.''
</P>
<P>
   The external forces, in this case, were such aliens as Childs,
Ewing, Camby and Sprewell, fresh from their spaceship.
</P>
<P>
   As for a conspiracy, anything's possible. But when checking
conspiracies, the Heat should make an investigation in their own
arena, starting maybe with the janitor. I mean, who put the lid on
the basket so the Heat could miss five free throws in the waning,
crunch moments of the game? It wasn't Van Gundy, or any of the
three referees, that anyone saw, anyhow. But where was the janitor,
and, for that matter, the butler?
</P>
<P>
   This is the lone matter from the Miami series that Van Gundy has
any concern with, other than fatigue, of course. And having little
time to draw up schemes to outnoodle Larry Bird and his cronies.
</P>
<P>
   Can the Knicks, meanwhile, after a bruising series against
Miami, get their legs, and their lungs, in proper order to combat
the Pacers?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly. These are professionals, and, except for a
sore-ankled Allan Houston, appear reasonably sound of body. Even
that battered antique, Patrick Ewing, has tapped some spectacular
reservoir of energy to come back in the last half of the last two
games to play as well as he has ever played.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, Reggie won't let anyone's mind wander. ``I hate
the Knicks,'' he said Monday afternoon in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie says these things because he enjoys driving people nuts.
He's like the kid at the zoo who jabs a stick through the bars to
annoy the lion when he's snoozing. It also motivates Miller,
apparently, to have people abhor him. Nice work if you can get it.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the blather, he's a marvelous, clutch player. ``And
Jalen Rose is having a career year, and Mark Jackson is a great
orchestrator and the Pacers have the best 3-point shooters and best
free-throw shooting team in basketball,'' said Van Gundy. ``It's
going to be tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Heat series, this one is a rematch from last year. So a
fan may be excused his ennui. After all, same old teams, same old
rivalry _ and same old drama, suspense, intrigues, tension,
pressure and passion. ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?'' can hardly
do better. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
