<HEADLINE>
CHIEF EXECUTIVE APPOINTED AT GRUNER &AMP; JAHR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany)   By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gruner &AMP; Jahr, the publisher of seven consumer magazines in the
United States including McCall's, Fitness and Parents, has named a
chief executive, three months after the departure of its previous
chief.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel B. Brewster, the president and chief executive of
American Express Publishing, resigned from that job Monday and will
take over at Gruner &AMP; Jahr on June 5. American Express Publishing,
which is a partnership between the Time Inc. unit of Time Warner
and the American Express Co., publishes four consumer magazines,
including Food &AMP; Wine and Travel &AMP; Leisure.
</P>
<P>
   For Brewster, the challenge will be to bring vitality to a group
of magazines that are not noted for their dynamism. Because of
their subject matter, which is largely geared toward family,
fitness, interior decorating and teen-age entertainment _ they have
missed out on two of the most abundant areas of magazine
advertising: luxury goods and Internet businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Gruner &AMP; Jahr publishes more than 80 magazines around the world,
mostly in Europe. Its magazines in the United States have been
particularly vulnerable to the recent changes in the consumer
marketplace, specifically, the consolidation of newsstand
wholesalers _ a trend that has by most estimates hurt the entire
industry by driving up costs _ and the tremendous fall-off in
subscriptions that had been generated in the past by American
Family Publishers and Publishers Clearing House.
</P>
<P>
   The move to hire Brewster signals a significant shift in the
company's strategy. Bertelsmann AG, the German media company that
owns 74.9 percent of Gruner &AMP; Jahr, sold its stake in AOL Europe
last year for about $8 billion, and Brewster has been given the
task of routing a portion of that windfall into reviving the
American magazine division.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have given me an absolute commitment that they are going
to substantially invest in their core titles,'' Brewster said
Monday. ``They will give me funding to pursue acquisitions, and we
will also have sufficient resources to develop new products
internally.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the company's first acquisitions may be Inc. magazine,
executives involved in the negotiations said. Gruner &AMP; Jahr has
just entered the second round of bidding for the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Time Inc. is also negotiating to buy Inc.; the asking price is
$200 million, the executives said.
</P>
<P>
   Gruner &AMP; Jahr's turnover rate has been among the highest in the
magazine industry, according to past and current executives, with
some employees _ including the last chief executive _ departing for
Internet businesses. John Heins, the former chief executive,
resigned in February to join Netscape as a vice president for
international sales and marketing. In another recent departure,
Andreas Wiele, the company's chief operating officer, resigned on
May 9 to join Axel Springer Verlag, based in Hamburg, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Brewster is a longtime employee of Time Inc. After beginning his
career as a CNN correspondent covering Congress and as a producer
for ABC News, Brewster joined Time Inc. in 1985 and worked through
the ranks, from promotional director at People magazine to
associate publisher of Life. He has been the chief executive of
American Express Publishing since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   His replacement has not been named, but executives at American
Express said that he had recommended Ed Kelly, the publisher of the
Travel &AMP; Leisure group, which publishes Travel &AMP; Leisure and its
spinoffs, T&AMP;L Golf and Travel &AMP; Leisure Family.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
