<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN OFFICIALS HOPEFUL ABOUT IMPROVED RELATIONS WITH MAINLAND
CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan _ In their first public statements since taking
office, two of Taiwan's top security officials expressed cautious
hope Monday that relations with the mainland will gradually improve
in the wake of President Chen Shui-bian's inaugural speech and a
surprisingly nonbelligerent reply from Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   And in Beijing on Monday, officials stressed that China would be
``pragmatic'' in its dealings with Taiwan, though they still
demanded that Chen unequivocally agree that Taiwan is part of ``one
China'' under Beijing's ultimate authority.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few weeks ago, China was pillorying Chen, who in the past
advocated Taiwan's formal independence, and some experts said that
military conflict was nearly inevitable. If Taiwan officials are
relieved and pleased by how well their first days have gone and by
the sudden shift in mood, they were coy about it in interviews
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In his inaugural address on Saturday, Chen promised not to
declare independence and made soothing comments about a shared
history and culture. In a cryptic statement that the officials
refused to elaborate on Monday, he referred to the ``question of a
possible future `one China.'''
</P>
<P>
   Beijing, after accusing Chen of being evasive, replied in a
vague statement of its own that now-frozen talks might resume if
the two sides could ``express in their own way orally'' their
support for the ``one China'' principle.
</P>
<P>
   More tangibly, both sides seem intent on allowing direct
commerce across the Taiwan Strait, perhaps as part of a trade
agreement as they both enter the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not disappointed'' by Beijing's response was how Tsai
Ing-wen, the new head of Taipei's Mainland Affairs Council, put it
Monday. ``My own reading,'' she said, ``is that they have softened
their position somewhat to try and find ways to move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Chiou I-jen, deputy chief of Taiwan's National Security Council
and a member of Chen's inner circle, would say only, ``At least the
situation has calmed down.''
</P>
<P>
   In separate interviews, both officials laid out the same
best-case vision: that by expanding economic, cultural and other
ties through negotiation, the two sides could, as Tsai put it,
``build the confidence we need to address the political issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen's speech, she asserted, had ``generated some good
momentum,'' and she added that ``we'll try to do something to
maintain that momentum'' but refused to give examples.
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing Monday, officials told reporters that China would be
``pragmatic'' in its approach to Taiwan, that it understood the
political constraints on Chen and would watch to see if he moves
toward accepting the idea of ``one China.''
</P>
<P>
   But they were unyielding on the meaning of that term, saying,
``There is only one China and Taiwan is part of China, and the
government of the People's Republic is the only legal government of
China.''
</P>
</TEXT>
