<HEADER>
A2782 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-VIGNETTE-COX     05-22 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIGNETTE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vignette Corp. buy software maker for $1.7 billion
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In what would be the largest acquisition by an
Austin company, Vignette Corp. said Monday it will pay $1.7 billion
for a small California software maker that will extend the reach of
its e-commerce software.
</P>
<P>
   But in another indication of Wall Street's newfound skepticism
in Internet-related stocks, Vignette shares plunged 20.4 percent,
or $8.94, to close at $34.88 in Nasdaq trading. They had fallen as
low as $30.75.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts who follow Vignette agreed that OnDisplay adds
important features to Vignette's e-business platform. But some said
they were puzzled by the pricetag on a company that lost nearly $17
million in 1999 on revenues of only $11 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty frothy deal,'' said Bill Chappell of the
Robinson-Humphrey equities firm in Atlanta. ``I'm a little
surprised by the price,'' he said, adding, ``but that doesn't mean
it's not a strategic fit.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge of putting a rational value on Internet-based
startups has dogged venture capitalists, stock underwriters and
investors since the Internet phenomenon captured investors'
attention a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It was only this spring that investors began taking a hard look
at a company's prospects for profitability, which has a lot to do
with the the 35 percent Nasdaq correction since March 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last six weeks, any company that made a purchase has
gotten creamed,'' said Fred Bush of Tejas Securities in Austin.
``People are starting to be more value focused.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the $1.7 billion for OnDisplay is 50 times the
company's expected revenue this year.
</P>
<P>
   Kent Antley, who heads the technology practice for the Atlanta
law firm of Southerland, Asbill and Brennan, said there is too
little history to measure what Internet companies are worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is like a once-in-a-century phenomenon, and
people are willing to take extreme risk to be one of the big
players in 15 years,'' Antley said. ``You see in these values just
how much Vignette is gambling.''
</P>
<P>
   Vignette's stock was also hurt by bad timing. The Nasdaq
composite index on Monday dipped to its lowest point this year
before eaking out a fractional gain late in the day.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq closed down 26.19 at 3,364.21. At its low Monday, the
Nasdaq was off nearly 218 points at 3,172.65 _ a level not seen
since last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Vignette Chief Executive Greg Peters called the deal ``landscape
changing.'' The Austin company is regarded as a leader at helping
medium and large companies to establish online businesses, manage
how their Web sites look and function and interact smoothly with
customers.
</P>
<P>
   OnDisplay, based in San Ramon, Calif., is focused on the part of
e-commerce that is invisible to the end-user, but no less important
to the success of an online business.
</P>
<P>
   As ``back-office'' technology, the company's software performs
such tasks as making sure that supplies of products that appear on
the Web site are available in inventory, and it automatically bills
the customer for the purchase. In addition, it can direct the sale
to a Web-site's lowest-cost supplier of products and assign the
lowest-cost shipper to deliver it, said Erik Josowitz, Vignette's
vice president of product strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always manage the customer-relationship side, which means,
when you visit a company's Web site, how your personalize it, shop,
buy and order,'' Josowitz said. ``But it's necessary that those
things connect to something.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal must be approved by OnDisplay's shareholders, who will
receive 1.58 Vignette shares for each share of OnDisplay. Shares of
OnDisplay Inc., the fourth company Vignette has acquired in the
past year, closed up 88 cents at $54.13 on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Peters, in an interview from San Ramon where he was visiting
OnDisplay's employees, said the two companies considered where the
e-business market is headed and what OnDisplay's contribution would
be worth.
</P>
<P>
   It's an optimistic view, shared by many analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Internet consulting company Forrester Research, for instance,
estimates that e-business market will grow to $1.3 trillion in
2003, up from $43 billion two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   As the largest acquisition by an Austin company, the deal also
runs counter to a trend of local companies being gobbled up by
bigger businesses from others states or, sometimes, other
countries.
</P>
<P>
   At $1.7 billion, which is based on Friday's closing prices for
shares in both companies, the deal is bigger than several recent
acquisitions that changed Austin's technology industry. In 1996,
IBM acquired Tivoli Systems for $743 million and Computer Sciences
Corp. bought Austin's Continuum Corp. for $1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, GEC of London paid for Tracor Corp., an Austin
defense-technology company.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest acquisition involving an Austin company came last
year, when Cincinnati Bell Inc. paid $3.2 billion for IXC Inc., a
telecom company that had fiber-optic cable buried in key U.S.
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Vignette wasn't the only company whose acquisition plans got
hammered by Wall Street on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In another deal between electronic-commerce companies,
webMethods Inc. of Fairfax, Va. said it would acquire Active
Software in a stock deal valued at $1.3 billion. WebMethods lost
$15, or 17.2 percent, to close at $72, while Active Software
slipped 92 cents to close at 32.8.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Jerry Mahoney at jmahoney(at)statesman.com or
445-3642.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
