<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-ELECTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOUBT IS CAST ON CREDIBLE ELECTIONS IN ZIMABWE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ Widespread political violence and unfair
electoral practices ruled out the possibility of credible
democratic elections in Zimbabwe, an international delegation
concluded Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe's government received another blow, when the nation's
highest court threw out charges against two of President Robert
Mugabe's severest press critics.
</P>
<P>
   The National Democratic Institute, fielding a team of
representatives from five African countries as well as the United
States and Canada, said the run-up to Zimbabwe's parliamentary
elections, due to be held June 24-25, was marred by ``acute
political polarization and intolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only had the southern African nation failed to meet its own
constitutional Declaration of Rights, the delegation found, but it
also had violated international conventions on human rights.
</P>
<P>
   At least 23 people have been killed and thousands more have been
badly beaten in politically inspired attacks over the past three
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The violence has created an atmosphere of anxiety and fear. It
has substantially restricted the exercise of freedoms of opinion,
expression, association, assembly, and movement, as well as the
right to be secure from physical bodily harm due to political
affiliation,'' the delegation stated. ``Immediate and concerted
efforts are therefore required to make improvements to the
political environment.''
</P>
<P>
   The government, against which the team lodged most of its
accusations, dismissed the report. ``When we had independent
elections in 1980, we had worse violence than this, and those
elections were declared free and fair,'' said Information Minister
Chenhamo Chimutengwende.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, Zimbabwe's highest tribunal threw out a government
attempt to prosecute two local journalists for stirring ``alarm and
despondency.'' Ray Choto and Mark Chavunduka, both of the Standard
newspaper, were detained 17 months ago and tortured for two weeks
after publishing a story of a possible military coup. The Supreme
Court ruled that the state's case against them was
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Chavunduka, the Standard's editor, is currently completing a
year at Harvard as a Nieman fellow.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling was hailed both as a triumph of the rule of law and a
victory for Zimbabwe's beleaguered media, which have been
repeatedly threatened and harassed in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Violence began three months ago, shortly after the fledgling
Movement for Democratic Change rallied voters to reject Mugabe's
draft constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe responded by exploiting the highly emotional issue of
land, casting the opposition as a puppet of the white minority and
unleashing his supporters against white commercial farmers.
Pro-government mobs have invaded more than 1,300 farms since late
February, violently intimidating black farmworkers into pledging
support for Mugabe's party. In recent weeks, university teachers,
students, and prominent businessmen have also come under attack.
</P>
<P>
   Worried about Zimbabwe's instability, South African President
Thabo Mbeki has urged the international community to fund land
reform in Zimbabwe, where the whites hold a vast majority of the
country's best farmland. Mbeki met with President Clinton Monday at
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Western donors have tied aid for land reform to peaceful
elections, but so far Mugabe has done little to end the violence.
Nor has he played by fair electoral rules, analysts said. The
government has so far failed to release the new voter rolls and
voter-district maps, making it impossible for parties to nominate
parliamentary candidates across the country ahead of the May 29
registration deadline.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition party filed a petition with the High Court to
force the state to release the voter information and extend the
nomination period.
</P>
<P>
   The delegation urged Mugabe to end the violence, promote
dialogue among competing parties to ensure a safe campaign
environment, release the voter rolls, and remove media bias. In the
past month, according to the local Media Monitoring Project, 93
percent of voices in political stories on local television news
have been aligned with the ruling party. The state owns the only TV
broadcasting service.
</P>
<P>
   Against this backdrop, Bill Kovach, head of the Nieman
fellowship program at Harvard, applauded the Supreme Court's ruling
in favor of Choto and Chavunduka. ``The timing is great,'' he said.
``It is encouraging to see the rule of law still trying to assert
itself'' in Zimbabwe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
