<HEADLINE>
OAS SUSPENDS ELECTION MONITORING IN PERU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA _ Throwing Peru's troubled presidential election into even
deeper turmoil, the Organization of American States on Monday
suspended its election monitoring here because of concerns about
fraud and a faulty computerized vote-counting system.
</P>
<P>
   The OAS announced its decision the same day that Alejandro
Toledo, the US-trained business school professor who has mounted a
heated challenge to President Alberto K. Fujimori, submitted a
letter to elections officials formally withdrawing from Sunday's
runoff vote. The move prompted one high-ranking Peruvian elections
official to declare that Toledo had ``forfeited'' the race and
handed victory to Fujimori.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued by the organization's office in Lima, the
OAS said it decided to end the work of its 20 observers in Peru
``because of a lack of consistency and precision observed'' in the
National Office of Elections Processes, the country's main voting
agency.
</P>
<P>
   Eduardo Stein, the former Guatemalan foreign minister who heads
the observation team in Peru, told reporters Monday afternoon
outside the US Embassy that the organization ``is not leaving the
country, only asking our workers to temporarily abstain from their
work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been consistently documenting problems in the general
management of the electoral procedures that could compromise the
legitimacy of the vote on the day that has been designated,'' Stein
said, adding that a more detailed report of their concerns would be
released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Since the first round of elections was held on April 9, the OAS
and other international observer groups, most of them from the
United States, have complained of voting irregularities largely
attributed to Fujimori's government.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the OAS, which was invited by Fujimori to oversee the
elections, publicly asked the national voting agency to postpone
the runoff vote, scheduled for Sunday, to correct technical
problems in the agency's computer system. On Thursday, Toledo
announced his withdrawal from Sunday's vote, calling for a later
election date and for supporters to withhold their vote as an act
of protest.
</P>
<P>
   The events of the past week have thrown the country's elections
into a dizzying tailspin, causing widespread confusion among
voters, uncertainty among investors, anger at the observers, and
concerns among officials from the United States and other countries
about Peru's democratic process.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the State Department said it supported the OAS
decision and called for Peruvian officials to take measures to
ensure a fair vote. Meanwhile, another US-based observer group said
it has put its plans to send observers to Peru on hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not boarding any planes right now, but we're hoping
there'll be more dialogue among everyone,'' said Kenneth Wollack,
president of the National Democratic Institute, which planned to
send about 20 observers to Peru. ``Postponing an election is
preferable to one that is fatally flawed whether in Peru or any
other country.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo campaign officials delivered a letter to the National
Office of Elections Processes Monday afternoon detailing the
challenger's decision to pull out of the race unless the date is
changed to mid-June and guarantees are made for clean elections.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Bringas, a juror for the elections office, told the
Associated Press Monday afternoon that Toledo's letter was
equivalent to a ``forfeit'' and that by default Fujimori should be
declared the winner.
</P>
<P>
   Observers and Peruvian election officials are at odds over a
vote-counting computer system, which was tested on Sunday in front
of observers and journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Later that evening, Peruvian officials declared the test a
success. The OAS, however, said serious problems still existed _
mostly that the software being used could not properly transmit
simulated data to the central offices from outside computers and
therefore could not adequately count the votes.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori, who is seeking a third term, won the first round of
voting with 49 percent to Toledo's 40. Fujimori has refused to
change Sunday's vote and did not offer immediate comment on
Monday's developments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
