<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2791 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-REACT-     05-22 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-REACT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEED OF BORDER COLLAPSE SURPRISES ISRAELIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALIZA MARCUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEL AVIV _ Ehud Barak rose to power a year ago with a pledge to
end Israel's bloody, 22-year occupation of southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   But no one expected it to end this way.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's withdrawal Monday from its security zone in southern
Lebanon looked more like a disorganized rout as members of its
allied militia fled their posts ahead and Israelis living near the
border were ordered into bomb shelters.
</P>
<P>
   The speed at which the situation deteriorated appeared to
surprise everyone, including Prime Minister Barak, who convened an
emergency Cabinet meeting to discuss the rapidly changing situation
in an area long under Israeli control.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are expecting several difficult days,'' Barak told state
television last night, ``but we know how to respond soundly to
every possible attack.''
</P>
<P>
   The rapid deployment of Hezbollah forces into areas abandoned by
Israel and its proxy Lebanese militia has made Lebanon a much more
dangerous place for Israeli forces, prompting discussion of moving
up the deadline for the final pullout from July 7.
</P>
<P>
   But even as Hezbollah raised its flags over 14 villages and
South Lebanon Army soldiers gave themselves up to the rebel group,
Israeli jets strafed a former Israeli military position to destroy
tanks and other heavy equipment left behind by fleeing SLA
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Two Lebanese civilians were reported killed in the bombing
raids, prompting fears of retaliatory strikes by Hezbollah
guerrillas, who in some areas are now just a mile away from
Israel's northern border. The Israeli military ordered people in
northern towns into bomb shelters as a precaution.
</P>
<P>
   The rapid breakdown of Israel's control over south Lebanon, and
the speed with which Hezbollah fighters are taking over, has
stunned not only Israelis but south Lebanese, many of whom had
fought for Israel for years against the Hezbollah militants, who
are backed by Syria and Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of relatives of men in the Israeli-financed and armed
South Lebanon Army besieged border crossing points, begging for
refuge in Israel. Israeli officials have indicated that SLA
fighters and their relatives will be resettled in Israel, but it
was unclear if those at the border would be allowed in.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials expressed dismay that UN forces, stationed in
south Lebanon since Israeli forces first entered in 1978, did not
stop the guerrillas from taking over the newly abandoned areas.
</P>
<P>
   The accelerating collapse of the so-called security zone
increased pressure on UN special envoy Terje Roed-Larsen to put in
place security arrangements after the Israeli withdrawal. While UN
Secretary General Kofi Annan announced plans Monday to increase the
UN troop presence, UN officials said any increase would come only
after a final Israeli pullout had been confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Israel, weary of steady troop losses from its occupation, had
initially wanted to withdraw as part of a peace deal with Lebanon
and Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon. When that proved
impossible, Israel hoped that either the United Nations would move
in to police the areas or that the Lebanese army would re-establish
control over south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   But the sight of Hezbollah fighters and sympathizers waving
victory signs as they plundered abandoned outposts for weapons was
a reminder of the risks entailed in withdrawing. The unilateral
pullout is popular among Israelis, except for those who live in the
northern border communities.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's deputy defense minister warned that Israeli troops
could be sent back in if its border communities were attacked.
Although few military specialists said that Israel would stage
another full-scale invasion like the one in 1982, there is little
to keep Israel from cross-border retaliatory raids as long as it
has no peace treaty with Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone wants to avert the need for us to go in again, the
way to do that is to keep Hezbollah away from the border,'' Ephraim
Sneh, the deputy defense minister, told Israel army radio.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah has always said that it is fighting to oust Israel
from south Lebanon, but the group's spiritual leader has also
indicated that the rebels may keep fighting even after Israel
withdraws.
</P>
<P>
   For the second day in a row, Hezbollah rocketed an Israeli post
in an area called the Sheeba Farms near the Israeli-occupied Golan
Heights, part of its campaign to force Israeli forces to also
withdraw from a strip of territory on the Golan heights that
Hezbollah says is part of Lebanon.
</P>
</TEXT>
