<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2792 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-OHAIR-COX     05-22 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHAIR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Burglars take the stand
 &HT;    By Andrea Ball
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The 1995 robbery began poorly, producing only an
old television that couldn't be pawned. So the three San Antonio
crooks gave it another shot.
</P>
<P>
   They distracted the clerk at the storage facility on Burnet Road
in North Austin, chose a second unit and opened its silver Master
lock with an illegal skeleton key.
</P>
<P>
   This time they hit it big: $500,000 in gold coins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was in a black suitcase,'' Joe Cortez, one of the burglars,
testified in federal court Monday. ``We unzipped it and it was full
of gold coins.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities say the coins belonged to atheist leader
Madalyn O'Hair, son Jon Garth Murray and granddaughter Robin
Murray-O'Hair _ and that the three burglars unwittingly walked off
with the spoils of a kidnapping plot that left the O'Hairs dead.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of the stolen gold came out Monday as the kidnapping
trial of Gary Paul Karr entered its second week.
</P>
<P>
   Karr, 52, is charged with holding the family hostage for the
$500,000 in gold. Prosecutors have continued to build their case by
following the money trail they say explains the O'Hairs 1995
disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Cortez, Jamie Valdes and Joe Cardenas told jurors how
they discovered the gold and how they spent it. All three were
granted immunity for admitting to the theft.
</P>
<P>
   It was Oct. 3, 1995, and high school buddies Cortez and Valdes
were looking for an easy score. Cortez had a skeleton key that
could open Master locks, so they headed to Austin to break into
storage units. They recruited Cardenas, a casual acquaintance, to
drive.
</P>
<P>
   O.J. Simpson's acquittal was on the radio as the trio searched
for a storage facility. They stopped at the first one they saw and,
after the unsuccessful theft of the TV, walked away with a black
suitcase filled with $500,000 in shimmering American Eagles,
Canadian Maple Leafs and South African Krugerrands.
</P>
<P>
   In nonchalant testimony, the burglars talked about driving to a
fast food restaurant and opening the suitcase in the trunk of their
car. After finding the gold, they went in for hamburgers.
</P>
<P>
   A trip to a bookstore revealed that each coin was worth between
$300 and $400. They returned home, divvied up the loot and parted
ways, Cortez testified Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said I'd see (Valdes) when the money ran out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The crooks traded the gold for cash in jewelry and coin stores
across San Antonio, often using friends to divert attention from
themselves. They never cashed in more than $10,000 at a time to
avoid filing a report with the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   Then they started spending. Cars, black leather couches, big
screen televisions, clothing, gold necklaces, diamond rings, $1,500
dollar watches. Cortez treated a half-dozen friends to a four-day
trip to Las Vegas. Cardenas bought a Mitsubishi Eclipse. Valdes
paid his girlfriend to stay home from work.
</P>
<P>
   And they all went to strip clubs. A lot of them, each man
spending $800 to $1,500 a night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd tip (the dancers) and buy drinks for them and everyone,''
Valdes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you didn't get receipts to prove how you spent the money?''
asked Tom Mills, Karr's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could go ask them. They still remember me,'' Valdes said
as the jury laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Within two years, the men had wasted away their sudden fortune.
By the time the FBI came calling in 1999, they had sold their
gold-funded goodies, saying they needed the money.
</P>
<P>
   Karr's lawyers sought to paint the three burglars as
inconsistent witnesses whose testimony was tainted by the immunity
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the federal trial has focused on David Waters, the
O'Hairs' former office manager whom prosecutors say masterminded
the kidnapping and killed the family. Karr, they say, helped hold
the family hostage.
</P>
<P>
   But Karr's attorneys claim the Michigan man was hired to guard
the family as they planned to flee the country. Plagued with IRS
troubles, the O'Hairs had often spoken of escaping to New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair's son, William Murray, testified Monday that he believed
those were empty threats and that his mother had a love-hate
relationship with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``She loved to hate it and would make disparaging remarks about
it,'' said Murray, who was estranged from his family at the time of
their disappearance. ``But it also gave her access to hundreds of
thousands _ sometimes millions _ of dollars each year that she
couldn't get anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen witnesses testified Monday in a fast-paced trial that
could go to the jury early next week. Fifteen prosecution remain to
be called. Defense attorneys expect their case to take up to three
days.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Andrea Ball at aball(at)statesman.com or
912-2506.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
