<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2794 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MAGELLAN-TECH-BOS &LR;      05-22 0435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGELLAN-TECH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIDELITY MAGELLAN BOUGHT TECH STOCKS JUST BEFORE FALL-OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Fidelity Magellan fund manager Robert Stansky
introduced more than 50 high-tech stocks to his portfolio in the
first quarter, according to the massive fund's annual report.
</P>
<P>
   Stansky added such names as Sycamore Networks, Akamai
Technologies, Veritas Software, CMGI, and Priceline.com during the
period ended March 31. All those stocks have shed from 20 percent
to 51 percent of their value since the end of the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the decline in many new technology stocks since March
10, Stansky wrote in the report that several stocks, including
Sycamore, Juniper Networks, and Redback Networks, had contributed
to the fund's gains in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   None of the bets on these young companies was large relative to
the size of the fund, which had assets of $109 billion on March 31.
Stansky bought $818,230 worth of Juniper and $314,683 worth of
Sycamore, his biggest plays among the new stocks in the fund.
</P>
<P>
   Stansky said in the report he relied in part on market
psychology to judge the young technology stocks. ``I had to
evaluate how the market might reward those with the brightest
potential long into the future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What's not clear is whether Stansky has stuck with those
volatile picks since the market fell. Fidelity declined to comment
on the fund's holdings, which are made public twice a year.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Lowell, an independent Fidelity watcher at
FidelityInvestor.com, noted, ``It sure sounds like you've got a
commitment to the group.'' He said Stansky had raised Magellan's
high-tech exposure to 35.2 percent at March 31 from 22.1 percent
six months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the first quarter, Magellan had a return of 4.85
percent year-to-date. Through Friday, the fund was down 3.9 percent
for the year _ better than the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index,
Stansky's benchmark, which was down 4.24 percent. The Nasdaq
Composite index, home to most upstart technology stocks, was down
16.68 percent through Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Several of Stansky's holdings likely have rewarded investors. To
name two, Lycos and Arrowpoint recently agreed to be acquired in
multibillion-dollar deals.
</P>
<P>
   Stansky said he thought many stocks were still pricey at the
time of the report, including technology stocks and cyclical
stocks. Stansky said, ``Strong growth in the US economy is long in
the tooth. At some point, that growth will slow, which could slow
the communications and Internet expansion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
