<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   SRI LANKA: PAPER BANNED
</P>
<P>
   In a continuing crackdown on its free press, the government has
banned The Sunday Leader for violating censorship laws. Rigorous
restrictions on reporting the news have been put in place as the
army attempts to fight off a critical campaign for the Jaffna
Peninsula by the Tamil Tiger rebels.
</P>
<P>
   KASHMIR: SEPARATISTS CRY MURDER
</P>
<P>
   Muslim separatist leaders have called for a three-day hunger
strike to protest what they say is the murder of prisoners by state
authorities. There have been 67 custodial killings since early
January, the separatists say. India has often denied the abuses
take place in such high numbers.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: STORM ON `NAZI' REMARK
</P>
<P>
   Interior Minister Jean-Pierre Chevenement has apologized for
saying Germany has not yet been ``cured'' of its Nazi past. The
remark in a television interview caused a political storm, with
French politicians from a range of parties denouncing the leftist
and often outspoken minister, who was discussing a German proposal
for restructuring the European Union. Chevenement said the proposal
showed that deep down, Germany was ``still dreaming of the Holy
Roman Empire,'' adding, ``It hasn't cured itself of its past
derailment into Nazism.''
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: CASH STRIKE CONTINUES
</P>
<P>
   A two-week-old strike of armored truck security guards that has
left thousands of automatic teller machines without cash is likely
to continue for a while. The strikers rejected a settlement
proposal after 20 hours of talks. Special measures have been put in
place allowing banks to replenish automatic tellers on their own.
But many machines remain empty.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA: 143 KOSOVARS SENTENCED
</P>
<P>
   A court in Nis sentenced 143 Kosovo Albanians to prison terms
ranging from seven to 13 years for terrorism in the biggest mass
trial of people arrested during the NATO air campaign last year.
The men, among them two minors, denied the charges and said they
were rounded up arbitrarily in the town of Djakovica.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: MILLENNIUM DOME'S TROUBLES
</P>
<P>
   Five months after it opened, the troubled Millennium Dome
secured a loan of $45 million in National Lottery funds to avoid
bankruptcy and early closing. The attraction by the River Thames
has already received some $800 million in public funding, but has
been unable to draw the crowds to pay its own way. The dome's
management says it expects 6 million to 7 million visitors this
year, compared with an initial forecast of 12 million.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: OCALAN REPORTED AILING
</P>
<P>
   The health of the imprisoned Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah
Ocalan is ``rapidly deteriorating,'' his brother Osman said. He
said the prisoner had trouble breathing and had lost his senses of
smell and taste because he was kept in a damp and stuffy cell 22
hours a day. He warned of ``serious agitation'' if Turkish
officials do not take steps to restore his brother's health.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: IRAN TIES WORSEN
</P>
<P>
   Relations between Turkey and neighboring Iran worsened in the
wake of charges that Iranian militants might have been responsible
for the murders of several secular Turks. Iran protested the arrest
of many Iranians in ``violent and orchestrated'' raids in Turkey.
Iran is among the most orthodox Muslim countries, while Turkey is
among the most tolerant.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   PARAGUAY: 70 HELD IN COUP BID
</P>
<P>
   More than 70 people, mostly military and police officers, have
been arrested and many others, including the local correspondent of
Agence France-Presse and two radio station owners, are facing
criminal charges on suspicion they were involved in a failed coup
attempt early Friday. President Luis Gonzalez Macchi ordered the
roundup under emergency powers granted him by Congress, but Gen.
Lino Oviedo, the former army chief the coup plotters supported,
remains at large.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: BORDER MOVE HAILED
</P>
<P>
   Canada has hailed a Clinton administration move to change a law
that would have required recording the names of all people crossing
the United States-Canada border. Canadians and legislators from
American border states feared that the 1996 provision, which has
never been put put into effect, would cause huge traffic delays at
the border. Every day $1 billion worth of goods cross the border
and every year 200 million people make the crossing.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: TV DEBATE IN DOUBT
</P>
<P>
   The second of two nationally broadcast debates, scheduled to
bring the three leading presidential candidates for the July 2
balloting together on Tuesday, has been thrown into doubt. After
rancorous negotiations, the candidates canceled the encounter and
blamed each other for the collapse. But leaders urged the
candidates to seek agreement on a format, and talks were
continuing.
</P>
</TEXT>
