<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2799 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-PA-PLANE-CRASH-NYT &LR;      05-22 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PA-PLANE-CRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LACK OF `BLACK BOX' HAMPERS INQUIRY IN PENNSYLVANIA CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The cockpit voice recorder was not working in the
twin-engine turboprop that crashed near Scranton, Pa., on Sunday
morning, and apparently never worked, because it was the wrong
model for that airplane, the National Transportation Safety Board
said Monday. And the plane did not carry a flight data recorder,
the other kind of ``black box.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This seriously hampers the investigation, let's face it,''
said George W. Black Jr., the safety board member assigned to the
crash scene, as investigators looked for clues that could explain
why the plane, on a flight from Atlantic City, crashed as it made
its second approach to the Wilkes-Barre/Scranton International
Airport, killing all 19 people aboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're now reduced on this accident to having only radar data
and whatever information we can glean from that,'' along with
statements from witnesses, Black said. The investigators also have
statements from a crew member to an air traffic controller,
including, ``we've lost both engines.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators continued to analyze the wreckage Monday, and were
seeking to retrieve fuel samples from the soil, trying to explain
why the engines appeared to have failed. A preliminary analysis of
a sample taken from the truck used to refuel the plane found no
problem. The truck was at Republic Airport, in Farmingdale, N.Y.;
the plane was operated by Executive Airlines, which is based there,
and was being flown as a charter flight.
</P>
<P>
   The plane was a BAE Jetstream 31, which is popular with commuter
airlines, and in that role it must carry a cockpit voice recorder
and a flight data recorder. The voice recorder also captures
cockpit sounds, including engine pitch. Black said investigators
now hoped to get that information from tapes of the pilots'
conversations with air traffic controllers.
</P>
<P>
   The flight data recorder captures engine performance, and, in
some cases, records warnings as they are issued to the crew. Under
Federal Aviation Administration rules, planes with six or more
passenger seats and for which two pilots are required must have
cockpit voice recorders, but charters do not have to have flight
data recorders.
</P>
<P>
   Black said that the voice recorder on the plane that crashed
needed 120 volts alternating current, but that the plane supplied
28 volts direct current.
</P>
<P>
   Other Jetstream 31's carry voice recorders with an inverter, a
device that turns direct current into alternating current. But this
one did not, Black said, and that would have been obvious every
time the recorder was tested. Federal regulations require the
planes to be equipped with a test device that indicates if the
recorder is working.
</P>
<P>
   An airline that flies the Jetstream 31 said Monday that its
procedures call for checking the cockpit voice recorder before the
first flight each day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard people say that the flight data recorder tells you
what happens and sometimes, if you're lucky, the cockpit voice
recorder tells you why something happened,'' Black said. ``So now
we don't have what happened because we have no data recorder and we
also do not have the voice recorder, which might have explained to
us some of the conversations between the crew during this last part
of the flight.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are trying to understand why both engines failed.
Failure of a single engine is unusual, but both at once is
extremely rare. Of the many possibilities, a flight data recorder
and cockpit voice recorder together might have made clear what
happened; for example, if one engine faltered and the crew tried to
shut it down but mistakenly turned off the wrong engine.
</P>
<P>
   Turboprops are essentially jet engines with a propeller attached
and have about the same reliability as other jet engines, in
contrast to the piston-driven engines common in single-engine
planes. As Black said Monday, ``one of the reasons for having two
engines is so that you can have two almost totally independent
systems, separate fuel feeds, separate ignition systems, just as
this kind of a backup.''
</P>
<P>
   The fire after the crash is an indication that the plane still
had fuel aboard, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time the safety board has found problems
with black boxes. After a Boeing 747 operated by Tower Air slid off
a snowy runway at Kennedy Airport in 1995, investigators found that
its flight data recorder was scrambling the data.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the crashes that the safety board investigates are of
planes with no recorders, because they are privately owned, general
aviation planes. But the results of those investigations are often
less authoritative than those with better data.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
