<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2801 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-OPEN-QUALIFYING-C     05-22 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-QUALIFYING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hopefuls try to qualify for U.S. Open
 &HT;    By John Manasso
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The golfers all came out to the U.S. Open local
qualifier at Braelinn Golf Club in Peachtree City with different
variations on the same theme.
</P>
<P>
   Some came not to embarrass themselves. Some came with the idea
of making history. Some came to get more tournament practice. Some
came because they like playing with the ''local hotshots.''
</P>
<P>
   But they all held out for the dream _ to earn one of the 88
slots open to qualifiers for this year's U.S. Open at Pebble Beach
next month. From Braelinn, the top 11 out of a field of 146 golfers
advanced to the sectional, which is June 6 at Roswell's Sittindown
Creek.
</P>
<P>
   The sectional is much more rigorous. The sectional is a one-day,
36-hole tournament with a field that includes players who were
exempt from the local qualifier, including many who have PGA Tour
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the elusive idea of the average Joe making the U.S.
Open remains.
</P>
<P>
   ''Oh, man, a bunch of times,'' Alvin Jackson said of the
prospect of making the field at Pebble Beach. Jackson, who shot a
75 at Braelinn, is a former college basketball player who was
drafted in the sixth round by the Utah Jazz in 1981. Golf is his
new game when he isn't teaching physical education class at Rosa
Taylor Elementary in Macon. ''You just don't know. (Making the
Open) would be nice, trust me.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Golf Association holds nearly 100 local qualifying
tournaments throughout the country, offering club pros, amateurs
and golfers on the mini-tours, such as Hooters and buy.com
(formerly Nike), the chance to make the Open.
</P>
<P>
   All they have to put up is $100. This year, a record 8,457
golfers throughout the country signed up. That's more than 500 than
competed last year.
</P>
<P>
   As golf continues to boom in popularity, these qualifiers have
become more select and they're not as ''Open'' as they once were.
Gone are the days when any local hacker could sign up. The ones at
Braelinn all had to have a handicaps of 1.4 or less.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, the Sunday golfer is a rarity. The most common
golfers at the local qualifiers are the ones who play the most:
high school, college, club and touring pro golfers.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the qualifiers have become so popular that Braelinn
could not handle all of those who signed up. Ninety other golfers
played at Griffin Country Club, with the top six moving on.
</P>
<P>
   The low medalist at Braelinn was Javier Sanchez, who qualified
for four consecutive U.S. Opens from 1993 to 1996. Sanchez fired a
7-under 65.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez said he was told in 1996 by USGA officials that he was
the first player to qualify four years in a row by going all the
way through the local qualifiers. If he qualifies through
Sittindown Creek _ the same course he qualified through in 1994 and
1996 _ five times also would be a record.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sure no one has done it five times and I'm hoping to be
the one to do it,'' Sanchez said.
</P>
<P>
   Four qualifiers at Braelinn made it without a playoff. They were
Chip Drury (66), Roland Thatcher (67), Charles Howell (68), Thomas
Roddy (68). Eight others tied at 69 and went to a playoff for six
spots.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Bolli, Reid Edstrom, Ryan Hybl, Chip Deason, Matt
Weibring and Bill McDonald were the others. McDonald escaped after
four holes, with Brian Duncan, 16, of Greenville, S.C. Duncan, who
was a member of the final threesome to come off, shot a 31 _ the
low 9-hole score of the day _ on the back nine to make the playoff.
</P>
<P>
   The six Griffin qualifiers were West Latimer (66), Jimmy
Johnston (67), Takeshi Mitsunaga (67), Don Wright (70), Rich Taylor
(70) and Heath Slocum (71), who defeated two others in a four-hole
playoff.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more recognizable names at Braelinn was that of Matt
Weibring, a sophomore on Georgia Tech's team whose father D.A.
plays on the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Weibring said his father is exempt for the Open and is hoping
they can become only the second father-son pair to make the Open
after Jack and Gary Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't get to see him so often,'' Weibring said. ''He's
designing courses and playing and I'm at school. We're always going
our different ways. It would be cool to spend a week with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike a player of Weibring's pedigree, David Nell, 48, of
Sharpsburg plays only once a week. Nell, a warehouse clerk in Union
City, called himself, ''the tinnest of tin cups.''
</P>
<P>
   In 14 or 15 years, he has made it to the sectional once. He shot
a 76 at Braelinn.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was fun,'' Nell said of the sectional. ''I got to see some
of the Tour players, a couple of guys I've heard of and read about.
I get a kick out of some of the guys I play with _ the local
hotshots and college players.''
</P>
<P>
   While Nell makes golf his hobby, Kyle Ritter, 26, of Canton
hopes to make it his career. Ritter, a former Illinois State
player, works part-time at Townlake Hills in Woodstock and hopes to
get good enough to get a sponsorship on one of the mini tours.
</P>
<P>
   ''I enjoy seeing the better golfers to see what it takes,''
Ritter said.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Lawson, a sophomore at nearby Starr's Mill, also got a
chance to see what it takes, competing in his first qualifier.
Lawson was hopeful after making the turn at 1-under, but he
finished with a 2-over 74. He lives less than a mile from Braelinn
and said he plays it ''every other day.'' U.S. Open dreams aside,
he was just seeking not to embarrass himself.
</P>
<P>
   Did he accomplish that?
</P>
<P>
   ''That's debatable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
