u f BC-TECH-MERGERS-NYT &LR;      05-22 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-MERGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO MERGERS HIGHLIGHT E-COMMERCE TRENDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Va., Calif., Texas)   By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The consolidation of the business-to-business
software market accelerated Monday with two big deals. The Vignette
Corp. said it was acquiring OnDisplay Inc. in a $1.7 billion stock
swap, while WebMethods Inc. is buying Active Software Inc. in a
stock deal valued at $1.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The four companies specialize in software that seeks to
integrate business processes within companies or transactions
between companies. Because this task requires multiple
capabilities, analysts say there will be more such mergers as
competitors strive to offer a complete package. Although most of
the companies pursuing this market are small start-ups, IBM,
Microsoft, Oracle and other heavyweights have indicated they will
have competing offerings.
</P>
<P>
   ``As B-to-B technology matures and advances, customers are
asking more of each individual vendor,'' said Clark Spurrier, a
principal with Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, which advised both
Vignette and WebMethods. ``This is not just layering and added
functionality. It's expanding into new product categories.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Vignette fell $8.9375, to $34.875, while OnDisplay
rose 87.5 cents, to $54.125. WebMethods fell $15, to $72, and
Active Software dropped 93.75 cents, to $32.0625, all on Nasdaq.
Analysts said the shares were caught in the early technology
sell-off but that the mergers made sense.
</P>
<P>
   Vignette, based in Austin, Texas, sells a suite of applications
called V/5, designed to allow companies to personalize individuals'
interactions with their Web-based systems. OnDisplay, based in San
Ramon, Calif., offers software that allows business information
like purchase orders, inventory status checks, invoices and product
catalog data to be integrated and exchanged among suppliers and
distribution partners.
</P>
<P>
   Vignette will swap 1.58 shares for each share of OnDisplay,
valuing the company at $69.22 a share. Based on Friday's closing
price, that is a 30 percent premium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our customers increasingly require coordination between
enterprise systems, suppliers and multiple online marketplaces,''
Greg Peters, Vignette's president and chief executive, said in a
statement. ``The acquisition of OnDisplay furthers Vignette's
stated mission to provide the broadest and deepest application
platform to support the needs of companies who are serious about
building businesses online.''
</P>
<P>
   WebMethods, based in Fairfax, Va., makes software that allows
the computer systems of a company to communicate with systems of
the company's suppliers and customers. Active Software, based in
Santa Clara, Calif., makes software that integrates a company's
internal computer systems, like order management and accounting, to
communicate with each other and run together. WebMethods and Active
have worked together at high-profile customers like Federal
Express, Juniper Networks and Hewlett-Packard.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, Active Software's shareholders will receive
0.527 share of WebMethods for each Active Software share. Based on
WebMethods' close of $87 a share on Friday, the deal values Active
Software's shares at $45.85, a 39 percent premium.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Scholler, an analyst with Meta Group, said that customers
increasingly wanted their enterprise application integration
software, the domain of Active, to mesh seamlessly with their
business-to-business integration software, or B2BI, the domain of
WebMethods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately these things are going to drive together as the
infrastructure vendors start to deliver the platform technology on
which a business can build its e-presence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Simon Yates, an analyst with Forrester Research, said that
because these two deals happened at the same time, ``what looked
clever yesterday has landed Vignette in a bind today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With this deal,'' he said, ``Vignette has thrown down the
gauntlet to commerce-platform competitors like Open Market and
BroadVision to develop a system-to-system commerce story of their
own.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of those companies had already formed partnerships with
Active, and now get WebMethods as part of the package. WebMethods
``is now stronger than OnDisplay,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 2131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
