<HEADLINE>
ASTRONAUTS FINISH FIRST PART OF MISSION AT SPACE STATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   (Undated) With external renovations of the international space
station completed, the Atlantis astronauts turned their repair
skills to the inside of the yet-to-be inhabited outpost late
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The highest priority of the shuttle's maintenance mission is an
overhaul of the electrical power system within the Russian segment
of the two-room station.
</P>
<P>
   The five-man, two-woman shuttle crew plans to replace four of
six large power storage batteries, four electronic devices that
control the charging and discharging of the batteries and a pair of
small voltage regulators.
</P>
<P>
   During the first foray into the station, astronaut Susan Helms
and cosmonaut Yuri Usachev planned to replace two of the 165-pound
batteries in the Russian module. The complete overhaul will
continue through Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're anxious to get in there and get to work,'' Atlantis
commander Jim Halsell told mission control as the astronauts were
awakened Monday evening. ``Is there anything to keep us from
getting under way early?''
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantis crew became the first humans to visit the fledgling
station since June as they docked late Saturday. The station's two
modules tower nearly 80 feet above the shuttle's cargo bay.
</P>
<P>
   As they floated aboard the station Monday, the Atlantis
astronauts lugged along portable fans, surgical masks and small air
quality monitors to fend off any of the same ill effects reported
by the June visitors. Those included headaches, itchy eyes and, in
one instance, nausea from poor air circulation.
</P>
<P>
   NASA said improvements in the air flow provided by the shuttle
should prevent any new ill effects.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of the flight is to prepare the first two modules of
the station. They were joined in Earth orbit in December of 1998
for the tardy arrival of the Russian crew module in July.
</P>
<P>
   Stalled by Russian economic and rocket problems, the addition of
the crew module will furnish the outpost with an independent life
support system, including the equipment that cleanses the air. Its
arrival will permit the first resident crew of astronauts and
cosmonauts to arrive in November.
</P>
<P>
   The battery system in the Russian segment began to falter late
last year, a circumstance that would not have been so critical to
the outpost had the arrival of the crew module not slipped so far
behind schedule. At least three of the six batteries must function
in order for the two currently orbiting modules to link with the
Russian crew module.
</P>
<P>
   Late Sunday, Atlantis astronauts Jeff Williams and Jim Voss
embarked on a near seven-hour spacewalk, scaling the exterior of
the international station for a wide range of repairs.
</P>
<P>
   During the trek, Williams and Voss re-secured a wobbly American
cargo crane, assembled and installed a similar Russian crane,
replaced a broken U.S. communications antenna and attached eight
new hand rails.
</P>
<P>
   Those tasks removed a potential obstacle to the addition of the
crew module in July. They improved the ability of NASA ground
control teams at the Johnson Space Center in Houston to communicate
directly with the outpost rather than through the Russian ground
station in suburban Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   All told, the station's construction will require an estimated
49 spacewalks, totaling 304 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The United States leads a 16-nation partnership in the
seven-year construction effort.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium envisions a complex spanning an area equal to two
football fields placed side by side, housing a crew of seven. The
project will be used for cooperative research in medicine, physics
and biology.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership also hopes to use the station for the
development of hardware that will enable human explorers to return
to the moon as well as explore Mars and other deep space
destinations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
