<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2805 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AMAZON-SHORT-STORY-1S     05-22 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMAZON-SHORT-STORY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMAZON RESCINDS HONOR IN SHORT STORY CONTEST 
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Okla.)  (Eds: Subs 4th graf, Amazon.com ruled ..., to add circulation
figures from magazine's Web site.) 
By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last Monday, the first PEN/Amazon.com Short Story Award was
announced and Meera Nair of Brooklyn won the $10,000 prize. It was
one of the largest prizes for an undiscovered writer _ for her work
entitled ``Video,'' about the havoc wrought on a young Indian
couple's marriage by the sexually explicit culture of the West.
With a disclaimer, Amazon is running the full text of the story
despite some complaints over the graphic descriptions of sex _ and
despite the fact that the story was found to be ineligible for the
award.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Amazon and PEN rescinded the prize, which includes
publication on Amazon and in The Boston Book Review, and gave it to
someone else when it was discovered that Nair had been published
previously in a national magazine, which technically meant she was
not a beginner.
</P>
<P>
   The judges gave the prize instead to one of the runners-up,
Marlene Reed Wetzel, of Bixby, Okla., for ``A Map of Tripoli,
1967,'' a love story about an American woman and a Jewish-Italian
man, set in Libya just before the Six-Day War. It is the first
published work of fiction for Wetzel, who is 63, and has lived and
worked in the Middle East. Up to now, Wetzel has published articles
only in local papers in the Oklahoma area, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com ruled Nair ineligible because one of her previous
stories had appeared in The Threepenny Review, which violated the
competition's rules that entrants must not have published a work of
fiction in a nationally distributed magazine with a circulation of
over 5,000. Nair had told Amazon about the Threepenny Review story,
but neither she nor Amazon initially realized that the magazine's
circulation was higher than that; according to its Web site, The
Threepenny is a ``quarterly review of the arts and society'' with a
circulation of ``10,000+.'' The decision to rescind the award was
made after someone called Amazon's attention to the magazine's
circulation figures. The judges for the prize were Sherman Alexie,
David Guterson and Jamaica Kincaid.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Nair will be allowed to keep the $10,000 and her story
remains on the Amazon Web site, said Patty Smith, an Amazon
spokeswoman. In the story, an Indian husband watches a pornographic
video and tries to persuade his wife to perform the acts he sees.
``Some of them did object to the sexual nature'' of the piece,
Smith said of the customers. ``Some people did not share the
judges' enthusiasm for this wonderful story.''
</P>
<P>
   But the customers' reaction had nothing to do with the prize's
withdrawal, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Amazon was very fair,'' Nair said. ``I don't think
they had any qualms'' about publishing the story.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon said 12,000 people entered the contest. The submissions
ranged from apocalyptic fantasies to stories about children and
horses. The other runners-up are Thomas Cockrell, Holiday Reinhorn
and Paul Rusconi, whose stories are available on Amazon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
