<DOCNO> NYT20000522.0410 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2808 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-1000(2     05-22 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL'S BUFFER STRIP IN SOUTH LEBANON COLLAPSING 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The center of Israel's buffer zone in southern
Lebanon collapsed Monday as Israeli-backed Lebanese militias
abandoned villages, command posts and arms to advancing Hezbollah
guerrillas, some barely a mile from Israeli settlements.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli television showed Hezbollah followers triumphantly
raising their Kalashnikov-emblazoned yellow flags atop heavily
fortified command posts that Israel had turned over to its militia
allies only days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   That handover was part of an ongoing Israeli pullback leading up
to a full withdrawal by July 7, a deadline set by Prime Minister
Ehud Barak. For the last 22 years, Israeli troops have occupied an
11-mile deep zone inside Lebanon, fighting alongside the
2,500-member Israeli-equipped South Lebanon Army.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Israeli warplanes repeatedly bombed Hezbollah fighters
and followers moving into the border zone, killing as many as five
civilians and wounding dozens, according to Lebanese reports.
Fearing Hezbollah reprisals, the Israeli army ordered Israeli
frontier residents into bomb shelters, but hundreds chose instead
to leave their homes and drive far out of range of Katyusha
rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Tanks and troops rushed from deep inside Israel to reinforce
outposts on the Israeli side of the border Monday night, with
pressure mounting on Barak to pull the remaining troops in Lebanon
back into Israel as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Israel had hoped for an orderly, staged withdrawal, with U.N.
troops replacing the Israeli army in the southern border zone. But
with the United Nations still debating whether to expand and
redeploy its 4,500-member peacekeeping force in Lebanon, and
Hezbollah suddenly in control of the central section of the border
zone, such a plan is no longer possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not expect the withdrawal to be completely without
dangers or difficult moments,'' Barak said Monday night as he
called an emergency meeting of his security cabinet. ``There have
been such moments, and there will be more in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting continued late into the night, and there was no
immediate announcement.
</P>
<P>
   In southern Lebanon, hundreds of Muslim villagers walked and
drove past abandoned Israeli army checkpoints, which were
apparently left without a fight, to occupy the border district.
</P>
<P>
   The South Lebanon Army began quickly disintegrating on its own
Monday, abandoning military posts and equipment throughout the
central swath of the border region.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of panicked militamen and family members fled into
Israel, which promised to provide at least temporary refuge to its
Lebanese allies. Many more surrendered to the Hezbollah forces,
which Monday seized six command posts and a dozen villages that had
long been under the control of Israel and the South Lebanon Army.
</P>
<P>
   For Israelis watching the televised images of the suddenly
transformed border zone, it was the beginning of the end of a
costly occupation that began with the invasion of Lebanon 25 years
ago, and was soon institutionalized with the creation of a border
``security zone'' patrolled by Israel and its militia partners. But
while opinion polls show that Israelis overwhelmingly support
Barak's planned withdrawal, those images _ and the prospect of
further fighting _ have proved deeply unsettling.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with army commanders on the Israeli side of the
border, Barak reiterated his pledge to pull all Israeli forces out
of southern Lebanon within ``a few weeks.'' His office denied
Israeli television reports that he had ordered the troops withdrawn
by the first of June, five weeks ahead of his original deadline.
</P>
<P>
   But in light of Monday's collapse of at least two battalions of
the South Lebanon Army, the security cabinet was said to be trying
to speed up the withdrawal, while reinforcing Isreali military
installations immediately south of the border.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said he could not promise border residents that they would
be out of danger soon. ``We have to realize that we are entering a
period in which there is a certain degree of uncertainty, and our
responsibility is likely to impel us to order them to remain in the
shelters a few days,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   All along the border, meanwhile, Israeli army trucks continued
to haul arms and other equipment out of Lebanon, while private
Israeli work crews erected new electrified fences. It was unclear
how many Israeli soldiers remained in Lebanese territory. Inside
Israel, army installations were reinforced Monday night by tanks
and troops redeployed from the south.
</P>
<P>
   In a message aimed at both Beirut and Damascus _ as well as at
an increasingly nervous Israeli public _ Barak warned Monday that
forces across the border ``should not test our resolve by daring to
fire at Israeli soldiers, and much less at northern border
communities'' during the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The response will be painful, and not necessarily here in the
villages across from us: not Ramle, not Kozeh, not Alma Shaab and
Aita Shaab,'' he said, citing nearby Lebanese towns often used by
Hezbollah artillery units. ``It will be in completely different
places, and very painful.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the South Lebanon Army's desperate scramble out of Israel's
shrinking security zone and the fear of rocket attacks on northern
communities have increased Israeli fears that the withdrawal could
set off a new round of intense cross-border warfare.
</P>
<P>
   Since Sunday night, Hezbollah forces have secured control of
most of the former Israeli command posts in the central border
region.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli planes Monday bombed Israeli tanks, artillery and
armored personnel carriers that the South Lebanon Army had
abandoned at the posts, in order to keep them from falling into
Hezbollah hands, the Israeli military said.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli opposition, calling for a special session of
Parliament on Tuesday to debate the withdrawal, Monday fiercely
criticized the border chaos as an indictment of Barak's plan to
withdraw from Lebanon even without securing a peace settlement with
Syria, Hezbollah's prime protector.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``We must not unilaterally withdraw without first establishing
quiet in southern Lebanon,'' said Ariel Sharon, the head of the
opposition Likud party, who led Israel's invasion of Lebanon a
quarter-century ago. ``That is the first thing that must be done.
Unfortunately, the prime minister can't stand the pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak's party responded in a tart statement that the prime
minister ``has no need for advice on Lebanon from Sharon, who was
disqualified from serving as defense minister in the wake of his
mishaps in Lebanon.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese withdrawal crisis completely overshadowed the
suspension of peace talks with the Palestinians as Palestinian
security forces kept firm control of continued demonstrations
Monday demanding the release of PLO prisoners in Israeli jails.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the SLA troops who surrendered their positions Monday
belonged to the Shi'ite minority faction of the militia, which is
considered less resolutely opposed to Hezbollah than the Christian
and Druze troops still patrolling outposts to the east and west.
Despite the collapse of the SLA central front, Antoine Lahad, the
self-styled general who commands the militia force, was quoted as
saying Monday that his forces would fight on unless granted a
blanket amnesty by the Lebanese government.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
