<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2818 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-SCOTUS-CLEANAIR-HNS &LR;      05-22 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-CLEANAIR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT TO RULE ON TOUGHER AIR POLLUTION STANDARDS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Editors: Has trims) 
 
By BILL DAWSON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) The U.S. Supreme Court agreed Monday to rule on
whether tougher national standards can take effect to reduce air
pollution.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration adopted the new standards in 1997 for
ozone, smog's chief ingredient, and tiny airborne particles, often
called soot.
</P>
<P>
   But in response to a legal challenge from industry groups led by
the American Trucking Associations, a federal appeals court in the
District of Columbia last year halted implementation of the new
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the issue represents one of the hottest
environmental debates in recent years, and the news that the
Supreme Court would be its final arbiter immediately renewed
competing claims. Health advocates said the standards are needed to
protect the public, but businesses said they would damage the
economy.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the justices decide, their ruling won't affect
Houston's obligation to bring ozone levels below an older, less
stringent standard by 2007.
</P>
<P>
   Older standards for ozone and airborne particles remain in
force.
</P>
<P>
   Houston has violated the old ozone standard for many years,
ranking last year as the city with the worst ozone record in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency has decreed that cities
like Houston, which violate the older smog standard, must comply
with its limit before moving toward complying with the new
standard.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The American Lung Association said the new pollution standards
``are essential to protecting the health of millions of Americans,
especially children, the elderly and those with lung and heart
disease, from exposure to unhealthy air pollution levels.''
</P>
<P>
   But the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, a leading critic of the
stricter standards, said letting them go into effect would ``be a
crushing federal mandate on U.S. businesses, with no scientifically
proven benefit to human health.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides deciding how the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency
regulates air pollution, the justices could set a far-reaching
precedent that determines the limits of many federal agencies'
administrative authority.
</P>
<P>
   Federal attorneys said the appeals court's ruling had ``opened
to potential constitutional attack ... numerous other federal
statutes containing similarly broad grants of authority to
administrative agencies.''
</P>
<P>
   By a 2-1 vote, a three-judge panel said the EPA's interpretation
of one section of the federal Clean Air Act involved ``an
unconstitutional delegation of legislative power.''
</P>
<P>
   The two judges called for the EPA to develop a
``constitutional'' interpretation of the act _ perhaps by modifying
the disputed ozone and particle standards. The Clinton
administration appealed the ruling, setting the stage for Monday's
Supreme Court action.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA said it adopted the new standards on the basis of
scientific evidence, gathered in recent years, which indicated the
stricter limits are needed to protect public health.
</P>
<P>
   Ozone, a respiratory irritant, forms during reactions of other
air pollutants, from cars, industrial plants and many other
sources.
</P>
<P>
   The extremely tiny particles covered by the new soot standard _
smaller than those regulated under the older standard _ come from
combustion and other sources.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Even with the new standards on hold, Texas officials are getting
ready for their possible implementation.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission
held meetings in Houston and five other metropolitan areas to
solicit public comments on how it should go about designating
violation areas under the tougher ozone standard.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
