<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2819 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-U.N.-N     05-22 0370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECRETARY-GENERAL LAYS OUT CONDITIONS FOR PEACEKEEPERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With ISRAEL-LEBANON) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Secretary-General Kofi Annan recommended to the
Security Council on Monday that the United Nations not increase the
size of its peacekeeping force in Lebanon until Israel withdraws
and Lebanon guarantees the safety of the U.N. troops.
</P>
<P>
   Only then would the United Nations consider increasing its force
to nearly 8,000 from the current 4,500 troops, according to a plan
Annan sent to the council.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want us to be a punching bag in the middle with everybody
taking pot shots at us?'' Annan said to reporters after a Security
Council meeting Monday when he was questioned about the measured
recommendations in his report. ``Everybody would then blame the
U.N. for everything we are not responsible for,'' he said,
apparently stung by a spate of recent criticism about the
performance of U.N. peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   As an interim measure, Annan recommended that the United
Nations, which has stationed peacekeepers in southern Lebanon since
1978, should augment the force only slightly _ to 5,600 troops _
strictly for the purposes of verifying the Israeli pullback and the
disarming of the Israel's Lebanese allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the responsibility of the government of Israel to ensure
that the de facto force, known as the South Lebanon Army, cease to
exist,'' the secretary-general's report says, calling the SLA
``part of Israel's presence in Lebanon.'' The United Nations will
not be involved in disarming it.
</P>
<P>
   According to U.N. plans, the secretary-general's envoy to the
region, Terje Roed Larsen, will return to the Mideast on Tuesday
after having met with U.N. officials and the Security Council on
Monday. Before verification flights can be made over the
Israeli-Lebanese border, he will have to get the approval of
Lebanon, Syria and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Only then can cartographers flying along the frontiers try to
demarcate the boundaries of Israel, Lebanon and Syria, but only in
order to monitor them. Troops for the larger monitoring and
peacekeeping force are not likely to be recruited until the Israeli
withdrawal is complete.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 2152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000522.0419 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2821 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-BUSH-MIDEAST-ART-NYT &LR;      05-22 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MIDEAST-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SAYS CLINTON MISSTEPPED IN ISRAEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT18 and NYT28 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(With ISRAEL-LEBANON, ISRAEL-LEBANON-U.N., ISRAEL-WOMEN) 
(Eds: Also moving in `p' category.) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush on Monday accused the Clinton
administration of taking sides in last year's Israeli election and
of trying to make Israel conform to American ``plans and
timetables'' for peace. The governor said his own support for
Israel was ``not conditional on the outcome of the peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush leveled his criticisms in a speech on the Middle East at
the annual policy conference of the American Israel Public Affairs
Committee, a pro-Israel lobbying group. His appearance was part of
a sustained effort in recent days to address what many consider to
be his chief vulnerability as a presidential candidate: his command
of foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who was repeatedly interrupted by applause, said little on
the Middle East that he had not said before. Once again, he pledged
that as president he would ``begin the process of moving the U.S.
ambassador to the city Israel has chosen as its capital,'' a
reference to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   His most pointed remarks concerned the administration's role in
Middle East peace talks over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In recent times Washington has tried to make Israel conform to
its own plans and timetables,'' he said, drawing applause, ``but
this is not the path to peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``A clear and bad example,'' he said, ``was the administration's
attempt to take sides in the most recent Israeli election. America
should not interfere in Israel's democratic process, and America
will not interfere in Israeli elections when I'm the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush did not elaborate. Aides said his comments about a
timetable referred to the nine days and nights of tortuous Wye
River negotiations on Maryland's Eastern Shore, which committed the
Israelis and Palestinians to actions they had promised in previous
agreements. The talks restored momentum to the peace process,
setting a detailed timetable for Israel's withdrawal from part of
the West Bank in three phases.
</P>
<P>
   Although some Republicans praised the agreement, others said
Israel was being unduly pressured.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the accusation of playing favorites in the
election, Chris Lehane, a spokesman for Gore, called it
``irresponsible to make such reckless comments concerning such a
sensitive part of the world'' and said ``it really does raise a
question of his readiness to be a leader in international
affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehane said, ``Al Gore's leadership credentials on facilitating
the Middle East peace process are impeccable, while Bush is
suffering from an antiquated analysis reminiscent of the Republican
approach of the 1980s.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Clinton administration maintained studied public
neutrality in last year's Israeli elections, it made little effort
to conceal its desire for Ehud Barak's victory over then-Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu. James Carville, President Clinton's
former political adviser, served in a similar role for Barak. In
1996, Clinton all but openly endorsed Shimon Peres, the Labor Party
candidate, over Netanyahu because of the difference in the
candidates' views of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   In appearances before Jewish groups, presidential candidates
frequently promise to move the U.S. Embassy in Israel to Jerusalem
from Tel Aviv. The status of Jerusalem, which Israel regards as its
capital, is a central issue in ``final status'' peace negotiations
between Israelis and Palestinians, and the administration says
moving the embassy would pre-empt the delicate negotiations and
destroy Washington's ability to act as an honest broker in peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
   In his failed presidential bid in 1988, Gore said he would
consider moving the U.S. Embassy to Jerusalem, but his aides now
say he sees the issue as something that should be worked out in
peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Barak was supposed to attend the American Israel Public Affairs
Committee conference Monday and meet with both Bush and Gore. But
over the weekend he canceled his visit to the United States because
of violence in the West Bank and South Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he was ``deeply disturbed'' by the reports of the
Palestinian police opening fire on Israeli soldiers last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is certainly no way to make peace a reality,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also said that Iran's leaders should be put on notice that
``America will judge them'' by the treatment of 13 Jews imprisoned
in Iran on charges of espionage.
</P>
<P>
   Little more than a year ago, Bush came under criticism for
silence on the West's air war in Kosovo. And more than a few
critics have questioned how capable he would be, as president, on
foreign policy issues. In the Republican primaries, his main
opponent, Sen. John McCain of Arizona, repeatedly said that he
himself would not need ``on-the-job training,'' a way of belittling
Bush's credentials to be commander in chief.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has openly acknowledged that he is studying international
issues, telling reporters that he is reading ``Lenin's Tomb,'' a
book about the Soviet Union by David Remnick, and ``Balkan
Ghosts,'' an account of turmoil in the Balkans by Robert D. Kaplan.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Bush has been raising his profile on
international affairs. Last week he took positions on pending
congressional disputes on financing for Kosovo peace-keeping and on
trade with China. He plans to speak further on national security at
a Washington news conference on Tuesday and to meet with the South
African president, Thabo Mbeki, in Austin, Texas, later this week.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki met with Gore on Monday before attending a state dinner
with Clinton.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Introducing Bush on Monday, Mayer Mitchell, a former president
of the public affairs committee, told the audience that if they did
not know Bush well, they did know the foreign policy advisers
surrounding him. Mitchell named a host of former aides to
Presidents Ronald Reagan and George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate appearance here Monday before the National
Association of Realtors, Bush called for a crackdown on ``frivolous
and junk lawsuits'' and said lawyers who filed multiple ``junk
lawsuits'' should be barred from appearing in federal court for
three years.
</P>
<P>
   And he ended the day with a fund-raiser that was expected to
bring in $350,000 to $400,000 for his campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 2156EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000522.0420 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
