<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR TUESDAY, MAY 23
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Tuesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-PEACEKEEPING-U.S.-NYT (moved on Friday, May 19)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, May 19,
about Senator Judd Gregg's blocking of money owed by the United
States to the United Nations for peacekeeping referred incorrectly
at one point to a staff member of the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee who commented. The staff member, Pat M. Holt, is a man.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CHINA-TRADE-EUROPE-NYT (moved on Friday, May 19)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, May 19,
about the coming vote in Congress on the bill to grant permanent
normal trading rights to China misstated the stance of
Representative Peter Deutsch, a Florida Democrat. He has not been
won over; he is undecided.
</P>
<P>
   BC-ECOMMERCE-COLUMN-NYT (moved on Sunday, May 21)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, May 21,
about the rigors faced by Internet companies trying to expand
globally, misstated the ownership of Boo.com, the British online
retailer. The company, which announced last week that it was going
out of business, is owned by its founders and private investors. It
has not made a public stock offering.
</P>
<P>
   BC-COMPUTER-BRIEFS-NYT (moved on Sunday, May 21)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, May 21,
about a parody Web site that takes visitors through the steps of
naming an Internet company and choosing its logo misspelled the
site's address. It is eNormicom.com, not eNoricom.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
