<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-TODD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS SCRATCH TODD OFF WISH LIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Clippers moved a baby step closer to choosing
next season's head coach by officially crossing one name off the
list.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, interim coach Jim Todd, who directed a 4-33 finish
after Chris Ford was fired Feb. 3, was scratched as a candidate to
coach the team on a permanent basis.
</P>
<P>
   The move is not expected to rock the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Elgin Baylor, the Clippers' vice president of basketball
operations, said Todd _ whose contract expires at the end of June _
could be retained as an assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   Todd was at his Staples Center office when the announcement was
made, but couldn't be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would like to be here, or somewhere, as an assistant next
season,'' Baylor said. ``Of course, a position on the staff would
be based on the wishes of the new head coach.'' Baylor said.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers hope to finally cross (ital) that (endital) bridge
before the June 28 draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been talking to various people about the head-coaching
vacancy,'' Baylor said. ``I'm not going to get into who is and who
isn't a candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he did confirm there have been discussions with
grapevine favorite Mike Fratello. Fratello coached the Atlanta
Hawks for eight seasons before a six-year run with the Cleveland
Cavaliers ended last year. He currently pays the rent by working as
an NBA game analyst for TNT and a talking studio head for NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Clippers assistant coach Dennis Johnson also has had talks with
Baylor and team executive vice president Andy Roeser about the
head-coaching job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say he's a candidate,'' Baylor said.
</P>
<P>
   As for on-court personnel adjustments, the Clippers' predraft
screening continues today when UCLA freshman Jason Kapono and Duke
senior Chris Carrawell arrive for workouts at USC's Lyon Center.
</P>
<P>
   Other prospects expected in this week include Bruins sophomore
power forward Jerome Moiso, Kentucky center Jamal Magloire and
gifted shooting guard Jimmie ``Snap'' Hunter, who led Life College
in Georgia to the NAIA championship after transferring from
University of Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   This week's visitors will be considered for the Clippers' second
and third picks (18 and 30, respectively) in the draft. Sunday,
ping-pong cruelty dropped the team from the lottery's favorite role
to the No. 3 spot. The Clippers' short list for that pick could
produce visits from Marcus Fizer (Iowa State), Stromile Swift
(LSU), Darius Miles (East St. Louis, Ill. High School) and Courtney
Alexander (Fresno State). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
