<HEADER>
A2831 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-INFLATION-PREVENTION-     05-22 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INFLATION-PREVENTION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FED TRYING TO COOL HOT STOCKS  &HT;     By ARTHUR M. LOUIS 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chroncile 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ On the six occasions that the Federal Reserve
has raised interest rates since last June, the official explanation
has always been essentially the same: The fast-growing economy has
to be cooled down or inflation will make a deadly comeback.
</P>
<P>
   But some observers say the principal target of the rate rises is
the stock market _ that the Fed is trying to gradually drain
speculative excess out of the market to prevent a potentially
disastrous crash.
</P>
<P>
   Although price inflation has remained persistently mild at both
the retail and wholesale levels, most economists and other Fed
watchers accept the official Fed explanation at face value.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Reaser, chief economist and senior market strategist with
the Bank of America Asset Management Group in St. Louis, notes that
unemployment has declined below 4 percent for the first time in 30
years, raising the potential for wage-driven inflation.
</P>
<P>
   She also points out that the gross domestic product lately has
been growing at a souped-up 5 percent annual rate, whereas 3
percent would be normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Federal Reserve is trying to achieve a balance in the
economy, so we are growing only as rapidly as we are capable of
doing,'' Reaser says. ``It is trying to rein in the growth of
spending to match our ability to produce goods and services.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same vein, Gary Schlossberg, an economist with Wells
Capital Management in San Francisco, says: ``There are indications
that inflation is beginning to turn in the wrong direction,
although not dramatically. The hike in rates is designed to deal
with broadly based signs of inflation pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   But a minority of Fed watchers say the current series of rate
increases _ amounting to a cumulative gain of 1.75 percentage
points _ primarily reflects worries about the no-holds-barred,
casino-style speculation that has lately characterized the stock
market.
</P>
<P>
   As far back as December 1996, when the Dow Jones industrial
average was at little more than half its present level, Federal
Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan expressed concern about
``irrational exuberance'' in the market.
</P>
<P>
   If the Fed wants to tame the bull market, its control of
interest rates is an effective tool. Rising rates hurt stocks,
because they crimp corporate profits and make fixed-income
investments relatively more attractive.
</P>
<P>
   But why should the Fed care whether stocks are up, down or
sideways?
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan himself has pointed to the so-called ``wealth effect''
of a booming stock market. People who have been enriched by paper
gains in their stock holdings are prompted to spend lavishly on
houses, luxury goods and everything else _ contributing to
inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart J. Pillette of Pillette Investment Management in San
Francisco, thinks this is a dodge.
</P>
<P>
   He says that the Fed is overemphasizing a scant inflation threat
as a ``convenient excuse'' and that it doesn't state the real
reason because that might provoke a public uproar.
</P>
<P>
   Pillette figures the Fed is afraid that there is real danger of
a calamitous stock-market crash that could ``very well lead to a
severe recession.''
</P>
<P>
   He explains that ``speculation in the Internet stocks, which
started more than a year ago, was growing rampant. It was spreading
from Internet stocks to most technology stocks. If left
unchallenged, it could very well have led to a 1929-style blow
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than allow a crash, the Fed chose to parade out a series
of small rate increases designed to slowly ``take the helium out of
the balloon,'' Pillette observes.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the first five rate increases was held to a minimal 0.25
percentage points. The most recent, on Wednesday, was pegged at 0.5
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's balloon-pricking strategy _ if, indeed, that is its
strategy _ finally appears to be succeeding. The half-point rate
increase in particular has spread heavy gloom among investors,
driving down all the leading market averages.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average has fallen 3.6 percent since
Wednesday and 4 percent since the first rate increase was announced
on June 30.
</P>
<P>
   The broader-based Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index is down 4.5
percent from Wednesday. It has risen 2 percent since June 30, but
that is a far cry from the 20-plus and 30-plus annual percentage
gains it enjoyed through the latter half of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index _ home to most of the leading
technology stocks _ continues to fly, although not nearly as high
as it did. It peaked on March 10 _ between Fed rate hikes No. 4 and
No. 5 _ and has since lost 33 percent of its value. It is down 9.5
percent since Wednesday, but it still boasts a 25 percent gain
since June 30.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Arthur M. Louis at  &LR; alouis(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
