<HEADER>
A2832 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MONEYBAG-COLUMN-SFCHR     05-22 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MONEYBAG: WALL STREET'S DIM VIEW OF KMART  &HT;     By ARTHUR M. LOUIS 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: How is it possible that Kmart Corp., with $36 billion in
annual revenues, has a market capitalization of less than $4
billion? Does this really represent all the outstanding shares, or
are there a lot of other shares held by company insiders?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: I can understand why you consider Kmart's market cap
surprisingly low. Nowadays, it's easy to find technology companies
with market caps of $4 billion or more and revenues of only a few
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   But the sub-$4 billion market cap for Kmart is, in fact, correct
_ it includes all the outstanding shares.
</P>
<P>
   There are several forces at work here.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers often have low profit margins _ meaning profits as a
percentage of revenues. If you have looked at Kmart's financial
statistics, perhaps you noticed that the company had net income of
$403 million last year, which amounts to only a bit more than 1
percent of revenues.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Kmart has a relatively low price-to-earnings ratio.
Its stock is selling for only about nine times last year's
earnings, which is less than half what investors are paying these
days for the average stock.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt the main reason for the low price/earnings ratio is
that Kmart has reported disappointing earnings recently. Its
earnings in the first quarter of the current fiscal year were down
more than 50 percent from the year-earlier quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The stock has lost half its value in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A Lot of Taxes
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: In 1977, I purchased a home and four lots in the Bay Area. My
house is situated on two of the lots, and I am in the process of
selling one of the vacant lots. Since the cost of each lot was not
separately identified when I purchased the property, how do I
figure, for tax purposes, the cost basis of the lot that is being
sold?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: Internal Revenue Service spokesman Jesse Weller suggests that
you search your records for a copy of the first property-tax bill
you received after buying the properties. It will show separate
assessed values for the land and your home.
</P>
<P>
   Take the ratio of the land value indicated on that bill to the
total value of the properties, and that will enable you to
calculate the assessed value, at that time, of each lot. If the
assessed value of the lot you are selling was, say, 15 percent of
the total assessed value of all the properties combined, then use
15 percent of your total purchase price as the cost basis.
</P>
<P>
   However, it may be that you no longer have a copy of that old
bill. In that case, call or visit the assessor's office in your
county, and see if they have the information in their archives.
</P>
<P>
   If that doesn't work, then Weller says you should use the oldest
bill you can find, either among your records or at the assessor's
office.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Faulty Stock Logic
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: 3Com Corp. stock recently was quoted at around $43 per share,
while the stock of Palm Inc. was around $25. 3Com owns most of
Palm, and its shareholders are slated to receive 1.5 Palm shares _
or $37.50 worth _ for each 3Com share they hold sometime in the
next few months. Doesn't that make 3Com a really good buy? For $43
you are getting $80.50 worth of stock.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: 3Com may indeed be a good buy, with or without the distribution
of Palm shares. But your logic is faulty. Once the Palm shares are
distributed, that action will be reflected in the value of 3Com's
shares, which almost certainly will drop in value.
</P>
<P>
   The question seems to be: Will they drop as low as $5.50 per
share _ the difference between 3Com's current $43 price and the
value of the promised Palm distribution, which has a current market
value of $37.50?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they will, maybe they won't. Nobody knows.
</P>
<P>
   But even if 3Com's price doesn't fall that sharply, you also
must reckon with the very real possibility that Palm's own price
will plummet.
</P>
<P>
   There certainly is precedent for that. On their first day of
trading in March, the company's shares changed hands for as much as
$165. They have been falling, with few interruptions, ever since.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send e-mail to  &LR; moneybag(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
