<SLUG> BC-STOCKS-REBOUND-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 INVESTORS SNATCH UP REELING TECH STOCKS  &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In a stunning rebound, the Nasdaq composite
index staged a late rally Monday to gain back nearly all its losses
after earlier plunging more than 200 points, or 6 percent, to a new
low for the year.
</P>
<P>
   By the closing bell, the tech-heavy Nasdaq was down 26.19 points
at 3,364.21 _ way off its intraday basement of 3,172.65 but still
nearly 34 percent below its March 10 high.
</P>
<P>
   The spurt of last-minute buying kept the Nasdaq above its April
14 low for 2000 of 3,321.29.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bizarre,'' said Richard Del Monte, who heads the Del
Monte Group investment firm in Danville, Calif. ``The market just
doesn't know what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 84.30 points to 10,542.55,
while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index dropped 6.23 to 1,400.72.
</P>
<P>
   When Monday's sell-off was at its fiercest, many analysts were
all but kissing off technology stocks and were predicting that the
Nasdaq wouldn't touch bottom until tumbling as low as 2,900.
</P>
<P>
   But bargain hunters found the lows too tempting to resist and
waded in with buy orders for many of the same big-name tech stocks
that just hours before had been dismissed as too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Like most other market watchers, Todd Gold, technical strategist
at Gruntal &AMP; Co. in New York, was left scratching his head over the
Nasdaq's renewed lease on life.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could we have such a significant rally in such a short
time?'' he asked. ``I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said the rally looked strong enough that investors
might be able to expect several days of advances before the market
again turns sour.
</P>
<P>
   While Gold expects the Nasdaq to return by year's end to the
lofty 5,000 level briefly touched in March, he believes the index
still will lose ground before recovering in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   Gold handed much of the credit for Monday's rally to Cisco
Systems staying above the $50 level. Analysts had viewed this as a
key measure of the strength of one of the market's tech bellwethers
_ and were not disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   After touching a low of $50, Cisco bounced back handily to close
$1.81 higher at $55.25.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly encouraging to see Cisco make this kind of
rebound,'' Gold said.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts predict that the market will remain volatile for
weeks to come as investors weigh the prospect for further interest
rate increases by the Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed boosted short-term rates by a half-percentage-point last
week in the latest effort to keep inflation at bay amid continued
economic expansion.
</P>
<P>
   A further quarter-point increase is expected when the Fed's
policy-making committee meets on June 28. Beyond that, it's
anyone's guess.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real water-torture type of market,'' said Eugene
Peroni, research director at John Nuveen &AMP; Co. in Radner, Pa. ``You
get a rally followed by another sell-off.''
</P>
<P>
   He sees a Nasdaq low of 2,700 before the index makes a
convincing return to higher levels. ``Ultimately, though, techs
will continue to carry the day,'' Peroni said.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Adams, managing director of First Security Van Kasper in
San Francisco, said he is advising clients to stand pat for the
time being.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a time to sell,'' he said. ``But it's still too early
to commit your money.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq is now near the same level as at the beginning of
last December.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. fell 88 cents to $64.19 after filing a brief
with the U.S. Justice Department elaborating on why it doesn't
think the company should be broken up.
</P>
<P>
   Other leading tech shares were mixed. Intel Corp. gained 50
cents to $118.38, while Sun Microsystems rose $2.63 to $79.88, and
Oracle Corp. slid $2.25 to $67.81.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Gurkink, an analyst at Ragen MacKenzie in Seattle,
thinks investors could do worse than to snap up companies like
these now that they've come down so steeply in price.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want long-term earnings,'' he said, ``technology's
still where it's at.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail David Lazarus at  &LR; davidlaz(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
