<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-TVSEX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT STRIKES DOWN LAW ON TV SEX 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Monday struck down as
unconstitutional a federal law designed to prevent children from
seeing sexually explicit images on cable, saying the statute
amounted to a ban on the free speech of programmers.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling allows cable operators to continue to send scrambled
signals from stations to non-subscribers. Parents who want to
prevent these signals, also known as ``signal bleed,'' can tell
their local cable operators to block the transmission. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; In its 5-4 decision, the court said Congress went too far in
the 1996 Telecommunications Act and violated the constitutional
rights of cable operators by limiting how and when they could air
scrambled images on sexually graphic stations.
</P>
<P>
   The legal restrictions, though designed to protect children,
illegally prevented constitutionally protected images from being
transmitted to many adults, the court said.
</P>
<P>
   The court indicated that government has less constitutional
authority to protect children from what is aired on cable than what
is broadcast on free television stations. The justices, who have
upheld foul-language restrictions on broadcast networks, were
unwilling to give lawmakers as much latitude on regulating sex on
cable largely because parents with a phone call to the system
operator can block programing on cable but not on free television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blocking enables the government to support parental authority
without affecting the First Amendment interests of speakers and
willing listeners _ listeners for whom, if the speech is unpopular
or indecent, the privacy of their own homes may be the optimal
place of receipt,'' Justice Anthony M. Kennedy wrote in the court's
majority opinion. ``Simply put, targeted blocking is less
restrictive than banning, and the government cannot ban speech if
targeted blocking is a feasible and effective means of furthering
its compelling interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress, fearing that curious and impressionable youngsters
could watch sexually graphic _ though blurry _ scrambled images,
required programmers in 1996 to either block the pictures out
completely or show them only between 10 p.m. and 6 a.m., times when
children were unlikely to be watching.
</P>
<P>
   About 62 million U.S. households receive cable television, the
federal government reported. The Playboy channel is in 20 million
U.S. and Canadian homes, a company spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Playboy Entertainment Group Inc., a media conglomerate that
provides sexually explicit cable programming and has scrambled its
images to non-subscribers, said the federal restriction in the
telecommunications law violated the company's First Amendment right
of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   The high court, in ruling for Playboy, said sexually explicit
cable images might harm children and offend most Americans but are
nevertheless constitutionally protected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Constitution exists precisely so that opinions and
judgments, including esthetic and moral judgments about art and
literature, can be formed, tested and expressed,'' Kennedy wrote.
``What the Constitution says is that these judgments are for the
individual to make, not for the government to decree, even with the
mandate or approval of a majority.''
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission, which oversees
television, urged parents to be more diligent with regard to what
their children are watching on cable following the high court's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents should remember that current law specifically provides
that cable customers can contact their local cable companies and
request that channels they find objectionable be blocked from their
homes at no cost,'' FCC Chairman William Kennard said.
</P>
<P>
   Playboy Enterprises, which also successfully challenged the law
in the U.S. District Court in Washington, D.C., has continued to
have scrambled messages on many cable systems, said company
spokesman Bill Farley. He said the scrambled image is not
intentional but rather a technological glitch between Playboy and
local cable operators.
</P>
<P>
   The company's chairman, Christie Hefner, hailed the court's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt it (the law) was an intrusion on individual choice by
the federal government,'' Hefner said. ``Our position has been
vindicated by today's ruling.''
</P>
<P>
   In its decision, the court expressed support for Congress'
effort to protect children from pornography. The justices said
lawmakers could still legitimately limit children's access to
sexually explicit images as long as the restrictions don't encroach
on the rights of adults to have access to the programing.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the court said, Congress can _ and does _ impose a
valid restriction on operators by requiring them to block access to
their channels at the request of parents and other subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Kennedy's opinion in United States vs. Playboy
Entertainment Group were Justices John Paul Stevens, David H.
Souter, Clarence Thomas and Ruth Bader Ginsburg.
</P>
<P>
   In a vehement dissent, Justice Stephen G. Breyer assailed the
court for failing to recognize what he called Congress' legitimate
method for achieving the compelling governmental interest of
protecting youngsters from sexually graphic images.
</P>
<P>
   Breyer said the court's ruling ``threatens to leave Congress
without power to help the millions of parents who do not want to
expose their children to commercial pornography.''
</P>
<P>
   He derided as ineffective the requirement that operators tell
parents they can have the channels totally blocked. The
overwhelming majority of parents don't read the message from the
cable operators, which is usually contained with the monthly bill.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Breyer's dissent were Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist
and Justices Sandra Day O'Connor and Antonin Scalia.
</P>
<P>
