(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) POMPTON LAKES, N.J. -- May 22, 2000 -- TEN-CANCER-PLAYER
-- Jim Nolan has emerged as a force and an inspiration for the
Pompton Lakes High School tennis team. Growing up in the area,
Nolan had dreamed of playing for the school's baseball team, which
had won several Passaic County championships. But when he lost his
right arm to cancer last summer, his baseball hopes were dashed.
After the surgery, Nolan decided to focus instead on tennis, a
sport he had never played before high school. (Vincent Laforet/The
New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) NEW YORK -- May 22, 2000 -- NY-GIULIANI-NRA --
Protesters at Duffy Square carried posters Monday opposing a
proposal for a restaurant and arcade in Times Square to be run by
the National Rifle Association. The menu for the restaurant would
feature wild game. (Don Hogan Charles/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) WASHINGTON -- May 22, 2000 -- BUSH-MIDEAST-2 -- Gov.
George W. Bush, the Republican presidential candidate, speaking at
the American Israel Public Affairs Committee's 41st annual policy
conference Monday, within sight of former President Harry S. Truman
and Chaim Weizmann, Israel's first president. Bush accused the
Clinton administration of taking sides in last year's Israeli
elections, continuing a pattern of the United States trying ``to
make Israel conform to its own plans and timetables.'' (Stephen
Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) UNDATED -- May 22, 2000 -- E-BOOK -- Amid signs of an
intensifying digital-rush in the American book industry, three
publishing giants and Microsoft were poised Monday to plunge deeper
into the emerging electronic literary market. An image from an
advertisement for a Pocket PC made by Hewlett-Packard (which
contains Microsoft Reader software) displays Michael Crichton's
novel ``Timeline.'' (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) UNDATED -- May 22, 2000 -- OBIT-HUGHES-B&AMP;W -- Mark
Reynolds Hughes, the multimillionaire founder of Herbalife
International, a nutritional supplement company that has been
controversial for both its products and sales methods, died last
weekend in his home in Malibu, Calif. He was 44. His death appeared
to be from natural causes, a spokesman for Herbalife said. An
autopsy is to be completed later this week. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) UNDATED -- May 22, 2000 -- CHINA-TRADE-ADS -- Supporters
and opponents of the China trade bill have taken their respective
cases to television with advertisements like the pro-trade bill
announcement at left and anti-trade bill commercial at right. The
Clinton administration, which considers the vote on permanent
normal trade relations its top remaining legislative priority,
expects a narrow win. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- May 22, 2000 -- ACCOUNTING -- Paul A.
Volcker, the former Federal Reserve chairman, was named Monday to
head a new body that will choose the people who will set new
worldwide accounting standards. The 14 people that they select will
replace the current International Accounting Standards Committee,
which has been dominated by accounting professionals. (Jack
Manning/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- May 22, 2000 -- JAPAN-FASHION-3 -- A young
woman's knit tam and crayon-colored minibraids show the influence
of Jamaican dance-hall music on the downtown Tokyo-in-New York
scene. Japanese street style is not really so much a fashion as a
gestalt. ``There's so much variety, it's almost chaotic,'' added
Robb Young, a fashion writer for aRude magazine. (Aaron Lee
Fineman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- May 22, 2000 -- JAPAN-FASHION-2 -- You can
barely avoid Tokyo street style - with its loopy blend of pop
cultural references, label mania cartoon iconography and overall
appetite for the cultural flotsam of the West - in downtown
Manhattan. The slacker/surfer look, as imported from Harajuku to
East Ninth Street, needs no translation. (Aaron Lee Fineman/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- May 22, 2000 -- JAPAN-FASHION-1 -- Tokyo
Street 2000 brought bubble gum fashion to the Chelsea catwalk last
week, left. Monster platforms and streaked hair are two hallmarks
of today's Japanese urban fashion, as seen at Hotel Venus on West
Broadway, right. (Aaron Lee Fineman/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) ALCANTARA, Brazil -- May 22, 2000 -- BRAZIL-SATELLITES
-- Located two degrees south of the equator, the Alcantara Launch
Center, built by the Brazilian military two decades ago, has become
the focal point for what is perhaps the most ambitious unmanned
space program in any developing country. A rocket carrying a
satellite is launched from the Alcantara Launch Center in December,
1999. (Agencia Espacial Brasileira/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- May 22, 2000 -- NY-LEVY-PROFILE -- As much
as anything, his pragmatic approach to management explains how a
high-level lawyer at Citigroup, with no experience running even a
single school, became chancellor of the New York City Board of
Education, the country's largest and most difficult school system.
In his first 125 days in office, he has managed to surprise even
the savviest insiders by going from dark-horse candidate for
interim chancellor to a unanimous choice. Levy during an interview
Monday. (Keith Meyers/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- May 22, 2000 -- BUSH-MIDEAST -- Gov.
George W. Bush, the Republican presidential candidate, following an
addresses to the American Israel Public Affairs Committee's 41st
annual policy conference, Monday. Bush accused the Clinton
administration of taking sides in last year's Israeli elections,
continuing a pattern of the United States trying ``to make Israel
conform to its own plans and timetables.'' (Stephen Crowley/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) LOS ANGELES -- May 22, 2000 -- CALIF-DAVIS-JUSTICE --
Halfway into his second year in office, Gov. Gray Davis is
establishing himself as more of a tight-fisted conservative on
criminal justice issues than his Republican predecessors, or any
other elected official in California -- if not the nation. (Monica
Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- May 22, 2000 -- JAZZ-LINCOLN-CENTER -- At a
news conference Tuesday, Lincoln Center is to unveil plans for its
new home - a 100,000-square-foot complex at Columbus Circle which
includes the world's first concert halls built especially for jazz.
Discussing plans, from left, Rob Gibson, executive director of Jazz
at Lincoln Center; Gordon J. Davis, chairman; Wynton Marsalis,
artistic director; and the architect Rafael Vinoly. (Vincent
Laforet/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) ALEXANDRIA, Va. -- May 22, 2000 -- SCI-RUSSIA-MIR-2 --
Jeffrey Manber, an American who is president of MirCorp, with a
model of the Mir space station, circa 1993, in his office in
Alexandria. MirCorp, whose majority stockholder is the Russian
government, was formed in February by Western investors to raise
money for the Mir. (Susana Raab/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) CHICAGO -- May 22, 2000 -- SKIP-CARAY-COX -- Harry
Caray, center, posed with his son Skip, right, and grandson Chip,
in Chicago, May 13, 1991. At 60, the middle rung on a broadcasting
dynasty that started with his father, Harry, and continues with his
son Chip, Skip Caray has been announcing Atlanta Braves games on
radio and TV for the past 24 seasons. This year, Caray has said
that he intends to be a ``new, mellow Skip,'' in contrast to his
normally grouchy, even Grinchy persona. (John Zich for the The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) BEDFORD, Va. -- May 22, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 28 --
D-DAY-MEMORIAL-COX-3 -- Roy Stevens next to a photo of his twin
brother Ray. The brothers were platoon sergeants in Company A, but
on D-Day, they landed in separate landing crafts. Roy Stevens
learned of his brother's death by reading the dog tag on a wooden
cross after landing on Omaha beach. (Rick McKay/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) BEDFORD, Va. -- May 22, 2000 -- -ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 28
-- D-DAY-MEMORIAL-COX-2 -- A model of how the completed D-Day
Memorial, including an adjoining education center, is to look by
the time it is dedicated on June 6, 2001, the 57th anniversary of
the historic landing that is now remembered as the turning point of
World War II. (Rick McKay/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) BEDFORD, Va. -- May 22, 2000 -- -ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 28
-- D-DAY-MEMORIAL-COX-1 -- This Memorial Day, this first phase of
the National D-Day Memorial, the arch and plaza seen recently
during sunrise, will be opened to the public. The completed
project, including an adjoining education center, is to be
dedicated on June 6, 2001, the 57th anniversary of the historic
landing that is now remembered as the turning point of World War
II. (Rick McKay/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- May 22, 2000 -- SCI-FLUORESCENT-MOLECULE-B&AMP;W
-- Pyramids of aluminum one-50,000th of an inch per side are
examined under an atomic force microscope, at left. Then, the same
specimens, right, are seen through the new optical microscope,
illuminated by a single glowing molecule. This technology could
help unravel the mysteries of molecules. (University of
Konstanz/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) BOSTON -- May 22, 2000 -- PROFILE-ISNER -- Amid a
national review of gene therapy experiments in the wake of a young
patient's death and other problems, Dr. Jeffery Isner's experiments
have been halted. Isner during a recent interview. (David L.
Ryan/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) CAMBRIDGE, Mass -- May 22, 2000 -- HARVARD-PRESIDENT --
Neil Rudenstine, a scholar of Renaissance poetry who led the
largest fund-raising campaign in the history of higher education,
plans to step down next spring after a decade as president of
Harvard, the United State's oldest and most prestigious university.
Rudenstine during an event at the Radcliffe Institiute in April.
(Matthew J. Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) JERUSALEM -- May 22, 2000 -- ISRAEL-WOMEN -- In a
landmark ruling, the Israeli Supreme Court said Monday that women
can pray in groups, read aloud from the Torah and wear praer shawls
at the Western Wall, practices that had been forbidden by law in
keeping with Orthodox practice. Celebrating the court ruling,
representatives of the group Women Of The Wall walk down the Wall
Plaza as they head to the Western Wall, Monday. (Rina
Castelnuovo/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) MORRISTOWN, N.J. -- May 22, 2000 -- SCI-LYME-DEBATE-2 --
J. Carol Goodman's recurrance of Lyme disease after being treated
for it is at the center of a bitter medical debate over treatment
for the illness which is transmitted by ticks. Goodman tended to
her garden last week. (Dith Pran/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) EAST HAMPTON, N.Y. -- May 22, 2000 -- SCI-LYME-DEBATE-1
-- Dr. Joseph Burrascano, an internist and small-town family doctor
in East Hampton, is regarded as a world leader in effectively
treating patients with chronic Lyme disease. Burrascano says the
bacteria the causes the disease can bore so deeply into bodily
tissue that they can evade initial antibiotic treatment. (Maxine
Hicks/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- May 22, 2000 -- SCI-RUSSIA-MIR -- Long the
subject of premature obituaries, Mir, the pride of the cash-starved
Russian space program, is now operating because of last-minute
money from Western investors. With the help of more than $20
million in outside money and spacecraft supplied by Russian
partners, it appears life of the 130-ton space station may extend
past its 15th anniversary in orbit next February. (NASA/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- May 22, 2000 -- SCI-MANDRILLS --
Primatologists are discovering new and exciting elements in the
life of the mandrills of Gabon. Except when females are in estrus,
the males are solitary dwelling creatures, who all but kill one
another when the females are in season. A male mandrill during
attachment of a radio collar. (Wildlife Conservation Society/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- May 22, 2000 -- OBIT-GIELGUD-2-B&AMP;W -- Sir John
Gielgud, one of the great actors of the English stage, who
enthralled audiences for more than 60 years with is eloquent voice
and consummate artistry, died Sunday at his home in Aylesbury, west
of London. Fittingly his last major movie role was as Prospero in
``Prospero's Books,'' Peter Greenaway's 1991 version of ``The
Tempest.'' (The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- May 22, 2000 -- OBIT-GIELGUD-1-B&AMP;W -- Sir John
Gielgud, one of the great actors of the English stage, who
enthralled audiences for more than 60 years with his eloquent voice
and consummate artistry, died Sunday at his home in Aylesbury, west
of London.. He was 96 years old. Gielgud as King Constant in the
NBC production of ``Merlin,'' in 1998. (NBC/The New York Times)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
