u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT &LR;      05-22 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS AND PACERS IN THE CONSPIRACY SERIES  

</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The conspiracy theories were spilling out of the
Miami Heat locker room Sunday evening and seeping into the public
consciousness in places as far away as Indiana. But it does not
matter to Jeff Van Gundy if a fan in the farmland nodded in
agreement when Tim Hardaway accused the officials of cheating the
Heat in Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   And he is not going to fret any more than usual if a Pacers
zealot in Muncie puts stock in Jamal Mashburn's assertion that the
Knicks had the three referees ``in their pocket'' and that the
big-market fix is in by a league sensitive to nervous ticks in the
ratings.
</P>
<P>
   If a perception becomes reality in the wheat belt, so be it.
</P>
<P>
   But Van Gundy, the Knicks' coach, does worry about any effect
the referee-bashing will have on the three officials who step onto
the floor of Conseco Fieldhouse Tuesday night for Game 1 of the
four-of-seven-game Eastern Conference finals against Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern is that by the constant belaboring of such foolish
points, somehow it will have a subconscious effect on both the
league office and the officials, and that it will affect the
upcoming series,'' Van Gundy said Monday during a conference call
nearly 24 hours after the Knicks eliminated the Heat, 83-82, in
Game 7. ``Last year, it went without any repercussions. I don't
know what it'll be like this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Pacers were the ones looking suspiciously at the
officials when their season was ended by the Knicks in the
conference finals. They were devastated when the official Jess
Kersey called Antonio Davis for a foul that resulted in a miracle
4-point play by Larry Johnson to win Game 3 of the series.
</P>
<P>
   This year, in here-we-go-again fashion, they bemoaned a call the
official Joe Crawford missed in a Knicks-Pacers game on April 10;
after the game, Crawford admitted that the crew blew the offensive
goaltending that Patrick Ewing committed to help Johnson's
3-pointer fall with 21.7 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   It is not surprising that the Pacers became semisympathizers
with the frustration emanating from Miami's main stars on Sunday:
the Heat players were incredulous over a no-call when Alonzo
Mourning rescued a loose ball turned jump ball in the final minute
and were irate at a mix-up by the referees on whether Latrell
Sprewell stepped out of bounds or called time out with 2.1 seconds
left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand where Miami was coming from, but Miami had
their shot to win it,'' Reggie Miller said after the Pacers
practiced Monday in Indianapolis. ``If they make a couple of free
throws, we're talking about Miami. But I can see where they are
coming from.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need no mysterious 4-point plays or no tip-ins or
nothing like that. Let the best team play. I've said that from Day
1. Come playoff time, as long as they let the best team win and
play, I'll handle that. If there is some funny business going on we
can't control, so be it.''
</P>
<P>
   There is something humorous about all this to Rod Thorn. Merely
the thought, as Van Gundy suggested, that the league would be
influenced by the Heat's pouting or that the National Basketball
Association's brain trust is somehow the Svengali over the outcome
to every game left Thorn, the league's vice president for
operations, chuckling at the absurdity of it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the league ever overtly or tacitly suggested that the
referees favor a particular team or player, it would take about 24
hours to be in every newspaper in the country,'' said Thorn, who is
investigating the remarks made by the Heat to see if fines should
be levied. ``That doesn't happen. We couldn't care less who wins or
loses. It's not right to say there is a conspiracy, but that seems
to be the popular thing to do today.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy might believe this. But it was good politics to bring
up the officiating angle with a series coming up against an Indiana
team that went to the free-throw line 113 times during its
four-game regular-season split with the Knicks, while the Knicks
went only 52 times. Van Gundy is well aware that Miller's whipsaw
reactions to contact on the floor often land him at the free-throw
line. Maybe, with that in mind, it was not such a bad idea to wring
his hands over the bluster coming out of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we shoot more free throws, it's a league
conspiracy,'' Van Gundy said. ``When Miami shoots 21 free throws in
the first half of Game 6, that's hard driving to the basket. It's
not my fault they're a jump-shooting team.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, we were 8-9 with that same officiating group this
year. The year before, with those same three guys we had in Game 7,
we were 10-12. If we had them `in our pocket,' we had them in the
wrong pocket. I just find it unfortunate. I can understand Miami's
disappointment. But certainly, with Mashburn and Hardaway, I really
believe they should be just as disappointed in themselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
