<HEADLINE>
NCAA CHAMPIONSHIPS GET INTERNATIONAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. _ Markovski. Senoglu. Ondrosiva. Jecminkovi.
Frignovic. Safarova. Tortorella. Uhlirova. Lesenarova. Venkatesan.
</P>
<P>
   Not the 10 Most Wanted, but 10 women's tennis players competing
for the NCAA individual championships.
</P>
<P>
   These are the national championships, not a United Nations
summit. Still, players travel from faraway lands such as Turkey,
Slovakia, Czech Republic and Argentina to take advantage of one
thing the United States offers them: the ability to study and play
tennis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have teams or sports in universities,'' said Virginia
Commonwealth's Andrea Ondrosiva, a Czech Republic native.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either you play sports, or you study,'' said Argentine Cintia
Tortorella of Pepperdine.
</P>
<P>
   SEEDS: The singles bracket lists eight seeded players, then
lists the nine through 16 seeds alphabetically. So no one knows the
exact seeding of UCLA's Sara Walker or USC's Jewel Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   It has been done that way for as long as anyone can remember.
Tournament referee Jane Goodman said the method started because it
used to be too difficult to compare players across the country.
</P>
<P>
   THE END: Amanda Basica's college tennis career ended Friday. She
only discovered that Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Basica, a UCLA senior, was to play doubles with Walker, but
Walker defaulted with a back injury. Doubles teams can't be split
up, so Basica, whose Bruins team lost Friday in the team
quarterfinals, is done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm bummed,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
