<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2852 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-REGGIE-MILLER-NYT     05-22 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-REGGIE-MILLER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUELED BY CONTEMPT, MILLER IS READY TO ROLL 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The player whose postseason career is tethered to
New York was asked Monday to clarify a comment he made. Yes, Reggie
Miller said on the eve of the Eastern Conference finals, he ``hates
but respects'' the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't like 'em,'' he said. ``I respect 'em. What's
wrong with that?
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think they always think they're bigger and badder than
everyone. They really don't want to give no one else respect. And
we know they don't give us no respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``So why should I give respect or like someone that doesn't give
us respect?''
</P>
<P>
   A year older but no less villainous, Miller is back in search of
the big-game reputation he lost last June at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Miller will turn 35 in August. Much like his coach, Larry Bird,
at the end of his Hall of Fame career, Miller has undergone the
same scrutiny from critics who believed his days as a legitimate
National Basketball Association star were over.
</P>
<P>
   And, like Bird, Miller has shut them up with huge shots and
gaudy numbers that belie his age.
</P>
<P>
   Through 10 postseason games, he is averaging 25 points, making
49 percent of his shots and almost 40 percent of his 3-pointers.
When the Pacers' season was a stake against the Milwaukee Bucks in
the first round, Miller dropped 41 points on the Bucks in Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   He followed up that clutch showing with a 40-point effort
against the Philadelphia 76ers in Game 1 of the semifinal series, a
game in which Jalen Rose also scored 40. Miller has made 26
3-pointers since the regular season ended and 52 of 57 free throws.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1990s, the news media often used a popular
beer-commercial advertisement to convey his playoff prowess. The
last few seasons, it has almost became a tired cliche. But the more
he keeps shooting down youngsters such as Ray Allen and Allen
Iverson, the more apropos ``Miller Time'' again begins to sound.
</P>
<P>
   Miller had just finished practice at the Conseco Fieldhouse
Monday, the day before Game 1 of the sixth Knicks-Pacers playoff
installment in the last eight years.
</P>
<P>
   His ultracasual ensemble _ the tan fisherman's hat pulled down
to his black designer shades, an oversize plaid-collar shirt and
baggy shorts _ suggested he was waiting on the Miami Heat. But he
wanted the Knicks. Anything else seemed to sabotage the script.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I wanted to play New York,'' Miller said. ``Like I
said after Philly in Game 6, I think we need to exorcise some
demons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have beaten New York, but it's never been in a conference
finals. Detroit had to get by Boston. Chicago had to get by
Detroit. So, there's always those teams you have to get by to move
on to the next level. And New York is that team for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller has used more than his mouth and his deep 3-pointers to
express his desire lately. In Game 4 against the 76ers, he
responded to a second flagrant foul on 76ers center Matt Geiger
with a lunging, two-handed shove to Geiger's face. The league
construed Miller's reaction as a punch, and he was fined and
suspended for Game 5. Geiger received a two-game suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Upset that his outburst cost the Pacers a game, Miller returned
in Game 6 to knock the 76ers out on their home floor. Taunting
venomous fans, throwing death stares at the 76ers bench, the player
who once wrote a book entitled ``I Love Being the Enemy'' had
succeeded in making another American city revile his every breath.
</P>
<P>
   No one dislikes Miller more than Manhattan, however.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1993 and 1999, the two teams have met five times in the
playoffs. Twice the Knicks went through Indiana to make it to the
NBA finals. But if the Knicks have inflicted pain on Miller's
career, he has also extracted emotional hurt from the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   The three most memorable moments are part of Madison Square
Garden lore. In 1994, he detonated for 25 of his 39 points in the
fourth quarter of Game 5, giving the Pacers a 3-2 series lead. The
Knicks, however, won in seven games
</P>
<P>
   In Game 1 of their 1995 semifinal meeting, he outdid himself.
With shocking suddenness, Miller scored 8 points with 16.4 seconds
left in the game, including two 3-pointers within 3.1 seconds of
each other to knot the score at 105 and wipe out a 6-point Knick
lead. The Pacers won the series in seven games.
</P>
<P>
   His last great Garden moment came in Game 4 of the 1998 Eastern
semifinals, when he let fly a 3-point bomb in front of a screaming
Spike Lee with 5.9 seconds left, a shot that sent the game into
overtime. The Pacers won the series in five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the best would the first time we ever did beat them
in a series,'' Miller said, recalling the Pacers' 1995 triumph.
``But of course the worst is losing. You never like losing, but I
hate losing to them.''
</P>
<P>
   He has faced off against Allan Houston for the last three years,
losing the duel badly a year ago when the Pacers were stopped in
six games. Miller shot an atrocious 3 for 18 in the deciding game,
taking and missing only three shots in the final quarter. Houston
took him outside and inside, bringing about a changing of the guard
in the East.
</P>
<P>
   Bird was asked if he could ever feel the same contempt for the
Knicks that Miller feels.
</P>
<P>
   He looked deadpan into the assembled gathering and said, ``It's
hard for me to really be ticked off at a team that I have more
championship rings than they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Miller, like Bird. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
