<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ISRAEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ISRAEL'S VOLATILE BORDER  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, May 23:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Israel's hopes for an orderly withdrawal from its security zone
in Southern Lebanon this summer were jolted Monday by the sudden
disintegration of large sections of the Southern Lebanon Army, a
pro-Israeli militia. With Syria's blessing, Lebanese Hezbollah
guerrillas quickly moved into the vacuum left by the militia's
collapse, seizing fortified positions laden with Israeli munitions
and occupying a slice of the zone reaching to the Israeli border.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah's advance, which seems to have caught Israel
unprepared, has increased the danger to Israeli troops still in
Lebanon and to Israeli civilians across the border. Prime Minister
Ehud Barak must respond to these dangers in a way that allows the
Israeli withdrawal to proceed on schedule. He is now sensibly
considering plans for an earlier withdrawal date than the one now
set for July, to minimize the chance for further chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Syria, as the dominant military power in Lebanon,
must see to it that Hezbollah does not use its new positions to
launch rocket attacks on Israeli territory. Any such shellings
could bring Israeli reprisals that could spread beyond the
immediate border area and involve both Lebanon and Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Barak promised during his election campaign last year to
withdraw Israeli troops from Lebanon within a year of his taking
office. That deadline runs out in early July. Most Israelis oppose
maintaining the 22-year-old security zone. It has left Israeli
troops exposed to constant guerrilla attack without significantly
increasing Israel's security.
</P>
<P>
   But carrying out the withdrawal became a lot harder after peace
talks between Israel and Syria broke down in March. Syria's
president, Hafez al-Assad, hoped to see the Lebanese border issue
resolved as part of a package deal that would also returned the
Golan Heights to Syria. With no such bargain in sight, Damascus
seems to feel little incentive to assure a smooth Israeli
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   For years the Arab world demanded that Israel withdraw from
Lebanon as provided under the terms of a United Nations resolution.
But now that Israel has begun doing so, the Syrian and Lebanese
governments are undermining a smooth transition. Syria ought to be
arranging for Lebanese Army units to move into areas vacated by
Israel and its militia allies. By instead permitting Hezbollah
guerrillas to move up to the Israeli border, Syria jeopardizes
Lebanon's chances for future peace and adds a dangerous new element
of instability to the Middle East.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 2235EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
