<DOCNO> NYT20000522.0447 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2857 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-SANDOMIR-COLUMN-N     05-22 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SANDOMIR-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE DAY THAT TIME STOOD STILL  

</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Speed had no place Sunday in the fourth quarter of Game 7 of the
Knicks-Miami grudge match. You could call it timeless basketball if
you were serving time. The quarter lasted 48 minutes 56 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The last two minutes _ the only part of a Knicks-Heat playoff
game that requires your undivided attention _ needed 16:46 to
complete.
</P>
<P>
   What took so long? The quarter did not have an excessive number
of free throws _ 16 were attempted _ or fisticuffs. NBC's Ahmad
Rashad did not conduct Coors Light pouring clinics during timeouts
with his commercial bud, Bill Russell.
</P>
<P>
   The slowdown did not commence until 1:33 remained on the clock.
A Tim Hardaway 3-pointer, putting Miami up, 82-81, prompted a
Knicks timeout. Two minutes of commercials followed. Another
timeout with 26.3 seconds left led to two more minutes of
commercials. A jump ball following a wild shot by Hardaway needed
32 seconds to set up. Having won the jump, Miami called time. More
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   All this resembled a baseball game, minus the dirt kicking,
meandering around home plate, wandering around the mound and
shaking off catchers' signs.
</P>
<P>
   A scramble after Clarence Weatherspoon's missed jumper with six
seconds left required 48 seconds of deliberation by the officials
before they determined that Latrell Sprewell (or another Knick) had
called a timeout. Another 90 seconds of spots ensued. A
recapitulation of the frantic sequence cost 40 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   When Charlie Ward could not pass the ball in, he called time. So
NBC sneaked in a 30-second spot. NBC returned before the timeout
ended with 48 seconds of players' backs. Finally, the nearly
50-minute quarter ended with Ward's inbounds pass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The elasticized fourth quarter did not bother viewers much. The
game generated an 8.7 overnight Nielsen rating, up 16 percent from
the comparable game last year. So far, it is NBC's highest-rated
playoff game this postseason. The last half-hour produced an 11.8
rating.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's Bill Walton and Steve Jones never acknowledged the
creeping pace of game time. Had he noted it, Walton would have
surely pronounced it ``horrible.'' And Walton, especially, offered
a characteristically provocative performance in Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the struggling Knicks forward Marcus Camby, Walton
said, ``The effort is there, but never mistake activity for
achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   When Knicks forward Kurt Thomas picked up a silly foul, then a
technical foul, Jones said his lack of control ``is his Waterloo.''
Walton, however, is too enamored of Thomas, often praising him as
if he were Charles Oakley.
</P>
<P>
   Walton rarely let up on his idea that Miami Coach Pat Riley
should not rest Alonzo Mourning at all. Riley subsequently rested
Mourning, who scored 14 points in the first quarter, plus Dan
Majerle and Jamal Mashburn, and all at once, early in the second.
When the Knicks tied the game at 29-29, after a 9-0 run, Walton
said: ``Riley only has himself to blame. He takes three guys out,
they lose the lead.''
</P>
<P>
   When Jones raised the notion later in the game that Riley should
rest Mourning again, Walton loudly said, ``Don't give him any
ideas!''
</P>
<P>
   Walton railed when Knicks Coach Jeff Van Gundy sat Sprewell.
``You can't do that,'' he said. ``You're down 4 points in the
fourth quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who exists to refute Walton's world view, said: ``You've
got 10 minutes to play. You know Miami will go on another
drought.''
</P>
<P>
   Walton said: ``I have never seen Latrell Sprewell need a rest.
Ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones persisted, saying Van Gundy saw a need to refocus
Sprewell, who was in a scoring drought, rather than give him a
rest. Trumped, Walton did not reply.
</P>
<P>
   In close games, Walton has toned down his extreme analyses _
which often sound contemptuous _ and his verbal excesses. Still, he
is blunt about unintelligent play, and impatient when great players
foul up.
</P>
<P>
   When Mourning risked stealing a pass to Ewing, who dunked it to
put the Knicks up for good, 83-82, with 1:20 to go, Walton said:
``He's blocking every shot coming at him. Ewing hasn't had a go-to
move all day, and Alonzo Mourning makes an ill-advised decision to
come over his back.''
</P>
<P>
   Walton, Jones and Tom Hammond will call the Eastern Conference
finals between the Knicks and Indiana on NBC, while Bob Costas and
Doug Collins are describing the Portland-Los Angeles Lakers Western
Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Where is Marv Albert, who will replace Costas in NBC's top
play-by-play slot next season? His deal with the MSG Network, which
employs him to call Knicks games on WFAN Radio and be the host for
``MSG SportsDesk,'' keeps him from calling any Knicks games during
the week, so Dick Stockton will call the Knicks-Indiana games on
TNT Tuesday and Thursday night. Meanwhile, NBC would not put Albert
on the series, out of loyalty to Hammond. When his laryngitis
clears up, Albert will call some of the games on WFAN. Gus Johnson
is assigned to call Games 1 and 2.
</P>
<P>
   John Andariese, the Knicks' WFAN analyst, who was suspended by
MSG from Knicks radio games before the season ended, is offering
pregame, halftime and postgame analysis for NBA.com TV, the
league's network. It is peculiar that Andariese can work for the
league but is still barred from WFAN games due to a violation of
Madison Square Garden's ticket policy. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
