<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-TOBACCO-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUNITIVE STAGE OPENS IN SUIT BY ILL SMOKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK BRAGG c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A lawyer for the plaintiffs in the punitive damages
stage of a landmark case against cigarette makers stood before
jurors Monday and slapped himself on the wrist, the punishment he
said tobacco executives felt they deserved for decades of
misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Cigarette makers want the country to believe ``they are good
boys and girls'' who have learned their lesson, said the lawyer,
Stanley Rosenblatt, in opening statements in what could be a
multibillion-dollar punitive judgment in Miami-Dade Circuit Court
against top cigarette manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if they have changed, that does not free them from paying
for wrongful behavior for decades,'' said Rosenblatt, whose
clients, three sick smokers who represent 300,000 to 500,000
Florida smokers, are seeking a $100 billion judgment.
</P>
<P>
   But Dan Webb, a lawyer for the country's largest cigarette
maker, Philip Morris, told the jury in his opening statement that
he would offer ``significant and compelling evidence'' that
cigarette makers had changed, that they now recognized that
cigarettes as a ``dangerous product'' that should not be marketed
to teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   The jury that will now decide on punitive damages in the case
has already found that cigarettes are a potentially deadly and
addictive product and has already awarded $12.7 million in
compensatory damages to the plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt said in his opening statement that the cigarette
makers had not really changed how they marketed their product. He
said the defendants, which include Philip Morris Inc., R.J.
Reynolds, Brown &AMP; Williamson, the Lorillard Tobacco Co. and Liggett
Group Inc., still ``target youths and children.''
</P>
<P>
   He said cigarette makers are still running full-page ads in
Rolling Stone and Entertainment Weekly, aimed at young people, and
in other magazines aimed at women.
</P>
<P>
   Most smokers are men, and if the industry really wants only to
maintain its business, why is it advertising in magazines mostly
read by others? Rosenblatt asked.
</P>
<P>
   The industry's assertions that it has changed is a public
relations ploy, he said. ``They're on the same page they've always
been on.''
</P>
<P>
   But Webb argued that tobacco companies have changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world has not stood still while you have been sitting as
jurors,'' he told the panel of six jurors and six alternates who
have been weighing evidence in various phases of the lawsuit for
almost 20 months.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for tobacco companies are expected to argue that, after
years of resisting scientific findings of the destructive nature of
tobacco use tobacco companies now accept that their product is
addictive and harmful.
</P>
<P>
   Top executives have changed, Webb said, giving way to a new
breed like Michael Szymanczyk, president and chief executive of
Philip Morris, which manufacturers the country's best-selling
brand, Marlboro.
</P>
<P>
   Szymanczyk believes tobacco ``is a dangerous product,'' but also
``a completely legal product.'' He said the company spends millions
to discourage teen-agers from smoking.
</P>
<P>
   He asked jurors to consider that the industry has changed, and
reminded them that they do not have to award any punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   Webb told the jury that the country's top five cigarette makers
are committed to $254 billion in settlements with all 50 states
over a 25-year period that ends in 2021.
</P>
<P>
   But Rosenblatt said the states do not have to give that money to
smokers and that the industry has yet to pay ``10 cents'' to the
people damaged by their product.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife's been on oxygen for eight years, has emphysema, and a
brain tumor, and doctors told us it was from smoking,'' said Bill
Herroin, a retiree who moved to Florida four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He came to the courtroom with his wife, Frances Herroin. She sat
quietly in a wheelchair, hooked to a respirator.
</P>
<P>
   Szymanczyk, in a deposition, said Philip Morris could not
survive a judgment even half as large as the $100 billion listed in
the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would not be able to pay this money if it was due in 30
days, or in two years, for that matter,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Rosenblatt said his clients would take payments on the
judgment, if it were to be awarded.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington Monday, the U.S. Supreme Court rejected efforts by
the cigarette makers to replace the presiding judge, Robert Kaye.
Kaye is a former smoker with a heart ailment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
