<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT HER DAY JOB, CLINTON IS THE HOSTESS OF A STATE DINNER
</HEADLINE>
  (With NY-UNDECIDED, NY-GIULIANI-NRA, NY-GIULIANI, NY-LAZIO) 
 By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Officially, Hillary Rodham Clinton, the Senate
candidate, took a night off Monday night. But she did not lounge on
the sofa at home in Chappaqua, N.Y., with a good book or soak her
tired feet in a White House tub.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Clinton's first lady incarnation was dancing and dining
and toasting at a state dinner for President Thabo Mbeki of South
Africa and his wife, Zanele.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton has reduced her first lady duties since
starting her New York Senate campaign, the White House social
office has remained up and running, providing Clinton with a series
of marquee social occasions to break up the monotony of the
campaign trail. Campaign food is a long way from the saffron
pistachio couscous, apricot ginger glazed lamb and cape
gooseberries that were served Monday night in a large tent on the
South Lawn to accommodate a larger-than-usual crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Her campaign staffers play down the importance of Clinton's
duties as first lady in her effort to replace Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, who is retiring. It will be her stances on health care
and education and other issues of importance to New Yorkers, they
say, that will determine the election results, not which heads of
state she welcomes to the State Dining Room.
</P>
<P>
   But the dinners, which receive scant attention outside
Washington, do give Clinton the opportunity to reward loyalists in
her campaign with coveted invitations.
</P>
<P>
   In February, at a dinner for the king and queen of Spain,
Clinton invited her campaign scheduler, Evan Ryan, but there were
few obvious campaign backers among the diners.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, however, many New Yorkers, most of them
African-American, received embossed invitations. These included the
Rev. Floyd H. Flake, the former congressman and pastor of the Allen
AME Church in Queens, who had just endorsed Clinton, and William A.
Johnson Jr., the mayor of Rochester, who has campaigned at her
side.
</P>
<P>
   C. Virginia Fields, the Manhattan borough president, attended,
as did David Dinkins, the former mayor, and New York Reps. Charles
B. Rangel, Gregory W. Meeks and Louise M. Slaughter. Other New
Yorkers in attendance included the director Spike Lee, state
Comptroller H. Carl McCall and Howard Rubin, chairman of the
computer science department at Hunter College.
</P>
<P>
   Although state dinners rarely make the nightly news, they are
followed closely in the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   Rangel said some of Clinton's duties as first lady do help her
campaign, but they are the substantive issue-oriented duties, not
the social ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Co-hosting a dinner is just not that newsworthy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton did emerge from Monday night's dinner with something
more tangible than the goodwill of some supporters. Her South
African counterpart gave her a 12-piece set of napkin rings in the
shape of African animals. There was a lion, an elephant, a leopard
and, perhaps most important for campaign strategy, a buffalo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 2248EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
