<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOX-CRAMER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX NEWS SUES TO FORCE COMMENTATOR BACK TO CABLE PROGRAM  

</HEADLINE>
   By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Fox News Network, which previously criticized
James J. Cramer for plugging a stock he owned on TheStreet.com
cable television program, went to court Monday to try to force
Cramer to continue appearing on the program.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, a unit of the News Corp., said it filed suit in New York
state court against TheStreet.com, an investor Internet site that
produces the program, and against Cramer, a hedge fund manager and
co-founder of TheStreet.com, who is a commentator for the program.
</P>
<P>
   The suit seeks to force TheStreet.com to keep producing the
program, which it intends to halt after this coming weekend's
broadcast, and to force Cramer to appear on it.
</P>
<P>
   In the suit, Fox said TheStreet.com and Cramer had ``blatantly
disregarded their obligations to Fox News in a transparent attempt
to extricate themselves from business deals they no longer like.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit asks for injunctions requiring the program to continue,
and barring TheStreet.com from reaching an agreement with any other
network. It also seeks unspecified monetary damages.
</P>
<P>
   Cramer, who has a separate contract with Fox, has not appeared
on the show since the taped April 14 program for broadcast the
following day. On that program, he recommended the stock of
TheStreet.com itself. More than a week later, a Fox spokesman was
quoted in The Daily News as criticizing Cramer. ``Despite offering
full disclosure of his ownership position, we do not approve of the
touting of stock for personal gain on the air,'' the spokesman was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
   The Street.com cited that statement as being a new policy in
announcing last week that it would stop producing the program. It
later relented, and last week's show was taped, but Fox said
TheStreet.com had notified it that this weekend's program would be
the last.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's suit maintains that TheStreet.com has a legal obligation
to continue making the program until May 7, 2001, and that Cramer
is under contract to Fox to appear on the weekly broadcast at least
40 times a year.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for TheStreet.com declined to comment on the suit,
saying she had not seen it.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Seiler, a lawyer for Cramer, said Monday night that
``through its prior actions, Fox News has repudiated the contract
with Cramer and he is available to appear on other programming.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``While we have not seen the specific allegations of
the complaint, we believe them to be totally without merit.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times Co. owns a 6.3 percent stake in TheStreet.com
and operates a nine-member joint newsroom with it that files
articles for the Web sites of both TheStreet.com and The New York
Times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 2249EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
