<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DIAGEO IN TALKS FOR ALL BESTFOODS
</P>
<P>
   Diageo, which owns Pillsbury bakery goods and Haagen-Daz ice
cream, is negotiating to buy all or part of Bestfoods, the maker of
Skippy peanut butter and Hellmann's mayonnaise, executives close to
the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   Diageo is holding trans-Atlantic negotiations with Bestfoods in
hopes of combining Bestfoods' bakery business with its own bakery
business, and possibly spinning off the newly combined unit into a
company that might be controlled by Bestfoods' management, the
executives said.
</P>
<P>
   MORE CONSOLIDATION IN B-TO-B SOFTWARE
</P>
<P>
   The consolidation of the business-to-business software market
accelerated with two big deals. Vignette said it was acquiring
OnDisplay in a $1.7 billion stock swap, while WebMethods is buying
Active Software in a stock deal valued at $1.3 billion. Shares of
Vignette fell $8.9375, to $34.875, while OnDisplay rose 87.5 cents,
to $54.125. WebMethods fell $15, to $72, while Active Software
dropped 93.75 cents, to $32.0625, all on Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   BATTLE OVER TRADE BILL BEGINNING
</P>
<P>
   With just two days before Congress decides whether to enhance
economic ties with China, corporate supporters opened a $1 million
advertising blitz and labor opponents stormed Capitol Hill as both
sides struggled to recruit the handful of undecided lawmakers who
hold the key to victory or defeat.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT FILES UNEXPECTED BRIEF
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. filed an unexpected brief with a federal judge
that quoted from a 5-year-old government legal document in which
the Justice Department argued that breaking up Microsoft would be
``against the public interest.'' The document risks annoying the
judge, who did not ask for another filing from Microsoft when he
laid out the schedule for the remedy phase of the antitrust case.
</P>
<P>
   NEW EFFORT FOR GLOBAL ACCOUNTING
</P>
<P>
   The goal of establishing worldwide accounting standards _ making
it possible for companies to compile one set of books for investors
everywhere _ is being promoted by new efforts to put together an
international standards setter.
</P>
<P>
   NAPSTER RECEIVES NEW FINANCING
</P>
<P>
   Napster, the Internet music site that has incurred the wrath of
the recording industry, received $15 million in new financing from
Hummer Winblad Venture Partners, which also placed one of its
partners, Hank Barry, as the company's interim chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   GRUNER &AMP; JAHR APPOINTS NEW CHIEF
</P>
<P>
   Gruner &AMP; Jahr, the publisher of seven consumer magazines in the
United States, including McCall's, Fitness and Parents, has named
Daniel B. Brewster chief executive, three months after its previous
chief departed. Brewster, who has resigned as president and chief
executive of American Express Publishing, will start his new
position on June 5.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO EXCHANGES STEP UP TALKS
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Board of Trade and the Chicago Board Options
Exchange have intensified merger talks in recent weeks as a
congressional proposal threatens to put them in more direct
competition trading stock derivatives.
</P>
<P>
   FOX SUES FINANCIAL COMMENTATOR
</P>
<P>
   The Fox News Network has filed suit in New York state court to
force James J. Cramer, co-founder of TheStreet.com and commentator
on its Fox cable television program, to continue appearing on the
program. Fox News previously criticized Cramer for plugging a stock
he owned on the program.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE TELECOM PURSING PHONE DEAL
</P>
<P>
   France Telecom and a Polish partner, Kulczyk Holding, received
exclusive rights to negotiate the acquisition of a 35 percent stake
in the former Polish telephone monopoly for roughly $4 billion. The
deal ushers in what will presumably be the final steps in the sale
of Poland's state phone company to private investors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
