<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-FLYERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS PLAY WITH PRECISION TO AVOID PLAYOFF ELIMINATION 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Perhaps Coach Larry Robinson's angry outburst
will have a positive effect on the Devils for the remainder of
their playoff series with the Flyers. Monday night, the Devils
played with desperation and avoided elimination in the Eastern
Conference finals with a convincing 4-1 victory over the Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils stayed focused from beginning to end in the physical
battle at First Union Center, building a three-goal lead.
</P>
<P>
   From Martin Brodeur in goal to the last player on the fourth
line, all the Devils performed with inspiration after New Jersey
had lost three games in a row to trail in the four-of-seven-game
series.
</P>
<P>
   Their 3-1 defeat on Saturday night inspired a dressing room
tirade from Robinson, who was incensed over the team's lack of
aggressiveness.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils, trailing the Flyers by three games to two in the
series, will meet Philadelphia in Game 6 on Wednesday night at
Continental Arena. If a seventh game is necessary it will be played
here on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils' Jason Arnott, Bobby Holik, Petr Sykora and Patrik
Elias scored against Brian Boucher, who faced 30 shots.
</P>
<P>
   Valery Zelepukin scored the lone goal for the Flyers against
Brodeur, who faced 21 shots.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils dominated play in the first period and took a big
lead when Arnott scored his fourth goal of the playoffs at 12
minutes 25 seconds, and Holik scored his third of the playoffs with
4:45 left before the first intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Arnott's goal came during the Devils' first power play.
Positioned at the left circle, he one-timed a pass from Brian
Rafalski and beat Boucher to the short side.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Malakhov started the action that led to Holik's goal by
keeping the puck in Philadelphia's zone. After Jay Pandolfo touched
the puck, it went to Claude Lemieux, who shot it on net.
</P>
<P>
   After the puck was knocked loose in the crease, Holik was in
position to convert from close range on the left of Boucher.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils almost scored at about the seven-minute mark of the
game, but were unable to get to rebounds after shots by Malakhov
and Arnott. They took 14 shots in the first period while the Flyers
had only six against Brodeur.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils went to work on offense, after killing a penalty to
Malakhov that carried over into the second period, and established
a three-goal lead on Sykora's sixth in the playoffs. Scott Stevens
started the play with a pass on the left flank to Elias, who found
Sykora alone near the right side of the crease for an easy goal at
1:47.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur and the Devils' defense went through some hectic moments
in the 12th minute of the period, when the Flyers had three chances
in the same sequence. Brodeur stopped one Flyer shot. One sailed
wide and the other went over the crossbar.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils were successful killing a penalty to Steve Kelly in
the period, but faltered when Malakhov took his second penalty in
the game with 5:05 left in the session.
</P>
<P>
   Zelepukin scored his first in the playoffs 50 seconds into the
penalty when he deked Brodeur with a move from right to left.
Zelepukin's power-play goal was only the second the Devils had
allowed on 44 attempts by the opposition in the playoffs and the
first they had yielded in 11 playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils regained the three-goal lead on Elias' fifth score of
the playoffs 54 seconds into the third period. He beat Boucher with
a backhander after a giveaway by the Flyers at their blue line.
</P>
</TEXT>
