<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2871 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PRIVACY-FTC-SFCHRON &LR;      05-22 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIVACY-FTC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PRIVACY PROPOSAL RANKLES INTERNET INDUSTRY  &HT;     By CARRIE KIRBY 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Internet industry groups lashed out Monday at
the Federal Trade Commission's recommendation that Congress make
laws establishing basic online privacy standards.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC's recommendation to create the first law to govern
Internet privacy is a departure from the commission's past stance
that the industry could enforce its own privacy rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem may be bigger than industry self-regulation itself
can deal with,'' Commissioner Mozelle Thompson said. He was quick
to point out that self-regulation initiatives such as the Truste
and BBBOnline privacy seal programs would still be an important
part of online privacy under the recommendation. The proposal,
released Monday, was approved Friday in a 3-to-2 vote by
commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC's report, which it will present to the Senate Commerce
Committee on Thursday, calls for a law requiring Web sites to give
Internet users a choice in what information is collected about
them, and let users have access to that information. Sites would
also have to keep data about consumers secure and post clear
privacy policies.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC's change in direction was prompted by a survey it
conducted earlier this year showing that only 40 percent of Web
sites abide by the basic practices of choice, access, security and
notice that the law would require.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC has also investigated possible privacy violations by a
growing number of Web sites, including online advertising firm
DoubleClick and portal Yahoo. So far, the commission has not
concluded that either of those sites actually committed any privacy
violations.
</P>
<P>
   Two industry groups, the Information Technology Association of
America and the Online Privacy Alliance, called the legislation
unnecessary, and said the Internet industry is already doing a good
job protecting consumers' privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Privacy policies are now ubiquitous online,'' said OPA adviser
Christine Varney, a former FTC commissioner. ``These policies
empower consumers to make informed choices about what personal
information to share.''
</P>
<P>
   The FTC's study did find that 100 percent of the Web's
most-popular sites post privacy policies. However, the FTC's
Thompson, who voted in favor of the recommendation, said that just
posting a policy does not mean that sites are adequately
safeguarding consumers' privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still some real issues about the quality of what
they're providing in terms of privacy policies,'' Thompson said,
pointing out that many Web sites' policies do not address all
aspects of consumer privacy. And some sites do not abide by their
own policies, Thompson added.
</P>
<P>
   Among local Internet companies, opinions about the
recommendation were split.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that self-regulation is the best way to go,'' said
Yahoo President Jeff Mallet. Co-founder Jerry Yang pointed out that
enforcing a privacy law would be difficult given the different ways
the Internet is used.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want my financial data treated very differently from my
e-mail and my health records,'' Yang said.
</P>
<P>
   Netcentives, a San Francisco company that helps Web sites reward
their users with frequent-flier miles and other incentives, called
the FTC's decision reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a gap between the (privacy) notices companies
post and their behavior,'' said David McKay, vice president of
marketing at Netcentives subsidiary Post Communications.
</P>
<P>
   David Steer, a spokesman for the Truste privacy seal program,
praised the FTC's move, calling it an ``endorsement'' of Truste and
the concept of privacy seals. Web sites that belong to Truste will
likely be compliant with any laws Congress comes out with, Steer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Internet privacy advocates, who have long called for the
government to protect Internet users' privacy, had restrained
praise for the recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   David Sobel of the Electronic Privacy I Center, said the
proposal should have been more detailed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're asking congress to provide what we would consider the
bare minimum of protection,'' Sobel said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the recommendation should have laid out what
compensation Internet users would get if their privacy rights are
violated, Sobel said.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Thompson said the recommendation was purposely kept
vague because of the fast-changing nature of Internet technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mistake for a legislative vehicle in this area to be
too detailed _ by its very nature it would become outdated,''
Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republican leaders believe regulation would be premature in
the young world of electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quickest way to kill the Internet is to regulate it to
death,'' said Ken Johnson, a spokesman for Rep. W.J. ``Billy''
Tauzin, R-La., chairman of the House Commerce subcommittee on trade
and consumer protection.
</P>
<P>
   But a group of Democrats, led by Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C.,
ranking member of the Senate Commerce Committee, said Monday that
they will introduce comprehensive privacy legislation to keep
companies from profiting from the sale of personal data gleaned
from unwitting consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Whether such legislation could get traction in Congress this
year appears doubtful. Lawmakers already have a full plate of
technology-related legislation awaiting action.
</P>
<P>
   Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carrie Kirby at  &LR; ckirby(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
