<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2873 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BRAZIL-SATELLITES-ART     05-22 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-SATELLITES-ART-(1800)2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL BUILDS SPACE PORT FOR MORE EFFICIENT SATELLITE LAUNCHINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT20 and graphic are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALCANTARA, Brazil _ In the satellite-launching business, as in
real estate, location is everything. Because of that simple fact,
the space port the Brazilian government has built here on the
eastern edge of the Amazon basin and is making available to foreign
companies and governments may soon become a valuable piece of
property.
</P>
<P>
   Situated 2 degrees south of the Equator, the Alcantara launching
center, built by the Brazilian military two decades ago, has become
the focal point of what is perhaps the most ambitious unmanned
space program in any developing country. But it is the boom in
telecommunications satellites that is likely to ensure it a
prosperous future.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of 1998, we calculated there were going to be 800
satellites launched around the world between 2000 and 2004, and
that billions of dollars were going to be spent,'' Ronaldo
Sardenberg, Brazil's science and technology minister, said in an
interview in the capital, Brasilia. ``We decided that we wanted to
take advantage of those favorable circumstances and that Alcantara
could and should be an important player on the international
market.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of Alcantara's proximity to the Equator, rockets
launched here can gain orbit faster and carry heavier payloads than
those launched elsewhere. This translates into substantial savings
for users and a longer useful life for the satellites. Brazilian
officials estimate, for instance, that a launching from Alcantara
can be as much as 30 percent more efficient than one from Cape
Canaveral, which is situated at 28 degrees north latitude.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the areas north and east of here are largely jungle
or ocean, meaning that in case of an accident, debris is unlikely
to fall on populated areas.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Alcantara, about 2,500 miles southeast of Miami, is
able to offer clients a choice of polar or equatorial orbits or any
trajectory in between.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world needs a greater availability of launch sites,'' Luiz
Gylvan Meira, director of the Brazilian Space Agency, said in an
interview, ``and while the niche that Alcantara finds will be
dictated by the market, it is a launch site that is both good and
cheap. It is good because of both its location and its
availability, and it will be cheap because the Brazilian government
has already put in the necessary infrastructure.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilian effort to turn Alcantara into a leading spaceport
got significant help in April, when the United States and Brazil
signed an accord that permits the launching of American satellites
on American launchers from the base here. In return, Brazil agreed
to a series of safeguards intended to prevent it from acquiring the
technology of its American clients or passing that information on
to other countries.
</P>
<P>
   The site here, its privileged geographic position
notwithstanding, is not the only one seeking a share of any
satellite wealth. Many European nations use a site at Kourou in
French Guiana, 5 degrees north of the Equator. [On May 19, Guyana
signed a deal with a Texas company, Beal Aerospace Technologies, to
build a launching site there.)
</P>
<P>
   Various proposals have also been floated to build spaceports on
the east coast of Africa and the east coast of Australia; because
of the earth's rotation, a site permitting a launch eastward over
water is always preferred. In addition, there have been efforts to
launch satellites from a sea platform in international waters in
the Pacific, as well as from high-altitude aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   But since United States companies account for about 80 percent
of the satellite market, April's agreement gives Brazil an
advantage over its competitors. There are 17 other launching sites
operating around the world, but only Brazil is now authorized to
launch both rockets and satellites of American manufacture.
</P>
<P>
   The Alcantara agreement, said Anthony Harrington, the United
States ambassador to Brazil, ``is symbolic both of the strength of
the U.S.-Brazil relationship and the level of trust that is
developing between the two governments.'' He predicted that several
American companies would soon begin operating here, adding, ``Cape
Canaveral has many advantages, but being right next to the Equator
is not one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sardenberg, the Brazilian technology minister, said ``eight of
the top 15 aerospace firms in the United States'' have already
visited the site here, including, according to the visitors'
logbook at the space center, Lockheed Martin, Orbital Sciences,
Rockwell International and Boeing. He noted that both Cape
Canaveral and Kourou ``have their schedules full,'' adding, ``Our
objective is that this base be a profit center that can accommodate
many users at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Last November, Brazil signed a wide-ranging agreement with
Ukraine. It calls for a consortium also including Fiat Avio of
Italy to use Ukrainian-made Tsyklon-4 rockets, a liquid-fuel,
three-stage rocket based on the Soviet SS-9 ballistic missile, to
launch as many as 60 satellites here over five years, starting in
2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is space for everyone here,'' said Col. Jose Campos
Lobato, commander of the base, with about 400 military personnel
and 200 civilians. ``We have almost 250 square miles of land, so we
can easily install four additional launch pads here and still have
some room left over.''
</P>
<P>
   Construction of the base here began in 1983, with the first
satellite launching six years later, after nearly $300 million had
been spent on roads, electricity, a command center, an airport and
other infrastructure. Since then, 276 satellites or rockets have
been launched from Alcantara, including 36 by NASA, though the
great majority of these were suborbital rockets.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Brazilian officials have made it clear that their space
ambitions go far beyond offering a launch site for others' use.
They hope to supply some of the satellites and rockets that will be
sent up, and have maintained a wide-ranging research and
development effort with that aim.
</P>
<P>
   The center of that program is in Sao Jose dos Campos, nearly
2,000 miles south of here. The National Institute for Space
Research has its headquarters there, engaging in activities ranging
from weather forecasting to industrial testing, and on an adjoining
campus is the Center for Aerospace Technology, controlled by the
Brazilian Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   The importance that Brazil attaches to its space program can be
seen by looking at the institute's budget: as other government
agencies tighten their belts, it has received a 36 percent increase
this year. The government intends profits from future launchings to
go to research and development.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a country like this, with all the problems we have, you
cannot do science just for the sake of doing science,'' said Marcio
Nogueira Barbosa, the director of the space institute. ``You have
to show results.''
</P>
<P>
   The pride of the Brazilian space effort is the Cbers satellite,
which has been jointly developed with China in a $300 million
program. The first of these satellites, which carry three
high-resolution cameras to study environmental and agricultural
conditions, was launched from Taiyuan, a Chinese base, in October,
and a second is being assembled at the Brazilian institute's campus
in Sao Jose dos Campos, with launching tentatively scheduled in the
second half of next year.
</P>
<P>
   Brazilian officials said that at least two more satellites are
likely to be launched with the Chinese, in an effort to turn the
program into a money-making operation that can compete with NASA's
Landsat program. ``Since we are a big buyer of satellite images,''
Sardenberg said, ``it is only natural that we would also want to
supply high-definition photographs to a market that is so large and
constantly in search of images from different angles.''
</P>
<P>
   Brazil is also a member of the consortium building the
international space station, the only developing country to be
invited to join the 15-nation group. A Brazilian astronaut is being
trained in the United States for that mission, and Brazilian
companies have been awarded about $120 million in construction
contracts for the space vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The weak link in the country's space program has been its rocket
program, which aims at building a reliable launching vehicle that
is cheaper than American or European rockets. An initial attempt to
launch a four-stage, solid-fuel missile in 1997 failed, as did a
second attempt in December, which led to widespread criticism and
mockery in the press.
</P>
<P>
   Still, officials say they intend to go ahead with the rocket
program. ``These things happen, it goes with the territory,'' said
Meira, the space agency's director, ``and there is no indication
that our rocket has a fundamental structural flaw. It's just that
other aspects of our space effort have developed and advanced more
rapidly.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the rocket and satellite programs began in the 1970s, when
Brazil was ruled by a military dictatorship. At that time, the
government encouraged the founding of companies to manufacture jet
aircraft for military use and another to make tanks and armored
personnel carriers, both of which were also based in Sao Jose dos
Campos. These quickly found markets in Latin America, the Mideast
and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, there were uncertainties at first whether the
objectives of Brazil's space effort were scientific and commercial
or primarily military. Those concerns lingered after the military
handed over power to a democratic civilian government in 1985 and
saw many of its other pet projects, like a costly nuclear program,
mothballed.
</P>
<P>
   As late as 1990, in the months before the Persian Gulf war,
Washington expressed concern about Brazil supplying satellite and
rocket technology to Iraq, a longtime buyer of Brazilian armored
vehicles. Gen. Hugo Piva, a former director of the Center for
Aerospace Technology, who was a strong advocate of a Brazilian
nuclear program, has acknowledged that he sought rocket parts on
the black market in an effort to accelerate the rocket program.
</P>
<P>
   But United States officials say that all such concerns have been
eliminated in recent years. Brazil, after refusing to do so during
the years of military rule, has signed a series of international
agreements, including ones on nonproliferation, that paved the way
for April's accord.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an evolutionary process in which they have moved in
the right direction,'' Harrington, the American envoy, said. ``We
don't have those concerns. On the other hand, the agreement is a
safeguards agreement, and it involves mutual assurances'' to
American companies likely to launch from here that ``there is no
risk of their technology being broadcast in an unauthorized
manner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
