<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUDY WHO? GOP EMBRACES SUCCESSOR  

</HEADLINE>
   By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. _ Republicans across the state began
chorusing Monday that Rep. Rick A. Lazio was turning out to be a
better Senate candidate than their first choice, Mayor Rudolph W.
Giuliani, who dropped out last week because of prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   As Lazio completed two days of flying around the state for
campaign appearances, his fledgling candidacy also received the
backing of the state Conservative Party Monday, a crucial
endorsement that could carry as many as 300,000 votes. No
Republican has won a statewide election without the Conservative
Party endorsement since 1974. Giuliani and Michael Long, the
chairman of the party, spent much of the last year in a standoff
over the endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows what enthusiasm can do,'' said James Cavanaugh, the
Westchester County Republican chairman who presided over a noisy
late-afternoon rally for Lazio here as people chanted ``Let's Go
Rick!'' and ``Way to Go, Lazio!''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's energizing people in a way that the mayor didn't,''
Cavanaugh added. ``You know, people would call me up and they would
say, `I want to volunteer for the mayor. What can I do?' And I
often didn't know what to ask them to do, because the mayor wasn't
really getting out and doing things. People now say, `Well, what
can I do for Rick Lazio?' I've got stuff for them to do. He's made
it plain: `I want rallies. I want people out registering voters.
We're going to do phone banks.'''
</P>
<P>
   This was Lazio's final stop on the 48-hour campaign swing that
took him from Long Island to Buffalo to Rochester to Syracuse to
Binghamton to Elmira to Utica to Watertown to Albany and then to
Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   At every stop, Lazio was cheerful, disciplined and nearly on
time as he repeated his stump speech about working in his father's
auto parts shop and growing up clamming in the waters off Long
Island _ a contrast to his opponent, Hillary Rodham Clinton, who
moved to the state five months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, who announced his candidacy on Saturday, also said he
would be back again and again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope you don't get sick of me, you're going to see me so
often,'' he told Republicans at a breakfast in Elmira this morning.
In Westchester County, he said, ``I hope you don't get sick of me,
I'm going to be back so often.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio traveled on a seven-seat jet with his wife and two young
daughters, Molly Ann, 7, and Kelsey, 6. In Elmira, the two girls
stood on a chair, took the microphone and said, ``Vote for my
Dad,'' during the hubbub after their father's speech. Republicans
who noticed them looked enthralled.
</P>
<P>
   In Albany, Gov. George E. Pataki and William D. Powers, the
state Republican Party chairman, presided over an airport rally of
100 whistling, cheering and clapping supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a man who 12 hours after he declared his candidacy can
get in front of the national media and lay out an agenda for New
York because he knows New York,'' Pataki said. In August, the
governor's endorsement of Giuliani was considerably more lukewarm.
</P>
<P>
   In Elmira, Sidney S. Graubard, a Chemung County legislator, was
equally welcoming of Lazio. ``In fact, I preferred him all along,''
he said. ``He's got the personality. You can see that he's a clean
kind of candidate. Rudy's ignored too many people. He'd be invited
to things, and he'd never come up.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, so many Republicans were saying such similar things all
day that it brought up the question of why they had ever supported
Giuliani in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The machine got behind the mayor,'' said Suzanne Swanson, 56,
a Westchester County legislator, who was referring to the party
leaders in Albany. But then she added: ``I think what happened was
the mayor presented himself as a viable candidate with a war chest
to take on Hillary Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenia Mucha, the governor's chief political aide, said:
``Everybody's happy. We're all one big happy family.''
</P>
<P>
   Mucha also said that if reporters missed the oversize
personalities and melodrama of the old Hillary-Rudy race, that was
fine with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``If reporters are bored by this campaign, then it means it's a
good campaign,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
