<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT DID THE
 RIGHT THING IN TV-SEX RUL
 ING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court on Monday made it theoretically easier
for kids to see sex on television.
</P>
<P>
   You should be glad.
</P>
<P>
   The court ruled that Congress vio lated free-speech rights when
it re quired cable TV systems to restrict sex-oriented networks to
the wee hours if they don't fully scramble the signal for
non-subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   I know what you're thinking: Yeah, yeah, the bleeding-heart
newspaper guy wants to protect First Amend ment rights at all
costs, no matter what the damage to society. And there is an
element of truth in that - the First Amendment keeps Mary Tyler
Moore from suing me, after all, when I say her TV movie stinks.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a bigger issue here than whether a channel-surfer
catches a glimpse of a topless woman on the Playboy Channel when
looking for The 700 Club. And it's a big one: parenting.
</P>
<P>
   Various groups have long argued that TV is too (take your pick:
violent, profane, obscene, etc.); that either the networks or the
govern ment have a responsibility to keep the airwaves safe for our
children. The same people will doubtless be outraged by the court's
decision, which is that same argument wrapped in different clothing
(or in this case, no clothing at all).
</P>
<P>
   These people are wrong. The respon sibility rests squarely with
parents.
</P>
<P>
   Being a parent is a tough job. I know. And the court's decision
makes that job a little tougher.
</P>
<P>
   But when the problem is TV, there is a nearly flawless solution.
It's called an off button, and parents should use it.
</P>
<P>
   And then explain why they did.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, some kids will sneak and watch, anyway. Some kids will
sneak a beer, too, or take an uncomfortable puff on a cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   I fully expect my daughter to one day try things I wish she
wouldn't. And when she makes what I hope are the right choices, I'd
like to be part of the reason.
</P>
<P>
   That's what makes the job worth doing. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-00 2314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
