<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER RACE, MAYOR FINDS RENEWED JOY IN DAY JOB  

</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC LIPTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He was boasting, once again, about New York City's
war on graffiti and street litter. He proclaimed _ somewhat
belatedly _ May as Pet Adoption Month. And by nightfall, Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani was out on Gracie Mansion's front lawn, holding a
party for the city's theater community, complete with a performance
by a star of ``The Lion King.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no mistaking it Monday. Candidate Rudy is out. And
Mayor Rudy is back in, and so far is sticking with his promised
kinder, gentler style.
</P>
<P>
   For the retired Senate candidate, this all was somewhat of a
relief, as he let Rick A. Lazio, his apparent replacement, dash
madly across New York state. The mayor stayed on home turf Monday,
tending to the details of running his favorite city and looking for
yet more opportunities to use his new favorite word, ``love.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is great. It is great. I love being the mayor,'' Giuliani
said at a morning news conference that attracted a dozen television
cameras, compared with the mosh pit of more than 40 when he
announced his exit from the Senate race on Friday. ``That is one of
the benefits, one of the bright sides, as I said on Friday, of all
that happened with health and everything. I love doing this job.
This is a great job, a very rewarding job, a terrific job, and I
found new reasons to love the city of New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani deferred all questions about political matters. No
decision, he said, on what he would do with his millions in unspent
campaign money. No decision on whether he would attend the May 30
Republican convention in Buffalo, where he was until Friday set to
become the Senate nominee. No thoughts yet about his future when
his second term as mayor runs out in 18 months. And no word on if
he has hired a lawyer to represent him in his planned separation
from his wife, Donna Hanover.
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter asked how he felt about beginning his ``first
week as a real lame-duck mayor,'' Giuliani laughed and responded,
``I feel pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the mayor spent the day on classic municipal affairs. He
gave an early morning speech at the Grand Hyatt Hotel to corporate
leaders, surveying the progress the city has made in recent years
to reduce crime and clean up the streets and sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   During the event, the mayor shared a table with his former
director of communications, Cristyne Lategano-Nicholas, who is now
the president of NYC &AMP; Co., the city's convention and visitors
bureau. It was the first public meeting of the two since Hanover
implied that the mayor and Lategano-Nicholas had a romantic
relationship when she worked for the mayor, a suggestion the two
denied.
</P>
<P>
   Back at City Hall, the mayor fondled two whimpering puppies as
he announced a stepped-up effort by the city's Center for Animal
Care and Control to find adoptive homes for strays.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, last night, he was the host as several hundreds guests
attended the city's annual ``Salute to the Theater'' under a tent
on the Gracie Mansion lawn.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor spoke about the progress in rebuilding Times Square,
including the soon-to-open Madame Tussaud's wax museum. ``Madame
Tussaud is soon to be there with, among other things, my wax
figure,'' he said, pausing and stiffly imitating his replica. ``It
looks better than me.''
</P>
<P>
   In the coming weeks, perhaps the top item on the mayor's city
government agenda will be ironing out a budget agreement with the
City Council. Formal negotiations will begin this week, with the
two sides split over competing tax cut proposals. Negotiations are
also under way with municipal labor unions representing almost all
city workers, whose contracts expire soon.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani indicated that it would most likely be about two weeks
before he decided, in detail, how he would follow up on his promise
on Friday to reach out to disaffected city residents, presumably
from predominantly black and Latino neighborhoods. He also has said
he intended to in some way express his condolences to the family of
Patrick Dorismond, the Haitian-American killed by a police officer
during a confrontation in March.
</P>
<P>
   There were other hints Monday that Giuliani was sustaining his
new image as a more sensitive, compassionate mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Before last night's party, he quietly left City Hall to visit a
sick teen-age girl at Ronald McDonald House of New York City, which
provides support for the families of children being treated for
cancer and other serious diseases. Her family had asked for a
signed photograph of the mayor; he decided to deliver that picture
in person.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding his health, the mayor said Monday he may not
immediately announce when he had settled on a treatment for his
prostate cancer, waiting instead until the care might require him
to miss some work. Until Friday, the mayor had been under pressure
to make his treatment choices quickly, saying he wanted to decide
on the medical matters before indicating if he would stay in the
Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to keep that decision to myself and then announce
it when I think it might have some impact on what I do as mayor,''
he said. ``In other words where I will have to take some time off,
or take a few days off, or a period of time off, as soon I know
that, everybody has a right to know that.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
