<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN BRIEFS  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS
</P>
<P>
   KEYES FIRM ON ABORTION &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The abortion issue continues to present potential problems for
the Republican Party, with Alan Keyes, a presidential candidate,
considering leaving the party if it weakens its stance against
abortion. Connie Hair, Keyes' press secretary, says he will
possibly join the Constitution Party and seek its nomination if the
Republicans do not retain a strong anti-abortion position in their
platform or if Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the presumed
Republican presidential nominee, picks a running mate who is not
anti-abortion. The Constitution Party is strongly anti-abortion.
Hair made her comments to USA Today over the weekend, then
elaborated on them Monday. Keyes has not been heard from much
lately. But Hair emphasized that while Keyes reserved the right to
abandon the Republican Party over the abortion issue, he was for
the moment still a candidate for the Republican nomination, had
delegates pledged to him and intended to attend the party
convention in Philadelphia. The Constitution Party already has a
presidential candidate, Howard Phillips, who said Monday, ``I am
prepared to discuss anything with Alan Keyes, including the
possibility of his becoming our candidate for president or vice
president, but my present intention is to continue as the
presidential nominee.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE GREENS
</P>
<P>
   NADER PRO-IMPEACHMENT
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Nader, the probable Green Party candidate for president,
said Monday that if he had been in the Senate during the
impeachment trial of President Clinton, he would have voted to
convict. ``I thought that he crossed that boundary so seriously in
that scandal that the House was proper in impeaching him and the
Senate really should have convicted him,'' Nader said on Political
Points, the Webcast of The New York Times and ABC News. ``I think
law licenses have been taken away from lawyers for less egregious
offenses than what President Clinton committed as president of the
United States.'' While the remark might please some disaffected
Democrats and independent voters, it could also anger some of the
liberals Nader has been courting in states like California, where a
recent poll shows him pulling just under 10 percent of the vote. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE STATES UP FOR GRABS
</P>
<P>
   Smelling vulnerability in the Republican incumbent, four
Arkansas Democrats each hope to be selected in Tuesday's primary to
be the challenger in the state's traditionally Democratic Fourth
Congressional District. Rep. Jay Dickey has represented the
district, which is about a quarter black, since 1992, but polls
have shown he is faltering, particularly after a remark he made in
January suggesting that he could not help a group of black farmers
unless they contributed money. The leading Democrat in Tuesday's
primary, state Sen. Mike Ross, is the only one of the group that
outranked Dickey in a recent poll by The Arkansas Democrat-Gazette.
The poll showed Ross leading his nearest competitor, former state
Rep. Judy Smith, by 21 points.
</P>
<P>
   THE ISSUES
</P>
<P>
   NRA RE-ELECTS HESTON
</P>
<P>
   Charlton Heston was unanimously re-elected Monday to an
unprecedented third term as president of the National Rifle
Association, the nation's largest gun group. He pledged to do all
possible to defeat Vice President Al Gore, a gun control advocate,
in this fall's presidential contest, and hinted that he might run
again next year for a fourth term as the association's leader. The
re-election of Heston, perhaps the most nationally prominent rifle
association president ever, was the last big item of business at
the organization's 129th annual convention in Charlotte, N.C. The
group amended its bylaws to allow Heston, 75, to run again.
Traditionally, association officers are elected to one-year terms
and may serve only two consecutive terms.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH
</P>
<P>
   Washington and Columbus, Ohio
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE
</P>
<P>
   Washington and Pittsburgh
</P>
</TEXT>
