<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LEGIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAILED COUP LEAVES SPEAKER STILL STANDING, BUT WOUNDED 
</HEADLINE>
   By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ A fierce debate erupted on the floor of the State
Assembly Monday, as Democrats in the majority engaged in a rare
public struggle over the future of their leader, Speaker Sheldon
Silver.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Silver and his allies beat back a coup attempt, as
was widely expected. But the leaders of the insurrection may have
accomplished something nearly as remarkable as toppling a sitting
speaker: wounding him politically.
</P>
<P>
   The coup attempt provided a remarkable display of defiance that
is nearly unheard of here in the Capitol, where the leaders of both
houses decide matters behind closed doors, with debate over
substantive issues rarely making it to the floor of the Assembly or
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The fight made for high political drama, with the 98 Democrats
who make up the majority in the Assembly turning on one another in
a clash that drew scores of people into the chamber's normally
empty gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Silver, for his part, never emerged from his office to defend
himself on the floor, reinforcing the widespread image of him as
isolated and aloof.
</P>
<P>
   The showdown had been building since late last week when Michael
J. Bragman, an assemblyman from the Syracuse area, announced that
he would try to overthrow Silver, a Democrat from Manhattan, in a
vote. Silver immediately stripped Bragman of his title as majority
leader.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman took his fight to the chamber late on Monday afternoon
even after he had publicly acknowledged that his base of support
had dwindled in recent days as Silver rallied his own troops,
punished disloyal lawmakers and threatened retaliation against any
other legislator who crossed him.
</P>
<P>
   On the floor, Bragman accused Silver of hoarding power and
keeping lawmakers in the dark about crucial decisions. He said that
Silver had stifled debate on major issues, reduced rank-and-file
lawmakers to bit players and given powerful lobbyists too much say
in the day-to-day affairs of the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is that we have to change the way this house
conducts itself,'' Bragman said as a crowd of spectators sat
mesmerized by the events unfolding on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone here has felt the frustration and dissatisfaction
with the current situation,'' he said. ``I know that better than
anyone else, because virtually everyone in the majority conference
has come to me, looked me in the eye, and expressed his or her
dissatisfaction.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Member after member is forced to go to the speaker
to ask for anything, from paper clips to chairmanships, from
parking passes to staff needs. And they have told me that they feel
that their requests are being kept in a favor bank. Either you do
what the speaker wants, or you don't get the things you need.''
</P>
<P>
   James F. Brennan, an assemblyman from Brooklyn, shared that
sentiment, calling Silver's leadership ``a virtual dictatorship.''
He added that there is ``a sense of anger and frustration and
bitterness about how the current administration conducts itself.''
</P>
<P>
   But lawmakers loyal to Silver struck back, accusing Bragman and
his allies of severely weakening Democrats both in their dealing
with Republicans over legislation and in this fall's elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've won our battles through this speaker,'' said Richard L.
Brodsky, an assemblyman from Westchester. ``We have kept our
majority through this speaker.'' Then, jabbing his finger at
Bragman, who was sitting just a few feet from him, he said: ``If
there's to be healing and progress, this is not the vehicle and
this is not the man.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Silver prevailed in an 85-to-63 vote that rejected a
motion to suspend the normal rules of the Assembly in order to
elect a new speaker. Silver received support from seven Nassau
County Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   But Bragman remained defiant, vowing to form an opposition bloc
that promises to shadow the speaker's every move and weaken his
authority. Bragman has the support of roughly 25 Democrats, who
joined him at a news conference earlier in the day to air their
grievances against Silver.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is far from over,'' Bragman said after the vote. ``This
is something that is not going to go away. My guess is that we are
more united than we were before.''
</P>
<P>
   His comments potentially open up a new front in his struggle
with Silver and raise questions about whether Silver can rule the
chamber as firmly as he now does. Silver needs a sizable majority
to control legislation in the Assembly, and Bragman poses a huge
threat to his ability to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden turn of events also raised a tantalizing prospect for
Gov. George Pataki and his Republican allies in the Legislature,
who have been trying to chip away at decades of Democratic control
in the Assembly, particularly since Pataki took office in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The Bragman camp represents a potential ally for Republicans,
who during Pataki's first term tried to pressure individual
Democrats to break ranks with Silver and support the governor's
drive to enact tax cuts, toughen criminal penalties and reduce
government spending.
</P>
<P>
   Silver's allies concede that the speaker is not all that open or
even friendly. But they contend that he runs a far more democratic
house than his critics charge. They say that all major decisions
are discussed in closed-door meetings, where the strategy for the
entire Democratic majority is hammered out.
</P>
<P>
   They also say that Silver never forces members to cast votes
that go against their consciences on issues like abortion or the
death penalty. More than that, they say, Silver has done an
excellent job of reaching consensus in an unwieldy and
ideologically diverse conference of 98 Democrats with strongly
competing interests.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman is one of the few members in the Assembly who is in the
position to mount a strong challenge to the speaker because of the
broad-based support he has developed with conservatives, moderates
and liberals.
</P>
<P>
   Silver has worked furiously to stop Bragman since he announced
his plans to topple the speaker on Wednesday. Silver also demoted
two high-ranking lawmakers who openly sided with Bragman, and he
called on powerful union leaders and party officials to discourage
any other Democrats in the Assembly from joining him. Silver also
made it clear that he would punish any member who defied him.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman referred to Silver's response during his comments on the
floor Monday, calling them heavy handed. He said many more
lawmakers would have joined his effort had they ``not feared
reprisals, as was evident in recent days.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
