<HEADER>
A3020 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-SCOTUS-YONKERS-NYT     05-22 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCOTUS-YONKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE REMAINS LIABLE FOR HALF OF YONKERS' INTEGRATION COSTS  

</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   YONKERS, N.Y. _ Rejecting an appeal by New York state, the U.S.
Supreme Court agreed Monday with Yonkers officials that the state
should continue paying half the cost of racially integrating the
city's schools.
</P>
<P>
   The court, without comment, let stand an appellate court's
ruling that the state must share with the city the costs of a
desegregation plan _ about $85 million a year _ that includes
magnet schools and voluntary busing in the city's 26,000-student
school district, the state's fourth largest.
</P>
<P>
   The decision reaffirms earlier court rulings that the state is
partly liable because it ``failed to take corrective measures'' to
desegregate the schools. As a result, New York State will no longer
contest fiscal obligations arising from the original case, which
dates to 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``We respect the court's decision,'' said Juanita Scarlett, a
spokeswoman for the state attorney general, Eliot L. Spitzer.
</P>
<P>
   Practically speaking, though, the decision is more symbolic than
substantive, since the state has been paying its share of
desegregation costs for the last few years _ albeit under protest.
A far more important and contentious issue is whether the state and
the city should pay as much as $1.1 billion more over eight years
to remedy damage from the ``vestiges of segregation'' _ intangible
effects like disparities in the test scores of white and minority
students.
</P>
<P>
   That issue, now in the hands of Judge Leonard B. Sand, is what
all the parties are gearing up for, possibly by late this summer,
as the next watershed in the tortuous 20-year battle to end racial
segregation here.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just another footnote,'' said Raymond P. Fitzpatrick
Jr., a Birmingham, Ala., lawyer who represents the City of Yonkers.
</P>
<P>
   The case, which has stirred deep and sometimes unruly passions,
began in 1980 when the federal government sued the city and the
Board of Education, accusing them of intentionally maintaining
racially segregated schools. The National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People later joined the suit.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, Sand, of Federal District Court in Manhattan, upheld
the suit; a year later, he ordered the city to desegregate the
school system by busing thousands of children across town and
creating dozens of magnet programs. He also ordered the city to
build subsidized housing in predominantly white sections.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, a federal appellate court ordered the state to pay
some of the costs of court-ordered desegregation. In 1997, the
state challenged that ruling, but the Supreme Court declined to
hear the case.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on a separate but closely related track, Sand ordered
the state in 1997 to contribute $575 million over eight years
toward various remedies addressing the results _ rather than the
intent _ of the segregation. The remedies included new curricular
standards, and the recruitment and training of new teachers better
equipped to handle a diverse student body.
</P>
<P>
   And for one school year, 1998-99, the school system did adopt a
budget addressing what the court called the ``vestiges of
segregation,'' with the state footing much of the additional bill,
said Michael Sussman, a lawyer for the NAACP. But that decision is
now on appeal, and the result has plunged the state, the city and
the school board into more budgetary conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The state even tried to excuse itself from financial obligations
for the results of segregation, only to be rebuffed, again, by the
Supreme Court Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this does is reaffirm the basic underpinning of the
case,'' said Lawrence Thomas, a lawyer for the Yonkers Board of
Education. ``It makes it very clear that the state is firmly on the
hook for any remedy that's deployed in Yonkers, and that includes
both the earlier remedy, and the proposed remedy with regard to
vestiges.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
