<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3022 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CARVER-BOARD-NYT &LR;      05-22 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARVER-BOARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARVER BANCORP ALLOWS 2 DISSIDENTS TO TAKE BOARD SEATS  

</HEADLINE>
   By LESLIE EATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Carver Bancorp, the Harlem institution that is the
largest black-run bank in the country, announced Monday that it had
given up its struggle to keep two dissident shareholders off its
board.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the dissidents, who are the owners of the Boston Bank
of Commerce, have agreed to drop a lawsuit against Carver that was
to have gone to trial last week. Carver will pay close to half a
million dollars to help cover their legal costs and will hold an
election next March at which the insurgents can take control of the
bank if they receive enough votes from other shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   The legal settlement is just the latest twist in the complex and
bitter fight over the future of the Harlem bank, which has been
trying to recover from financial problems. Carver lost money in its
last fiscal year, and has been classified by regulators as a
troubled institution; its stock price has plunged from $17.50 in
late 1997 to just under $8 Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Only three months ago, Carver's executives swore that they could
not tolerate having the Boston Bank officials, Kevin Cohee and Teri
Williams, on the board. Deborah C. Wright, Carver's president, and
David R. Jones, its chairman, have repeatedly said that the Boston
bank is a competitor that has tried to take over Carver, and that
the presence of Cohee and Williams on the board would be
disruptive.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the reversal, Ruth Pachman, a spokeswoman for
Carver, said, ``Well, it's time to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   The settlement is by no means a truce. Robert Patrick Cooper,
general counsel for the Boston bank, immediately protested Carver's
decision to keep on its board Jones and David N. Dinkins, the
former mayor. The dissidents contend that the two men were defeated
by Cohee and Williams at an election held in February.
</P>
<P>
   After the election, Carver announced that Jones and Dinkins, who
were incumbents, had won by about 30,000 votes out of the 1.7
million cast. But last month, a Delaware judge invalidated about
86,000 votes cast for the incumbents.
</P>
<P>
   In dropping its lawsuit, Boston Bank of Commerce, which is
black-owned, has given up its fight to get Carver to revoke the
sale of $2.5 million of preferred stock to two Wall Street firms
allied with Wright. The deal, announced in January, gave Morgan
Stanley and Provender Capital control of about 8 percent of
Carver's common shares; Boston Bank owns 7.4 percent of Carver's
common.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1948, Carver survived for decades as one of the few
savings banks to serve minority neighborhoods, and its conservative
management kept it going even through the savings and loan crisis
of the 1980's. But the bank made few loans, angering customers as
well as regulators.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, it expanded into auto loans and credit cards,
with bad results. A year ago, the board brought in Wright, the
former president of the Upper Manhattan Empowerment Zone, to try to
turn the bank around.
</P>
<P>
   Cohee and his supporters have criticized Wright for her lack of
banking experience; she and her supporters have, in turn,
criticized the Boston bank as an interloper without the community
ties that Carver needs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
