<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3024 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DIAGEO-BESTFOODS-NYT &LR;      05-22 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIAGEO-BESTFOODS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIAGEO REPORTED IN TALKS TO BUY PART OF BESTFOODS  

</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON, May 22 _ Diageo PLC, which owns Pillsbury bakery goods
and Haagen-Daz ice cream, is negotiating to buy all or part of
Bestfoods, the maker of Skippy peanut butter and Hellmann's
mayonnaise, executives close to the talks said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations come after an $18.4 billion cash offer for
Bestfoods from Unilever, the Dutch-British consumer products
conglomerate that recently bought Ben &AMP; Jerry's Homemade and
Slim-Fast. That unsolicited offer _ for $66 a share _ was rebuffed,
and Bestfoods has since been seeking another partner to stave off
Unilever's bid.
</P>
<P>
   Diageo is holding trans-Atlantic negotiations with Bestfoods,
based in Englewood Cliffs, N.J., in hopes of combining Bestfoods'
bakery business with its own bakery business and possibly spinning
off the newly combined unit into a company that that might be
controlled by Bestfoods' management, the executives said. While
several executives close to the talks called the negotiations
advanced, no agreement has been reached. The executives also
cautioned that the two companies could still abandon the effort.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Diageo rose 11 pence, to 557.75 pence, while Bestfoods
rose 25 cents, to $63.25.
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear how much Diageo would have to pay for the
Bestfoods bakery business, which provided $1.66 billion of
Bestfoods' $8.64 billion in sales in 1999. If Diageo proceeds with
the acquisition, the deal would put such household brands as
Pillsbury, Entenmann's, Thomas' English muffins and Friehofer's
breads under one roof.
</P>
<P>
   Diageo's other businesses include, among others, Burger King,
Johnnie Walker, Guinness and Tanqueray. It had annual sales of
$16.3 billion in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Unilever has continued to press the Bestfoods board to hold
talks, though those requests have been spurned. Unilever could
still decide to raise its bid, executives close to the company
insisted.
</P>
<P>
   And Bestfoods has set up several ``poison pill'' provisions and
other hurdles to protect it from hostile takeover attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in acquiring Bestfoods is being driven by the raft of
consolidation in the supermarket business, leaving companies that
have food manufacturing arms like Diageo with little leverage and
control over pricing their goods, forcing margins down.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, it was reported that Bestfoods was in talks with H.J.
Heinz. At the time, Bestfoods denied any conversations were in
progress.
</P>
<P>
   A Bestfoods spokesman said the company had no comment on talks
with Diageo. In rejecting the Unilever offer earlier this month,
Bestfoods indicated that the price was too low and added ``it is
not opportune to consider a sale of the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, executives from Unilever and Bestfoods have been
busy making their cases to Wall Street analysts and investors.
Bestfoods has scoffed at Unilever's claim that it could trim $500
million in costs by combining the two companies. Bestfoods
executives put the potential savings at $1 billion, which some
analysts think is an argument for consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   The Unilever offer for Bestfoods, which is considered to have
one of the best-performing international food businesses,
particularly in Latin America, signaled the start of what could
turn out to be a wave of mergers in the food industry. Investors
have been impatient with the sector's slow growth and lackluster
returns, and some believe merging companies could produce cost
savings and speedier product innovation, as well as give the new
company more power in negotiations for retail shelf space than two
smaller companies would have on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Nabisco brands, which include Oreo cookies, Ritz crackers and
LifeSavers candy, are also on the block as Nabisco Group Holdings,
the holding company that owns 80.6 percent of Nabisco stock, seeks
a buyer. Possible contenders include Philip Morris, the tobacco and
packaged-food giant, which already owns Kraft Foods; and Groupe
Danone, the French foodmaker that bought Nabisco's European cookie
business in 1992.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
